<SLUG> BC-BBN-CARDS-MARLINS-NYT </SLUG>
  
 McGWIRE'S EARLY SHOW IS NIGHT'S ONLY THRILL  
 (bl)  
 By IRA BERKOW   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Mark McGwire returned home Tuesday night to the
Cardinals' nest, Busch Stadium, after a nine-game road trip and a
giant step toward reaching the home run record for a season. He
departed with 47 home runs, and returned with 53, two in front of
Sammy Sosa of the Chicago Cubs and eight short of the record of 61
set by Roger Maris 37 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   He remained eight behind Maris, with 32 games left, after going
0 for 4 with a walk Tuesday night against the Florida Marlins, who
beat the Cardinals, 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   When McGwire left St. Louis for the road, there was no
controversy about muscle-building supplements. When he returned,
Tuesday morning's front-page headline in The St. Louis
Post-Dispatch read, ``Effects of Andro are Hotly Debated.'' The
subhead read, ``Not much is known about the supplement McGwire is
taking _ studies are unclear, doctors say.''
</P>
<P>
   Androstenedione, an over-the-counter supplement, has been a
muscle-builder of choice this year for McGwire. It is legal in
baseball and in the National Basketball Association, illegal in the
National Football League, the National Collegiate Athletic
Association and in the eyes of the International Olympic Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems people are always trying to discredit legitimate
achievement,'' said Marlins manager Jim Leyland. ``I don't care
what anyone takes, guys just don't hit 93-mile-an-hour sliders like
he does.'' This seems to echo the general sentiment of baseball
personnel.
</P>
<P>
   In his first trip to the plate Tuesday night, McGwire faced the
right-hander Rafael Medina. With the home crowd in a rhythmic chant
filled with expectation, McGwire belted a long drive to center
field. But it was caught near the 402-foot marker. It was his best
shot of the night.
</P>
<P>
   In the third inning, McGwire reached first base on a fielder's
choice. In the fourth, he batted with the bases loaded, two out and
the Cardinals leading by 1-0. McGwire has 11 grand slams in his
career, two this season. But after several foul balls and extending
the count to 3-2, he walked. The fans, as has become customary in
such an eventuality, booed with conviction, even though McGwire was
credited with driving in a run to increase the home team's lead to
2-0.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth, with a man on third and two out, he grounded out
to third, and in the eighth, with Florida leading by 4-3, McGwire
grounded out with a man on first to end the inning. At that point,
many among the crowd of 29,130 got up and headed for home. So did
McGwire after the game, fulfilling a pre-game stance that he would
not speak with reporters if he did nothing noteworthy in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Before the opener of this six-game homestand, McGwire began with
what has become one of most appealing and spectacular acts in
sports: his batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark feels an obligation to perform,'' said Tony La Russa, the
Cardinals' manager. ``He knows fans are coming to the ball park
early just to see him bat. Not just to bat, but hit the ball into
the stands. It's like playing a doubleheader. He's told me he feels
less pressure in the actual game. At least, a single or double
isn't a disappointment, as anything less than a ball hit into the
outfield stands is in batting practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, a few thousand fans stood along the Cardinals'
dugout and filled sections of the lower and upper left-field decks,
lustily cheering McGwire when he came to bat about an hour and a
half before the game.
</P>
<P>
   An elderly woman held up a poster: ``When I grow up I want to be
just like Mark.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Marlins stopped their activities, whether it was
stretching in front of their dugout or playing catch, and watched,
just like the fans. Derrek Lee, a rookie infielder for the Marlins,
edged forward on the dugout steps.
</P>
<P>
   The park grew silent at 5:46 p.m. as McGwire waved his bat in
anticipation. He swung at the first batting-practice pitch and sent
it soaring into the lower left-field deck. The crowed oohed. He hit
the second and third pitches into the upper deck. He failed to
homer on the next three pitches.
</P>
<P>
   At 5:47, he hit one homer in four swings. At 5:48, he went one
homer for three. At 5:49, it was 1 for 2, and, in his last trip
into the batting cage, at 5:50, getting one swing, he provided the
fans with one more treat to remember by lofting a pitch deep into
the upper deck, above the neon sign that says ``BigMac Land.''
</P>
<P>
   Applause rang around the stadium as he moved to the dugout.
McGwire's homer stat: 7 for 16.
</P>
<P>
   Just before Lee took the field, he shook his head. ``That was
awesome,'' he said. ``You've got to watch him _ he's the best.
That's incredible what he just did.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
