<SLUG> BC-NY-MARKETSPAN-LILCO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW MARKETSPAN LEADERSHIP INCLUDES 9 OF LILCO'S TOP 26
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JOHN T. McQUISTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HICKSVILLE, N.Y. _ Marketspan announced a new management team
Tuesday, and it includes only nine of 26 former officers of the
Long Island Lighting Company. The others chose to leave the company
rather than return lucrative severance checks or were not asked to
stay on.
</P>
<P>
   Marketspan officials said that they hoped the announcement would
help to calm Wall Street concerns about the company's focus and
direction, which intensified during the bitter dispute over the
severance checks that the 26 top Lilco executives received when
Lilco merged with Brooklyn Union Gas to create Marketspan in May.
</P>
<P>
   The severance packages totaled $67 million, with most of the
money _ $42 million _ going to Dr. William J. Catacosinos, the
former Lilco chairman, who was forced to resign on July 31 under
pressure from stockholders and state officials who said Catacosinos
misled them about the severance payouts.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials said that all the members of Marketspan's new
management team shared the same basic benefits package, including
stock options and other longterm benefits, but that each package
was ultimately based on the individual officer's performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to create a team and have everyone going forward on
the same basis,'' said Robert Catell, who became Marketspan's
chairman and chief executive after Catacosinos' resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who chose to leave was Michael Bray, a senior vice
president for electrical operations who opted not to return his
$800,000 severance check. But Bray agreed to remain on the job
until a replacement could be found and trained, according to Robert
Mahony, a spokesman for Marketspan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bray's decision to stay on and help us out, especially through
the hurricane season, speaks well of his relationship with the
company,'' Mahony said.
</P>
<P>
   Marketspan, which is based in Hicksville, has a long-term
contract with the Long Island Power Authority to manage the
authority's electric service operations. LIPA Chairman Richard
Kessel recently expressed concern about the possibility of Bray's
departure, noting that during the hurricane season, ``the loss of
experienced people is a very serious problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Mahony said that Marketspan hoped Bray's agreement to remain, if
only temporarily, would help allay such fears. Bray did not return
telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   The consolidation of Marketspan's management team, and the
return of the severance payouts by some of Lilco's former
executives, was welcome news to Kessel, who noted that he and Gov.
George Pataki had been highly critical of the payouts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
