<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHUMER-NYT </SLUG>
  
 SCHUMER PROPOSALS AIMED AT POOR, MIDDLE CLASS  (mk) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Asserting that Wall Street's wave of prosperity had
failed to lift most inner-city neighborhoods in New York, Charles
Schumer, a Democratic candidate for Senate, proposed a series of
federal spending programs Tuesday to encourage development in
downtrodden cities and to raise the incomes and savings of the poor
and middle class.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer, a congressman from Brooklyn, urged a sharp increase in
the minimum wage, tax credits for first-time home buyers who move
into designated urban neighborhoods and a new tax-free savings
account program in which the government would partially match
savings that low-income families put aside for at least five years.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer framed his proposals, which he gave in a speech in
Jamaica, Queens, as a specific appeal to minority voters, who tend
to make up a significant proportion of the turnout in Democratic
primaries. Schumer _ one of three Democrats seeking the nomination
to challenge Sen. Alfonse D'Amato _ said that poor minority
neighborhoods had failed to share in Wall Street's good fortune,
producing what he warned was a dangerous imbalance in the state's
economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember the '20s,'' Schumer said, referring to the decade
leading up to the Great Depression. ``If the prosperity and the
wealth is concentrated at the very top, sooner or later there's not
enough buying power in the rest of the population.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumer noted that New York has ranked near the bottom of the 50
states in job creation. ``That's unacceptable,'' he said. ``When
you consider how much the bull market on Wall Street has done to
help our economy, you realize just how poorly the rest of New York
is faring.''
</P>
<P>
   The representative, who has proposed a variety of spending
programs in this campaign _ including making college tuition
deductible _ said the cost of his latest proposal would be less
than $1 billion. He added that he would pay for the proposal by
cutting defense spending or agriculture subsidies. ``I think we can
easily find a billion dollars,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The speech came after a period in which Schumer had kept a
relatively low-profile public campaign schedule, possibly
reflecting the fact that candidates in all the major races this
year have found it difficult to compete for attention with
President Clinton's legal difficulties and the bombings in Africa.
Schumer, however, has been running a heavy schedule of campaign
advertisements, unlike either of his rivals, Mark Green, the New
York City Public Advocate, and Geraldine Ferraro, the former Queens
representative.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer delivered his speech at the Jamaica Business Resource
Center, a nonprofit organization that assists minority and
small-business owners. The congressman sat at one end of a table,
addressing an audience of just 15 people, including his mother and
father, who were in the neighborhood and stopped by to hear their
son speak.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the details of Schumer's proposals, which he described
as a ``major policy address,'' appeared to be falling into place as
the day went on. Asked after his address if interest earned on his
proposed savings account would be tax-exempt, Schumer responded:
``You know, that's a good question. I don't think it would be
tax-free, but maybe it should be. Making it tax-free would be a
good idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumer also proposed raising the minimum wage, now $5.15 an
hour, to $7.50 by 2002, and linking it after that to inflation.
Efforts to raise the minimum wage have been strongly resisted by
Republicans in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer also proposed that first-time home buyers get a $2,000
tax credit when they buy homes in low-income neighborhoods
designated by the Department of Housing and Urban Development. And
he said that nonprofit groups, like churches and hospitals, should
get the same payroll-tax credit for hiring people on welfare that
is currently awarded to private business.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of what I talked about today constitutes a handout,''
Schumer said. ``A handout is temporary.''
</P>
</TEXT>
