 PM-BUDGET-NYT 
 (sw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For WEDNESDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Wednesday, Aug. 26.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-FLOODS (Beijing) _ As charges mount here that bad policies
and official neglect have worsened this summer's floods, the
Chinese government has made an unusual admission that its mistakes
in land use are partly to blame and announced some sweeping changes
in direction. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-SUDAN (Khartoum, Sudan) _ At the end of the Persian Gulf
war in 1991, when Sudan was one of Iraq's few remaining friends in
the world, the government here struck a bargain with Baghdad,
foreign diplomats and Sudanese said Tuesday. In return for Iraqi
financial help and assistance by military and civilian experts,
Sudan agreed to allow its installations to be used by Iraqi
technicians for steps in the production of chemical weapons, they
said. The deal was beneficial to both countries. Struggling Sudan
got economic help, and Iraq was able to move ahead with chemical
weapons far away from the gaze of U.N. weapons inspectors. By Jane
Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   IMF-RESPONSE (Washington) _ The IMF, reacting to events, finds
itself forced to become increasingly flexible in trying to salvage
the global financial system. Even Russia's threat to write off debt
might not disqualify it from IMF loans. By Louis Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-POWELL (Washington) _ Retired Justice Lewis Powell dies at
his home in Richmond, Va., at 90. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   FOSTER-SIBLINGS (Undated) _ The new push to keep siblings
together in foster care. By Pam Belluck.
