<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 00:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2236 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKL-COOPER-HNS &LR;      08-26 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-COOPER-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By W.H. STICKNEY JR.  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
There she stood, hoisting another Most Valuable Player trophy to an
ovation from the 11,901 gathered at Compaq Center to watch a WNBA
semifinal playoff game.
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Cynthia Cooper soaked up the atmosphere, a million thoughts
raced through her mind.
</P>
<P>
   She thought of how fortunate she was to be voted the best in the
WNBA for the second time; of how much it meant to her, her mother
and family.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper thought about how the trophy was partial repayment, a
thanks of sorts, to the thousands of fans throughout the Houston
area who have supported the Comets and made her feel so warm and at
home the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really feel like I've been blessed throughout my whole
(12-year professional) career,'' Cooper said Tuesday. ``But I never
imagined it would be this way, this special, and that I would have
an opportunity to live a dream like I'm living right now, to be a
part of something so unique and so special.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there were the Comets' 27-3 record, their 15-game winning
streak and their 10-game home winning streak, all of which were
WNBA records. And Cooper this season became the first player to
reach 1,000 career points in the WNBA.
</P>
<P>
   She set a basketful of other records and is often referred to as
the best female player in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's awesome,'' Cooper, 35, said. ``I've always thought I
have a very good game. I've always thought I was a hard worker. But
I never thought I would be in position to be named or titled `the
best female basketball player in the world.' Never, ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always been a goal of mine, but you never think you're
going to arrive at that goal. When I say it's a dream come true, it
really is. And I really feel like I'm living a dream. It's
something very special to me.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cooper then thought of some moments that might best be
forgotten. There were the physical hurdles _ a mild concussion, a
bruised knee, a scratched eyeball, a bruised thigh and a
hyperextended elbow. And there was what Cooper perceived as a lack
of respect, in some instances, by some players and officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of different emotions going through me that
I'm still trying to harness, put them on the back burner and just
concentrate on the second WNBA championship,'' Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
   As the applause and screams of the fans became louder and
longer, Cooper considered the day-to-day grind that accompanies
being the head of a vast household and caretaker for her ailing
mother.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper is ``mom'' to seven nieces and nephews who reside at the
family home in Sugar Land. She is constant companion, overseer and
comforter to her mother, Mary Cobbs, who single-handedly raised
eight children but is locked in a battle with breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper says Cobbs is doing well but every so often has some
rough days.
</P>
<P>
   During ceremonies before the Comets eliminated the Charlotte
Sting 77-61 on Monday night and advanced to the WNBA finals a
second time, Cooper was on the floor for about five minutes as she
accepted the MVP trophy from WNBA president Val Ackerman.
</P>
<P>
   Brief. But it was time enough for the flood of thoughts, for the
rush of emotion that had characterized her day of honor to be
revisited.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, during the ceremony and even at the news conference
earlier in the day, I thought about all of the sacrifices I had to
make personally, that my teammates had to make for me and for other
players on the team,'' Cooper said. ``I thought about all of the
ups and downs, the very tense moments at practice, the intense
moments during a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year has been really tough, mentally and physically.
Mentally, you never knew from day to day who was going to do what
out here, what personality they were going to come with.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think my teammates have been committed to putting team
first. So that's made it all better, made it all work out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm going to write a book about this experience when
it's over. I'm going to tell of how you've got to persevere through
the hard times, that even though it gets tough, something good is
going to come of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The MVP awards, the first-team WNBA honors, winning that first
WNBA title, and hopefully a second, and even that we had the
opportunity to fight for a second championship. These are all
special moments that other teams don't have and other women don't
have. So we should feel very fortunate that we're even in this
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The ride, Cooper said, has been exciting and often bumpy. But
it's one she would like to take again next season. Like all
second-year players in the WNBA, Cooper's contract expires in
December.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is I want to play with Tina (Thompson) and Kim
(Perrot) and I want coach (Van) Chancellor to be my coach,'' Cooper
said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, without fanfare, she walked away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
