<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS ROOKIE ELLIS LEARNING AS HE GOES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
Ellis wants at end of line 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I told Walter to go out and jump him a little bit because I
knew he wasn't used to it; we wanted Walter to take his moves away
right away. If anything, that seemed to bother Greg. The thing he
needs most work on is stopping the run. ... I think he has a chance
to be a really good player.'' _ Gregg Smith, Seahawks offensive
line coach
</P>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Seattle offensive line coach Gregg Smith was
talking about Cowboys defensive end Greg Ellis, the club's
first-round draft choice who lined up against Seahawks offensive
tackle Walter Jones, an all-rookie selection in 1997, in a
preseason game July 31.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Cowboys' first preseason game, and Ellis was limited
to one solo tackle and no quarterback sacks or pressures. Smith's
comments could have applied to Ellis' play in each of the next two
games. Spending time at both left and right end, he had one solo
stop against Patriots tackles Bruce Armstrong and Zefross Moss.
Ellis did not even appear on the stat sheet against Raiders tackles
Pat Harlow and Lincoln Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   At North Carolina, Ellis was used to overpowering people or
beating them with his quickness. But he acknowledged that the pro
game is totally different, and he said he was having a hard time
adjusting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those (veteran tackles) are smart,'' he was saying, with a
sigh, at his locker the other day, ``They are big and strong, and
they can be physical and hit you in the mouth if they have to. But
they are excellent technicians. The way they block you, sometimes
they let you go where you want to go and use your own momentum and
ride you right out of the play. That's something I'd never seen in
college. Hey, these are smart guys. They are not just big bulky
guys that can't think.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Ellis said he might have been thinking too much in
the Cowboys' first three games. He just decided to play with
reckless abandon in the game against St. Louis last week, and he
had three tackles and two quarterback pressures against the
formidable Orlando Pace.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coaches said it was Ellis' best game, and Ellis was all
smiles in the locker room Monday as he talked about his play. More
than anything, though, Ellis knows he'll have to continue to
improve to quiet questions about whether the Cowboys did the right
thing by drafting him with the eighth overall selection.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just want people to know that you can play football,''
Ellis said. ``I can't please everybody. I'm aware that some people
wished the Cowboys would have picked Randy Moss. Had they done
that, I think the fans would find something wrong with him. I've
just got to play, that's all. I'm just going to play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
