<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ANGELS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS TOP YANKEES, 7-6 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If there has been anything more magical than the New
York Yankees' season, it has been the magic with which the Anaheim
Angels have mesmerized the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   For the fifth time in eight games this season, the Angels
defeated the Yankees on Tuesday night, this time 7-6 behind a
four-run flurry in the seventh inning against two members of the
Yankees' incendiary relief corps, Mike Stanton and Mike Buddie.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Glaus, a rookie, who was hitting .209 at game time, drove
in the final two runs in the seventh with a double against Buddie
after the pitcher had knocked him down with his first pitch.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels' five games to three edge is unique in this season in
which the Yankees are threatening to set a major league record for
most victories. None of the other 17 teams the Yankees have played
this season has even a .500 record against them.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of this game also gave the Yankees their first
three-game losing streak since the first three games of the season.
The Angels, who lead the American League West, have been
responsible for two-thirds of each streak.
</P>
<P>
   To salvage their latest victory, the Angels needed a good
late-inning relief effort from their closer, Troy Percival, and
they got it. Relieving with one out and two on in the eighth after
Paul O'Neill's single reduced the Angels' lead to a run, Percival
struck out Bernie Williams and retired Tino Martinez on a grounder
to second base on a 3-2 pitch.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what happens in the remaining three games of the
five-game series. two games on Wednesday and one on Thursday, the
Angels have already succeeded in making a point _ to themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was important for our guys to find out they can play with
them,'' Terry Collins, the Angels' manager, said before the game at
Yankee Stadium. ``Absolutely, no question about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels' ability to beat the Yankees is important because the
teams could meet in the playoffs, either in the division series or
in the league championship series.
</P>
<P>
   Results in the regular season often have no bearing on the
outcome of a post-season series, but if the Angels had been blown
away by the Yankees during the season, they might have a
post-season problem.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing that issue, Collins said: ``When you're a young team
like we are still _ and I know we have some guys that have four or
five years in the big leagues, but age-wise they're fairly young _
to be able to walk out there and say we can compete with the New
York Yankees in the year they're having, yeah, I think it will be
important. If it gets to that point where we have to play them,
certainly it can only help us have more confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   With Hideki Irabu continuing his two-month streak of
inconsistent pitching, the Yankees couldn't be certain whether they
were watching the Perils of Pauline or the Pearls of Hideki. Irabu
kept getting into trouble, then escaping the danger he had created.
</P>
<P>
   He executed his most noteworthy escapes in the fourth inning and
the sixth. Clinging by his fingernails to the sheer cliff he had
created for himself, Irabu emerged unscathed after loading the
bases with one out in the fourth, then survived with a one-run lead
after allowing two runs with one out in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   But when Irabu walked Randy Velarde at the start of the seventh
inning, the director of the Yankees' huge hit of a show, Joe Torre,
decided his stomach had been subjected to enough abuse for one
evening. Before him, after all, lay a day-night doubleheader on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Torre's move settled his stomach. He summoned Mike
Stanton, who all too often has played firebug rather than fireman.
Stanton wasted no time unsettling Torre further, as well as
provoking frequent outbursts of boos from the spectators. Before he
had tossed a pitch in his attempted preservation of a 4-3 lead,
Stanton threw to first base; that is, he threw somewhere in the
vicinity of first base. Nowhere that Tino Martinez could have
caught the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Velarde went to second on the error and promptly scored the
tying run as Darin Erstad drilled a double along the right-field
line.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad moved to third on Tim Salmon's fly to right, then scored
the lead run as Garret Anderson rapped a hard grounder through an
infield playing in hoping to cut Erstad off at the plate. When Jim
Edmonds followed with a single to right, Torre extinguished Stanton
for the rest of the night.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem was that Mike Buddie couldn't extricate the
Yankees from the mess Stanton had got them into. After Edmonds
stole second, Troy Glaus, the Angels' rookie third baseman, who was
hitting .209 at game time, lashed his second successive
run-producing hit.
</P>
<P>
   Glaus had singled home a run in the previous inning, and this
time he cracked a line drive to left field for a two-run double and
a 7-4 lead. Interestingly, on his first pitch to Glaus, Buddie
might have been sending a message from his fellow rookie pitcher,
Ryan Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Buddie's pitch was high and inside, knocking Glaus down, and it
was reminiscent of the encounters Glaus had with Bradley when
Bradley played at Arizona State and Glaus at UCLA. The pitch,
however, didn't intimidate Glaus, and it made no impression either
on Matt Walbeck, who singled Glaus to third. But Buddie finally
ended the madness, inducing Gary DiSarcina to ground into an
inning-ending double play.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
