<HEADLINE>
NFL OFFENSES IN A RUSH TO EMBRACE LATEST TREND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe it is the vision of Denver running back Terrell Davis
slashing through the Green Bay defense in last season's Super Bowl.
It could be that John Elway's 22 passes were the fewest by a
winning Super Bowl team in a dozen years.
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps it is another telling statistic: NFL teams that
attempted more rushing plays than passes during 1997's regular
season won a whopping 69 percent of their games.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever is prompting the talk, the word is out that the run is
in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things go in cycles in sports and music,'' said Dallas Cowboys
defensive coordinator Dave Campo. ``And right now, the trend
definitely seems to be coming back around to the running game.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis and Barry Sanders can be considered the trendsetters after
their run at the 2,000-yard mark last season. Sanders posted the
third 2,000-plus season in league history with a total of 2,053
yards in leading his team to the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Davis ran for 1,750 yards last season and ran off with the Super
Bowl most valuable player award after gaining 150 yards and rushing
for three touchdowns against the Packers. During the regular
season, NFL running backs topped the 200-yard mark a record seven
times and the 100-yard mark 121 times, the most since the 1970
AFL-NFL merger.
</P>
<P>
   Former San Francisco coach Bill Walsh, widely credited with
introducing to the NFL what has come to be known as the ``West
Coast offense,'' says he believes teams are beginning to turn away
from the trendy run-and-shoot offensive formations with three and
four wide receivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``A two-back offense with a tight end gives you much more
versatility,'' Walsh said. ``I think we'll see more of a return to
that, and that probably means a greater emphasis on running.''
</P>
<P>
   In the West Coast offense, high-percentage short passes and runs
are typically used for ball control, and to set up the long pass.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco team of 1994, coached by George Seifert, used
that offense nearly to perfection and was almost invincible. The
49ers blew out San Diego, 49-26, in a Super Bowl in which a record
93 passes were thrown.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the next year the run slipped a notch in
priority leaguewide.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, 43.3 percent of the NFC's offensive plays from
scrimmage (excluding punts and field goals) were runs, compared to
45.1 and 47.5 percent the previous two seasons. The AFC dropped to
44.9 percent that year.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this league, we're all copycats,'' admits Miami offensive
coordinator Kippy Brown.
</P>
<P>
   But not every pass has Steve Young on one end and Jerry Rice on
the other, Brown points out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone had to ask themselves, `Do I have the people to do
that?' And the truth is, a lot of teams don't,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   With that realization, the percentage of runs in the NFC
rebounded to 45.7 in 1996 and again to 46.8 percent last year. The
AFC was at 46.1 last year.
</P>
<P>
   The pendulum could swing further toward running this year, many
are predicting.
</P>
<P>
   According to Campo, defenses across the league have begun to
adapt to the West Coast offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The West Coast offense uses the short pass as a running play,
and that's fine,'' Campo said. ``But it also limits the different
types of passes a team throws, and what has happened is that
defenses will catch up to that.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, it's like playing against the wishbone, with only so
many running plays you have to stop. When there are only so many
pass patterns to defend, teams get used to that, and the defense
has a chance to control it a little bit more.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, New York Jets coach Bill Parcells has pledged to
reemphasize the run.
</P>
<P>
   So has Brown's boss, Dolphins head coach Jimmy Johnson, who won
three Super Bowls at Dallas with the kind of balanced offense he
hasn't had at Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the years,'' Brown said, ``statistics have proven that
teams that have a certain number of running attempts win a certain
percentage of their games, regardless of yards per carry. People
are really starting to understand that.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, only seven NFL teams ran the ball more than they threw
it. Topping the AFC in run percentage were Tennessee, Pittsburgh,
Kansas City and Denver. They went a combined 44-20 for the season.
</P>
<P>
   The NFC leader in run percentage? None other the 49ers, who
without injured Jerry Rice still finished with a 13-3 record by
running the ball 54.7 percent of the time.
</P>
<P>
   Other NFC teams on the short list were the surprising Tampa Bay
and New York Giants, who along with San Francisco logged a combined
33-14-1 record.
</P>
<P>
   None of that surprises Walsh, who points out that although his
1984 championship team - regarded as one of the NFL's all-time
greatest - is best remembered for Joe Montana and Rice, it also was
among the league leaders in rushing with two 1,000-yard backs in
Roger Craig and Wendell Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game goes in cycles, to a certain extent,'' Walsh said.
</P>
<P>
   The current run cycle includes young rushers such as Tennessee's
Eddie George, Cincinnati's Corey Dillon and Oakland's Napoleon
Kaufman, who each had 200-yard games last season.
</P>
<P>
   However, Walsh cautions not to expect any dramatic changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're likely to see more running, but make no mistake, this is
still going to be a game of the forward pass,'' he said. ``The
forward pass typically dominates in the NFL, and the teams that do
it most effectively are the ones that consistently win.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm expecting more teams to try to it from the framework
of a more balanced attack. That's the direction the league seems to
be headed again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
