<SLUG> BC-BBA-COLUMN-THIEL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
M'S BULLPEN TO BLAME FOR LACK OF ONE-RUN WINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Mike Timlin was in a mildly defiant mood.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people write us off,'' he said after Monday's 11-10
win over Chicago, a game that featured more weirdness than Mark
McGwire's medicine cabinet. ``Please. Go ahead. Write us off.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might come up and bite you.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the sort of attitude a pitcher can take when he gives up
a grand slam and still gets a save. The Mariners have not been
blessed with such serendipity this season, so Timlin can be
forgiven his misplaced swagger.
</P>
<P>
   It's the club owners who wrote off Timlin and his pals when they
dealt Randy Johnson for nothing that will help in 1998. But that
dead horse has been pummeled into Big Unit dog food, so we won't go
there again this morning.
</P>
<P>
   Of more curiosity was the four straight wins by one run over the
White Sox, after the Mariners went the previous 125 games with four
single-digit wins.
</P>
<P>
   The major league record for fewest one-run wins in a season is
10, so the Mariners are still capable of reaching a team mark as
dubious as the home-run chase is magnificent.
</P>
<P>
   The potential Mariner achievement might be even more amazing,
since most clubs via the law of averages will win a half-dozen
games a season like the Mariners did Monday. As manager Lou
Piniella dryly put it: ``We put up a lot of runs, and one more than
they scored.''
</P>
<P>
   It is hard not to win a fair number of one-run games, just
because of baseball's virtue of balance between offense and
defense. Over the last seven years, bad teams and good, the
Mariners have averaged about 20 one-run wins.
</P>
<P>
   Some, like David Segui, are prone to dismiss the development as
another irrelevant statistical anomaly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody thinks about that in here,'' the Mariner first baseman
said in the clubhouse. ``That's for you guys to write. The way
we've played, it's not surprising.''
</P>
<P>
   True enough, except that a reversal of a half-dozen of those
close losses would have the Mariners locked into contention. The
8-20 ledger is not a cause but a symptom of what ails a team that
should be biting.
</P>
<P>
   Piniella listed the lamentable litany.
</P>
<P>
   ``Relief pitching, defensive execution, and men left on base,''
he said. ``Most of that came early. June was the worst. Since the
All-Star break, we've been doing better. Early in the year we
didn't add runs, and other teams crept back into games.''
</P>
<P>
   In the four games against the White Sox, the Mariners corrected
nearly all of those deficiencies, and covered up the one mess _
seven runs surrendered by the pen in Monday's last two innings _
with prodigious offense and consecutive run-scoring wild pitches by
the AL's rottenest veteran pitcher, Jamie Navarro.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Mariners won a lot in that fashion (25-21 in
one-run games) on the way to a club-record 90 regular-season wins.
As the Baltimore Orioles pointed out, that kind of style doesn't
work so well in the postseason. But it was certainly better than
this season's woefulness.
</P>
<P>
   Piniella's litany pointed out the deadly combination that has
brought down the club this season. And while the most egregious
evidence is third baseman Russ Davis's 33 errors, which continue to
bury the club record of 29 set by shortstop Craig Reynolds in 1978,
the bullpen's profound ineptness has helped corrupt the club's one
major asset _ offense.
</P>
<P>
   Mariner hitters over the last three years have become so twitchy
over the fact that too many runs are never enough that they are
locked into a head game of one-swing solutions. A macho bunch to
begin with, they remain so addicted to the low-percentage trick of
the home run that they are on the verge of setting a club mark for
men left on base.
</P>
<P>
   They are averaging 7.5 runners left on per game, up from the
mark of 7.1 of 1996, a tell-tale sign with so few one-run wins. So
many times hitters have found themselves with just three or six
at-bats to recover from a sudden deficit created by the Gasoline
Gang that the desperation plays into the group's greatest
collective weakness.
</P>
<P>
   As a first-year Mariner coming from the National League, where
small-ball prevails, Segui is hip to the consequences of addiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've thought about that, and it's the only thing that might be
right,'' he said. ``We have so many guys who can hit home runs, we
try to roll the dice all at once, instead of the higher percentage
move.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the only thing I can think of. It might help to change
the approach.''
</P>
<P>
   Tough to do, since the habit here runs so deep, notwithstanding
the streak over the Weak Sox.
</P>
<P>
   The John Dalys of baseball will lead the game in home runs for a
second consecutive year and will have a single post-season win,
Game 3 in Baltimore last October, to show for it.
</P>
<P>
   The highest-salaried bullpen in baseball is even more costly
than the payroll shows.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
