A2265 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     08-26 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
 
PITCHERS WARY OF BEING McGWIRE'S CHUMP 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The 11 biggest Mark McGwire fans on the continent
are in town this week. And they're easy to pick out of the general
population. They're wearing Montreal Expos uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody's rooting harder for McGwire to break the home run
record, the sooner the better, than Expos pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   They'd ship him enough Androstenedione to fill a kitchen
cabinet, if that would help him get home run No.62 out of the way
before Sept. 25. And if McGwire doesn't have a kitchen cabinet,
they'd build him one.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 25 is the Friday night the Expos go to Busch Stadium to
begin the final, three-game series of the season, against McGwire
and the St. Louis Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it won't mean anything,'' Expos pitching coach Bobby
Cuellar said at Dodger Stadium, where the Expos are facing the
Dodgers. ``Hey, it might rain for three days.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything's possible,'' Cuellar said, hopefully, over his
shoulder as he ran onto the field.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, that series might make the difference between
McGwire breaking Roger Maris' 37-year-old record and not, and it
might make one of the Expos' young pitchers an indelible footnote
in baseball history.
</P>
<P>
   For every historic homer, there's been a chump. Maris had Tracy
Stallard, a Boston Red Sox right-hander who did nothing more
distinctive in a seven-year career. Hank Aaron, for No. 715 in
1974, had Al Downing, a left-hander of note who, unfortunately, is
best known for his appearance on that videotape. Reggie Jackson,
hitting his third homer of the New York Yankees' clinching victory
over the Dodgers in the 1978 World Series, had Charlie Hough.
</P>
<P>
   Who will it be for McGwire? Mike Thurman, the Expos right-hander
who started against the Dodgers on Tuesday? Ugueth Urbina, the only
Expos All-Star. Anthony Telford, the Expos workhorse?
</P>
<P>
   How about you, Javier Vazquez?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be happier if he hits 62 before he faces us,'' said the
22-year-old, who is 4-13 this season. ``I'm not looking for any
attention.''
</P>
<P>
   And you, Steve Kline?
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, he does it before we get to town,'' said Kline,
who, as a left-handed reliever, is unlikely to face the
right-handed McGwire in any case.
</P>
<P>
   They might get their wish. McGwire, homerless Tuesday night
against Florida, has 53 in the Cardinals' 132 games. At that pace,
he'd hit his 61st in the team's 152nd game, Tuesday, Sept. 15
against Pittsburgh, and his 62nd in the team's 155th game,
Saturday, Sept. 19 at Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't take much of a change of pace, though, to give the
Expos a real big headache.
</P>
<P>
   Say this for them: They're talking tough. They realize there
would be no shame in giving up No. 62. There would be shame only in
being too chicken to throw McGwire a strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people will pitch to him,'' said Carl Pavano, one of
six rookie pitchers on the Expos roster. ``It's part of the game.
He deserves (the chance to swing).''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a competitor, you want to challenge him,'' said
Jeremy Powell. ``Personally, for the good of the game, I'd like to
see him (get the record). If he hits it off me, it happens.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not giving him anything,'' reliever Miguel Batista said.
``If he hits it, I'll be the first to say, `He did it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Expos have given up only one McGwire homer this season. The
pitcher, Trey Moore, is on the disabled list now.
</P>
<P>
   If it's the final weekend, McGwire is still ahead of Sammy Sosa
and the record is on the line, everybody will deal with it in his
own way.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe somebody will make like Denny McLain, who, in his 31st
victory of 1968, gave up Mickey Mantle's 535th home run, good for
third place on the all-time list. Mantle had motioned for a
fastball across the letters. McLain had thrown it there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I give up a lot of home runs,'' McLain was quoted as saying.
``I don't think one more makes any difference.''
</P>
<P>
   That's one way of looking at it.
</P>
<P>
   The Expos have a novel way of their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should we dread it?'' said Pavano. ``A lot of people know
our pitching staff for being rookies. I think it would be kind of
cool if McGwire came into (the Expos series) with 61, and our staff
of rookies shut him down.''
</P>
<P>
   The Expos, 36{ games out of first place, haven't had much at
stake this year. And they haven't been on national TV in the United
States, as they will be if McGwire's bid comes down to the final
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   So maybe they're dreaming of the possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to know. They seem genuinely fond of McGwire, and
they'd like to see history made. They'd just prefer not to watch
from the pitcher's mound.
</P>
<P>
   So are they telling McGwire to break a leg or just sprain it?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-26-98 0102EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
