<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DID M'S LOSE? 10-4, GOOD BUDDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ This is where Stan Williams came in. The Mariner
pitching coach noticed the similarity Tuesday and was neither
amused nor happy.
</P>
<P>
   He was more upset than at any time during his tenure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like going in there and apologizing to the team,''
Williams said after Bobby Ayala blew another gasket and two
subsequent relievers were nearly as ineffective in Seattle's
11-walk, 10-4 loss to the Cleveland Indians before 43,113 fans at
Jacobs Field.
</P>
<P>
   The game was the opener of a grueling nine-game road trip
against the three best teams in the American League.
</P>
<P>
   Although starter Bill Swift absorbed a large portion of an
Indians assault led by Manny Ramirez, who went 4-for-4 and drove in
five runs, Williams directed his postgame wrath at the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm embarrassed,'' he said. ``The (relief) staff didn't give
the club a chance to win the game after we battled back. This was a
big game for the team, an important road trip for us. I'm very
disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   The 11 free passes issued by Seattle pitchers were the most in
one game since the 10 walks given to the Indians on April 14,
Williams' first game after replacing Nardi Contreras.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no excuse for that, not this late in the season,'' he
said. ``I don't blame Swifty as much as the others. I didn't like
what I saw (from the relievers).''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said there are games when the starter is going to
struggle, as Swift did last night. In those games, he believes the
relievers must step up.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to come in, show some pride and get the job done,''
he bristled. ``I'm more than a little disgusted. More than I've
been, or at least shown, all season.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners, who had their four-game winning streak end with a
resounding thud, took a 1-0 in the first inning on Alex Rodriguez's
RBI double, but fell behind in the fourth when Cleveland scored
five two-out runs.
</P>
<P>
   Down but not out, the Mariners scored twice in the fifth and
once in the sixth, on David Segui's 17th homer of the season,
slicing the deficit to two runs. They never got closer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a chance to get back in the game and then had no
chance,'' Williams added.
</P>
<P>
   Ayala pitched a scoreless fifth inning, but got hammered for
three hits and three runs in the sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We closed the gap, but couldn't hold the game in check,''
manager Lou Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, changing the subject somewhat, he said, ``I'm looking
forward to seeing some of our young pitchers, I can tell you
that.''
</P>
<P>
   That won't happen for another week, when rosters can be
expanded.
</P>
<P>
   Mac Suzuki will join the team from Class AAA Tacoma. So will
Brett Hinchcliffe and perhaps Freddy Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly what happens to Ayala is anyone's guess, but Piniella
seems to be running out of patience.
</P>
<P>
   Finally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think his record (1-9 with a 7.16 ERA) speaks for itself,''
Piniella said. ``It hasn't been the best of years.''
</P>
<P>
   Ayala, however, is signed through next season.
</P>
<P>
   Swift doesn't have the luxury of a contract beyond this season
and several of his recent starts have been clunkers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what's going on,'' the right-hander said. ``I
pitch well for three or four innings then all hell breaks loose.
It's hard to say what is happening, but I'm not really
concentrating the way I should.''
</P>
<P>
   At least he has an excuse.
</P>
<P>
   For the second straight start, Swift (10-8) had to contend with
the after-effects of Benadryl, a medication he needed to combat two
outbreaks of hives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if that's the reason, but my energy level has
been down,'' he said. ``(The medication) makes me drowsy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indians pounded him with two-out thunder.
</P>
<P>
   The American League Central Division leaders scored their first
run with two outs in the third inning _ after Swift retired the
first two batters _ and erupted for five more runs in the fourth.
This time, they had two outs and one runner on base before Kenny
Lofton doubled over Ken Griffey Jr.'s head, Omar Vizquel and Brian
Giles singled and Ramirez drove his 31st homer of the season into
the left-center field bleachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like they had a lot of two-out hits,'' Swift said.
</P>
<P>
   Eight to be precise and nearly as many two-out walks _ six.
</P>
<P>
   The last two, compliments of Heathcliff Slocumb in the seventh,
forced in Cleveland's final run and put the Indians into
double-digits in runs for the first time in its past 34 games.
</P>
<P>
   But they paid a price.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Travis Fryman, who went 0-for-5, tried to help
with his defense in the eighth inning. He raced toward the stands
attempting to snag Joey Cora's pop fly, but went head-over-heels
after colliding with the rolled-up tarp, suffering a broken nose
and a cut above his left eye.
</P>
<P>
   He was taken to a local hospital for precaution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
