<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAY LOST AMONG COLORFUL SIGNEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND, Wash. _ Chris Gray could be called the forgotten
Seahawk.
</P>
<P>
   That's unremembered as in this year's free-agent addition who
became a footnote because was he signed the same day as Pro Bowl
center Kevin Glover.
</P>
<P>
   That's forgettable because Gray is the only member of this
year's free-agent class who is not starting, a 305-pound runt in a
pick-of-the-litter group that includes running back Ricky Watters,
linebacker Darrin Smith, guard Brian Habib, punter Jeff Feagles and
Glover.
</P>
<P>
   Forgotten. Forgettable.
</P>
<P>
   That could sum up Gray, a journeyman guard who started 25 games
in five previous NFL seasons with the Miami Dolphins and Chicago
Bears. Except, that is, for one small detail: He just keeps doing
things that make it impossible to overlook him.
</P>
<P>
   Not the types of things that send fans into a frenzy or have
reporters hanging on his every word. But the types of things that
endure a player to his coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Like when backup centers Greg Bloedorn and Frank Beede went down
with knee injuries six days apart early in training camp. Gray was
pushed into the position during the preseason opener at Dallas and
has held it.
</P>
<P>
   Or like when Washington State rookie Jason McEndoo was
struggling with the snapping for field goals and PATs. The coaches
handed the ball to Gray and he hasn't given it back _ a big factor
in McEndoo being released this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we first started working with Chris, he was kind of
shaky,'' special teams coach Pete Rodriguez said Tuesday. ``He got
progressively better. And last week, all of a sudden, it was like
the light bulb went on and he snapped perfect in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Gray has taken it all in stride, and with a somewhat whimsical
outlook:
</P>
<P>
   -- On being the team's other free-agent signing.
</P>
<P>
   ``After me, all the big-time guys signed,'' Gray said.
</P>
<P>
   It must have been the allure of getting to play with Chris Gray.
</P>
<P>
   ``That must be what it was,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he was smiling.
</P>
<P>
   -- On becoming a center out of necessity in the middle of a
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of surprised,'' he said. ``I have a new respect for
the center position, I'll tell you that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm pretty well suited to play center.''
</P>
<P>
   -- On inheriting the snapping job after not doing it since his
second season with the Dolphins in 1994. If Gray had not snapped up
the job, the Seahawks would have been forced to use linebacker
Jason Kyle, a 242-pounder who does the long snapping for punts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had worked on it in Miami,'' Gray said. ``But they had a guy
there they signed just to snap. So I worked on it during the
offseason and in minicamps. I got fairly good at it then, but that
was a long time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   -- On playing with a large gash on the bridge of his nose _ the
one that develops from his helmet being pushed into face and finds
a way to bleed despite being covered by an extra-large protective
strip.
</P>
<P>
   ``This thing started back in college,'' said Gray, who was a
second-team All-American his senior season at Auburn.
</P>
<P>
   Turning to show his profile and emphasis the lump on his nose,
Gray offered, ``I guess you could call it a Seahawk beak.''
</P>
<P>
   Or a badge of honor for a lineman who plays the game with as
much intensity and tenacity as Gray.
</P>
<P>
   ``On game day when it gets busted open, it looks pretty good,''
Gray said. ``You should see some of the looks I get from defensive
linemen when they look up and see this thing all bloody.''
</P>
<P>
   In a word, it's unforgettable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
