<HEADLINE>
AT LONG LAST, AN UPGRADE AT SHORTSTOP FOR RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Far back in the franchise annals, as far back
as the Benji Gils and the Jeff Kunkels, as distant as the Dickie
Thon era and the Bucky Dent era, and even traversing in time past
the infamous Mendoza Line, the Texas Rangers have had this thing
with shortstops.
</P>
<P>
   As great a career as Bert Campaneris had, Campy hit only .230
when he played shortstop for the Rangers in the late 1970s. Kunkel,
a No. 1 draft pick, spent parts of seven seasons at short here and
batted .224.
</P>
<P>
   The Mendoza Line, baseball's benchmark of hitting futility, as
originally defined by George Brett, was based on Mario Mendoza,
Rangers shortstop, 1981-82.
</P>
<P>
   With all due respects, therefore, to Dent and to Toby Harrah,
who both manned the position with distinction while here, it's not
exactly like Royce Clayton has a rich legacy to follow.
</P>
<P>
   All the more reason, however, to marvel at Clayton.
</P>
<P>
   The newest of the Rangers shortstops has quickness. He has a
cannon of a throwing arm. He has the range of a guard dog. He has a
lively bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the time he's been here,'' general manager Doug Melvin
said, opting for understatement, ``I think you can say he's done
pretty well.''
</P>
<P>
   You can say more, but anything Melvin says might be held against
him when he sits down with Clayton's agent after the season. Free
agent-eligible Clayton is a keeper, and at such a talent-thin
position, the Rangers need to make signing him a foremost
off-season priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want energy at that position,'' continued Melvin, who made
the trade with St. Louis that brought Clayton and (wince) Todd
Stottlemyre. ``Not to take anything away from Kevin Elster, who did
a great job for us in '96, but Royce brings that level of energy.''
</P>
<P>
   It isn't only Melvin and Rangers fans who have noticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents have been in town and they say they haven't seen me
smile like this in an awfully long time,'' Clayton said.
</P>
<P>
   The irony in Royce Clayton's eight-year big-league career was
that he had grown up always wanting to be like Ozzie Smith. His
bedroom back in Southern California had an Ozzie poster on the
wall. Ozzie is why he became a shortstop, Royce says.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin remembers going to Playa del Rey, Calif., to scout the
young St. Bernard High School prospect. When the team took the
field, Clayton raced out to shortstop and duplicated Ozzie's
trademark flip.
</P>
<P>
   In Clayton's ninth professional season, however, the dream
turned into an ugly reality. The great Jim Murray, who passed away
last week, wrote about it once under the headline, ``Be careful
what you wish for.''
</P>
<P>
   It chronicled the trade that sent young Clayton from the San
Francisco Giants to the Cardinals. Clayton was anointed Smith's
successor. The problem was, Ozzie wasn't ready to go anywhere,
especially quietly.
</P>
<P>
   ``No man should be put in that position,'' Clayton told Murray
back then. ``The crowds were the worst. You expect to be booed on
the road. But I was getting booed at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith turned an obvious chilly shoulder to his announced
successor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't easy,'' Clayton says now. ``It was tough on
everybody, including my family and fiancee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could have been something that really set my career back.
But I was able to battle through it. I think, in the end, I really
grew up as a person and as a player by having to deal with that.''
</P>
<P>
   By most standards, Clayton, now 28, bridged the transition more
than capably for the Cardinals. After a .277 average in his first
season, Clayton made the National League All-Star team in 1997. No
NL shortstop fielded more chances (699).
</P>
<P>
   That one statistic says all that Rangers fans need to know about
Clayton. Elster, his predecessor, alas, will be remembered here
more for the ground balls he didn't get to, rather than the ones he
did.
</P>
<P>
   The upgrade is startling. Nary a home night has gone by where
stadium announcer Chuck Morgan hasn't toasted a Clayton defensive
play with the ``SportsCenter'' theme.
</P>
<P>
   The talk in St. Louis was that Clayton was still pressing, that
he was hurrying plays and that he wasn't going to be worth what he
would be asking for in free agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to comment on anything Tony La Russa might have
said,'' Clayton says, simply. ``If the Cardinals feel they were
doing me a favor by trading me, then I thank them very much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know, though, that it's been a blessing to be here in a
place where I feel I'm needed and where the fans have welcomed me
so graciously.''
</P>
<P>
   In St. Louis, for obvious reasons, Clayton never got to repeat
his high school Ozzie Smith flip.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he helps us win the division,'' GM Melvin said, ``maybe
I'll do the flip.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
