<HEADLINE>
BIGWIGS COURTED IN SEARCH FOR GM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Los Angeles Dodgers' search for a new general
manager has stepped up, with GMs from the past two World Series
champions part of the interview process.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Watson, who helped lead the New York Yankees to a title in
1996 despite the presence of high-profile owner George
Steinbrenner, met with Dodgers president Bob Graziano Tuesday and
watched the game against Montreal in the private box of interim GM
Tom Lasorda.
</P>
<P>
   Watson, who resigned from his Yankees position before this
season, refused to discuss the interview with Graziano and Lasorda.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Graziano will meet with Dave Dombrowski, general manager
of the Florida Marlins, who won the World Series last year. During
the Dodgers' visit to Florida last week, Lasorda met informally
with Dombrowski, a favorite of the team's new owners at Fox.
</P>
<P>
   But Watson brought excellent credentials to the interview. He is
a Los Angeles-area native and has run the baseball operation in New
York, the No.1 market in major-league baseball. He is a longtime
major-leaguer who began his post-playing career as an assistant GM
with the Houston Astros.
</P>
<P>
   Watson is also the only African-American to have interviewed.
Another candidate, Omar Minaya, the assistant GM and head of
international scouting for the New York Mets, is Latino.
</P>
<P>
   __ Valdes update: Injured right-hander Ismael Valdes will make a
second rehabilitation start Thursday at Class-A San Bernardino
against the Lancaster JetHawks.
</P>
<P>
   The club hopes Valdes would be ready to join the rotation after
missing a month with a strained muscle in his left side. However,
during his first rehab start last Friday for Class-A Vero Beach,
Fla., Valdes developed a blister on the index finger of his
pitching hand and was limited to 47 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't in good conscience put him in a big-league game
after just 47 pitches,'' said Dodgers manager Glenn Hoffman. ``He
is pain-free, but we need to get a better look at the total
picture. We need to see him pitch out of certain situations, throw
all his pitches in tough spots. You can't just figure he will do
all those things.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Hot Hubbard: After going 4 for 9 on the recent trip, Trenidad
Hubbard was given the start in left field Tuesday night against
right-hander Mike Thurman. Matt Luke, who normally would start in
left as part of a lefty/righty platoon, batted .091 (1 for 11) on
the trip. Since Luke's season average peaked at .337 at July 4, he
has gone 13 for 96 (.135) with five homers and 10 RBI.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
