<SLUG> BC-RANGERS-TIGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOTTLEMYRE STRUGGLES AGAIN IN RANGERS LOSS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Texas Rangers general manager Doug Melvin
described right-hander Todd Stottlemyre as a ``bulldog'' upon
acquiring the 33-year-old pitcher on July 31.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers await Stottlemyre's bite.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre, who earlier this season served as the anchor of the
Cardinals' rotation before a five-player trade delivered him to
Arlington, recorded only 10 outs before his early dismissal during
the Rangers' 8-7 defeat to the Tigers on Tuesday night at The
Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre (3-2) surrendered five runs on eight hits _ six of
those for extra bases _ during 3 1/3 innings and shackled the
Rangers with a four-run deficit.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers nearly overcame Stottlemyre's performance and a
costly, seventh-inning mistake on the bases by second baseman Luis
Alicea with a three-run ninth inning. Tigers right-hander Doug
Jones, though, induced a game-ending ground ball from third baseman
Todd Zeile to preserve the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the Rangers will enter Wednesday's game with a 3 1/2-game
deficit to the American League West-leading Angels, who defeated
the Yankees, 7-6, Tuesday night in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've looked at tape,'' said Stottlemyre, who entered Tuesday
night's appearance with a 3-1 record largely on the strength of 43
runs scored by the Rangers during his previous four starts. ``It's
nothing mechanical. It's nothing physical. It's just a matter of
making the pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is more frustrated than I am right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre's most significant achievement of the evening
occurred during the third inning. The right-hander retired
designated hitter Frank Catalanotto, second baseman Damion Easley
and first baseman Tony Clark in order. It represented only the
second time in the 26 innings started by Stottlemyre that the
opponent did not produce a base runner.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre continues to throw well during his bullpen sessions
between starts, yet it does not translate into success when it
matters most. Nevertheless, manager Johnny Oates remains
encouraged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect his next start to be outstanding,'' Oates said.
``I've seen him pitch before. I've seen him get people out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers tagged Stottlemyre for three first-inning runs as
four of the first five batters reached on doubles. Catcher Paul
Bako's fourth-inning, run-scoring triple represented the end of the
line for Stottlemyre.
</P>
<P>
   ``We dug a hole and couldn't get out of it,'' Oates said. ``We
did some things wrong. We had a couple of mental mistakes out there
and missed a couple of signs that hurt us.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps no mental mistake hurt more than Alicea's.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers entered the bottom of the seventh inning staring at
an 8-2 deficit, but Tigers manager Buddy Bell removed right-hander
Brian Powell (3-4) after shortstop Royce Clayton and center fielder
Tom Goodwin reached safely.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Matt Anderson promptly issued a walk to Alicea to
load the bases, and left fielder Rusty Greer followed with a
two-run single. Anderson, though, retired right fielder Juan
Gonzalez on strikes for the inning's first out, which brought first
baseman Will Clark to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Bell summoned left-hander Sean Runyan from the bullpen for the
lefty-lefty matchup, and Clark responded with a well-hit ball. The
line drive, though, found the glove of right fielder Juan
Encarnacion.
</P>
<P>
   Alicea, the runner at second, did not expect the ball to be
caught and became easy prey for the inning-ending, rally-killing
double play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took a chance where I shouldn't have,'' Alicea said. ``We
were down four runs there. I was too aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers scored three times during their final at-bat, which
included a sacrifice fly by Gonzalez and a two-run homer by Clark.
Yet, Jones and the Tigers survived.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Rangers await the time when Stottlemyre will
pitch more like a No. 1 starter than a journeyman toting a 7.03
earned-run average.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still believe the next one,'' Oates said, ``will be the one
where he goes out and pitches a masterpiece.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
