<HEADLINE>
PETTITTE TIPOFF?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jim Kaat, an announcer for the MSG network which
broadcasts New York Yankees games, said Monday night during the
telecast he thought Yankees pitcher Andy Pettitte might have been
tipping his pitches in the Angels' five-run seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Some Yankees scoffed but not ex-Angel Chili Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The camera panned in on (hitting coach) Rod (Carew) and showed
him talking to hitters and making a motion with his hand like he
was pitching,'' Davis said. ``Rod's very good at doing that.
They've got a couple guys over there that are very smart like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis, however, said that if the Angels were picking something
up with Pettitte, there was nothing wrong with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not considered cheating,'' he said. ``Whatever experience
you have, you should use to your advantage. If I was good at
picking up pitches, believe me, my hitters would know about it.''
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!Vintage McDowell: &UR; !off! &LR;  Pitcher Jack McDowell is 2-0
with a 1.29 ERA since his return from the disabled list, including
Monday's victory over the Yankees. Is he a different pitcher?
</P>
<P>
   He's says no, that he still throws the same pitches. The
difference is in his approach, now that his elbow allows him only
to do so much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to be a maximum-effort pitcher,'' McDowell said. ``I
would throw every ball as hard as I could.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, McDowell has to locate his pitches accurately and pitch
through the pain, so he doesn't throw as hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you didn't know he had arm problems, you'd think he's 100
percent healthy,'' shortstop Gary DiSarcina said. ``He's out there
pitching on guts, determination and guile. We have a lot of guys on
this team like that. Tim Salmon, guys that put whatever they have
on the line. It's been productive and inspirational.''
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!Playing with pain: &UR; !off! &LR;  The welt DiSarcina suffered on
his left shin Monday was as big as a golf ball and hurt so bad
DiSarcina said he thought he broke his leg.
</P>
<P>
   But it was news to Angels manager Terry Collins. Before
Tuesday's game against the Yankees, Collins was asked how
DiSarcina's shin was, and he looked puzzled. When told that
DiSarcina fouled a ball off his leg in batting practice Monday,
Collins said: ``He disguised it very well.''
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina said Tuesday his shin felt like ``somebody hit me with
a sledgehammer,'' but it didn't keep him out of the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!Positive sign: &UR; !off! &LR;  Pitcher Ken Hill threw 40 pitches
in a two-inning simulated game Tuesday and felt no problems with
his surgically repaired right elbow. He's scheduled to start Friday
in Boston.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
