<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS CLAIM CADARET FROM ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 BULLPEN-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The Texas Rangers got the second left-hander
they wanted for the bullpen, claiming veteran Greg Cadaret on
waivers from the Anaheim Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Cadaret is expected to join the Rangers on Wednesday. He teams
with Eric Gunderson to give the club two left-handed relievers for
the first time since Scott Bailes went on the disabled list on Aug.
1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scott Bailes' injury made us look for a left-hander,'' general
manager Doug Melvin said. ``It's evident the teams we just played _
Cleveland, Boston and New York _ have some key left-handed
hitters.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers didn't have a left-handed reliever who could get
them out on a consistent basis. Left-handed batters are hitting
.317 (39-for-123) against Gunderson.
</P>
<P>
   Cadaret, 36, was attractive because he held left-handers to a
.230 (14-for-61) average while with the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a low left-handed batting average,'' Melvin said.
``He's got a good arm, he's durable, and he can fill a couple of
roles.''
</P>
<P>
   Cadaret, who will be owed almost $47,000 of his $250,000 salary
by the Rangers, is 38-32 with a 3.98 earned-run average in a
10-year career with seven teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cadaret is one of those guys who hangs around for a reason,''
manager Johnny Oates said. ``He gets people out. He's a veteran who
knows how to pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates hasn't decided what role Cadaret will fill, whether he'll
be the late-inning left-handed specialist or if he'll enter the
game sooner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see what works out for us,'' Oates said. ``We'll play it
by ear for a few days and see what works.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates is glad to have Cadaret because his moves were limited
with one left-hander.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's certain things you can't do,'' Oates said. ``You've
only got so many bullets to fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Cadaret was released even though he pitched effectively for the
Angels. He was 1-2 with a 4.14 ERA and one save in 39 games when he
was designated for assignment on Aug. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, because of the waiver process, he now could help the
team trying to catch the Angels in the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't control who a player goes to,'' Melvin said.
``That's just a gamble you take.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin said he believed the Rangers had a good chance to acquire
Cadaret when the Angels placed him on unconditional release
waivers. If more than one team claims a player, he goes to the team
with the worse record, and Texas has the worst mark among teams in
serious playoff contention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the last potential playoff team,'' Melvin said. ``I
didn't think there would be a team behind us that would claim
him.''  &LR; tagtop:Simon Gonzalez, (817) 390-7760
 &LR; tagbottom:''gonzalez\Nstar-telegram.com''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-26-98 0118EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
