<HEADER>
A2279 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      08-26 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
The Astros have been waiting for the Mike Hampton of old to
resurface, and maybe they still are. In the meantime, they'll be
more than happy to settle for performances like the one they
received from the player wearing No. 10 on Tuesday night at the
Astrodome.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The finesse-pitching ground-ball artist turned into a miniature
version of Randy Johnson, striking out a career-high 12 batters and
seemingly willing the Astros to a 3-2 victory over the Atlanta
Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton, who was hardly wild despite walking five batters, kept
the Braves off-balance with a brilliant array of pitches, most of
which had dazzling movement. The nifty performance helped the
Astros extend their winning streak to five games and snapped a
four-game streak for the Braves, whom the Astros are chasing along
with San Diego for the best record in the National League.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you beat the Braves, it's never easy,'' Astros
manager Larry Dierker said. ``This was a good win for our team but
especially for Mike Hampton. He had extra-good stuff and a lot of
movement on his pitches. He pitched a really powerful game.
Hopefully, this will start him on a streak of good pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Tuesday, Hampton's best streak had been for no-decisions
_ three in a row and six in his past nine starts. To his credit,
Hampton has pitched well enough to keep the Astros in most of his
starts (the Astros are 17-9 in games he has started), but he hasn't
always been able to hang around long enough to reap the benefits.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't the case Tuesday, when he delivered a workhorse
effort, lasting eight innings and throwing a season-high 130
pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really care if I get a win as long as the team wins,''
said Hampton (10-6). ``There have been times when I felt like I've
let the lead slip away because I wasn't maintaining my focus, and
that's something that upset me.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I was able to stay focused (Tuesday), and I felt good even
after I left the game. I didn't know how many pitches I had thrown
until they told me. This is a good feeling; I'm not going to lie
and say it isn't. Any time you go eight innings and the team wins,
you feel good.''
</P>
<P>
   And as if the Braves hadn't struck out enough, Dierker brought
extra-fresh closer Billy Wagner from the bullpen to pitch the ninth
inning. Wagner, who hadn't pitched in five days, punched out three
of the four batters he faced to earn his 25th save. The 15 combined
strikeouts were the most in a game by the Astros this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, I probably would have walked a couple of guys if I
had gone this long without pitching,'' Wagner said. ``I guess
getting hit in the head has made me focus a little more on where
I'm throwing those pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   After scoring 60 runs in their previous nine games, the Astros'
offense cranked out a mere three, but that was enough to put
Hampton back in the win column.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did too well for us to let him down,'' Astros center
fielder Carl Everett said. ``He did an outstanding job. It was
unbelievable watching the way his ball moved from center field. If
we had lost this game for him and gave him another no-decision, it
would have looked bad on our part (as hitters).''
</P>
<P>
   So Everett took matters into his own hands in the sixth. His RBI
double off Braves starter Kevin Millwood (14-8) broke a tie at 2
and gave the Astros a final push toward their 15th victory in their
past 19 games. Everett's clutch double scored Jeff Bagwell, who
singled to lead off the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Everett, who began the season as the Astros' fourth outfielder,
has become one of the best run producers on the team. The talented
center fielder has 68 RBIs, 11 more than his previous career high.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like pressure,'' Everett said. ``A lot of guys don't, but I
do. Whether I succeed or fail, I enjoy being in those situations.''
</P>
<P>
   As fluid as the Astros' offense was during their three-game romp
in Chicago, it didn't flow from all faucets. Derek Bell and
Bagwell, who were a combined 3-for-24 against the Cubs, opened
their offensive valves in the first inning of Tuesday's game to
give the Astros an early lead.
</P>
<P>
   Bell whacked a two-out double into the left-center-field gap,
and Bagwell drove him home with a single up the middle. The Astros
have scored in the first inning in each of their past four games.
</P>
<P>
   They added a run in the second when Ricky Gutierrez hit a
leadoff single, advanced to third and scored when Hampton grounded
into a double play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty much everyone played well in Chicago except Derek and
I,'' said Bagwell, who was 2-for-4 on Tuesday. ``But that's just
the way this team is. There's a different hero every night, and
that's what makes us so good.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton struck out five in the first three innings, but the
Braves struck back in the fourth. Catcher Javy Lopez blasted a
leadoff homer into the center-field seats to pull the visitors to
within a run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made that pitch where I wanted to make it,'' Hampton said.
``But Javy's a good hitter, and he was able to get the good part of
the bat on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopez, who has a .346 career batting average against Hampton,
drew a leadoff walk in the sixth and scored on a double by Michael
Tucker, who was a late lineup replacement for left fielder Danny
Bautista.
</P>
<P>
   That was pretty much the end of the Braves' offensive
production. They managed only a pair of infield singles after
Tucker's double, and five of the six Braves went down swinging _
three courtesy of Wagner, who didn't even have to unveil his new
and improved slider.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Catcher) Brad (Ausmus) felt that I had a good fastball and
that I was locating it really well, and he didn't see any reason to
mess around with anything else,'' Wagner said. ``I was happy with
the way I threw the ball. I wasn't hitting 100 mph (on the radar
gun), but I had good location.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost as good as the Astros, who are in the process of
establishing themselves as perhaps the team to beat in the NL.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
