<HEADLINE>
RANGERS MANAGER GOING WITH `HOT-HAND' THEORY
</HEADLINE>
 NOTES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The at-bats normally reserved for injured
designated hitter Lee Stevens will continue to be distributed to
``the hot hand until you get burned,'' Texas Rangers manager Johnny
Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   That explains the presence of reserve outfielder Roberto Kelly
in the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly, who Tuesday night drove in the Rangers' first run with
his second-inning double, entered the game hitting .500 (10-for-20)
with four home runs and nine runs batted in during his past seven
games.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly became the player of choice as reserve outfielder Mike
Simms began to slide. Simms entered Tuesday night's game hitless in
his past 18 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly replaced right fielder Juan Gonzalez in the outfield, and
the latter served as the designated hitter because of tightness in
his right calf.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kelly is hot right now, so he's getting the playing time,''
Oates said. ``That's usually the way the manager goes. Simms was
probably the MVP during our last road trip. Since then, he's cooled
off a little bit.'' BAILES HAS TORN ROTATOR CUFF
</P>
<P>
   The magnetic resonance imaging test of Scott Bailes' left
shoulder revealed a partial tear of left-hander's rotator cuff.
</P>
<P>
   Bailes, who went on the 15-day disabled list Aug. 1 with
bursitis in the shoulder, will continue his rehabilitation program.
Bailes received a cortisone shot yesterday and does not plan to
throw again until Friday at the earliest.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's confusing to me is that my arm feels great today,''
Bailes said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers expressed hope that rest and rehabilitation will
allow Bailes to pitch by early September.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Scott would like to get through September without
surgery,'' Oates said. SEARCHING FOR ANGELS
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Charlie O'Brien (fracture, right thumb) began his
medical rehabilitation assignment Tuesday night with Double-A
Midland of the Texas League.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels expect to reinstate O'Brien by Sept. 1, although the
catcher could rejoin the team before then. The Angels acquired
O'Brien July 30 from the White Sox. BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ The Rangers' 12-10 victory Sunday against the Yankees scored
the highest Nielsen rating for Fox Sports Southwest in the Fort
Worth/Dallas area since the network began tracking the figures. The
telecast registered a 6.2 total television rating and an 11.9 cable
television rating. That surpassed the previous mark of 5.9 total
television rating (11.3 cable rating), established Aug. 4 when
right-hander Todd Stottlemyre made his debut with the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Rangers scheduled shortstop Royce Clayton as the guest for
Friday's ``Fort Worth Star-Telegram'' Chat Room. The session,
scheduled for 2-2:15 p.m., can be accessed through the Rangers'
Internet Web site at www.texasrangers.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ The organization promoted right-hander David Manning to
Triple-A Oklahoma from Class-A Charlotte. Manning replaces
right-hander Terry Clark in the RedHawks' rotation. Clark went on
the disabled list this week. FARM REPORT
</P>
<P>
   _ Triple-A Oklahoma (Pacific Coast League): Left-hander Ricky
Pickett, a product of Eastern Hills High School, earned his fourth
victory in five decisions as the RedHawks (72-58) defeated Omaha,
9-8, on Monday. Pickett (6-4, 3.13) surrendered four runs on nine
hits and recorded four strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   _ Double-A Tulsa (Texas League): The Drillers (74-61) defeated
Shreveport, 8-5, as shortstop Kelly Dransfeldt went 3-for-4 with a
home run and two runs batted in.
</P>
<P>
   _ Class-A Charlotte (Florida State League): Left fielder Craig
Monroe went 2-for-4 with his 15th home run and drove in two runs as
the Rangers (74-50) beat Sarasota, 9-2.
</P>
<P>
   _ Class-A Savannah (South Atlantic League): Third baseman Travis
Hafner hit his 16th home run and drove in two runs, but the Sand
Gnats (62-74) lost to Augusta, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pulaski (Appalachian League, rookie): Right-hander Daniel
Boublis (4-7, 4.74) allowed one unearned run on four hits in seven
innings as the Rangers (28-36) defeated Bluefield, 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gulf Coast (Gulf Coast League): Catcher Fredrick Torres threw
out three of four attempting to steal, but the Rangers (32-25) lost
to the Red Sox, 6-1.
</P>
</TEXT>
