<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-GIANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS DEFEAT METS, 7-3 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Starting pitching is supposed to separate the
Mets from the Giants and the Cubs in the National League wild-card
race.
</P>
<P>
   But Rick Reed, one of the team's most reliable starters, is
struggling, and that's trouble for a team trying to reach the
post-season.
</P>
<P>
   Reed was hit hard again on Tuesday night in the New York Mets'
7-3 loss to the San Francisco Giants. It was the third consecutive
loss for the Mets, who lead Chicago and San Francisco by a game in
the wild-card race with eight games left on this West Coast trip. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reed (15-8) could not hold the three-run lead Mike Piazza had
given him with a first-inning home run. Reed would allow two homers
himself, not to mention seven runs in five-plus innings, and would
wind up being outpitched by the 24-year-old right-hander Russ Ortiz
(2-3), who now has two major league victories _ both against the
the Mets in the last three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza's home run was his third in the last six days and his
24th of the season. It followed an error by the former Met Jeff
Kent, whose misplay on a hard-hit John Olerud grounder turned a
potential inning-ending double play into a big rally.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Reed has 15 victories this season, he has been
struggling. In his last three starts _ all victories _ Reed had
allowed 13 runs and 26 hits in 20 innings, for an earned run
average of 5.85. More alarming, the veteran right-hander had
surrendered five home runs in those three starts.
</P>
<P>
   So, it was not all that surprising when Barry Bonds _ the first
player in major league history to record 400 homers to go with 400
stolen bases _ launched No. 401 to deep right-center in the bottom
of the first to make the score 3-1. It could have been 3-2 if
Piazza had not thrown out Marvin Benard trying to steal second one
batter earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the Giants began to chip away at the Mets lead. Benard
(who had hits in his first three at-bats) doubled home a run in the
third with a little help from Todd Hundley, who bobbled the ball in
left-center field, to make it 3-2. Then Ellis Burks drove home the
tying run in the fourth with a sacrifice fly after back to back
singles from Jeff Kent and Charlie Hayes. And the score was tied,
3-3.
</P>
<P>
   In the bottom of the fifth, the Giants took the lead on a Kent
sacrifice fly, which followed an infield single by Benard that Reed
could not come up with along the first-base line, a hit batsman
(Rich Aurilia) and a Bonds groundout.
</P>
<P>
   On Reed's first pitch in the sixth, Ellis Burks launched his
18th homer of the season _ and just his second with the Giants _
for a 5-3 lead. After allowing back to back singles to the next two
batters, Bill Mueller and Brian Johnson, Reed bounced a throw to
first on an Ortiz sacrifice, Carlos Baerga could not make the pick,
the bases were loaded and Reed was headed for the showers.
</P>
<P>
   Reed was charged with 10 hits and 7 runs in five-plus innings.
He has now allowed seven homers in his last four starts, and has an
era of 7.20 over that span.
</P>
<P>
   Benard greeted the left-hander Dennis Cook with a sacrifice fly
for a 6-3 lead. Then, Cook walked Aurilia to load the bases for
Bonds, who lined a hard single to right on a 1-0 pitch for another
run to make it 7-3. And, even though Cook eventually left the bases
loaded, the Mets were about to squander a solid opportunity in the
wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   The schedule does not favor the Mets. They have only 9 of their
30 remaining games at home, compared to 11 of 30 for Chicago and 18
of 30 for San Francisco. Also, the Mets have seven games left with
the first-place Braves, a team they have not beaten this season,
including the final three of the season in Atlanta. The Cubs,
meanwhile, finish the season with three games in Houston, the team
they trail in the N.L. Central.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants will play their final three games on the road, too,
but in Colorado against the struggling Rockies. Meanwhile, the
Giants play only four more games with teams over .500, while the
Mets have 15 and the Cubs just 7.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
