<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GIULIANI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI URGES RESTRAINT ON CLINTON SCANDAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani of New York City said on
Tuesday night that the Republican Party should not try to
capitalize on the moral implications of President Clinton's
relationship with a White House intern, and he expressed his hope
that the affair would not injure the office of the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's remarks, at a fundraising event sponsored by
Wisconsin's Republican Party, drew applause from just 2 of about
100 people present, and then only briefly.
</P>
<P>
   The issue came up after the mayor, who is in the Midwest to
raise his national profile, had finished his familiar account of
the resurrection of New York City under his watch and offered to
answer questions.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said he thought that Kenneth Starr, the Whitewater
independent counsel, was right to focus on accusations of
obstruction of justice and perjury.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't think that it's our role to get involved in the
president's private life,'' the mayor said. ``And I think that as a
political party it would be a very big mistake if we emphasized
that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-26-98 0145EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980826.0033 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 01:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2297 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     08-26 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
HE liked winning a division in his first try, but Larry Dierker
didn't especially like how he won it. Last year's Central Division
champion Astros were only 84-78, hardly a record worthy of playoff
participation.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker, as old-school as they come when it comes to baseball,
wasn't comfortable backing in with a record that in the old days
could have relegated the Astros to second-division status. Bogus
was bogus, and he knew it, although he was careful not to denigrate
his team's accomplishments publicly.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the Astros hadn't won anything in 11 seasons. Bogus
would be better than nothing.
</P>
<P>
   These Astros, in contrast, needn't worry about the skipper's
sense of propriety or aesthetics. They are going to repeat as
division champions with a record eminently worthy of such a
distinction. A second victory over the Braves tonight, after
Tuesday's 3-2 beaut, and they will be 84-50, meaning they could
blow 27 of the last 28 and still improve on their finish of a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   You know, I sort of like their chances.
</P>
<P>
   For that matter, I like their chances of winning 100, something
they have never done before.
</P>
<P>
   But why stop there? There's only one truly magic number left.
From this day forward, the Astros' primary, all-consuming goal
should be to win exactly one more game than the Braves. Just on
principle, to show they can. The home-field advantage in baseball
isn't that big a deal.
</P>
<P>
   While this would have been an absurd objective when the season
began, a lot has changed since then. As highly regarded as Moises
Alou was when he arrived, lugging his world-championship ring and
RBI-laden bat, who could have imagined that he would whack 38 home
runs _ before September? As for Randy Johnson's coming, that was
out there somewhere beyond unfathomable.
</P>
<P>
   Even after his five starts, I'm not sure I fully believe he's
here.
</P>
<P>
   No, opportunities such as the current season presents don't come
along very often. In Houston's case, they apparently come along
once every 37 years. So the moment must be seized, and that means
not only winning the Central, which is already a foregone
conclusion, or chasing down the Padres but catching _ and passing _
Atlanta, too.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, they've got four games left against the Braves.
They're four wins behind the Braves. Nothing complicated about the
math, is there? It ain't calculus.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros have Atlanta's undivided attention, believe me. The
way the playoffs shake down today, with the Astros having buried
the Cubs over the weekend, thereby giving the Mets a leg up in the
wild-card chase, an Atlanta-Houston rematch in the first round
beckons, and Mister Johnson will have had five days to rest up
before the opener.
</P>
<P>
   R.J. could probably pitch Game 5 as well, if necessary. Don't
think the Braves haven't already begun to contemplate same. And
they don't relish the scenario one bit.
</P>
<P>
   While Atlanta is always the team to beat, it almost always gets
beat at some point in the playoffs. The ``Team of the Nineties''
has won one World Series. Although this bunch of underachieving
Braves has yet to succumb in the preliminary round, they have also
never faced a team as armed and dangerous as Houston's straight out
of the chute.
</P>
<P>
   I suspect they'll be Cubs fans from here on out. They would
rather let San Diego worry about the Astros first.
</P>
<P>
   While the sweet-strokin' 'Stros weren't trying to send any loud
messages Atlanta's way _ or so they say _ they delivered one
anyway. Mike Hampton, Houston's self-proclaimed Little Unit, has
been the weakest link in the starting rotation of late, but he came
out with a serious mad on for the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   If his six-hit, career-high 12-whiff semi-masterpiece _
punctuated neatly by Billy Wagner's three-K ninth for his 25th save
_ is proof positive that Hampy has righted himself, the Astros
appear to have no obvious weakness. They're in good health and a
confident frame of mind.
</P>
<P>
   They know they are good. Damn good. It's not speculation,
conjecture or wishful thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing at a level we're capable of,'' Dierker said. ``I
don't think Atlanta is over there worrying too much right now about
losing one game, but I'm sure they realize we've improved a lot
since they knocked us out last year.''
</P>
<P>
   The three-game, over-almost-before-it-was-over division-series
sweep was indicative of the two teams' relative strengths in 1997.
Those Astros barely belonged on the same field with the Braves.
These Astros? They can beat Atlanta. They might not, but they can.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
