<DOCNO> NYT19980826.0038 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 01:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2306 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IS-YELTSIN-FINISHED?-     08-26 1375
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IS-YELTSIN-FINISHED?-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAS VADANYA, BORIS: IS YELTSIN KAPUT?  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This excellent, insightful 1,200-word ``separate buy'' profile of
Boris Yeltsin is from The Independent newspaper in London.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
fax her at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``a''
general news, ``i'' international news and ``k'' commentary news
files.)  
  
 By PHIL REEVES  
 c.1998 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The reign of ``Czar'' Boris Yeltsin has entered its
twilight.
</P>
<P>
   His television appearance Monday to explain why he had
reappointed a prime minister whom he sacked only five months ago
was not quite as humiliating as a prime-time confession to an
affair with a White House intern. But it was bad enough.
</P>
<P>
   His choice of a premier who is widely disliked, and whose name
is associated with fudge, economic decline, and cronyism, is a
personal defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin knows he will be seen as having buckled under the
pressure of a narrow clique of oligarchs who exploited the
privatization of state assets to build vast fortunes _ and
subsequently used them to pressure the Kremlin to defend their
interests.
</P>
<P>
   But the events of the last 48 hours may also mark a larger
watershed in the rule of Boris Yeltsin, a seven year helter-skelter
ride in which he has veered across the political spectrum, from
autocrat to rough-hewn democrat.
</P>
<P>
   The snowy-haired man who in 1991 stood on a tank outside the
White House, flourishing his democratic credentials in the face of
drunken Communist coup plotters, also launched war in Chechnya,
surrounded himself with hard-liners, and used tanks to bombard a
recalcitrant parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Exhausted by hard-living, heart trouble and the sheer enormity
of the task of trying to pilot the country through the post-Soviet
chaos, this same contradictory man may now have concluded that it
is time to ease his way out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like the president is starting to withdraw from
office step by step, handing over power to the heir,'' said his
arch-enemy Mikhail Gorbachev. For once, the former Soviet leader's
views did not sound purely like sour grapes.
</P>
<P>
   Boris Yeltsin loves power, and is a master at centralizing it on
the Kremlin. He is also incorrigibly unpredictable, whether it be
his ludicrous exploits _ drunkenly conducting an orchestra in
Berlin, pinching a secretary _ or in politics.
</P>
<P>
   He proved that yet again on Sunday, sacking his government at
the height of a fiscal crisis, adding political chaos and limbo to
the economic maelstrom. What he does today, he can _ and often does
_ undo tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Witness the case of Anatoly Chubais, his financial
troubleshooter whom he has sacked three times.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the zealous Sergei Kiriyenko was almost certainly
fired because he was construed as a threat to the oligarchs'
empires _ which are rooted in energy, banking and the media.
Several of them feared his government would allow their banks to
collapse, unable to pay vast foreign debts.
</P>
<P>
   But, having bankrolled Yeltsin's election campaign in 1996, they
appear to have called in the favor by demanding _ and getting _ a
compliant prime minister. (The country's most prominent oligarch,
Boris Berezovsky, Monday warmly welcomed the appointment of
Chernomyrdin, a development which his own newspaper _ Nezavisimaya
Gazeta _ foresaw with suspicious accuracy last week.)
</P>
<P>
   Yet signs are beginning to surface which suggest Yeltsin may now
have accepted his rule is winding down.
</P>
<P>
   The well-connected Ekho Moskvi radio station quoted sources
saying Chernomyrdin had insisted, as a condition of his return to
office, that he has the right to appoint the head of the ``power
ministries'' _ the Interior Ministry, the Federal Security
Services, and the Ministry of Defense.
</P>
<P>
   No one understands the importance of retaining control over the
security forces better than Yeltsin. If the story is true, then it
amounts to a significant reduction of his sweeping powers.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech to the nation Monday, the President clearly
anointed Chernomyrdin as his preferred successor in the election of
2000.
</P>
<P>
   His departure cannot come too soon for his growing army of
critics, whose ranks embrace the majority of Russians, almost all
the lower house of parliament, and plenty of enraged international
investors, who view Chernomyrdin's appointment as the kiss of death
to Russia's efforts to make the transition to a healthy market
economy.
</P>
<P>
   They point to the evidence that Yeltsin is no longer up to the
job. Although he appeared to recover well from the quintuple
coronary bypass surgery in late 1996, questions have repeatedly
arisen over Yeltsin's mental state.
</P>
<P>
   This is theme which has a bleak familiarity for the Siberian
former construction boss who these days appears far older than his
67 years. He has long been prone to bouts of depression and
withdrawal, and has openly admitted to ``dark thoughts.''
</P>
<P>
   A best-selling kiss'n'tell by his former bodyguard and estranged
friend Alexander Korzhakov claimed that in past years Yeltsin twice
tried to commit suicide by leaping into the Moscow River and
locking himself in a steam baths.
</P>
<P>
   There is certainly little doubt that he had a nervous breakdown
when he was banished by Mikhail Gorbachev to the Soviet
construction ministry in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Although he has retained a gift for springing political
surprises, as he demonstrated by his brilliantly judged last-minute
appearance at the reburial of the last czar, Nicholas, in St.
Petersburg last month, the number of embarrassments has grown with
the passage of time.
</P>
<P>
   During a trip to Sweden late last year, he appeared unsure of
where he was, and seemed to think Germany and Japan possessed
nuclear arsenals.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, he blotted his copybook again by appearing to refer
to the U.S. attacks on Sudan and Afghanistan as an ``act of
terrorism.'' (His spokesman hastily offered a watered-down version
of Russia's position).
</P>
<P>
   And only three days before the government announced its decision
to devalue the ruble last Monday, Yeltsin was publicly declaring
that devaluation ``won't happen... It is not a question of what I
think, of my own fantasies, of what I do or do not want to see. It
is all calculated.''
</P>
<P>
   True, this may have been a last-ditch _ and, as it turned out,
vain _ attempt to build confidence in the beleaguered currency; but
it is as likely that he was simply out of touch. After all, he had
been on vacation for five weeks despite a rapidly worsening
political crisis.
</P>
<P>
   How long he will stay in the Kremlin now depends on several
factors.
</P>
<P>
   He is mindful of his place in history which, while recognizing
his faults, will at least give him credit for holding the first
democratic transfer of power in Russia for 1,000 years.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving, he will want to be sure that Chernomyrdin (or a
similar ally) stands a strong chance of succeeding him, and will
defend the interests of the ruling elite that has evolved during
the Yeltsin years.
</P>
<P>
   This could conceivably mean striking a deal with the
Communist-nationalist opposition which includes rewriting the
constitution to allow the president to be appointed not by popular
vote, but by parliament.
</P>
<P>
   And much rests on the advice of the so-called Kremlin ``Family''
_ dominated by his daughter and image-maker, Tatyana, and his chief
of staff, Valentin Yumashev.
</P>
<P>
   As Russians look on with bewilderment as the Kremlin staggers
from one disaster to another, there are plenty who hope that the
old man's aides will now gently tap him on the shoulder, and point
to the door. &QL; 
