<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 01:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2307 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN     08-26 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISCUES HELP DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Even in the worst of seasons, the Los Angeles
Dodgers can always count on the Montreal Expos.
</P>
<P>
   Not the Expos in Montreal, the same team that swept the Dodgers
earlier this month. The Expos who rarely get it right when they
play in L.A.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers took advantage of several Expos blunders Tuesday
night to open a 12-game homestand with a 4-3 victory in front of
30,183 at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Young scored the winning run on a wild pitch in the seventh
inning that helped the Dodgers snap a three-game winning streak. It
also raised their record to 113-61 against the Expos at Dodger
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers even picked up a game on the New York Mets in the
wild card, drawing within seven games with 29 to play.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Mlicki (7-6) pitched 62/3 innings to move his record over
.500 for the first time this season. Former Dodger Wilton Guerrero
probably had the worst 4-for-5 game ever.
</P>
<P>
   For Guerrero, acquired by the Expos July 31 in the trade that
also sent three minor-league prospects to Montreal for left-hander
Carlos Perez and shortstop Mark Grudzielanek, the game started
badly. All could have been forgotten when Guerrero doubled off the
glove of left-fielder Trenidad Hubbard with one out in the ninth
off reliever Jeff Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   But Shaw, who allowed two ninth-inning homers in Atlanta the day
before, retired the final two batters to get his 38th save and 15th
as a Dodger.
</P>
<P>
   Guerrero's brother Vladimir hit his 32nd home run off Mlicki in
the fourth. And Grudzielanek made two errors at short after making
just two in his first 22 games with the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Guerrero opened the first inning with a single but immediately
got doubled off first on F.P. Santangelo. In the third, he stole
second, but when Charles Johnson's throw sailed into center, Raul
Mondesi already had the ball when Guerrero took off for third. He
was thrown out easily.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth inning, with Hubbard at first, Mondesi flied to
left. Hubbard tagged and raced to second. F.P. Santangelo's throw
had Hubbard beaten, but Guerrero failed to apply the tag in time.
</P>
<P>
   And with two outs in the same inning, Guerrero failed to catch
Johnson's pop-up to shallow right field that enabled the Dodgers'
third run to score.
</P>
<P>
   Because he was no longer one of their own, Dodgers fans cheered
Guerrero all night.
</P>
<P>
   But they found a target in Bobby Bonilla, who should have scored
from second on the pop-up. He was booed the rest of the night,
except for when he was lifted for pinch-runner Roger Cedeno after
walking with one out in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers were coming off a 2-5 road trip to Pittsburgh,
Florida and Atlanta and needed this kind of help.
</P>
<P>
   Guerrero's baseball instincts were criticized during his time
with the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Montreal manager Felipe Alou was far more interested in getting
the prospects acquiring Guerrero. He entered the game with a .239
average in 22 games since joining the Expos. He went 3 for 4. He
had an RBI single in the seventh that cut the Dodgers lead to 4-2.
Mlicki walked the next batter Santangelo and Scott Radinsky entered
the game.
</P>
<P>
   Pinch-hitter Shane Bennett popped to short to end the inning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
