<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980826.0044 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 01:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2314 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-K-STATE-TEX     08-26 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-K-STATE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH BISHOP, LOSING PASSE FOR KANSAS STATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A native Texan and infrequent follower of college football
during his formative years, Michael Bishop knew nothing of Kansas
State's dismal success rate preceding coach Bill Snyder's arrival
in Manhattan, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   He had no clue that, in Snyder's initial season, a 20-17 victory
against North Texas triggered a toppling of goal posts at KSU
Stadium because it ended a 30-game winless streak. It also marked
the Wildcats' lone victory of 1989, a season that ended with Kansas
State sporting the lowest winning percentage in the history of
Division I-A football (.380), with a career record of 299-501-39.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Bishop finished leading Blinn College to its second
consecutive junior college national championship in 1996, however,
such numbers seemed moot. Snyder provided his future quarterback
all the history lesson he would need by pointing to the Wildcats'
projected vacancy at the position, as well as a rapidly expanding
trophy case to house mementos from recent bowl excursions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew for the past couple of years, they'd had nine-win
seasons,'' Bishop said, reflecting on his initial reaction to being
courted by Kansas State. ``I knew coach Snyder would give me a
chance to play right away. Other than that, I didn't know all that
much. I just knew that, if I joined a competitive team, we'd have a
chance to win 10 or more games if we took advantage of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bishop and the Wildcats did that in 1997, setting a school
record for victories during an 11-1 season. Now, the Willis High
School graduate is considered the focal point of a Kansas State
team that returns 18 starters and is considered a contender for its
first national championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could be a pretty special season for us. The anticipation
hasn't always been there,'' said linebacker Travis Ochs, a
fifth-year senior. ``But everyone is excited knowing what this team
is capable of. And Michael Bishop is a big part of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Bishop's arrival, Snyder has tweaked his pro-style offense
to add more rollout passes and option plays. Receivers run deeper
routes in dropback situations, taking advantage of Bishop's arm
strength (19.5 yards per completion last season) and opening the
field for potential scrambles by the school's single-season record
holder for rushing yards (566) and rushing touchdowns (9) by a
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   More important, in Snyder's estimation, is his quarterback's
mental make-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael Bishop is extremely competitive in everything he
does,'' Snyder said. ``He wants to be the best player that he can
conceivably be, and that attitude rubs off on the team. Plus, he
can run and throw with the best of them. Those are the things I
love about Michael Bishop.''
</P>
<P>
   Bishop capped his first season in Division I-A by throwing for
317 yards and four touchdowns, as well as rushing for 73 yards, in
a 35-18 victory against Syracuse in the Tostitos Fiesta Bowl. The
performance earned him offensive player of the game honors and
improved his record to 35-1 as a college quarterback (24-0 at
Blinn, 11-1 at Kansas State).
</P>
<P>
   Bishop, however, views it as a tease for what is about to happen
now that he has a better grasp of the Wildcats' offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm a whole lot better than I was last year,'' Bishop
said. ``A year ago at this time, I was just playing on enthusiasm.
I hadn't learned the offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that I've been through spring (drills), I feel like I know
everything that I need to know to go out and lead my team. I feel I
have a great amount of talent and can make some key plays to take
my team to the next level.''
</P>
<P>
   Bishop's rapid emergence netted second-team all-conference
honors in 1997. It also earned him favorable comparisons to
Missouri quarterback Corby Jones, who rushed for 887 yards and
threw for 1,658 while being chosen by coaches as the league's top
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Both players return this season. Both are seniors. Who is
better?
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people ask me that,'' said Bishop, who ran for a
season-high 196 yards during last year's 41-11 rout of Missouri.
``I'd say we're equal until the Saturday we play each other (Nov.
21). Then we'll find out.''
</P>
<P>
   Missouri coach Larry Smith hedged, saying both players can
dominate a game with their arms, legs or leadership abilities. He
termed a comparison between Bishop and Jones ``about as close a
parallel as you can run between two players.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones agreed, but pointed to advantages on both sides of the
equation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been around the Division I game longer than Bishop. I've
captured the speed of the game better,'' Jones said. ``But he's
definitely got the edge in arm strength. He told me he can throw
the ball 93 yards in the air, and I'm lucky if I can get to 75. I
don't know how to compare and contrast us beyond that. I just know
he's fun to watch when he's not playing us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-26-98 0156EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
