<HEADER>
A2328 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-MERCURY_ROCKERS-A     08-26 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-MERCURY_ROCKERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN AID SAVES MERCURY  
 STEPANOVA'S LIFT OFF BENCH HELPS CLINCH BERTH IN FINALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The ruble might be rubble elsewhere, but in Phoenix
today, anything Russian is highly prized.
</P>
<P>
   Because a little-used Russian teenager came up as big as her
6-foot-8 future suggests and because Bridget Pettis gave Jennifer
Gillom a night off, the Mercury (21-12) ravaged the Cleveland
Rockers with a 25-4 second-half start Tuesday in advancing to the
WNBA championship series.
</P>
<P>
   The defending champion Houston Comets (29-3) come to the scene
of one of their rare regular season losses, America West Arena, for
the opener at 5 p.m. Thursday. Games 2 is on Saturday in Houston
and Game 3, if necessary, is on Tuesday in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always liked our chances physically in a back-to-back
because we have so many big bodies,'' said Mercury Coach Cheryl
Miller, who on a hunch selected the biggest, Stepanova, to replace
Michelle Griffiths when she signaled for a breather a little more
than four minutes after halftime.
</P>
<P>
   The 19-year-old, a spectator in Games 1 and 2 of the series,
responded with six points, two rebounds, a block, a steal and an
assist before returning to the bench for good with six fouls in
nine minutes. By then, the job was done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was waiting, always waiting,'' Stepanova, who had not played
since Aug. 14, said through her interpreter, Irina Viktorova. ``I
accumulated the anger and the enthusiasm, the energy. I was more
than ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Within its 25-4 run, the Mercury scored 19 consecutive points in
transforming a 35-32 halftime deficit into a 57-39 lead with 10:15
remaining. Stepanova fouled out with the lead still at 11, and the
Eastern Conference champion Rockers (21-12) could get no closer
than seven before falling 71-60, its fifth loss in six tries vs.
Phoenix this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the most effective nine minutes that I've seen,'' said
Miller, who has lost sleep recently trying to figure how to get the
raw but conscientious rookie into a game. ``Rebounding, scoring,
putting the pressure on. Maria's presence really allowed us to
relax offensively because all of a sudden, Cleveland is looking at
the 6-8 kid and she's mobile and she's moving around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marlies (Askamp, 6-5 backup center) has been playing well for
us, but the last couple of days, Maria's practice regimen has been
so good, I just couldn't waste it. To see that big grin on her
face, she was the absolute difference, her and Bridget Pettis.''
</P>
<P>
   As good as Stepanova in the short term, Pettis was from the
opening tip.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-9 shooting guard, who emerged from a midseason patch of 11
games in which she averaged only 6.5 points to score at 15.1 clip
in the regular season stretch, dropped a career-high-tying 27 on
Cleveland. She added a career-high 11 rebounds for her first WNBA
double-double, not to mention five assists, two steals and a block.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, Pettis throttled Michelle Edwards, whose 18 points
Monday were critical to a 67-66 Cleveland win. Edwards scored only
five, and 6-5 center Isabelle Fijalkowski (17) was the only Rocker
to reach double figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our backcourt needed to step up,'' Pettis said. ``Edwards did
a great job (Monday), and all I was thinking was contain them
defensively first, and then if I find my shot, knock it down. I
guess I was in a zone. Even the trainer said, `You look like kind
of dazed,' so I must have been zoning.''
</P>
<P>
   With Pettis, Stepanova and Griffiths (14 points, 9 rebounds)
silencing Gund Arena, the crowd of 8,420 forgot about its worst
nightmare before Tuesday. Jennifer Gillom, who averaged 28.2 points
in the first five games vs. the Rockers, was relatively quiet (11
points, 7 rebounds), usually the first clue to a Mercury loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really so proud of Bridget,'' Gillom said. ``I was
double-teamed, triple-teamed, and she came out and did her job. And
what a great job she's done.''
</P>
<P>
   Even at halftime, the Mercury had positive signs, especially its
17-14 lead on the boards that stretched to 38-29 by game's end.
Phoenix was outrebounded in the first two games of the series and
was embarrassed, 16-7, on the offensive boards in the first half
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Mercury beat the Comets, 69-66, on June 24, then Houston
rebounded with three-, 10- and 11-point wins en route to taking the
Western Conference title away from the Mercury. The teams last met
Aug. 6, and Phoenix is 8-2 since then in clinching a playoff berth
on the final day of the regular season and advancing to the finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last season, we were content to sit up there when the lights
go out and the popping and the bells and the whistles and the
fireworks,'' Miller said. ``We were just happy to be there. This
season, we wanted to be in the finals. We didn't want to just be 11
players that were overachievers. We wanted people to recognize
we're a very good team.''
</P>
<P>
   With a secret Russian weapon. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
