<SLUG> BC-BBN-PIRATES_DIAMONDBACKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIRATES PUMMEL SODOWSKY   
 FORMER TEAMMATES SEND STARTER PACKING IN 5TH  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Pittsburgh Pirates were thoughtful enough to give
Diamondbacks pitcher and former teammate Clint Sodowsky a couple of
team jerseys before Tuesday night's game at Bank One Ballpark. The
kindness ended there.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates knocked Sodowsky out of the game in the fifth inning
and went on to beat the Diamondbacks, 9-6, before a season-low
crowd of 38,960.
</P>
<P>
   With a bunch of young and/or inexperienced players not generally
known outside of Pittsburgh (nor within the much of the city's
environs, for that matter), the Pirates aren't exactly a hot
ticket. But they are a team with promise. They also are the hottest
team in the majors after winning their eighth straight.
</P>
<P>
   A pair of rookies led Pittsburgh. Third baseman Freddy Garcia's
three-run homer in the seventh off Aaron Small broke open the game
after the Diamondbacks made it close. And Sean Lawrence, a
27-year-old left-hander making his major-league debut, got the
victory. Lawrence worked five innings, giving up two runs and four
hits.
</P>
<P>
   Sodowsky, who was 2-2 in 45 games with the Pirates last year
before the Diamondbacks took him in the second round of the
expansion draft, encountered his defining moment in the top of the
fifth with the score tied at 2, two outs, runners on second and
third and Jason Kendall at the plate. Kendall began the evening
fourth in the National League in hitting, at .336. But Sodowsky
took the initiative, working the count to 1-2. Then Kendall, the
Pirates' lone representative on the NL All-Star team, lined a
single to left to score Lou Collier and Tony Womack for a 4-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   What started as a promising evening for Sodowsky deteriorated
further. Kendall stole his 18th base and Kevin Young reached first
on a single that would have scored Kendall had third baseman Matt
Williams not made a terrific play to keep the ball from reaching
the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   That was it for Sodowsky, who gave up just a walk in the first
three innings and tied his career high for strikeouts, six, which
he set last year with the Pirates. Ben Ford came in with runners on
first and third and got out of the jam by retiring Jose Guillen on
a soft liner to second baseman Tony Batista.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks opened the scoring in the first on Bernard
Gilkey's lead-off single, a single by Jay Bell and Devon White's
sacrifice fly. They made it 2-0 in the second when Damian Miller
hit his third homer of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh tied the score in the fourth when Adrian Brown led
off with a triple and scored on Kendall's double. One out later,
Guillen's single sent Kendall home.
</P>
<P>
   After Kendall broke the tie in the fifth, the Pirates went up,
6-2, in the sixth against reliever Chris Michalak on pinch-hitter
Manny Martinez's run-scoring force out and Tony Womack's single.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez had been sent up to bat for Lawrence, and the
Diamondbacks immediately took advantage of the rookie's absence,
scoring three runs in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   White led off with his 19th homer, off reliever Jeff McCurry.
Williams struck out, Lee singled, and after Batista flied out,
Miller blooped a double that scored Lee. Yamil Benitez walked, and
pinch-hitter David Dellucci singled to make it 6-5. But the rally
ended when Gilkey hit into a fielder's choice.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia then settled things in the seventh with his sixth homer
of the year, his fourth since being recalled from Triple-A
Nashville on Aug. 11.
</P>
<P>
   Benitez's sacrifice fly in the eighth provided the Diamondbacks
their final run. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
