A2336 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-CASSTEVENS-HEISMA     08-26 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CASSTEVENS-HEISMAN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEISMAN: BEST TALENT OR BEST TALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Heisman Trophy campaigns are mapped out during the summer. A
school publicist interviews the team's star athlete. His job is to
profile the young man's life.
</P>
<P>
   The more interesting he is, the more hardships he has endured,
the better his story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Butch, are you an orphan?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, sir.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You ``sure?''''
</P>
<P>
   ``Positive. My mom's the greatest. Dad taught me how to throw a
football when I was four years old. They've seen every game I've
played.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Where are they now. Prison?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Puerto Vallarta. We've got a time share.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell me a little more about yourself. How much adversity would
you say you've had to overcome?''
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you mean?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Growing up, how tough was it? Were you vitamin-deficient as a
kid? Ever have to quit school and go to work to pay the rent?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Never.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you share a room with 10 brothers and sisters?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an only child.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever donate a organ?''
</P>
<P>
   ````What?''''
</P>
<P>
   ``An organ. Northwestern's got an All-America tailback who gave
a kidney to his 70-year-old grandmother. ``60 Minutes'' did a big
story on him. Ever do anything like that for a friend or
relative?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you ``received'' an organ?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you ``play'' an organ? Piano? How about the saxophone?
Ever sing in the church choir? . . . '' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Can you top this? &QL; 
 &QL; 
Not all Heisman Trophy candidates have compelling stories.
Nowadays, however, it seems that more and more do.
</P>
<P>
   I would hate to be a voter.
</P>
<P>
   As a small child, ASU's J.R. Redmond wore shoes with steel
braces because his feet turned inward. At age 9, he was injured in
a car wreck. If J.R. has a Heisman-like year, how can you not vote
for him?
</P>
<P>
   But there's also Texas All-American Ricky Williams to consider.
</P>
<P>
   ``ESPN The Magazine'' paints a heart-tugging portrait of
Williams' boyhood. In high school, Ricky was so poor he either went
without lunch or asked his friends to buy it for him.
</P>
<P>
   One Christmas, unable to afford a tree, the family decorated a
small artificial house plant.
</P>
<P>
   Do you want to vote against a kid who said no to the pros and
returned for his senior year?
</P>
<P>
   Williams has a chance to break Tony Dorsett's all-time career
rushing record. In his bio, he says his lifetime goal is to become
an elementary school teacher. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Take a picture &QL; 
 &QL; 
West Virginia has a Heisman Trophy candidate. ``Famous'' Amos
Zereoue came from the Ivory Coast to America with his father, a
photographer.
</P>
<P>
   When Amos became involved with the wrong crowd, his father
placed him in a group home to help him learn discipline and
respect.
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin tank Ron Dayne is another Heisman hopeful. He is one
of 12 children.
</P>
<P>
   But the best story has to be that of Daunte Culpepper. Daunte
was born in a Florida prison. He was conceived during a visit by
the mother's boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   The mother begged a prison employee, Emma Culpepper, to care for
the child.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Ms. Culpepper was 62 years old. She already had
raised 14 kids: her brother's four children, seven by her
sister-in-law and three others she adopted.
</P>
<P>
   The boy grew to become a multisport star in high school. The New
York Yankees drafted him as a pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Daunte Culpepper, 6 feet 4, 235 pounds, is the star
quarterback for the Central Florida Golden Knights. A future
first-round draft pick.
</P>
<P>
   A student on the dean's list, he is on schedule to earn his
college degree and fulfill the promise he made to an 83-year-old
woman to whom he owes everything. &QL; 
 &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at david.casstevens(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
