<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 02:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2340 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDINALS-WADSWOR     08-26 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINALS-WADSWORTH-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WADSWORTH HOLDOUT FAMILIAR TO CARDINALS' DEFENSIVE PAIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Holdout'' is now in its 36th day, and even if Andre
Wadsworth is signed tonight _ which, of course, he won't be _ it's
becoming less and less likely he can be an effective force in the
Cardinals season opener at Dallas in 11 days.
</P>
<P>
   For perspective on the Wadsworth predicament, the Cardinals have
two experts in outside linebacker Jamir Miller and defensive end
Simeon Rice.
</P>
<P>
   Rice shares much in common with Wadsworth. Not only do they
employ the same agents, Eugene Parker and Roosevelt Barnes, but
Tuesday was the anniversary of the day on which Rice's celebrated
rookie holdout ended two seasons ago.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, too, was a late arrival who didn't come to terms with
the team until two days before the second preseason game.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have the opportunity to learn the defense, and if
you don't know the defense, then you can't really be a factor,''
Miller said. ``It really depends on how fast a learner he is. We
don't run a very difficult scheme, but it still will set him back
quite a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways Rice was in a more difficult position than
Wadsworth is now. The team was against the wall with the salary
cap, and to sign Rice it had to waive Garrison Hearst, who was
extremely popular among his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing Andre, it won't be hard for him,'' Rice said. ``But in
terms of football shape, you have to get used to contact and
running off contact. It's a different type of shape. You've got to
be able to go full speed and give a hit that takes a lot out of you
_ that sort of oomph with your body _ and still come back and play
hard and do it for four quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a feat. I'm not going to lie, but you can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Each also knows the anxiety that Wadsworth is undergoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can understand what he's going through,'' Miller said.
``This is a business, which is something people often lose sight
of. But to be honest, I'm tired of hearing about him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of sight, out of mind. He can't do anything to help me get
through the day, and he can't help me get through tomorrow. Until
he's here and is my teammate, I don't want to hear about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not it is a product of his relationship with the
agents, Rice has a different perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to get it over with. You can't wait,'' he said.
``There's a lot of anticipation. But you also have to allow the
people you hired to represent you to do it right. Make sure
everything goes right for you and the Cardinals. There has to be
common ground so everything is behind you when you come in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hired Eugene and Roosevelt for their integrity and
competency. One thing about Eugene is he looks out for his clients
and takes care of them. He's a good buffer.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the longer Wadsworth sits, impatience grows among coaches
and teammates, who have undergone two-a-days and practices in
Valley heat. Rice, even in the face of Hearst's departure, was
fortunate to be accepted as soon as he was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had two sacks and made some plays in my first preseason
game, which shocked some people,'' he said. ``In the first regular
season game, I tackled (the Colts') Marshall Faulk in the backfield
on the first play and did some things to pressure Jim Harbaugh. It
got some to open their eyes and say, `This kid can play.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Andre will have to be in shape and come in with a reason and a
goal on his mind.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-26-98 0214EDT &QL; 
