<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS2-LADN(WRITETHROUGH) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEX BITES EXPOS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Even in the worst of seasons, the Los Angeles
Dodgers can always count on the Montreal Expos.
</P>
<P>
   Not the Expos in Montreal, the same team that swept the Dodgers
earlier this month. The Expos who rarely get it right when they
play in L.A.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers took advantage of several Expos blunders Tuesday
night to open a 12-game homestand with a 4-3 victory in front of
30,183 at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that happened to us in the past is over,'' Dodgers manager
Glenn Hoffman said. ``We're home for 20 of the last 30 games. WE
still have a chance.'' Eric Young scored the winning run on a wild
pitch in the seventh inning that helped the Dodgers snap a losing
streak at three games. It also raised their record to 113-61
against the Expos at Dodger Stadium. And Dave Mlicki (7-6) pitched
62/3 innings to move his record over .500 for the first time this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you expect when you have a bunch of kids playing one
of the richest teams in baseball,'' said Expos manager Felipe Alou,
whose team has a $9 million payroll compared to the Dodgers $61
million. ``We play hard; that's all I ask....''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers even picked up a game on the New York Mets in the
wild card, drawing within seven games with 29 to play.
</P>
<P>
   Former Dodger Wilton Guerrero probably had the worst 4-for-5
game ever.
</P>
<P>
   For Guerrero, acquired by the Expos July 31 in the trade that
also sent three minor-league prospects to Montreal for left-hander
Carlos Perez and shortstop Mark Grudzielanek, the game started
badly.
</P>
<P>
   All could have been forgotten when Guerrero doubled off the
glove of left-fielder Trenidad Hubbard with one out in the ninth
off releiver Jeff Shaw. But Shaw, who allowed two ninth-inning
homers in Atlanta the day before, retired the final two batters to
earn his 38th save and 15th as a Dodger.
</P>
<P>
   Guerrero's brother Vladimir hit his 32nd home run off Mlicki in
the fourth. And Grudzielanek made two errors at short after making
just two in his first 22 games with the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wilton is doing okay,'' Alou said. ``If he was polished as a
second baseman or as a basestealer, he wouldn't be here. He's not
Craig Biggio. Guys like that cost $8-10 million a year. Guys like
that don't play here.''
</P>
<P>
   Guerrero opened the first inning with a single but immediately
got doubled off first on F.P. Santangelo.
</P>
<P>
   In the third, he stole second but when Charles Johnson's throw
sailed into center, Raul Mondesi already had the ball when Guerrero
took off for third. He was thrown out easily.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth inning with Hubbard at first, Mondesi flied to
left. Hubbard tagged and raced to second. F.P. Santangelo's throw
had Hubbard beat, but Guerrero failed to apply the tag in time. And
with two outs in the same inning, Guerrero failed to catch
Johnson's pop up to shallow right field that enabled the Dodgers
third run to score.
</P>
<P>
   Because he was no longer one of their own, Dodger fans cheered
Guerrero all night.
</P>
<P>
   But they found a target in Bobby Bonilla, who should have to
scored from second on the pop up. He was booed the rest of the
night, except for when he was lifted for pinch runner Roger Cedeno
after walking with one out in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came up to me afterward and apologized,'' Hoffman said of
Bonilla. ``He just lost track of the outs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers were coming off a 2-5 road trip to Pittsburgh,
Florida and Atlanta and needed this kind of help.
</P>
<P>
   Guerrero's baseball instincts were criticized during his time
with the Dodgers. He entered the game with a .239 average in 22
games since joining the Expos.
</P>
<P>
   He went 3 for 4 with an RBI single in the seventh that cut the
Dodgers lead to 4-2. Mlicki walked the next batter Santangelo and
Scott Radinsky entered the game.
</P>
<P>
   Pinch hitter Shane Bennett popped to short to end the inning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
