<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-OLSON-WIFE-CANCER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLSON'S WIFE BEING TREATED FOR CANCER  
 PROGNOSIS GOOD; COACH WON'T QUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arizona basketball Coach Lute Olson on Tuesday confirmed that
his wife, Bobbi, is being treated for ovarian cancer but denied
rumors that he plans to step down as coach of the Wildcats.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many rumors flying around,'' said Olson, the UA
coach since 1983. ``There is so much stuff out there. But Bobbi is
doing fine. She has regained about 18 of the 25 pounds that she
lost. She still has her good days and her bad.''
</P>
<P>
   The diagnosis was made in Tucson in June, shortly after the
Olsons returned abruptly from Hungary, where Olson was conducting a
coaching clinic. Bobbi Olson underwent emergency surgery in Hungary
and then was referred to the Arizona Cancer Center in Tucson upon
their return.
</P>
<P>
   ``The surgery in Hungary was related to this,'' said Dr. David
S. Alberts, an oncologist at the Arizona Cancer Center who is
treating her. ``They saw a pelvic mass, but they did not make the
diagnosis there.''
</P>
<P>
   Alberts said Bobbi Olson, 63, has Stage 3 cancer in the pelvis
and upper abdomen and that her prognosis ``is outstanding,'' based
on initial response to treatment indicated by CA-125 blood
readings.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is the most accurate prognostic factor,'' Alberts said.
``After four courses of chemotherapy, we have normalized all
markers of ovarian cancer. She has normalized CA-125, which is as
low as we see in normal women. These results are correlated with
very, very long survival, well in advance of five years. In fact,
these results are correlated highly with long-term cure.''
</P>
<P>
   Lute Olson, who will be 64 next month, did not attend the annual
summer circuit of basketball camps for the first time in his
head-coaching career. Instead, the Wildcats received an NCAA
exemption that allowed Olson to turn over off-season, off-campus
recruiting duties to associate head coach Jim Rosborough, while
Olson stayed home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I plan to retire? No. Am I planning to leave the program?
No,'' said Olson, who guided Arizona to the national championship
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Bobbi Olson has been almost as much a part of the Wildcats as
Olson himself, the matriarch of the winningest program in NCAA
Division I over the past decade, characterized by her outgoing
personality and warmth. She accompanies her husband worldwide to
every game or coaching clinic. The Olsons have been married for 45
years and have five children.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released Tuesday by Olson, he said he wanted to
end the rumors and confirm that his wife has been treated for
ovarian cancer at the Arizona Cancer Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of our desire for privacy, we hesitated making her
condition public until we as a family understood the implications
of this disease and what we are facing,'' Olson said in the
statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobbi and I want to assure everyone that she is doing great,
and we have every reason to believe that her prognosis is
excellent.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we are dealing with a serious diagnosis, the good news
is that Bobbi's disease is very treatable, and her response to only
four courses of chemotherapy has demonstrated remarkable results.
Our medical team has developed a course of treatment for her over
several months that includes both chemotherapy and routine surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very grateful for the thoughtfulness and concern that
everyone has expressed over the summer. We also appreciate the
respect for our privacy and hope this will continue as we move
forward with further treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   Alberts said the treatment will include another surgery next
month and additional chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ovarian cancer is curable today, even in advanced stages,''
Alberts said. ``Bobbi is in outstanding health. She has regained
normal weight and normal physical activity. She is asymptomatic.''
</P>
<P>
   Alberts said the survival rate for the average woman has gone
from one year in the 1960s to five in recent studies, and that
predates the use of the drug Taxol (paclitaxel), which is delivered
directly to the intra-abdominal space through a surgically
implanted catheter. Bobbi Olson will be receiving that treatment,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taxol is a wonder drug of the early 1990s,'' Alberts said.
</P>
<P>
   The ability to inject the drug directly onto the tumor makes it
1,000 times more effective than intravenous chemotherapy, Alberts
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can get the tumor to a small size, this technique can
be used to kill off the last tumor cell,'' Alberts said. ``You can
pour the drug directly onto the tumor cell like salt on a steak and
dissolve the tumor layer by layer. That's a tremendous advance in
the treatment of ovarian cancer.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
