<HEADLINE>
EDWARDS NOT READY TO GIVE UP ROSTER SPOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anthony Edwards has been in the Turk's shadow before _ many
times _ and used his guile to wriggle away and survive. He has
persevered through two knee surgeries, dozens of young hotshots and
never-ending skepticism that a given season is going to be his last
in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   But this might be the biggest challenge ever for Edwards, who is
trying to make it with the Cardinals in his 10th season as a
receiver and special teams player.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards returned to practice Tuesday, less than a month after he
underwent his latest knee surgery, and on the day the Cardinals
trimmed their roster from 76 to 60 players. Edwards survived that
cut. The next one is Sunday. Seven more players must go.
</P>
<P>
   The Casa Grande native is convinced he still has what it takes
to squeeze onto a roster after a decade in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I go compete these next five days and do what I need to do
and prove I can still do the things I've done in the past, I'm not
on the bubble,'' said Edwards, who appeared in every game the past
two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But there is the injury, his age (32) and another group of young
challengers who have shown in preseason action that they can do the
one thing that always has been Edwards' forte: special teams.
Edwards led Cardinals special teams with 20 tackles on coverage and
69 blocks on returns last season.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Vince Tobin said Edwards still has ``the wherewithal to
make a lot of teams and be productive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Anthony realizes it's been a challenge for him to stick for
the last 10 years,'' Tobin said. ``Come Sunday, we have to make a
decision on who we think are our five best receivers, so it was
good to have him back out here practicing to see how much his knee
injury has hurt or helped him. Getting it cleaned out might have
helped him run better.'' &QL;  &QL; 
Cut to chase &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The only surprises among the Tuesday roster reductions was that
veteran running back Ron Moore went and free agent offensive
lineman Jon Clark stayed. Moore, who rushed for 1,898 yards during
his first two seasons for the Cardinals (1993-94), was released
early because ``I owed it to him to give him the opportunity to
possibly land with another team,'' Tobin said. ``And he probably
will catch on.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore was behind Adrian Murrell, Mario Bates and Michael
Pittman.
</P>
<P>
   Clark (6 feet 6, 345 pounds), in his third pro season from
Temple, stuck because of injuries to linemen Anthony Clement and
Jerome Daniels, and because ``he's a young player on the come who
has gotten better,'' Tobin said. &QL;  &QL; 
Cornerback acquired &QL;  &QL; 
Later in the afternoon, after the initial roster moves were
announced, the Cardinals acquired veteran cornerback J.B. Brown
from the Pittsburgh Steelers for an undisclosed draft choice. To
make room on the 60-man roster, the Cardinals waived rookie wide
receiver Phil Savoy, a seventh-round draft pick.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, 31, was a 12th-round draft pick in 1989 who played with
the Miami Dolphins for eight seasons before being signed by the
Steelers last year. He has appeared in 135 games, starting 88, and
intercepted 16 passes during his nine-year career. Brown is an
insurance policy at right corner with Tom Knight, the projected
starter, and backups J.J. McCleskey and Ty Howard all coming off
injuries that severely restricted their preseason action. &QL;  &QL; 
Quick kicks &QL;  &QL; 
Clement, Daniels, Eric Metcalf, Edwards and Knight returned to
practice but none has completely recovered from injuries. Sitting
out were defensive tackle Mark Smith (ribs), lineman Allen
DeGraffenreid (knee), wide receiver Frank Sanders (back) and
defensive end Brad Ottis (foot).
</P>
<P>
   Joe Nedney made a 53-yard field goal under pressure during the
practice.
</P>
<P>
   With Smith hurting, the first defensive line had Jerry Drake at
left end, Eric Swann at left tackle, Bernard Wilson at Smith's
right tackle, and Simeon Rice at right end.
</P>
<P>
   Swann, who was ejected from Saturday's game when officials
charged him with kicking a Seattle player who was down, denied it:
``Truthfully, I didn't do it. We're reviewing game films now. If
the league fines me, I'll appeal. I'm not in the habit of giving
away free money.'' &QL;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
