<HEADLINE>
FOX'S REST RETURNS GILKEY TO FAMILIAR ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bernard Gilkey hit leadoff for the Diamondbacks on Tuesday night
for the first time since the outfielder was acquired from the New
York Mets on July 31. Andy Fox has virtually owned the slot,
leading off in 80 games this season, but Manager Buck Showalter
gave Fox the night off against Pittsburgh Pirates starter Sean
Lawrence, who was making his major league debut.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence is a lefty and Fox bats left-handed, but that wasn't
the primary reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been beat up and banged up, he's been hit by pitches. I
think he's up in the league leaders in that,'' Showalter said.
</P>
<P>
   Fox has been hit 13 times, fifth in the National League and
three times in his last two games.
</P>
<P>
   Although he had just 20 leadoff at-bats with the Mets this year,
Gilkey is accustomed to the job. Going into the game, he was a
career .297 hitter in 343 at-bats hitting out of the No. 1
position. The only other spot in the order in which he has batted
more is third.
</P>
<P>
   The move paid off instantly against the Pirates when Gilkey
lined a single to start the first inning and scored the first run
of the game on Devon White's sacrifice fly. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Lee fights slump &QL; 
 &QL; 
Rookie Diamondbacks first baseman Travis Lee entered the game in a
7-for-59 skid since coming off the disabled list on Aug. 7. But he
singled off Lawrence in his first at-bat and singled again off
reliever Jeff McCurry in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Showalter said before the game that the manner in which Lee has
dealt with all the hype and expectations is perhaps the most
pleasant surprise of the season. During tough times such as these,
Lee outwardly maintains an even keel. But don't be fooled.
Sometimes he leaves the dugout and ventures up the clubhouse runway
to let off steam.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's human,'' Showalter said. ``Sometimes with his
personality, people don't realize how competitive he is, how much
of a perfectionist he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people don't handle success well. Some people don't
handle failure well. He's been able to handle both.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Short stops &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not only was Tuesday's attendance of 38,960 the lowest of the
season, it was the third time in their past four games the
Diamondbacks drew fewer than 40,000. The club had exceeded the
figure in each of its first 56 home games.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks might be at or near the bottom of the league in
several offensive categories, but no team in the majors has hit
more triples. The club had 36 going into Tuesday's game. Next were
Pittsburgh, Boston and Tampa Bay with 31.
</P>
<P>
   Runs might be at a premium, but at least the Diamondbacks know
what to do when they get them most of the time. They are 46-29
(.613) when scoring at least four runs in a game, compared with
4-54 (.069) when held to three or fewer runs. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
