</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YELTSIN-RUSSIAN-ROULETTE-OPED-ASAHI-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIZARRE BORIS: MOSCOW'S MYSTERY MAN DOES IT AGAIN  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Commentary)   (This 625-word ``separate buy'' commentary is from the Asahi News
Service.)  
  
 (EDITORS: Get your news from Japan and the Pacific Rim straight
from the source _ the Asahi News Service. Its Monday through Friday
report of news, features and distinctive analysis is culled from
The Asahi Shimbun, Japan's foremost newspaper, renowned for its
integrity and thoroughness (with a daily circulation is 12
million.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
fax her at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``i'' international news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By HIROKI IZAWA  
 c.1998 Asahi News Service  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Russian President Boris Yeltsin's dismissal of Prime Minister
Sergei Kiriyenko on Aug. 23 was ostensibly a move to take
responsibility for the financial crisis the country faces.
</P>
<P>
   But in reality, the crisis is a legacy of Kiriyenko's
predecessor, Victor Chernomyrdin, who has been reappointed as prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
   What kind of manager decides to pull a pitcher off the field in
a huff, only to return him when his replacement was also battered
by hits?
</P>
<P>
   Making no clear explanations for his move, Yeltsin has only
succeeded in revealing the instability of his presidency, which has
less than two years left.
</P>
<P>
   The current financial crisis is rooted in Russia's decision in
1995, when Chernomyrdin was in charge, to switch from a policy of
extending government loans aimed at covering the large fiscal
deficit, to the issuance of high-interest short-term bonds. The
plan was endorsed by the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   While the move was aimed at reducing inflation, the bonds
snowballed. By the end of this year, over $18 billion in bonds are
expected to mature.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial banks that rushed to borrow huge amounts of U.S.
currency to invest in the bonds are now struggling to repay the
loans, resulting in the current crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Under Chernomyrdin, the Russian government also failed to deal
with the drop in industrial production, evident in the mining
industry, which saw a plunge in production in 1996 to 44 percent of
its 1990 level.
</P>
<P>
   It was also under Chernomyrdin that the government failed to
create a proper taxation system, despite the obvious need to
increase state income.
</P>
<P>
   When Kiriyenko was appointed five months ago, it was in the
expectation that he would deal with the aftermath of Chernomyrdin's
problems.
</P>
<P>
   The plunge in the value of the ruble, in Russian loans and in
the country's stocks can be attributed to structural distortion in
the Russian economy, the retreat of capital from new markets _
triggered by the Asian currency crisis _ and falling oil and
natural gas prices.
</P>
<P>
   Some also point out the lack of political clout held by the
36-year-old prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   However, compared with Chernomyrdin's unclear policies, which
focused on encouraging a balance among the military-industrial
complex, energy companies and new business plutocracies,
Kiriyenko's stance was clear as daylight.
</P>
<P>
   Kiriyenko managed to get major portions of his economic
stability bill, which outlined measures to collect taxes and reduce
government spending, passed in the State Duma last month.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Kiriyenko attempted to break the strong ties
between the government and wealthy business plutocracies. He
focused on finding deputies who could get the job done, introducing
reformists such as Boris Nemtsov into his Cabinet and appointing
Communist Party member Yury Maslyukov as industry and trade
minister.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian economic crisis has not resulted only from
mismanagement of the economy _ no, this crisis is on a different
plane. It is a result of a distorted structure that has seen no
increase in investments for productive activities.
</P>
<P>
   The reappointment of Chernomyrdin, who could be seen as the
cause of this problem, cannot possibly help solve the economic
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   When one considers that Chernomyrdin is a possible candidate for
presidency in the year 2000, a more radical but unpopular solution
to the situation would be difficult to imagine.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, Yeltsin has dismissed deputies whenever his abilities
have come into question.
</P>
<P>
   Could it be that Yeltsin merely wanted to fend off a political
crisis brewing over the ruble's devaluation one day earlier, which
could have precipitated a vote of non-confidence in the Duma?
Chernomyrdin is, after all, popular with the assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Whether this latest move will rescue Yeltsin _ and Russia _ in
the end remains to be seen. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Hiroki Izawa is Asahi Shimbun's Moscow Bureau
Chief) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 625-word commentary from the Asahi News Service,
it must be purchased _ the rate is not prohibitive _ from New York
Times Syndicate sales representative CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
