<SLUG> BC-AQUIFER-FILLING27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Edwards Aquifer rising after heavy rains
 &HT;    By Dick Stanley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Remnants of Tropical Storm Charley dumped more
rain on the western edge of the Hill Country, adding 12 inches to
the western portion of the Edwards Aquifer and boosting estimates
of water level increases at Lake Travis.
</P>
<P>
   The aquifer already saw a 6.3-foot rise over the weekend, and
the recent addition of several inches of rain continued to brighten
the outlook for San Antonio's water supply.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at 661 feet now,'' said Jeanne Jones, a spokeswoman for
the Edwards Aquifer Authority in San Antonio. ``It's a much better
picture than it was as recently as August 4th, when we had a low of
639.5 feet.'' The extra rain also led the Lower Colorado River
Authority to revise its estimates of the effect on Lake Travis. The
authority forecasts an additional 3-foot rise in the lake, from 663
feet above sea level to 666 feet by Labor Day. The lake is
considered full at 682 feet above sea level.
</P>
<P>
   The additional rains had little effect on rivers, creeks and
streams in Central Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The Guadalupe and Blanco rivers continued to recede from Monday
morning's flood stages, and the southern branch of the Llano River,
although swollen by Tuesday's additional rain, funneled only minor
amounts of new water into the Highland Lakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two waves came down the Llano, but it was less than what we
had Monday,'' said Bob Rose, a meteorologist with the Lower
Colorado River Authority.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy rain north of the Llano's southern branch could put some
water into dry stretches of the San Saba River today, but much of
it is expected to sink into the ground, Rose said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
