<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    This much fun's gotta be criminal
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Crime. If you conducted a poll, most people
would come out against it. But let's be honest. People love to
watch crime being fought because, gosh darn it, it's fun, cheap
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Call it Toni Hinojosa's big day.
</P>
<P>
   It was around 5 Monday morning when Toni, who lives on South
Trace Drive in South Austin, left her house to walk Hercules, her
Shih Tzu, which means ``rat on steroids'' in Chinese. ``As I opened
the door I saw all these cop cars pointing their lights at the
house across from us,'' Toni recalled. ``I couldn't figure out what
was going on. They were all lined up there like oh my gawd, there's
some crazy criminal around here.''
</P>
<P>
   Toni says there were about 50 cop cars up and down her street.
Toni didn't know this at the time. But shortly before 4 a.m., the
cops had gone to the house across the street from Toni's to arrest
a suspected parole violator, who had locked himself inside and
refused to come out.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was having a ball watching all this,'' said Armando,
Toni's husband, a retired Air Force staff sergeant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so exciting to me that I couldn't believe it,'' Toni
said.
</P>
<P>
   So there was Toni, out on her front lawn around 5 a.m., walking
Hercules, the Shih Tzu. And now here came this nice policeman.
</P>
<P>
   ``A policeman came over and said, 'Ma'am, would you please go
inside?' `` Toni recalled. ``I said, 'Why?' and and he said,
'There's a subject in the house. And a SWAT team is coming. So you
have to go inside.' ``
</P>
<P>
   A real, live SWAT team. Wow. Coming to this neighborhood. Toni
wasn't about to miss the chance to catch an actual SWAT team in
action. `` wanted to watch,'' she said. ``I'd never seen a SWAT
team.''
</P>
<P>
   So after Toni took Hercules back into the house and dumped him
off, she craftily snuck back outside, and hid behind the ornamental
bush near her front door _ ``so I could see what the SWAT team was
going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   This move proved to be a disappointment. Toni hunkered down
behind the bush for ``probably an hour and a half. I was getting
tired, believe it or not. I was kind of squatting.'' But other than
sore joints, nothing much had happened _ yet.
</P>
<P>
   When the sun came up, Toni left her spot behind the bush and
went back into her house. ``I thought they (the cops) might see me
and tell me to go away,'' she explained. But she wasn't giving up.
This could still get ugly.
</P>
<P>
   So she went into her kitchen and began watching through her
front window with her binoculars.
</P>
<P>
   So Toni's persistence paid off. ``Finally they (the cops)
started talking to him on that loudspeaker. I even heard a
helicopter go by over the house. It was like in the movies.''
</P>
<P>
   The five-hour standoff ended around 9 a.m. after the cops shot
tear gas into the house across the street from Toni's and rousted
out Martin Lee Kennedy, 38, for a parole violation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when he came out with his hands up,'' Toni said. ``Boy,
what an exciting morning I had.''
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso writes a humor column on Mondays, Wednesdays and
Fridays. He can be reached at 445-3606 or at jkelsostatesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
