<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Talking back about school, reunions
 &HT;    By Don McLeese
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ On school vacations, TAAS tests and family
reunions, readers respond:
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree with the basic premise of your (Aug. 16) article _
that summer ends too early and that we should not be starting
school so early, (but) there are two points you made to which I
feel compelled to respond. The first was the suggestion that the
first month of school consists of mainly review of old material.
Not true. Due to changes in the school schedule and an increase in
the material we are expected to cover, I am doing new material (as
a teacher at Taylor High School) from the very first bell of
school. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``The other comment had to do with schools being `geared to
passing that silly TAAS test.' There is a tremendous pressure from
the administrators to do that (in some schools, not necessarily
mine), but there are a lot of very dedicated, hard-working teachers
who are resisting that trend. We teach well above TAAS, and those
scores should take care of themselves. I would have to ask you,
`How much does the media contribute to the emphasis on TAAS
scores?' How many times has your newspaper done a story on any of
the other (academic) indicators? OK, SAT scores also get some
press, too, but TAAS always makes the front page. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not trying to be a wise guy. It's just very frustrating
that some of the great things we are doing that go well beyond TAAS
never get any coverage.'' _ Dixie Ross
</P>
<P>
   ``Our kids started at Casis, but we gave up there when the
5th-grade creative-writing unit was dropped to allow for more
TAAS-preparation time. Talk about `Wag the Dog!' We're at the
Austin Waldorf School now, which opens humanely in early September,
usually the Tuesday after Labor Day, and which gives not a fig for
the TAAS and its self-reinforcing dumbing-down of curricula
everywhere.''_ Michael DiLeo
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a teacher at Austin High School. As you stated, the
rationale for the August school opening was to end the semester
before Christmas. The important point here, however, is so that
secondary school students could take their exams before the long
break and not forget too much. Well, the surprise for us this year
was that, due to most courses being year-long, we may not be giving
semester exams any more. Therefore, the whole reason for the
pre-Labor Day opening will be moot!'' _ Mary Nichols
</P>
<P>
   ''Except for running out of space, why did you stop giving
reasons why the schools should not start until after Labor Day? . .
. What does it take to get a taxpayer revolt that demands common
sense and responsibility about the way our school tax dollars are
spent?'' _ Elizabeth A. Strohm
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel exactly the same way about (family) reunions. And, as
an old rock 'n' roller who could hardly wait to move away from
home, I surprised everyone as being the one who loves the reunions
the most (but only once a year!).'' _ Tim Basham
</P>
<P>
   ''After reading your column, I had to chuckle. You mentioned a
`big' family of four siblings and a reunion of 19. Imagine this: A
four-day event, lodging spread out in five hotel rooms and three
private homes. . . . Do you know how much brisket, coleslaw, potato
salad, baked beans, banana pudding and ice tea it takes to feed 52
people?'' _ Liz McIntyre Don McLeese writes Sundays and Tuesdays in
Metro &AMP; State. He can be reached at dmcleesestatesman.com or at
445-3610.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The AMERICAN-STATESMAN, AUSTIN, TX
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-08-24-98 2045E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
