<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BENGALS-BLAKE27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Blake booted by Bengals?
 &HT;    By Chick Ludwig
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Deposed quarterback Jeff Blake slipped into his
sneakers, fastened the belt on his blue jean shorts, tugged on the
bill of his white New York Yankees cap and headed for the door at
Spinney Field.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't speak with reporters, but you could see intense pride
in the man who threw 74 touchdown passes for the Bengals from
1994-97. And you couldn't help but wonder: Will his next exit be
permanent . . . before the first snap of the 1998 regular season?
</P>
<P>
   Team president and general manager Mike Brown refused to confirm
if he has asked Blake to renegotiate a contract that calls for $1.9
million in '98 and $2.65 million in '99.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to get into that right now,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Blake's ideal scenario would be a one-year deal that would cut
him loose in February and turn him onto the free-agent market. But
a two-year deal? To be the Bengals' backup? No way will he accept
that.
</P>
<P>
   It's already difficult enough for him to stomach the fact he's
No. 2 behind starter Neil O'Donnell and possibly No. 3 behind Paul
Justin.
</P>
<P>
   If Brown stands firm on the two-year offer and Blake doesn't
accept a lower salary, he could be among the final casualties
Sunday, when the NFL's 53-man rosters are set.
</P>
<P>
   The Bengals without Blake as insurance is a scary thought.
O'Donnell has played well enough to deserve the starting
assignment, but he's in his ninth NFL season and has yet to play a
full 16 games in any year.
</P>
<P>
   Justin is a talented backup, but can you trust him at the wheel
of the offense if O'Donnell gets hurt? That's a huge risk. A major
gamble.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he senses that he's the top backup to O'Donnell, Justin
said: ``I have no sense. I don't know where it's going or what's
happening. I wish I did, but I have no idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Head coach Bruce Coslet was asked how Blake is holding up. ``I'm
not going to speak for him,'' Coslet said. ``I can't. All I can do
is tell you what I expect from him. I expect him to come in,
prepare like he's the starter, go out and practice hard and get
ready to play Friday night. Case closed.''
</P>
<P>
   Not quite.
</P>
<P>
   With trade prospects dwindling _ reports out of Atlanta and St.
Louis say the Falcons and Rams aren't interested in a trade, but
may look into grabbing him if he's cut _ keeping Blake and his hurt
feelings on the sidelines could be an unsavory distraction for a
team rebuilding with a full-throttle youth movement.
</P>
<P>
   That's why he may be let go.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The DAYTON NEWSPAPERS INC., DAYTON, OHIO
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-08-25-98 2306E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
