A2702 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAMILY-MISSION27-COX     08-26 0250
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-MISSION27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    So you think your family is dysfunctional?
 &HT;    By Charlise Lyles
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gather the spouse, kids and Lassie and write a mission or vision
statement.
</P>
<P>
   What is the purpose of your family? What are your core values?
Where do you want to be in five years?
</P>
<P>
   Mission statement? Core values? Sounds more like running a
business than a family, right?
</P>
<P>
   Wrong, according to motivational guru Stephen R. Covey. The
author of the highly acclaimed management bestseller The 7 Habits
of Highly Effective People told more than 2,300 people at Ohio's
Memorial Hall recently that they can apply similar habits to forge
a happy family.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, parents have be proactive'' in their approach to family
problems, said Covey who in 1997 wrote The 7 Habits of Highly
Effective Families (Golden Books, $25) . ``Don't blame your past.
It isn't nature. It isn't nurture. It's the power to choose, the
moral agency to choose your response to anything that happens. What
does that mean to a family?
</P>
<P>
   ``It means we can become the agent of change in our own
family,'' he said. ``Even though we were abused as a child, we
don't have to abuse our own children. Even if we were raised in a
family that had no vision about the worth of people. Or we may have
been in a contentious family with fighting, use of survival
tactics, infidelity and extreme brokenness.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-26-98 1021EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980826.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 10:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2703 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN27-COX     08-26 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   No telling where it will end
</P>
<P>
   By Rowland Nethaway
</P>
<P>
   c: 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   GLEN ROSE, Texas _ Like turtles on a log, the men sat side by
side on park benches.
</P>
<P>
   The cafe across the street was still serving breakfast, but the
morning sun kept the men tucked together in the shade cast by big
pecan trees on
</P>
<P>
   the west side of the courthouse square.
</P>
<P>
   The old Somervell County Courthouse faces south, which probably
is no accident. Wherever statues honor Confederate veterans,
courthouses often
</P>
<P>
   moon the north.
</P>
<P>
   The men were in a perfect spot to track all the comings and
goings in their 2,000-population community 50 or so miles southwest
of Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   We parked our motorcycles next to an old pickup that had the
tailgate down to show off a nice load of watermelons. We nodded at
the men and
</P>
<P>
   crossed the street for a cup of coffee.
</P>
<P>
   When we returned, we decided to sit a while with the men.
</P>
<P>
   ``You boys with all those motorcycles down by the river?'' asked
one of the men.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. Don't know anything about them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Big group. Vietnam veterans. Supposed to be 2,000 or more this
weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't get near that much,'' offered another man.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not with them. We're just riding around. We came north
because it's raining south of Waco. We're from Waco.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't rained here all summer. It's rained all around us.
But it hasn't rained here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's that nuclear power plant they built near here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe. If that's it, I wish they'd turn it off long enough to
get a good rain.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I go to Waco once a year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether you need to or not?''
</P>
<P>
   ``For the annual statewide convention of the Masonic Grand Lodge
in December. We nearly quit going to Waco. They jacked up the rates
on us.
</P>
<P>
   I once asked the man at my motel why he charged me $80 when the
card on the back of the door said $40. He said they double the
prices when the
</P>
<P>
   Masons come to town.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At least those Baptists are honest. They may charge double,
but they don't lie about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The men watched the traffic as they talked. They had been born
and reared right there in Glen Rose and Somervell County.
</P>
<P>
   They pointed out where the 10-cent picture show used to be and
where the drug store with the marble counter and the honky tonk
used to be.
</P>
<P>
   Right after the remark about Waco ethics, we watched a blue
pickup pulling a trailer loaded with hay swing wide to make a left
turn where
</P>
<P>
   the old drug store used to be. A bale fell off.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner had the pickup with the trailer disappeared than
another man stopped to remove the hay bale from the street. He put
it on the
</P>
<P>
   sidewalk and drove away.
</P>
<P>
   The lost hay bale and the thoughtfulness of the passing stranger
were still being discussed when another man in a new white pickup
pulled to a
</P>
<P>
   stop next to the hay bale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look. Look at this,'' someone said as we watched the driver
put the bale in the back of his pickup.
</P>
<P>
   The watermelon man gave a sharp yell that froze the hay thief in
his tracks. He stared in our direction, noticing for the first time
that men
</P>
<P>
   were watching him from the shade of the pecan trees.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, he didn't know what to do next. Finally, he made up his
mind. The thief made his getaway.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later the man in the blue pickup returned looking
for his hay bale. But it was gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``That hay bale didn't sit there more than six minutes. In Glen
Rose, I figured that hay bale would sit there at least a day before
anyone took
</P>
<P>
   it.''
</P>
<P>
   Yep. First the nuclear power plant stops the rain and now this.
Glen Rose is changing fast.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco (Texas)
Tribune-Herald.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: RNeth(at)aol.com
</P>
