<SLUG> BC-BISHER-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Baseball again simple pastime when you're 6
 &HT;    By Furman Bisher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ I got a different view of a baseball game the other
day. The eyes were 6 years old. I borrowed them for a few innings.
They belonged to my grandson, just catching on to the tricks of
life, like finding that if he goes to the ballpark, he can order
pizza and a thing called a slushy, and peanuts, which he doesn't
care for a lot. Too much work.
</P>
<P>
   What you go to a game with a 6-year-old it's a trip back to
basics. It turns into a review of all the things you've taken for
granted. Like when a batter is out at first. He hits the ball, a
fielder throws him out. James the Third wanted an explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see, when the batter hits the ball, the fielder must throw
it to first before the batter gets there, and the batter is out,''
his father explained.
</P>
<P>
   I guess I'd just never thought of it that way. It does make
sense.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves were playing the Dodgers, and naturally the Dodgers
wore gray road uniforms. Little James wanted to know why. His
father came through again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players in the gray uniforms,'' he said, ``they are the
bad guys, the Dodgers. The team in white are the good guys. They're
the Braves.''
</P>
<P>
   Happily, no Dodger pitcher hit Andres Galarraga and started a
brawl, for I don't know how he'd have explained that. The
6-year-old had met ``Mr. Galarraga'' before the game and considered
him a close personal friend.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time I'd sat in one of the pews at Turner
Field, so most of it was as new to me as it was to him. We did all
the things tourists do. I'd never been closer to the big Coke
bottle than the press box. I didn't realize it's made of bases,
gloves, bats, balls, chest protectors and all kinds of equipment.
Little James took one look at the little patch of infield and
stepped into the batter's box. He took a big imaginary swing and
tore out for first base. Obviously he was safe, and thereupon
celebrated his triumph with a loud, ``Yay!''
</P>
<P>
   He inherited something from old grandad. He has a distinct
respect for heights. He showed no interest in looking over the side
at the field below. He sat in the fake dugout and crossed his legs
like Casey Stengel used to do. Once his tour was done, he took the
misty walk back, cooling his fevered brow, and there was triumph in
his stride.
</P>
<P>
   The museum was next, presided over by Carolyn Serra. He didn't
tarry long at the silver shovel old grandad had helped break ground
with at the old stadium, or at the Cracker uniform out of his
gallery at home. But there was joy at the sight of the Pullman car,
the way the Braves had traveled in olden days. He romped up and
down and in and out and played conductor, then it was time for
pizza, slushy and the game. Oh, and of course, the essential
tomahawk, which can be endangering to anybody near a free swinger.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is a strike, Granddaddy?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   That caught me tongue-tied. I'd been trying to decide what one
was since each umpire decided on his own. I stammered, then said,
``It's when a batter swings at a ball and misses, and sometimes
when he doesn't swing.''
</P>
<P>
   That quieted the curiosity for a few minutes, until he finished
his pizza. Then a Dodger fouled off a pitch, and of course, the
umpire signaled strike. He looked at me with a question in his
eyes, but finished his slushy and let me off the hook.
</P>
<P>
   We were leaving, still taking in all the glitter, remembering
back to Ponce de Leon Park, where his father was almost born.
``They've taken a plain old game,'' his father said, ``and turned
it into an experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Furman Bisher is the Sports Editor of The Atlanta Journal,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
