<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRIDGE-CLOSING27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Laredo bridge closures could affect trade
 &HT;    By Lori Hawkins and Ben Wear
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAREDO, Texas _ Business people on both sides of the border
waited nervously this week to hear whether the Laredo bridge
closings would be a small inconvenience or a big financial blow.
</P>
<P>
   ``How bad it is depends on how long the bridges are closed,''
said Sylvia Segovia, a traffic supervisor at Express Carriers, a
Laredo trucking company. ``The longer we have to wait, the more
money we lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials closed commercial traffic over the two international
bridges connecting Laredo's downtown to that of Nuevo Laredo in
Mexico. When they will reopen depends on the Rio Grande. Crossings
at Del Rio and Colombia are also closed indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the loss of one day's operations we're talking about
millions of dollars lost,'' said Miguel Conchas, president and
chief executive of the Laredo Chamber of Commerce. ``We expect we
will see it return to normal (on Wednesday).''
</P>
<P>
   Laredo is the largest inland crossing between the United States
and Mexico in terms of freight. Last year, 1.2 million trucks
entered the United States at Laredo, and 5.4 million people crossed
on foot to shop and to work. Total trade at the Laredo crossing
reached $50 billion in 1997, according to the Bureau of
Transportation Statistics and the Border Trade Institute.
</P>
<P>
   ``You name the product, and it's going to be crossing at
Laredo,'' said Brennar Stewart, research team director at the Texas
Department of Economic Development.
</P>
<P>
   Trucks loaded with electronic components and car parts are
shipped from the United States to assembly plants called
maquiladoras on the Mexican side of the border. Cars, consumer
electronics, furniture and food are shipped both ways.
</P>
<P>
   Laredo Mayor Betty Flores acknowledged that closing the bridges
will make the area's shared international economy take a hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the economic impact is hard to tell,'' Flores said. ``One
day is not that much. Believe me, they (truckers) know how to make
it up and they will.''
</P>
<P>
   The same types of goods move back and forth the Del Rio
crossing, but on a much smaller scale. Last year, 71,000 trucks and
262,000 pedestrians crossed into the United States through Del Rio.
Trade totalled $2.3 billion for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Segovia's company, which ships car parts to maquiladoras and
ships assembled parts back to the United States, decided against
rerouting trucks as a result of the Laredo bridge closings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too much of a hassle to reroute, so we're just going to
sweat it out for a little bit,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   On a typical day, Express Carriers receives 56 trailers carrying
goods from Mexico. On Tuesday, it received 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each load generates at least $1,500 worth of freight income,''
she said. ``That's a lot of money lost. And no one knows for sure
what will happen on Wednesday.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Flores said that lives are more important than
livelihoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worse thing we can have is a death on our hands,'' she
said. ``If people need to stay to go to work, then they need to
find some way to stay in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   Reinigio Rodriguez, Jr., headed home to Mexico Tuesday evening
to his wife and two young sons and away from his job installing and
repairing air conditioners in Laredo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tomorrow, I won't be able to work,'' he said. ``One day of
rest won't hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   And if it turns into several days because of lingering high
water? No problem, at least for Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   ``My boss is my dad,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
