<SLUG> BC-WALKER-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Survey of kids say, Clinton should remain in office
 &HT;    By Ana Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of the 12-year-old boys polled in my most recent survey of the
American people who live at my house regarding President Clinton's
television revelations Monday, 100 percent of respondents said,
``He didn't say he was sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   The five of us watched together, and no one had much comment
immediately afterward. Maybe we were hoping it was all over.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of days later, the Walker respondents were ready to
talk and that's when our son made his pronouncement.
</P>
<P>
   Of the male heads of household who are parents of two daughters,
ages 20 and 16, 100 percent said he fervently hopes that the
president knows that his stature has shrunk to the size of a
thimble in his daughter Chelsea's eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 16-year-old female respondents, 100 percent said Clinton
shouldn't leave office. ``They knew what he was like when they
elected him.'' Of his admitted ``inappropriate'' behavior: ``That
was stupid on his part, like he wasn't gonna get caught.''
</P>
<P>
   The more politically seasoned 20-year-old female responded very
strongly that the president should not leave office but her remarks
were not completely supportive, either. A summer employee at a
local restaurant, she has conversations with many members of the
public. She spoke of one agitated mother who said she did not want
her 9-year-old child to hear anymore about ``that dress.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just embarrassing,'' the 20-year-old said, probably
putting her finger on the reason most Americans seem to want the
whole mess to just go away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was embarrassing to watch the president talk about that on
television.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the female heads of household who live at our address, 100
percent feels relieved that her son knows that you're not only
supposed to feel remorse, you are supposed to express it.
</P>
<P>
   She wants to believe that if the president's mom were alive, she
would have throttled him.
</P>
<P>
   She hopes Hillary's mom does.
</P>
<P>
   She knows if Monica were her daughter, the young woman would
have been throttled years ago.
</P>
<P>
   She's troubled because a 21-year-old girl became involved in a
relationship with a 50-year-old married man. She worries about that
girl's seeming lack of self-worth. She's angry because the
50-year-old man should have had the maturity and the sense to help
the girl or get someone else to help her.
</P>
<P>
   She's very angry, not just because he is the president, but
because the ``take it if it's there for the taking'' attitude has
been accepted and encouraged for generations.
</P>
<P>
   And she's angrier still because even after the Bill/Monica
whirlpool has fizzled, that attitude will go on.
</P>
<P>
   Ana Pecina Walker is managing editor of the Longview
News-Journal. E-mail: awalker(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
