<DOCNO> NYT19980826.0083 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 10:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2710 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINOR-COLUMN27-COX     08-26 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINOR-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Did you ignore Bonnie, or are you one of them?
 &HT;    By Emily J. Minor
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm thankful for Bonnie, the hurricane that doesn't affect me,
me, me anymore, not just because she came and went so
unceremoniously. Bonnie, as it turns out, had a big effect on my
life.
</P>
<P>
   She gave me the thinking time to advance a new theory I have
about human behavior in South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   You see, folks, there are two kinds of people driving around out
there on I-95. You can call them Type A's and Type B's if you want.
But here on the coast, where six months out of the year the world
revolves around coordinates and categorized wind speeds, I suggest
we break life into something a little more meaningful.
</P>
<P>
   Like people who have candles, D batteries, bottled water and
Ravioli in their cupboards, and people who do not.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to hurricane unpreparedness, I guess you could
call me a Category 5. I used to have all the stuff. The sterno. The
stick matches. The jugs of purified water. Then one day my kid had
some friends over, and I found myself standing at the kitchen sink
pouring all the Zephyrhills down the drain so we could take the
Exacto knife and turn the jugs into giant sand shovels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cool, Mom. Thanks,'' the 7-year-old said, which was nice to
hear, but you can't exactly quench your post-storm thirst with a
kid's compliment, can you?
</P>
<P>
   Please understand, though, I am not a complete loser. After all,
I have a child to think of. And even though I ate all the Dinty
Moore's Beef Stew one night after too many beers at the baseball
game, I know exactly where all seven of our flashlights are.
</P>
<P>
   They're right there where I last saw them, in the treehouse,
adrift in brown rain water.
</P>
<P>
   If you are like me, which at least half of you must be _
otherwise all those hurricane supplies I saw at the grocery store
last night would have been gone by now _ you might be surprised to
know there are some people out there who are not like us.
</P>
<P>
   I guess you could call them the other half.
</P>
<P>
   These are the people who have a cabinet set aside for storm
supplies and, if I were a betting woman, I'd say five bucks
everything is labeled, maybe even with glow-in-the-dark tape. I
suspect my neighbor falls into this category. In the preparedness
division, she is probably, no, definitely, a Category 1.
</P>
<P>
   This is a wonderful, caring woman who is raising a nice playmate
for my son. But she has this buying habit that shocks me.
</P>
<P>
   Let's say that she is shopping for school clothes in June and
let's say she sees something on sale, a bargain. Well, she buys it
and stashes it away for a Christmas present.
</P>
<P>
   What this means is that I live next to a woman who could handle
a hurricane and Christmas without a trip to the store.
</P>
<P>
   I, on the other hand, wait until that nutty pilot flies through
the eye and comes out crying before I think, `Hmm, maybe that storm
is going to come this way.' I, on the other hand, crave disaster,
which probably explains my votes for Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   So, call me a Type A. Call me a procrastinator. Call me a big,
lazy drama queen. Just don't call me this Friday.
</P>
<P>
   That's the night I'm having the neighbors over for a candlelight
Ravioli dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
