A2712 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLIFFSNOTES-TEACH27-C     08-26 0537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLIFFSNOTES-TEACH27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Teacher's pet peeve
 &HT;    By Jeff Houck
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just because Cliff Hillegass himself writes on the inside cover
of every pamphlet that ``a thorough appreciation of literature
allows no short cuts'' doesn't mean students don't dodge Moby Dick
and run straight for the Cliffs.
</P>
<P>
   Or that teachers don't know it.
</P>
<P>
   ``English teachers love to hate Cliffs Notes,'' said Carol Jago,
who served on the National Council of Teachers of English's
literature commission. A high school English teacher for 25 years
in Santa Monica, Calif., Jago says the ``truth of it is, they are
good study aids.''
</P>
<P>
   Jago relied on Cliffs to help her tackle Tom Jones when she
attended St. Louis University. She had read only about 150 pages of
the book and had a paper due the next day. ``I tell the students
this story all the time to show that even good students get into a
bind,'' she said. ``I would have to be a moron to think that (all)
of my students get through the books I assign.''
</P>
<P>
   Jago believes Cliffs Notes should be used as ``scaffolding'' for
those reading the classics. In California, for example, where
English is a second language for large numbers of students, Cliffs
can be crucial for navigating tougher texts, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are those who try to skate by on Cliffs Notes
alone. Some go as far as quoting patches of the pamplets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same student profile as always, the lazy students who
can't be bothered,'' Jago said. ``Let's face it, a rigorous high
school curriculum is hard work and high school students do not like
hard work.''
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Rinear, a retired English teacher who taught at Martin
County High School in Stuart for 27 years, said she had students
try to pull the same trick on her, too. She thinks that high school
is no place for Cliffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a positive place for college students, but for high
school, you want to teach them critiquing skills that go beyond
more than just using the resources that are available,'' Rinear
said. ``I tried to steer my students away from them and get them to
read as great a variety as possible so that they could form an
opinion about a book.''
</P>
<P>
   Fred Standley, chairman of Florida State University's English
department, said students need to be aware of a couple other
factors. Some texts include inaccuracies, such as dates of works
and plot summaries _ although Standley couldn't cite any
specifically. He also said that they might give readers a false
sense of security.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always warn students not to assume that since they've read a
summary that they've read the novel, because there will be varying
interpretations,'' Standley said.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say he holds his nose up at the product. About
four years ago Cliffs asked him to pen an analysis of James
Baldwin's Go Tell it on the Mountain for the tidy sum of $1,400.
Standley seriously considered the offer but declined because he had
a full plate of other literary obligations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you do write one, you do it for the money,'' he said. ``Who
knows? I might do it if I get desperate for the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
