<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 10:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2714 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HILLEGASS27-COX     08-26 0449
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLEGASS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The odyssey of Cliff Hillegass, in brief
 &HT;    By Jeff Houck
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forget the millions of copies of pamphlets with his name on them
all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   Cliff Hillegass, 81, is awed by the impact his Cliffs Notes
study aids have had on education and American culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``To use his words, he is very humbled,'' said Robert Covolik,
the president of Cliffs Notes in Lincoln, Neb., and a longtime
friend of Hillegass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have always classified Cliff as a people person,'' Covolik
said. ``He has a great deal of warmth.'' (He does not, however,
give interviews. ``He's retired here in Lincoln and he hasn't done
an interview in about three years,'' said one company spokesman.)
</P>
<P>
   Born in rural Nebraska, Hillegass grew up with a love of
literature, especially after an operation when he was 7 left him
bedridden for two months. The only thing he could do was read, so
he devoured book after book.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up, he had a milk route, two paper routes and also sold
magazines. By 14, he saved a sizable sum of money, but lost it all
when the local bank closed during the Depression.
</P>
<P>
   He rebuilt the sum by the time he went to Midland College in
1934. He graduated in 1937 and after attending graduate school at
the University of Nebraska _ where he studied physics and geology _
he took a sales job at the Nebraska Book Company.
</P>
<P>
   His career was interrupted when he served in the Army Air Corps
during World War II. When he returned to his job, he got to know
most of the country's college bookstore managers during sales
calls.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Cole, a friend who owned the largest bookstore chain in
Canada and developed and sold a line of study guides called Coles
Notes, encouraged Hillegass to produce a similar line in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   When the Nebraska Book Company declined to publish the study
guides, Hillegass got approval to work on the line in his spare
time. Working out of his basement and borrowing money to start the
venture, he printed 32,000 copies of 16 Major Plays of Shakespeare.
They sold out within a year.
</P>
<P>
   By 1961, he sold 129,000 copies and sales doubled each of the
next four years. Sales have continued to increase.
</P>
<P>
   Hillegass knows what some kids are up to when they use his
product. Not everyone reads the classics and Cliffs. His hope, he
says, is that if they read the notes instead of the novel now, one
day they will go back to the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way it goes,'' Hillegass told the Arizona Republic
in 1994. Students ``get cornered on time, or just plain don't like
to read.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
