<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 10:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2716 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTION27-TAKE2     08-26 1427
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTION27-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A on the news
 &HT;    By Colin Bessonette
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED: Q: Has there ever been a first lady who filed for
divorce while her husband was in office?
</P>
<P>
   Q: A member of Congress can get a pension after five years of
service. What is the amount of that pension? If it's a range, what
is the minimum and maximum? And when can they start collecting?
</P>
<P>
   A: Lawmakers are vested after five years and can begin
collecting upon retirement from the government if at least age 50,
said Pete Sepp of the National Taxpayers Union in Alexandria, Va.
The fewer the years of service, the later members have to wait;
those with five years must wait until 62. They're entitled to 2.5
percent of their salaries per year of service, capped at 80 percent
of the final year's pay, with subsequent cost-of-living increases
(current salaries for members of Congress are $133,600 a year).
</P>
<P>
   The pension plan for members of Congress is part of the civil
service retirement system, but the formula used for computing their
benefits is more generous than the one rank-and-file federal
employees normally would have, Sepp said.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If fugitive bombing suspect Eric Robert Rudolph were hiding
within the Cherokee reservation in North Carolina, could he be
apprehended? From what I understand, law enforcement officers
cannot go in there.
</P>
<P>
   A: Not so. There's a federal warrant out for Rudolph's arrest.
If he's hiding anywhere in the United States, that warrant gives
the FBI jurisdiction. If Rudolph is hiding on an Indian reservation
_ or if someone there is harboring him _ the FBI still has the
primary investigative jurisdiction, said agency spokeswoman
Celestine Armstead, and agents would be allowed to go on the
property ``and do whatever is necessary'' to apprehend him.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Everyone's talking about Kenneth Starr's investigation
costing the taxpayers $40 million. How much would that amount to,
per person, if it were divided among everyone living in the United
States?
</P>
<P>
   A: Based on the Census Bureau's projection of a resident
population of the United States of 270.4 million, each of us would
cough up just under 15 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Every time I ask my bank for Susan B. Anthony dollar coins,
I'm told that there are very few left, or none at all. Is the
government trying to take them out of circulation? Also, I've never
seen any that were not minted in 1979 or 1980. Were these the only
two years they were made?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Susan B. Anthony dollar coin was minted for circulation
only in '79 and '80, said Michael White of the U.S. Mint; a small
number was minted in '81, but only for uncirculated sets.
</P>
<P>
   The probable reason your bank doesn't have the coins is that
there's so little customer demand for them, White said. But a bank
can order them from the Mint if it chooses. As of July 31, 83.3
million of the Anthony coins were still in the Mint's inventory and
available to banks.
</P>
<P>
   The government is not trying to take them out of circulation,
and in fact the Mint would like to see all of them in the
possession of the public in the next year or two. If everything
goes according to plan, the stock of Anthony coins should be
depleted by the time a new dollar coin becomes available in 2000,
White said.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, stamp vending machines in many post offices return
the Anthony dollars in change.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm very annoyed at Sen. Orrin Hatch because of his negative
comments about President Clinton, and I want to tell him so. How
can I write him?
</P>
<P>
   A: The address for the lawmaker from Utah: Sen. Orrin G. Hatch,
Russell Senate Office Building, 131, 1st and C streets NE,
Washington, DC 20510.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who was the Republican or Whig party member who voted against
impeaching Andrew Johnson, the Democratic vice president who became
president when Abraham Lincoln was assassinated?
</P>
<P>
   A: The case involved the Tenure of Office Act of March 2, 1867,
which prohibited the president from removing without Senate
approval any presidential appointee who had been confirmed by the
Senate. On Aug. 12, 1867, in defiance of this act, Johnson
dismissed a Cabinet officer, Secretary of War Edwin Stanton.
</P>
<P>
   That move led to a showdown between the president and Congress,
and on Feb. 24, 1868, the House voted 126-47 to impeach Johnson.
His fate then was in the hands of the Senate, which could remove
him from office with a two-thirds vote. On March 13, Johnson's
trial began in the Senate chambers, with Chief Justice Salmon Chase
presiding. Two months later, the Senate voted 35-19 for the
impeachment articles, one vote short of the necessary number needed
for conviction. Although Johnson's radical Republican opponents
controlled the Senate, seven believed that the charges didn't
warrant his removal and voted against conviction.
</P>
<P>
   The decisive not-guilty vote that acquitted Johnson belonged to
freshman Sen. Edmund G. Ross (R-Kan.), and the proceedings
terminated May 26.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When Billy Mayfair won the Buick Classic golf tournament
recently, he dedicated his victory to the wife of Stuart Appleby.
What happened to her?
</P>
<P>
   A: Renay Appleby, 25, was killed July 23 in a freak accident in
London. A cab driver mistakenly thought he was in reverse, and
instead lunged forward into her, crushing her between his car and
another car.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Barney Kessel was one of the greatest jazz guitarists of the
'50s and early '60s. I know he continued to record into the '80s,
and a lot of his albums are now being rereleased on CDs. The last
interview of his that I saw was in 1991. Is he still alive and
playing?
</P>
<P>
   A: Kessel, 74, is still living, but was sidelined by a stroke
several years ago. Along with jazz legends James Moody, Billy May
and Johnny Best, he was honored in May by a benefit, ``Four
Generations of Jazz,'' in San Diego, Kessel's home since 1989.
Proceeds from the concert went to the emergency relief fund of the
Musicians Association of San Diego County. Kessel, who established
his reputation working with Billie Holliday, Charlie Parker, Oscar
Peterson and other jazz greats, was awarded an honorary doctorate
in 1996 from the University of Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have heard Myanmar, which used to be called Burma,
pronounced in many different ways on the local news. What is
correct?
</P>
<P>
   A: Each ``a'' should be pronounced like the a in father; the
emphasis is on ``mar.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Director Steven Spielberg seems to be a convenient target for
criticism, most recently because he didn't include any sight or
mention of African-Americans in ``Saving Private Ryan.'' As I
recall, Spielberg and his company were sued for copyright
infringement in a case involving the film ``Amistad.'' What is the
status of that?
</P>
<P>
   A: Barbara Chase-Riboud, the author who accused Spielberg and
his production company, DreamWorks SKG, of ``brazenly'' stealing
from her work to make ``Amistad,'' dropped her plagiarism suit
against the company in February. Chase-Riboud is the author of such
novels as ``Echo of Lions'' and ``Sally Hemings.'' Her $10 million
copyright infringement lawsuit against DreamWorks said the company
had taken material from ``Echo of Lions'' for ``Amistad.''
</P>
<P>
   DreamWorks lawyers contended that Chase-Riboud had ``lifted
entire passages'' and ``directly taken'' from a book by William
Owens about the Amistad uprising, a true-life revolt in 1839 of
Africans on a slave ship in Cuban waters.
</P>
<P>
   In December, The New York Times published an article saying
Chase-Riboud's 1986 novel ``Valide: A Novel of the Harem''
contained entire passages that appeared in a scholarly book
published 50 years earlier. Chase-Riboud admitted that she had used
the material from the earlier book without attribution, but
asserted she had done nothing wrong. She said DreamWorks was
conducting a ``smear campaign'' against her.
</P>
<P>
   At the time Chase-Riboud's suit was dropped, this statement
attributed to her was released by DreamWorks: ``After my lawyers
had a chance to review DreamWorks' files and other documents and
evidence, my lawyers and I concluded that neither Steven Spielberg
nor DreamWorks did anything improper, and I instructed my lawyers
to conclude this matter in a timely and amicable fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
