<HEADER>
A2722 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS27-TAKE     08-26 1869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS27-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A on the news
 &HT;    By Colin Bessonette
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've seen frequent references to Jane's Intelligence Review
in the news lately in connection with the bombings in Africa and
retaliatory U.S. attacks in Sudan and Afghanistan. Where is this
review based? What is the format? How can I obtain it?
</P>
<P>
   A: The review is one of the enterprises of Jane's Information
Group Ltd., based on Coulsdon, England. It's a monthly magazine
providing what a Jane's spokesman called ``a global view on
security, terrorism and geopolitics'' and deals with worldwide
issues including the recent U.S. embassy bombings in Africa and
subsequent U.S. cruise missile attacks.
</P>
<P>
   A subscription is $330 a year. To subscribe, write Jane's
Information Group, Inc., 1340 Braddock Place, Suite 300,
Alexandria, VA 22314-1651, or call 1-800-824-0768. Or check
www.janes.com on the Internet for complete information about
various Jane's magazines, products and services.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If President Clinton resigns, would he still be eligible for
a pension?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. He would get $151,000 a year, said Pete Sepp of the
National Taxpayers Union. The only way Clinton would lose the
pension would be if he is impeached or convicted under
constitutional procedures, Sepp added.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've been told that when Bill Clinton was running for
Congress in the 1970s, he said something to the effect that if
President Richard Nixon had lied to the government, he should
resign. Can you confirm?
</P>
<P>
   A: In 1974, Clinton, a junior faculty member at the University
of Arkansas law school and Democratic nominee to represent
Arkansas' Third Congressional District, called for Nixon's
resignation with this statement: ``There's not any point in putting
the country through an impeachment since he (Nixon) isn't making
any pretense of innocence now.''
</P>
<P>
   Nixon had surrendered the famous ``smoking gun'' tape in which
he virtually confessed to obstructing justice in the Watergate
affair, which is what Clinton meant by ``now.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: If China's Yangtze is the third-longest in the world. What
are first and second?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Nile, in Tanzania, Uganda, Sudan and Egypt, is No. 1 at
4,145 miles; the Amazon, in Peru and Brazil, is No. 2 at 4,007
miles. The Yangtze-Kiang is 3,915 miles long. For the record, these
are the other rivers and combined rivers making the world's top 10
longest, with lengths in miles: Mississippi-Missouri-Red Rock,
3,710; Yenisey-Angara-Selenga, in Mongolia and Russia, 3,442; Huang
Ho (Yellow River), China, 3,395; Ob'-Irtysh, Mongolia, Kazakhstan
and Russia, 3,362; Zaire (or Congo), Zaire, 2,920; Lena-Kirenga,
Russia, 2,734; Mekong, Tibet, China, Myanmar, Laos, Cambodia and
Vietnam, 2,703.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I saw a dog show in which it was stated that in Britain,
German shepherds are known as ``Alsatians.'' My husband said he had
heard that people in Britain changed the name of the breed as a
result of World War II. Do you have any information?
</P>
<P>
   A: The names indeed are different on either side of the
Atlantic. The Encyclopedia of American Dogs lists the breed under
the name German shepherd, with the subtitle Alsatian. It then goes
on to say the breed is ``in the English-speaking world often
incorrectly called the Alsatian.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gillian Cooper of the British Consulate in Atlanta said she
had never heard the breed called German shepherd until she moved to
the United States. She cited Concise Oxford Dictionary as defining
Alsatian, in reference to dogs, as ``a large breed used as a guard
dog,'' with the name traced to Alsace, a region of eastern France.
The use of the word Alsatian instead of German shepherd ``has
nothing to do with the German people or World War II,'' she added.
``The dogs of that breed have always been called Alsatians in the
United Kingdom.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: I understand that Bo Gritz, leader of that volunteer search
for Eric Rudolph in the mountains of western North Carolina, once
ran for president. Do you have any information?
</P>
<P>
   A: James G. ``Bo'' Gritz, highly decorated Special Forces
veteran and former Green Beret lieutenant colonel, ran as a
Populist Party candidate for president in 1992. He was on the
ballot in 18 states and was a write-in candidate in 24 others,
either as a candidate of the Populists or the America First
Coalition. His slogan: ``God, Guns and Gritz.'' According to
statistics from the Committee for the Study of the American
Electorate, he received 106,911 votes.
</P>
<P>
   Four years earlier, he was a vice presidential candidate on the
Populist Party ticket, but he withdrew when the Populists nominated
former Ku Klux Klan grand wizard and Nazi sympathizer David Duke as
presidential candidate. Also in 1988, Gritz sought California's
American Independent Party nomination for president, receiving
5,401 votes statewide. And in that same year he unsuccessfully
sought the Republican nomination for a Nevada seat in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When Roger Maris hit his 61 home runs in 1961, what was his
batting average and how many RBIs did he have that year?
</P>
<P>
   A: Batting average, .269; runs batted in, 141.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If President Clinton were to resign with more than half of
his second term remaining, and Al Gore became president, would Gore
be eligible to serve two more full terms of his own, or only one?
</P>
<P>
   A: The 22nd Amendment to the Constitution (1951), which
prohibits any person from being elected president more than two
times, also addresses this situation. It says: ``. . . no person
who has acted as president for more than two years of a term to
which some other person was elected president shall be elected to
the office of the president more than once.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: I read months ago that people can buy pieces of coal salvaged
from the wreckage of the Titanic. How can we do that?
</P>
<P>
   A: Contact RMS Titanic, which describes itself as ``the only
company legally entitled to recover objects from the Titanic,'' at
1-800-274-5568 or at www.titanic-online.com if you have Internet
access.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of the quarter-size pieces of coal is $14.99, plus
shipping and handling, with a limit of two per order. The coal is
sealed in a plastic bag and has a certificate of origin, according
to the company. It's packaged in a box similar to what earrings
come in, with the name Titanic on the cover, a company spokeswoman
said. Other Titanic-related memorabilia, such as replicas of cups
and jewely discovered at the wreck site, also are available.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is ``Saving Private Ryan'' based on a true story? Were there
really four soldier brothers in the war? I have a bet riding on
this. I say it's true, but I was told that it's Hollywood fiction.
</P>
<P>
   A: There was no Ryan family. But perhaps the closest thing to
the movie's account is the case of the Niland family, as documented
by author Stephen Ambrose, an expert on World War II. Ambrose wrote
about Pvt. Fritz Niland of Tonawanda, N.Y. Two of Niland's brothers
were killed in the D-Day invasion, and a third was killed in Burma.
Their mother received three telegrams from the War Department
within a short time frame notifying her of her sons' deaths. Her
fourth son, fighting in France, was snatched out of the front line
by the Army and was sent home.
</P>
<P>
   The problem of several members of one family being killed in
combat was a real issue during World War II. The most famous
example of losses to one family was that of the five Sullivan
brothers, who were serving aboard the same Navy vessel and died in
a single engagement. A movie about them was released during World
War II and celebrated the loss as heroic. Many Americans were
appalled that such a thing had been allowed to happen, and the
government stepped up efforts to avoid such situations in the
future. That provided the basic inspiration for ``Saving Private
Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recently saw a TV program about a giant dam being built on
the Yangtze River in China. Was it damaged by the floods this
summer?
</P>
<P>
   A: The worst flooding is along the 1,000-plus-mile stretch of
the Yangtze downriver from the famous Three Gorges landmark. The
dam, scheduled to be completed in 2003, is said to be the biggest
and most technologically challenging in the world. The devastation
downriver occurred because crude earthen dikes, devised thousands
of years ago, failed to stem the surging waters of the world's
third-largest river. Entire counties were submerged and thousands
of homes swept away, with an enormous loss of lives, but the $20
billion dam project wasn't seriously affected.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm trying to help someone who wants to visit the gravesite
of a relative, a World War I veteran buried at Arlington National
Cemetery. Is there a way to locate a particular grave? What are the
hours when the cemetery is open?
</P>
<P>
   A: Just inside the cemetery gates, on Memorial Drive and just
across the Memorial Bridge from Washington, you'll find the Visitor
Center. Free maps are available, and the staff can provide
information about the location of specific gravesites. Cemetery
hours: 8 a.m.-7 p.m. April 1-Sept. 30; 8 a.m.-5 p.m. Oct. 1-March
31.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If President Clinton resigns or is impeached, and Vice
President Al Gore succeeds to the presidency, who becomes the new
vice president?
</P>
<P>
   A: There's no automatic person or office in that situation. No
provision was made in the original Constitution to fill vacancies
in the office of vice president. But in 1965, Congress passed the
25th Amendment, part of which established a mechanism for replacing
departed vice presidents, not by succession but by presidential
appointment and congressional confirmation. The amendment was
ratified by the states and became part of the Constitution in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   So in your scenario, Gore would nominate someone to fill his
previous office after he became president, and the nominee would
take office when confirmed by a majority vote of both houses of
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A recent article mentioned a security system for automobiles
called LoJack. It helps police find stolen vehicles. Where can I
get more information about LoJack?
</P>
<P>
   A: LoJack is available through many auto dealerships. If you
have Internet access, the LoJack site _ www.lojack.com _ lets you
enter your state and type of vehicle, and then it will list
appropriate dealers. If you don't have Internet access, write
LoJack, 333 Elm St., Dedham, MA 02026, or call 781-326-4700.
</P>
<P>
   LoJack transmitters cost about $595. The device, about the size
of a deck of cars, is placed somewhere in the vehicle. If the
vehicle is reported stolen, it can be tracked by police using
high-tech tracking equipment. The company reports about a 90
percent recovery rate nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Has there ever been a first lady who filed for divorce while
her husband was in office?
</P>
<P>
   A: No ``first couple'' has been divorced while the husband was
president.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
