<P>
   TEXAS STORMS
</P>
<P>
   BRIDGE-CLOSING _ LAREDO, Texas _ Business people on both sides
of the border waited nervously this week to hear whether the Laredo
bridge closings would be a small inconvenience or a big financial
blow. Officials closed commercial traffic over the two
international bridges connecting Laredo's downtown to that of Nuevo
Laredo in Mexico. When they will reopen depends on the Rio Grande.
Crossings at Del Rio and Colombia are also closed indefinitely.
(Hawkins/Wear, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WEATHER-WARNINGS _ AUSTIN, Texas _ The deadly floods on the
Texas-Mexico border point out an old problem for Texans: the need
for timely warning of severe weather while there's still a chance
to get out of its way. (Stanley, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   AQUIFER-FILLING _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Remnants of Tropical Storm
Charley dumped more rain on the western edge of the Hill Country,
adding 12 inches to the western portion of the Edwards Aquifer and
boosting estimates of water level increases at Lake Travis. The
aquifer already saw a 6.3-foot rise over the weekend, and the
recent addition of several inches of rain continued to brighten the
outlook for San Antonio's water supply. (Stanley, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE (l category)
</P>
<P>
   NEWS-QUESTIONS_ Q&AMP;A on the news, in four takes. (Bessonnette,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) (l, a)
</P>
<P>
   FAMILY-MISSION _ Gather the spouse, kids and Lassie and write a
mission or vision statement. What is the purpose of your family?
What are your core values? Where do you want to be in five years?
Mission statement? Core values? Sounds more like running a business
than a family, right? Wrong, according to motivational guru Stephen
R. Covey. (Lyles, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CLIFFSNOTES-MAIN _ Your buddy Cliffs Notes has turned 40. The
Lincoln, Neb., company that publishes the pamphlets is celebrating
the milestone in a big way. And there's a new Web site that touts
real-life stories of how Cliffs saved the day (www.cliffs.com).
(Houck, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   HILLEGASS _ Forget the millions of copies of pamphlets with his
name on them all over the world. Cliff Hillegass, 81, is awed by
the impact his Cliffs Notes study aids have had on education and
American culture. ``I have always classified Cliff as a people
person,'' Covolik said. ``He has a great deal of warmth.'' (He does
not, however, give interviews.) (Houck, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CLIFFSNOTES-TEACH _ ``English teachers love to hate Cliffs
Notes,'' said Carol Jago, who served on the National Council of
Teachers of English's literature commission. A high school English
teacher for 25 years in Santa Monica, Calif., Jago says the ``truth
of it is, they are good study aids.'' (Houck, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CLIFFSNOTES-SIDE _ The Top 10 Cliffs Notes. (Houck, Palm Beach
Post) MOVED.
