<P>
   _ U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas
ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY -- No. 399 -- August 26, 1998 We are offering
the following articles for sale. Please contact us for availability
your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
</P>
<P>
   1. TODAY'S BLOCKBUSTER HOLLYWOOD SCRIPT FACTORY One writer adds
a few jokes, another beefs up romance, still another polishes
dialogue - these days, a big budget movie travels an ever-growing
conveyor belt of specialists to production. By Jaime Wolf. From The
New York Times Magazine. 2,000 words. 2. THE UNSINKABLE CELINE DION
The ``Titanic'' soundtrack has sold 25 million copies. It's the
top-selling soundtrack of all time and the best-selling record of
the year. It's the fuel that has propelled Canadian singer Celine
Dion into a Streisand-like stratosphere, from which she will mount
a two-year world tour. In this interview she says the
emotion-drenched song ``My Heart Will Go On'' was recorded in just
one take. By Steve Morse. BPI. 1,200 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 3.
'CELEBRITY DEATHMATCH' CATCHES ON MTV has found a hit in
``Celebrity Deathmatch.'' Using clay figures, it matches
celebrities on screen in combat. The animated half-hour shows drop
news makers into a wrestling ring, where they can pulverize each
other. (Hillary Rodham Clinton hammering away at a certain ex-White
House intern, for instance, is a scene unlikely to be realized
anywhere else but here.) Matthew Phenix looks at this phenomenon
and talks to the show's creator. From The New York Times. 800 words
+ photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 4.
WESLEY SNIPES SHARPENS ``BLADE'' ``Blade'' is not for the squeamish
- the vampire-action movie spills buckets of blood. Wesley Snipes
is both star and producer of the film, which delivers a visceral
punch both as a horror movie and as a mystery. One of the first
African-American comic-book heroes, ``Blade'' is a human with the
characteristics of a vampire. (The superhero dispatches an
ever-growing legion of the undead whose goal is to take over the
planet.) `` 'Blade' gave me an opportunity to pay homage to some of
the classic Asian films,'' says Snipes, who is trained in the
martial arts. By Joshua Mooney. BPI. 1,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   5. DANCES WITH RANDA HAINES Randa Haines is the seemingly
mild-mannered director of films like ``Children Of A Lesser God''
and ``The Doctor'' - emotional dramas about people struggling to
communicate. Her latest film is set in the rhythm-heavy world of
professional salsa dancing and, in the end, this film too is about
communication. Haines is passionate about salsa, ever since she
went to a salsa club by accident a few years ago, where she met a
dancer who had an idea for a screenplay. The result is ``Dance With
Me,'' starring Vanessa Williams and Puerto Rican music sensation
Chayanne. The moves and music are hot, while the film itself is
old-fashioned. (Haines says she even took out a love scene to put
in more dancing.) By Joshua Mooney. BPI. 1,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 6.
KELSEY GRAMMER Kelsey Grammer's acclaimed TV comedy series
``Frasier'' is in its sixth season. Grammer talks about his demons
and how he puts pressure on himself in the role of a psychiatrist.
By Ian Spelling. 1,200 words + photo. 7. FACE VALUE : SHRINKING
GRAMMER In this new cartoon feature, cartoonist Ricardo Castaneda
offers a view of Kelsey Grammer in his hit TV comedy show
``Frasier.''
_______________________________________________________________ 8.
LARENZ TATE HAS THREE WIVES AT THE SAME TIME - ON
</P>
<P>
   FILM, OF COURSE Larenz Tate is fairly unknown, but in the
upcoming movie ``Why Do Fools Fall in Love?'' he plays a 1950's
black singer who marries three women at the same time. Only they
don't know about each other. Discussing his first starring role,
Tate talks about what it was like to marry three women, and
describes his climb up the Hollywood ladder. By Cindy Pearlman.
1,400 words + photo
_______________________________________________________________ 9.
THE STRANGE WORLD OF TRIBUTE BANDS Low-grade acts have ruined the
reputation of many tribute bands, but in many respects they do have
a head start over groups who are agonizing over original material.
They play familiar songs and have a ready-made fan base. Some
hard-working groups have earned their own share of fame through
paying tribute to someone else. There is even a website which
provides information and links tribute bands all over the world.
Perhaps one of the most famous tribute groups is ``Bjorn Again,''
(Abba,) which has played at concerts in more than 30 countries. By
Jason Zasky. From Musician magazine. 1,800 words.
</P>
