<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY YOU DON'T NEED A LAPTOP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By HIAWATHA BRAY   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since it's the season for confessions, here's mine: I, Hiawatha
Bray, technology reporter, don't own a laptop. Never have, and with
luck, never will.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing against laptops, you understand. They're pretty cool _
until you switch one on and the red-hot Pentium chip inside sets
your lap on fire. And then there's the misery of running through
airports with 10 pounds of dead weight slung over your shoulder,
and the bother of turning it on under the suspicious eye of the
ladies at the metal detector.
</P>
<P>
   And heaven help you if you put the computer down for a moment
and turn your back. According to Safeware, a Columbus, Ohio,
insurer, thieves made off with over a billion dollars' worth of
laptops last year. That's not as remarkable a number as it sounds.
Laptops generally cost two or three times as much as an equivalent
desktop machine.
</P>
<P>
   I've been known to borrow a laptop from the Globe for a road
trip. Frankly, it's one reason I avoid road trips. And when I do
ship out, I look for excuses not to take a computer.
</P>
<P>
   I wish more of my guests would do the same. Several times a
month, computer executives drop into the Globe, laptops in tow, to
inflict a uniquely modern method of torture _ the PowerPoint slide
show. PowerPoint is a presentation graphics program that comes
along with the more useful parts of the Microsoft Office software
suite.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing that they're stuck with it anyway, some people can't bear
to let PowerPoint sit idle. Instead they waste hours of their time
whipping up a couple dozen tedious slides, and a half-hour of mine
showing them off.
</P>
<P>
   PowerPoint shows have their uses _ they're helpful when
addressing large groups, for instance. But more often than not,
they're a waste of good electrons. Next time you go to pitch a
client, print out your notes and charts on a few sheets of paper,
and leave the laptop behind.
</P>
<P>
   A computer also makes a handy way to carry around your address
book and appointment list, if you don't mind booting up every time
you have to check. Better to tote one of those pocket-sized digital
assistants for that purpose. There's the 3Com PalmPilot for around
$300, or the Franklin Rex, for as little as $129.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, you don't have to carry your contact information at
all. Store it on the Internet, and it'll be available to you from
any Web site. The Cambridge-based PlanetAll Internet community
offers just such a service free of charge. It'll accept data from
Microsoft's Outlook information manager, or a PalmPilot, and links
to other information managers are under development.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, to use your PlanetAll contact data, you need access
to the Web. But that's a mighty strange reason to haul a $4,000
gadget around. If you need a computer, use somebody else's. It's
taking long enough, but public Internet access points are gradually
popping up throughout the country. Alas, they're not always easy to
find. That's a good excuse to bookmark an impressive Internet site,
the Internet Cafe Guide at
</P>
<P>
   http://www.netcafeguide.com. Here you can find listings of 1,700
Internet cafes in 98 countries, and Internet kiosks in hotels and
airports.
</P>
<P>
   Cybercafes come and go, and you might not want to bet your
livelihood on one of them. The business services firm Kinko's is
another matter. There are 900 Kinko's shops in the United States,
with Internet-linked computers in every one. Expect to pay about
$12 an hour to use them, with extra charges for printouts.
</P>
<P>
   Once you're on line, you shouldn't have any trouble getting your
e-mail, as long as your company's mail server uses the standard
POP3 protocol. You can hardly visit a Web site without seeing an
offer for free e-mail service. Say you sign up for a free account
at Microsoft's HotMail site. You get yet another e-mail address to
play with. But you can also set it up to act as a mailbox for any
POP3 account you may have. Now you can get your e-mail wherever
there's a Web browser.
</P>
<P>
   None of this matters to some of you _ the engineers and such who
have to lug their high-tech firepower wherever they go. But amateur
gearheads like me can do without. And very likely, so can you.
</P>
<P>
   (You can send Hiawatha Bray electronic mail at
bray(at)globe.com)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-20-98 1341EDT &QL;
</P>
