<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Wednesday, Aug. 26, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Thursday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PEPPER-SPRAY (San Francisco) _ The forewoman of the jury that
deadlocked on whether sheriff's deputies used excessive force by
daubing pepper spray around the eyes of non-violent protesters
called the police action disturbing. The federal jury of 6 men and
two women deadlocked 4-4 Tuesday, and U.S. District Judge Vaughn
Walker set Nov. 16 for a new trial. By SETH ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   AFFIRMATIVE-ACTION (San Francisco) _ San Francisco Mayor Willie
Brown, brushing aside the threat of lawsuits, is backing an effort
to keep San Francisco's affirmative action program in place for
another five years despite California's Proposition 209 that barred
race and gender preferences for government contracts. By GREGORY
LEWIS.
</P>
<P>
   DESTROYER-VET (Albany, N.Y.) _ It had been 53 years since Ed
Whitmore stood on the deck of a World War II destroyer escort, 53
years since he'd hunted German U-boats. He was among 510 members of
the Destroyer Escort Sailors Association and their spouses who came
to Albany to visit the USS Slater, the last destroyer escort still
afloat in the United States. By EDWARD FITZPATRICK.
</P>
<P>
   PHYSICIANS-EXECUTION (San Francisco) _ A lawsuit seeking to bar
doctors from participating in executions may be an attempt to stop
something that isn't happening. A spokeswoman for the California
Department of Corrections said technicians, not doctors, insert the
intravenous line that delivers the lethal drugs to the condemned
prisoner. By ULYSSES TORASSA.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CAREERS (San Francisco) _ As far as Eric Douglas is concerned,
good communication is a matter of style. The author of the recently
published ``Straight Talk'' believes that people will do better in
work and in life if they understand not only their own
communication style, but the styles of associates. By DAVE MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MAGNET-THERAPY (Albany, N.Y.) _ Skeptics call it hype. Believers
offer personal testimonials to back up their claims that magnets
aren't just for the refrigerator anymore. Suffer from lower back
pain? There's a magnetic seat cushion. Have a headache? Try a
magnetic headband. By SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-MAGAZINES (Undated) _ If anyone wonders what is one of the
fastest-growing segments in the publishing industry, take a look at
your local newsstands. You will find more and more titles dealing
with herbs, tea, beer and the various ethnic cuisines. By WILLIAM
M. DOWD.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-HILLS (Undated) _ Tamara Jenkins' new movie, ``Slums
of Beverly Hills,'' is sneaky. Disguised as a comedy, the film
tackles such weighty subjects as the sexual objectification of
women and the effects of class consciousness on a decidedly
downwardly mobile family. Thank God none of that is evident in the
advance publicity or people would likely stay away from this movie
in droves, which would be a shame. By CRAIG MARINE.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-CUTRUFELLO-REVIEW (Houston) _ Mary Cutrufello, 27, is on
the edge of living out her dream. Her major-label debut, ``When the
Night Is Through,'' was released Tuesday on Mercury Records, and
she'll appear on ``The Tonight Show'' Thursday. Says her manager,
Holly Gleason: ``To Mercury, it's `This is a great record,' not
`This is a great record for a black woman from Yale with dreadlocks
playing guitar.''' By RICK MITCHELL.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-McGWIRE-SUPPLEMENT (Albany, N.Y.) _ The man must bring the
national nightmare to an end so that we can all get on with our
lives. It's time. The man needs to throw himself on the mercy of
the court of public opinion. He doesn't have a private life. He
belongs to the American people. Mark McGwire needs to say: ``All
the reports and rumors are true. I'm guilty of using a dietary
supplement in conjunction with my exercise program.'' By STEVE
CAMPBELL.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Here's where I hit the wall on
President Clinton and his problems. I was reading the transcript of
Monday's White House briefing by press secretary Mike McCurry. I
read these to congratulate myself on not being a White House
reporter. I wouldn't even accept the Martha's Vineyard beach beat.
By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Schenectady, N.Y.) _ Despite efforts by the city
to shut down strip joints, a federal judge has ruled that stripping
to some music is a form of expression protected by the
Constitution. The battle will cost taxpayers a few hundred grand.
This is what happens when politicians try to impose their visions
of morality and art appreciation on everybody else. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
</TEXT>
