<SLUG> BC-CPT-INTERNET-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Online global voices expand debate, news 
By Frances Katz  
c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Americans glued to CNN, MSNBC or ABCNews.com can get
another perspective on the cruise missile strikes by visiting
international news and information Web sites and chat areas.
</P>
<P>
   Here, it's possible to get a glimpse of how the United States
and its foreign policy are perceived around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the English-language information is a few days old, but
it provides insight on American relations with Sudan and
Afghanistan before Thursday's strikes.
</P>
<P>
   An interview with Osama bin Laden, whose network was the target
of the strikes, appears on the Web site of the fundamentalist
Islamic Azzam Publications, http://www.
</P>
<P>
   webstorage.com/(tilde)azzam/html/.usamahbinladin.html). The site
is devoted to advancing the cause of Islamic holy war. Other
articles talk about fragile relations between the United States and
Afghanistan before the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Real-time chats are another way to gauge world reaction.
</P>
<P>
   Surprise, shock and stunned amazement were the Islamic world's
online reactions to the U.S. attacks on Sudan and Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are American acts not terrorist when they kill civilians
in Iraq or anyplace else?'' asked one chat participant in a
Muslim-oriented chat room sponsored by Taliban Online.
</P>
<P>
   Taliban Online, http://www.taliban.com, the English-language Web
site of the controversial fundamentalist group, had a small but
passionate group discussion about the action and U.S. foreign
policy in general.
</P>
<P>
   The conversation was not a unilateral call for a jihad or
terrorist acts against the United States. Rather, it was a
thoughtful discussion of how the Islamic world should respond to
U.S. foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it has become clear that terrorism is a U.S. policy,''
said one chat room participant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe (terrorism) is the only language they will understand,''
said another.
</P>
<P>
   The few Americans in the chat room seemed as puzzled as their
international counterparts about the motivation behind the strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Some Afghans living abroad reported news they had received from
their families at home. One participant claimed 900 civilians were
killed. Another simply logged on to say none of their family
members was hurt.
</P>
<P>
   The participants in the Taliban chat were primarily Europeans,
Afghans or Pakistanis living abroad.
</P>
<P>
   There were some tense moments when one American entered into a
heated debate with another chat room member.
</P>
<P>
   ``It matters that brothers allow the slaughter of other
brothers, and that should not be allowed,'' said one.
</P>
<P>
   ``So you support killing Americans, but not Muslims?'' asked
another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right.''
</P>
<P>
   But for the most part, the participants in this chat spent more
time wondering what motivated the attacks than how or when to
retaliate.
</P>
<P>
   Most chat room members were interested in discussing peace
rather than war. Much of the discussion centered around whether the
United States or any nation could solve anything through terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no justification for what the U.S. or any nation is
doing,'' said one person.
</P>
<P>
   Added another, ``Somebody has to break the circle of violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
