<HEADLINE>
TIME TO GO BACK TO `SWEAR' ONE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY  
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: Not long after I installed Win95 on my PC this
spring (after a memory upgrade), it refused to start up correctly.
About halfway through the startup cycle, I get a recurring message,
``Unable to read Drive C: Abort, Retry, Ignore.'' Is this
catastrophic?
</P>
<P>
   _ Breakdown
</P>
<P>
   DEAR BREAK: You are, to use a technical term, hosed.
</P>
<P>
   There are a lot of reasons you may be getting that error
message. Most of them are pretty grim, but don't give up. The first
thing you should do is dig back into the computer's innards to make
sure everything is hooked up correctly. Doublecheck the big flat
cable that hooks the drive to your motherboard or drive controller
card. Some have special tabs that will only allow a correct
connection and keep you from being a dunce; some don't. If you have
one that doesn't, look for a red stripe on one side of the cable
and make sure it goes to the same number pin on either end.
</P>
<P>
   There may be more than one place to plug the cable in, so dig
through the trash until you find the instruction manual, which
should have a motherboard diagram. Now, make sure the four-wire
power connector is tightly in its socket on the drive.
</P>
<P>
   Also check the drive for a little jumper that should be set to
the ``master'' position instead of ``slave.'' Do you think the guy
who dreamed that up was feeling lonely?
</P>
<P>
   Assuming everything's hooked up right and that you didn't at
some point spill your tropical drink into the computer so that the
little paper umbrella is jamming the works, try booting again.
Didn't work? Ha ha ha ha ha ha! Sorry. Just my cruel little joke. I
didn't think all that would work, but you never know.
</P>
<P>
   As long as you've got the case open, take out the memory you
added. I don't think that will work either, but we need to try and
get things back to the way they were before the trouble started.
</P>
<P>
   Now try starting your computer's built-in setup program. It's
possible a bad battery caused the PC to forget what sort of hard
drive it had. You'll have to dig out the books to figure out all
the gibberish it's asking for, but if it indicates that you
currently have no hard drive, there's your problem. Of course, if
that really were the case, it should also be forgetting things like
the correct time or whether you have a floppy drive.
</P>
<P>
   Most likely, you have a physically corrupted hard drive. No,
that's not Freudian. It just means something's goobered up on your
disk. Make yourself a boot floppy disk (oh, just find a geek at
work who knows how to do it) with Scandisk.exe on it. Start things
up, then run Scandisk on your hard drive to repair things. Didn't
work? I'm not surprised.
</P>
<P>
   There are about a hundred other things you can try, but stop
making yourself crazy. Nuke the drive. Reformat it and start over.
It's not doing you any good like it is. And get your geek buddy to
help. That way you can blame him if anything else goes wrong.
</P>
<P>
   If things still aren't working, then the drive is probably
cratered. New ones are cheap and not that hard to install, but have
the store do the work anyway. If the real culprit is a bad
motherboard, you won't have to mess with returning the drive. All
you'll have to do is figure out how to pay for a new computer. And
this time, don't buy the cheapest one in the store.
</P>
<P>
   OK, OK, you can try replacing the motherboard first. I was just
trying to save you some frustration. And, no, I don't get a
kickback from the store. We're still negotiating that.
</P>
<P>
   (Noted computerologist Dr. Emilio Bombay offers occasionally
accurate advice about most things electronic. He can be reached on
Internet at drbombay(at)star-telegram.com; via snail-mail at Fort
Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth 76101; or fax: (817)
390-7257. His real name is Michael Gerst, editorial systems manager
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-21-98 1440EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-26-98 1124EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
