<SLUG> BC-CPT-ONLINEBANKS-IMPROVEMENTS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BETTER FEATURES, ACCESS HAS CUSTOMERS BANKING ON THE WEB 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By PETER SINTON   
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Online banking has a growing number of fans but it has yet to
become a favorite indoor pastime.
</P>
<P>
   That could soon change as more financial institutions let
customers bank with ease over the Internet and work out ways for
customers to get their bills as well as pay them online.
</P>
<P>
   Just 3 percent of U.S. households now use their home computers
to transfer money between accounts and pay bills, according to
Forrester Research of Cambridge, Mass. However, this is expected to
jump to 20 percent of households within five years.
</P>
<P>
   Driving this growth are falling computer prices, better
encryption systems to protect online privacy, more online banking
features and easier access.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the 1990s, banks have been touting the virtues of
banking online _ checking balances, transferring funds between
accounts and paying bills without the bother of writing a check,
sticking a stamp on the envelope and trotting to the mailbox.
</P>
<P>
   Online banking was supposed to save both banks and their
customers untold millions of dollars and hours of time. But
economic benefits have been hard to measure.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, home banking was cumbersome. Customers had to
load their computers with special software and dial toll-free
numbers. Often, they were told the service was down.
</P>
<P>
   But things are getting better. About 80 percent of the top 100
banks now offer online banking over the Internet, making it much
easier for consumers to access their accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the greatest innovations are happening right here in the
Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   Bank of America is the nation's best Internet bank and Wells
Fargo ranks No. 3, according to Gomez Advisors, which tracks online
financial services.
</P>
<P>
   BofA ranks best in two of five categories: customer confidence
and relationship services (which covers the number of products that
can be accessed online).
</P>
<P>
   In another ranking,SmartMoney magazine in June declared
Citibank, BofA, BankBoston and Wells Fargo the top four cyberbanks.
</P>
<P>
   PC-savvy consumers are particularly keen on online banking. ``I
do pretty much everything online but get cash,'' said Niall McKay,
an Irish journalist who banks with Wells Fargo. ``It beats dealing
with a teller. Since decisions are made by computers anyway, it's
better to deal with the computer itself.''
</P>
<P>
   The first time consumers like McKay pay a bill online, they
usually have to type in the name, address and phone number of the
payee as well as their account number. The next time the same bill
comes, however, all they have to do is enter the amount and the
date they want the payment sent. If they want to pay the same
amount on the same date each month (for mortgage or cable TV
bills), they can schedule these payments for up to a year with just
one click.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only negative is that they should pay me for using the
service,'' said McKay. ``Like booking cinema tickets over the
phone, it saves time and is cheaper for everyone, so I don't see
why the bank should charge $5 a month (for bill payment services)
unless you have a $5,000 balance.''
</P>
<P>
   Fees for those who don't meet minimum balance requirements or
have their paychecks deposited automatically have kept some
potential online customers at bay.
</P>
<P>
   Some banks, though, not only provide online banking for free,
they offer incentives to try it.
</P>
<P>
   Citibank, for example, is offering $25 cash to new customers who
use its Direct Access Internet banking service to pay at least two
bills by September 30. Citibank is targeting customers in
California because its research shows that 40 percent of the 26
million households that surf the Web live here.
</P>
<P>
   To lure customers, banks are offering more and more services
online, including stock trading and loan applications.
</P>
<P>
   But some researchers doubt that one-stop shopping is what
customers want.
</P>
<P>
   After surveying 126,000 consumers this year, Forrester Research
reports that online consumers have accounts with four different
financial institutions on average, and 84 percent of them are more
interested in going to multiple sites for ``best-of-breed''
services than getting everything with one click of the mouse.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that ``banks increasingly view online banking
as a delivery channel rather than a product that can be sold by
itself,'' said David Weisman, a Forrester Research director.
</P>
<P>
   At Wells Fargo, 470,000 customers _ about 10 percent of the
bank's total _ use online banking and the number is growing about
1,000 per day.
</P>
<P>
   Bank of America's online customer base doubled last year and is
expected to grow another 70 percent this year, according to
Executive Vice President Mike DeVico. The service costs $5.95 per
month for unlimited bill payment but this fee is waived for direct
deposit and many other customers.
</P>
<P>
   Even more consumers will likely rush online when they are able
to get their bills as well as pay them online. ``The next killer
app will be bill presentment,'' said Wells Executive Vice President
Dudley Nigg.
</P>
<P>
   Wells is one of the banks testing electronic delivery of bills
using technology from Microsoft and First Data Corp.
</P>
<P>
   A competing joint venture involves Integrion, a collaboration of
banks, IBM and CheckFree that processes about 85 million online
bank payments annually.
</P>
<P>
   Individual companies, including AT&AMP;T, Con Edison and BellSouth,
are testing billing their own customers online. But most consumers
would prefer getting their bills from one Web site rather than
multiple sites.
</P>
<P>
   Complex technical issues have held up broad introduction of
online billing.
</P>
<P>
   Nigg expects ``meaningful consumer trials'' early next year. But
Forrester's Weisman expects ``it will take until 2001 for bill
presentment to reach critical mass.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-24-98 0104EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-26-98 1125EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980826.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 11:26 </DATE_TIME>
