u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-CYBERSCENE25-COX &LR;      08-26 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-CYBERSCENE25-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Year 2000 exchanges magic for hysteria 
By Bill Husted  
c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For those who are middle-aged or older, the Year 2000 had a
magical sort of feeling. Back in the '60s and '70s, the new
millennium was seen as almost impossibly far away. And, if folks
thought about a Year 2000 problem at all back then, the problem was
in living that long.
</P>
<P>
   The Year 2000 is almost here now. It's no longer magical. And,
for the governments and businesses of the world, it is a
multi-billion dollar problem.
</P>
<P>
   By now, unless you live in a cave somewhere around Katmandu, you
have read all about the Y2K bug that plagues many computers. The
stories have taken on an almost hysterical tone, with serious (and
perhaps credible) predictions of everything from a paralyzed air
traffic control system, to the failure of the government to be able
to handle Social Security payments, to a nuclear war triggered by
faulty software running the missile system in some relatively
underdeveloped country.
</P>
<P>
   Since even the experts have trouble agreeing and since _ for
people who aren't computer programmers _ the problem itself is so
difficult to understand, let's start today's trek through the World
Wide Web at a site that provides a very basic look at the problem,
what causes it, and what makes fixing the problem so difficult.
</P>
<P>
   The site is called What is the Y2K Millennium Problem and it's
located at http://www-de
</P>
<P>
   .ksc.nasa.gov/specsintact
</P>
<P>
   /sib1096/year2000/sld003.htm. As you'll notice, this is a NASA
site. The information is presented in slide show fashion. Instead
of clicking on links, use the VCR-like control buttons at the
bottom of the page to move ahead or backwards on the site.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the lack of fancy graphics, this site can be a little
slow. If you'd like a faster text page, simply press the icon for
the letter ``A'' on that same control panel.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft also has a slide show that's the heart of an online
seminar called Solving the Year 2000 Problem. You'll find the show
at http://www
</P>
<P>
   .microsoft.com/seminar/98
</P>
<P>
   /Y2KStrategy714/portal.htm. By Microsoft's estimate you'll be
able to cover the material _ presented on 17 slides _ in little
over 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are, especially for PC users, a lot of the software in
your computer comes from Microsoft. The giant software company has
done a good job explaining the problem and offering help.
</P>
<P>
   If you're still hungry for more information from Microsoft,
there's an entire collection of links that deals with almost every
aspect of the Year 2000 problem. You'll find this general purpose
collection at http://www
</P>
<P>
   .microsoft.com/year2000
</P>
<P>
   /?RLD &QC; 53. Once there, you can follow the links to pages that
offer information at various degrees of technical complexity.
You'll also find a link to a section that lets you find out just
what problems Microsoft's own software has with the Year 2000 bug.
</P>
<P>
   While at the Microsoft site, make sure you visit the FAQ
(frequently asked questions) section devoted to the problem at
http://www.microsoft.com
</P>
<P>
   /ithome/topics/year2k/2kfaq
</P>
<P>
   /2kfaq01.htm. You'll have to search hard to find a place that
does a better job explaining almost any facet of the problem. And
since it's organized by question, you can jump right to the part
that interested you most.
</P>
<P>
   This is all serious stuff. And by now, if you've followed all
the links, you may be a bit depressed. So save this link for last.
It's called 12 Reasons to Ignore the Y2K Problem at
http://www.ecl.udel.edu/(tilde)hague
</P>
<P>
   /ignore.htm.
</P>
<P>
   Among the reasons cited: ``4. Nostradamus never mentioned this
problem. 5. You believe a comet is due to hit the Earth in 2000 _
why bother?''
</P>
<P>
