<SLUG> BC-CPT-MAC-REPORT25-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
iMac making mark in sales, offering a symbolic success for fallen
Apple 
By Charles Haddad  
c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ This week was one of the most important in Apple
Computer's recent history.
</P>
<P>
   It marked the company's re-entry into the consumer market. And
it was quite a debut.
</P>
<P>
   Star of the ball was its iMac computer, a model that includes a
built-in screen and retails for $1,299. It's the best deal Apple
Computer has ever offered on a new computer.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, iMac sales have been brisk. Stores in Atlanta
and nationwide have reported people standing in line to see this
new computer, which resembles an iridescent gumdrop.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the iMac was selling well before Apple Computer even
released it. The company announced two weeks ago that it had
pre-sold 150,000 iMacs.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts are forecasting that Apple Computer will
sell 250,000 iMacs by year-end, helping raise sales nearly 13.5
percent to 740,000 for the fourth quarter. The company sold 652,000
computers in the same period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, brisk sales of the iMac are expected to dilute the
company's profit margin. That's because the iMac sells for such a
low price. Wall Street analysts estimate Apple's profit margin will
shrink to about 20 percent from a current 25.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   While not a financial windfall, the iMac is an important
symbolic success for Apple. It has repositioned the company as once
again the computer industry's hip innovator.
</P>
<P>
   Reviewers in The Wall Street Journal, New York Times and other
leading newspapers have heralded the iMac as the most interesting
new computer since, well, the original Mac. It also was an
all-in-one unit.
</P>
<P>
   These high-profile reviews have more than turned back the storm
of criticism that nearly swamped the company during the past two
years. Respect for the company is rising and so is its profit and
market share, although it remains a small player with about 5
percent of total computer sales.
</P>
<P>
   What Apple needs to do now, many observers believe, is expand
its small market share. That means attracting customers other than
current Mac users. Will the iMac do that? Industry observers say
it's too early to tell.
</P>
<P>
   While selling well now, the iMac may lose steam once users start
kicking the tires. It lacks some key features standard in most
computers today. One of them is a floppy drive, which lets users
easily copy and move files via a 3.5 inch disk.
</P>
<P>
   Another feature missing is standard connections for today's
peripherals such as printers. The iMac instead uses a new standard
that the industry is slowing moving toward.
</P>
<P>
   What that means is users will have to buy either a new printer
or a special device that lets them use their old ones with the
iMac. And, of course, that adds to the computer's price.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-24-98 1040EDT &QL;
</P>
