<SLUG> BC-CPT-DIGICAM25-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
It's a snap taking a photo now that you can see and send almost
instantly 
By Kristi E. Swartz  
c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Strike a pose.
</P>
<P>
   Grab a disc.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the film, just say ``cheese.''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to digital cameras _ photography of the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Perfect for the impatient, the computer geek or anyone who wants
to see photos in seconds, these hand-held and sometimes
pocket-sized cameras allow you to snap pictures, and see the images
on a computer screen or on paper within minutes. And you can use
your computer to edit the photographs _ no darkroom required.
</P>
<P>
   Like any other high-tech toy, these cameras are becoming more
available and more affordable to consumers. They now range in price
from $200 for low-end, user-friendly models to $800 for the most
technologically advanced. The average price is about $500.
</P>
<P>
   When the cameras first hit the market several years ago,
professional photographers and techies were the only ones with
their fingers on the flashes. Now cameras are falling in the hands
of almost everyone _ real estate agents, insurance adjusters and
parents wanting to show off their child's first steps to Grandma
and Grandpa.
</P>
<P>
   James Harris, who works at Elemental Interactive, an
Atlanta-based Internet development company, has been using a
digital camera to check out commercial real estate and office
furniture in San Francisco, where the company just opened a new
office.
</P>
<P>
   The company bought a camera a year ago, and employees took it
across the country to snap shots of potential office space, desks,
chairs, carpets, etc.
</P>
<P>
   Harris bought his own digital camera to take on vacation. Last
year, he and some friends created a Web page of their snowboarding
trip to show to the friends who couldn't make it to the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot easier to take these digital pictures and put them
on the Web and e-mail them to people instead of taking regular
pictures and having them developed and scanned in,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone should throw away their film and pick up these
digital gadgets. Here's the advice consumers get from a local
photography expert.
</P>
<P>
   ``They take terrible pictures, that's the first thing I tell
them,'' said Cliff Whitney, Wolf Camera vice president for
technology development.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get him wrong. Whitney raves about the cameras, as long as
the prints are only to be viewed on a computer screen. For that
kind of application, the images are just as serviceable as those
from a film camera. But when the images are turned into prints, the
film camera is much better.
</P>
<P>
   And no matter how you use them, Wolf Camera and Video is a top
vendor of these toys. The cameras are becoming all the more popular
with people being more Net friendly. Eastman Kodak and Olympus
America are the top manufacturers, with nearly 40 other ones close
on their heels. The cameras also can be found in such stores as
Best Buy, Sharper Image and Brookstone.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to be film-free, the first thing to tell the
behind-the-counter camera salesperson is how you plan to use the
camera, Whitney said. Once that's decided, he said it's best to buy
a digital camera that's similar to a typical ``film'' one _ with a
zoom lens and a built-in flash. Kodak's DC210 has a 2X zoom lens,
equivalent to a 29-58mm range on a 35mm camera. It also can take
pictures as close as eight inches, and the lens is focus-free for
point-and-shoot ease.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some other things to consider when shopping:
</P>
<P>
   -- LCD vs. optical viewfinding
</P>
<P>
   An LCD shows images stored in the camera to view before being
loaded up on a computer or printed out. This way you always have a
second chance to get that first shot.
</P>
<P>
   -- Resolution
</P>
<P>
   It plays a major role in the precise detail and quality of
photos taken and in maximum image size you can display or print
without enlarging the photo. Most digital cameras have a resolution
at 640x480, but others in the high-price range, such as the Fuji
MX700, have a resolution of 1280x1024.
</P>
<P>
   -- Uploading images
</P>
<P>
   Before the use of digital cameras, images could be transferred
to a computer using a scanner. Now they can be stored in the camera
with either a floppy disk or a memory card.
</P>
<P>
   Most cameras come with cables to connect the camera directly to
the computer and also software for viewing the images.
</P>
<P>
   -- Printing
</P>
<P>
   Pictures can turn out OK if the printer used has the same
resolution as that of the camera. Anything lower than the camera's
resolution makes shots look grainy or washed out. But prints will
not be anywhere near as good as the ones from a film camera.
</P>
<P>
   (salinity)Please seeCAMERAS, P7
</P>
<P>
   Cameras: What digital offers
</P>
<P>
   (salinity)Continued fromP1
</P>
<P>
   Kodak
</P>
<P>
   The Kodak DC210 offers an LCD viewfinder, a resolution of
1152x864 and storage capacity for 60 photos for $700.
</P>
<P>
   Kodak DC210
</P>
<P>
   Price: $700
</P>
<P>
   Picture storage: 60
</P>
<P>
   Resolution: 1152X864 pixels
</P>
<P>
   Viewfinder:1.8 color LCD
</P>
<P>
   Additions: 2X zoom lens
</P>
<P>
   Epson
</P>
<P>
   The Epson PhotoPC 550, costing $300, has an optical viewfinder
with 640x480 resolution. A separate playback unit (at right) has an
LCD screen for viewing pictures that have been taken.
</P>
