 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
It's eBLAST searching the Net, thanks to Encyclopaedia Britannica 
By John Ghirardini  
c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Encyclopaedia Britannica has been published since
1768, and in the 230 years since its founding in Edinburgh,
Scotland, the venerable reference work has saved countless numbers
of students who waited until the night before an essay was due to
start writing.
</P>
<P>
   The entire 32-volume set has been available on the World Wide
Web since 1994 at http://www.eb.com, and as a two-disc CD-ROM for
Windows and Macintosh computers.
</P>
<P>
   In July the company opened another chapter in its long history
by launching eBLAST, a free Web navigation service featuring a
searchable and browsable directory of more than 125,000 sites
chosen by a team of 25 Britannica editors for their quality and
usefulness.
</P>
<P>
   The site also offers an editorial forum for some of the world's
leading thinkers and writers. Early contributors have included
novelist Scott Turow, Slate editor Michael Kinsley,
artificial-intelligence expert Marvin Minsky and civil rights
activist Lani Guinier.
</P>
<P>
   There are two ways to search on eBLAST. Users can enter a word,
name or phrase in a window on the opening screen, or browse an
outline of 17 major subjects, clicking anywhere in the outline to
find subtopics that will lead to a Web site. eBLAST uses AltaVista
technology for its searches.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best features is the Britannica Quick Search, a
toolbar that gives access to the entire suite of online reference:
eBLAST, Sample Search from the online encyclopedia, and the
Merriam-Webster dictionary and thesaurus. After a one-click
download, the EB button resides in a corner of the computer screen.
All the user has to do is click on it, type in a search term and
indicate the reference desired.
</P>
<P>
   Encyclopaedia Britannica Inc. is based in Chicago. For more
information, call 1-800-747-8503.
</P>
<P>
   New mouse a mighty mite
</P>
<P>
   A lack of available space can be just as much of a problem on a
desktop as it is on a hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   Suncom Technologies is trying to remedy that with its Atom
Mouse.
</P>
<P>
   The mouse measures just 3 1/2-by-3 1/2 inches. To control the
cursor position on the screen, it uses an optical code bar that
moves in a small arc on a stationary pad that takes up no more
space than a trackball. The mouse never leaves the pad.
</P>
<P>
   The company is targeting users of laptop, notebook and portable
computers, and ``road warriors'' who use computers in cars, trains
or planes.
</P>
<P>
   Suncom, the Wheeling, Ill.-based subsidiary of a Hong Kong firm,
is best known for its F-15 Strike Fighter series of joysticks for
air-combat software. For more information, check out the company's
Web site at http://www.suncominc.com.
</P>
<P>
   The Atom Mouse retails for $40.
</P>
<P>
   Bringing fine art home
</P>
<P>
   Images of staggering beauty reside within the walls of museums.
But many of us never get to visit the great repositories of art in
our own country, much less the Prado in Madrid, Spain, or the
Hermitage in St. Petersburg, Russia, or the Louvre in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Software maker Broderbund is trying to bring some of the
museums' offerings to the rest of us with FineArt, the latest in
its ClickArt family of products.
</P>
<P>
   FineArt includes more than 8,500 images, divided into categories
such as scenic watercolors, fine art oil paintings and elegant
landscapes, as well as 36 fonts and four decorative alphabets. The
software is intended for use in cards, invitations, address labels,
advertisements or just about anything that could use an elegant
splash of color to dress it up.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the images are lifted from museum walls, but the company
says each was handpicked based on its beauty and artistry.
</P>
<P>
   The software includes a full-featured image
browser/viewer/converter and works with dozens of desktop
publishing programs. It requires Windows 3.1 or Windows 95 running
on at least a 486 computer with 4 to 8 megabytes of RAM, a
256-color display and a 2X or faster CD-ROM drive.
</P>
<P>
   FineArt retails for $30. Broderbund's other offerings in the
ClickArt series can be seen at the company's Web site:
http://www.broderbund.com.
</P>
<P>
   Bat makers step up to plate
</P>
<P>
   Two baseball bat manufacturers have sued the NCAA over changes
to bat specifications and performance scheduled to take effect Aug.
1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA rules change _ which included reducing the diameter of
the bats and decreasing the allowable speed of a ball coming off a
bat _ was a response to concerns that high-tech bats could lead to
serious injury.
</P>
<P>
   Easton Sports Inc., maker of the Z-Core scandium-alloy aluminum
bat, filed a restraint-of-trade lawsuit this month against the NCAA
in U.S. District Court in Kansas City, Kan., and is seeking $267
million in damages.
</P>
<P>
   Baum Research and Development, which makes wood composite bats,
also sued for unspecified damages, accusing the NCAA of conspiracy
to monopolize the bat industry.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-08-21-98 2050E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
