<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-TOOLS25-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Digital video disc can swallow CD-ROMs 
By Jack Warner  
c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ My (relatively) new computer is equipped with a
DVD-ROM drive, a technology for which little appears to be
available presently, so I had to go afield for something with which
I could make valid comparisons.
</P>
<P>
   For the purpose, Microsoft sent me the DVD, or digital video
disc, version of its popular Encarta Deluxe encyclopedia.
</P>
<P>
   The chief advantage of DVD is an enormous increase in capacity.
Digital video discs are the same physical size as ordinary CD-ROM
discs; my drive will read both kinds.
</P>
<P>
   But the single disc of the DVD version of Encarta not only
contains the two-disc CD version, but also Microsoft Bookshelf and
Virtual Globe. DVDs will hold as much as 4.7 gigabytes of
information, as opposed to the roughly 680 megabytes on the
standard CD-ROM.
</P>
<P>
   What formerly required five discs now fits on one, and in an
enhanced form, too. It is difficult to determine exactly how much
has been added to this version of Encarta itself. My CD-ROM version
of the encyclopedia contained 73 videos; the DVD-ROM has 104.
Furthermore, they can be expanded from their very small starting
size to what would be full screen if you are running your video
card at 800x600. Quality is excellent at that greater size.
</P>
<P>
   There are more of the 360-degree views included in the tour
section.
</P>
<P>
   It will be interesting to see how rapidly this technology
becomes commonplace. It comes at a time when publishers are
becoming more willing to expand programs onto multiple discs, which
is not really a problem for games, where the insertion of new discs
is progressive and there is no need to swap them in and out.
</P>
<P>
   But putting encyclopedias on more than one disc, and forcing the
user to swap them back and forth, is annoying to us couch potatoes
who went through all that with floppies years ago and thought it
was a thing of the past.
</P>
<P>
   I'm no reliable predictor of industry trends. But since DVD-ROM
drives will read both formats, the changeover from one format to
the other would be relatively painless. Unfortunately, the world we
live in now doesn't seem to be driven by things such as
encyclopedias and other electronic reference tools, despite their
enormous value.
</P>
<P>
   It took a game _ ``Myst'' _ to bring the CD-ROM into every
computer room. It will probably take some gargantuan game, with
exquisite graphics running full screen with no loss of quality, to
put DVD over the top.
</P>
<P>
   Since I have reviewed Encarta 98 already, and since the 99
version will be forthcoming soon, I won't rehash that, rather than
to say the DVD version is even nicer than the standard one.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Bookshelf now contains nine separate reference works:
Roget's Thesaurus, the Columbia quotations book, an encyclopedia,
dictionary, the latest World Book almanac, an atlas, something
called The People's Chronology, an Internet directory and, wonder
of wonders, Microsoft's excellent computer dictionary.
</P>
<P>
   If you had the computer dictionary, you would be able to
understand the computer writers who talk about really heavy stuff
like thin clients and thin servers. You would also be pleased to
know there are fat versions of these things, too.
</P>
<P>
   You can access just one of these books, or search through the
entire collection.
</P>
<P>
   Virtual Globe is an excellent study tool. Its chief selling
point is its flyovers of certain parts of the world, marking the
cities and showing the terrain. But this is limited; its greatest
value is its excellence as a standard atlas, fully up to the job of
dealing with the homework of most students through high school. It
is very easy to navigate through, too.
</P>
<P>
   Having all these tools on a single disc is as close as we can
get right now to research nirvana on the personal computer.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-08-21-98 2050E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
