<HEADLINE>
SURFING THE WEB FOR NEWS IN A BLOCKBUSTER NEWS WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By LISA NAPOLI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Traffic to news sites on the World Wide Web soared last week,
suggesting that more people than ever turn to the Web to follow
breaking news stories _ particularly from the workplace, where
television sets can be scarce. Indeed, on both Monday afternoon,
while President Clinton was testifying, and Thursday afternoon,
when he was announcing military strikes on terrorist targets,
record numbers on news sites were reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt that our busiest times are during the U.S.
business day,'' said Kerrin Roberts, a spokesman for CNN
Interactive. For Monday, the site reported a 31 percent increase
over its previous busiest day, which occurred in April.
</P>
<P>
   Relevant Knowledge, a measurement firm in Atlanta, reported an
increase of nearly 43 percent to 11 news sites _ including MSNBC,
ABCnews.com and The New York Times on the Web, as well as the
Drudge Report, which was included because of its role in reporting
on the brewing Monica Lewinsky matter in January.
</P>
<P>
   While the quest for the latest information is part of the
attraction of the Web, many of those who went online did so to do
what the Web allows for best: the expression of personal opinion.
Opinion was something that was not in short supply during the
week's news events.
</P>
<P>
   ``The promise and the expectation of the Internet is the ability
to reach out and touch everyone,'' said Jim Schulte, editor of the
online edition of USA Today. ``That's the whole strength. Everyone
gets their 2 cents in.''
</P>
<P>
   More people posted messages to bulletin boards on America Online
about the Clinton-Lewinsky relationship than in the aftermath of
the death a year earlier of Diana, princess of Wales. That could be
as much a reflection of the growth of the online medium as it is
the nature of the news reports involved, experts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is building as more and more people get online,'' said Adam
Clayton Powell III, vice president for technology at the Freedom
Forum, a free-speech advocacy group based in Arlington, Va. He
foresees a day when the primary sources of news will be online.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each time we have one of these big events, it's another big
boost up,'' he said, ``and each time the peak is a little higher.
The thing that's hard to predict is where it all starts to
plateau.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-23-98 1925EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-26-98 1130EDT &QL; 
