<SLUG> BC-CPT-FCC-HDTV-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FCC WANTS HDTV GLITCH SOLVED SOON
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By JOEL BRINKLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The chairman of the Federal Communications
Commission, worried that a small technical problem will impede the
transition to digital television that is scheduled to begin in just
10 weeks, has written a sharp letter to industry leaders demanding
that the problem be solved by Nov. 1.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is the special cable that is needed to carry a digital,
high-definition television signal from a set-top cable converter
box to an HDTV set. The technical work on that new cable is not
finished. This means that cable subscribers who buy the costly new
sets will be unable to receive any of the digital programming that
broadcasters are scheduled to begin showing in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``These compatibility problems must be resolved quickly to
ensure that American consumers are able to enjoy the benefits of
digital television starting this fall,'' FCC Chairman William
Kennard wrote on Aug. 13. Two-thirds of the nation's television
viewers are cable subscribers, and the transition to digital
television will be hobbled if these people are unable to receive
any of the new digital programming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see no reason why this should not be complete by Nov. 1,
1998,'' Kennard wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The letter was addressed to Decker Anstrom, president of the
National Cable Television Association, and Gary Shapiro, president
of the Consumer Electronics Manufacturers Association. So far,
neither has answered it.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, Shapiro and a cable association spokesman both
said work was proceeding at a rapid pace. But neither was willing
to commit himself to completing it by Nov. 1. After receiving
Kennard's letter, however, Shapiro's group created an internal
committee to concentrate on solving the problem.
</P>
<P>
   The research work is under way at an industry-supported
laboratory, Cable Television Laboratories Inc. in Colorado. Richard
Green, the laboratory's president, said he expected to have a draft
specification complete by Oct. 1. At that time, he added,
manufacturers could begin designing equipment for the new cable.
</P>
<P>
   But approval by national standard-setting bodies probably will
not come until late November, Green said, and world standards
bodies will not be able to approve the new device until early
spring.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Kennard's deadline is met, the first digital television
sets with the new cable jacks probably will not go on sale until a
year later. So Kennard urged the industries to find some sort of
interim solution as well.
</P>
<P>
   Several television manufacturers, including Sony and Zenith, say
they may have their own proprietary solutions.
</P>
<P>
   But Kennard wrote, ``I call on your industries to communicate to
the American public that these solutions will be available and to
redouble your efforts to enable the American public to receive
digital broadcast programming over cable for display on
first-generation digital-television sets.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-23-98 1804EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-26-98 1131EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
