<DOCNO> NYT19980826.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 11:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2836 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-TECH-BANKING-ART-     08-26 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-BANKING-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 PHILADELPHIA: doing that. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the same time, mergers have also sometimes accelerated
electronic banking. Rubin, the Tower analyst, points to two
examples of this: the combination of NationsBank and Florida's
Barnett Bank and the acquisition of Corestates Financial Corp. by
First Union Corp. In both cases, he said, a smaller, regional bank
that had been slow to offer online banking was forced to change
plans once it was purchased.
</P>
<P>
   ``Institutions were slower to introduce Internet banking than we
thought,'' Rubin said. ``Of the top 100 banks, only about 30 have a
transactional Web site. Another 30 to 40 more are planning to offer
it this year.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he added, so-called virtual banks, which were
created to exist solely on the Internet, have reluctantly had to
acknowledge the need for face-to-face interaction with customers
for products like loans and have opened conventional
brick-and-mortar branches.
</P>
<P>
   The oldest of these, Atlanta-based Security First Network Bank,
was created in 1995. It opened its first branch _ it calls it a
``city office'' and the staff ``customer assistants'' _ in January
1997, said Eric Hartz, bank president.
</P>
<P>
   Security First also has a software division that competes with
Integrion, and dozens of banks now use its Internet-based system.
</P>
<P>
   Security First was acquired earlier this year by Royal Bank of
Canada, which has said it plans to spin off the software division
as a publicly traded company.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin projects that U.S. banks will spend $336 million this year
for online initiatives and accelerate that process at an annual
growth rate of 29 percent for the next four years.
</P>
<P>
   Original estimates were off base, he said, because the banking
industry looked at the explosion of Internet use in 1994 and 1995
and predicted a similar pattern for electronic banking.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, banks found themselves limited by systems they had
built around personal finance software, which required the user to
buy frequent upgrades and limited the design of the overall
service.
</P>
<P>
   Internet-based systems do away with those issues and offer other
strengths as well: questions can be answered quickly by e-mail,
applications for accounts and services can be transmitted
electronically, and a bank can more closely track a customer's
account, which in turn enables it to market products or services
like insurance, credit cards and auto and home loans.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers had any number of reasons for not quickly embracing
electronic banking. The software was expensive, the service was
often unreliable, technical support was limited, and the security
of financial data was unproved.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Integrion's Wallace said, the services were not
well designed. Bill payment, for example, often cost a hefty
monthly fee for not much added convenience.
</P>
<P>
   Internet-based systems now emerging enable utility, phone,
credit card and other companies to bill customers electronically;
customers, in turn, can approve payments by e-mailing instructions
to the bank.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even with the newest software and best system designs,
many questions have to be answered before banks start closing
branches and eliminating staff. Don Kunz, manager of electronic
banking for PNC Bank of Pittsburgh, said that it was anyone's guess
when the bank might see real savings from the Web-based system it
introduced in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still struggling with `What does the customer want to
do?' and `As a bank, have we created a redundant way of doing
business?' '' Kunz said.``Our biggest criteria for success will be
customer usage. We need to figure out whether it adds revenue or
just additional expense.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-23-98 1720EDT &QL;
</P>
