A2837 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-TECH-BANKING-ART-     08-26 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-BANKING-ART-680(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERGERS AND YEAR 2000 SLOW ONLINE BANKING
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 By DAVID J. WALLACE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Earlier this decade, bankers and software
developers looked ahead eagerly to 1998 and 1999 as the period when
electronic banking would evolve from a niche business to a
ubiquitous service, saving financial institutions millions of
dollars in transaction costs.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it is proving to be the era of megamergers and
millennium preparation, two issues that have distracted software
and system developers and have, for the time being anyway, delayed
consumer banking via personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have expected more activity at this point in our
evolution,'' said Scott Wallace, director of marketing for
Integrion Financial Network LLC, a leading developer of electronic
banking software. ``But the rapid consolidation diverts the
attention of institutions. It takes a long time to integrate two
different systems.''
</P>
<P>
   Original estimates that 15 percent of banking customers in the
United States would be on line by 2000 have now been pushed back
two years. Now, about 6 percent of customers nationwide have
electronic banking available, said Ian Rubin, senior analyst at
Tower Group in Newton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The main distraction has been the greatest rush of bank mergers
in history _ more than $200 billion in the first half of this year
alone. In each case, a merger requires a melding of different and
sometimes stubbornly incompatible computer systems. And as the
millennium approaches, solutions that the merging banks have
adopted to fix the year 2000 problem must also be made compatible.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, banks that saw themselves as takeover targets
halted further development of electronic-banking initiatives, Rubin
said.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, there has been a bright side to the delay. A new
generation of consumer electronic banking, based on Internet
connections, promises to replace today's myriad bank-specific and
incompatible software programs that offer access by direct dial-up
connections to a bank's computer. Bank analysts predict that
improved systems using Internet browser-based software will draw
millions of new customers to online banking as merger frenzy slows
and prices for the services decline.
</P>
<P>
   Citibank introduced its Internet-based system, the latest
incarnation of its Direct Access electronic banking service, in
October after upgrading to the most robust encryption security
available, said a spokeswoman, Maria Mendler.
</P>
<P>
   The bank has offered various versions of Direct Access since
1984, when forecasters were predicting a personal computer on every
kitchen table by 2000, Ms. Mendler said. Today, the bank has about
300,000 electronic-banking clients and those using the older
software will be moved to the Internet-based version by the end of
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Customers, she said, are motivated by cost more than technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw a real jump in 1995, when we eliminated the fee,'' Ms.
Mendler said.
</P>
<P>
   The industrywide shift to Internet-based systems has come at the
expense of personal financial management software like Microsoft
Corp.'s Money, Intuit Corp.'s Quicken and Meca Software's Managing
Your Money. All three had been widely used by banks on the consumer
end of direct dial-up systems. But such software has serious
drawbacks. If a customer changes banks, for example, he usually has
to switch software as well, because no two bank systems integrate a
program in the same way.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, browser programs for navigating the World Wide Web
offer customers and banks a universal interface on almost any
computer system and eliminate problems that customers often
encounter installing proprietary software.
</P>
<P>
   Foremost among the open systems is a package developed by
Integrion, a Philadelphia-based consortium of 17 banks, IBM and
Visa USA. Integrion created a platform for banks to interact with
customers for a range of retail services using the Internet, direct
dial-up software or a telephone.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last six months,'' Integrion's Wallace said, ``the Web
has become more important, and banks that might not have focused on
a transactional Web site now are doing that.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
