<HEADER>
A2842 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-CATTLE-INTERNET-A     08-26 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-CATTLE-INTERNET-ART-1,000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATTLEMEN IN SEARCH OF STOCK TURNING TO THE WEB 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (Eds.: Please note that the word AT within parentheses has been
used in the 9th graf instead of the symbol, which the company uses
as the first letter of its name but which is non-transmittable to
many newspaper systems.) 
(ART ADV: A photo of David Reynolds is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 By ARLENE WEINTRAUB   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What with working his day job as a technician for a company that
sells artificial insemination gear to the cattle industry, and then
running his own side business breeding and selling Holstein dairy
cows, David Reynolds does not have much time to attend the cattle
auctions that are a crucial part of his vocation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I work seven days a week, so it's hard for me to travel to an
auction yard and sit in a tent and bid,'' said Reynolds, whose
small business, Higher Plain Genetics, is in Cooperstown, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily for Reynolds, animal husbandry _ like so many other
commercial endeavors these days _ has gone online.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great,'' Reynolds said. ``You just get up in the morning,
log on, see where the prices are and place your bid.''
</P>
<P>
   Web-based transactions still represent but a tiny fraction of
the $31 billion annual beef-cattle and $23 billion dairy-farming
industries. But the number of Web-based commercial cattle resources
is estimated at 1,000 and growing, with the leaders including
Cattle Offerings Worldwide _ or COW, for short.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, when Reynolds was in the market for
top-of-the-line Holstein embryos, he logged onto COW
(www.cattleofferings.com) and clicked his way through an auction,
pulling up snapshots of the donor cows and reading their vital
statistics and ancestry _ all the while watching bids stream from
around the world. Within an hour, his own bid of $520 each for four
embryos from a Virginia breeder had been accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Before he even had time to arrange for delivery, though,
Reynolds received a call from someone else who had been
participating in the auction and wanted to know if he would be
willing to resell the Holsteins-in-waiting at a higher price to a
breeder in Italy. ``So I resold them and made a $600 profit in 15
minutes,'' Reynolds recalled. ``The eggs were top quality and from
one of the best cow families in the United States. But I'm not
averse to making a profit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is still finding its place among the more
established methods that farmers use to buy and sell cattle, like
live auctions, advertisements in agricultural publications, and
business relationships nurtured by generations of farming families.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our sense is that farmers are using the Net now mostly to get
breaking news,'' said John Walter, editor of (AT)griculture Online
(www.agriculture.com), an electronic offshoot of Meredith
Publishing's Successful Farming magazine. ``I don't think there's a
heck of a lot of commerce going on yet,'' Walter said. ``But we're
just on the verge of seeing things start to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a whole host of livestock professionals have gone to the
Web, most offering some form of classified advertising. Online
Livestock Corner (www.onlinelivestockcorner.com), for example,
posts ads not only for cattle, but also for horses, sheep, bison
and dogs. Other Web sites, though, deal only with specific breeds
of cattle, like www.beefalobeef.com, whose offerings range from ``O
Bar R's Semen'' to ``Big Sky Beefalo Meat Products.''
</P>
<P>
   But the lifeblood of the cattle trade is still the traditional
auction. That is why many industry experts believe that online
auctions could eventually make the Internet as vital a farming tool
as branding irons and milking machines.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Zaitz, founder and president of privately held COW, is one
of the pioneers of the Internet cattle industry. He started his
ad-supported site three years ago primarily as a meeting place for
buyers and sellers. But it was not until the advent of the Java
programing language for Web applications that he was able to
perfect a way for all auction players _ sellers, auctioneers and
buyers _ to conduct business in real time in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed a system where everyone who was logged on would get
instant feedback,'' said Zaitz, a former cattle dealer who is based
in Chapel Hill, N.C. ``If you had the bid you would know instantly,
and if you were cut you would know instantly,'' he said. ``Java
allowed us to proceed.''
</P>
<P>
   Since COW's auction system went operational last year, Zaitz
said, about $300,000 worth of cattle, embryos and bull semen have
been traded. COW earns commissions ranging from 2 percent to 15
percent on each transaction.
</P>
<P>
   Another leading player in the field, Cyber Stockyard
(www.cyberstockyard.com), based in Starkville, Miss., takes a
slightly different approach. Scott Sanders, Cyber Stockyard's
president, sends representatives to real auctions who provide live
chat-room coverage via the Web. Customers can log on, view a
catalog of the offerings, and submit their bids electronically to
the Cyber Stockyard representatives, who call them out as the
auctioneer is also hearing bids from those in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, whose family has been in cattle trading for decades,
also offers a placement service that electronically searches for
cattle based on a buyer's or seller's specific needs.
</P>
<P>
   How have ranchers and dairymen reacted to all this new
technology?
</P>
<P>
   ``Some think it's the best thing since sliced bread,'' Sanders
said. ``Some think it's the stupidest thing they've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   But the converts tend to be optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Yackley, customer relations and marketing manager for
Express Ranches in Yukon, Okla., concedes that his company's cattle
sales through Cyber Stockyard have been minimal so far _ only seven
head among hundreds sold in one recent auction, for example.
</P>
<P>
   But ``the real advantage for us is that it opens up a worldwide
market,'' Yackley said. ``People from, say, Brazil or Australia can
bid, and people in the U.S. who might not be able to afford to
travel from point A to point B can come to the auctions, as well.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-23-98 1705EDT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention less wear and tear on the livestock. ``When you
put cows on trucks and haul them to auctions, they lose weight,''
Zaitz said. ``When they get chased around and jostled, they get
nervous _ they make manure and urine, and that causes weight
loss.'' This ``shrink,'' as it is known in the industry, typically
knocks a few percent off a cow's value.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the health issues. ``Taking a cow to auction is
much like putting a child in day care,'' said James Henderson, a
market analyst at Cattle-Fax, an information service based in
Englewood, Colo. (www.cattle-fax.com). ``Just as a child can get
sick from being around other children, when cattle from different
places get together and one herd's health program is not so good,
all the cattle might get sick. When you sell straight off the farm,
you eliminate the problem of commingling.''
</P>
<P>
   For all these benefits, though, neither COW's or Cyber
Stockyards' auctions are profitable yet. ``I'm just as good at
losing money as Amazon.com,'' Zaitz joked.
</P>
<P>
   Changing traditional ways of farming and ranching will take
time, Zaitz predicted, because cattlemen ``just don't have time to
make something new work when they've got to make a living.''
</P>
<P>
   And simply getting on the Net can often be a challenge in rural
areas. ``Reasonably priced Internet access is not as good as it is
in the city,'' said Walter, the online editor. ``But it's
improving.''
</P>
<P>
   And so, evidently, is the interest. According to Gallup's 1998
``Trends in Agriculture'' survey (www.agpub.org/gallup/index.htm),
while only 22 percent of beef producers currently use the Internet,
an additional 55 percent say they intend to start within the next
three years. Among dairy producers, only 16 percent use the
Internet now, but another 62 percent expect to log on within three
years.
</P>
<P>
   Zaitz's goal is to reach those cattle buyers by providing
auction-house owners with the technology they need to make a Web
presence a standard part of their business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you need the Internet to sell a couple of oddball steers in
Kentucky?'' he said. ``Maybe not. But why should people have to
travel from stockyard to stockyard buying herds of cattle when they
can use the Internet?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-23-98 1705EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
