<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTINGQ&AMP;A-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Printers On the Way For the iMac  
 By David Einstein   
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Q: &LR;  I've been thinking about getting an Apple iMac. The only
thing that concerns me is whether I'll be able to get a printer
that will work with it, since it only has a USB port. Is anybody
planning to come out with a USB printer soon? And what about other
peripherals such as mice and Zip drives?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: &LR;  All major printer-makers will have USB models within the
next few months that will work with any computer that has a USB
port. Also, companies are starting to sell cables that convert a
standard parallel port printer to USB. In fact, Hewlett-Packard
already has announced USB cables for its DeskJet 670C and 690C
printers, and Epson has announced one for its Stylus 600.
</P>
<P>
   USB-compatible mice are already available from market leaders
Microsoft and Logitech. And Iomega is planning to introduce a USB
version of its popular Zip drive soon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: &LR;  I am in my truck a lot calling on customers, and I want to
use a laptop to keep track of my contacts. I will be booting up
anywhere from three to 10 times a day after sales calls. Because I
won't be near an electrical outlet, I'm afraid I'll run down the
battery in the computer. Is there a way to recharge using the
battery in the truck?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: &LR;  As Curley would say, ``Soitenly.'' All the big
computer-makers sell special cables that let you plug your lapt &QR; 
ePfw41~to the cigarette lighter in the car or truck or boat or
whatever. You can treat this connection just like a regular plug in
your house. That is, you can run the computer off it, or use it to
recharge, or both. Expect to pay about $90.
</P>
<P>
   You also can find cables that convert your regular laptop power
cord into a mobile charger. That's a good option if you can't find
a car cable for your specific model laptop.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: &LR;  I've got a Packard Bell with a 75 MHz Pentium and 16
megabytes of memory. I'm thinking of getting Windows 98, and I'd
like to know: A) Will I need more memory? and B) If so, how can I
find out what kind I need? Also, is it hard to upgrade, or should I
let a store do it for me?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: &LR;  You don't need any more memory to run Windows 98 than you
need for Windows 95. But doubling your memory to 32 megs would
speed up your system appreciably. So it's definitely worth the
upgrade, especially because the kind of memory your computer uses
has become pretty cheap. You should be able to get 16 megs for
under $30.
</P>
<P>
   I believe your Packard Bell uses standard 72-pin SIMM chips. But
just to be sure, check the manual or call the company. That way
you'll know exactly what kind and how many chips to buy. As for
upgrading, it's a simple procedure, but if you feel queasy about
opening up the PC, let the store do it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: &LR;  I recently removed several programs I was no longer using
by deleting their folders in Windows Explorer. Then I noticed that
when I go to Add/Remove Programs in the Control Panel, the programs
are still listed. When I try to remove them, I get a message saying
``Cannot locate install.log.'' How do I get rid of the programs and
make sure they're truly gone?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: &LR;  Don't worry, they're gone. But since you didn't use
Add/Remove Programs to delete them, Windows thinks they're still
there. It's possible to remove the names, but it's complicated and
involves going into the Windows Registry. You don't want to do
that. Trust me. Just live with it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Netscape Update &LR;  _ Last week, I noted that Netscape
Communicator doesn't let you view a list of e-mail messages and a
directory of e-mail folders in the same window. But Netscape has
corrected that oversight with version 4.5 of Communicator, which is
now in beta testing and can be downloaded for free at
www.netscape.com. This new version can display the directory of
folders on the left and the list of messages on the right. In
addition, you can view the text of a selected message below the
list of messages. And you can drag messages from the list to any
folder in the directory.
</P>
<P>
   TIP OF THE WEEK &QC; Want fast access to files you create in Word,
Excel or another Microsoft Office application? Put a shortcut to
the My Documents folder on your desktop. Just go to My Computer,
find the folder in the ``C'' drive and drag it to the desktop using
the right mouse button. Then click Create Shortcut(s) Here. When
you open the My Documents shortcut, double-clicking any item will
launch the associated application and open the file.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Got a computing questions? E-mail it to computers(at
sign)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-24-98 2156EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
