<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 11:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2847 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-SCI-COMPUTER-COLU     08-26 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-SCI-COMPUTER-COLUMN-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE ABOUT WEBTV: AMBITIOUS NEW CARD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By ROB FIXMER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week's column on WebTV for Windows stirred up enough
questions from readers about TV cards for personal computers to
warrant a review of the latest and most ambitious of this breed of
hardware, All-in-Wonder Pro from ATI Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   As the name implies, this product is an all-in-one television,
video and graphics upgrade that can be installed in any Pentium
computer with an available PCI slot. PCI (for Peripheral Component
Interconnect) is a standard introduced several years ago by Intel
Corp. for high-speed, multitasking devices like video hardware.
</P>
<P>
   Most Pentium computers have two PCI slots, so before buying a TV
card or other high-speed video upgrade _ especially the new
generation of 3-D video cards _ make sure the machine has a free
PCI slot.
</P>
<P>
   Another version of the All-in-Wonder Pro is available for owners
of Pentium II computers that have the new Accelerated Graphics
Port, or AGP, which can handle larger, more complex 3-D animations
by borrowing memory from the computer's RAM. This is especially
useful if the computer is often used for 3-D games or other
applications that do extensive three-dimensional rendering.
</P>
<P>
   The All-in-Wonder comes in two versions, the original, which has
a minimum of two megabits and maximum of four megabits of
high-speed, EDO (Extended Data Out) memory.
</P>
<P>
   The card tested for this column was the All-in-Wonder Pro, a
more powerful version that offers twice as much memory, to a
maximum of eight megabits, and the memory is slightly faster. In
addition, the Pro version adds what is known as a 3-D Triangle
setup engine, which uses a sophisticated math processor to add
detail to complex 3-D animations, and DBX brand television audio,
which cuts the background hiss and static to deliver clear, bright
sound approaching CD quality.
</P>
<P>
   The Pro also allows people with similar equipment to conduct
videoconferences and includes extra features beyond the scope of
this review. It also comes bundled with multimedia and game
software that show off the card's capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   The basic All-in-Wonder retails for about $150. The Pro version
is twice as much.
</P>
<P>
   Installation is straightforward and well-documented, and all the
drivers and other setup software are delivered on a self-starting
CD-ROM. But installing the card requires opening the computer, so
users who are squeamish about exposing the machine's guts should
probably buy the card from a retailer that will install it.
</P>
<P>
   Both cards were tested in low-end machines. The All-in-Wonder
was installed in a home-built 100-megahertz Pentium computer
running Windows 95, and the Pro version was installed in an AST
computer with a 166-megahertz Pentium MMX processor running Windows
98.
</P>
<P>
   The only glitch in both cases was that installing the
All-in-Wonder for some reason removed the speaker icon from the
tool bar tray and muted the line input in the Windows sound mixer,
resulting in no sound from the on-board television until the
original audio settings had been restored. This problem is not
mentioned in the original or supplemental documentation for either
card, but it was not difficult to diagnose and fix.
</P>
<P>
   Once the hardware and software are installed, the card has to be
told whether it is connected to an antenna or cable system. It then
scans to find all available channels _ as many as 125 on cable
systems and 70 on antennas. In either case, the setup time, from
breaking the seal on the package to sitting back to watch
television, was about 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Reception on a Comcast cable hookup was far superior to
reception of standard televisions in the same house _ or at least
seemed to be. Some of this is an eye-brain trick that's performed
by many TV cards, a result of the higher scan rate of computer
monitors relative to televisions, and the fact that viewers tend to
sit much closer to a monitor than to a television set.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the soft, flicker-free image can be
attributed only to fine electronics in the tuner part of the ATI
card. Previously tested cards connected to the same cable system
could not match the ATI's image quality.
</P>
<P>
   The software that comes with the card is rich in features. While
WebTV, the television software that comes with Windows 98,
showcases the strength of blending the Internet with television,
ATI's software demonstrates that mating the computer and the
television can produce a surprisingly useful information appliance.
</P>
<P>
   For example, on a standard television, closed captioning is
primarily a technology for people with hearing disabilities,
although it is occasionally used to avoid bothering someone
sleeping in the same room or in noisy public places like Times
Square, where audio is not possible.
</P>
<P>
   On a PC-TV hybrid, closed captioning takes on data-base
characteristics. The text can be searched for keywords, stored in a
file as a complete transcription of a program, or told to flag the
viewer if certain words are spoken on any channel that is being
scanned. This feature can be set so that a television window pops
up, either full screen or in a smaller window on the desktop,
whenever certain words are spoken in a program, allowing the user
to work uninterrupted until certain subject matter appears.
</P>
<P>
   Complete transcripts of programs can be saved in several
formats, which ATI calls ``TV magazines.'' The advantage of these
is that the text is saved in rich text format (.rtf files) that can
be read by most word processors. The magazine feature also
intersperses black-and-white screen shots in the text at a
frequency defined by the user _ that is, one picture per so many
words of text _ and changes the all-capital-letter text that closed
captioning delivers into upper- and lower-case text.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-24-98 1714EDT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the most useful of ATI's tools is a feature that
continuously scans the channels available and builds a grid of
thumbnail images of what is playing on each channel at that moment.
On a monitor set at a resolution of 1,024 by 768 pixels, this
feature displays the current programing on as many as 80 channels
simultaneously. The user can double-click on any thumbnail to tune
to that channel.
</P>
<P>
   The memory in the card is employed in several ways that make the
PC-TV hybrid more interesting than standard television, including
storing two to 10 seconds of video streams for instant replays.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who has used a high-quality image editing program like
Adobe Photoshop will appreciate the ability of ATI software to save
``screen grabs'' as graphic still images. And, ATI's television
software allows the user to define a rectangle on the television
screen by dragging a mouse and then zooming in to just that portion
of the image.
</P>
<P>
   The software also captures full-motion video and/or audio and
saves it as an AVI (audio-video interleave) movie, although no type
of data eats disc space faster. The Pro version bundles MGI
Videowave, a video editing program that works with any source,
including the television tuner or a VCR, enabling users to edit
piece of video and create rudimentary special effects, fades and
titling.
</P>
<P>
   The card offers audio-visual input and output connections that
make it usable with any television, VCR, DVD, video CD or stereo
component. These include the single-cable S-Video connectors that
have become a standard for camcorders and VCRs, plus old-fashioned
composite video connectors that take traditional patch cords.
</P>
<P>
   The All-in-Wonder viewer can be used for video formats other
than television, including MPEG (Motion Pictures Experts Group) and
AVI movie formats, and it includes a CD music player that is
slightly more advanced than the one shipped with Windows.
</P>
<P>
   For a generation accustomed to equating television with the
passive medium that spawned generations of couch potatoes, the
PC-TV hybrid begs a rethinking of what the appliance can, and maybe
should, be. At the very least, it is a lot more entertaining than
either of its progenitors. At best, it is an interactive
information machine that promises to grow more powerful over time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-24-98 1714EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
