<HEADLINE>
BLESSING: GOD HAD NO PC FOR CREATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By DAVID HOYE   
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Wed be in a world o' hurt if God had used a PC for
creation!
</P>
<P>
   That's all I can conclude after collecting entries for the past
couple of weeks in our latest contest. Readers were asked to send
in examples of how things would be if God had used a PC to create
things.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top three entries:
</P>
<P>
   Our second runner up was Bob Lind, who wrote that creation
``would have taken a lot longer than seven days. You'd have to
allow for the time He'd spend on hold for tech support!''
</P>
<P>
   Our first runner up was Doyle Holcomb, who wrote, ``God did
consider using a computer to create the universe, but he was unable
to come to an agreement with Bill Gates on the software to run it.
Talks broke off when Gates refused to use the word ``apple'' in a
program about two people in the garden.''
</P>
<P>
   First place went to Steve Hrovat, who sent in several great
examples of how things would be if God had used a PC for creation.
</P>
<P>
   My favorite was: ``Having a baby is considered a slow, painful
process by many. This was done out of God's frustration at having
to download an entire universe on a 2400-baud modem. It was a slow,
painful process. He figured he'd make `downloading' a baby an
equally painful process so people realize what he went through.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's another gem from Hrovat: ``All humans are expected to go
to school at least 12 years to have any chance of success. This is
a throwback to the days of MS-DOS, which took God about 12 years to
figure out.''
</P>
<P>
   And another: ``The Ten Commandments were done on a clay tablet
because God's printer driver had some type of bug in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, that was fun, eh? Thanks to everybody who sent in an
entry!
</P>
<P>
   We'd better stop now, though, or we'll all get struck by
lightning! &QL; 
Passwords to success
</P>
<P>
   A couple weeks ago I wrote about the growing problem of
passwords. These days, most people are walking around with one or
two in their heads. And it's not unusual to have five, 10 or more
passwords to remember, thanks to things like ATM machines and
Internet access accounts.
</P>
<P>
   I asked for your suggestions on good ways to remember passwords.
Here's what you said:
</P>
<P>
   - Several readers suggested using a single password for
everything. (This might work for some people, but there's got to be
something better you can do.)
</P>
<P>
   - Here's a variation on that theme from a reader named Eric:
Think of a person or pet in your life and use it to create slightly
unique passwords everywhere. Say your dog is named ``Fido.'' Your
password to log on to your computer could be ``fidocomp001.'' To
check your e-mail, the password could be ``fidoemail002'' and so
forth. (Not a bad idea.)
</P>
<P>
   - One reader said he put all his passwords in a computer file
and gave the file a mysterious name. That way he can open the file
any time he's online and needs a password quickly. (Interesting
idea, but not very secure.)
</P>
<P>
   - One guy proposed creating passwords based on your favorite
things _ you favorite fruit, favorite sports team, etc. Use the
first letter from each to make up the password. (An idea with some
merit.)
</P>
<P>
   - A reader said he maintains a free e-mail account and uses it
only to keep e-mails he sends himself that contain passwords and
other account information for accounts he sets up. ``Risky?'' he
asked. ``Sure, but what isn't?''
</P>
<P>
   - Here's a good one: A reader named Rozanne suggested thinking
up a sentence that has personal meaning. Then, use the first letter
from each word to create the password. Example: ``My father was
born on 3/7/22'' would create the password ``mfwbo3722.''
</P>
<P>
   - A Phoenix area company called Micro System Designs makes a
program called ``WebPassKey.'' It watches where you browse the Net
and remembers passwords and login names automatically. On your next
visit, it automatically enters the info for you. The software also
can be used to store passwords for other applications. Interested?
Call (602) 788-6000, or visit their Web site at www.maxlock.com.
</P>
<P>
   - A reader named Antoniu suggests keeping passwords in a single
file, then encrypting the file with a program such as PGP.
</P>
<P>
   - John recommends using Password Safe, a free program you can
download from www.zdnet.com. ``It's like having a little safe to
keep all of your passwords in,'' he wrote. ``Only one catch: You
need a password to get into Password Safe.''
</P>
<P>
   - Juergen says he uses his Palm Pilot to keep his passwords
safe. He puts them all in a single file, then uses a Palm Pilot
program called Secret to scramble the contents. Of course, you need
a password to read the file later.
</P>
<P>
   Well, there you have it. I hope some of those suggestions help
you out. I know I'm going to try a couple! &QL; 
Just another hoax
</P>
<P>
   Internet users have been passing around an e-mail lately that
refers to ``Time'' magazine article.
</P>
<P>
   Supposedly, the article states that two engineers at Intel
somehow managed to write the words ``Bill Sux'' on the surface of a
Pentium microchip. The graffiti is supposedly visible under a
powerful electron microscope.
</P>
<P>
   The e-mail points out that the reference to ``Bill'' is aimed at
Bill Gates, the billionaire head of Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Well, it's fun to think that this actually happened. But, it
didn't.
</P>
<P>
   An Intel spokesman confirmed that the e-mail claim is somebody's
idea of a joke.
</P>
<P>
   To read more about the hoax and view an image of the altered
``chip,'' visit snopes.simplenet.com/spoons &QL; 
/faxlore/chipshot.htm &QL; 
David Hoye is an online editor and covers computer- and
Internet-related issues for Arizona Central, the Web site of The
Arizona Republic. He can be reached at dhoye(at)pni.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-24-98 1531EDT &QL;
</P>
