 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Intel's New Pentium Chip to Send PC Prices Lower  
 By David Einstein   
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Intel's new top-of-the-line chip, the 450 MHz Pentium II, made
its debut this weekend, and at least one retailer, CompUSA, is
selling a system with the new chip for under $2,000. To anyone who
has followed the PC industry, that's nothing short of remarkable.
</P>
<P>
   It was only a few years ago, after all, that you had to pay over
$3,000 to get a system with a brand new high-end Intel chip. And
$2,000 barely got you last year's chip.
</P>
<P>
   But never mind my nostalgia. The bottom line here is that if
you're in the market for a new PC, put on your shopping shoes,
because prices are about to take a nose-dive across the board.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the introduction of the new Pentium II will force
prices lower for other desktop PCs using Intel chips, as well as
for systems that sport competitive chips from AMD and Cyrix.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, PCs with 266 MHz chips _ now considered the low
end _ could soon be available for less than $750 from some dealers.
And 300 MHz systems, which now sell for as little as $1,000, should
move down below $900. By year's end, the 300 MHz will be the entry
level.
</P>
<P>
   The picture isn't so rosy for`}ntel. The big Santa Clara company
is selling the new Pentium II 450 to computer-makers for $669 (when
bought in volume). That's a good deal less than the $824 it got for
the Pentium II 400 when it appeared in April _ and far below the
nearly $1,000 it commanded for the first Pentiums five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't take an economist to conclude that when you shave
that much off the price, your profit margins go down. Intel will be
able to cushion the blow, because it continues to reap tremendous
profits from its notebook chips and chips used in corporate
workstations. But it's gotta hurt nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   Intel's overall gross margins this year should be around 52
percent. That's still high, but it's less than in years past, when
it topped 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A more imminent threat may face AMD, which has carved out a nice
business for itself selling chips for low-end systems. That
company's profit margins already are thinner than model Kate Moss,
but they're about to get thinner, and that could dampen AMD's hopes
of returning to profitability.
</P>
<P>
   AMD also faces renewed competition from the latest version of
Intel's Celeron _ Intel's entry in the sub-$1,000 market _ which
was introduced along with the Pentium II 450 over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The new, improved Celer{bEc1e &QL; 
[`Rb &QC; hmbt
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-24-98 2155EDT &QL;
</P>
