<HEADLINE>
BAD NEWS TRAVELS FAST ON THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By HIAWATHA BRAY   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Retailers beware. On the Internet, everybody will know if your
product is a dog.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is turning disgruntled shoppers into fearless
consumer advocates. Consumers can create or tap into a host of
``anti-sites,'' Web sites where customers can share complaints
about cheesy products and lousy service with an audience of
millions.
</P>
<P>
   Visit the Yahoo Internet search service and run a search using
the words ``consumer opinion.'' You will find dozens of sites built
by ordinary people who want to denounce _ or occasionally praise _
a particular product. For fast food-phobics, there is the ``I Hate
McDonald's'' page. An angry airline passenger offers the ``Untied
Airlines'' page _ targeted at United Airlines. The boycott against
the Walt Disney Co.'s ``anti-Christian'' policies is backed by a
number of sites, while others support the company. And this does
not count another popular Internet service _ the Usenet, a system
of public bulletin boards or ``newsgroups'' devoted to thousands of
different topics. Usenet visitors routinely post messages slamming
companies that have left them unsatisfied.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the best-known consumer watchdog in cyberspace keeps
his eye on theInternet's most powerful company, America Online.
</P>
<P>
   David Cassel, a 34-year-old freelance writer in Berkeley,
Calif., was amusing himself in an AOL chat room in 1994, when a
fellow chatter used a four-letter word. Shortly thereafter, the
offending chatter was electronically silenced by AOL.
</P>
<P>
   That casual act of censorship turned Cassel from an on-line
neophyte to a crusading avenger dedicated to exposing the evil of
AOL and all its works. He started AOL Watch, a Web site which,
according to Cassel, gets as many as 1,000 visitors a day. He also
claims 32,000 people receive regular AOL Watch newsletters via
electronic mail.
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt that when Cassel speaks, people listen. He
reported last year that AOL planned to sell the phone numbers of
its 12 million users to outside firms for marketing purposes. The
story made headlines nationwide and forced the company to abandon
the plan. ``Who knows how much money they would have made off
that,'' Cassel said, ``and who knows how many people would have
suffered?''
</P>
<P>
   The lesson of David Cassel has not been lost on corporations,
which is good news for James Alexander. The former television
production worker runs eWatch, a New York firm that keeps track of
what Internet users say about various businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Over 600 firms have employed eWatch. The company uses ``software
agents,'' software that automatically scans thousands of Web pages
and Usenet newsgroups in search of words and phrases related to the
client companies. All relevant material is then examined by
editors, who write up a daily report for the client.
</P>
<P>
   The company does not attempt to contact disgruntled consumers.
``We're just a listening post,'' Alexander said.
</P>
<P>
   He said some of the gripes are actually planted by cunning
investors hoping to spread false information to depress the value
of a company's stock.
</P>
<P>
   But when customers complain about real problems, eWatch reports
can provide client companies early warning about product
shortcomings that need fixing. Said Alexander: ``We are improving
customer service, without a doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so. But most of the credit goes to angry consumers who
have begun using the Internet to broadcast their gripes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-24-98 1318EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
