<HEADER>
A2861 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-COMPUTER-COMPOSER     08-26 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTER-COMPOSER-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
A maestro of the new media 
By Ernest Holsendolph  
c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ James Oliverio, in his own way, answered the question
before it could be asked. Is he a technology aficionado disguised
as a musician, or vice versa?
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother was a pianist, one of my favorite pictures is of me
in diapers trying to sound a note on a string, and I was the church
organist at 10, playing a Hammond B3,'' he said. Enough said. Next
question...
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech's first composer-in-residence is a man who loves to
talk music and technology, and that's why he's so right for his
job. He has accumulated a wealth of musical experience and credits
in Hollywood with his standalone pieces, such as his Concerto No. 1
for Orchestra and Timpani.
</P>
<P>
   But he is also comfortably at home with his colleagues in the
Interactive Media Technology Center at Tech, where he employs
electronics to extend the musical palette. Other specialists in the
cheerfully collegial media lab include authorities in education and
sports technology, and experts who know of ways to heal with a
combination of computer and human techniques.
</P>
<P>
   Oliverio's works are voluminous and varied. They include film
scores, a high-tech opera called Star Child that premiered from the
Olympic Village prior to the opening of the Games in 1996, and
various other works large and small.
</P>
<P>
   His works have been played by the Cleveland Orchestra and the
Atlanta Symphony, as well as by the DeKalb (Ga.) Symphony and the
orchestras of Chattanooga, Tenn., Albany, Ga., Macon, Ga. and Fort
Wayne, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   Oliverio, a Cleveland native, who lived in Los Angeles before
moving to Atlanta, has won four Emmys and other awards for his
music.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe no piece was more important to Atlantans than his musical
score for the film ``Time and Dreams'' about the city. The film,
produced by William VanDerKloot, was instrumental in helping to win
the Olympics for Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   A truly modern artist, Oliverio's sketch pad is the computer.
Though, like some writers, he often indulges his need to be
physically in touch with his work by putting pencil to paper, as
often as not he starts with an electronic grand piano. It's a real
piano, but it plays into the computer.
</P>
<P>
   He then is able to build and augment with computer-generated
tones.
</P>
<P>
   Through the power of the computer, artists will be able to feed
the insatiable appetites for something new, Oliverio said.
Combining the sounds with visual values will be one of the avenues
for new excitement.
</P>
<P>
   Artists like Oliverio and Tech technicians have already produced
ballet performances that included a dancer miles away from the
active stage, projected onto a screen and performing in real time
with the ``live'' performers. The remote dancer at times was
portrayed in changing colorful garb, sometimes flaming, sometimes
ghostly, all by computer manipulation.
</P>
<P>
   With the greater bandwidths possible with newer technology,
Oliverio said, a world class pianist here in Atlanta may perform
live with, say, the Albany symphony. It will be a way of extending
the living presence of world class performers, and also creating a
new kind of experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Live is important,'' Oliverio said. ``Unlike a pre-taped
performance, the combination remote performer brought by digitized
communication, and the orchestra in the auditorium allows
interaction among orchestra, conductor and the audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Oliverio believes musical challenges ahead will simply be new
ways to create music, but also ways to pull together music and
communication.
</P>
<P>
   ``Music listeners, especially our young people, look for
excitement,'' he said. ``Orchestras will have to turn from their
fears of the new and at least include newer things to build their
following.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he has been able to see firsthand, at Georgia Tech, the
possibilities of enticing smart young people to embrace new sounds
and production values in music.
</P>
<P>
   ``The students I teach are mostly from traditional engineering,
and some from computer sciences, looking for a new kind of musical
experience to carry through their lives,'' Oliverio said. They are,
in effect, a sampling of the audience of the future.
</P>
<P>
   Watching Oliverio do his thing at Tech, you realize he is an
embodiment of the audience he strives to reach.
</P>
<P>
   Though he teaches courses at Tech in the history of electronic
music, history is not his driving interest. Pushing the borders of
musical expression is. And he is not locked into computer generated
tones. It is an odd but instructive sight to see him turn from his
machines, and strike a note from the tuned kettledrum nearby.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the timbre of the notes I'm listening for,'' he
explains. Though he looks to a horizon, he stays in touch with his
musical base.
</P>
<P>
   His biggest pending project, he said, is his second Timpani
concerto, which will not be completed until the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it will be one of the most talked-about pieces of the
late 20th century,'' he said with a smile, ``or maybe the first in
the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-25-98 2105EDT &QL;
</P>
