<SLUG> BC-CPT-MICROSOFT-GINGRICH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GINGRICH QUESTIONS JUSTICE DEPARTMENT PURSUIT OF MICROSOFT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By MICHAEL PAULSON   
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ House Speaker Newt Gingrich, in his strongest
criticism to date of the government's case against Microsoft,
suggested Tuesday that the Justice Department would be better off
pursuing drug dealers or campaign finance violators than going
after the software giant.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich, speaking at a Seattle fundraiser for Rep. Rick White,
R-Wash., also said Congress should investigate whether the Justice
Department improperly has attempted to persuade foreign governments
to initiate their own legal cases against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Justice Department could do a variety of things _ they
could be looking more effectively into bringing drugs into the
country illegally, they could be looking more effectively at
illegal foreign campaign contributions _ there are a range of
opportunities for the Justice Department other than trying to
destroy jobs at one of America's leading companies and trying to
weaken America's role in the world market,'' Gingrich said.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Gingrich at first seemed to attribute that stance
to White, Rep. Jennifer Dunn, R-Wash., and Sen. Slade Gorton,
R-Wash, but a spokesman said later that Gingrich shares the
pro-Microsoft sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich, who posed for a photo with Microsoft vice president
William Neukom before giving his speech, seemed particularly
disturbed about the Justice Department's conversations with foreign
goverments.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Justice Department began to raise questions about
Microsoft the way they did, all over the world other countries also
began to raise questions,'' Gingrich said. ``There's some very real
question whether or not there was in fact collusion by the American
Justice Department encouraging foreign governments to file a
lawsuit against an American company.''
</P>
<P>
   Calling such activity ``entirely inappropriate,'' Gingrich said
it is ``something we're going to work very hard to get to the
bottom of. ... The purpose of the American government is to
strengthen American companies in the world market and increase
American exports in the world market, not to undermine American
companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich's complaint echoes one made last month by Sens. Jeff
Sessions, R-Ala., Jon Kyl, R-Ariz., and Spencer Abraham, R-Mich.,
who alleged that investigations of Microsoft by Japan, Israel,
Brazil and others were prompted by senior Justice Department
antitrust officials. The senators pointed out that shortly after a
visit to Tokyo by Justice Department antitrust chief Joel Klein,
the Japanese Fair Trade Commission raided Microsoft's offices
there.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did Gingrich make positive comments about Microsoft,
but he excised from his standard stump speech a positive reference
to technology manufactured by Sun Microsystems Inc., a California
company that is now suing Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the Justice Department defended the agency's
conduct. The Justice Department has been embroiled in various legal
battles with Microsoft for four years, most recently with a broad
antitrust suit accusing the company of illegally trying to extend a
monopoly on computer operating systems into the market for Internet
browsers. That case is scheduled for trial Sept. 23.
</P>
<P>
   ``The charge that the Department colluded with, solicited, or
encouraged foreign governments to take legal action is completely
false,'' said Justice Department spokeswoman Gina Talamona.
</P>
<P>
   Talamona also said it was appropriate for the Justice Department
to press its case against Microsoft, saying that ``The antitrust
division is about protecting consumers and enforcing laws, and we
need to continue to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   White said he has been encouraging the speaker to be more
outspoken on behalf of Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're indicating to him that he needs to speak out a little
bit more on the Microsoft situation, and I think he's relatively
receptive to that message,'' White said.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich has been spending parts of this week in Washington
state. On Saturday he attended the King County GOP picnic on Vashon
Island and a state GOP fundraiser in Seattle. On Monday he attended
a fundraiser in Pasco for Rep. Doc Hastings, R-Wash. Tuesday, in
addition to the White fundraiser, he visited the Pacific Science
Center at Seattle Center. Wednesday and Thursday he is to tour the
Hanford nuclear reservation, the Hanford Reach, and the North
Cascades National Park.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich has sharply limited his accessibility to the news media
while in Washington state, generally declining to answer questions
or grant interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich's staff Tuesday cancelled a promised question and
answer session at the Pacific Science Center, and physically
blocked reporters from following the Speaker around the private,
non-profit museum. Gingrich's spokesman said he did not want to be
distracted by questions about President Clinton's sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-25-98 2007EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
