<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 11:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2875 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-PORTALS-COX &LR;      08-26 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-PORTALS-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Web sites search out new ways to hang on to surfers 
By Frances Katz  
c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Memo to Web surfers everywhere: Knock it off.
</P>
<P>
   Find one comprehensive site and stay there. Search there. Shop
there. Check your mail there. Read the news there. Monitor the
stock market there. Plan your day there. Build a Web site there.
Surf on over. Stay a while.
</P>
<P>
   The newest scheme Web sites are adopting to eke out some kind of
profit is to load up their sites with additional products and
services in addition to their core businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo (http://www.yahoo.com) was perhaps the first company to
realize people conducting searches find what they want and leave.
To stop that disturbing trend, Yahoo has added a variety of new
services including phone service and a travel service.
</P>
<P>
   CNNfn (http://www.cnnfn.com), the Cable News Network's financial
Web site, plans to add a shopping area before the end of the year.
City-sites are also trying to hold on to audiences who have already
gotten into the habit of stopping by for local news and
entertainment information.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Interactive Media, which operates AccessAtlanta (http://www
</P>
<P>
   .accessatlanta.com), is planning a redesign of its 21
city-specific sites to include search capabilities aimed at
attracting a broader audience to the site. Both companies are owned
by Cox Enterprises Inc., which also owns The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems that everybody is thinking about portals,'' says Lisa
Allen, a senior research analyst at Forrester Research. ``There is
an epidemic case of portal envy, and it seems to be contagious
because it first appeared at the national level.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, CNNfn, one of the most popular financial sites on the
Web, announced it had taken an equity stake in C2B Technologies to
integrate an electronic commerce shopping area into the CNNfn site.
Craig Forman, vice president of CNNfn Interactive, says the area
will launch before the end of the year. The C2B shopping service
will include e-commerce as well as e-commerce comparison shopping.
</P>
<P>
   Helen Kim Whelan, CNNfn's vice president of business
development, says the addition of e-commerce to the CNNfn site is a
natural evolution for the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we found out on CNNfn is something that we've known for
quite a while _ our users are a well-heeled, educated bunch.''
</P>
<P>
   Most are middle-aged males with an average income of $87,000.
CNNfn users are also slightly ahead of the curve when it comes to
making purchases on the Web. Statistics show they've bought more
books, software and airline tickets. Like the TV networks who
understand the money to be made from a night of ``must see TV,''
media Web sites are just beginning to see it's not enough to have
users surf through your site. You've got to do something to make
them stay a while.
</P>
<P>
   Developing sites that will engage users for more than a minute
or two is a dramatic shift from the way Web sites were developed in
the Internet's infancy only three or four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started, it was all about breaking news and finding
news on the Internet,'' says CNNfn's Forman. ``We realized the Web
was something people wanted to come to for breaking news.'' But in
1998, CNNfn, finds itself with a huge loyal audience checking in
every day. (Measurement firm Relevant Knowledge ranks it the fourth
most-visited commercial network site on the Web). With 87 percent
of CNNfn's users returning daily and with research indicating they
are established e-commerce customers, the Web site decided to
provide shopping resources to keep users on the CNNfn site.
</P>
<P>
   Over at Cox Interactive Media, which oversees not only Access
Atlanta, but the sites around the country, users already get local
news and information courtesy of Cox companies such as this
newspaper as well as a variety of nationwide media partners. CIM
says the advantage of being ``the home team'' in each of these
markets is a key drawing point, but the goal is to draw even more
users into the site and keep them there. By mid-September, Access
Atlanta and Cox sites nationwide will add a search engine called
``LookSmart.'' It offers intelligent Web searches delivering local
Web information first followed by national and international
information.
</P>
<P>
   George deGolian, acting general manager of CIM's Atlanta studio,
says the addition of a search engine will draw more users to the
site including women and minorities _ two of the most rapidly
growing user groups on the Web. ``A few months ago we determined we
had a clear leadership in this space,'' deGolian says. ``Then we
looked at the Net as a whole and we realized the number one thing
people do on the Web is search.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The average Web user doesn't spend much time on the Web'' adds
marketing manager Beth Goldstein. ``We want to offer both features
and functionality _ a place where users will want to stay longer
because of the information we are able to provide. We don't want
users to visit our sites for local information and then hop off to
Yahoo! to look into buying a car.''
</P>
<P>
   Forrester's Allen calls this kind of tactic, whether it's adding
e-commerce to CNNfn or a high-powered search engine to Access
Atlanta ``sticky products.'' She says the goal of ``sticky
products'' is to get users to go a site and stay there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's enough to say, 'We want to be your first
stop when you log on to the Internet,''' she says. ``A better
approach is to not only strive to be the first site, but the site
where users spend the most time. You want users to spend time and
enjoy it. You don't want users to just walk. ``
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
