<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 12:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2931 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIANA-ANNVERSARY-$ADV     08-26 2132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIANA-ANNVERSARY-$ADV30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A YEAR LATER, DIANA'S DEATH . . .
 &HT;    With DIANA-INVESTIGATIONS-$ADV30; DIANA-WILLIAM-$ADV30.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (l) Lifestyle
categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, Aug. 30 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREAT BRINGTON, England _ Dorothy Jackson talks about a friend
who's gone away.
</P>
<P>
   She sits with her closest friends in a circle of folding chairs
arrayed around coolers topped with an assortment of quiches, fancy
cheeses, green salads and two nearly empty bottles of good white
wine. They await their appointed time to enter Althorp House,
Princess Diana's childhood home and final resting place. This
refined tailgate party is set between the neat rows of cars parked
in the grassy field that serves as a parking lot across a gravel
road from the grand country manor. With all the Mercedes, BMWs and
even a Rolls Royce in the lot, it is clear this isn't Graceland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had mixed feelings about this, actually,'' Jackson says with
both guilt and reverence in her voice. ``We were coming to Diana's
memorial, yet we were making it festive with a picnic.''
</P>
<P>
   She pauses and then continues on a new track. ``We've really
come to celebrate her life. She was a very lively extroverted kind
of character, so we've come to celebrate her.''
</P>
<P>
   Her cousin, John Massey, a courtly man wearing a navy blazer and
honey-colored necktie, chimes in cheerfully. ``I'm sure she's
looking down and thoroughly approving.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hmm,'' Jackson says approvingly. ``Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Then a sadness emerges in her voice. ``I miss her. I miss the
color that she brought to everyday life,'' she says. ``Suddenly,
she would be on the front of the paper or you would open the
newspaper and she was there, doing something, always. She gave this
feeling of, whatever she suffered, she was quite a light, wasn't
she?''
</P>
<P>
   To Jackson and her friends -- and to millions more worldwide --
Princess Diana of Wales still represents a powerful combination of
the glamorous and familiar.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her privileged and aristocratic background -- some say
her lineage was more royal than the royals -- she connected to
ordinary folks. They talk about her as if they hung out with her at
Kensington Palace, and shopped with her in the Sloane Street
boutiques. They know the failings of her marriage, her successes as
a mother and hold well-developed positions on her peculiar
relationship with the press.
</P>
<P>
   In the way that Americans over the age of 40 can tell you where
they were when they got news of President John F. Kennedy's
assassination, many Britons have fixed in their minds the moment
they learned about Diana tragic accident.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, a year after her death, Diana remains alive in the press,
still young and beautiful. Her blue eyes radiate from the front
pages of tabloid newspapers that hounded her in life. Television
chat shows and news magazines frequently re-hash the familiar story
of the black Mercedes slamming into the 13th pillar of the famed
Parisian tunnel resulting in the violent death of a 36-year-old
woman whose warmth and vulnerability touched so many people.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, virtually all major London dailies carried special
magazine sections marking the anniversary of her death. Taking note
of the potential for Diana overkill, a London Times media writer
recently used his computer to determine that the word ``Diana'' had
been used in news stories in the British press 72 times in a
three-day period of mid-July.
</P>
<P>
   Her life has been a rich mine for other media, as well. In
addition to a seemingly endless supply of books, authorized and
otherwise, two new Diana plays have opened here. There is talk of a
Walt Disney Co. movie.
</P>
<P>
   At times, the industry of commemoration has slipped into
exploitation.
</P>
<P>
   The Diana souvenir business has been brisk with an estimated
$165 million in sales to date. In gift shops throughout London's
touristy districts are Diana coffee cups, plates, posters, T-shirts
and yes, souvenir thimbles, piled high in gift shops.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers from Diana's estate and the Diana, Princess of Wales
Memorial Fund have been deployed to rein in the numerous
unauthorized uses of her image and name.
</P>
<P>
   They may have to work extra billable hours to keep up with the
inspirations of enterprise. One Parisian hotel is offering what can
only be described as a brief tour of Diana's death. ``I am simply
responding to demand from my clients,'' an unabashed Emile
Cacciari, manager of the three-star Odeon Hotel on the Left Bank,
told Reuters news agency.
</P>
<P>
   For $25 -- free to guests -- Cacciari is offering the chance to
relive Diana's final moments. For a little more, he can provide the
authenticity of a black Mercedes. ``We have a lot of American
visitors, and whenever they leave the hotel in the morning they
want to know two things and two things only: where is the Eiffel
Tower, and where is the Pont de l'Alma. People want to go (to the
scene of the crash); it's as simple as that.''
</P>
<P>
   The proceeds, he said, will be donated to the memorial fund.
</P>
<P>
   There are varying schools of thought about Diana's lasting
legacy here. Some people believe she has permanently altered
British life, as if people impressed by the warmth of her example
now have come in touch with their feelings and have opened up.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Lashmar, a London man who was at the gates of Kensington
Palace the night the city learned of her death, believes the
experience has helped Britons get in touch with their feelings. ``I
think we've definitely grown up since then,'' he says. ``I don't
think we would have behaved the way we do with the outpouring of
grief, and (us) being afraid to cry in public. I mean, that night
there were grown men of all shapes, sizes and descriptions crying
their eyes out.''
</P>
<P>
   The mourning has never really stopped. Bouquets with handwritten
notes still appear faithfully at Kensington Palace -- Diana's
former home -- where the world kept a televised vigil in the days
after her death.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such public displays, there are those who believe the
outpourings have been misinterpreted.
</P>
<P>
   Decca Aitkenhead, a columnist for the Independent newspaper
here, said on a recent TV chat show that she believes people were
moved more by the larger-than-life proportions of Diana's life,
death and celebrity than by real feelings for the woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kinds of emotional outpourings we saw in the week after
her death were genuine in so far as they were real emotions,''
Aitkenhead said. ``The mistake was to interpret them as grief, that
people were grieving for Diana. I think what people were
demonstrating was their desire to feel a part of a big momentous
occasion, to feel a part of history, to feel they can suddenly talk
to strangers and they could bond in queues waiting to write in a
condolence book.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I think as the year has passed, we're seeing it fade into
something that's just closer to sentimentality rather than a new
emotional maturity.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed a new study suggests that Britain was not as united in
its grief as the TV images suggested. Research by the British Film
Institute suggests that many people here were displeased that so
much airtime was consumed by the commotion surrounding Diana's
death. Nearly 40 percent of the 500 people surveyed said the
coverage was excessive and overly sentimental. Many were irritated
that soaps, soccer and cricket matches were sacrificed to the
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, but whatever it is, it persists.
</P>
<P>
   Within a week of going on sale, tickets to Althorp House were
snapped up by 152,000 people like Jackson and her friends. More
than 3,000 people a day have passed through Althorp's gates since
the estate was opened to the public July 1. Inside they find an
exhibit describing Diana's journey from gawky bride to
sophisticated patron. It ends with a visit to her grave on a small
island in a lake on the estate. Althorp's gates will close for the
year on Sunday(Aug. 30), the eve of the first anniversary of
Diana's death in a car crash in Paris' Pont de l'Alma traffic
tunnel, along with her boyfriend, Dodi Fayed and driver Henri Paul.
It has not been determined when they will open in 1999, a
spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   In Paris, where sentimentality is aggressively spurned, a
candlelit march on Monday(Aug. 31), to mark the moment of her death
is expected to draw 10,000 mourners. The underpass, where emergency
workers struggled to save the fatally injured Diana, has become a
point of pilgrimage for hundreds of people each day.
</P>
<P>
   And a recent opinion poll showed that 70 percent of Parisians
want a nearby boulevard renamed to honor the late princess.
However, the city's mayor has responded by saying that Parisian
streets and buildings cannot be dedicated to celebrities until they
have been dead for five years.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Purkins, who heads the memorial fund in Diana's name,
believes there is something deeper to her appeal. This, in part
because of her embrace of poor people and people on the margins,
and of causes such as Third World Poverty, AIDS research and
ridding the world of land mines that have in the past made the
British aristocracy squeamish.
</P>
<P>
   Diana's genuine regard for ordinary and damaged people will
stick, he said. ``That's something people instinctively know should
endure and is important, and is something that can be distinguished
from the more transitory emotions.''
</P>
<P>
   The fund, with a balance of nearly $80 million -- more than $30
million of which came from the proceeds of Elton John's ``Candle in
the Wind'' tribute -- intends to give $8 million to $10 million a
year to causes that trustees believe Diana would have supported.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps her most lasting influence is a change in the perceived
way the Royal Family interacts with the public. At times, this
regal populism can be awkward as with the recent visit by Queen
Elizabeth to a McDonald's restaurant. Perhaps fortunately, she
didn't order any food, saving a counter worker from having to utter
the phrase, ``And would one wish to have one's order
'Super-sized?'''
</P>
<P>
   Queen Elizabeth, who was accused of not emoting sufficiently
after Diana's death, ordered flags at royal residences to fly at
half-mast on Monday(Aug. 31), to mark the first anniversary of
Diana's death.
</P>
<P>
   The queen and husband, Prince Philip will be joined by Prince
Charles and sons William and Harry, for family prayers at Crathie
Church, just outside the grounds of Balmoral Castle in Scotland.
Also at the service will be Prime Minister Tony Blair and his wife,
Cherie. William, now 16, and Harry, 13, were told of Diana's death
by Charles while they were staying at Balmoral last summer.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest change in image has come to Prince Charles, once
vilified for being cold-hearted to the genial Diana. While still
far from hugging his future subjects in public, the prince is often
seen with his two sons in comfortable ordinary surroundings, the
picture of the modern dad.
</P>
<P>
   Less than four months after the crash, an opinion poll suggested
public approval of Charles had leaped nearly 20 points, from 42
percent last August to 61 percent in December.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun, that tabloid that dispensed its share of vitriol at
Charles' expense, patted him on the back this summer and even
advised him to go public with his longtime affair with Camilla
Parker Bowles -- once arguably the most hated woman in England.
</P>
<P>
   One of the new plays about Diana, ``Love Upon the Throne''
offers Charles a kind of forgiveness by expressing on his behalf,
sentiments he never would have shared in public -- even if he
really felt them. At the end of the play, the Charles character
utters these words to the stage Diana: ``I'm very, very, very sorry
for not loving you as I should have.''
</P>
<P>
   Waiting to pay her respects at Diana's grave, Jackson, dressed
in a tasteful dark dress selected with Diana inspired sensibilities
-- expresses the common feeling toward the princess.
</P>
<P>
   ``She became a legend in my lifetime and that's not something
one often experiences really,'' she said. ``She did leave a mark on
the world, and it's quite remarkable.''
</P>
<P>
   Her explanation of Diana's appeal is that the princess, despite
her advantages, was an underdog who survived in a hostile world and
in so doing discovered herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``She could have been a recluse and hidden from the world in the
later years, but she went off to help people. She decided to do
this herself, and that's what makes it all the more commendable.''
</P>
<P>
   She sips her wine thoughtfully.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the opportunity -- no, we all had the opportunity -- to
see a human being flower.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
