<HEADER>
A2953 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAGNET-THERAPY-HNS &LR;      08-26 1112
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGNET-THERAPY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME PAIN SUFFERERS FIND AN ATTRACTION TO MAGNETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Whenever Joan Schermerhorn feels a twinge of pain
in her knees, she reaches for a magnet rather than a bottle of
ibuprofen.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do feel like a kook,'' she said about applying magnets the
size of half-dollars to her knees. But, after almost a decade of
chronic pain from a rare disorder known as stiff man's syndrome,
Schermerhorn, 64, says she can't shrug off the fact that she feels
better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've tried every product I can think of for pain,'' she said
from her home in Clifton Park, N.Y. ``They're definitely a
relief.''
</P>
<P>
   If this sounds like snake oil _ and some physicians aren't
buying it _ consider that one of the largest manufacturers of
therapeutic magnets is reporting annual global sales of more than
$1.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics call it hype. Believers offer personal testimonials to
back up their claims that magnets aren't just for the refrigerator
anymore. Suffer from lower back pain? There's a magnetic seat
cushion. Have a headache? Try a magnetic headband.
</P>
<P>
   You'll find magnetic insoles for your shoes, magnetic mattress
pads for you bed and magnetic wraps for your arms, wrists and
knees.
</P>
<P>
   What you won't find are any good scientific studies in the
United States proving that magnets work.
</P>
<P>
   Though they are licensed medical devices in Korea and Japan,
magnets have not yet undergone any vigorous testing in the United
States. The Office of Alternative Medicine at the National
Institutes of Health is hoping to fill that gap with a study at the
University of Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, consumers are on their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe there is any good evidence the magnets do
anything,'' said Dr. Doyt Conn, senior vice president of medical
affairs for the Arthritis Foundation in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Like most alternative therapies, magnets aren't approved or
regulated by the Food and Drug Administration. And technically, any
salesperson who pitches magnets as a medical device is breaking the
law.
</P>
<P>
   Sellers and supporters of therapeutic magnets claim they promote
healing by improving circulation to the affected area.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the magnetic field is believed to attract and
repel charged particles in the blood, creating movement and heat.
As a result, blood vessels dilate, making it easier for blood to
circulate.
</P>
<P>
   They differ from common refrigerator magnets in their strength
and polarity.
</P>
<P>
   Fridge magnets register about 4 gauss, a measure of magnetic
strength, while therapeutic magnets register 800 to 4,000 gauss.
The magnetic field delivered by these magnets is static with no
frequency.
</P>
<P>
   A more accepted form of magnetic therapy in this country uses
pulsed magnetic fields. The FDA has long approved the use of pulsed
magnetic fields in ``bone-growth stimulators'' to promote the
healing of hard-to-heal fractures.
</P>
<P>
   Yet many physicians are skeptical that the static cousins, being
sold from basements, catalogs and stores across the country, have
any value.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no real science there that a physician or a consumer
can rely on to explain how it works or to know they're not being
ripped off,'' said Dr. Joel Kremer, a professor of medicine and the
head of the division of rheumatology at the Albany Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   That hasn't deterred people from using magnets in various ways
for centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Cleopatra reportedly slept with a magnetic lodestone to prevent
aging. Paracelsus, a Swiss physician and alchemist who lived from
1493 to 1541, theorized that since magnets had the power to attract
iron, they could also attract diseases and pull them from the body.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most famous proponent of magnets was Franz Anton
Mesmer, a German from whose name comes the word mesmerism. He
promoted the theory of ``animal magnetism.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, many horse trainers have started using magnets
on their injured thoroughbreds.
</P>
<P>
   Today, magnets are making a marketing comeback, in part because
of numerous endorsements by professional athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Steve Atwater, a starting safety for the Denver Broncos
who sleeps on a magnetic mattress pad. Jim Colbert, a top golfer on
the senior PGA Tour, reportedly credits his success to the magnets
taped to his back. New York Yankees pitcher Hideki Irabu uses
dozens of tiny magnets taped to his body.
</P>
<P>
   Also credited for the success of magnets is a convincing
marketing strategy, known as network marketing, used by Nikken, the
largest seller of magnets in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes associated with shady pyramid schemes, network
marketing thrives on word-of-mouth referrals.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of interest in those who are pushing it to
succeed,'' Kremer said. ``Therefore there's a lot of hype. All you
can say is consumer beware.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Physicians, at a loss to explain how magnets work, aren't
dismissing the power of suggestion. Studies have shown that 20 to
40 percent of people who unknowingly take a ``sugar pill'' or any
other placebo report an improvement in their symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   No one is saying the placebo effect isn't valid: if you feel
better, you feel better, no matter what the reason.
</P>
<P>
   The concern, however, is that people with chronic pain,
especially those suffering from some forms of progressive
arthritis, will opt for magnets rather than medical treatment and
that underlying problems could get worse.
</P>
<P>
   Conn, of the Arthritis Foundation, believes one reason people
are so willing to try magnets is because they aren't aware of the
medical options.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can do a very good job of managing most types of arthritis,
if we catch it early,'' he said. ``There's a general misconception
in the population that there's not much you can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Conn said he had no problem with people using magnets as long as
they don't use them in lieu of getting a diagnosis from a physician
and as a long as they don't discard other medical treatments.
</P>
<P>
   But he cautioned against investing a lot of money and hope in
unproven treatments. Magnets don't work for everybody and pregnant
women and people with pacemakers are advised not to try them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pain makes you vulnerable,'' Conn said.
</P>
<P>
   Schermerhorn has spent more than $200 on magnets and accessories
since she saw an ad for them in March in a free circular.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's worth every cent,'' she said. ``I can't get over it.''
</P>
<P>
   But she added that she has no plans to abandon her other
medications or regular visits to her neurologist. ``It's a relief,
not a cure,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-26-98 1217EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
