NYT-08-26-98 1234EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980826.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 12:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2990 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOURNAL-RUSSIA-$ADV27     08-26 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOURNAL-RUSSIA-$ADV27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LETTER FROM MOSCOW: DEAR MOM, SEND CASH
 &HT;    With RUSSIA-ECONOMY-0827.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International (k) Commentary categories.
 &HT;    For Use Thursday, Aug. 27 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ A note to Bill Clinton: On your scheduled trip to
Moscow next week, please bring dollars. The 10,000 American
expatriates in this city, not to mention 10 million or so Russians,
could use them.
</P>
<P>
   We'll write you a check ... honest.
</P>
<P>
   It is grim business for Russia, this main event of faltering
banks, plummeting stocks and the withering ruble -- a financial
crisis called ``Indonesia with nukes'' by some Western bankers.
</P>
<P>
   It has spawned a curious sideshow: Dollars are scarce and people
are spending considerable amounts of time and effort trying to find
them.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors of spotting an automatic teller machine (ATM) that will
accept a U.S. bank card and spit out dollars now spread through the
city like news of a UFO sighting.
</P>
<P>
   A woman I know was nearly mobbed on the street the other day as
she pulled a $20 bill out of her wallet on her approach to a
currency-exchange window. The eager Russians around her wanted to
trade their rickety rubles for her bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is sort of ironic that we are so used to U.S. dollars being
available everywhere and all of that seems to be over for the time
being,'' said Paul Backer, an American lawyer in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   The ruble may be legal tender in Russia, but the dollar is
serious cash. It is illegal to pay in dollars for goods and
services, and unlawful for merchants to accept them. But, well,
let's just say it happens -- often.
</P>
<P>
   In value terms, estimates say there are as many U.S. dollars in
circulation in Russia as there are rubles.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Aug. 17 announcement of devaluation that allows the
ruble to slide against the dollar by as much as 34 percent -- to
9.5 rubles to the dollar compared to its previous value of 6.2 --
dollars were easily accessible at banks, at American Express and
from ATMs in major hotels.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes before the announcement, I happened to walk in to the
American Express bank and cashed a U.S. check in order to pay my
telephone bill and other work expenses. They handed over $1,000 in
rubles and $2,000 in U.S. currency without a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Ten minutes later, the government devalued the ruble. Twenty
minutes later, an American colleague went to AmEx to pick up $8,000
wired to him by his editors. All banking services were closed. He
is still waiting for his money.
</P>
<P>
   Well-salaried expatriates are cash-starved. An American woman in
search of a working ATM posted a message on a computerized bulletin
board last week. Where can I go to get dollars, she asked. Someone
replied: Try the corner of 52nd and Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   It is no joke. Some Americans are contemplating trips to
Helsinki or Warsaw simply to get dollars wired from America and
bring them back to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   As for Russians, most of whom receive their pay in rubles, they
spend what they need to survive and convert the rest to dollars as
a form of cookie-jar savings account.
</P>
<P>
   That's why there are almost as many currency-exchange booths in
Russia as there are places to buy vodka, in other words, on just
about every other street corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dollar is in fact our national currency,'' quipped the
newspaper Sevodnya about last week's ruble devaluation, ``so let it
grow.''
</P>
<P>
   But with the ruble dropping, the price of dollars is going up.
Nervous banks and people are hoarding. Large Western companies
doing business in Russia are getting their dollars for now, but
they fear their corporate wire-transfers eventually could be
affected.
</P>
<P>
   Komsomolskaya Pravda newspaper offered a clip-and-save guide for
Russians to cope with the crisis, including tips such as: if you
were waiting to buy that TV or fridge, do it now. And don't
needlessly rush to exchange rubles for dollars as that will only
weaken rubles further.
</P>
<P>
   The advice concluded: ``If your savings are in a strong, hard
currency, you have just wasted your time reading this list.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
