<HEADER>
A3004 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-CUTRUFELLO-REVI     08-26 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-CUTRUFELLO-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUTRUFELLO `ON THE EDGE OF LIVING' HER DREAM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Thursday, Aug. 27) 
(Eds.: Cutrufello to appear on ``The Tonight Show'' on Thursday is
cq) 
(Attn: Conn.) 
 
By RICK MITCHELL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The first words heard on Mary Cutrufello's
cool-rockin' new album are ``Ain't it good to be alive on a sunny
day ...''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, every day feels like a good day to be alive for the
Houston resident who, in recent months, has maintained a low
profile locally while commuting between her management office in
Nashville and her record label in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wonderful place to be, on the edge of living your
dream,'' said Cutrufello last week prior to a gig at a local pub.
</P>
<P>
   Cutrufello's major-label debut, ``When the Night Is Through,''
was released Tuesday on Mercury Records. On Thursday, she will
appear on ``The Tonight Show'' with fellow guests Halle Berry and
Rob Schneider before starting what could become an extended
national and international tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting out there and playing in front of a crowd, that's what
I love to do,'' she said. ``I've got a hot band, and I'm putting
out a record I really dig. I've been working toward this for such a
long time. It's fun, because you can really feel the momentum
starting to build.''
</P>
<P>
   Cutrufello, 27, grew up in New Haven, Conn., listening to her
parents' album collection of Broadway musicals and mainstream rock
'n' roll on the radio. She moved to Texas in 1991 after graduating
from Yale University.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to play the guitar for a living,'' she explained.
``It seemed like Texas was the only place in the country you could
do that.''
</P>
<P>
   After landing in Austin and then moving to Houston, she immersed
herself in the regional honky-tonk culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something I sort of discovered while I was at the end of
my college years,'' she said of her passion for country music. ``I
graduated with a degree in American studies, so I figured I would
go study some American culture that I didn't know anything about.''
</P>
<P>
   Cutrufello proved to be a quick study. She soon found herself
playing for two-steppers in small-town dives, as well as for hip
roots-rock fans in Austin, Dallas and Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got to play three or four hours a night, three or four
nights a week,'' she said of her apprenticeship in country music.
``That's a great thing for learning how to entertain a crowd. I
also learned a lot about the importance of craft in becoming a
solid songwriter.''
</P>
<P>
   But eventually there came a point when Cutrufello realized she
had to get back to her own roots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I could do a pretty good facsimile of country _
for a kid from Connecticut. But if it's not your home, it's only
going to be so authentic.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a big difference between what I do and what Dale
Watson does, because (country) is Dale's home. One of the lessons I
learned was, I should go back to my home. I grew up on Petty, the
Stones, Bruce, Mellencamp, all that stuff. Where I feel most
comfortable is where I'm the most effective.''
</P>
<P>
   A national tour playing lead guitar with Jimmie Dale Gilmore
raised her profile in the music industry, as did an exhilarating
set at a rock showcase in Nashville. She was signed to Mercury
Records in March 1997 following her South by Southwest performance
at the Austin Music Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Night Is Through'' was recorded in Los Angeles with
producer Thom Panunzio, who has worked with U2, Black Sabbath and
Lone Justice, among other rock acts. Cutrufello and Panunzio put
together a studio band, including such heavyweights as drummers
Kenny Aronoff (John Mellencamp, Bob Seger) and Jim Keltner (Little
Village), bassist Bob Glaub (Jackson Browne, John Fogerty) and
keyboardist Rami Jaffee (the Wallflowers).
</P>
<P>
   But if Cutrufello was at all intimidated to find herself in such
heavy company, it doesn't come through in the recording. Her
throat-shredding vocals and attack-mode guitar are front and center
in the mix, while her songs reflect the influences of the Rolling
Stones, Springsteen, Mellencamp and other classic rockers. Jaffee's
organ, in particular, adds a soulful, vintage vibe.
</P>
<P>
   While the image of a dreadlocked black woman guitarist is not
quite as unexpected in rock as it was in country music, Cutrufello
still could prove to be a tough sell to rock radio programmers
unwilling to take a chance on anything different. A single, ``She
Can't Let Go,'' has been sent to adult-alternative and album-rock
formats.
</P>
<P>
   Cutrufello's manager, Holly Gleason, said a big factor in the
decision to sign with Mercury was the company's top-to-bottom
support for Cutrufello's musical vision. The cover art for ``When
the Night Is Through'' features a silhouette of Cutrufello on a
darkened street corner, guitar in hand, dreadlocks flying.
</P>
<P>
   ``To Mercury, it's `This is a great record,' not `This is a
great record for a black woman from Yale with dreadlocks playing
guitar.''' Gleason said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That Mary is all those things certainly makes her stand out,
but it's not like she needs special treatment. More than anything,
she sees herself as a guitar player who wants to rock.''
</P>
<P>
   The band Cutrufello will take on the road includes her Texas
rhythm section of bassist Roland Denny and drummer Dana Myzer, plus
former E-Street Band keyboardist Danny Frederici, who came out of
semi-retirement to do the tour.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas Frederici's former boss, Springsteen, has reinvented
himself as a folk singer in recent years, Cutrufello maintains a
firm faith in the healing properties of full-assault rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rock 'n' roll to me is a very powerful force that can bring
people together. It's a way to get through the hard times and
celebrate the good times,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a kid, I used to listen to rock radio out of New
York City. You got a sense of being in the community of believers.
It's like a sacred trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Rock 'n' roll could use a few more true believers these days,
and Cutrufello is ready, willing and able to pick up the fallen
flag. But whatever happens with her career, she's not planning on
moving to the music industry centers in New York or Los Angeles
anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Houston a lot. I like the spirit, the whole downtown
revival thing with the Astros,'' she said. ``Once you've come out
for small-market baseball, you can't very well move to a big-market
city.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-26-98 1250EDT &QL; 
