r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-26 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HEEL AND THE HEALING PROCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Here's where I hit the wall on President Clinton
and his problems.
</P>
<P>
   I was reading the transcript of Monday's White House briefing by
press secretary Mike McCurry. I read these to congratulate myself
on not being a White House reporter. I wouldn't even accept the
Martha's Vineyard beach beat.
</P>
<P>
   One reporter asked McCurry: ``What can we construe from the fact
that the first family didn't go to church yesterday and the
president hasn't set foot on a golf course of (sic) yet this
vacation.''
</P>
<P>
   McCurry answered: ``That they were enjoying their time _ well,
they were spending time together ...''
</P>
<P>
   At that point I just laughed.
</P>
<P>
   Then a reporter asked: ``Mike, you said the other day that it
was your sense that the healing process was not completed yet. Any
update on ...''
</P>
<P>
   The reporter wants an official update on the healing process? It
was at that point I began the screaming process.
</P>
<P>
   What about our healing process? Is there no relief from the
speculating heads on CNN, and the talk-show Monica jokes? The
nation is dying of Clinton water torture, as regular leaks drip
into our brainpan.
</P>
<P>
   The public may think that, because of Clinton and Ken Starr, we
in the news or commentary business are in hog heaven right now. No,
we're in pig hell.
</P>
<P>
   Our president acted like a pig, and we've been printing the
details, sometimes in wire stories citing a single unidentified
source, such as ``a legal source close to the Lewinsky camp.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What is there, a Camp Lewinsky?'' asked an editor who has to
look at stuff like this all day.
</P>
<P>
   Another editor said he hit his personal wall when he read a
story citing ``a source close to the garment.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, it wasn't a dry-cleaner.
</P>
<P>
   The above comments were made by staff members of the San
Francisco Examiner airing feelings about coverage of all the
president's problems. You could call it part of the healing
process, but this is a newspaper, not a touchy-feely presidency, so
this unofficial meeting was called ``a gasbag session.''
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't be right to divulge all the hot air that was vented.
Let's just say that when it comes to Clinton coverage, there's as
much free-floating anxiety and anger inside newspapers as there is
outside. OK, I'll mention a couple of ideas that came out of the
gasbag session:
</P>
<P>
   1) One reporter said that if Ken Starr's report to Congress on
the Clinton-Lewinsky affair isn't fit for children, it should be
printed in a section clearly marked ``Keep out of reach of
children.''
</P>
<P>
   2) Another reporter dissented, saying the Clinton sex scandal
was the first thing to get her teen-age nieces and nephews
interested in reading the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a literacy program that works. To make it more
effective we can do the same as (1) above, and mark it ``Keep out
of reach of children.''
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, I care more about my parents reading all this stuff.
They're old-fashioned. They don't like to read about sex in the
newspaper, and they don't like the idea that a president lied to
the nation, his family and supporters _ which until last week
included them.
</P>
<P>
   There's no healing process that will make them like Clinton
again. They yearn for a president they can respect.
</P>
<P>
   We're in a downward spiral, with Matt Drudge and yakking heads
on TV devaluing the national discourse. One editor here says, with
some exaggeration, that she looks back fondly at the O.J. Simpson
trial. At least she knew where all the leaks were coming from, and
didn't have to worry about a source close to the garment.
</P>
<P>
   We say we've had enough. We know we'll get more no matter what
we say. Everyone says they've had enough. They say they're just
buying the newspaper for the Yeltsin news.
</P>
<P>
   Man, that Yeltsin is so popular that newspapers are selling like
Beanie Babies.
</P>
<P>
   You won't get a media culpa from me. There is only one man to
blame for this toxic national Love Canal, not some vast right-wing
conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   This is the man who signed the Defense of Marriage Act, thereby
interfering in the private lives of gays who want to get married.
Now he's saying we're interfering in his marriage and private life.
</P>
<P>
   This is the man who got rid of Surgeon General Joycelyn Elders
after she made some controversial comments, including one in favor
of masturbation. Now we have a president who has tried to define
oral sex as a sin comparable to having extra cheese on a Big Mac.
</P>
<P>
   This is a man who started an affair in the Oval Office with an
intern when he was in the middle of a sexual harassment lawsuit.
What we have here is one arrogant, sanctimonious guy. All we got
from the man from Hope was hypocrisy.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton doesn't think he deserves everything that's happened to
him. The thing is, the American people don't deserve everything
that's happening to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, Democrats don't deserve what's happening to them.
Clinton has led them into a blind alley, and Republicans are
getting ready to pound them.
</P>
<P>
   If you're tired of this whole thing, turn off CNN and stop
buying newspapers. As for me, I am starting my healing process.
This will be my last Clinton column until the next shocking
revelation or act of war.
</P>
<P>
   Give it a few days.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-26-98 1258EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
