<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 12:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3014 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-26 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NAKED TRUTH ABOUT POLITICIANS AND MORALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCHENECTADY, N.Y. _ She was tall and blonde. She wore a bored
expression and very little else. She was on stage Tuesday afternoon
at Goldfingers, a strip joint on State Street, and music was
blasting.
</P>
<P>
   The tall blonde was performing some art. That's official now. A
federal judge has ruled that the relentless effort by the City of
Schenectady to shut down strip joints violates the First Amendment
of the U.S. Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning of this huge flap in Schenectady _ the one
that'll cost taxpayers a few hundred grand in damages and legal
fees for the ladies and their employers _ the issue has been
whether stripping to music is art or obscenity. That and who gets
to decide that question _ the performers, the customers or local
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Is that we want our politicians doing, telling us what's art and
what isn't?
</P>
<P>
   Last year, when the cops were raiding these joints every 15
minutes, I dropped by one of the clubs. What I saw was a giggling
squad of girls young enough to be my daughters _ and Bill
Clinton's, too, by the way _ adorned with tattoos and nose rings.
They were gleefully exhibiting for a bunch of goggle-eyed strangers
what they ought properly to display only for their husbands. Or, in
some cases, their gynecologists.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody, however, had gone out and dragged those spectators in
there. My admission fee was paid by my newspaper's expense account.
Hey, journalism is hell. But these guys had to cough up the money
themselves, and they did it willingly. If that's their idea of
artistic appreciation, whose business is it? Not mine. Not yours.
And certainly not Al Jurczynski's.
</P>
<P>
   Jurczynski, Schenectady's mayor, argues that he was just trying
to protect public decency. Well, fine. Nobody can argue that he's
been anything but a conscientious mayor. And he's right when he
says that these joints degrade the neighborhoods in which they're
located.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, though, the solution to that problem was to
zone these businesses into specific neighborhoods _ away from
homes, away from people who find their presence on the block
offensive. Zoning is a legitimate function of local politicians to
protect property values and neighborhood integrity. That's what
Rudolph Giuliani is doing in New York City, and the courts have no
problem with that. That's what city after city has done across the
country _ Boston, Baltimore, San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The republic still stands, doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   What politicians in those places have not done is to say to the
citizenry, ``We'll decide what you can see and not see. We'll
decide what's good for your character and what's not.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what that federal judge objected to, and he was
completely right to do so. Al is the mayor. Nobody elected him art
critic. Nobody elected him daddy.
</P>
<P>
   If it's true that prostitution is taking place in these joints _
and that's the criminal charge against one of these places _ then
prosecute the crime, don't try to board up the club.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I'm delighted that Mayor Al and Mike Broadbank, his
city lawyer, are not liable for personal damages in this case. But
I'm not thrilled that the taxpayers of Schenectady will have to pay
damages to these strippers, the club operators and their lawyers.
When Jurczynski had his cops start busting these people, it should
not have required a Felix Frankfurter to see where this would end
up.
</P>
<P>
   That's precisely what happens, though, when local politicians
try to impose their visions of morality and art appreciation on
everybody else. You can approve or not approve of strippers and
stripping, but this particular art form has been around at least
since Salome.
</P>
<P>
   And it really is dangerous when some local politician like Al
Jurczynski starts counting her veils.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
