<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-STRING-BEANS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREEN BEANS ARE NOW HAILED ON THE PLATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHERYL JULIAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ If only Jack had known: All beanstalks are magical. He
wouldn't have traded his mother's only cow for a handful of beans
and wouldn't have had to endure her sorrow as she tossed them
outside. Of course, there would have been no castle above the
clouds and no frightening giant with a hen who laid golden eggs.
</P>
<P>
   To find ordinary magic, however, Jack could have just planted
bean seeds and watched them grow. The stalks reach skyward
overnight. They appear so willingly, the vines looping up and
around, turning themselves into airy bushes laden with slender
green ornaments, that it's nothing short of garden enchantment.
</P>
<P>
   It suits the beans. They've finally reached their glory. A
vegetable once so dependable in its frozen state that a generation
of American children knew little else, fresh beans are now treated
with the same reverence as the garden's exotica. They've moved out
of their amandine rut into an exalted position on the plate. They
appear bathed in balsamic vinaigrette and toasted walnuts, tossed
with grilled portobellos, wrapped up with a vinegary white anchovy
fillet, sauteed Asian-style with fermented black beans, and steamed
with native halibut and a handful of summer herbs. Wet weeks and
dry spells both slowed down the harvest briefly, but green beans
are now bountiful _ and beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   They weren't always. Before the renovation of the American menu,
green beans were stringy (hence the name string bean), often chewy,
rarely very slender, and cooked to an olive color. When they were
fresh in summertime, they were ``boiled,'' which sounds frightening
_ and was. It seemed as if some people put the beans on to cook
after breakfast, in anticipation of the midday meal.
</P>
<P>
   Today, when good cooks offer green beans in August, they're
always native, often harvested that morning. ``Imports,'' or beans
that come from New Jersey, for example, are never considered. And
each bean has been plucked from the vine by hand. ``On the
hand-picked you find the stem on, on the machine pick you'll see a
cut,'' explains produce distributor Henry Wainer of Sid Wainer and
Son in New Bedford, who always goes for the hand-picked bean.
</P>
<P>
   There are machines that act like hand-pickers. At Wilson Farms
in Lexington, where all beans offered are hand-picked, Calvin
Wilson points out that new mechanical pickers leave on the calyx,
or stem end. The biggest disadvantage to the machine, he says, is
that beans have to be large enough for it to pick. They're ``not
the perfect size you want to pick,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Though you can buy beans all over town, native beans are found
only at farm stands and farmers' markets. Local wholesalers give
growers so little money for their beans, says Steve Verrill of
Verrill Farm in Concord, that he wouldn't offer beans to the
vendors at New England Produce Center in Chelsea because ``you come
back without a shirt on.'' Verrill would rather plow them under
than take less than they cost him to pick. At his farm stand he
gets $1.79 a pound, which is the going rate. They're exactly the
right size to eat, the beans aren't bursting out of the pods, and
nothing is bruised.
</P>
<P>
   In bean terminology, hand-picked beans are the elite corps. So
are beans that you can call by name. These include Maxibels, very
slender and extra long; Fire Dragons, off-white beans streaked
dramatically with purple and green; Royal Burgundy, green inside
and dark purple outside, meant for eating young in salads; and
Triumph de Farcy, or haricots verts, thin, tender French beans that
need only the slightest cooking.
</P>
<P>
   On the plate, wherever they turn up, they have their pointed end
on. ``The groovy part,'' says Stan Frankenthaler of Salamander
restaurant in Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   And there are other unwritten rules. Green beans arrive on the
plate nicely crunchy (never underdone) and if they're served raw,
the chef knows who picked them and when.
</P>
<P>
   Frank McClelland of L'Espalier in Boston picks his own beans
some mornings. He goes into his South Hamilton garden with his
6-year-old son, Keppler; his 5-year-old daughter, Annie; and baby
James, 18 months. His home garden is his ``inspiration garden,'' he
says. Most of L'Espalier's produce comes from Green Meadow Farm in
Wilbraham.
</P>
<P>
   His own beans might be sliced very thinly lengthwise (what is
often called ``Frenched,'' to replicate the skinny French beans).
He does the Frenching to order, he says, so the beans hardly sit
before they're served _ without blanching _ as a garnish for a
seared piece of fresh tuna. ``It's a little tedious,'' he admits,
``but when you get a vegetable that's that fresh it cries with
moisture.''
</P>
<P>
   Frankenthaler serves speckled Fire Dragons or the purple Red
Burgundies raw in salads, dressed with a lemon vinaigrette and
shallots. ``We do that purposely to keep the decorative look and
the crunch,'' he says. Another of his signature dishes is a saute
of mixed beans tossed with hot sesame oil, garlic, ginger, and
fermented black beans.
</P>
<P>
   Frankenthaler's produce comes from Nesenkeag Farm in Litchfield,
N.H., and from Hutchins Farm in Concord. Both have a system for
informing Frankenthaler and the other chefs in town the day before
what they will be picking _ or not picking. Two weeks ago, because
of the heavy rains in June, Hutchins had no beans to ship to
restaurants. The few that pickers culled from the beanstalks, says
Hutchins co-owner Gordon Bemis, went to the farm stand. Stalks
planted after the rains allowed him to send out lots of beans the
following week.
</P>
<P>
   Bemis is growing a Kentucky Wonder bush bean, a bean that used
to grow only on poles. He describes it as having ``good bean
flavor.'' Some chefs describe the fleshy Romano beans, which are
wide and flat, as having a ``meaty'' flavor. Romanos need more
cooking than ordinary green beans.
</P>
<P>
   To ensure maximum bean flavor, chefs use the ``blanch and
shock'' method of cooking, in which the beans are dropped into
boiling water for a minute or two, then plunged into an ice-water
bath. The technique gets its name from the shock of the ice after
the heat of the boiling water. The blanching offers a head start on
the cooking while the ice brings back the beans' bright green
color.
</P>
<P>
   Michele Belben, general manager of East Meets West catering,
says that when chef Greg Topham sees native beans that are
``gorgeous _ long with the stems on,'' he blanches and shocks them.
Then he tosses them with a balsamic vinaigrette, dusts them with
crushed walnuts or pine nuts, and marinates them overnight.
``They're best at room temperature,'' says Belben.
</P>
<P>
   Both Frankenthaler and Ana Sortun of Casablanca in Cambridge are
using Nesenkeag's golden beans. ``They're not like yellow wax
beans,'' Sortun says. ``They're a darker yellow, they're smaller
and brighter _ not quite as bright as tiny yellow tomatoes.''
</P>
<P>
   When striped bass was in season, Sortun made a compote of golden
beans with tomatoes and ribbons of zucchini to set under the fish.
Now she's doing the same dish with halibut.
</P>
<P>
   Sortun doesn't blanch the beans first for all dishes because
she's convinced that small slender beans have thin enough skins
that don't need extra cooking. ``It's the difference between a good
fresh pea and a woody fresh pea.''
</P>
<P>
   Her antipasto contains beans roasted in olive oil and tied into
bundles with a pickled white anchovy fillet. ``Beans are sort of
like potatoes,'' she explains. ``They need something kind of salty
that will bring out their sweetness.''
</P>
<P>
   For John Ingalls of Palmer's restaurant in Andover, the beans
need smoke. He tosses grilled portobello mushrooms with hard-cooked
egg, adds shaved Asiago cheese, and finishes the dish with slender
haricots verts.
</P>
<P>
   Ingalls learned green beans amandine in cooking school. In 1977,
at the Culinary Institute of America in Hyde Park, N.Y., they ruled
the menu, he says. ``We sauteed almonds, the sliced kind, until
they had a nice brown color on them.'' The beans had already been
blanched and shocked. As a dish was ordered, ``we steamed the beans
to warm them up, then dropped them in the saute pan with the
almonds, salt, and pepper. We served them with beef _ either prime
rib or filet mignon.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Verrill, whose farm sends half a dozen bean varieties
including Jade and Garden Jumbo to 15 restaurants inside Route 128,
goes into his kitchen at home and makes what he calls ``a big
production.''
</P>
<P>
   It drives his wife crazy, but he insists on steaming all the
varieties separately. ``Two different kinds of beans in two
different pans,'' he explains. Then he pulls a bowl from the
cupboard and sits down to eat. ``I like to eat beans just steamed
in a cereal bowl with butter, cream, salt, and pepper,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Let the chefs fuss with flavors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
