<HEADER>
A3020 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-BEAN-RECIPES-BOS     08-26 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-BEAN-RECIPES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME RECIPES FOR FRESHLY PICKED STRING BEANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHERYL JULIAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TO BLANCH AND SHOCK GREEN BEANS
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fill a large bowl with ice and water. Trim the stem ends of the
beans, leaving the pointed ends intact. Bring a large saucepan of
water to a boil (you need 3 quarts). Add a generous pinch of salt.
Drop in the beans and let them cook, turning them several times,
for 3 to 5 minutes, depending upon the recipe.
</P>
<P>
   Drain them in a colander and immediately plunge them into the
ice water. Leave them until cold. Use as directed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
GREEN BEANS IN BALSAMIC VINAIGRETTE
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from East Meets West catering in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   1 pound slender green beans, blanched for 4 to 5 minutes or
until cooked through and shocked (see instructions)
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup walnuts, coarsely chopped and toasted until golden
</P>
<P>
   Drain the beans, spread them out on paper towels, and pat them
until they are dry. Transfer the beans to a bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Whisk together the salt, pepper, balsamic vinegar, and mustard
in a small mixing bowl. Gradually whisk in the oil, a little at a
time, until the dressing emulsifies. Pour the dressing over the
beans and sprinkle with walnuts. Cover with plastic wrap and
refrigerate for several hours or overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
GREEN BEANS WITH GRILLED PORTOBELLOS
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Palmer's restaurant in Andover, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   4 portobello mushroom caps
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil, for sprinkling
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs, cooked in boiling water for 12 minutes, then transferred
to ice water
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound haricot verts, blanched for 2 minutes, and shocked
(see instructions)
</P>
<P>
   2 Belgian endive, pulled apart into leaves
</P>
<P>
   Balsamic vinegar, for sprinkling
</P>
<P>
   Shavings of Asiago cheese, for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Light a charcoal grill. Sprinkle the mushrooms with oil, salt,
and pepper. Grill the mushrooms until they are cooked through,
turning them often, and taking care not to char them too much.
Remove them from the grill and let them cool.
</P>
<P>
   Peel and chop the eggs coarsely.
</P>
<P>
   Drain the beans, spread them out on paper towels and pat them
until they are dry.
</P>
<P>
   Divide the endive leaves among 4 salad plates. Arrange the beans
and the mushrooms on the leaves. Sprinkle with the vinegar. Then
sprinkle on the chopped eggs and garnish with Asiago shavings.
Season with salt and pepper, and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
SAUTEED GREEN BEANS WITH FERMENTED BLACK BEANS
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Salamander restaurant in Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   1 pound slender green beans, blanched for 3 minutes, and shocked
(see instructions)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons dark Asian sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons chopped fresh ginger root
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup fermented black beans, rinsed in a strainer under a cold
tap, drained, and finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup water
</P>
<P>
   Drain the beans, spread them out on paper towels, and pat them
until they are dry.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in a large skillet, and cook the ginger and garlic
until the garlic begins to brown. Add the beans and water, cover
the pan, and steam the beans for 2 minutes, turning once or twice,
until they are cooked through. Taste for seasoning, add more salt
if you like, and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
ROASTED BEANS TIED WITH AN ANCHOVY
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Casablanca restaurant in Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   1 pound slender green beans
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil, for sprinkling
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   4 white pickled anchovy fillets (available at specialty markets)
</P>
<P>
   Set the oven at 400 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Trim the stem ends of the beans, leaving the pointed ends
intact. Transfer to a bowl and drizzle with oil. Sprinkle with salt
and pepper. Spread the beans in a roasting pan and transfer to the
oven. Roast the beans, tossing them often, for 25 minutes or until
they are cooked through, still crunchy, and slightly shriveled.
</P>
<P>
   Use tongs to arrange the beans in 4 clusters on a dish, so that
all the beans are stacked in the same direction. Drape an anchovy
fillet onto each bundle and serve at once, or use as part of an
antipasto platter.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
