 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 GET YOUR DIANA T-SHIRT HERE! (and other travesties)  
 &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of Richard Roeper's popular
weekly columns, now being offered as a regular New York Times
Syndicate feature. For a bio &AMP; photo _ as well as special contract
rates _ please contact your sales representative:
 &HT;    _ If you're in the Eastern time zone or Canada, call BOB FARNELL
at 1-800-535-4425. Or send a fax to him at (717) 646-4850.
 &HT;    _ If you're in the Central time zone, call CONNIE WHITE at
1-800-444-0267. Or fax her at (816) 822-1444.
 &HT;    _ If you're in the Pacific or Mountain time zones or in Latin
America, call OLIVIA VASQUEZ at (310) 996-0075. Or fax her at (310) By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.1998 The Chicago Sun-Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Pop quiz!
</P>
<P>
   Which of the following Princess Diana-related stories is not
true:
</P>
<P>
   A. To mark the first anniversary of Diana's death in an auto
accident, the British ballet superstar Wayne Sleep recently
recreated the dance he performed in 1985 with the princess onstage
at London's Covent Garden. At the end of the tribute dance, he left
a single rose in a spotlight in Diana's memory and exited the
stage.
</P>
<P>
   B. Tubs of butter bearing the official logo of Princess Di's
memorial fund were made available to the public.
</P>
<P>
   C. Donald Trump told reporters he regretted Diana's death
because he, and we quote here, ``never had a chance to ask her
out.''
</P>
<P>
   D. The Odeon Hotel in Paris is offering a ``Diana Tour,'' taking
you through the final hours of her life. For $25 you can ride in a
black Mercedes (just like Di's death car!) from the Ritz Hotel,
where Diana and Dodi had their last meal; to the Pont de l'Alma
tunnel, where the crash occurred; to the Pitie-Salpetriere
Hospital, where Diana was declared dead.
</P>
<P>
   E. While anchoring the live coverage of Diana's funeral, NBC's
Tom Brokaw fell in and out of a fake British accent and said things
like, ``That shan't be too long.''
</P>
<P>
   F. A committee overseeing Princess Di's memorial fund is
considering a number of ways to spend the money _ including a plan
to bankroll a team of student nurses who would specialize in the
care of sick children. The nurses would be known as ``Diana's
Angels.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As you probably guessed, it's a trick question. The answer, of
course, is that all of the above items are TRUE, and they represent
just a small portion of the stupefyingly bizarre ripple effect of
perhaps the most shocking celebrity death we've ever known _ the
auto accident in Paris on Aug. 31, 1997, that claimed the lives of
three people, including the Lady Formerly Known as Princess, Diana
Spencer.
</P>
<P>
   Within days of Diana's death, she was elevated to
premature-death pop-sainthood, right there with Elvis and Marilyn,
John Lennon and James Dean.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, given her worldwide popularity before the tragic
accident and the volcano of emotion that erupted following her
death, she may be the queen of them all. She's certainly in a
position to challenge Elvis (whose death-anniversary is Aug. 16,
just 15 days away from Di's) for the crown of most marketable
celebrity, post-mortem category.
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Diana, Princess of Wales Memorial Fund was established to
raise money for some of her favorite charities, including the
Leprosy Mission, the National AIDS Trust and the Royal Marsden NHS
Trust for cancer and organizations benefiting land-mine victims,
and to put some sort of restrictions on the hundreds of
opportunists seeking to market the name and image of Diana.
</P>
<P>
   To date the foundation has raised nearly $100 million. One item
alone _ Elton John's ``Candle in the Wind 1997,'' the top-selling
single of all-time _ has accounted for approximately $40 million.
</P>
<P>
   About 60 companies have the endorsement of the fund _ meaning
they can use the official logo of a purple replica of Diana's
signature.
</P>
<P>
   Literally hundreds of other organizations and individuals have
attempted to profit from her demise. Some of these unauthorized
attempts to sell Di merchandise, including the Franklin Mint's line
of dolls, plates and jewelry, have resulted in the fund taking
legal action (which is still pending) in an effort to protect her
image; more obscure efforts have flown under the legal radar.
</P>
<P>
   Available officially or otherwise, Princess Di products number
in the dozens, if not the hundreds. A partial listing:
</P>
<P>
   _ Rose-scented candles.
</P>
<P>
   _ At least five video tributes.
</P>
<P>
   _ A CD of the entire funeral mass. (When exactly would you pop
this in the stereo and listen?
</P>
<P>
   _ The Princess Diana Dollar Bill _ a real $1 bill with the image
of Diana slapped over George Washington's picture.
</P>
<P>
   _ T-shirts, including one with the factually incorrect slogan,
``Born a Princess, Died a Saint.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Soap dishes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Coffee mugs.
</P>
<P>
   _ A CD of songs about death and sadness (most of them written
well before Diana's death) recorded by pop artists such as George
Michael, Paul McCartney and Whitney Houston.
</P>
<P>
   _ More than 100 books.
</P>
<P>
   _ A cheap-looking ``reproduction'' of Diana's driver's license,
listing her height as 5-11 and her weight as 125. Her supposed
license photo appears to have been snapped at a cocktail party.
</P>
<P>
   _ A number of posters, including one with a doctored photo
purporting to show Diana unzipping her jeans.
</P>
<P>
   _ Souvenir plates.
</P>
<P>
   _ Comic books.
</P>
<P>
   _ Playing cards.
</P>
<P>
   _ A $200, 18-inch ``Queen of Hearts'' porcelain doll, produced
by the Society For the Preservation of History, Inc., whatever that
is.
</P>
<P>
   _ The special edition, purple Beanie Baby bear, which retailed
for $5.99 but routinely sells for more than $300 on the open
market.
</P>
<P>
   _ Key rings.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bumper stickers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Refrigerator magnets.
</P>
<P>
   _ A Christmas ornament bearing a portrait of Diana on one side
and the inscription ``Princess of the Common People'' on the other
side.
</P>
<P>
   _ Music boxes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Postage stamps from a number of tiny countries you probably
never heard of, such as Togo. Most of the art isn't good enough to
be displayed at flea markets.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere there are people who buy these things _ not as kitsch,
not with a wink-wink, nudge-nudge sense of wicked playfulness, but
with the most serious and sincere intentions of hanging the Di
ornament from their Christmas tree, proudly displaying the
porcelain doll in a place of honor in the living room, and lighting
that scented candle before taking a bar of soap from the Princess
Di soapdish and drawing a bath.
</P>
<P>
   I just don't know where these people are.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Richard Roeper (rroeper &LR; suntimes.com) can be heard on the
``Media Creatures'' show, which airs daily in Chicago from 10 a.m.
to 2 p.m. on WMVP-AM (1000) and appears Tuesday and Thursday at
7:55 a.m. on WFLD-TV's ``Fox Thing in the Morning.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (A daily columnist for the Chicago Sun-Times, Roeper has also
written for TV Guide, Spy, Playboy, Chicago magazine and many other
publications, and has appeared as a guest on ``Nightline'' and
``Oprah.'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ---------------- &QC;
</P>
