<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENNOCHI-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK ON MY MIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN VENNOCHI  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The shadow of New York looms ever larger in Boston these days.
</P>
<P>
   From West 34th Street, Macy's East confirms it is kicking a
beloved New England holiday tradition out of its downtown Boston
department store.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown Crossing's Enchanted Village will be relocated _
hopefully _ to Boston City Hall Plaza, according to a press release
entitled ``Macy's Enchanted Village Statement.''
</P>
<P>
   The retail space that once housed the village will be converted
to office use.
</P>
<P>
   For nostalgic New Englanders, the quick conclusion is that
nothing good happens when out-of-state corporations buy out the
locals.
</P>
<P>
   Federated Department Stores, Macy's corporate owner, is actually
based in Cincinnati, not Manhattan. But Macy's flagship store is
located in the Big Apple. And the chain's overall image and appeal
is grounded in its sense of New York fashion, flair, and style.
</P>
<P>
   Federated acquired R.H. Macy Co. and its Jordan Marsh
subdivision in 1994. A new corporate division was created, called
Macy's East. It didn't mean much locally until 1996, when the
company decided to kill the 145-year-old Jordan Marsh name,
replacing it with Macy's.
</P>
<P>
   Reaction here was predictably dour _ especially since news of
the name change was accompanied by a notice to customers that
Macy's credit card finance charges would be 20 percent higher than
Jordan's.
</P>
<P>
   Macy's executives tried to lighten the mood with promises of
increased commitment to local causes. To symbolize their good
intentions, they served baskets of Jordan's famed blueberry muffins
at a business breakfast to discuss the name change.
</P>
<P>
   But as of this July 4, Boston's downtown Macy's stopped selling
blueberry muffins.
</P>
<P>
   ``They weren't selling,'' says Macy's spokesman Ronnie Taffet.
``We were giving away more to the Pine Street Inn than we were
selling to customers.''
</P>
<P>
   No more muffins? And the Enchanted Village, if it exists at all,
will operate out of heated tents on City Hall Plaza _ possibly at
public expense?
</P>
<P>
   Macy's is talking about donating the animated recreation of an
old-fashioned New England winter. But it would be the city's
responsibility to operate it. Mayor Thomas M. Menino estimates it
would cost about $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Menino reacted sternly at first to Macy's planned eviction of
the Enchanted Village. ``We're not going to let the Grinch steal
Christmas,'' he told the Boston Herald.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday, the mayor softened his tone. ``Ho, ho, ho,'' he
joked, insisting: ``Macy's is not the Grinch.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it isn't.
</P>
<P>
   Macy's pays for the annual tree-lighting display on Boston
Common. It sponsors Menino's annual holiday trolley tour to Boston
neighborhoods. And according to its official Enchanted Village
statement, ``the holiday excitement at Macy's ... will continue
with Santa in residence daily and a host of seasonal events and
entertainment through Christmas Eve.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, Macy's sponsors weekly special events in Downtown
Crossing. Macy's also works with the city's tourist industry to
help sell Boston as a destination, according to Patrick Moscaritolo
of the Greater Boston Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have more than delivered on what they said they would
do,'' said Moscaritolo, adding: ``Would it be wonderful if we could
freeze-frame everything and there could always be an Enchanted
Village? Of course. But businesses are constantly evolving.
Business plans are constantly changing.''
</P>
<P>
   The global economy means there are fewer and fewer homegrown
businesses working directly with their community.
</P>
<P>
   Macy's is working hard to maintain a strong relationship with
Boston. Moving the Enchanted Village isn't so terrible. And it
would be even less terrible if Macy's would continue to pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Macy's Santaland ``is alive and well'' on the eighth
floor of its Herald Square store in New York, according to Taffet.
</P>
<P>
   Ho, ho, ho.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Joan Vennochi is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
