<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 13:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3036 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIRTUAL-CLASSROOMS-BO     08-26 1363
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIRTUAL-CLASSROOMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CYBERCLASS IS IN SESSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANN MULLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a moment, Bruce Hunt felt like he'd leaped into an episode
of the space-age cartoon, ``The Jetsons.''
</P>
<P>
   With a few clicks of his computer mouse, Hunt found himself in a
``virtual classroom'' with about a dozen other Kronos Inc.
colleagues scattered around the world, listening and watching as an
instructor in Chelmsford, Mass. briefed them on the latest features
of Kronos' labor management software.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of spooky, having a voice come out of my laptop,''
said Hunt, a California-based product manager whose job is to
oversee the installation of Kronos software for the company's West
Coast customers. And it was strange, he said, to participate in a
live group discussion with people he couldn't see through his
computer screen.
</P>
<P>
   But like many technology sales and service professionals who are
pressed for time, Hunt quickly concluded that spending an hour or
two in a virtual classroom on the Internet is a lot better than
wasting two or three days traveling between his regional office in
Long Beach and Kronos' Waltham headquarters for the typical product
training session.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Leon Navickas is counting on. His start-up company,
Centra Software Inc. of Lexington, Mass., is lining up some big
customers for its Internet software, called Symposium, which helps
companies reduce their training costs and boost productivity
through distance learning and collaboration over the World Wide
Web.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Kronos, other major companies using Symposium include
AT&AMP;T Corp., Motorola Inc., Hewlett-Packard Co., and Bay Networks
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   But corporations aren't the only ones attracted to the
interactive, multimedia features of Centra's distance learning
software. Colleges and universities are also recognizing its
usefulness, especially for coursework that's designed for midcareer
professionals who can't take time off from their jobs to head back
to campus.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Tennessee, for instance, this year began an
executive MBA program for physicians that uses Symposium to conduct
on-line class sessions on Saturday mornings.
</P>
<P>
   During focus groups, university administrators learned that
physicians were eager for advanced business instruction tailored to
the medical field but couldn't afford to spend more than four weeks
a year away from their practices.
</P>
<P>
   The solution, said management professor and program director
Michael Stahl, was to create a curriculum incorporating four,
one-week sessions on campus and a yearlong series of Saturday
morning classes on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Each Saturday from 9 a.m. to noon (eastern time), 21 doctors
from 12 states tap into their home or office computers to
participate in live, instructor-led courses in finance, accounting,
and other business-related topics.
</P>
<P>
   They watch and listen as the instructor presents material on
their computer screens, and they ask questions by ``raising a
hand'' _ tapping a key on their keyboard that causes a little
hand-shaped icon to pop up on the participants' screens.
Individuals can't speak up, however, until they are recognized by
the instructor, who maintains control of everyone's microphones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Often in a traditional classroom, one or two people may
dominate a discussion,'' said Dr. Arthur Porter, a prominent
Detroit physician enrolled in the course. ``With these mechanical
constraints, it puts in a little bit more discipline,'' said
Porter, who admits, nonetheless, that he found the first few
on-line classes to be ``a little disembodying.''
</P>
<P>
   But Porter, who is associate dean of the School of Medicine at
Wayne State University and senior vice president of the Detroit
Medical Center, a group of Michigan hospitals, says he's amazed
that he is able to continue working, keep up a busy travel
schedule, ``and still not miss class.''
</P>
<P>
   During the past year, he has attended his MBA class by simply
plugging his computer into a phone line in hotel rooms in London,
Cancun, and Jamaica _ even in a small town in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's great is that you can log into a local phone number in
any of these countries, and end up spending three hours with your
colleagues back in Tennessee, or elsewhere in the United States.
The only thing you really have to remember is what time zone you're
in.''
</P>
<P>
   None of this would have been possible just a few years ago. But
as the Internet has matured, companies such as Centra and
Kentucky-based DataBeam Inc. _ which was recently acquired by Lotus
Development Corp. _ are finding ways to harness the power of the
Web to provide real-time, interactive collaboration in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   Lotus, a Cambridge, Mass. unit of International Business
Machines Corp., pioneered the idea of groupware in the early '90s
with its introduction of Lotus Notes, a software program that
allows far-flung employees to collaborate on a single project or
document.
</P>
<P>
   Navickas, a 12-year Lotus veteran who once headed the Notes
research and development effort, left the company shortly before
its 1995 acquisition by IBM to build his own company that would
take the collaboration idea a step further.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas Notes focuses on document management or workflow within
an organization, ``we're modeling a higher level of human
interaction,'' Navickas said.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of Symposium, he said, is to use multimedia technology
to mirror the energy of a roomful of people who are trying to
promote teamwork, problem-solving, and decision-making.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Centra is targeting its Symposium software at the
sales, service, and support organizations of large, global
companies that want to become more competitive by reducing the time
it takes to bring new products to market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technology changes so quickly. Any competitive advantage is a
big plus,'' said Stephen Henry, director of educational services
for Bay Networks' North American operations. The big computer
network equipment company is using Symposium to keep its
salespeople and distributors up-to-speed on its latest products so
they can take the information to customers more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The other big advantage for companies that buy the $35,000
software is the cost savings and increased productivity.
</P>
<P>
   Navickas estimates that American companies will spend upward of
$60 billion this year on corporate training, but the lion's share
of the money will be spent on airline tickets, hotels, and meals.
</P>
<P>
   Hands-on training is important when a brand-new product is being
introduced, but often that's not necessary for simple product
updates, companies say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't make sense to fly someone from Australia to Boston
for a two-hour class. It's cost prohibitive,'' said Michael
Courtemanche, a Kronos training specialist who has conducted more
than 30 on-line classes using Symposium software.
</P>
<P>
   On-line training, he said, works best when the material is
sharply focused for the audience and doesn't cut into employees'
work time.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as what you're tyring to teach is in little bite-sized
chunks, it's ideal,'' he said, noting that no one has the endurance
to stare at a computer screen for more than an hour or two at a
time.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Richardson, vice president of research strategy at AMR
Research in Boston, said he believes there are many more
applications for the interactive technology that Symposium offers.
</P>
<P>
   His company, for instance, has purchased the software and
intends to use it for monthly analyst conference calls with
clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not all our guys are Jay Leno,'' he said. ``They can't do
monologues. We want to be able to dress up the conference calls we
do with clients. It's too boring to talk for an hour.''
</P>
<P>
   And Stahl, the University of Tennesse professor, predicts more
colleges and universities will latch on to the idea of interactive,
on-line education, especially for professional programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the executive's point of view, why should he or she
travel every other weekend to go to campus, when the campus can be
brought to the computer in their office as they sit there in a
warm-up suit with a cup of coffee?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
