<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYERS TAKEN BY SURPRISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Revolution's collapse during a 5-1 defeat against
Los Angeles Saturday led to the resignation of coach Thomas Rongen.
But Revolution players insist they continued to believe in Rongen's
methods, though the team has the worst record in the MLS.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I'm surprised, and I'm saddened by what happened, to be
real honest,'' forward Joe-Max Moore said Tuesday. ``Thomas is a
great guy and a great coach and he will have success wherever he
ends up. Unfortunately, he had one of the toughest jobs in the
league, in my opinion. He did as much as he could with what he
had.''
</P>
<P>
   Walter Zenga, a goalkeeper for the Revolution last season, will
guide the team starting with Sunday's visit to Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of who comes in at this point, if we don't win this
game, it's close to over for us,'' Moore said. ``We have to come to
play for 90 minutes and get a result. I don't think the majority of
players lost faith in Thomas. Most of the players have a lot of
respect for Thomas. He prepares the team extremely well. You don't
go from coach of the year to not being a good coach. He was given a
tough assignment.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore was the most outspoken player on the team after the loss,
criticizing teammates. He remains frustrated by the Revolution's
failings _ they have earned 91 points in 92 regular-season games in
three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see it with teams all over the world, where a new coach
comes in and players want to prove themselves, and sometimes it
creates a spark,'' Moore said. ``The timing of the change is a
little strange. I have a lot of respect for Walter as a player,
most people around the world do, but he doesn't know the players
and he hasn't been around team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to come in and decide who the starting 11 should be.
He will need a lot of help. He might be a great coach, but this is
a tough situation. If he gets results, everyone will be much
happier. We haven't had a winning product for three years here, and
everyone is frustrated. I don't want to be part of a losing team. I
want to be somewhere where we are winning consistently.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Revolution captain Mike Burns:
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of respect for Thomas and I would play for a
Thomas Rongen-coached team again in a minute. A lot of times the
coach is going to take the fall for the team's record and so a
decision was made. I've always been a big supporter of Thomas and
believe he is a good coach. Now, we have a six-game season and if
Walter comes in and we get in the playoffs, everything looks good.
Without a doubt, it's an uphill battle, no matter who the coach is.
It all boils down to one game. If we get 3 points in this game, and
we are 3 points behind with five games left, anything can happen.
</P>
<P>
   Burns, who will be suspended for a game after being ejected
midway through the second half against Los Angeles, is optimistic
about the change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe, just a change will be good for this team,'' Burns said.
``Walter knows some of the players, the organization, and everyone
has a lot of respect for what he has done on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's his first coaching experience, so we'll see. It's a
no-lose situation for Walter because a lot of people have already
written us off. I know Walter and he is very charismatic and
knowledgeable about the game. If he can find a way to spark the
team and push the right buttons, and get us into the playoffs,
that's what counts.''
</P>
<P>
   Team dissension became apparent after the Galaxy game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it can be corrected, if not we have no chance this
season,'' Burns said. ``We have to put personal feelings aside. We
don't have to like each other but we have to respect each other.
This is like a championship, a one-off game, and I hope we can push
aside everything because we are all professionals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
