<SLUG> BC-BBO-SPORTS-DRUGS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS ARE WARY OF DIETARY SUPPLEMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Home run hitter Mark McGwire may or may not be sending more
baseballs over the wall by taking a duet of dietary supplements.
</P>
<P>
   But he's definitely sending the wrong message to millions of
young fans.
</P>
<P>
   That was the warning Tuesday sounded by a series of doctors
familiar with creatine and androstenedione, two naturally-occurring
substances sold over-the-counter that McGwire last week
acknowledged taking. The physicians admit they don't have all the
answers on whether the supplements are dangerous, but they say that
makes them nervous and therefore cautious.
</P>
<P>
   Start with creatine, an amino acid that is in the meat and fish
we eat and in muscles as creatine phosphate, a compound that helps
muscle cells replenish their supply of energy. In the late 1980s
researchers discovered that loading up on creatine could give
athletes the fuel they need for longer, harder workouts. But since
getting the doses needed would mean eating more meat or fish than
was practical, scientists developed synthetic powders that are
mixed with fruit juice or water.
</P>
<P>
   Last year creatine sales worldwide reached $350 million, with up
to 18 million people taking the supplements.
</P>
<P>
   But is it safe?
</P>
<P>
   ``From the studies we've done on short-term acute effects it
appears to be safe,'' says Charles Yesalis, professor of health and
human development at Penn State University and author of ``The
Steroids Game.'' ``In five to 10 years I will be able to speak to
you about its long-term effects.''
</P>
<P>
   That uncertainty is why the Association of Professional Team
Physicians, which covers all the major sports, takes a go-slow
approach. ``People are starting to take mass dosages, they're
loading up, and our physicians say loading adds strain to the
liver,'' explains Mark Allen, vice president of the association.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do know, and the manufacturers prove this in all their
marketing propaganda, that it will build muscles, but the question,
`At what cost?' I can't tell you it's harmful because we don't have
that data, but I can't tell you it's not harmful. When you don't
know something, the best thing is to take a conservative stance.''
</P>
<P>
   Androstenedione is even more controversial, in part because its
benefits for athletes are less clear-cut while its risks could be
more substantial.
</P>
<P>
   The hard-to-pronounce supplement is a steroid. In some people it
raises the level of testosterone, which can enhance performance by
building lean muscle mass; in others it can increase concentrations
of female hormones, or simply do nothing at all. It is unclear
whether it builds in tissues the way the much-used and abused
anabolic steroids do.
</P>
<P>
   Is androstenedione helping McGwire? ``It is likely not
contributing to his success at all,'' says Dr. Carlon Colker,
medical director at Peak Wellness, a Connecticut center that
specializes in research on human performance and natural
supplements.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Scott Connelly is more upbeat, which isn't surprising since
he manufactures an enhanced form of the supplement at the company
he founded and heads, MET-Rx Engineered Nutrition. Taking his
androstenedione product elevates testosterone levels by as much as
30 percent for short periods which, when combined with
conditioning, yields ``strength increments and lower levels of body
fat, and a bunch of psychological effects in which sex drive and
libido are increased.''
</P>
<P>
   While it doesn't singlehandedly explain McGwire's keeping pace
with Roger Maris's record-setting home run clip, Connelly adds,
``It is part of his success.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever its benefits, the supplement could pose risks. Many
users ``are probably taking pharmacological amounts at industrial
strength,'' worries Dr. Chip Souba, chief of surgical oncology and
director of nutrition support at Massachusetts General Hospital.
``At those kinds of doses, over long periods, exactly what it
translates into is uncertain.''
</P>
<P>
   The NFL, NCAA, and International Olympic Committee banned
androstenedione. The Association of Professional Team Physicians
has asked for the supplement to be taken off the consumer market
and made available only by prescription.
</P>
<P>
   While that group and others are worried about the use among
professional athletes of creatine and androstenedione, what they're
even more worried about is the lessons such usage offers to young
athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Over just the last two days, as word has circulated about
McGwire's taking the supplements, MET-Rx has seen a tripling of new
orders for androstenedione and a doubling of existing orders, much
of which presumably is going to youthful users.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an ethical question that needs to be answered by Major
League Baseball: Is this what they want us to perceive as winning _
winning at all costs?'' asks Arnold Scheller, Celtics team
physician. ``I don't think it's sending a good message to the
younger population.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
