<HEADER>
A3048 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKO-LEWIS-INSURANCE-B     08-26 1300
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-LEWIS-INSURANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWIS CASE RAISES QUESTIONS FOR INSURERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BENJAMIN LIPSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Revelations surfacing pertaining to alleged cocaine use
by late Celtics star Reggie Lewis raise serious insurance
questions.
</P>
<P>
   Were the Boston Celtics and Donna Harris-Lewis, who shared in
the reportedly more than $14 million of life insurance proceeds as
a result of Lewis's death, not only beneficiaries of life insurance
policies on his life but also beneficiaries of technical baskets
made after time ran out?
</P>
<P>
   A provision contained in all life insurance policies issued in
this state, as mandated by Massachusetts law, prevents insurance
companies from denying death benefit claims on policies more than
two years old even if a material misrepresentation was made on the
policy application.
</P>
<P>
   What is even more disturbing is the report that the Equitable
Life Assurance Society of New York paid a claim to a beneficiary on
a policy that was purchased on Lewis's life less than two years
before he died. If there was a material misrepresentation made on
the application at the time of its purchase, that policy should
have been rescinded and no claims paid.
</P>
<P>
   Surely the insurance company involved has a fiduciary
responsibility to its shareholders and policyholders to make
certain that only legitimate claims are paid. State insurance
regulators have a statutory obligation to enforce that
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   If any of the other widely reported 1991 policy purchases were
less than two years old on April 30, 1993, the date of Lewis's
controversial stay at New England Baptist Hospital, and more than
two years old at the date of his death _ July 27, 1993 _ there
could be further insurance company embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to be a Harvard Law School graduate to know that
if an applicant for a multimillion-dollar life insurance policy
conceals a history of cocaine use, it is a prima facie material
misrepresentation.
</P>
<P>
   That's why one of the insurors of Lewis's life insurance
policies requires the insured _ or a corporate officer or a partner
in a partnership, if that kind of entity is the policy owner _ to
affix a signature on the policy application to certify that it is
understood that coverage could be invalidated if any information
provided in answers to the questions asked on the application is
materially misrepresented. Other insurance companies have similar
wordings in their applications.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance companies are risk takers, but insuring someone with a
history of cocaine use is one risk that is off the charts.
</P>
<P>
   At the insurance physical, the applicant is asked about any drug
history by the medical examiner. More than one company's medical
examination form contains the following question: ``Have you ever
used or are you now using valium or other tranquilizers;
barbituates or other sedatives; marijuana, cocaine, hallucinogens,
or other mood-altering drugs; heroin, methadone, or other
narcotics; amphetamines or other stimulants; or any other narcotics
or controlled substances, except as legally prescribed by a
doctor?'' Others are only interested in only drug uses for a period
of several years immediately preceding the date of the application.
</P>
<P>
   After the questions pertaining to any present or past drug use
and others pertaining to the applicant's health are answered, the
insured is asked to sign the following statement, which appears on
most policy applications: ``To the best of my knowledge and belief,
the above statements are complete and true.'' Some insurers extend
that certification to include, ``It is understood that if any of
the above statements is a material misrepresentation, coverage
could be invalidated as a result.''
</P>
<P>
   Before any company can proceed with the underwriting of a life
insurance policy, the applicant is also required to sign a broad,
all-inclusive authorization form that allows the insurance company
to obtain medical records from any source and talk to anyone,
including physicians, neighbors, and associates, regarding his or
her character, lifestyle activities, and general reputation.
</P>
<P>
   The authorization form is, in effect, a blanket privacy release
related not only to the information the applicant provides to the
medical examiner but also to any other fact that may be uncovered
during the investigation of the applicant's medical and lifestyle
history.
</P>
<P>
   It then remains for the insurance company to determine the
validity of the information provided and also _ through the use of
everything from field investigators from credit reporting companies
to interviews with friends, associates, neighbors, employers, etc.
_ to determine the insurable interest of the parties and whether
there is any other information that could result in unfavorable
underwriting.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance companies have significant experience in underwriting
multimillion-dollar life policies, and in the Lewis case it is
highly unlikely they didn't act prudently in the first instance to
ferret out the appropriate information they were authorized to
obtain.
</P>
<P>
   Individuals contacted may have been unaware of damaging
information in the applicant's background or were reluctant to
disclose its existence, knowing the adverse consequences of such
revelations not only to the insurance applicant or his or her
family or employer but also to themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Too often the distinctions between the time frame and under what
circumstances a life insurance policy can be rescinded or a claim
denied are misunderstood.
</P>
<P>
   If a misrepresentation in the policyholder's life insurance
application is uncovered within two years of the date of issue of
the policy, recision by the insurance company is a slam dunk. The
two-year contestable period found in life insurance policies is
operable, and the insurers can and must take unilateral action
consistent with policy provisions.
</P>
<P>
   However, when an insured dies after a policy has been in force
for more than two years, the insurer is powerless to deny paying
the beneficiary even if it is determined that there was not only a
material misrepresentation but also fraud involved when the policy
was purchased.
</P>
<P>
   The statute mandating that, part of Massachusetts insurance law,
was last amended in 1907. It is obvious the legislators at that
time never contemplated the emergence or ramifications of the drug
culture, the need to know about the presence of the AIDS virus
(HIV) antibody, or that an insurance company would be selling
multimillion-dollar life insurance policies to corporations,
partnerships, and affluent individuals.
</P>
<P>
   So as it stands now, insurance applicants with an uninsurable
medical history or a serious history of drug usage can rely on the
fact that if they apply for life insurance, lie, conceal derogatory
information, make sure those who know them conceal vital
information, and live two years or more, their beneficiaries will
collect the policy benefit on their death.
</P>
<P>
   Owners of professional sports teams, particularly those who are
seeking taxpayer money to build new stadiums, would be well advised
to explore the availability of life insurance before signing
superstars to guaranteed, multimillion-dollar, long-term contracts
unless they are willing and have the ability to self-insure the
life insurance risk.
</P>
<P>
   If there was a material misrepresentation in the Lewis case, the
lessons to be learned will cause future underwriting evaluations
and background investigations for multimillion-dollar policies to
be more stringent. Life insurance companies don't like to be
snookered. The medical histories and lifestyle activities of
superstar athletes can be expected to be put under the microscope
when they apply for life insurance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-26-98 1312EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
