<DOCNO> NYT19980826.0184 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 13:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3058 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIA-WOMEN-2TAKES-AR     08-26 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-WOMEN-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN LEADING SOME OF THE COUNTRY'S MOST INNOVATIVE NEWSPAPERS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jeannine Guttman, editor of the Portland (Maine) Press Herald,
recalls the lessons of being the only women in a room full of male
editors. ``When you talk, your colleagues stare at the ceiling or
look at their watches or interrupt you,'' she explains. ``I think
when it comes to readers feeling (disenfranchised), we understand
it because we've been there.''
</P>
<P>
   Martha Steffens edits the Binghamton (N.Y.) Press &AMP; Sun-Bulletin
and cares for her two children while her husband works out of town.
She believes female newsroom executives tend to be more creative
with their newspapers because they often have to be more creative
to make their lives work. ``The mother of invention,'' she notes,
``that's a woman.''
</P>
<P>
   For about a decade now, women in journalism schools have
signficantly outnumbered their male counterparts. Yet they are
still a distinct minority atop newspaper mastheads. (Only about 15
percent of the 850 members of the American Society of Newspaper
Editors are female.) Despite the numbers, some observers believe
that women editors whose experiences have informed their
journalistic values are the vanguard of a newspaper revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Top editors like Guttman, Steffens, The Charlotte (N.C.)
Observer's Jennie Buckner, Susan Deans of The (Myrtle Beach, S.C.)
Sun News, Tonnie Katz of The Orange County (Calif.) Register, Kay
Tucker Addis of The Virginian-Pilot and The Idaho Statesman's Karen
Baker are guiding some of the most reform-minded newspapers in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   In a profession traditionally averse to change, they write
columns explaining their decisions to readers. They reshape
newsroom hierarchies. They invite citizens to sit in on news
meetings. They hire nontraditional journalists. They search for
solutions to pressing local problems. And they embrace ``civic
journalism'' projects that directly engage readers by using
everything from polls to casual coffee shop chats to solicit
citizen views on important issues in the community.
</P>
<P>
   Women are not alone in shaking up their newsrooms. Some of their
male counterparts are engaged in similar efforts. But the
indisputable fact is that women editors are aggressively
experimenting with newspaper journalism. The touchy question is
whether being women makes them more inclined to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Schaffer is executive director of the Pew Center for Civic
Journalism, which funds media outlets working on civic journalism
projects. Her experience suggests women are more likely than men to
try new methods of connecting with readers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women were able ... and maybe not afraid to develop more
intimate ties to the community,'' Schaffer says. ``I hate to
stereotype, but sometimes women can listen better. ... They're
willing to take risks to create new things.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of female editors accept that basic premise for reasons
that range from nature to nurture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is a difference in how men and women approach
the situation,'' says Baker, who has been executive editor of the
65,000-circulation Idaho Statesman for a year. ``I think women are
sometimes more sensitive to people and not just the people on the
staff, but readers as well.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The old definition (is) that news is something that happens to
or near an editor,'' adds Susan Deans, who has spent eight years
editing The Sun News in rapidly growing Myrtle Beach, S.C. ``Women
tend to have different things happen near or to them.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No pigeonholing
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's tricky trying to establish linkage between gender and job
performance. And some female news executives are reluctant to do
so, worried that they will be pigeonholed as ``women editors''
instead of simply ``editors.'' Asked if female editors are more
naturally innovative, Geneva Overholser, the former Des Moines
Register editor and ex-Washington Post ombudsman, pauses and says:
``Probably so. But beware (of stereotypes).''
</P>
<P>
   Tonnie Katz, who has edited the 364,000-circulation Register
since 1992, says there wouldn't be a breast-feeding room next to
her office if there were a male editor at the paper. And she
pointed out that the Register's 1996 Pulitzer Prize for its
investigation of unethical fertility practices at a research
hospital was the result of women editors immediately understanding
the significance of the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Katz, who worked at both Boston dailies, calls herself a
journalistic maverick. But ``I know a lot of male editors who think
like me,'' she says. ``I think it's a personality quirk as opposed
to a gender quirk.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Women generally tend to be more collegial in seeking input
from others,'' says Addis, editor of the 199,000-circulation
Virginian-Pilot. But she thinks it's hard to connect innovation and
gender.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly there are some female editors who are products of a
system that was adventurous before they took the reins. In
addition, some of these editors run smaller dailies where it is
considerably easier to change the internal culture and create
intimacy with readers than at larger institutions.
</P>
<P>
   But it's hard to ignore the changes that these newsroom managers
are implementing. Guttman, who was named editor of the Press Herald
in Maine (circulation 72,000) a year ago, writes a regular Sunday
column concerning journalism issues as part of what she calls a
``pen-pal relationship with readers.'' Every few weeks, she holds
an in-house seminar with staffers to discuss the paper's
performance. The Press Herald has engaged in several large-scale
civic journalism projects, including a eight-day series on alcohol
abuse in Maine that generated a statewide dialogue on the subject.
And several months ago, Guttman hired a full-time community
coordinator to help the paper reach out to its readers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-26-98 1313EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980826.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3063 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-EIGHTH-BOS &LR;      08-26 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-EIGHTH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EIGHTH DISTRICT RACE PRODUCES SOME UNUSUAL CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A bizarre tale of death threats, extortion, and
prostitution rings involving a former business associate of
congressional candidate John O'Connor is threatening to distrupt
the campaign as it heads into its final three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor, a Democratic contender in the Eighth District, says he
is the victim of a shakedown attempt by the former friend and
associate, John A. DeFrancisco Jr., of Somerville, and has hired
bodyguards to protect himself after DeFrancisco allegedly
threatened physical violence.
</P>
<P>
   DeFrancisco is demanding $350,000 or he will leak damaging
information about O'Connor's businesses to news outlets, O'Connor
says.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor, a nationally known enviromental and community activist
who is using his wife's inherited supermarket fortune to launch a
political career, said he has refused to meet DeFrancisco's demands
and instead has asked the attorney general's office to investigate
what he says is an extortion attempt.
</P>
<P>
   But DeFrancisco denies making any threats against O'Connor and
his family and says he wants only what he is owed from their
business dealings and that some of his comments were ``taken out of
context.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to portray me as a violent person,''
DeFrancisco said. ``It's a total set-up.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor hired DeFrancisco in 1994 to run one of his for-profit
firms _ a Cambridge-based company that sells a device that
significantly slows down corrosion of heating oil tanks.
</P>
<P>
   DeFrancisco confirmed he was interviewed on Monday by a state
trooper and an assistant attorney general assigned to the criminal
division. The attorney general's office Tuesday declined comment,
saying it does not confirm or deny investigations.
</P>
<P>
   DeFrancisco, meanwhile, accused O'Connor of creating a
fabricated story to discredit his allegations about their business
dealings and to silence him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's like `Wag the Dog,''' he said, referring to the movie
about a president who creates a fake war to protect himself from a
sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   He said O'Connor, worried about his political career, wanted him
to lie about their relationship, because DeFrancisco has a criminal
record that stems from charges four years ago he was running a
$20,000-a-week prostitution ring.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Connor's friends and advisers say the strange developments
came about because the candidate has a history of using his wealth
to help people who are struggling or are down on their luck such as
DeFrancisco. He has financed tuitions, made large donations to
causes, and helped a host of poor and disadvantaged people with
financial aid.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those who have been helped by O'Connor have had scrapes
with the law, others are struggling with drug and alcohol problems.
But in this case, those aides say, O'Connor's charity and big heart
has come back to haunt him unfairly.
</P>
<P>
   ``After this guy threatening me and my wife _ and partcularly my
wife _ I have decided to legally take the gloves off,'' O'Connor
said. ``This hurts me. I am going to do everything in my power to
make sure this criminal pays for the crimes he has committed. We
can't let lawbreakers go unpunished.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor had hired DeFrancisco in 1994 to run Tank Protectors
Inc., shortly after he had been indicted by the Middlesex district
attorney's office on charges he and his wife had operated a
suburban prostitution ring.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor says DeFrancisco, whom he has known since their
freshman year in college, had maintained his innocence and promised
him he would beat the charges. O'Connor, believing his friend, paid
for his legal bills.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed the charges against DeFrancisco seemed far less serious
when the case was disposed of in March 1996. He pleaded guilty to
reduced charges of conspiracy to commit prostitution, a
misdeamonor, and was sentenced to 30 days in jail. He served 18
days, was fined $25,000, and given 350 hours of community service.
He resigned as Tank Protection president.
</P>
<P>
   In a severance agreement signed in October 1996, DeFrancisco
received $53,000 in cash and other benefits. At the same time, he
also wrote a letter to O'Connor, still proclaiming his innocence,
but said he needed to save time and money and to ``move foward with
my life.''
</P>
<P>
   But O'Connor said DeFrancisco reappeared this spring just as he
was getting his campaign in full swing, angrily demanding more
compensation and claiming he had been cheated in the severance
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   As negotiations stalled between his aides and DeFrancisco in
recent weeks, O'Connor rebuffed the demand, charging his old friend
was threatening him with physical harm and thinly veiled death
threats.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter breaking off negotiations, O'Connor's attorney,
Anthony J. Barsamian, outlined what they said were the threats they
said were made at various meetings in front of O'Connor's wife,
Carolyn Mugar, his lawyer, and a Mugar family financial manager, at
various meetings over the past month.
</P>
<P>
   The letter, addressed to Somerville lawyer John F. Zamperelli,
states: DeFrancisco ``has said at various times that unless the
demands were met, he would `hurt' John O'Connor, that he has
trained in martial arts and was therefore `capable of hurting
John', that he `has been thrown under a bus and now someone was
going to throw John under a bus,' and that he would `take this to a
level that John didn't understand,'' that John should go to
confession or do an act of contrition without delay.''
</P>
<P>
   The O'Connor attorney also alleged DeFrancisco had threatened to
expose certain O'Connor's business dealings, ``legal and illegal,''
and said his deadline for a settlement was the September 15
primary. DeFrancisco has raised allegations that O'Connor allowed
unemployment fraud to take place at his various profit and
non-profit firms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
