<SLUG> BC-MOB-FLEMMI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLEMMI, BULGER FORGED SHARED FBI BOND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHELLEY MURPHY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It seemed like a risky move.
</P>
<P>
   James ``Whitey'' Bulger was working for the Winter Hill gang
back in 1975 when he offered to introduce fellow gang member Stevie
Flemmi to one of his friends: FBI Special Agent John Connolly.
</P>
<P>
   Alone in a Somerville garage, Bulger confided to Flemmi that he
was ``doing business'' with Connolly _ and that the agent wanted
Flemmi to meet him, Flemmi testified Tuesday in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   Bulger did not actually admit that he was an informant, Flemmi
said, but ``it was obvious he had a relationship'' with the bureau.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Bulger had told Flemmi earlier that Connolly had
reached out for him, and at that time Flemmi advised, ``It's a
pretty good idea, go ahead and meet him.''
</P>
<P>
   So, it came as no surprise that Bulger had forged an alliance
with the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   But while exposing himself as an FBI informant might have
brought reprisals from some of his other gangster friends, Bulger
apparently knew he had nothing to fear from Flemmi, who had been
giving information to the FBI since 1965.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had some background information on me before he made the
approach, that was obvious,'' said Flemmi. He speculated that
Connolly told Bulger about Flemmi's informant status.
</P>
<P>
   There was no way Bulger would have asked Flemmi to meet an FBI
agent unless he already knew that Flemmi was also an informant,
Flemmi said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I didn't have a relationship (with the FBI), I would have
said, `What are you, crazy?''' Flemmi said. ``I would have looked
at him differently. I would have distanced myself from him.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, their shared FBI bond brought Bulger and Flemmi closer.
</P>
<P>
   With Flemmi's consent, Bulger arranged for FBI agent Dennis
Condon to introduce Flemmi to Connolly at a Newton coffee shop in
late 1974 or early 1975, Flemmi said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just wanted to meet me, it was a transition,'' said Flemmi,
whose previous FBI handler had been transferred to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the meeting, Flemmi had just returned to the
Boston area after living as a fugitive in Canada for five years,
dodging an attempted murder charge in the case of a lawyer who was
injured in a car bomb. The case was dropped when a witness recanted
testimony that had implicated Flemmi.
</P>
<P>
   Flemmi said he was eager to go straight, but Condon and Connolly
were ``very persuasive people.'' He said they convinced him to
fraternize with the local Mafiosi, then report any intelligence
they had on the mob.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Flemmi said, he was using Bulger to funnel information
about local Mafia activities to Connolly. Later that year, Flemmi
said, he began accompanying Bulger to meetings with the agent.
</P>
<P>
   For the next 15 years, Bulger and Flemmi kept up a double life
as FBI informants while ascending in the underworld. But today,
Flemmi blames the FBI for pushing him back into crime to boost his
value as an informant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't relish my relationship with the FBI,'' Flemmi said.
``I wasn't going to make a career out of it. I didn't plan it that
way. It just happened that way.'
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
