A3075 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKO-LEWIS-CLAUSE-BOS &LR;      08-26 0358
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-LEWIS-CLAUSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLAUSE UPHELD BY STATE SUPREME COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BENJAMIN LIPSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The more-than-90-year-old insurance law that
established the two-year incontestability clause found in all life
insurance policies issued in this state was reaffirmed in a
Massachusetts Supreme Judicial Court decision a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1995 case of Protective Life Insurance Company v. D.
Sullivan, the insured, who was HIV positive, was issued a $100,000
life insurance policy in November 1981 after he did not disclose in
his application that he was recieving medical treatment and
medications for his condition despite questions calling for this
information.
</P>
<P>
   Two years after the policy was issued, when the insured made a
claim for a waiver of premium benefit, the insurer investigated the
claim and brought suit in the US District Court in Boston to
rescind the policy, claiming the insured had obtained coverage
through fraudulent misrepresentation. The court found that the
insured had indeed committed fraud and ruled in favor of the
insurance company.
</P>
<P>
   That District Court judgment in favor of the insurer,
Prospective Life, was overturned by the Supreme Judicial Court.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Margaret Marshall wrote in her opinion that since the
statute does not specifically exclude fraud as part of the
incontestability clause, its absence does not violate public policy
and should not imply such an exemption. She also added that the
insured's willful concealment of his medical condition was
deplorable and deserves condemnation.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of that decision, earlier this year the life
insurance industry filed with the Massachusetts Legislature an
antifraud bill that would allow for one standard to be used within
the two-year contestable period. Thereafter, fraud still would
remain a valid ground for not paying a policy.
</P>
<P>
   Largely because of the efforts of the AIDS Law Project of Gay
and Lesbian Advocates and Defenders and the Catholic Charitable
Bureau of the Boston Archdiocese, the bill never reached the House
floor for a vote.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
