<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOM-EQUIPMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN MOVE INTO THEIR OWN GEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Hinda Miller is cq)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Twenty years ago, Hinda Miller and Lisa Lindahl were avid
joggers but were growing tired of the lack of support _ literally.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the 1970s, there were six million women in the United
States running,'' said Miller. ``That's a lot of bouncing breasts.
We felt self-conscious, but loved our running.''
</P>
<P>
   So combining their need for better support with Yankee
ingenuity, the two Vermont women set out on a mission. First, they
went to a local bra store, took some samples into the dressing
room, and jumped up and down.
</P>
<P>
   ``But nothing really caught our fancy or worked,'' Miller said
of the thin straps and underwire. So the research was on hold, but
the idea was still on their minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Late one night, about six of us were having dinner and were
talking about it, and were kind of giddy,'' Miller said. ``One of
the guys pulled a jockstrap out of the hamper, stretched it over
his breast, and said `look, a jockbra.'''
</P>
<P>
   It made sense to Miller, a costume designer, who figured out how
to sew two jockstraps together and _ voila! _ the Jogbra was
created.
</P>
<P>
   And they weren't the only ones trying to figure out how to bring
women's equipment into the mainstream. Barbara Longstreth, who was
field hockey coach at Long Beach State in California, was importing
sticks from Pakistan and selling them from her station wagon.
</P>
<P>
   And Elaine Sortino, now the softball coach and assistant
athletic director at the University of Massachusetts-Amherst, had
to cut part of the shinpads off and stuff padding in a
first-baseman's glove to outfit herself as a catcher.
</P>
<P>
   What a difference two decades makes.
</P>
<P>
   Now the original Champion Jogbra is in the Smithsonian
Institute, and the name has become associated with any type of
sportsbra; Longstreth's enterprise has become a mail-order business
for women's field hockey, lacrosse, and softball gear; and
fastpitch softball players now have real catcher's mitts to use,
not to mention shinguards that fit.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that baseball cleats and ice hockey skates sized to a
woman's foot; uniforms made gender-specific and not unisex, and
baseball gloves that are autographed by Olympians Dot Richardson
and Lisa Fernandez, and it's obvious that sporting goods
manufacturers are waking up to the fact that girls and women are
making up the fastest growing segment of their consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Girls playing fastpitch softball and ice hockey today might not
know or care what difference equipment makes, but their coaches do.
</P>
<P>
   Robyn King, a sophomore on the softball team at Boston
University, admits she has ``always used the same glove,'' but does
notice a big difference in shoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``In high school, I always used to end up wearing men's cleats _
buying man's two sizes too small. But now I can buy women's
cleats,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Deb Solfaro, King's coach at BU, notices more than just the
shoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I caught, I had to use a fielder's glove,'' she said.
``And the catcher's equipment was way too big for women. It didn't
fit right. The uniforms have gotten better, too. We used to wear
men's uniforms, but like it or not, women have hips.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Whyte, of Saugus, who played on the US gold-medal ice
hockey team, said, ``I basically just used guys' stuff, the
majority still do.''
</P>
<P>
   That meant smaller-sized gloves and kneepads; either boys' or
``junior'' sizes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you end up wearing a boys' kneepad, the protection isn't as
good,'' she said. ``Not that women need to have as superior stuff
as men in the NHL, but I still think there needs to be a balance of
equipment that can be small but good quality, and has same level of
protection.''
</P>
<P>
   Skates were a problem, too, she said, before manufacturers
started making them for women
</P>
<P>
   ``We're small, but heavy-muscled women,'' she said. ``So a woman
who weighs 150-160 pounds, and wears a size-4 skate, has to wear a
boys' size. A lot of women at the college level double stitch them
to reinforce at the boot, so the leather holds up better.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, for all her complaints, Whyte said she'd never use lesser
equipment as an excuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we've been burdened by not having women's stuff.
But it would be nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Dyer, the former Northeastern hockey player, now works for
Louisville Hockey as product manager for female hockey equipment.
The company hired her as an adviser in 1993 and, ``I started
talking about women's gear as soon as I got there.''
</P>
<P>
   As seamstress for the US women's national hockey team for four
years, Dyer knew the drawbacks well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players would all put on equipment and come see me, I was
the alteration specialist,'' she said. ``I'd get out the sewing
kit, and go around pulling and tweaking.''
</P>
<P>
   She convinced Louisville that small adjustments would mean a
lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's little things, like the fasteners below and not at your
chest; gloves are narrower through the thickness of the fingers,
pants have more room in the hip, and the shoulder pads have a chest
protector.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dyer is well aware Louisville is looking at the bottom line
as it creates a new line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, it takes a lot of money,'' she said. ``There are 27,000
registered women hockey players, and 425,000 men. So even if we
capture 90 percent of the market ... '' she said. ``But we're
working through it, and have a great product and the growth
potential.''
</P>
<P>
   And Dyer said the company is careful not to put too much
spotlight on its women's line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call it the 800-series and say it's for females on the hang
tag,'' she said. ``But other than that, it looks the same.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, she said, some players like Adam Oates prefer the
equipment _ like the gloves that are made with a combination of
nylon and leather instead of all leather _ for their flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry Jarrell, the vice president of marketing at Easton agrees
that the company has to walk the line between gearing equipment to
women and appearing patronizing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our first foray into this five years ago didn't go well,'' he
said. ``We had bags, and batting gloves, that were purple and pink.
``And we found women don't want that. Our research shows they
appreciate equipment made for them, but don't want it to look
different.''
</P>
<P>
   Longstreth began her mail-order business _ with a retail store
near Philadelphia _ 12 years ago. She added a softball line eight
years ago, and sells brands ranging from Easton bats to Rawlings
gloves to Cooper chest protectors.
</P>
<P>
   Ronnie Maurek, who was the softball coach at Temple University
for 17 years, oversees the division that she admits had a hard time
taking off.
</P>
<P>
   ``That first summer, some of the major manufacturers were
reluctant to even entertain opening this as an account,'' Maurek
said. ``They said, `Are you sure you want to do that?' And some of
those are usually the first ones in line to tell how how good it
is.''
</P>
<P>
   But there's a long way to go, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't even come close to rounding the corner, but there's
an awful lot of potential and still a lot of work to be done,''
said Maurek. ``But more manufacturers are are starting to see the
potential.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; cc12p2 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; cf58,15,15 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A new way
</P>
<P>
   to play hockey
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufboxlabel &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HOCKEY PANTS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufgothic,8,9 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (FL) &UR; Men
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Boxier cut is wider in waist, narrower in hip; more padding on
hips; more layers of foam.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Women &LR; (FR) &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Longer in leg, shorter in crotch; fuller hip, narrower waist;
smaller padding on hips
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufboxlabel &LR;
</P>
