<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-DRUGS-VAUGHN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAUGHN SAYS LEGAL SUPPLEMENTS ARE FAIR GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Mo Vaughn said he does not use androstenedione, a
naturally produced steroid used by St. Louis slugger Mark McGwire,
but decried the criticism directed at the man challenging Roger
Maris's home run record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't bring the man down,'' Vaughn said Tuesday. ``Look at the
things he's doing, the real picture. That other stuff is
irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a guy on the verge of changing history, and some people
are a little bit upset. Everybody should be happy for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Androstenedione acts in the production of the male hormone
testosterone, which can trigger muscle growth. It is banned by the
NFL, NCAA, and International Olympic Committee, but is legal in
Major League Baseball. It is sold over the counter in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn said he uses other strength-enhancing supplements, and is
a spokesman for MET-Rx Engineered Nutrition, which in its line of
products markets androstenedione. The Red Sox first baseman said he
does not use creatine, the dietary supplement and muscle-builder.
Vaughn said he uses another muscle-building product called PRO-hGH,
a food supplement that also is sold over the counter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody sees that in today's game, it's a big man's game,''
Vaughn said. ``Strength is the key.
</P>
<P>
   ``But as long as we're not doing illegal things, and I'm not
doing anything illegal and I don't know guys who are, then it
shouldn't be a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn said he doesn't use creatine because it makes him feel
``tight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And if I used a steroid, I'd weigh about 280 pounds,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn said that before he began using any products, he
consulted a doctor. He said he never has investigated
androstenedione.
</P>
<P>
   Merle Baker 3d, the Red Sox' strength and conditioning
coordinator, said the team's policy is to encourage players to
consult the team's training staff if they have questions about
supplements. The team physician, Arthur Pappas, is part of the
consulting process, Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   Baker said that he has not researched androstenedione in depth.
``I haven't addressed it because to my knowledge, no one uses it on
the Red Sox, I haven't been asked about it, and I haven't seen it
in the clubhouse,'' he said. ``Does that mean we discourage its
use? No. But if we were asked about it, we would research it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never recommend anything that I wouldn't be
comfortable using myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker agreed that it would be naive to believe that there aren't
some major leaguers using illegal steroids. ``There are kids in
high school using steroids just so they can get jacked and look
good for girls,'' Baker said. ``What makes you think that grown men
wouldn't roll the dice so they could make more money?''
</P>
<P>
   Some players, like Red Sox outfielder Darren Bragg, say they use
creatine, though Bragg says he uses it only on occasion, and only
in the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Nomar Garciaparra uses an energy supplement drink,
Baker said, which is fortified with extra vitamins and proteins.
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder Darren Lewis, who works out religiously in the
off-season with Giants star Barry Bonds, said he does not use any
supplements.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not for me,'' he said. ``My game is slapping the ball
around, a speed game. For me, it's more important to stay light and
lean.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn was asked if he would recommend supplements like creatine
to teenage athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things today are so different than when I was a kid,'' he
said. ``It's a big business, even in colleges and high school. The
fact of the matter is, whatever makes money, they're going to
market the product, and they don't care who's doing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have to got to make right choices. Until you get
well-educated about the whole thing, I'm not recommending anything
to anybody. Wait till guys go to college.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
