<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAWSON GETTING HIS KICKS IN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ It takes no more than a glance at the top of
Phil Dawson's locker at Foxborough Stadium to understand the nature
of this free agent kicker's football life in the final days of
preseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dawson, P. 8'' is written on a piece of white paper, taped to
the top of the locker. Guys returning from last year have engraved
name plates and the other first-year players at least have their
names on computer printouts.
</P>
<P>
   Dawson gets hand-lettering.
</P>
<P>
   Not that he's complaining.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, his status in Foxborough _ where he has survived to
kick another week as Adam Vinatieri continues to recovery from a
groin injury _ beats where he was a week ago by a long shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I was on my way home from Oakland at this time last
week,'' Dawson said before practice Tuesday. ``It's kind of been a
whirlwind week for me. I'm ready to know what's going to happen,
just like anyone else. But anytime you're trying to get your start
you're going to bounce around and that type of thing. But I sure
will be happy when the dust settles.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Patriots shut down Vinatieri after their Monday night
game in Mexico City last week, they put in a call to Dawson and he
arrived at 1 a.m. Friday. Saturday night, he kicked a 37-yard field
goal late in the first half, then a 41-yard game-winner with 2 1/2
minutes left to beat the Redskins, 20-17.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't be more happy with the opportunity,'' Dawson said.
``I'm very happy to be here. But I'm not one of those guys who's
just happy to be here. I'm a competitor and I want to do the best I
can. And I think I can be the best. I just needed an opportunity
somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Vinatieri plans to start kicking again Monday, which would give
him time to be ready for the opener Sept. 7 in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   The injury, the kicker said, developed in the early days of camp
while he worked on Olindo Mare-style pop-up, onsides kickoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got sore after doing them four or five days and
unfortunately I didn't give it any rest,'' he said. ``I kept
kicking and kicking and aggravated it. It was never a major pull or
tear, just soreness. We're rehabbing the heck out of it right now
to try to get it feeling good and get the swelling down. It feels
pretty good right now. We're being cautious. A groin injury for a
kicker is like a shoulder injury for a quarterback. You use it
every time you kick.''
</P>
<P>
   If Vinatieri is ready to go Monday, Dawson hopes he showed
enough against the Redskins and gets a chance to show enough
against Philadelphia this Saturday to get a shot somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   That's all he was looking for when he sought and received his
release in Oakland. With three kickers in camp, he felt he wasn't
getting the chance he expected, or needed. He missed his only field
goal attempt, a 48-yarder, with the Raiders and then when he didn't
get on the field in another exhibition, asked for his release.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just said, it looks like a decision has been made,'' he
said. ``I said I understand that. I'm not arguing with the
decision. But I would like to be out of here. I don't want to waste
anyone's time.''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the week he was a Patriot _ at least for a week or
two.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it all goes back to the confidence I have in being
able to perform at this level,'' Dawson said. ``I think a lot of
guys would have been scared to do what I did. Like, it's their one
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   His is a confidence born of a career at the University of Texas,
a career which opened with a 50-yard field goal to beat Pittsburgh
and ended with Dawson as a team captain with impressive numbers. He
was 13 for 16 with a long field goal of 54 yards last year and was
63 of 83 for his career, including 10 of 16 from 50 yards or
longer.
</P>
<P>
   He kicked and played on the offensive line at 5 feet 10 inches
and 190 pounds at Lake Highlands High School in Dallas, where he
was a teammate of Patriot running back Derrick Cullors.
</P>
<P>
   Cullors doesn't remember much about Dawson on the offensive
line.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he was our kicker, and he was great,'' Cullors said. ``I
was in college when he kicked like a 59-yarder to win a playoff
game.''
</P>
<P>
   So Cullors was not the least bit worried when Dawson lined up
for the game-winner Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone was nervous and I was standing there and I told Ben
Coates, `I have confidence in him, I know he's going to make it,'''
Cullors said.
</P>
<P>
   He did. And now he gets another chance to show his stuff
Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
