u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS &LR;      08-26 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
NET GAIN IN BATTLE OF SEXES; DRUNK GIRLS ON CAMPUS 
</HEADLINE>
 MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In this sizzling summer of Monica-gate, what red-blooded
American hasn't surveyed the muck and mire of our national politics
and said, ``Enough, already''?
</P>
<P>
   And what better way to prove that the appetite for sinning and
spinning is sated than to peruse some of the latest political
periodicals _ looking for any story without a Washington dateline.
</P>
<P>
   Since its debut in 1995, John F. Kennedy Jr.'s George magazine
has tried to synthesize celebrity and politics, leaving both a
little worse for the wear. The flashy bylines in the September
issue belong to the Reagans' wayward daughter Patti Davis (writing
about Monica, so we'll take a pass), and recording artist Liz Phair
explaining what she'd do as president (Merv Griffin as secretary of
commerce?).
</P>
<P>
   But one fun read is Billy Jean King's recollection of her
25-year-old, gender-stereotype shattering win over tennis hustler
Bobby Riggs. That 1973 Houston Astrodome extravaganza was one of
those culturally resonant sports spectaculars of the 1970s, the
precursor being the epic Ali-Frazier 1971 heavyweight championship
between the so-called draft-dodging Muslim and the so-called
``Uncle Tom.''
</P>
<P>
   King, then under 30, trounced 55-year-old male chauvinist pig
Riggs and is candid about her strategy. She just made the old guy
run out of gas by hitting the ball softly. The most interesting
tidbit is that George Foreman, then heavyweight champ, gallantly
escorted King to safety in the pandemonium that followed the match.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling the event, King writes that ``for at least one night,
it got women and men to talk to one another about the equality of
the sexes.'' Maybe it was also the onset of Foreman's
transformation from destructive hulk to jovial giant.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The September/October issue of Tikkun, the ``Jewish Critique of
Politics, Culture and Society,'' has a series on ``Spirituality in
America.'' But with my morality meter running on empty right now, I
opted for an unusual profile of Asa Yoelson (a.k.a. Al Jolson) by
actor Stephen Mo Hanan.
</P>
<P>
   The author argues that the blackface performer was not only
``the first open Jew to be celebrated by the American masses,'' but
the ``unlikely ... bridge'' through which early black artists like
Fats Waller and Duke Ellington ``entered popular culture.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a pretty impressive legacy for a guy borrowing a minstrel
show model that dated back to the 1840s. But Hanan makes a case for
Jolson's primitive if pioneering crossover act by explaining that
the Lithuanian immigrant brought the street culture of Washington,
D.C., and the jazz riffs of turn-of-the-century New Orleans to a
mainstream audience.
</P>
<P>
   For good measure, Jolson was also noted for ``below-the-waist
gyrations not seen again from any white male till the advent of
Elvis'' and for singing several songs in ``female persona'' with
touches gleaned from gay friends. Makes it seem like Neil Diamond
wasn't the right guy to play him in the movies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The October issue of the liberal journal Mother Jones has a
snazzy redesign and a clever eight-page assault on media mogul
Rupert Murdoch that looks like one of Rupe's tabloids.
</P>
<P>
   But that's too ideological. So the story that caught our eye was
a scary ``Ladies' Night'' feature on the increase in problem
drinking among college women. Seems they largely imbibe to ease
sexual inhibitions: One survey claimed that nearly two-thirds of
the women who had used alcohol in the past month did so to loosen
their libido.
</P>
<P>
   What's particularly worrisome is the evidence that alcohol is
more destructive to women than to men _ and it's not just about
body mass. Oral contraceptives, dieting, and PMS can all have an
impact on alcohol absorption. So does the fact that women have
fewer of the enzymes needed to break down alcohol in the system.
</P>
<P>
   Although this is probably more theory than science, the story
also points to evidence that women who work in more traditional
fields such as nursing or education have fewer problems with
alcohol than those joining the boys in banking and high finance.
One more piece of ammo for the anti-feminism backlash.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The debut issue of Brill's Content media magazine generated huge
headlines with a story alleging that Independent Counsel Kenneth
Starr improperly leaked grand jury information. The new September
issue has plenty of follow-up, including a long rebuttal letter
from the prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   But politics is verboten, so instead we'll turn to a summer
piece about how baseball announcers _ who are either hired by the
team or must be approved by the team _ should never be mistaken for
journalists. We read about broadcasters who moan about close
pitches that go against the home team but wouldn't let fans know
about an impending trade because the club wants to keep mum on such
matters.
</P>
<P>
   One announcer who refused to tank for the home team was Jon
Miller, now of the Sunday night ESPN broadcast. Miller departed the
Baltimore Orioles after the 1996 season because owner Peter Angelos
(who makes George Steinbrenner seem like a statesman) wanted his
men behind the mike to be ``advocates for the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing too earthshaking here. But at least baseball _ with Mark
McGwire and Sammy Sosa chasing Roger Maris and the potential for a
Yankees-Sox playoff showdown 20 years after Bucky ``Bleepin'' Dent
_ is having a good summer. That's more than you can say for anyone
in Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-26-98 1325EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
