<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXASWEATHER-CROPS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARLEY'S RAINS DEVASTATE, RESTORE TEXAS AGRICULTURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WORTH WREN JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The deadly storm system that hit the state
this week has been both cruel and kind to South and Southwest Texas
agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   The spinoffs from Tropical Storm Charley are running from a
virtual wipeout on up to 8,000 acres of irrigated cotton in the
Winter Garden area to a boost for the red grapefruit crop, revived
ranch pastures in some areas and desperately needed irrigation
water in the still-parched Lower Rio Grande Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``The South Texas drought is not over,'' cautioned Joe Paschal,
the Texas Agricultural Extension Service's livestock specialist for
the Coastal Bend and far South Texas.
</P>
<P>
   For people raising cattle, sheep and goats, Paschal said, the
impact ranged widely. Rain bypassed or barely wet wide sections of
ranch country while reviving pasture and range land grasses across
other large areas. Even in many areas that were deluged, though,
the rain fell too fast and ran off without soaking the ground, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Tropical Storm Charley nearly bypassed the Lower Rio Grande
Valley, which received some extremely spotty 0.3-inch to 1-inch
showers, farmers and produce shippers said.
</P>
<P>
   But the storm's heavy runoff into the Rio Grande's Falcon and
Amistad reservoirs is expected to be a godsend for the Lower
Valley's short- and long-term crop irrigation needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those folks are going through a living hell up there'' in the
Laredo-Eagle Pass flood areas, but ``it looks like a silver lining
for us,'' said Bill Weeks, president of the Mission-based Texas
Produce Association, a Lower Valley shippers and shipper-growers
trade organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we have the potential of a larger citrus crop than last
year's, and we're looking at possibly the largest crop since the
1989 freeze,'' Weeks said.
</P>
<P>
   Grapefruit and orange production could reach 380 million pounds,
up from 348 million pounds last year, he said. The 1989 freeze not
only destroyed most of that year's crop but wiped out thousands of
trees.
</P>
<P>
   Irrigation water from the Rio Grande has been shut off this
summer to seven of 27 Lower Valley water-control districts, and
five more districts are on the verge of depleting their current
water allocations for farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all of the region's irrigation water, as well as cities'
water supplies, is drawn from the river. The four- to five-year
drought in the Falcon and Amistad watershed areas has depleted the
lakes' reserves to their lowest levels on record, since a hurricane
filled them in the early 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   Now with heavy Charley runoff, delivery of irrigation water
could resume as early as next month, and the runoff could satisfy
more long-term needs, Weeks said.
</P>
<P>
   Produce growers and shippers are seeking an emergency allocation
to speed up the process. One priorty is citrus trees; about 25
percent to 30 percent of the citrus acreage has been without
irrigation water for up to two months.
</P>
<P>
   But the extra water may be too late for a significant portion of
the sugar cane crop, where 25 percent to 30 percent of the acreage
has also been without irrigation water.
</P>
<P>
   Billie Mack Simpson, who farms in the Rio Hondo area, said
little or none of his 630 acres of sugar cane can be saved even if
the water arrives this month.
</P>
<P>
   The storm's biggest agricultural losses are expected to be up to
8,000 acres of irrigated cotton farther north in the Winter Garden
area.
</P>
<P>
   ``We probably lost our cotton crop,'' said Charles Stichler, the
extension service's Uvalde-based regional agronomist and a Winter
Garden crops specialist.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers from south of Uvalde to the San Antonio area had just
barely started their harvest when 5- to 22-inch deluges washed
cotton fiber away, pulled it out of the bolls to the ground or
lowered its quality with stains from splattering mud, he said.
</P>
<P>
   What's left on the plants is being further damaged by molds and
seed germination in the bolls, he said.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
