NYT-08-26-98 1326EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980826.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3108 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIA-WOMEN-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE     08-26 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-WOMEN-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... its readers.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Steffens, who took over at the Press &AMP; Sun-Bulletin (65,000
circulation) in June 1997, hooked up with a Binghamton television
station and university (which, she points out, has a woman
president) to conduct a ``Facing Our Future'' civic journalism
project to examine the area's economic prospects. ``We decided to
let citizens define what they meant by economic revitalization,''
she says. ``It was very cathartic for the community.'' Since
becoming editor, Steffens has also made a series of unorthodox
hires, tapping a former assistant district attorney to cover the
courts and a teacher as a copy editor. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A quiet statement
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Idaho Statesman, where Baker has served as editor since last
September, has opened up newsroom meetings to readers, convened
weekly reader panels out in the Boise community, and initiated a
column called ``Life After Deadline'' in which staff members write
about personal experiences. On July 19, when the paper chose an
unorthodox way to cover the Aryan Nations march in Idaho _ by
surveying what ordinary people around the the state were doing that
day _ Baker took another unusual step. Over the objections of other
editors, she wrote a Page 1 note to readers explaining that
decision.
</P>
<P>
   And Katz's Orange County Register may be the most radically
risk-taking paper in the country. To solicit public feedback, the
Register brings in reader groups to critique the paper, hosts
hundreds of community meetings, polls citizens, and even puts up
suggestion boxes in Starbucks coffee shops. Internally, the
Register has reorganized the newsroom according to cross-functional
teams, calls its top editors ``the board of directors'' and
encourages bottom-up decision making, and is immersing staffers in
an eight-session curriculum designed to better connect the newsroom
to the community.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a zealot when it comes to serving the community,'' says
Katz. And the Register's outreach ``gives the public a stake in the
newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea that female editors might be more eager to generate
dialogue between the paper and its readers goes to the heart of the
gender theory. Writing earlier this year in The New Yorker, Ken
Auletta interviewed several dozen female executives in the
entertainment and information industries and ``heard them say that
women are better managers _ more nurturing, more collegial, more
communicative and more instinctual.''
</P>
<P>
   That communication stream seems to run both ways, both inside
the newsroom and out toward the community. Idaho Statesman editor
Baker explains that her weekly column is designed to ``let readers
understand how we make decisions. ... Our business is a mystery to
most readers. One of the things I've tried to do is demystify the
process.''
</P>
<P>
   The other instinct that seems to guide many women editors is the
opportunity to effect change. Here the model may be Jennie Buckner,
editor of The Charlotte (N.C.) Observer (circulation 246,000). The
Observer was a 1995 Pulitzer finalist for a ``Taking Back Our
Neighborhoods'' civic journalism project designed to focus public
and private resources on reclaiming the city's most crime-ridden
enclaves. (In her office, Buckner displays a quote from the late
Knight-Ridder CEO Jim Batten that says: ``Newspapers, well edited,
well-published, are wonderfully situated to be instruments of
helping America find its way, solve its problems, seize its
opportunities.'')
</P>
<P>
   Piggybacking on that effort, The (Myrtle Beach) Sun News
initiated a similiar project that revitalized a beleaguered
neighborhood near that newspaper. When the paper used its pages to
solicit help for the residents, Deans says, it generated about 200
calls the first day alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is why many of us got in the business,'' explains Deans.
``To make a difference.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A quiet statement
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even if you accept the theory that female and male editors
operate differently, there is the question of whether there will be
sufficient numbers of women at the top to change the newspaper
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are more women in the pipeline,'' says Sandra Mims Rowe,
editor of The (Portland) Oregonian and past president of the
American Society of Newspaper Editors. ``But I've been saying there
are a lot of women in the pipeline for five years.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, some observers say the kind of newspaper leadership
female editors are demonstrating is becoming the irresistible
reality _ for both sexes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are certain qualities today that are admired in
editors that did not use to be admired,'' says Rowe. ``But they are
not gender specific. The model of the `take no crap' city editor
and managing editor ... is not accepted,'' anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Former Christian Science Monitor editor Katherine Fanning says
``there's something to the fact that women tend to have a different
style of management'' from ``the old hierarchical style'' that was
once in favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most men that I know that are still in the business,'' she
adds, ``have had to learn.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
