<HEADLINE>
CLINTON REACTION RAISES QUESTIONS ABOUT NATION'S VALUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What does it say about the country's moral health when most
Americans, if the slew of opinion polls are a fair gauge, seem to
be unperturbed that President Clinton admitted to lying when he had
denied having a sexual relationship with former White House intern
Monica Lewinsky?
</P>
<P>
   Is American society sliding down a slippery slope to a place
where there is no longer a core of commonly held values? Should a
president be expected to adhere to a code of conduct that makes him
an example of virtue to the country?
</P>
<P>
   Theologians, clergy, and others concerned about ethics are
wrestling with these and other troubling questions as the scandal
about Clinton's transgressions, and his private life, dominates the
national agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is important for women and men who are leaders to
be people of integrity,'' said R. Judson Carlberg, president of
Gordon College in Wenham, Mass. and a nationally known speaker on
character and leadership development.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are people who are role models, who have a
responsibility to pass along to future generations a solid
framework upon which to build our culture, and if we don't have
some agreed-upon base for our moral development then we begin to
erode our societal underpinnings,'' Carlberg said.
</P>
<P>
   As the Rev. Canon Martin Eppard, a member of a national
conservative clergy group, told reporters in Washington this week,
``The unfortunate fact of the matter is that we have become a
society that has lost its ability to blush.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton can staunchly maintain that the testimony he gave in
January before a federal grand jury regarding his relationship with
Lewinsky was ``legally correct.'' But as a Christian he is clearly
a sinner, theologians and clergy assert.
</P>
<P>
   Fundamentally, Clinton broke two of the commandments enshrined
in the Old Testament: He admitted to lying, and he committed
adultery.
</P>
<P>
   In some Christian congregations, particularly conservative
churches, Clinton, a Southern Baptist, would face disciplinary
action for his behavior that might include being put on probation.
In an interesting twist, the Rev. J. Philip Wogeman, pastor at
Foundry United Methodist Church in Washington, where the Clintons
often worship, is a specialist in Christian ethics.
</P>
<P>
   Some clergy and theologians say they are troubled by what they
view as Clinton's failure to express true contrition during his
televised speech Aug. 27.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the problem is that the country is paralyzed because
to be able to move on, I think there is a strong need for
forgiveness,'' said Thomas Groome, a professor of theology at
Boston College and the author of a recently published book,
``Education for Life: A Spiritual Vision for Every Teacher and
Parent.''
</P>
<P>
   From a theological perspective, Groome added, forgiveness
requires ``saying you did wrong, secondly saying you're sorry, and
lastly saying, `Please forgive me.' But Clinton never did any of
those three.''
</P>
<P>
   Lost amid the seeming obsession with the scandal's salacious
details, some say, are serious issues about the unscrupulous abuse
of presidential power.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's someone using his authority to take advantage of someone
else,'' said Rabbi Moshe Waldoks of Temple Beth Zion in Brookline,
Mass. ``It's not that Clinton's behavior is uncommon. What's
reprehensible is to think it should be considered acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Others said that in judging Clinton, Americans should remember
the idea of a merciful God. ``Our God is one who judges with
unclouded vision and always responds with understanding love _ a
model for our human lives,'' said the Rev. Joan Brown Campbell,
general secretary of the National Council of Churches.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many in the world of religion regard Clinton to be a
successful political leader but a failed moral leader _ a major
liability in a country they say is in desperate need of higher
standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Clinton has broken the covenant of honor that the American
people entrust to their president every four years,'' the Pilot,
the official newspaper of the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Boston,
charged in an editorial in Thursday's edition. ``Without that
fundamental trust, we all flounder.''
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton prepares to resume his vaction on Martha's Vineyard
``among the `glitterati,''' the editorial said, ``one can only hope
that he becomes more acquainted with his better angels who will
speak to him of our common human need for reconciliation.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Religion Notes
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _In what critics charge is another example of the Vatican's
authoritarian style a liberal priest in Rochester, N.Y., hailed for
reviving a parish in decline has been removed for alleged practices
that violated church teaching.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. James Callan has conducted same-sex commitment
ceremonies, supported priest-like roles for women in worship, and
dispensed Holy Communion to non-Catholics _ all actions prohibited
by the Roman Catholic Church.
</P>
<P>
   Callan's supporters believe that the priest's removal from
Corpus Christi was ordered by the Vatican even though it was
officially carried out by Rochester Bishop Matthew Clark, who is
himself considered a liberal American prelate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Vatican's pressure demonstrates how not to run a church,''
Sister Maureen Fiedler, national coordinator of Catholics Speak
Out, a liberal Maryland-based church reform group, told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Callan's downtown church has drawn a far-flung and diverse
membership and is well-known for its social and economic
ministries, including providing free legal, medical, and dental
services and operating a food pantry, homeless shelter, and
hospice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deep down, I knew this day would come, that I would be
removed,'' Callan told the Associated Press last week. ``I was
hoping since it went on so long, that everybody would look the
other way and just let reform happen in the church. But I guess
it's not going to happen that easily.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _The Assemblies of God, one of the world's fastest-growing
denominations, will place its heritage on display when it opens a
museum next January at its headquarters in Springfield, Mo. The
Flower Pentecostal Heritage Center, named for J. Roswell Flower, an
early Assemblies of God leader, also will explore the broader world
of Pentecostalism.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Comments may be sent to The Spiritual Life, c/o Diego
Ribadeneira, Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378; or via e-mail to
religion(at)globe.com.
</P>
