<HEADLINE>
THE '68 DEMOCRATIC CONVENTION: WHERE FOLLY AND EGO COLLIDED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO -- The Blackstone Hotel, which still stands at
Balbo Drive and Michigan Avenue, housed the original ``smoke-filled
room'' on its fourth floor, where Republican bosses, amid the aroma
of fine panatelas, planned the nomination of Warren G. Harding in
1920. In 1968, when I stayed at the Blackstone, stink bombs and
tear gas created a rancid aroma of protest and repression in the
streets of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Assassinations led to grief and turmoil 30 years ago, but the
Democratic National Convention of 1968 had a more profound impact.
That week-long tragedy combined unintended consequences and
avoidable outcomes.
</P>
<P>
   Folly and ego collided, lengthening the Vietnam War, ushering in
the Nixon era, imperiling democracy, and engulfing the Democratic
Party in a boisterous bonfire of the vanities, yet to be quenched.
</P>
<P>
   In his book on 1968, ``The Year the Dream Died,'' Jules Witcover
reports that Robert F. Kennedy once called Eugene J. McCarthy ``a
vain man.'' Since all politicans are vain about something, even
integrity, the charge was probably true. But history will be kinder
to Kennedy and McCarthy than to other figures from that turbulent
week.
</P>
<P>
   The vanity prize goes to Lyndon B. Johnson, who celebrated his
60th birthday by threatening to rescind his five-month-old pledge
not to accept renomination. At issue was a platform plank about the
war in Vietnam. LBJ still thought the war was a swell idea and if
Vice President Hubert H. Humphrey wavered, Texas would nominate
Johnson. Humphrey never called the bluff, vain about his loyalty,
even loyalty to a dishonest bully, which LBJ was that week.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago was the last convention that did not ratify the decision
of voters in primaries. As such, it was a crisis for democracy. Of
the primaries in 1968, McCarthy won six, Kennedy five, and Humphrey
none. In the primaries, McCarthy won 2.9 million votes and Kennedy
2.3 million. Both opposed the war in Vietnam. Only 666,463 voted
for Humphrey, the nominee, who supported the war.
</P>
<P>
   When bosses steal a convention, protestors fill the streets. One
myth persists in Chicago that antiwar activists were violent and
somehow menaced the police and National Guard. The opposite was
true. The cops outnumbered kids by four-to-one and while some
protestors were vile, insulting and provocative, a well-trained
police force would have kept order.
</P>
<P>
   Authority collapsed in Chicago because Mayor Richard J. Daley
condoned what an Illinois state commission later called ``a police
riot.'' ``What would you do when they called you all kinds of
names?'' the mayor asked later. The answer is: I would have done
what my commanding officer told me to do. He would have done what
his boss, the mayor, told him to, which in Chicago meant police
anarchy.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, Aug. 28, 1968, after hours of arguing, the
delegates approved a platform, then nominated Humphrey. After
covering the convention near the stockyards, I returned to the
Blackstone at midnight and witnessed what Senator Abe Ribicoff
called ``Gestapo tactics in the streets.''
</P>
<P>
   The cops also clubbed reporters, because as Daley said later,
``Many of them were hippies themselves.'' I resented that because I
liked cops and even looked like one.
</P>
<P>
   Before a taxi deposited me near the hotel, I removed all press
credentials and walked slowly along Michigan Avenue, unmolested. I
could have been from homicide or the FBI, but I never deceived
anyone. I greeted by the name on his uniform the cop guarding the
Blackstone's door. He was impressed and held it open. I then went
to my room to file by telephone notes on the carnage I had
witnessed.
</P>
<P>
   That week, Soviet tanks moved on Prague to crush the
Czechoslovakian revolution, making the furor in Chicago seem
self-indulgent. Yes, some protestors were childish, but ego-smitten
adults like Johnson, Humphrey, and Daley bear the burden of the
history still smoldering from Chicago in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
