<HEADLINE>
TOO MUCH FISHING, TOO FEW FISH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   People might get the picture if they were to go to Legal Sea
Foods, sit down with their mouths watering for the catch of the
day, open the menu, and find these specials:
</P>
<P>
   (itals)Fresh Lake Leech in Muck Sauce, $16.95
</P>
<P>
   Grilled Algae Bloom with Sandfly Fritters, $15.95
</P>
<P>
   Fried Jellyfish with Greenhead Peas, $14.95.
</P>
<P>
   Poached Garden Eel with Urchin Spine Fries, $18.95(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   Are you ready to order? Based on the news this summer, it seems
as if this is all that will be left in a few decades.
</P>
<P>
   Biologists in New England said we may soon face a lobster
collapse. Cod, fished to collapse on Georges Bank, are now near
collapse in the Gulf of Maine. Down in Chesapeake Bay, the blue
crab harvest was the worst in recorded history. This is on top of
deep ongoing concern about swordfish, bluefin tuna, shark, and the
fact that 70 percent of the world's fishing stocks have been
depleted.
</P>
<P>
   The howls from those observing our plunder are as fairly
absolute. On the Gulf of Maine, Steve Murawski, biologist for the
National Marine Fisheries Service, says, ``The fishing rate ought
to be cut to as close to zero as possible.'' Murawski believes that
lobsters are being caught at twice the rate of reproducing
themselves. ``There's no way in God's green earth that these
catches are sustainable,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Murawski's warnings are part of a global alarm. This month, the
World Wildlife Fund released a report titled, ``Too Much Fishing
Fleet, Too Few Fish.'' The technology of catching fish has become
so much child's play that the fishing industry is capable of
snaring 155 percent more fish than the oceans can reproduce.
</P>
<P>
   Gareth Porter, the researcher for the report recommends that the
world fishing fleet be reduced by two-thirds in the hope that fish
species can recover.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, it's a race for the fish,'' Porter said by
telephone from Washington. ``You could see a crash of the total
catch at some point. It gets more difficult to catch fish as they
get smaller and smaller and younger and lower quality. There's a
real possibility that things could get a lot worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Porter did not want to predict how many years it would take a
crash to drastically alter our menus. But pictures in the Globe's
Health/Science section last week should frighten people who
understand that food chains start with the smallest of creatures.
</P>
<P>
   The pictures, provided by the US Geological Survey, showed how
fishing boats that drag their nets along the sea bottom catch far
more than fish. The draggers rake the floor clean of sponges,
anenomes, worms, and juvenile fish. They leave behind an underwater
moonscape of lifeless gray rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a persistent loss of diversity and of complexity,'' said
Eleanor Dorsey of the Conservation Law Foundation and editor of the
foundation's new book, ``Effects of Fishing Gear on the Sea Floor
of New England.''
</P>
<P>
   The primary recommendations from conservationists are no less
diverse and complex: Fewer boats, fewer traps, no dragging.
International agreements on catches. Ending government subsidies
for fishing fleets. Vessel buyback programs.
</P>
<P>
   The primary response from the fishing industry is usually denial
about the damage it does, excuses that they have to keep up with
boats that violate the laws and swift retoolings to exploit the
next possible fish.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the closure of Georges Bank resulted _ only four
years later _ in the devastation of cod in the Gulf of Maine is
evidence how the fishing industry cannot police itself. Where the
National Marine Fisheries Service says the New England fleet of cod
boats should be cut in half, Barbara Stevenson, who owns three
groundfishing boats in Maine, recently told the Associated Press,
``A lot of things are getting a lot better; it's just that at the
moment Gulf of Maine cod is not getting any better.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be a United Nations conference on the world's
fisheries in October in Rome. The debate between environmentalists,
the fishing industry, and the world's governments, some of which
have begun to wake up to the need for limits and others which
subsidize the depletion of the oceans, is at an impass unlikely to
be broken by those forces alone.
</P>
<P>
   The stalemate has to be broken by us, the consumer. That will
require major departures in culture, particularly in New England,
so wedded as we are to lobster, cod, haddock and swordfish. Some
restaurants have made a symbolic stand in recent months by taking
swordfish off their menu. Others play up farm-raised fish.
</P>
<P>
   That is a start, but much more debate about what fish to eat and
when to eat it has to occur before the fishing industry takes any
of this seriously. Judging by the latest news, we are headed to a
future where the only fish left will be the kind one would consider
only if one were shipwrecked and starving on a desolate island.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
