<HEADLINE>
READING BETTER _ ELECTRONICALLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was just three years ago in this space that former New
Republic editor Michael Kinsley named the breakthrough that would
transform electronic publishing: ``When you get a great computer
screen that you can take to the john with you _ that will be the
triumph.''
</P>
<P>
   A few months later, Kinsley launched the on-line magazine Slate.
Slate has many virtues, but one huge shortcoming: you cannot take
it with you to the john. It is best read on an expensive, powerful
computer, preferably one belonging to your employer.
</P>
<P>
   Before the end of this year, two Silicon Valley start-ups plan
to launch ``electronic books,'' essentially jazzed-up computer
screens with plenty of memory and a few fancy fillips that seek to
replace paper-and-paste books. I've spent the past two weeks with
Softbook, which will be the first to market and the cheaper ($300)
of the two rivals. It is also the company that returned my call.
</P>
<P>
   Softbook weighs 2.9 pounds. Bound in floppy leather, it has the
heft of a high school yearbook. Do you know how to plug in a phone?
Then you know how to use Softbook.
</P>
<P>
   The screen is easy to read, and works mainly by touch. To fetch
a book from the Electronic Bookstore, you plug in the phone line
and tap a couple of icons. For experimenters like me, the bookstore
_ really a computer in Palo Alto, Calif. _ offers several titles,
including ``Angela's Ashes,'' the ``Iliad,'' and Michael Wolff's
gossipy Internet expose, ``Burn Rate.'' Wolff's book took about two
minutes to download into my Softbook.
</P>
<P>
   (By the end of the year, the company says, thousands of titles
should be available, each costing a few dollars. Once purchased,
books can be downloaded repeatedly.)
</P>
<P>
   Thus began what Softbook CEO Jim Sachs infelicitously calls a
``booklike experience.'' To prolong the Palo Alto patois: Softbook
has lots of functionality. Translation: It can do a lot of things.
You can bookmark or even ``dogear'' pages electronically. By
pressing gently on a plastic toolbar, you advance the page. Using a
small plastic stylus, you can write anywhere on any page, and find
your notes instantly. Where Wolff writes, ``All technology is ...
transitional,'' I note: ``Duh.''
</P>
<P>
   You can highlight passages, and return to them easily, or select
a name or phrase, and flash immediately to each page where it
occurs. In about 60 seconds, I searched all of ``Burn Rate'' for
derogatory information about MIT's new media guru Nick Negroponte.
I am pleased to report that there was none. Just a few weeks ago, I
could have used this feature while reading the Patricia Cornwell
whodunit ``Unnatural Exposure.'' When the psycho-perp was unveiled,
I had to rustle back hundreds of pages to find out who she was.
With Softbook, this takes seconds.
</P>
<P>
   But wait, there's more. Softbook shuts down automatically when
you fold the plush leather cover over the screen, and, when
reopened, displays the last page you read. The battery, which can
be recharged while reading, lasts for several hours. The screen can
be backlit for reading in the dark. If Softbook sells Stephen King,
this will be the summer camp accessory for 1999!
</P>
<P>
   Problem One: I had trouble reading the Softbook in direct
sunlight. However, I have trouble reading real books in sunlight
too. Problem Two: I'd like Softbook to go on a diet. Yes, I could
read it in bed, but surely technological advances could slim this
gizmo down to the size of, say, the December issue of Vanity Fair.
</P>
<P>
   Those quibbles aside, I went in a skeptic, and emerged a
believer. For the immediate future, Softbook's scale of operations
may be limited by whatever deals it strikes, or fails to strike,
with publishers. But imagine if the holdings of your favorite
bookstore, or of the Library of Congress, were just a few touches
away. I've seen the future, and it reads very smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   You can try it out yourself. Starting in November or December,
Softbook will be sold from the company's Web site,
http://softbook.com. Not available in stores!
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Alex Beam's e-mail address is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
