<HEADER>
A3124 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-INTERNET-BOS     08-26 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-INTERNET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLERGY CLICK WITH CYBERWORSHIPERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; It was a gut-wrenching story, the kind of tale the Rev.
Douglas Showalter usually hears in the privacy of his office
underneath the white steeple of the First Congregational Church in
Falmouth, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   But the woman's tale, of the beatings her son had suffered at
the hands of her sister _ who was now dying _ was posted on an
Internet message board that anyone with a computer and a modem
could read. And the woman was identified only as Teresa.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the medium, a far cry from the way most clergy conduct
pastoral counseling, Showalter gave Teresa the same kind of
encouragement and advice that he does in person. But his
interaction with her is a telling example of how the Internet and
the World Wide Web are revolutionizing the world of religion and
making cyberspace the new spiritual frontier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, you still want to talk to people one-on-one and
provide that human touch that can be really necessary in times of
crisis,'' said Showalter, who created the forgiveness message board
that included Teresa's story. ``But you can't ignore the reality of
the Internet as a place where people are turning to for religious
purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   From on-line pastoral counseling to Bible studies to prayer
requests, the Internet has become a powerful tool for
denominations, missionary societies, congregations, and other
religious organizations seeking to tap into America's rising
spiritual yearning.
</P>
<P>
   For some, the Web provides an anonymous, safe, and fast way to
find a spiritual home. At the same time, it has helped many
churches and ministriesreach people in their 20s who may be
uninterested in walking into their neighborhood church but are very
keen on _ and skilled at _ surfing the Web.
</P>
<P>
   The proliferation of religion on the Internet goes beyond
publishing weekly church services. What strikes many scholars is
that many denominations are using the Internet to communicate with
and attract spiritual seekers.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the dawn of this new technology, Christians have been
painfully absent and we're trying to change that,'' said Dave
Spalding, the president of Merrimack Valley Access Network in
Haverhill, Mass., who has created Web sites for churches and
Christian ministries in Greater Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Type the word ``God'' into Alta Vista, an Internet search
engine, and more than 10 million entries pop up. At one popular
Jewish Web site (www.shamash.org), visitors can discuss the Torah,
Jewish feminism, or what it's like to be a gay Jew.
</P>
<P>
   For a church, said software engineer Jeffrey Lomicka, ``the
Internet can provide a nonthreatening way to introduce yourself to
the public.'' Lomicka designed the Web site for Acton Christian
Community Church, where people can listen to the pastor's Sunday
sermons on line. ``It can be a lot more threatening to invite
someone to a church in person,'' he said, ``than to just have them
surf the Web and listen to the sermons and get a sense of what our
church stands for.''
</P>
<P>
   While most of the church's 80 or so members found the church the
old-fashioned way _ through the Yellow Pages _ Lomicka said a
couple of recent members came to the church after finding it on the
Internet. In fact, the pastor, the Rev. Eric Robinson, sent his
resume to the church over the Internet after his wife found the
Acton congregation on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of religious groups are finding that if you're really
serious about evangelizing and preaching the gospel and bringing
the word of God to people, then you probably have to have a
presence on the Internet,'' said Quentin Schultze, professor of
communications at Calvin College in Grand Rapids, Mich., and
executive editor of the Internet for Christians Newsletter, a
biweekly on-line publication (www.gospelcom.net/ifc) with about
100,000 subscribers worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Charles Henderson, a Presbyterian minister based in New
Rochelle, N.Y., has created a site called the First Church of
Cyberspace (http://christianity.miningco.com/) complete with
sermons, scripture readings, and choir.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though there are many congregations, denominations, and other
religious groups that advertise their presence on the Web, we are
the first to organize within cyberspace itself,'' the church's Web
site claims. ``Making connections, constructing links, dropping
clues that point to the presence of the Creator within the creative
chaos of the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Schultze said the Internet also has given religious dissidents a
louder voice and greater clout.
</P>
<P>
   In the Greek Orthodox Church, for example, people angry at
church leadership created a massive Web site last year
(www.voithia.org) filled with articles, e-mail, and reports that
have helped mobilize a widespread grass-roots campaign to reform
the church.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet has allowed many more folks in the pews to have a
say in what goes in their denomination,'' Schultze said. ``It can
create a much more democratic forum.''
</P>
<P>
   For some pastors, the Internet has eased the ever-challenging
task of preparing a Sunday sermon. A few taps on the computer
keyboard and they can access dozens of Web sites that include
various versions of the Bible.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can type in a word or phrases like `love,' `Jesus,' or
`adultery' and immediately get back responses from the 10 or so
versions of the Bible,'' said Steve Wike, president and publisher
of Media Management, a Roanoke, Va., form that runs a Christian Web
site (www.goshen.net). The site contains a directory of 15,000
Christian-related groups. Wike said the Bible section is the most
popular link on the site, attracting pastors, Sunday school
teachers, and Bible group leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most popular religious sites on the Internet are
chat rooms and message boards that allow people to discuss and
debate faith issues. Indeed, the Internethas helped tear down walls
by offering ecumenical chat rooms where Christians, Jews, and
Muslims can wrestle with thorny issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are opening up to each other's theological positions in
a way that may not be as easy if you put them all in the same room
_ that is, if you can get to be in the same room,'' Wike said.
</P>
<P>
   Some denominations, particularly evangelical Christians and
Muslims, are using the Web to gain converts. Ron Hutchcraft
Ministries, for example, a Christian group based in New Jersey,
claims to have attracted 500 new born-again Christians since
January.
</P>
<P>
   At Hutchcraft's site (www.gospelcom.net/rhm), you can accept
Jesus as your personal savior simply by clicking a sequence of
screens explaining biblical passages. ``Your Creator is the end of
the search for answers,'' the site promises.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
