<HEADER>
A3134 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HERB-MARJORAM-TEX     08-26 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERB-MARJORAM-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERSATILE PERENNIAL SPICES MEATS, STEWS, VEGETABLES AND CHEESE
SPREADS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROL NUCKOLS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABCs: Marjoram is a tender perennial native to North Africa and
Southwest Asia, cultivated in North America. Its velvety,
light-green leaves have a flavor similar to that of oregano. It
grows 1 to 2 feet tall.
</P>
<P>
   Growing conditions: Loose, well-drained soil; full sun; plenty
of water. Plant from transplants after last frost.
</P>
<P>
   Food pairings: Meat, poultry, fish, vegetables, stews, cheese
spreads.
</P>
<P>
   Caveats: Treat white flies, aphids and spider mites with
insecticidal soap.
</P>
<P>
   BAKED VEGETABLE MEDLEY
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6 to 8
</P>
<P>
   1 medium-size eggplant
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup plus 2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 medium-size red onions, peeled, halved and cut into thin rings
</P>
<P>
   2 large garlic cloves, peeled, crushed and minced
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds potatoes (about 5 medium-large), washed, peeled and cut
into 1/4-inch rounds
</P>
<P>
   2 large zucchini (about 1 pound each), washed, trimmed and cut
into 1/4-inch rounds
</P>
<P>
   2 large green bell peppers, washed, trimmed, seeded and cut into
1/4-inch rings
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped fresh marjoram
</P>
<P>
   1 1/3 cups peeled, chopped plum tomatoes (1 small can)
</P>
<P>
   Trim stem and bottom off eggplant. Cut in half lengthwise and
then into crescent-shaped slices about 1/4 inch thick. Place
eggplant in a colander and sprinkle each layer generously with
salt. Place a weight (such as a pot lid) over eggplant and let it
drain for 1 hour. Rinse and drain well, squeezing gently to remove
excess liquid, and pat dry.
</P>
<P>
   Heat 2 tablespoons of the olive oil in a large skillet over
medium heat and saute onions and garlic until wilted and clear,
about 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375 degrees. Lightly oil a large, deep
earthenware baking dish. Spread one third of onions and garlic on
bottom. Place half the potato slices, zucchini slices, eggplant
slices and pepper rings in one overlapping layer on top of onions.
Season with salt, pepper and marjoram. Spread another third of the
onions over first layer and top with half the tomatoes. Drizzle 1/4
cup of olive oil over tomatoes. Repeat with remaining ingredients.
Cover baking dish loosely with aluminum foil and bake for 1 hour
and 15 minutes, or until all vegetables are tender. Remove and cool
slightly before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 258 calories, 14 grams fat, 31
grams carbohydrates, 4 grams protein, 0 milligrams cholesterol, 13
milligrams sodium, 49 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Greek Vegetarian,'' by Diane Kochilas (St. Martin's
Press, $24.95)]
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   PORK TENDERLOIN MEDALLIONS WITH FRESH MARJORAM
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   3/4 to 1 pound pork tenderloin, butterflied and lightly pounded
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   3 or 4 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 medium-size sweet red bell pepper, roasted, peeled and cut
into strips 3 or 4 inches long by 3/8-inch wide
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon whole fennel seeds
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fresh marjoram
</P>
<P>
   6 tender sprigs fresh marjoram, each about 6 inches long
</P>
<P>
   2 generous tablespoons toasted pine nuts (Toast in a pie pan in
a 325-degree oven, stirring occasionally, until golden brown, about
5 minutes)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Paprika to taste
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons sweet red vermouth
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkle meat with salt and pepper and rub with minced garlic.
Arrange the roasted pepper strips vertically to cover the meat and
sprinkle with fennel seeds and chopped marjoram. Lay the fresh
marjoram sprigs vertically, then tightly roll up meat from end to
end; place seam-side down in a baking dish. Rub olive oil into
meat; sprinkle generously with sweet paprika and rub it into meat.
Sprinkle with more salt and pepper if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Place in a preheated 450-degree oven for approximately 6 to 8
minutes. Remove from oven and reduce temperature to 300 degrees.
Drizzle 2 tablespoons sweet vermouth over meat and return
immediately to oven. Cook approximately 30 minutes, basting with
remaining vermouth the last 5 minutes. Do not overcook; red peppers
may stain the meat somewhat pink, so do not mistake stain for
uncooked pork.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 190 calories, 9 grams fat, 2
grams carbohydrates, 21 grams protein, 56 milligrams cholesterol,
41 milligrams sodium, 45 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Herb Garden Cookbook,'' by Lucinda Hutson (Texas Monthly
Press, $21.95)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   PASTA WITH SAUSAGES AND MUSHROOMS
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 small onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, chopped
</P>
<P>
   10 ounces sweet Italian sausages, casings removed and sausage
crumbled
</P>
<P>
   10 ounces assorted mushrooms, wiped and thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   3 cups plum tomatoes, peeled and chopped, or canned with the
juice
</P>
<P>
   Handful of marjoram leaves, or 1 tablespoon fresh thyme leaves
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces fresh pasta
</P>
<P>
   Heat oil in a large frying pan over medium heat. Add onion and
garlic and fry for about 3 minutes, until transparent. Add sausages
and saute until slightly golden. Add mushrooms and continue cooking
for 3 more minutes, stirring a couple of times. Add tomatoes,
marjoram, and salt and pepper to taste. Lower heat and cook,
covered, about 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, bring a large saucepan of water to a boil. Add salt
and pasta and cook until water returns to a boil and pasta floats
to the top. Drain and add to sauce in pan. Stir for a couple of
minutes, then transfer to a warmed serving platter and serve
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 628 calories, 26 grams fat, 77
grams carbohydrates, 22 grams protein, 33 milligrams cholesterol,
411 milligrams sodium, 38 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Lorenza's Pasta,'' by Lorenza de'Medici (Clarkson Potter,
$40)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
