<HEADER>
A3145 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-MAGAZINES-HNS &LR;      08-26 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-MAGAZINES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAT, READ, BE MERRY: NEW FOOD MAGAZINES ARE WORTH SAMPLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM M. DOWD  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ If anyone wonders what is one of the
fastest-growing segments in the publishing industry, take a look at
your local newsstands. Forget the teen-scene, computer and travel
magazines. Zero in on those dealing with food and drink in their
myriad forms.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the many ``health'' magazines pushing one form of diet or
another, we find more and more titles dealing with herbs, tea, beer
and the various ethnic cuisines. Sorting through the offerings to
find those that are worthwhile becomes quite a chore.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a sampling:
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Culinary Trends, published quarterly by Culinary Publication
Inc., 6285 East Spring St., Long Beach, Calif. 90808. Cover price:
$5.95.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp color photography, lots of recipes, a lengthy list of
which chefs are moving to which jobs across the nation, a culinary
calendar and timely stories, such as one on seafood safety.
</P>
<P>
   There isn't much this California publication lacks, and its
editors obviously strive to make it more than just another pretty
West Coast face.
</P>
<P>
   Probably the most readable story in the current issue is ``The
South Florida Chef,'' a detailed look at a particularly innovative
regional cuisine and its practitioners. But the magazine also takes
us to Berlin, the Perigord region of France, a Caribbean cooking
competition in Puerto Rico, and behind the scenes at the new
International Institute of Culinary Arts in Fall River, Mass. This
title is a bargain, and definitely for the serious foodie.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Simply Seafood, published quarterly by Waterfront Press Co.,
5305 Shilshole Ave. NW, Seattle, Wash. 98107. Cover price: $2.95.
</P>
<P>
   If getting recipes from the top prize-winners in the magazine's
``Seafood Chef the Year Awards'' doesn't intrigue you enough to
plunk down a mere $2.95, how about an article entitled ``Rocky
Mountain Seafood''?
</P>
<P>
   Going from there, such gems as tips on stove-top smoking (plus
an article on wines that go with smoked foods) and a selection
guide to texture and flavor of fish as well as how much to have
per-person show the care lavished on this underpriced package. This
Seattle outfit knows its stuff. It also publishes Alaska
Fisherman's Journal and Seafood Leader. For both the serious
seafood cook and the rank beginner, Simply Seafood has something to
offer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Food Illustrated, published monthly by John Brown Publishing
Ltd., London. U.S. address: 330 Pacfic Ave., Virginia Beach, Va.
23451-3630 $5.95.
</P>
<P>
   This English import gives the lie to the stereotype about
British food being on a par with the U.K. dental plan. It calls
itself ``The world's most beautiful food magazine.'' I can't agree
(Saveur tops it, for example), but it certainly is chock full of
lavish photographs from thumbnail size to two-page spreads.
</P>
<P>
   But pictures can take you just so far. What about content?
Despite a side trip to Bermuda, Food Illustrated is, for the most
part, by, for and about U.K. people, cooking and products.
</P>
<P>
   That aside, there is plenty to read and contemplate here _ no
one-topic emphasis, but instead lots of smartly-chosen topics. In
this issue: what to eat this month, mini book reviews, a look at
``Mexican New Wave'' cooking, the joys of fresh buffalo mozzarella
and the start of a series on great chefs (this installment looks at
signature recipes of the greats and the ethics of ``borrowing''
recipes).
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Valley Table, published quarterly by The Valley Table Inc.,
P.O. Box 2173, Middletown, N.Y. 10940. Cover price: $3.50.
</P>
<P>
   This is a regional food magazine for the Hudson Valley _ or,
part of it.
</P>
<P>
   The new quarterly, based in Middletown, has released its
inaugural issue as a complimentary project. A good idea for a first
issue, but if editor Jerry Novesky can maintain the quality of the
first issue, its $3.50 cover price won't be out of line.
</P>
<P>
   The 34-page publication has a color cover and black-and-white
inside pages. It contains a variety of stories on food and wine,
with such bylines as culinary historian Peter Rose and wine expert
Stephen Kolpan of the Culinary Institute of America.
</P>
<P>
   Publisher Janet Crawshaw says the new publication is meant to
help publicize the Hudson Valley as a culinary destination.
However, it tends to ignore the northern part of the Hudson Valley.
</P>
<P>
   By ignoring it, the new publication looks a bit too parochial
and bypasses a fair amount of the food scene.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-26-98 1351EDT &QL; 
