<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-INJURIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINE-TUNING MEDICINE: HEALERS TAKE NOTE OF WHAT AILS MUSICIANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL BOURGEOIS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Pull a hamstring or groin muscle and sports
medicine specialists know what to do. But what about the
debilitating pain associated with clarinet wrist, trombone elbow or
fiddler's neck?
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Center for Music and Medicine isn't a household name,
but soon this new collaborative effort between the University of
North Texas Health Science Center in Fort Worth and University of
North Texas in Denton could be a major national center for research
and treatment in the budding field of performing arts medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bernard Rubin, who is director of the rheumatology
department at the health science center, and Kris Chesky, a
professor of music at UNT, said advances in research, treatment and
prevention of performing arts pain may soon filter to middle and
high schools to stem the pain, psychological problems and the
ensuing drug and alcohol abuse common among musicians.
</P>
<P>
   Violinists complain of elbow problems, guitarists can develop
shoulder and wrist pain, and many pianists report something akin to
carpal tunnel syndrome, as well as pain in their necks and lower
backs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can use the model of sports medicine,'' Rubin said. ``We
now have people who specialize and they understand the problems
that athletes get and we are better at taking care of these
people.''
</P>
<P>
   He said professional musicians are generally underserved by
medical professionals because there hasn't been enough research
into medical problems particular to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many musicians play six or more hours a day,'' Rubin said.
``You get pain in the neck, arms, shoulders, fingers. Who do you go
to for help? Many physicians don't know about the specifics of
playing an instrument.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin and Chesky said their program emphasizes research and
prevention. There are clinics that deal with pain after it
develops, but none that takes such a fully developed and holistic
approach, they said.
</P>
<P>
   That includes developing different techniques for playing
instruments, and perhaps alterations in the instruments themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The research goes beyond ]isolated pain into the use of drugs
and alcohol that develops among some performers, perhaps to
mitigate the pain or the depression from not being able to pursue
one's livelihood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know first hand that musicians have a difficult time with
many issues,'' said Chesky, who has played trumpet for more than 20
years. ``The physical demands of playing night after night, also
the social difficulties, working in environment with alcohol and
drug abuse, working late at night.''
</P>
<P>
   Chesky said research has primarily focused on the problems of
classical musicians. He said that with the 1,400 music students at
UNT, ``we have the full range of musician types here to study.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said: ``What we would like to be is a clearinghouse for
musicians, voice problems in singers, leg problems in dancers,
alcoholism, stage fright, the psychological problems of artists and
hearing problems. And we have a unique situation here. We have a
medical school and a huge music school at UNT, the second-largest
music school in the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only is Fort Worth a major medical center, Rubin said, but
it is also home to a vibrant arts community, a symphony orchestra,
an opera and ballet company, the new Bass Performance Hall, and
music schools at Texas Christian University, the University of
Texas at Arlington and Texas Wesleyan University.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nowhere else,'' Chesky said, ``is there a medical school/music
school marriage where the clinical is closely tied to the research,
which is closely tied to the education of musicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to educate people about medical problems of musicians
and we want to educate the music teachers.''
</P>
<P>
   A questionnaire developed by Chesky and available on the
Internet _ www.scs.unt.edu/surveys/msurvey/index.html _ has
attracted wide interest, with responses from more than 4,000
musicians.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said the financial support of both universities has been
supplemented by grants from the National Academy of Recording Art
and Sciences. The National Endowment for the Arts has also
expressed interest in the project.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin and Chesky said they are eager for input from other health
professionals along with calls from foundations interested in
helping fund their research.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
