<HEADLINE>
JURY LEADER IN PEPPER SPRAY CASE SAYS POLICE ACTION WAS EXCESSIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SETH ROSENFELD  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The forewoman of a deadlocked jury considering a
lawsuit against sheriff's deputies who smeared pepper spray around
the eyes of protesters said the police action was disturbing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can't sit down in a nonviolent way and protest on
behalf of your beliefs without being subjected to the police
swabbing your eyes with pepper spray or some other chemical agents
... I think that's sort of going back to the days of the cattle
prod and the fire hose,'' the forewoman, Pat Schimke, said.
</P>
<P>
   The jury of six men and two women reached a 4-4 impasse Tuesday
in deciding whether Humboldt County deputies were guilty of using
excessive force against environmental protesters. U.S. District
Judge Vaughn Walker declared a mistrial and set Nov. 16 for
retrial.
</P>
<P>
   No other police department has been known to condone the wiping
of pepper spray liquid on non-violent people. A videotape of the
swabbings _ showing the demonstrators writhing and screaming in
agony _ was televised last year.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Harris, a lawyer for the nine young environmental activists
who brought the civil rights lawsuit, called it a test of whether
police officers around the country may similarly use the spray. The
case, he said, ``will set limits on what we as a society will
accept from our law enforcement agencies in terms of their use of
force against political protesters.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Delaney, a lawyer for the sheriff's department in the
Northern California county, said the jury's failure to unanimously
find by a preponderance of the evidence that the deputies used
excessive force ``certainly shows that it is not an abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the deputies acted properly and used the spray to avoid
other injuries while countering the passive but increasingly
resilient methods of protest.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit stemmed from three separate pepper spray episodes
during protests last fall against the logging of redwoods in and
around the Headwaters Forest on California's North Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Most were first-time protesters who were using metal devices _
called lock boxes _ to attach themselves to one another and their
demonstration sites. Several were teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   Pepper spray is incapacitating, causing those who come into
contact with it severe pain and symptoms that range from coughing,
twitching eyes, temporary loss of upper body control,
disorientation and anxiety, said Macon Cowles, the plaintiffs' lead
lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Schimke said the four jurors who saw the dabbing as excessive
believed the deputies could have used less painful methods to
remove the protesters, including waiting them out, talking to them
or cutting through metal sleeves they were using to make their
removal difficult.
</P>
<P>
   But others believed the deputies did just fine. ``Some made the
argument that police need to use anything in their toolbox that was
necessary,'' said the forewoman, who was among those who found the
force was excessive and the only juror to comment on the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just had a philosophical difference,'' said Schimke, a
retired medical technician from the Children's Hospital in Oakland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
