<SLUG> BC-CAESARSALADS-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: within two days. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Croutons
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8
</P>
<P>
   4 cups sourdough bread, cut into 1-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried oregano
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried thyme
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Place bread cubes in bowl. In a measuring cup, combine oil with
spices and mix. Sprinkle oil mixture over bread and toss to
distribute oil evenly. Spread onto a sheet pan and bake for 30
minutes, or until croutons are light brown and very crisp. Toss and
mix bread from time to time to achieve even browning.
</P>
<P>
   _ Chef Grady Spears
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ANGELUNA'S CAESAR SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Serves 18
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons pasteurized egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons toasted garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons roasted garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons raw garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon Coleman's dry mustard
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon sambal (see Note)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fish sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 cup canola
</P>
<P>
   1 cup extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon tamarind puree
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup grated Romano cheese
</P>
<P>
   36 cups torn romaine lettuce leaves
</P>
<P>
   Note: Sambal is an Indonesian condiment made primarily with
chiles and brown sugar, often available at Asian markets.
</P>
<P>
   Place all ingredients in food processor except oils and cheese.
Slowly add oil with machine running. It will be very thick, like
mayonnaise. When well blended, stir in cheese. Toss with lettuce; 1
ounce will coat 2 cups of romaine. Add more cheese, as well as
capers and anchovies, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 260 calories, 26 grams fat, 3
grams protein, 4 grams carbohydrate, 37 milligrams cholesterol, 131
milligrams sodium, 91 percent calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ Chef Clark McDaniel
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   PALOMINO CAESAR SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   1 cup egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon plus 2 teaspoons Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon Tabasco sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 teaspoons Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces whole anchovies, finely minced or pureed
</P>
<P>
   2 cups extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   10 ounces romaine lettuce, washed and cut into 1/2-inch strips
</P>
<P>
   Note: Recipe yields 3 cups dressing; each serving, however, is 4
ounces.
</P>
<P>
   In a mixer with whip attachment, whip egg yolks until frothy.
Add garlic, pepper, vinegar, lemon juice, mustard, Tabasco and
Worcestershire sauce and mix 1 to 2 minutes until combined. With
mixer running, slowly add olive oil to emulsify the dressing. Once
all the oil is added, continue to mix for 2 to 3 minutes to thicken
the mixture. Keep cold until ready to serve.
</P>
<P>
   In mixing bowl, combine dressing and greens, tossing to coat
greens evenly.
</P>
<P>
   _ Chef Chris Huff
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   A SHORT HISTORY OF CAESAR SALAD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The widely accepted Caesar salad creation story is the one that
says an Italian chef named Caesar Cardini made the salad with a few
things he had on hand in his Tijuana restaurant in 1924.
</P>
<P>
   According to the ``Food Lover's Companion'' (Barron's, $12.95),
the classic Caesar is torn romaine lettuce tossed in a dressing of
Worcestershire sauce, lemon juice, coddled egg, oil and anchovies,
along with grated Parmesan and croutons.
</P>
<P>
   But few restaurants today actually make a salad similar to the
classic _ and when's the last time you saw one made tableside?
Today's Caesar dressings are more often than not a creamy variety,
which doesn't seem to be what Cardini had in mind.
</P>
<P>
   At least two factors can be credited for what a purist would
call the Caesar's moral decay. First there was the salmonella
scare; a raw egg is often used in the classic dressing. Some chefs
answer that problem by using pasteurized eggs, which have been
briefly heated to kill bacteria. Other chefs believe that enough
lemon juice in the dressing will ``cook'' the egg with natural
acid.
</P>
<P>
   The faux Caesar offensive could also be blamed on anchovies.
They're not necessarily cheap, so chefs may well have decided to do
without _ and how many diners whose preferences run to Chili's and
T.G.I. Friday's would object, anyway?
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
