<HEADLINE>
CAESAR THE DAY WITH THESE AWARD-WINNING SALADS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JUNE NAYLOR RODRIGUEZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The more established chefs in the competition topped
their Caesar salads with wood-roasted salmon and flatbread shards,
or sided them with tuna tartare in crisp won ton baskets.
</P>
<P>
   It was newcomer James Neel, however, who won the annual Great
Caesar Salad competition with a simple, traditional recipe, mixed
the old-fashioned way in a wooden bowl with a fork.
</P>
<P>
   Neel, the kitchen chief at the white-hot new Al Biernat's
restaurant in Dallas, was one of seven noted area chefs invited to
the competition last Sunday at Dallas' Fairmont Hotel, sponsored by
the American Institute of Wine &AMP; Food.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the chefs _ such as Grady Spears of Fort Worth's Reata _
had competed before, but this was Neel's first try. ``The chefs
have always been so enthusiastic in wanting to do more than just
the salad, and they're always trying to outdo each other,'' says
Paula Lambert of Dallas Mozzarella Co., who founded the event seven
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Neel served his salad with triangular sesame-Parmesan flatbread
crisps and a very spicy crab cake _ about the size of an Oreo
cookie _ on the side. Simple and smart, the salad held just the
right balance of garlic, lemon and anchovy flavors.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Neel's competitors were doing extraordinary things
with their salad accouterments. Chris Huff of Dallas' Palomino
topped his salad with wood oven-roasted salmon and shrimp, then
piled salad and seafood into a lavosh (crisp flatbread) tower.
</P>
<P>
   Clark McDaniel, executive chef at Angeluna in Fort Worth,
decorated his salad with fried anchovies and big sheets of fresh
Parmesan. Always the Asian cuisine enthusiast, McDaniel used sambal
(an Indonesian condiment), tamarind puree and fish sauce in his
Caesar dressing, and offered side servings of tuna tartare in
crispy baskets of paper-thin fried won tons.
</P>
<P>
   Englishman Nick Barclay, owner-chef at the Dallas restaurant
bearing his name, went with an English theme, with a dressing
including English mustard and croutons made from English
walnut-herb bread.
</P>
<P>
   Lines were longest at the Reata table, where Spears and several
helpers piled salad on plates, then crowned them with jumbo beef
tenderloin tamales. Reata's Reggie Parks, who recently left Star
Canyon in Dallas to join Spears, spent parts of three days stuffing
and tying the 500 tamales.
</P>
<P>
   After the lines dwindled and the ballots were cast, last year's
winner _ Jim Severson of Sevy's in Dallas _ took the podium. The
envelope was opened, and Neel's name was announced. He was awarded,
appropriately, a head of romaine lettuce.
</P>
<P>
   AL BIERNAT'S CAESAR SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Serves 10
</P>
<P>
   2 heads romaine lettuce, washed, trimmed and dried
</P>
<P>
   1/8 cup anchovies
</P>
<P>
   1/8 cup fresh minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon dry mustard
</P>
<P>
   1/8 cup fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   4 pasteurized egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces Parmesan cheese, grated
</P>
<P>
   Work anchovies, garlic and dry mustard into a paste in a wooden
bowl with the back of a fork. Add lemon, vinegar and egg yolks and
continue to mix together. Slowly pour in olive oil while mixing
until all is incorporated. Finish with black pepper and Parmesan
cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Combine romaine lettuce with dressing and top with more
Parmesan.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 254 calories, 26 grams fat,
.22 grams carbohydrate, 5 grams protein, 90 milligrams cholesterol,
172 milligrams sodium, 91 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ Chef James Neel
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   REATA CAESAR SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   1 head romaine lettuce
</P>
<P>
   1 cup Caesar dressing (recipe follows)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup shredded Asiago cheese
</P>
<P>
   4 cups sourdough croutons (recipe follows)
</P>
<P>
   Wash and trim lettuce and tear into bite-sized pieces. Place
lettuce in large bowl and add dressing, half the cheese and all the
croutons. Toss mixture to combine thoroughly. Divide among four
chilled salad plates and top with remaining cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 601 calories, 57 grams fat, 13
grams carbohydrates, 10 grams protein, 53 milligrams cholesterol,
448 milligrams sodium, 86 percent calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   Dressing
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8
</P>
<P>
   1 very fresh egg yolk
</P>
<P>
   8 anchovy fillets
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon freshly squeezed lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   7 cloves garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons dry mustard
</P>
<P>
   1 3/4 cups olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Combine all ingredients except oil in blender. Puree everything
on low to medium speed. Remove the blender top and, covering
loosely with your hand, drizzle 1/4 cup of oil in very slowly with
blender running. Dressing will become thick. Transfer pureed
ingredients to bowl of mixer. Using whip attachment at medium
speed, slowly add remainder of olive oil, making sure the oil is
absorbed before continuing. If stored, dressing must be kept cold
and used within two days.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
