<SLUG> BC-ECONOMY-COLUMN-RAMSEY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINNING IS LOSING MONEY IN THE HEALTH INSURANCE GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRUCE RAMSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Providence Health Plan sent a shudder through the
market last week by walking away from Medicaid and the state's
Basic Health Plan. It had bid to offer the insurance in 1999, but
when it found that the new, higher rates for its services would be
among the lowest _ and hence most popular _ in the market, it cut
and ran. Its 70,000 members, mostly low- to lower-middle income,
will have to switch to other carriers.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect does not fill those other carriers with enthusiasm.
``We don't have any expectations to make any kind of profit in this
business,'' says Ed Freutel, vice-president at Regence Blue Shield,
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Losses have not been equally spread among the government plans.
Regence is near break-even on Medicaid. It lost $13.3 million last
year on the Basic Health Plan, most of it in the unsubsidized pool,
which serves customers with incomes double the poverty line and
above.
</P>
<P>
   For 1998, Regence raised rates 30 percent in the subsidized pool
and 130 percent in the unsubsidized pool. Suddenly it was the most
expensive in the market. Since December, its Basic Health Plan
membership has plunged from 50,000 to 15,000.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of Regence customers fled to NYLCare, which has the
lowest unsubsidized Basic Health Plan rates. NYLCare now has 43
percent of the business statewide, to the grief of its owners. Next
year it will raise rates in that pool by 120 percent, passing on
the Old Maid to someone else _ judging from the rate table, QualMed
and Kaiser.
</P>
<P>
   What's going on here?
</P>
<P>
   David Ford, president of NYLCare Health Plans Northwest, says
that it's huge claims for prescription drugs. That tells him people
in this pool are suffering from serious illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The Basic Health Plan's administrator, Gary Christenson, says
it's also maternity claims. In a normal health plan, 15 to 20
percent of hospital admissions are for maternity. In the
unsubsidized Basic Health Plan, 64.6 percent of hospital admissions
are for maternity.
</P>
<P>
   Another statistic: In 1996, 13.7 percent of people in Washington
had no medical coverage. But less than 3.6 percent of the mothers
bearing children had no coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Where did they get it? Quips insurance broker Brian McCulloch,
``The Baby Pool.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's what's happened. In the past four years, the state of
Washington, in a rush of progressivism, has decreed that no
insurers may deny policies to any person who applies. Health exams
are forbidden. Everybody, from athletes to AIDS patients, pays
standard rates. If the individual had insurance before, the new
insurer must provide coverage immediately; otherwise in 90 days.
</P>
<P>
   In employee groups the rules have long been similar. But in a
group, you have little or no power to ``game'' the system. The
carriers have to take you, and you have to take them. But as an
individual, you can shop around for whatever coverage you think you
might need _ and they have to take you.
</P>
<P>
   Insurers quickly figured that whoever had the richest plan would
be a dead duck. They cut benefits, and reduced their offerings from
4 percent homogenized to skim milk.
</P>
<P>
   And that left Washington state holding an ice cream cone.
</P>
<P>
   Are you sick? Really sick? Buy into the Basic Health Plan. It
has no deductibles and no million-dollar cap on lifetime benefits.
It has full coverage for addiction treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Are you pregnant? Buy into the Basic Health Plan. In the
individual market, no carrier is required to cover maternity, but
if it does, it must provide coverage immediately. For those
carriers, that's about $10,000 each. All the carriers except Group
Health have eliminated maternity coverage on individual policies.
But the Basic Health Plan offers it.
</P>
<P>
   The Basic Health Plan is, in today's market, not a basic plan at
all. ``Unfortunately, the unsubsidized plan is becoming the state's
high-risk pool,'' said Dennis Braddock, chief executive of
Community Health Plans of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The solution? That depends on whether you think medical
insurance should be offered in a market, with lots of variety, or
as a benefit, with every plan up to a high standard.
</P>
<P>
   To those in the second camp, like Insurance Commissioner Deborah
Senn, the problem is that health-care mandates signed by Gov. Mike
Lowry in 1993 were partly repealed by the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Senn's deputy, Robert Harkins, says the system ``doesn't offer
benefits on an equitable basis and spread that risk throughout the
market.''
</P>
<P>
   The insurance carriers take the opposite tack: It mandates too
many benefits, and interferes too much in the judgment and pricing
of risk. The
</P>
<P>
   carriers' hands are tied, and their customers can ``game the
system.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Ramsey is a reporter and columnist for the P-I. His e-mail
address is bruceramsey(at)seattle-pi.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
