<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ECONOMY _ MOSCOW _ The Russian Central Bank announced
that it would no longer intervene in propping up the country's
sagging ruble against the U.S. dollar. Within 45 minutes of the
opening of trading on the currency markets, the ruble fell five
percent -- after a 10-percent slide on Tuesday. Officials halted
trading after the first hour, and later said they would invalidate
all transactions that had happened on Wednesday. In further
evidence of falling confidence in the deteriorating economy, the
run on the banks has begun with hundreds of Russians standing
outside banks demanding money. (Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move by 5 p.m. EDT in both the (i) International and (f)
Financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   JOURNAL-RUSSIA _ MOSCOW _ The search for U.S. dollars is
reaching a fever pitch during the current economic crisis in
Russia. A drastic change in the situation either Monday or Tuesday
for the better not withstanding, the dollar supply has dried up and
Russians and expatriates are unable to lay their hands on
greenbacks. American Express Corp., a major money-changer here, is
holding up wire transfers from the States. It has been almost
impossible since Monday, Aug. 17, for Visa and American Express
card-holders to get cash from ATMs here. One woman said she was
preparing to cash dollars for rubles and was accosted outside a
currency-exchange booth by Russians begging to buy her $20 bill.
And then there's me, the absolute wolf of Wall Street, who shrewdly
exchanged $1,000 for rubles at the 6.2 rate on Monday, literally
minutes before the government announced its devaluation. Go figure.
(Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
