<HEADER>
A3215 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-HILLS-HNS     08-26 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-HILLS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEVERLY HILLS COMEDY IS SERIOUS ABOUT POVERTY, GENDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CRAIG MARINE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tamara Jenkins' new movie, ``Slums of Beverly Hills,'' is
sneaky. Disguised as a comedy, the film tackles such weighty
subjects as the sexual objectification of women and the effects of
class consciousness on a decidedly downwardly mobile family.
</P>
<P>
   Thank God none of that is evident in the advance publicity or
people would likely stay away from this movie in droves, which
would be a shame.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's interesting,'' said Jenkins, sitting in a conference room
at San Francisco's Hotel Monaco, fumbling with a cigarette and
waving her unruly black curls from her face. ``The European press
really picked up on the class angle, the way the movie tried to
deal with the issue of poverty in America through humor, how the
characters handle their place in society _ Europeans eat that stuff
up.''
</P>
<P>
   As usual, Jenkins laughs. She is very serious about ``Slums,''
which she both wrote and directed. It's her first effort for a
major studio and she clearly has a lot riding on its success. But
it's not like she's going to get all worried and stop having a good
time.
</P>
<P>
   She even jokes about how audiences will react to the film's
trailers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Manhattan, they can be just brutal,'' says Jenkins, a
transplanted Easterner. ``They'll sit there and yell `Stink bomb!'
and less refined comments. The thought of my little trailer being
put out there all alone is a bit frightening _ though I've heard
people are laughing. In the right places.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Slums'' is set in 1976, and concerns a 15-year-old girl
struggling to understand the peculiarities of her nomadic family
while at the same time coming to terms with her physical
maturation, expressed in the form of the large breasts she has
grown seemingly overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Either story line would make an interesting film. When presented
together, there is enough post-viewing conversation fodder to fuel
a marathon gabfest.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins said that one of the difficulties in making the film was
explaining to some of the men in the production team that sprouting
large breasts is not necessarily a wonderful thing for a teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys would be incredulous, like `Don't they like having
breasts? We loved it when the girls got breasts. We'd line up to
dance with them and rub our elbows against their breasts.' I had to
say, `Well, did you ever stop to think what that might have been
like from the girls' point of view?' After awhile, they got the
message,'' Jenkins said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Slums'' stars Natasha Lyonne as the 15-year-old, growing up in
an all-male household where her father and her two brothers felt
within their rights to comment on her chest size.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an adolescent, if you wake up and have breasts, the world
starts treating you differently. A lot of this has to do with the
history of objectification of women and a lot of it has to do with
the preconceptions people _ men _ have about women with large
breasts; that they are highly sexed or want to call attention to
themselves,'' Jenkins said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And young women have to contend with all of this in a public
way, relatives saying, `My, you've really filled out,' and those
are among the kinder things. You never see people say to boys, `My,
your balls are sure getting bigger.' It's like your body becomes
sexualized way before you are emotionally able to deal with it.
You're not necessarily prepared to be treated as a sexual object.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyonne had to use stunt breasts for the film, a set of falsies
to fill out her comparatively modest natural assets.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins said that she hopes the female perspective of the film
doesn't limit her potential audience. Having the film labeled as a
``women's film'' gives her the shivers.
</P>
<P>
   The class issues in the movie should help make the appeal more
universal. The movie brood's father, played by Alan Arkin, is
determined to keep his children within the Beverly Hills city
limits to provide them access to a superior school system.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their glitzy area code, however, the family lives on the
fringe, staying in one dilapidated apartment after another, often
skipping out on the rent with midnight excursions. Such contrast
makes the children acutely aware of their station in life,
something Jenkins plucked directly from her own upbringing.
</P>
<P>
   ``That part came straight from my life,'' she says. ``We lived
in Beverly Hills, but we were poor. We were surrounded by wealth.
And outsiders, particularly in adolescence, can become obsessed
with fitting in.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In one sequence, after moving to a nicer apartment with the
financial help of a relative, the children try to analyze whether
they have, in fact, now become part of the bourgeoisie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoyed having these kids discuss their place in the world
using Marxist terminology in such a quintessentially American
city,'' Jenkins said, allowing herself a dose of pride at her
efforts. ``They so much want to just blend in, to be as close to
`normal' as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   While Jenkins hopes the audience won't be limited to women, she
also hopes that the women who see the film will connect with the
heroine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely told from a female perspective, and I think
women will be pleased to see their point of view on the screen,''
she said. ``I think if there were more women in the film industry,
it might not be so out of the ordinary, but for the time being,
there aren't that many movies being made by women with women in
mind. At least, not yet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
