A3278 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-McGWIRE-SUPPLEMEN     08-26 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-McGWIRE-SUPPLEMENT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 ENOUGH, ALREADY, ON McGWIRE'S DIETARY SUPPLEMENT  
 Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE CAMPBELL  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The man must bring the national nightmare to an
end so that we can all get on with our lives.
</P>
<P>
   It's time. We have stock tables to check, stones to hurl at the
next guy who moves into a glass house.
</P>
<P>
   The man needs to swallow his pride, keep his anger in check over
what he considers a reckless invasion of his ``private life'' and
throw himself on the mercy of the court of public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't have a private life. He belongs to the American
people. He is a role model, occupying a position of public trust.
He owes each and every citizen and sincere look in the eyes and a
confession.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm guilty,'' Mark McGwire needs to say _ and mean. ``All the
reports and rumors are true. I'm guilty of using a dietary
supplement in conjunction with my exercise program. I'm guilty of
using a supplement that is available over the counter and legal in
50 states. I'm guilty of using a supplement not red-flagged by the
Food and Drug Administration, in violation of none of the rules of
major-league baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to make excuses, but I can't. The plain truth of the
matter is, I must accept full responsibility for willfully engaging
in a behavior that is neither illegal, nor immoral, nor against the
rules of baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   To call the thunderstorm around baseball's leading home-run
hitter a ``controversy'' would be to give it a legitimacy it
doesn't deserve. The revelation that McGwire uses androstenedione _
better known to its users as ``andro'' _ has led to the most
ridiculous debate since Abbott and Costello pondered over who's on
first.
</P>
<P>
   Some doctors classify andro as an anabolic steriod that allows
the body to produce additional quantities of testosterone, the male
hormone that allows athletes to train longer and recover from
injuries faster than they normally would. Other doctors question
whether andro has any appreciable effect on the long-term
production of testosterone.
</P>
<P>
   A lack of conclusive evidence of andro's helpful or harmful
effects hasn't deterred a panel of assorted doomsayers from
determining that McGwire has defiled the home run race. They live
for these moments, these stolen opportunities to tear down anything
or anybody audacious enough to rise into prominence. They live by
the credo: If you can't beat 'em, tear 'em down.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire is a soft touch for charitable causes, a man who donates
$1 million a year to campaign against child abuse, and even he
isn't immune to the cheap shots.
</P>
<P>
   To hear the doom and gloom set tell it, McGwire has tainted his
accomplishments, endangered his health, corrupted the youth of
America and weakened the office of president. The presumption is
that McGwire is guilty of some sort of wrongdoing if he breaks the
season record for home runs. The International Olympic Committee
has banned andro. The National Football League has banned andro.
</P>
<P>
   Major-league baseball hasn't.
</P>
<P>
   Neither has the FDA.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire is operating under the law of baseball and the land.
Anybody who has a problem with McGwire taking a dietary supplement
that may or may not help him produce extra testosterone, that may
or may not carry health risks, needs to take it up with the FDA
first and major-league baseball second. Besides, the IOC list of
banned substances is good for more laughs than CBS's lineup of
sitcoms. The IOC is the same body that bans over-the-counter cold
remedies while allowing dope-smoking snowboarders to win gold
medals.
</P>
<P>
   Any suggestion that McGwire is a monster created by chemistry
ignores how he hit 49 home runs as a rookie _ long before he
happened upon his regimen of better baseball through body-building.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire admittedly began using andro about a year ago, which
wouldn't explain the 52 homers in 423 at-bats in 1996. Or the 39
homers in 317 at-bats in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire works out religiously. He studies pitchers. He had an
uppercut swing made for home runs when he entered the majors, and
he has had more than a decade to smooth off the rough edges. He is
an intelligent hitter who knows the strike zone. Tying his success
to using the latest in dietary supplements is as insulting as
attributing Maris' 61 homers in 1961 to having a short right-field
porch in Yankee Stadium, or hitting in front of Mickey Mantle.
</P>
<P>
   Babe Ruth had a short porch in right when he hit 60 homers, and
he didn't have to face pitchers who threw sliders, and he didn't
have night games, and he didn't play against African Americans. Do
those things diminish Ruth or Maris? Of course not.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe time will tell us that McGwire, sadly, has used andro at
the expense of his health. In the end, it is McGwire's body.
McGwire's health.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   People knowingly try things _ cigarettes, pizza, beer, caffeine,
candy _ all the time. McGwire insists he has thoroughly researched
what he is doing. Even if he hasn't, it's his business. He is old
enough to decide for himself whether or not to use a legal product
that doctors cannot say with certainty can cause testicular
atrophy, rages (perhaps the byproduct of the testicular atrophy),
acne, breast enlargement (another possible cause of rage) and acne.
</P>
<P>
   And please, let's keep the kids out of this.
</P>
<P>
   Only a hypocrite would accuse McGwire of doing a disservice to
impressionable young athletes across the country by setting an
unseemly example. The only reason people know that McGwire uses
andros is because an Associated Press reporter snooped around his
locker. If kids start buying andros by the case, it's because they
read and/or heard that McGwire was using the stuff.
</P>
<P>
   At last look, there weren't any television commercials or print
ads starring a hulking redhead who says, ``Hi, I'm Mark McGwire. I
used to be a regular 98-pound weakling, unable to hit a pop fly out
of the infield. Then I tried an amazing new product. Andros. I used
to spend hour after hour in the weight room, building up my
strength. Thanks to andros, I can get the same results lying on the
couch eating donuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind, too, that there is a watchdog group out there that
is responsible for seeing to the safety of the kids.
</P>
<P>
   Parents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
