<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-CALM-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR STATE, FEDERAL OFFICIALS, THE CALM BEFORE THE STORM 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By KIRSTEN B. MITCHELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RALEIGH, N.C. _ As Hurricane Bonnie churned toward land
Wednesday, state and federal officials took a breather before
disaster hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have done everything that we feel like we should do at this
time,'' Richard Moore, secretary of crime control and public safety
said. ``The entire coast has been emptied and Bonnie's track bears
out that we should have emptied the entire coast.''
</P>
<P>
   Some 71 shelters as far inland as Fayetteville were opened and
850 National Guard troops were dispatched to Clinton, Greenville,
Lumberton and Kinston where a supply of generators, chain saws and
heavy equipment was stashed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot deploy any more resources until we know where to
send them,'' Moore said. ``We would be getting ahead of
ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   So as storm barrelled toward the coast, officials in the
Emergency Operations Center in the basement of the state
Administration Building watched satellite images and waited.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're kind of waiting until the storm passes,'' said Maj. Gen.
Rudy Rudisill of N.C. National Guard.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Wednesday, Jim Graham, state agriculture secretary,
announced a program for farmers to rent generators for tobacco
barns, poultry houses and other uses. The department obtained the
generators from a contractor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's right now in the middle of harvest, particularly corn,''
Graham said. ``Bonnie's going to affect the corn.''
</P>
<P>
   He was not as concerned, he said, about tobacco because 60
percent of the state's cash crop had been harvested.
</P>
<P>
   Nursing homes and hospitals are first in line for generators
from the National Guard, said Sara Kempin, spokesman for the
Department of Crime Control and Public Safety.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
