A3307 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PHYSICIANS-EXECUTION-     08-26 0416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHYSICIANS-EXECUTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA THINKS LAWSUIT OVER DEATH PENALTY IS FRIVOLOUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ULYSSES TORASSA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A lawsuit seeking to bar doctors from
participating in executions may be an attempt to stop something
that isn't happening.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen California physicians Tuesday asked a state appeals
court to reinstate their suit seeking to prevent the state from
using doctors to carry out the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   But Christine May, a spokeswoman for the California Department
of Corrections, said technicians, not doctors, insert the
intravenous line that delivers the lethal drugs to the condemned
prisoner. A physician's only role is to attend and certify the
death, which is required by state law.
</P>
<P>
   ``From our perspective, they do not participate,'' May said,
adding that all those involved, including the physicians in
attendance, are volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen D. Schear, the lawyer representing the doctors, said
documents from the department dated as recently as 1996 showed that
physicians were part of the execution team, although their exact
role was vague. He also said if the state isn't using doctors to
carry out executions, they should not oppose the request for an
injunction.
</P>
<P>
   The facts surrounding the department's practices have not been
explored in court because the lawsuit was dismissed in 1996 before
it could be heard by a jury. At the time, a San Francisco Superior
Court judge said the state Legislature had established a public
policy that provided for the death penalty and included the
involvement of doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Major medical groups like the American Medical Association and
the California Medical Association oppose the participation of
doctors in executions. Schear said it amounts to unprofessional
conduct on the part of physicians who have taken an oath to protect
the interests of patients. He said it could harm a patient's trust
in his doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Schear said his clients do not oppose the practice of using
psychiatrists, who are also medical doctors, to certify that
convicts are mentally competent to be eligible for execution.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more distant from the actual execution,'' he said. No
executions are currently scheduled in California, although there
are 510 people on death row, according to the corrections
department.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court is expected to decide whether to reinstate the
lawsuit within the next two months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
