<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 15:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3353 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFFIRMATIVE-ACTION-HN     08-26 0450
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFFIRMATIVE-ACTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO MAYOR BACKS AFFIRMATIVE ACTION IN DEFIANCE OF LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GREGORY LEWIS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Mayor Willie Brown, brushing aside the threat of
lawsuits, supports an effort to keep San Francisco's
affirmative-action program in place for another five years despite
a voter-approved initiative that bars race and gender preferences
for government contracts.
</P>
<P>
   City Supervisor Amos Brown unveiled a ``carefully crafted''
proposal on Monday that would continue the city's
Minority/Women/Local Business Enterprise program, which assists
minorities in bidding on municipal contracts.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said his preference was to maintain the city's
affirmative-action program despite the approval of Proposition 209
two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Board of Supervisors has extended the old ordinance for the
past two years, but Supervisor Brown's proposal would replace the
old ordinance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The proper hearings will be conducted and I believe it will
ultimately be passed and signed into law,'' the mayor said. ``I
think it will stand any court challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   University of California Regent Ward Connerly, who headed the
campaign to pass Proposition 209 in 1996, said on Monday he was
``just drooling at the prospect'' of a legal challenge to San
Francisco's affirmative-action program if it is extended.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor, a frequent critic of Connerly, said the Sacramento
businessman is ``entitled to file any lawsuit he may wish. All I
would suggest is that he should at least read it unlike what he
normally does.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, asked if he feared a lawsuit, the mayor said, ``I don't
go through life with a cloud over my head.''
</P>
<P>
   He and city officials believe the proposed ordinance meets the
U.S. Supreme Court standard for allowing affirmative action as a
remedy where discrimination can be shown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our affirmative-action program began through a Supreme Court
test and it survived a challenge according to that Supreme Court
test before Proposition 209 came along,'' Supervisor Michael Yaki
said. ``So we are simply following extending that program ... (and)
ensuring diversity and opportunity for minorities.''
</P>
<P>
   A city report on $2.5 billion in municipal contracts awarded
from 1992-95 showed blacks received 1.44 percent of the amount.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses owned by white women received 1.37 percent; companies
owned by Arab Americans and Native Americans received no contracts.
Asian Americans received 3 percent of the construction money and
Hispanics got 5.28 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Companies owned by white men received 88.92 percent of the
construction contract dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-26-98 1522EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
