<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-GUIDEBOOK-GUIDE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GUIDEBOOK GUIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature culled from The
New York Times Syndicate's ``Way To Go!'' travel package _ the rate
is not prohibitive _ contact one of the following sales
representatives:
 &HT;    (_ U.S. and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.
 &HT;    (_ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (_ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at (310)
996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!---------------------
 &HT;    ONE COLOR SLIDE is available by mail (or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number) AT NO EXTRA CHARGE to
purchasers of this article. Please specify that you want the art
when you order the article.
 &HT;    ---------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (HERE'S AN OFFER YOU CAN'T REFUSE: TRY A FREE TRIAL OF THE ``WAY
TO GO!'' PACKAGE AND SEE FOR YOURSELF HOW IT CAN ENHANCE YOUR
PAGES! SEE ABOVE FOR A SALESPERSON IN YOUR TERRITORY.)
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By EVERETT POTTER 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Dozens of new travel guidebooks have recently arrived in
bookstores and on Internet bookstore sites. Here's a selection of
the best.
 &HT;    ``Time Out Dublin,'' edited by Peter Fiennes (Penguin, 1998,
$14.95) is Time Out's first guide to the booming Irish capital.
Hip, street-smart and savvy, it runs the gamut from gay bars to
hurling matches.
 &HT;    Accommodations, from bed &AMP; breakfasts to The Clarence, the chic
hotel owned by the rock band U2, are also well-covered.
 &HT;    There are detailed descriptions of the best pubs, such as
Mulligan's, which offers ``a legendary pint of Guinness _ perhaps
the most celebrated and discussed in the entire town.'' And there
are suggestions for excursions out of Dublin, such as to Thor
Ballylee, home of the poet W.B. Yeats. All told, it's the only
guide that the Dublin-bound should need.
 &HT;    Lonely Planet has published a slew of new guides of late. Among
them are ``The Deep South: Louisiana, Mississippi, Alabama'' by Kap
Stann, et al (Lonely Planet, 1998; $19.95), which offers close to
600 pages on plantation mansions, blues clubs and gumbo
restaurants.
 &HT;    Their ``London,'' by Pat Yale (Lonely Planet, 1998; $14.95), is
a much-needed guide to one of the most expensive cities in Europe
and a good source for restaurants and hotels that are easy on the
wallet.
 &HT;    But the best of the lot is ``Chicago,'' by Ryan van Berkmoes
(Lonely Planet, 1998; $15.95), a detailed labor of love.
 &HT;    The author knows his city very well. He's informed, informative
and opinionated. He offers a wry 90-minute tour of the Art
Institute of Chicago.
 &HT;    After watching the Cubs lose, he suggests a stop at Bernie's
Tavern, which ``doesn't jack up its prices on game days to fleece
unsuspecting fans, as the many upscale joints in the neighborhood
do.'' And he advises walking around Chicago as the best way to see
it ``except when huge chunks of windblown sleet are smacking you in
the face.''
 &HT;    Like the smart aleck on the next barstool, van Bermoes is
cranky, funny and obviously loves the Windy City. His book is the
next best thing to a personal tour.
 &HT;    Two books have staked out one of America's most beautiful areas,
the California coast. ``The California Coast; A Traveler's
Companion,'' by Donald B. Neuwirth and John J. Osborn (Countryman
Press, 1998; $17.95) is readable and easy to use.
 &HT;    Besides noting scenic high points, hotels and restaurants, the
book offers profiles of people like Rim Fay, a retired Los Angeles
lifeguard, and Rene Avant, a coast ranger. Pack it for a family
driving tour.
 &HT;    The other guide worth perusing is ``Coastal California,'' by
John Doerper (Compass American Guides/Fodor's, 1998; $19.95). With
photographs by one of America's best-known outdoors photographers,
Galen Rowell, this book is a rich look at the history and the
culture of the area. Birders, wine lovers and sightseers will be
well served by it.
 &HT;    The Compass series is one of the best around for those who crave
well-written background information. But this one also shines with
practical details about hotels and restaurants _ not to mention
tattooed La Jolla surfers, ocean kayakers and the Channel Islands.
 &HT;    With Rowell's stunning photographs and Doerper's sensitive and
intelligent prose, this is an ideal travel guide.
 &HT;    The Compass series has also produced ``Underwater Wonders of the
National Parks,'' by Daniel J. Lenihan and John D. Brooks (Compass
American Guides/Fodor's, 1998; $19.95). Spectacular photography and
a wide range of locations makes this a terrific read.
 &HT;    From Devil's Hole cave in Death Valley to St. John in the U.S.
Virgin Islands, Isle Royale in Lake Superior to Biscayne National
Park in Florida, this book shows a watery side of America's
National Parks that is rarely glimpsed.
 &HT;    Moon Travel Handbooks, noted for their detail and no-nonsense
prose, has recently tackled New England. Their ``Maine Handbook,''
by Kathleen Brandes (Moon, 1998; $18.95) offers a close look at the
state that calls itself ``Vacationland.''
 &HT;    On her top 10 list of attractions, Acadia National Park ranks
first, L.L. Bean's store in Freeport ranks fourth.
 &HT;    She notes that what ``looks like a squished spider on Maine's
license plate is actually, of course, the state's favorite menu
item _ a lobster.''
 &HT;    But Maine's wilderness is what she really loves. Brandes remarks
that ``looking out over Maine from Mt. Katahdin today, as Thoreau
did in 1857, you get a view that is still a mass of green
stretching to the sea, broken by blue lakes and rivers.''
 &HT;    Also deserving a look are ``New Hampshire Handbook,'' by Steve
Lantos (Moon Travel Handbooks, 1998; $18.95) and ``Massachusetts
Handbook,'' by Jeff Perk (Moon Travel Handbooks, 1998; $18.95).
 &HT;    Finally, ``Frommer's San Francisco from $60 a Day,'' by Erika
Lenkert and Matthew R. Poole (Macmillan Travel, 1998; $14.95) is a
find for anyone who's tried to beat the high cost of visiting the
city by the Bay.
 &HT;    Cheap eats? Readers will learn about dim sum at the Hong Kong
Flower Lounge, pizza to go at Golden Boy Pizza in North Beach and
Latino specialties at Pozole in the Castro District.
 &HT;    There are loads of recommendations for cheap sleeps throughout
the city, as well as sightseeing and shopping tips that should
please anyone who's watching their budget in San Francisco.
 ---- 
 &HT;     (Everett Potter is a New York-based free-lance writer.)  
 &HT;     c.1998 Everett Potter  
