<HEADLINE>
SAILORS RECALL THEIR WARTIME DUTY ABOARD A TRUSTED FRIEND 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN: Ohio, Massachusetts)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDWARD FITZPATRICK  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ It had been 53 years since Ed Whitmore stood on
the deck of a World War II destroyer escort, 53 years since he'd
hunted German U-boats, 53 years since his crew had plucked the
bodies of dead American sailors from the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday morning, he was among 510 members of the Destroyer
Escort Sailors Association and their spouses who were in Albany to
visit the USS Slater, the last destroyer escort still afloat in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Whitmore, now 85, moved slowly across the Slater's gray gun
deck, recalling the days when he was commander of another destroyer
escort, the USS Otterstetter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to stand here and look at this ship,'' he said with
the sun brilliant overhead, the Hudson River placid below. ``I can
still see the salt water running across the deck here, three feet
deep.'' It was November 1944. A brutal storm in the North Atlantic.
He was the skipper and waves were battering his ship, rolling it 40
degrees, 45 degrees, 50 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wake up at night sometimes,'' Whitmore said. ``I can still
see the ship rolling.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitmore had come from Akron, Ohio, to attend the 23rd
convention of the Destroyer Escort Sailors Association. Others had
come from California, Florida and Maine. The association was
meeting in Springfield, Mass., but members took a day trip to
Albany, marking the single largest group to visit the Slater since
the 306-foot-long warship arrived here in October of last year.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the government produced 563 destroyer escorts between
1942 and 1945. But nearly all were later scrapped, used as targets
or given to other nations, said Martin Davis, director of the
Destroyer Escort Sailors Association. The Otterstetter became a
target for a guided missile.
</P>
<P>
   The Slater served in the Greek Navy from 1950 to 1990 before
being saved for restoration. ``This is a gem,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph F. Freese, the association's executive administrator, said
the ship is important for World Ward II veterans, as well as for
younger generations.
</P>
<P>
   ``For many people, this will be the first time to see this, and
the last time,'' he said. There may be another chance, however: The
Destroyer Escort Sailors Association plans to hold a convention in
Albany in 2000, said Gordon Lattey, a board member of the Destroyer
Escort Historical Foundation, which is restoring the Slater as a
maritime museum.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said these conferences allow veterans to share memories
from a defining chapter in their lives. With the average age of
sailors 20 and commanding officers 27, the war marked the first
time that many of them had been away from home and their first
venture overseas, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Albert St. Jean said he was 17 when he first stepped aboard the
Otterstetter as a carpenter's mate. ``They brought me up,'' he said
of the ship's crew. St. Jean, now a 79-year-old resident of
Russell, Mass., helped guide the Slater up the Hudson River from
New York City, and he stood on the gun deck Tuesday wearing a white
shirt and pants covered with silk-screen images of a destroyer
escort, plus a white sailor's cap.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the best commander in the Navy,'' St. Jean said,
putting a hand on Whitmore's shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say that,'' Whitmore replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got back alive didn't we?'' St. Jean said. ``What more
proof do you need?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
