A3408 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-MUZAK-NYT &LR;      08-26 1301
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-MUZAK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODERN MUZAK: IT'S NOT YOUR PARENTS' ELEVATOR MUSIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (jt)  
 By DAVID KUSHNER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Time for a root canal. Inside the dentist's waiting room,
nervous patients thumb through ancient magazines. A drill squeals
from the back room. Mouths go dry, throats gulp. But then, seeping
from the ceiling, comes a gentle melody in soft lapping waves. By
the time the work starts, the patient is calm and relaxed.
</P>
<P>
   This is one of the promises of Muzak, the ubiquitous music heard
in Crate &AMP; Barrel and Citibank, in malls and McDonald's. Here it
calms and there it soothes, not to mention the Muzak company's
sales pitch: that properly chosen background music can boost sales
and increase productivity.
</P>
<P>
   But now, instead of the Muzak stereotype of endless blenderized
instrumental versions of songs like ``Afternoon Delight,'' the
company is offering the rapper Puff Daddy and the grunge rock band
Nirvana, lyrics and all, in the quarter of a million businesses
that buy Muzak's wares.
</P>
<P>
   In July, the Seattle-based company unveiled an extensive image
makeover. It's all part of a new campaign to take this often
ridiculed business into the next millennium as a hipper, more
creative version of its former self.
</P>
<P>
   Over the company's 65-year history, it has doggedly built its
reputation _and melodies _ on what it called ``the science of
business music.'' Muzak was founded in the early 1920s by Maj. Gen.
George Owen Squier, a retired Army Signal Corps officer. Something
of a protogeek, General Squier experimented with ways to deliver
music directly into homes via electrical lines.
</P>
<P>
   His company, originally known as Wired Radio, began transmitting
over telephone lines, later expanding its broadcasts into hotels
and restaurants. A 1937 study by British industrial psychologists,
``Fatigue and Boredom in the Workplace,'' reinforced Squier's
efforts, finding that under certain ``planned sound conditions,
productivity in work areas is stepped up,'' according to Muzak's
company history.
</P>
<P>
   This morale-boosting science remained Muzak's mantra for
decades. In a brochure sent to prospective clients in the
mid-1990s, Muzak touted the ``subtle psychological lifts'' of its
specially designed tunes. A patented process the company called
``Stimulus Progression'' was developed to counter an employee's
``work efficiency dips'' (photos show a scientist taking notes
while a young man covered in electrodes listens to Muzak).
</P>
<P>
   This is the way stimulus progression works, according to Muzak:
most employees have a dip in productivity around 10:30 a.m. To
counter that, stimulating music _ chosen for its variations in
tempo and instrumentation _ is piped in through office intercoms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Muzak can motivate achievement,'' the brochure says.
``Stimulate sales. Inspire creativity. Decrease absenteeism. And
increase productivity. Muzak creates the sound of better business
for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Muzak's vice president, Alvin Collis, said the sound has
changed. ``Background music used to play a covert role in a
particular environment,'' he said. ``Now businesses recognize that
they can put the power of music to work to create emotional
connections. It's all about team building.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Muzak has jettisoned the flavor of its past
promotion for a spunkier, MTV-style approach. New brochures ditch
the graphs and wires of the old days for shots of Muzak tattoos and
snowboards.
</P>
<P>
   The staff members are no longer electrode-wielding men with
clipboards tweaking the mixing boards; now they're Gen-X musical
hipsters. (In fact, Muzak has long attracted struggling musicians
from the Seattle area; former employees include the founders of
legendary indie label Sub Pop records, plus grunge rockers from
bands like Tad and Mudhoney.)
</P>
<P>
   But despite this new approach, Muzak still relies upon a
high-tech, highly orchestrated system of design and distribution.
The process begins with Muzak's 18 ``audio architects,'' who
oversee the creation and selection of more than a million songs in
Muzak's database. These songs fall into two basic categories:
foreground and background.
</P>
<P>
   The elements of foreground music, which makes up the vast
majority of Muzak's catalog, are pop songs in their original form.
With 60 channels available to Muzak subscribers, the company wants
to offer a varied mix of styles; songs are chosen accordingly.
Instrumental background music, also known as environmental music,
is what people most associate with the company, though it's only a
small portion of Muzak's services. Audio architects research
sources like Billboard magazine and MTV, choosing songs that will
be re-recorded instrumentally. This recording process, however, is
proprietary. Declining to describe it, Collis said, ``That'd be
like giving the recipe of Coke.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While Muzak no longer talks about ``stimulus progression,'' it
still uses ``quantum modulation,'' the company's term for how songs
are classified in its database. After a song is commissioned in its
original form or transformed into environmental music, it is
evaluated by an audio architect.
</P>
<P>
   The architect rates the song in 45 detailed categories: the mood
of the music; its instrumentation; its color (dark or light), and
whether it is by a male or female vocalist. Once analyzed, the
songs are assigned what the company calls ``quantum modulation''
figures and stored in the database for future retrieval.
</P>
<P>
   Every day, audio architects assemble 24-hour playlists, ranging
from country to pop hits, for 60 broadcast channels. Songs are
selected, Collis said, to provide the necessary blend and balance
of stimulation throughout the day. ``We want to create an
atmosphere that is dynamic and constantly changing,'' Collis said.
``We don't want to be boring.''
</P>
<P>
   With the database updated, Muzak representatives meet with
prospective clients to create an ``audio image'' _ a musical
personality. They examine the client's marketing goals, mission
statement and products, then suggest an appropriate Muzak program.
A shoe store in a rural area needs to keep kids mellow; maybe the
country channel might be appropriate. An urban sneaker store wants
to enhance the customer experience; how about Muzak's channel with
Puff Daddy songs?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe someone wants Puff Daddy and Shania Twain. No problem. A
customized channel can be tailor-made. Fulfilling the vision of
General Squier's Wired Radio, the music is then sent by modem from
the Seattle headquarters to satellite uplink stations in Cheyenne,
Wyo., and Raleigh, N.C. Subscribers receive the transmissions via
18-inch dishes on their roofs. Muzak also provides compact disks if
clients would rather program sounds on their own.
</P>
<P>
   The company's current customer base of a quarter of a million
businesses compares with 125,000 subscribers in 1978. And its
earnings have risen to $50.5 million for 1997, from $26.7 million
in 1989, according to company figures. Aside from smaller
background music companies in local markets, Muzak dominates the
industry. While some businesses choose to use for background music
something like, say, an easy listening station, Muzak says that the
frequent commercial breaks are a downside to such practices.
According to Muzak's Lauren Hower, the problem for the company is
when offices or retail stores prefer to work without any music at
all. ``Our biggest competition is silence,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   These days, listeners might be hard pressed to find ``You Light
Up My Life'' wafting through elevator shafts. In the 1940s uzak was
pumped into elevators to soothe fearful riders. Those days, as
Collis is quick to point out, are long gone. Elevator music, he
said, ``is just an urban myth.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
