<HEADER>
A3424 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-HARD-DRIVE-CLEANU     08-26 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-HARD-DRIVE-CLEANUP-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEANING UP? PROCEED WITH CAUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
(jt) 
 By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I will never have a neat office. But even a mentally healthy
person who has accepted her own messiness can sometimes get a
little, well, depressed at having lost control. So the other day,
as I sourly surveyed the old-computer graveyard in the corner, the
floppy disks strewn like cocktail coasters and the baby playing on
the floor with a spare power cord, I decided to clean up . . . my
hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   It was the perfect plan. It would enable me to avoid physical
contact with smelly cleaning products and the thorny questions of
what to do with an expired passport and a crumpled coupon for a
free car wash.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a set of system tools that came with Windows 98 would
exercise control over at least a portion of my environment.
</P>
<P>
   I made a bold list:
</P>
<P>
   1. Get rid of unnecessary files.
</P>
<P>
   2. Reorganize hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   3. Remove extraneous programs.
</P>
<P>
   I admit it looked a little harsh on paper, at least for someone
whose previous philosophy consisted mainly of equal parts fear and
panic. So I started slow, bypassing Windows 98's new Maintenance
Wizard, which lets you automatically run a number of the system
tools simultaneously. Instead, I opted to run each tool separately,
starting with Disk Cleanup, to remove unnecessary files. Disk
Cleanup told me I could free an additional 4.92 megabytes of space
on the hard drive by emptying my Recycle Bin and deleting some
obsolete files that my browser had cached.
</P>
<P>
   It sounded reasonable, but for all I knew, Disk Cleanup could be
the kind of reckless program that would throw away an expired
passport. I clicked on View Files to see the earmarked files. They
consisted mainly of Web pages I would probably never visit again.
</P>
<P>
   So I took a deep breath, and clicked OK.
</P>
<P>
   With that action, I felt suddenly liberated. I had shed far more
than a mere 4.92 megabytes. I had taken control.
</P>
<P>
   Next, I ran Disk Defragmenter. It took nearly an hour for it to
sort all the scattered bits of data on my hard drive, group
together related pieces and identify my most frequently used
programs for faster access. It was time well spent. Then I boldly
deleted a half-dozen or so superfluous programs that I had
installed to evaluate during the last few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   What I wanted to do next was to sort through all the files on
the disk and delete useless, duplicate versions. But since I could
find no system tool to do that, I decided to ask Kip Crosby,
co-author of ``The Windows 98 Bible,'' for a recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   I clicked on the icon to start Eudora to send him e-mail and
realized immediately that I had done something wrong. Eudora
refused to respond. Instead, a window appeared to inform me that
the program could not locate an essential file called MSVCRT40.dll
in my Windows System folder.
</P>
<P>
   My heart sank. I must have deleted the file. But how?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way of knowing,'' Crosby said cheerfully, after I
reached him by phone. It turned out the missing file contained a
chunk of code that the operating system relies on to run any number
of programs that execute common functions. ``Maybe you deleted it
as part of an application that you removed,'' Crosby said.
</P>
<P>
   But if Eudora needed the file, wouldn't it have created a
separate copy during installation?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not necessarily,'' Crosby said. ``If two programs installed
the same file in the same folder, one copy would overwrite the
other.''
</P>
<P>
   My only choice was to go over to my husband's computer, copy the
missing file onto a floppy, then transfer it to my computer. This
took longer than expected (surprise!) because the floppy, which I'd
bought for use on a Macintosh, had to be reformatted. Plus, I had
to take a break to retrieve the baby from the computer graveyard,
where she was trying to insert her foot into the CD-ROM drive of an
expired Power PC.
</P>
<P>
   The fix worked, but I realized only after I replaced
MSVCRT40.dll that another version had existed all along on my hard
drive, in the Tools 95 folder. But Eudora could not see it because
the central database called the Windows Registry typically points
programs toward the Windows Systems folder.
</P>
<P>
   This reminder that I was not in control of my computer is the
sort of thing that used to scare me. But no more. It turns out that
computers are like life. You cannot avoid honest mistakes.
Sometimes you fix them, sometimes you can't, sometimes they fix
themselves. In any case, be glad you tried something new.
</P>
<P>
   With Eudora cured and the baby's efforts rerouted toward banging
a defunct keyboard against the cat, I felt brave enough to test a
program (recommended by Crosby) called Dupeless. Published by PC
Magazine last spring, Dupeless is designed to identify duplicate
files and remove them.
</P>
<P>
   After I obtained the program from
 &UR; www.hotfiles.com/utilities.html &LR; , Dupeless found 272 duplicates on
my hard drive. All I had to do was check off the ones I wanted to
delete.
</P>
<P>
   But I had been burned once already, so I phoned Dupeless'
creator, Neil J. Rubenking. ``Is it safe to delete a weird file if
you have a bunch of copies?'' I asked him. ``Also, I see a bunch of
duplicate .dll files. That got me into trouble before.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubenking gave me some tips:
</P>
<P>
   If you have duplicates, do not delete the version in the Windows
Systems folder _ that's the one likely to be shared by programs.
</P>
<P>
   Also, instead of immediately deleting duplicates, send them to
the Recycle Bin for a few days, until you're sure you will not need
to retrieve any.
</P>
<P>
   And most important, examine the contents of each file. If you
cannot identify its purpose, leave it for now.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, I threw out another four megabytes of unnecessary
junk and the coupon for the car wash. The whole room looks cleaner.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
