<HEADER>
A3428 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHAMBER-MUSIC-$ADV30-     08-26 1414
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAMBER-MUSIC-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVIVING THE GLORY OF STRING QUARTETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., Aug. 30)  
 (JT)  
 By DAVID MERMELSTEIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's odd how quickly the world forgets about chamber players.
For a time they may occupy something close to center stage in the
public imagination, then, almost without warning, they disappear
from the scene. The process may seem natural where retirement or
death is concerned. Still, it is hard to see why the performers
should vanish from the communal memory.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the presence of several faces, rather than one, is a
factor. Certainly, conductors, star soloists and opera singers
often dominate discussion long after they have stopped practicing
their art. Some (like Toscanini, Horowitz, Heifetz and Callas)
virtually transcend death, haunting their successors as
unassailable specters. But matters are different for chamber
musicians, even great ones. The Budapest and Amadeus Quartets cast
giant shadows over the world of chamber music not long ago, but who
talks of them now? And who clamors for reissue of their old
records?
</P>
<P>
   Yet Testament, a small British label, has seen fit to buck
convention by reissuing waves of old string quartet recordings on
CD. Not long ago, it brought renewed attention to the Hollywood
String Quartet and the Pro Arte Quartet of Belgium, and now it
shines a light on two post-World War II European ensembles, the
Smetana Quartet and the Quartetto Italiano.
</P>
<P>
   Testament's Smetana series actually began a few years ago, with
a pair of Dvorak and Janacek CD's. Now four generously filled disks
of music by Mozart, Haydn, Schubert, Schumann, Tchaikovsky and
Brahms expand our appreciation of the taut yet expressive style of
this ensemble.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in Prague in 1945, the Smetana Quartet didn't assume its
final form until 1956, when Milan Skampa, the violist, joined Jiri
Novak and Lubomir Kostecky, the violinists, and Antonin Kohout, the
cellist. The group disbanded in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Quartetto Italiano, in its early years, and the storied
Kolisch Quartet, the Smetanaperformed without scores and honed its
playing relentlessly. As a result, it achieved an extraordinarily
balanced and focused sound, but its playing was also distinguished
by vibrancy and sinew.
</P>
<P>
   On an album of Mozart, Haydn and Schubert from the mid-'60s (SBT
1118), the Smetana's talents show to excellent effect. Its
performance of Mozart's ``Dissonance'' Quartet starts creepily, but
a cheery spirit soon prevails. Only a labored Menuetto disappoints
amid the tight energy of the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Two Haydn Quartets, the ``Bird'' and the ``Lark,'' are even
better. The Smetana connects uncannily with this music, melding
authority and high-stepping joy with soaring, sparkling bowing and
robust tone. And the controlled verve in Schubert's
``Quartettsatz,'' which concludes the disk, is no less impressive.
</P>
<P>
   An album of three Mozart works (SBT 1117) includes the Smetana's
first recordings with Skampa, in the Quartets in D minor (K. 421)
and E flat (K. 428), both from 1956. Though an attractive folklike
quality suffuses the performances, the music's inherent elegance is
never compromised, and the group's unwavering ensemble is
remarkable. In the E flat Quartet, effervescence competes with
concentrated intensity. Contrast comes in the A major Quartet (K.
464), recorded in 1966, with a more fluid, relaxed pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Smetana adds another cellist, Milos Sadlo, in a 1973 account
of Schubert's glorious String Quintet, approaching the work with
bold attacks and sustained drama (SBT 1120). The Adagio may be too
swift, but the players lend irresistible Gypsy verve to the finale.
Brahms' B flat String Quartet, an often disappointing work, is also
included and becomes, in the Smetana's hands, a showcase for
flights of string fancy.
</P>
<P>
   The Romantic spirit surfaces again in a disk devoted to
Schumann, Schubert and Tchaikovsky (SBT 1119). Schumann's Piano
Quintet, with the able Pavel Stepan at the keyboard, opens the disk
on a note of infectious exuberance. The Smetana is at its most
ebullient here, digging into the composer's sweet phrases with
relish. A gentler but still sprightly touch graces Schubert's E
flat Quartet (D. 87). And the group offers a schmaltz-free yet
moving account of Tchaikovsky's First Quartet; even the famous
Andante Cantabile sounds fresh. The performances were recorded in
the mid-'60s.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Smetana Quartet reissues, which concentrate on the
ensemble's prime, Testament's three Quartetto Italiano disks focus
on an earlier period: the 1950s, when that group's playing was
characterized by winning spontaneity and natural charm.
</P>
<P>
   The Quartetto Italiano was formed in 1945 by four music students
who had met in Siena, and was forced to change violists a mere two
years later. Piero Farulli assumed the vacant chair, joining Paolo
Borciani and Elisa Pegreffi, the violinists (who married each other
in 1952), and Franco Rossi, the cellist. From then until 1977, when
Farulli suffered a heart attack, the quartet's personnel remained
unchanged. The group disbanded in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   The Italiano, one of the most refined of quartets, deftly
combined innate musicality with unforced urbanity. In later years,
a cool perfection crept into its interpretations, but here, in
vibrant yet poised performances, elegant phrasing, a light, airy
tone and gentle bowing carry the day.
</P>
<P>
   A disk of works by Vitali, Vivaldi, Galuppi, Boccherini and
Cambini (SBT 1124) brings together material from two of the group's
finest LP's (``The Italian String Quartet in the 17th Century'' and
``The Italian String Quartet in the 18th Century,'' recorded in
1956 and 1957), and makes for an excellent introduction to its
craft. Lavishing attention on what is essentially an assortment of
bonbons, the Italiano fuses a slightly astringent tone with
impeccable, mellow phrasing. The results, like a fine Barolo wine,
are a treat.
</P>
<P>
   A collection of Haydn, Mozart and Schubert quartets (SBT 1125),
mostly from 1956, provides more substantial pleasures. The
recording of Haydn's ``Bird'' Quartet offers significantly less
rhythmic thrust than the Smetana account but no dearth of
ebullience.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Italiano's complete survey of Mozart's string
quartets on Philips (recorded between 1966 and 1973) remains justly
famous, the two Mozart items here hold special appeal. The ``Hunt''
Quartet is full of un-self-conscious dash, with a quirky Minuet and
a songful Adagio lending character. The G major Quartet (K. 156),
which was recorded in 1959, is also endearingly rendered, its
punchy Minuet almost blared by the players. The disk closes with
the first complete recording of Schubert's Quartet in C (D. 32). By
turns sober and bright, this performance has yet to be improved on,
almost 30 years later.
</P>
<P>
   The most interesting disk is one devoted to Prokofiev,
Stravinsky, Milhaud and Malipiero (SBT 1123). Though the Italiano
was an exemplary interpreter of the Classical and Romantic styles,
it was also a sincere advocate of more modern repertory.
</P>
<P>
   Prokofiev's folk-inflected Second Quartet proves a superb
vehicle for the group in a 1955 account that is as heartfelt as it
is technically adept. In Stravinsky's Three Pieces for String
Quartet, recorded in 1959, the Italiano zealously spins sharp
phrases and clean lines.
</P>
<P>
   Darius Milhaud dedicated his 12th Quartet to the memory of
Faure, but it more recalls the Debussy and Ravel Quartets, of which
the Italiano was a celebrated interpreter. In its 1954 account of
the Milhaud, the ensemble gives a loving, supple tribute to a minor
but attractive work.
</P>
<P>
   A compatriot of the Italiano players, Gian Francesco Malipiero
wrote eight string quartets. His Fourth, featured here in a 1955
recording, is a muscular yet lyrical ode. The group, treating it as
a work of consequence, elevates the music.
</P>
<P>
   Authoritative, lucid notes by the Scottish-born quartet scholar
Tully Potter add to the value of both the Italiano and the Smetana
CD's.
</P>
<P>
   Testament's commitment to the art of string quartet playing may
not single-handedly rescue a form of music-making in need of
greater attention. But the label forcibly reminds listeners that
past glories have present implications and that chamber players of
today descend from various traditions. Keeping that history alive
helps to preserve options and prevent homogeneity. Other labels,
big and small, should follow Testament's lead.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-26-98 1555EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
