<SLUG> BC-CIR-CARS-IDIOTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ART OF DRIVING IS ALL THE RAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (bl)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once you have come to terms with the number of computers inside
your car, try looking at the number of cars on your computer _ Web
sites devoted to just about all aspects of the automotive
experience. And when it comes to popular driving topics on the Web,
road rage is all the rage.
</P>
<P>
   Road rage, the phenomenon of agitated drivers' becoming
aggressive, dangerous and potentially lethal to other drivers, has
triggered a number of sites set up to record license plates and
automotive offenders on the Web. Yahoo keeps a comprehensive index
of recent news stories and Web pages about the topic
(headlines.yahoo.com/FullCoverage/US/RoadRage).
</P>
<P>
   Two rage pages in particular take vastly differing views on the
subject. The Principles of Driving Psychology
(www.aloha.net/dyc/ch11.html) is a paper published on the Web by
Dr. Leon James that explores attitudes and moral implications
concerning transportation manners among individuals. A lengthy
treatise on human behavior behind the wheel, the page also offers a
test called What's Your Moral Driving IQ? (Sample yes-or-no
question: ``When I encounter road-hugging pedestrians, I feel like
pushing them out of my way.'')
</P>
<P>
   If you are in the mood for more rage than road, try the scathing
site How to Drive Like a Moron (members.aol.com/doggiesnot).
Decorated with illustrations and animations that bring to mind the
look of Comedy Central's crudely animated ``South Park'' cartoon,
the site sarcastically compiles just about every possible
bad-driving habit as part of its instruction in the art of idiot
behavior. In the Shopping Center Parking Lots area, for example,
the site suggests: ``Always park on the lines, taking up as many
spaces as possible. Diagonal parking is preferred.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of its size and traffic congestion, the New York
metropolitan area most likely has more than its share of angry
drivers. For those wanting to know what they're getting into before
leaving the office, there's the Metro Commute site, which will let
you check a number of local regions for accident alerts,
construction areas and traffic warnings and posts an illustrated
map regularly (www.metrocommute.com).
</P>
<P>
   If you've finally made it home and find yourself locked in the
Web's slow lane, you can even check out the Internet Traffic Report
(www.internettrafficreport.com) to see how much congestion the Net
is under. And remember, whether you're driving a Jeep Cherokee or a
Dell Pentium, let's be careful out there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
