<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-PC-PETZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTTING A VIRTUAL DOGGY IN YOUR WINDOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (bl)  
 By J.C. HERZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Do we train pets, or do they train us?
</P>
<P>
   It's a disturbing question when your pet is a string of ones and
zeroes. It's even more disturbing when the digital pet in question
isn't some low-resolution key-chain toy with no intelligence or
personality. Demanding as they are, Tamagotchis aren't complex
enough to sustain a real relationship _ they're more like goldfish
or sea monkeys.
</P>
<P>
   But what about something that wags its tail, learns tricks,
likes to play fetch and pants contentedly when scratched behind the
ears? What about something that engages in spontaneous games of
tug-of-war, buries its toys, knocks things over on your desktop and
looks guilty when it has been bad?
</P>
<P>
   What about something that acts so much like a puppy that you
can't help adoring it and scolding it _ despite yourself?
</P>
<P>
   That's the problem with Petz. Dogz 3, PF Magic's virtual answer
to man's best friend (CD-ROM for Windows 95, $29.95, to be released
in October), looks and acts so much like a genuine canine that you
end up behaving like a genuine pet owner. (PF Magic will
simultaneously release Catz 3, but software that fastidiously
ignores you is somehow less impressive.)
</P>
<P>
   Like real pets, these artificially intelligent puppies and
kittens need affection and care. You have to feed them, but you
also have to play with them, reward them when they're good and
punish them when they're bad. If you want the virtual doggy in the
window, you have to sign a pledge to that effect.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, it's a software licensing agreement that demands
emotional commitment. A dialogue box pops up, you enter your name
and the contract appears:
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day that I, J.C., play with Petz 3:
</P>
<P>
   ``I promise to give Oscar, my Dachshund, love and affection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I promise to feed and play with Oscar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I promise to pet Oscar and reward good behavior with treatz.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand that if neglected or abused, Oscar will run away.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you accept this Adoption Pledge, please press the Adopt
Button.''
</P>
<P>
   Once you've agreed to all these care and feeding conditions, you
are the proud owner of a brand new virtual puppy that, given enough
food and love, will grow to full adult size.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you will need accessories for this.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the Petz 3 Toy Closet on the disk is stacked with
food and water bowls, treats, rattles, Frisbees, bones, pillows,
chew toys and other doggie playthings. Should you be inclined to
subject your pet to the indignity of clothing, there is also a
Clothes Closet full of baseball caps, socks, sweaters and other
ridiculous costumery.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the notes that accompany these items (``Dogz love to
dress up with the Plaid Sweater''), even virtual canines look
extremely sad when clothing is inflicted on them and will initially
try to wriggle out of it.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't find the right doggie knickknacks on the disk, you
can always hit the Web site,  &UR; www.petz.net &LR; , where more than
500,000 people have registered their Dogz and Catz and regularly
download new breedz and toyz, at no charge. For now.
</P>
<P>
   Once you've stocked up on pet necessities, you can watch your
virtual puppy play in several locations: the backyard, with a white
clapboard fence and the sound of lawn mowers in the background; the
family room, with a fireplace you can turn on and off; the kitchen,
or a beach where your dog can gambol in the sand and get its nose
bitten by a crab.
</P>
<P>
   You can even take your puppy out on the desktop, where it will
scamper over your carefully aligned file folders and bound up to
your cursor, toy in mouth, while you have other programs running.
(Finally, something to do while waiting for Web pages to download _
play fetch!) Toss a Frisbee across the screen, and the dog will
eventually learn to leap and catch it.
</P>
<P>
   If you ignore the dog, it will push its water bowl around for a
while and finally curl up to sleep. Sometimes you can hear its
little doggy snores. But even when it's just snoozing silently, it
provides a sense of companionship. It keeps you company. So you end
up working on this kind of domesticated desktop with the dog's food
and water bowls and chew toys lying all over the place while you
crunch numbers on a spreadsheet.
</P>
<P>
   And as long as the Petz program is running, a thin blue bar at
the bottom of the screen is prompting you to interact with your
cybernetic companion: ``Double-click anywhere to call your Petz to
your cursor . . . Reward and train your Petz for good behavior by
feeding and petting them . . . Discipline your Petz with the Spray
Bottle when they are naughty . . . Teach your Petz to do tricks _
hold a treat out for them and see.''
</P>
<P>
   This is where the big difference between Dogz and Tamagotchis
becomes obvious. Tamagotchis are annoying because, when you take
care of them, there's no real reward _ just a break before they
beep for more attention. They're bratty. Dogz, on the other hand,
really know how to emote. They know how to express need. And they
love you to pieces when you give them what they want.
</P>
<P>
   When Dogz are thirsty, their tongues hang out and their eyes
sort of plead. The dialogue bar flashes ``Quench your Petz' thirst
with some cool, refreshing water.'' So you set the water bowl down,
and the little fella runs over to it. The computer executes the
``dog lapping water'' sound file. And the pup looks happy and licks
your cursor, and you feel swell. Dogz know how to deliver the
emotional payoff that motivates users _ behind those adorable
little muzzles is some rather sophisticated artificial intelligence
code. And it's training you.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, I've lost track of how much time I spent teaching
my virtual dog to catch a Frisbee on the computer screen. But when
Oscar finally leapt up and caught the thing in his mouth, I felt
like a million bucks.
</P>
<P>
   Humanz can do tricks. Hold a treat out for them and see.
</P>
<P>
   e-mail address: Herz(AT)nytimes.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
