A3446 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL_RACIALMIX-AZR &LR;      08-26 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL_RACIALMIX-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
25-LANGUAGE SCHOOL IS PREVIEW OF U.S. DIVERSITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos have been sent to NYTNS photo clients)  
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIE AMPARANO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Five-year-old Nikolay Dimitrov speaks Bulgarian
fluently, but still can't understand English.
</P>
<P>
   Piroska Barabas, 10, switches between Hungarian and English in a
flash.
</P>
<P>
   Nine-year-old Norman Tan prefers English but can carry on in
Cantonese or Mandarin too.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four nationalities. Twenty-five different languages. One
school.
</P>
<P>
   This is Hugh E. Laird Elementary in Tempe. The school is a
melting pot of cultures, a mini-United Nations and a picture of
America in the next century.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very proud of our diversity,'' explains Mary Lou Torres,
principal of Laird, where about 64 percent of the population is
minority. ``This is the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States and Arizona are seeing more of a racial
mix,'' says John Wright, vice president of the Arizona Education
Association. ``That's being reflected in our schools. And I believe
the cultural diversity it brings will be a benefit to all.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, many schools across the country are witnessing
dramatically changing populations.
</P>
<P>
   In Arizona, about 43 percent of the students in primary and
secondary schools are members of a racial minority, according to
Rose O'Keefe of the Arizona Department of Education.
</P>
<P>
   In the Tempe districts, that translates into 67 different
languages at its campuses. Phoenix Union High School District
boasts 70 languages.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, more than one-third of all students are members of a
racial minority, according to Annette Kolodny, who takes a look at
21st-century education in her book ``Failing the Future.''
</P>
<P>
   The percentage is even higher in California, New Mexico, Texas,
Mississippi and the District of Columbia. In those states, Kolodny
says, more than half of the students are minorities. &QL; 
 &QL; 
ASU, CHURCHES SEND SOME
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fueling this trend are immigration and higher birth rates for
minorities.
</P>
<P>
   School officials at Laird attribute its diversity to Arizona
State University and church groups who sponsor families from
war-torn and economically ravaged countries.
</P>
<P>
   Situated less than two miles from Laird, ASU has many
foreign-born students who, while pursuing their degrees, send their
children to Laird, if they live in the area.
</P>
<P>
   That's why second-grader Aishen Shi is attending Laird. Her
family moved to Phoenix from China so her father could obtain a
doctorate in engineering.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each year, it seems like we add one or two more
nationalities,'' said Torres. This year, for instance, Romania and
Argentina were added to Laird's list of countries.
</P>
<P>
   Torres' office is a testament to the school's diversity.
</P>
<P>
   On a bookshelf behind her desk rests an assortment of trinkets
from around the world. In a delicate box, a miniature calligraphy
set from Korea is on display. From Singapore, there is a statue of
a ``merlion,'' a beast that is half-lion and half-fish.
Representing Costa Rica is a cup and saucer and from Thailand, an
urn.
</P>
<P>
   Having classmates from so many different cultures benefits
children in many ways, according to parents and experts.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, children grow up with fewer prejudices.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't see the color of a person's skin,'' says Laurie
Staalberg, an American who has a fifth-grade son and first-grade
daughter attending Laird. ``Their friends are their friends. They
don't care what country they come from. It's very nice.''
</P>
<P>
   In the book ``40 Ways to Raise a Nonracist Child,'' Mary Ann
French and Barbara Mathias write that one of the best ways to
eliminate racism is to encourage children to play with youngsters
from different cultures.
</P>
<P>
   Alberto L. Pulido, an assistant professor of racial relations at
ASU, explains: Being exposed to so many different cultures in such
a positive environment ``creates a more sensitive community, and
the children benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   The view of the world is also much larger for these children. &QL; 
 &QL; 
NO HUNGARIAN ICE CREAM?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   During a break in class, for instance, Norina Asante, from Ghana
in Africa, and her best friend Piroska Barabas, the young
Hungarian, talk about differences in their homelands.
</P>
<P>
   Piroska chatters about what her country looks like and how
people there live. Then she states in complete disbelief: ``But
they have no playgrounds. And we couldn't get any ice cream.''
</P>
<P>
   Norina returns the banter, talking about life in Ghana. One
benefit of her country, she confesses: ``You don't have to worry
about people stealing you there like you do in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Holding hands, the girls talk about how they met in the first
grade. Barabas was crying because she didn't speak any English and
couldn't understand the teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I held her hand,'' says Norina, bobbing her head and sending
the multitude of braids on her head shaking. The two then skip off
to another part of the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   Every day, the richness of cultures is evident.
</P>
<P>
   In Jean Behrens' fourth-grade class, students are quietly
studying English when Norman Tan breaks out in Cantonese. A
classmate who recently arrived from China is asking him about the
lesson.
</P>
<P>
   As they talk, a girl from Latin America marvels at the sight and
boasts: ``He can speak three different languages. I only speak
two.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Norman explains that the two were discussing the
``physical properties'' of the English language.
</P>
<P>
   But language isn't the only new subject to learn. American food
can be very perplexing.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, Laird kindergartners ate lunch in the English as a
second language classroom. There they would learn about American
food.
</P>
<P>
   Why are hamburgers called hamburgers when they have no ham? What
are the English names of foods they already enjoy _ like cabbage,
broccoli and lentils?
</P>
<P>
   The school week for many of these children doesn't end on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Many Chinese children, like Norman, must attend ``Saturday
school,'' where they learn to read, write and speak the language of
their homeland. That way, Norman explains, if they return to China,
he'll know the language and culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like English better,'' confesses Norman. ``Chinese is too
hard.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
24 Countries represented at school &QL; 
 &QL; 
Argentina &QL; 
Romania &QL; 
