<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-POP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cheesy covers aside, John's talent apparent
 &HT;    By Nick Tate
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Musical footnotes such as this odd relic rarely deserve more
than passing mention. But this intriguing compilation from the
vaults is an exception.
</P>
<P>
   Recorded during Elton John's salad days for a variety of labels,
the 16 tracks on this collection offer a rare glimpse of the
part-time Atlanta resident before he navigated the slippery slope
from unknown studio musician to pop music superstar.
</P>
<P>
   There is much here that John no doubt would prefer remain locked
away. His cheesy covers of Badfinger's ``Come and Get It,'' White
Plains' ``My Baby Loves Loving'' and Brotherhood of Man's ``United
We Stand'' are wince-inducing. And the AM-radio production values,
Mormon Tabernacle Choir harmonies and tinny string backdrops that
warp these ersatz classics make them sound as dated and shallow as
any Osmond Brothers LP.
</P>
<P>
   But beneath the surface of these obvious cut-and-run commercial
recordings, there is some real gold that reflects John's
distinctive musical signature. His soulful retread of Cat Stevens'
somber ``Lady D'Arbanville'' hints marvelously at the introspective
side that would mark his later work with Bernie Taupin on tracks
such as ``Your Song'' and ``Mona Lisas and Mad Hatters.'' At the
other extreme, his raucous, wide-open readings of Stevie Wonder's
``Signed Sealed Delivered'' and Creedence Clearwater Revival's ``Up
Around the Bend'' echo the R&AMP;B boogie of such early hits as ``Take
Me to the Pilot'' and ``Honky Cat.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, this is an eclectic mixture with at least as many
misses as direct hits. But John's soulful vocals and personalized
piano riffing distinguish the collection, making it more than
simply a retrospective worthy of the K-Tel brigade.
</P>
<P>
   ``16 Legendary Covers from 1969/70''
</P>
<P>
   Elton John. Purple Pyramid. 16 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   The verdict:
</P>
<P>
   A guilty pleasure for Elton fans.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
