<HEADER>
A3448 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-REVIEWS27-COX     08-26 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-REVIEWS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Audio minireviews: The latest word on the latest sounds
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton, Al Levine, Richard L. Eldredge, and Russ
Devault
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   -- SOUNDTRACK
</P>
<P>
   ``Back to Titanic''
</P>
<P>
   Various artists. Sony. 13 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   How much more money can be wrung out of the highest-grossing
movie of all time? Apparently, the makers of this follow-up to the
25 million-selling ``Titanic'' soundtrack think, a smidge more. But
far from being a slapdash effort, ``Back to Titanic'' is a tasty
sampler of leftovers and re-recorded numbers from the original
soundtrack. The Irish jig music from the below-decks party scene is
included, as is the formerly promotional-only recording of the
Celine Dion megahit ``My Heart Will Go On,'' with dialogue added.
All in all, a quality product, and timely too, because it's sure to
get a big sales boost from the video release of ``Titanic'' on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   -- ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``See Through Me''
</P>
<P>
   Randall Bramblett.
</P>
<P>
   Capricorn Records. 11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Known primarily for his keyboard and sax work with Sea Level,
Gregg Allman and Steve Winwood, this journeyman session player and
Georgia native takes center stage on his first solo album in 20
years. Bramblett has made little effort to modernize during that
time _ ``See Through Me'' mines a very organic, very 1970s groove.
The title track recalls the extra-crispy R&AMP;B of Delbert McClinton;
``I Burn for Someone'' walks the same lonely city streets Bruce
Springsteen drifted down on ``Darkness on the Edge of Town.'' If
the lyrics tend toward the generic,
lost-soul-in-search-of-redemption variety, the evocative,
heart-grabbing melodies carry the day.
</P>
<P>
   -- COUNTRY
</P>
<P>
   ``Stepping Stone''
</P>
<P>
   Lari White. Lyric Street. 11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   With plenty of fiddle and pedal steel as the backdrop for lyrics
describing Daddy turning on the sprinkler and kids running through
it ``in our underwear,'' then catching fireflies and putting them
in a jar, they can't say Lari White ain't country enough anymore.
That was the knock when RCA pulled the plug on her record deal a
couple of years ago. She's back to prove them wrong. The title
track may be an autobiographical comment on her journey: ``This
ain't no stumbling block, it's just a stepping stone.'' This solid
set is terrific proof.
</P>
<P>
   -- POP
</P>
<P>
   ``For the Masses''
</P>
<P>
   Various artists.
</P>
<P>
   1500/A&AMP;M. 16 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   This tribute to Depeche Mode by musicians inspired by the
pioneering synth British pop group isn't nearly as calculated as
other recent ``tribute'' projects. What's more, the quality of the
assembled material is both inventive and as nearly addictive as the
original versions. The only previously released track is an
excellent cover of ``Never Let Me Down Again'' that the Smashing
Pumpkins recorded in 1993. Other surprise treats include a
synth-stripped, rocked-up version of ``Policy of Truth'' by
Dishwalla and the unexpectedly touching cover of ``Somebody'' by
Veruca Salt. The oddest contribution is fellow influential Brit act
the Cure doing ``World in My Eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   -- BLUES
</P>
<P>
   ``Come On In''
</P>
<P>
   R.L. Burnside.
</P>
<P>
   Fat Possum/Epitaph. 12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   No matter whether listeners hear R.L. Burnside's music as
amped-up electric blues, an insult to tradition or blues for the
millennium, it's worth hearing. Burning away under the sound
supplied by Burnside's family band and the high-tech mixing of Tom
Rothrock (perhaps best known for his work with Beck) is a solitary
Mississippi hill country bluesman with a guitar. It's as simple as
fife-and-drum music, yet so relentlessly insistent that it can win
acceptance as trance blues or punk blues. Key cuts include
``Rollin' Tumblin','' ``Been Mistreated'' and three takes of ``Come
On In.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
