<HEADER>
A3449 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-WEB-MYSTERIES-ART     08-26 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-WEB-MYSTERIES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MYSTERY SITES EASY TO DEDUCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By MICKEY MEECE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Marisa Babjak laughs when she thinks about the noose pin she
sold to the judge in Florida, but she has other, more serious
things on her mind now. Like visiting the Orange County, Calif.,
morgue on a slow night to take a look at a few toe tags. She thinks
the toe tags will lend themselves nicely as a stern message to
friends and loved ones, as in, ``You're dead meat if you don't
write.''
</P>
<P>
   Unpleasant reality filtered through humor sells well for Ms.
Babjak, 39. She markets mystery-related items by catalog and
through her Web site, Femmes Fatales (mall6.register.com/femfatal).
There you can scroll through a limited list of gift items, like the
Mad Mother Shower Curtain, police patches from the former Soviet
Union, T-shirts and all manner of pins _ guns, hatchets, thumb
prints.
</P>
<P>
   Femmes Fatales opens a window on hundreds of mystery-related
Internet sites where people have taken up residence to chat, read
about their favorite authors, buy gifts and books, solve whodunits
and answer trivia questions. There are other Web pages dedicated to
Agatha Christie and Arthur Conan Doyle, and modern authors like Sue
Grafton and John Grisham.
</P>
<P>
   Links to many of those can be found at Mysterious Strands
(www.idsonline.com/userweb/cwilson/mystery.htm).The sites tend to
leave trails, or links, to other sites, making it easy to find a
slew of others.
</P>
<P>
   There are true-crime sites, like Black Dahlia
(www.bethshort.com), and other reality-based fare, like the Smoking
Gun page (www.thesmokinggun.com). For a serving of rock-and-roll
and mystery, there's www.paulisdead.com, which invites you to solve
the drowning of a fictional rock star, Paul Lomo.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jiro Kimura, 49, of Kanazawa, Japan, writes a regular column on
the Internet mystery scene for Hayakawa's Mystery Magazine and
opened the Gumshoe page in January 1996 (www.nsknet.or.jp/jkimura).
``I usually write in Japanese to make money,'' she said in a recent
e-mail exchange, ``but I wanted to write something in English too
for non-Japanese mystery fans. I thought the Web site would be the
best way.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the site, which is impressive in its simplicity, she
describes what's new and lists some of her favorite bookmarks.
``The Internet is just another means by which mystery fans
communicate with one another,'' Ms. Kimura said in her e-mail. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Often that communication leads to a face-to-face visit at the
many mystery conventions held each year. At Partners &AMP; Crime, an
independent bookstore in New York City's Greenwich Village
(www.crimepays.com), e-mail correspondents who have been at the
shop's site looking for first-edition copies or original art make a
point of stopping at the store when they are in town, said Kizmin
Reeves, a partner in the store.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a huge world out there and it's really quite
diverse,'' said Patty Suchy, who runs Novel Explorations
(www.erols.com/novelexp), a travel company based in Columbia, Md.,
that this winter held a mystery-theme vacation cruise. ``People
become more aware to the possibilities on the Internet,'' she said,
where they can find like-minded groups and other places to go. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For those with a particular interest in Sherlock Holmes, there
is the Sherlockian Holmepage
(watserv1.uwaterloo.ca/credmond/sh.html), created in 1995 by Chris
Redmond, author of ``A Sherlock Holmes Handbook.'' The idea, he
said, was to have a page pointing to all things about Sherlock
Holmes on the Web. ``Sherlockians have always been great at letter
writing and newsletters,'' he said. ``A lot of that has shifted on
the Web.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Susan Dahlinger, a writer in Secaucus, N.J., has signed onto two
mailing-list sites for mystery aficionados, mostly to do research,
she said. One is by invitation only, she said. The other, Hounds of
the Internet (www.bcpl.lib.md.us/lmoskowi/hounds/hounds.html), is
open to anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Many authors and publishers are using the Internet to publish
the first couple of chapters in their books to get fans hooked.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Babjak, who lives in Lakewood, Calif., said her Femmes
Fatales catalog and site grew out of her hobby of making and
selling gift items to mystery fans at conventions. Femmes Fatales
(French for ``deadly women'') was created with the help of her
husband, Jim, in 1995 to broaden her business and her love of
mysteries.
</P>
<P>
   New morbid items may show up for sale at Femmes Fatales.
Customers like police officers, coroners and an entomologist Ms.
Babjak has nicknamed ``Maggot Man'' keep requesting more unique
items. When you think about it, she says, when's the last time you
saw a T-shirt for a bug guy?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-26-98 1609EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
