</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-POP27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fugees' Hill taps roots of black pop
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   An instant contender for album-of-the-year honors, the solo
debut of Fugees frontwoman Lauryn Hill is something to marvel at.
This autobiographical song cycle is an evolving treatise on
womanhood, spirituality, hip-hop and black history that seductively
weaves together seemingly every scrap of African-influenced musical
tradition you can imagine. Right down to the album's cover, a
likeness of the 23-year-old singer carved into the top of a school
desk that recalls the image of Bob Marley on the reggae star's
``Catch a Fire'' album.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, hip-hop is all about referencing and reinventing, but
Hill goes beyond the obvious in assimilating strands of reggae,
1960s and '70s R&AMP;B, Stevie Wonder's utopian melodies, guest
appearances by Carlos Santana and jazz violinist Regina Carter, and
even a sample of the Doors' ``Light My Fire.'' She seeks to embody
what critic Greg Tate once called the ``unified field theory'' of
African-American pop and, at the same time, assert herself as the
higher consciousness of hip-hop. ``People feel Lauryn Hill,'' she
sings on the cautionary ``Final Hour,'' ``from New-Ark to Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   What shapes the album's complex mixture of protest, prophecy and
philosophy is a profound moral sensibility: a righteous vibe. Track
to track, Hill celebrates roots that stretch back centuries while
evoking a kind of biblical authority. Her duet with Mary J. Blige,
``I Used to Love Him,'' offers these lines of praise _ ``Father you
saved me and showed me that life / Was much more important than
being some foolish man's wife'' _ while on the sweet, redemptive
``To Zion,'' a tribute to her new son, Hill parallels her pregnancy
with the Annunciation. Coming from Tori Amos, that might seem
pretentious. Here, with Santana's unmistakable guitar in the
background, it makes perfect sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Miseducation of Lauryn Hill''
</P>
<P>
   Lauryn Hill. Columbia. 14 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: The Fugees vocalist makes a hip-hop classic.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
