<HEADER>
A3452 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-SOUNDTRACK-COX     08-26 0296
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-SOUNDTRACK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lesser names steal `Dance' thunder
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Credit Epic Records with good intentions. For this soundtrack to
the new Vanessa L. Williams movie, which sets a story about
professional ballroom dancers to an infectious Latin beat, the
label uses name acts _ Gloria Estefan, Jon Secada and Williams
herself _ to draw in listeners, then exposes them to purer Latin
artists, including Ruben Blades and Albita.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that the bankable names threaten to douse the
fiery spirit that infuses this highly danceable disc. Sergio Mendes
gets the party started with the propulsive ``Magalehna,'' then
Estefan clears the floor with the flavorless disco workout
``Heaven's What I Feel.'' Cuban vocalist Albita revs things up
again with the ebullient salsa number ``Fiesta Pa' Los Rumberos,''
only to have Secada break the mood with the Muzak-ready ballad
``Want You, Miss You, Love You.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams and her co-star, Puerto Rican singing sensation
Chayanne, croon two versions of the movie's love theme, ``You Are
My Home.'' The first is a slick ballad complete with goopy strings
and generically ``Latin'' guitars. Naturally, it's the single. The
second reconfigures the song as an upbeat salsa number, with far
better results. These two versions emphasize the soundtrack's
schizophrenic feel, which should have listeners of all stripes
leaping for the program button on their CD player.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dance With Me _ Music From the Motion Picture''
</P>
<P>
   Various artists. Epic Records. 15 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   The verdict:
</P>
<P>
   A spicy sampler of Latin music, but skip the bland bits from the
big names.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
