A3453 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-4GIRLS-COX     08-26 0245
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-4GIRLS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    4 slain girls remembered
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``4 Little Girls'' (unrated)
</P>
<P>
   In September 1963, a bomb went off in the Sixteenth Street
Baptist Church in Birmingham, killing four young girls. It was a
seminal act of cowardly savagery. And it had the unintended effect
of changing the bombers' world forever. In the words of the Rev.
Jesse Jackson, ``We were able to transform a crucifixion into
resurrection.''
</P>
<P>
   Spike Lee's Oscar-nominated documentary works as both a portrait
of the murdered children (three of them 14, one 11) and a cruelly
poignant perspective on the civil rights movement, which the
bombing switched into a higher gear. The film gives us insight into
the now unthinkable segregation rules of the Deep South. We see
black-and-white footage of Police Chief ``Bull'' Conner's men
assaulting protesters with dogs and fire hoses. And Lee gets in his
licks against then-Gov. George Wallace, contrasting his
``segregation forever'' stance in the '60s with his current,
unconvincing claims that his best friend is an African-American.
</P>
<P>
   While the movie's second half could have used some tighter
organization, ``4 Little Girls'' is seeded with emotional land
mines. Heartbreaking moments occur unexpectedly as siblings and
parents remember the girls taken from them 35 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
