<DOCNO> NYT19980826.0268 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3455 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-ERINGEL27-COX     08-26 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-ERINGEL27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Keep summer spirit alive with blasts from the past
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the summer of 1998 fades into history, everybody probably has
at least one favorite summer movie they'd like to see again. But
with theaters changing bills to make room for the fall openings,
that might not be so easy.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few suggestions should you find yourself at the video
store and still in a summertime mood.
</P>
<P>
   -- If you liked ``Deep Impact'' ... check out ``On the Beach''
(1959). Set in the ``near future'' _ that would be 1964 _ Stanley
Kramer's film looks at the end of the world through a 1950s prism
of nuclear paranoia. After an atomic blast irradiates the Northern
Hemisphere, an all-star cast (including Gregory Peck, Ava Gardner,
Fred Astaire and a pre-``Psycho'' Anthony Perkins) await their
inevitable fate in Australia. The picture was actually shot in
Australia _ the first major Hollywood production to go on location
there. Gardner was heard to remark when she arrived, ``I'm here to
make a film about the end of the world, and this sure is the place
for it.''
</P>
<P>
   -- If you liked ``There's Something About Mary'' ... check out
``Kingpin'' (1996). The Farrelly brothers had already had a hit
with ``Dumb and Dumber,'' but this riotous gross-out comedy about
bowling was, at the time, more than most audiences could take. Too
bad, because it's a marvel of mock-epic idiocy _ part ``The
Natural,'' part ``Ren and Stimpy.'' Woody Harrelson plays a bowling
phenom from the '70s whose career was sabotaged by the sleazy
reigning champ, Bill Murray. He gets a second chance coaching an
Amish lad (Randy Quaid) with a golden arm. As in ``Mary,''
anything's fair game: prosthetics, bodily fluids and more bad hair
than should be legally allowed in one movie.
</P>
<P>
   -- If you liked ``The Mask of Zorro'' ... check out ``The Mark
of Zorro'' (1940). A protege of 20th Century Fox mogul Darryl F.
Zanuck, Tyrone Power was more or less hand-picked by Zanuck to play
Zorro in this lavish remake of the Douglas Fairbanks silent
swashbuckler. To make up for not lending Power to a rival studio
for ``Golden Boy,'' Zanuck also hired that movie's director, Rouben
Mamoulian. Like the current Antonio Banderas-Anthony Hopkins film,
Power's version both buys into the derring-do and has fun with it
(in a '40s way). One nice bit of continuity: The master swordsman
who trained Fairbanks also coached Power. He gave him Fairbanks'
sword, too.
</P>
<P>
   -- If you liked ``Out of Sight'' ... check out ``Get Shorty''
(1996). It took star John Travolta, producer/co-star Danny DeVito
and director Barry Sonnenfeld to finally get Elmore Leonard
onscreen as he should be. This breezy adaptation of Leonard's novel
about murder, money and script meetings in Hollywood often follows
the book word for word. Miami loan shark Chili Palmer (Travolta)
travels to Los Angeles to chase down a bad debt. But when he meets
the guy who owes the dough _ cheesy Z-movie producer Gene Hackman _
Chili pitches him a screenplay instead of pitching him off a cliff.
</P>
<P>
   -- If you liked ``The Truman Show'' ... check out ``The
Prisoner'' (1968-69).
</P>
<P>
   This made-in-Britain TV series ran only two summers (17 episodes
altogether), but it was one of the most distinctive programs ever
aired. Like ``The Truman Show,'' it's set in a deceptively
picturesque town (actually, a resort on Cardigan Bay in Wales)
where nothing can be taken at face value. However, as the title
suggests, the tone is considerably more ominous. The Prisoner
(a.k.a. No. 6) is a former government agent being held against his
will. Why? Any number of reasons. To extract top-secret
information. To keep him from sharing top-secret information.
Perhaps simply to test him. Star Patrick McGoohan created and
produced the series and also wrote some of the scripts.
</P>
<P>
   -- If you liked ``Six Days, Seven Nights'' or ``The Horse
Whisperer'' ... check out almost any of the Spencer Tracy-Katharine
Hepburn movies. It doesn't matter whether it's 1942's ``Woman of
the Year'' (about a political columnist and a sportswriter), 1952's
``Pat and Mike'' (about a star athlete and her trainer) or 1949's
``Adam's Rib'' (about married lawyers), because the setup is always
the same: high-handed, high-strung, stylish dame brought off her
pedestal by a gruff, down-to-earth, no-guff guy. Interestingly,
Tracy's contract guaranteed him first billing. When once asked
about this less than gallant behavior, he replied, ``A film isn't a
lifeboat.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
