<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-REVIEWS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini views: Reviews of the latest on video
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   -- ``Men With Guns'' (R) _ Writer-director John Sayles' (``Lone
Star'') mournful journey into a modern heart of darkness. Federico
Luppi (``Cronos'') plays a sheltered doctor in an unnamed Latin
American city who ventures into the mountains to check on the
students he trained three years ago to treat the country's poor
Indian natives. The mountains have been raked with guerilla warfare
for some time. And the deeper the doctor goes into them, the less
clear it becomes who is the enemy and who are the ``men with guns''
responsible for the carnage that he encounters everywhere. A
haunting modern parable, the film has the power of a terrible
dream. In Spanish, English and Indian dialects, with subtitles.
Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Leading Man'' (R) _ Torn between his wife (Anna
Galiena) and actress mistress (Thandie Newton), a successful London
playwright (Lambert Wilson) agrees to an odd proposal: He'll let
the Hollywood actor (Jon Bon Jovi) who's starring in his new play
seduce his wife, in order to take the pressure off. Things don't go
as planned. Despite an attractive, talented cast, director John
Duigan's backstage comedy never really creates the wicked fun you
know it's after. Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Woo'' (R) _ An uneven but spirited comedy about trying to
find true love amid a meat-market mentality. Jada Pinkett Smith is
the title character, a woman who's been so burned by the doggy
behavior of guys that she approaches her latest blind date (Tommy
Davidson) with the determination to prove his innate canine drive.
Unfortunately, the movie walks a very fine line between making Woo
wacky and making her seem criminally insane. Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Pocahontas II: Journey to a New World'' _ Actually, it's
not a new world, it's the old one: England, to be precise. And once
our Native American princess arrives there, this mediocre,
straight-to-video sequel dolls her up in European dresses and
makeup, sapping whatever all-natural life she had in the first
flick. The songs are forgettable, too. Priced to buy, $26.99.
Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Real Blonde'' (R) _ A fine ensemble cast reels around
the fringes of show biz in Tom DiCillo's entertaining episodic
film. Matthew Modine, Catherine Keener and Maxwell Caulfield are
thirtyish types working in (or trying to work in) various Manhattan
glamour jobs (acting, fashion, etc.). Heftier names such as Daryl
Hannah, Kathleen Turner, Denis Leary, Marlo Thomas and Buck Henry
turn up in assorted cameos. No major insights here, but it's
easygoing and funny. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel, c. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
