<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Author learns the political world in writing latest novel
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   No one can accuse Richard North Patterson of not doing his
research. For his latest novel, ``No Safe Place'' (Knopf, $25.95),
the best-selling author of legal thrillers such as ``Degree of
Guilt'' and ``Silent Witness'' interviewed George Bush, traveled
with Bob Dole on his campaign, hung out with Secret Service agents,
and joined the roving band of reporters covering the 1996 election.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are honest with you if they know you are writing
seriously about this political world, and not doing a cartoon,''
says Patterson, 51, whose books have sold 6 million copies. ``One
thing I set out to do was to revive the political novel as a
serious form. What we've had in political fiction seems to be roman
a clefs or ridiculous books about conspiracies where someone
hijacks Air Force One. The last great political novel was `Advise
and Consent,' and that was written 40 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing Patterson learned in his research was the lengths to
which reporters will go to unearth a political scandal, a key
element in his new novel. ``No Safe Place'' focuses on the
presidential campaign of Sen. Kerry Kilcannon, a charismatic Irish
politician haunted by the assassination of his brother during his
campaign in California 12 years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of the campaign, a right-to-life fanatic murders
three people at an abortion clinic and sets out to kill Kilcannon.
Complicating matters further is a secret affair that Kilcannon had
with one of the journalists covering the campaign _ an affair that
resulted in an abortion. When a reporter is handed a psychologist's
notes documenting the affair, he is torn between going with a
one-source story or ignoring it.
</P>
<P>
   In the current atmosphere of tabloid journalism and the Monica
Lewinsky matter, Patterson admits such soul-searching may be rare.
``The prevailing belief seems to be that the press _ and the public
_ is entitled to know everything. Given the power of the press to
destroy careers, and indeed lives, any reporter with a conscience
is going to feel the qualms I portray here.''
</P>
<P>
   Patterson's road to political novelist has been as circuitous as
a presidential campaign. As a lawyer in Birmingham in 1976, he
became hooked on Ross MacDonald novels and decided to write a
mystery himself. His first effort, ``The Lasko Tangent,'' won the
Edgar Allan Poe Award for best first novel. But by the mid-1980s,
his books were not selling and he quit writing for eight years.
When he tried again in 1992 with ``Degree of Guilt,'' the timing
was right for legal thrillers: It sold more than 250,000 copies.
</P>
<P>
   After writing three more novels about the legal system,
Patterson decided to leave the courtroom for the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a natural evolution,'' says Patterson, who divides
between San Francisco and Martha's Vineyard with his third wife and
six children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been interested in politics and social problems.
Pursuing the presidency is the modern odyssey. It is the most
difficult, invasive and grueling process an American can go
through. The risks are fantastic. Your opponents are scrutinizing
your every move. You have no safe place to go.''
</P>
<P>
   -- CHOICE DICKEY: Until now, if you wanted the best of James
Dickey's poems, you had to buy several different books. That
changes next month when Ohio University professor Robert Kirschten
publishes ``James Dickey: The Selected Poems'' (Wesleyan University
Press, $35), a collection of the poet's major works in one volume.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like many visionary poets of the ecstatic imagination,''
Kirschten says, ``Dickey experimented in a wide variety of literary
styles. This volume brings together the finest work from each of
the periods in Dickey's extremely controversial career.''
</P>
<P>
   Included are ``Sleeping Out at Easter'' from ``Into the Stone
and Other Poems'' (1960), ``The Lifeguard'' from ``Drowning With
Others'' (1962), ``Cherrylog Road'' from ``Helmets'' (1964), and
``The Sheep Child'' from ``Falling'' (1967).
</P>
<P>
   -- LITERARY LINDY: Two very different books on Charles A.
Lindbergh are headed for stores next month. The major work is
``Lindbergh,'' A. Scott Berg's definitive biography, and the other
is ``Under a Wing,'' a personal memoir by Reeve Lindbergh, the
aviator's youngest daughter. Berg, the National Book Award-winning
author of ``Max Perkins: Editor of Genius,'' was granted access to
thousands of boxes of Lindbergh family papers by Anne Morrow
Lindbergh. ``Under the Wing,'' which was excerpted in The New
Yorker, gives an inside account of life with a stern father who was
larger than life. Also in the works is a film by Steven Spielberg
based on Berg's biography.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
