<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-PAPERBACKS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Here are paperback suggestions for readers who like to read
 &HT;    By Carolyn Nizzi Warmbold
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Readers who like reading about reading will find plenty of pithy
axioms in Anna Quindlen's ``How Reading Changed My Life''
(Ballantine, $8.95). The Library of Contemporary Thought original
paperback will be especially enjoyable to baby boomers who grew up
hooked on books. Quindlen's essay is blessed with an amorphous
structure. Open it anywhere and ingest quotes like these:
</P>
<P>
   -- ``All of reading is really only finding ways to name
ourselves, and, perhaps, to name the others around us so that they
will no longer seem like strangers.''
</P>
<P>
   -- ``There are very few books in which male characters, much
less boys, are portrayed as devoted readers.''
</P>
<P>
   -- ``At age thirteen, `David Copperfield' often seems less of an
invitation to `Bleak House' than a clarion call for Cliffs Notes.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, readers who like reading Southern literature will
enjoy Padgett Powell's introduction to ``New Stories From the
South: The Year's Best, 1998'' edited by Shannon Ravenel
(Algonquin, $12.95). ``The literature of the South,'' Powell writes
in the preface, ``is full of people running around admitting or
denying their whippedness. The blend of this confession and denial
can be complex ... but finally that is the key: the people have
been whipped, and whipped good.'' Powell, Frederick Barthelme, Tim
Gautreaux, John Holman, Sara Powers and Mark Richard are among the
19 writers featured. Booklist says the collection illustrates that
the short story form continues to survive and evolve.
</P>
<P>
   Other new paperbacks include:
</P>
<P>
   Fiction
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Magician's Assistant'' by Ann Patchett (Harcourt Brace,
$13). When a magician dies, his widow, who had been his assistant
for 20 years, finds that the family he claimed he lost in an
accident is alive. Reviewers used words like ``elegant,''
``lyrical'' and ``beguiling'' to describe the novel.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Chin Kiss King'' by Ana Veciana-Suarez (Plume, $12.95).
A Miami neighborhood is the setting for this tale of three
generations of Cuban-American women and their care for a baby born
with a birth defect. The Boston Globe called it ``a powerful and
haunting story of the world of our spirits and spirituality.''
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Into the Forest'' by Jean Hegland (Bantam, $12.95). Two
sisters, living in a country on the brink of anarchy and collapse,
must forage through the forest, and their past, to survive.
Publishers Weekly says the book is ``a truly admirable addition to
a genre defined by the very high standards of George Orwell's
`1984.'''
</P>
<P>
   Nonfiction
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Summer for the Gods: The Scopes Trial and America's
Continuing Debate Over Science and Religion'' by Edward J. Larson
(Harvard, $14.95). Larson, a University of Georgia professor, won
the Pulitzer Prize in history for this account of the Scopes trial
and its impact on the teaching of evolution in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Leaving a Doll's House'' by Claire Bloom (Back Bay,
$13.95). The stage and screen star recalls her accomplishments and
romances, including her turbulent 18 years with novelist Philip
Roth. While our AJC reviewer found that ``Bloom's voice on the page
just isn't likable,'' Newsweek noted that Bloom ``puts the
memorable back in memoir.''
</P>
<P>
   -- ``When Work Doesn't Work Anymore: Women, Work and Identity''
by Elizabeth Perle McKenna (Delta, $12.95). Women don't have to
choose between having a career and having a life. Time magazine
said that ``all working men and women can benefit'' from McKenna's
suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
