<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Four book history of Dahlonega is pure gold
 &HT;    (Embargoed until August 30: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A lot of people are writing books about their families and their
hometowns. Before they get going, I want to recommend that they
read Anne Amerson's four books about Dahlonega, Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   So many hometown books are dull. One about a city I know pretty
well was written by an alleged historian. If it has a wisp of
history in it, I didn't find it. It is mainly a collection of mug
shots of local business leaders _ valuable for the town museum,
maybe, but not interesting.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Amerson's ``I Remember Dahlonega,'' volumes 1-4, are great
fun to read and valuable keepsakes for future students of Lumpkin
County, the gold mining era and the people who settled there.
</P>
<P>
   I have to confess that the last of the series came when I was
somewhere else, got swallowed up by other books, and I didn't get
around to reading it until it fell on my head the other day. I took
it home to bed and read it before I slept.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Dahlonega may be more colorful than most hometowns. I
love the names, for instance. There was a gold miner named Charles
and Napoleon Bonaparte Tankersley. (The ``and'' is part of the
name.) He was called ``Bony Tank.'' His descendants still live in
the area.
</P>
<P>
   And there are other families named Wimpy, Dowdy and Gooch. You
find yourself wishing you knew them all. I am especially sorry that
it's too late to get acquainted with Oscar Cannon, an amazingly
gifted woodworker who made spinning wheels and board games named
``Fox and Geese,'' using corn-like checkers to represent the fowls.
Mr. Cannon was doing this work at 97 years old. He died in 1995 at
age 98.
</P>
<P>
   There are gifted quilters in this mountain town. A young woman
named Nancy Patchell created an original for the Paralympic Games
in Atlanta. There is a picture of it in the book, and a good
discussion of the art of quilting.
</P>
<P>
   It reports that Ms. Patchell embroiders Bible quotations on many
of her works. A particularly moving one was ``This is the day the
Lord has made, we will rejoice and be glad in it.'' It was, the
author reports, an expression of her faith, and it sustained her in
her grief after her 12-year-old son was killed.
</P>
<P>
   The old courthouse, now a gold museum, has always been one of my
favorite places, and I was interested to read that when they
rebuilt it, they found the mud between the brick contained gold
dust.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, I missed another wonderful artifact _ mad stones. It
seems that a mad rock was used to draw poison from wounds caused by
snake bite and dog bite _ and you just may find one in Dahlonega,
because rock hounds abound there.
</P>
<P>
   You can even buy rocks at a shop on the square if you don't want
to prowl the mountainsides prospecting. But you will miss
beautiful, interesting scenery if you buy instead of finding.
</P>
<P>
   Many Georgians grew up reading the colorful Dahlonega Nugget,
which has been published since 1890. Jack Parks, former editor,
retiring in 1982, is remembered as being politically savvy and the
friend of people like Sens. Richard Russell and Walter George and
congressman Phil Landrum.
</P>
<P>
   But when President Truman fired Gen. Douglas MacArthur, it did
not make the front page of The Nugget. The reason, Parks wrote, was
that ``news from Yahoola and Frogtown crowded the general off the
front page.''
</P>
<P>
   Chestatee Publications, Anne Amerson's company, published these
lovely books. You can reach her at 706-864-6589 or write Chestatee
Publications, 689 N. Chestatee St., Dahlonega, GA 30533.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
