<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tri-fold, bi-fold or money clip: Chic wallets hold it all
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL AUGUST 30: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   They are always functional, sometimes fashionable but mostly
they're out of sight.
</P>
<P>
   Today's sleek, streamlined wallets are small enough to slip
neatly into a pocket, yet large enough to do double-duty as a
stylish evening clutch.
</P>
<P>
   Women make the majority of wallet purchases, according to
retailers and manufacturers. Fifty percent of the wallet purchases
in the United States are made by women for women; women also make
70 percent of the wallet purchases for men.
</P>
<P>
   Curt Ratledge, of Norcross, has received plenty of wallets
during his 70 years, but still favors his 20-year-old,
barely-there, brown pocket secretary, which he enjoys pulling out
to the amusement of store clerks.
</P>
<P>
   Dunwoody investment banking partner Richard Lawry, of EGL
Holdings Inc., carries two 10-year-old black wallets _ one in his
jacket pocket for non-essentials and one in his back pocket for
credit cards, a driver's license and money.
</P>
<P>
   Wallet turnover for women occurs more frequently. Aida Flamm, of
Atlanta, has several and changes them, depending on which handbag
she carries. Her current favorite is a thin green alligator skin
that holds four credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   Wallets made of fabric are this season's trend for women.
Water-resistant nylon or polyester microfiber offer a cutting-edge
look, especially in black, chocolate brown or red. Microfiber
wallets fall into the $28-$40 range.
</P>
<P>
   Other popular choices are crochets, denim and embossed faux
alligator looks. Leather, both textured and smooth, continues to be
the mainstay for wallet makers in classic brown, burgundy and tan,
as well as black, the number one color for men's and women's
wallets. Leather can go for $60-$120 or more; and if you prefer
exotic skins, look for prices starting at $250.
</P>
<P>
   Favorite wallet styles for women are the tri-fold clutch, the
zip-around with an accordion-style interior and the 7-inch rec-
</P>
<P>
   tangular wallet/checkbook combo.
</P>
<P>
   Popular fashion choices are anything from Coach, Fossil and 9
West. In designer wallets, Fendi, Chanel, Prada and Gucci get the
nod. Some can go for $500 for a leather clutch.
</P>
<P>
   Men won't be left holding an empty bag when it comes to stylish
choices, either.
</P>
<P>
   The bi-fold is popular because it's roomy enough for credit
cards and paper money and has a removable plastic picture insert;
the tri-fold holds credit cards, bills, has a removable picture
holder and even a compartment for keys.
</P>
<P>
   There's good news for men who like to travel light _ the money
clip wallet is your best bet and prices start at $18. This thin
design boasts a clip for paper money with a small credit card/bill
holder attached.
</P>
<P>
   The average life span of a leather wallet is anywhere from three
to five years, but some men have difficulty letting go.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Bosca, vice-president and design director of the Hugo
Bosca company, theorizes that it's sentimentality that causes men
to carry on with their wallets long past their average life span.
</P>
<P>
   He also said some men simply might not care what their wallets
look like because it's not a part of their outerwear.
</P>
<P>
   Lawry has a simpler explanation: ``You know where everything is
in an old wallet.''
</P>
<P>
   TAKING CHARGE OF YOUR WALLET
</P>
<P>
   To keep your wallet from taking over your pocket or handbag,
Margaret Hughes, a member of the Georgia chapter of the National
Association of Professional Organizers, has these streamlining
tips:
</P>
<P>
   -- Have an annual wallet cleaning on your birthday. Throw out
old receipts, expired coupons, out-of-date IDs.
</P>
<P>
   -- Simply carry the essentials. Your wallet is not a photo album
of your life nor is it a file cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   -- If you do have a checkbook in your wallet, make sure you can
close it.
</P>
<P>
   -- Keep your folding money in an orderly fashion: from small to
large bills all facing in the same direction.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
