<SLUG> BC-TV-BENBEN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Benben back on T.V. with his own show
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The new fall TV season has a number of stars from past series
who are starting over with new characters and shows. This week, we
look at five of them.
</P>
<P>
   -- Who: Brian Benben
</P>
<P>
   -- Best known as: Martin Tupper, book editor on HBO's ``Dream
On'' who was put down by everyone he encountered, yet somehow
managed to bed a beautiful woman every week (being on HBO may have
had something to do with it).
</P>
<P>
   -- Next known as: Brian Benben, local TV news anchor (demoted to
reporter) on ``The Brian Benben Show.'' (Debuts Sept. 21 on CBS.)
He's using his own name, but not playing himself.
</P>
<P>
   -- Dramatic stretch: Once again, he's put down by everyone he
encounters. He has a lot less sex though, now that he's on CBS
instead of HBO. ``I'd be hard out to describe the differences,'' he
says. ``I'm not wearing a fez and caftan.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Between shows: He and his wife, actress Madeline Stowe, spent
a lot of time on their ranch near Fredericksburg, Texas, and had a
daughter, May, now 2. Made a sitcom pilot for CBS that didn't get
picked up.
</P>
<P>
   -- Behind the scenes: Benben and producer Robert Borden
considered different titles, including ``Benben'' and ``The Benben
Show.'' ``People thought it was a children's clown show,'' says
Benben. ``I'm not kidding. You know, eight people get out of the
little car and the last person is Brian Benben.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Looking back: ``I started out doing the theater in New York,
and I never did comedies. I only did dramas, and I was always
playing the biggest scum you'd ever seen _ the nasty guy. You move
the bureau that hasn't been moved in 20 years and the thing that
crawls out _ that's what I played.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Why he's back: ``When you spend three years not working,
you've got to come up with the cash.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Coming Friday: Christina Applegate
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
