A3466 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-HOLLERIN-ONLINE-N     08-26 0544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-HOLLERIN-ONLINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C.)  
 VIRTUAL VIRTUOSOS OF THE HOLLER 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (bl)  
 By TINA KELLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Internet is not just a place for crass commercialism, vapid
flirtation and the homogenization of American life. It is a
timeless storehouse of priceless, rare, indigenous oral tradition.
Honest. If you don't believe it, head on over to
sunsite.unc.edu/hollerin/hollerin.htm and get a load of grown folks
hollerin' their hearts out. It's a hoot.
</P>
<P>
   Don't try this at work. The vocal samples, all in streaming
(more like screaming) Real Audio, sound like Tarzan's first
yodeling lessons or a cross between an apoplectic elephant and a
submerging submarine. But they're virtuosic, the brightest and best
of the National Hollerin' Contest, held each June in Spivey's
Corner, a hamlet in North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Web site, hollering is thought to be one of the
earliest forms of human communication and falls into four
categories: functional, communicative, pleasure and distress, with
the last known for its ``falsetto and a sense of urgency,'' though
nearly all hollering might be said to fit that description.
Folklore researchers have found hollering to be most prevalent in
black communities of the Southeast, though on this site and in
Sampson County, N.C., home of the competition, most hollerers are
white.
</P>
<P>
   The art form's roots reach back to the 1700s, the site says,
when men transporting logs by river from Sampson County developed a
system of hollers to avoid bashing into one another and to call for
help if they ran aground. Hollers can be heard up to three miles
away and were used on isolated farms to find lost children and
summon help in case of house fires. A skilled hollerer could call
in his or her hogs, cattle, sheep, dogs, children or spouse, and
the art was particularly handy for separating animals grazing on
common land.
</P>
<P>
   The contest began in 1969 with the help of Ermon Godwin, 70,
whose grandfather Bud Godwin ``was a hollerin' man'' and whose
9-year-old granddaughter appeared on David Letterman's show as the
junior hollerin' champion. He figures he can identify, just by
their hollers, all 30 contest champions. ``It has brought a sense
of feeling to our people here in Spivey's Corner, especially for
the young people,'' Godwin said. ``We have something unique to give
to the world, though we're just a little crossroads community of
49.''
</P>
<P>
   You can hear hollerin' quartet versions of ``Amazing Grace,''
``Old Gray Goose'' and ``The Lion Sleeps Tonight,'' as presented by
Suzie Bolotin, in audio and video, with arpeggios that could
challenge a violinist reared on Vivaldi.
</P>
<P>
   And where else can you hear the North Carolina Agriculture
Commissioner Jim Graham do a hollering impression of a mule, with
high, eerie overtones and alarming similitude?
</P>
<P>
   The Web site is a project of Paul Jones' class in
cyberpublishing and cybercasting at the University of North
Carolina School of Journalism. His students were surprised when
they taped Ms. Bolleton. ``They thought they were going to get 15
seconds and they got 3 minutes 50 seconds,'' he said, not to
mention having a hollerin' champion who is a Klezmer singer who won
with a Zulu song.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
