<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-FLOODS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH TEXAS MATRIARCH SURVIVES FLOODING ORDEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARRY SHLACHTER 
c.1997 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEL RIO, Texas _ When three generations of Calderons fled the
rising waters of San Felipe Creek here this week, Leonara Calderon,
a stubborn octogenarian who uses a walker due to old age and
Parkinson's disease, refused to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, we've had these floods before,'' one of her sons, Pat
Calderon, 56, recalled the 82-year-old saying not long before
spending several harrowing hours floating on a couch near the
ceiling of her living room.
</P>
<P>
   The Calderons live in similar stone houses along Calderon Lane,
which was quickly flooded early Monday when 18 inches of rain sent
nearby San Felipe Creek out of its banks.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Calderon made it through waist-deep water and was supposed
to return with a truck to get Grandma Calderon, but couldn't get
back because of the high water.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Calderon said on Tuesday, ``I put my mother on the bed, but
the water kept coming up _ coming up and coming up. I grabbed hold
of the mattress and dragged it into the living room and shifted her
over to the love seat, which gradually began floating.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept holding onto the love seat so it wouldn't topple
over,'' he said. ``The water was up to my chest, then my neck.
Luckily the TV fell over and I climbed on top.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like that scene in the `Titanic' with the girl holding
the boy up,'' said Calderon, a fifth-grade teacher. ``I kept
holding on as the water rose higher for five hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one point, with the water about 7 feet high, my mother
asked, ```Mi hijo (my son), what are the ceiling fans doing here?'
She couldn't quite grasp what was happening, which was good. She
was very calm, didn't at all panic.''
</P>
<P>
   Somehow word spread that Leonora Calderon was trapped.
</P>
<P>
   With rumor confounding rumor, a local radio station and an Eagle
Pass TV station both prematurely reported the matriarch's demise,
even though her son's heroics had helped her survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still getting condolence calls,'' Pat Calderon said
Tuesday as he salvaged photographs and other family mementos from
the house, where a love seat rested incongruously atop a bar
counter.
</P>
<P>
   As for his mother, she's doing well under the circumstances, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This morning I found her staring off into nothingness.
</P>
<P>
   ```Are you all right?' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``She snapped out of it and smiled at me.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Grandma was safe, the Calderons estimated they lost
$250,000 to the flood.
</P>
<P>
   An uncle's Lincoln rested on a customer's Chevy pickup at the
family-run auto parts and body shop around the corner. Each of
their houses had 3 inches of mud on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   And Billy Calderon lost 220,000 baseball cards he had been
collecting with his sons for 11 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my Griffeys. That hurt. Just gone. All gone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
