<HEADER>
A3471 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CATALINA-CHICHI-LADN     08-26 1318
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATALINA-CHICHI-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAMBO MAMA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENIFER HANRAHAN 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Her name was Chi Chi. She was a showgirl.
</P>
<P>
   But that was 30 years ago, when they used to have a show.
</P>
<P>
   When Clarita Fazzari danced the mambo, her silky brown
undulating body made men's faces burn and reminded women to watch
their men. Some say she shook so vigorously in a fringed bikini top
and sarong, she looked like a waterfall.
</P>
<P>
   They called her Chi Chi, the Cuban Fireball. On summer evenings,
Hollywood stars, yachtsmen and their dates lined up to see her
perform.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, disc jockeys have replaced live bands, and Fazzari,
who's from a generation of female entertainers who would sooner
reveal her age than forgo the limelight forever, is mostly retired,
splitting her time between homes in Las Vegas and Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   But her son, Valentino Fazzari, who grew up in the nightclubs
where his mother entertained, is banking that she can still draw a
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Clarita ``Chi Chi'' Fazzari will dance the mambo at the second
Festival Catalina on Saturday afternoon at the Wrigley Stage in
Avalon. Other acts will include bands playing musica romantica,
ranchera, rock en espanol, and mariachi; a local children's
folklorico dance troupe; and the Pete Escovedo Orchestra with
Sheila E.
</P>
<P>
   While Catalina hosts more than 50 special events every year,
with themes varying from blues to country music jams, Festival
Catalina is the only event _ other than a Cinco de Mayo festivity
for schoolchildren _ that celebrates the cultural heritage of the
island's large population of Latinos, about 40 percent of its 3,500
residents.
</P>
<P>
   Valentino Fazzari, 37, of Studio City promotes Latin
entertainers and organized the festival to honor his mother and
Catalina's Latino community. The festival is free to the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Latin heritage on the island is so flavorful and so
strong, it's ridiculous there wasn't an event that gives these
people an opportunity ... to celebrate the heritage they rightfully
believe in,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The way Clarita Fazzari recalls it, the Santa Catalina Island of
the 1950s and '60s was a glamorous outpost, only 26 miles from Los
Angeles but seemingly closer to a tropical paradise.
</P>
<P>
   When the S.S. Catalina steamship pulled into town, it carried
more than 2,000 passengers who, while waiting to disembark, threw
coins into the water and cheered as local youths dove for them.
</P>
<P>
   Strolling mariachis serenaded couples on Crescent Avenue, a road
that runs along the bay where boat lights shimmered.
</P>
<P>
   Fazzari, who is of Scotch Irish, Cherokee, Chinese and
Afro-Cuban descent, had no formal dance training, instead learning
the mambo in the parks of Cuba that came alive on Sundays with men
banging drums and bottles and mambo dancers swirling seductively.
</P>
<P>
   ``You didn't need a partner,'' she said. ``You just got out
there and danced. Like Americans go jogging, Cubans danced.''
</P>
<P>
   Her father, a Marine Corps master sergeant, loved the night
life. He was stationed in San Francisco and often took his daughter
out with him.
</P>
<P>
   One night, he gave her permission to compete in a dancing
contest. She won and was soon booked in clubs up and down the West
Coast and, later, Havana. She married an Army enlisted man she met
while entertaining at a military base. And in 1955, she moved to
Catalina so she could work at the Chi Chi Club. Her husband stayed
in San Francisco, where he ran a chain of furniture stores.
</P>
<P>
   With her bare legs, tanned belly and high heels, her act was
considered risque.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was Elvis Presley's time, when they wouldn't show him
from the waist down,'' she said. ``I was bad because I shook. But
it drew them in because they wanted to see what I was doing.''
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of the Chi Chi Club's bamboo and burlap decor
was a painting of a topless Tahitian woman in a sarong, with her
hands on her hips and a hibiscus tucked behind one ear. One night a
customer came in, took one look at Clarita Fazzari and asked if she
was the woman in the painting.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Taylor, a former longtime mayor of Avalon and owner of the
club, told the customer ``yes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I came home and I was hysterical crying,'' she said. ``To be
known with no top on was a disgrace.''
</P>
<P>
   But the name stuck. Soon many of the customers called her Chi
Chi, and in time she became proud of her stage name.
</P>
<P>
   While his mother entertained, Valentino Fazzari would sleep in
the dressing room. As a young boy, he'd sneak downstairs and hide
under the booths.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being on the side of the stage before she went on, I was just
mesmerized by her beauty,'' he recalled. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Clarita Fazzari brims with stories from the old days.
</P>
<P>
   An underage William Wrigley Jr., heir to his father's
chewing-gum fortune that included ownership of Catalina Island,
sneaking into the club.
</P>
<P>
   Her ``close friend'' Marlon Brando sending a helicopter to pick
her up and take her to the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   John Wayne sauntering down Crescent Avenue, doling out coins to
the kids who chased after him.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Taylor choosing her as the first Miss Catalina. She became
a one-woman welcoming committee who'd prance around in a bikini,
holding hands with her two sons and her pet gibbon ape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved Catalina,'' Clarita Fazzari said. ``I thought it was
my island. I didn't think it belonged to the Wrigleys. I got that
island fever.''
</P>
<P>
   But by 1968, when the Fazzaris bought the club from Mayor
Taylor, times were already beginning to change. Competition from
Los Angeles strip clubs was making it hard to keep the Chi Chi Club
afloat.
</P>
<P>
   The following year, the Chi Chi Club burned.
</P>
<P>
   In their pajamas, Clarita Fazzari and her sons ran to watch the
flames consume the bamboo siding. They rebuilt, this time forgoing
bamboo for safer stucco.
</P>
<P>
   As the '70s wore on, lower-cost air fares allowed Angelenos to
travel to more distant getaways. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; In a last attempt at reviving it, she converted the Chi Chi
Club to a topless bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``It caused an uproar,'' she remembered. ``The people in the
town didn't want it, but the place was packed. We put a sign
outside: `If it should offend you, don't come in'.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, she sold the club and left the island in a futile
attempt to try to save her failing marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not the same,'' she said. ``The magic was gone. The
spell was gone that was over me.''
</P>
<P>
   But, in some ways, Clarita Fazzari never has left the island or
her club. The fire may have destroyed the painting of the topless
Tahitian woman from which Fazzari derived her nickname, but before
she left Catalina, Fazzari posed for a photograph to re-create the
image.
</P>
<P>
   Her visage still adorns Chi Chi Club T-shirts today, worn by
club bartenders and tourists alike.
</P>
<P>
   Even at her age, Fazzari's quest for the limelight has not
dimmed. She ran for president in 1988 as a write-in candidate and
spent six months as a volunteer in the Israeli army in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   And now her son is taking up the cause of restoring to the
island some of the glamour of Chi Chi's days. Last October, he
revived the Miss Catalina beauty pageant, a competition where
contestants wore evening gowns and retro-style, Esther
Williams-designed swimsuits with gardenias in their hair.
</P>
<P>
   Julien Foreman, public relations manager for the Catalina Island
Visitors Bureau and Chamber of Commerce, said events such as
Festival Catalina are important in a place where tourism is the
main industry.
</P>
<P>
   And some residents expressed hope that the festival would help
teach Latino children about their heritage.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the kids here are second-, third- and
fourth-generation Latinos,'' said Lourdes Thoricht, who teaches
folklorico to the high school students scheduled to perform at the
festival. ``For them it's a big part of their heritage that they
might not know otherwise.''
</P>
</TEXT>
