<HEADER>
A3500 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-Q&AMP;A-NYT &LR;      08-26 0266
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MESSAGES THAT POP 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I need an Internet provider that offers POP3 capabilities.
How can I find one?
</P>
<P>
   A. For those who need a little background: POP stands for Post
Office Protocol, a method that e-mail applications use to download
messages to the computer from e-mail servers on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Once the message gets to the e-mail server, the user can dial in
to his or her Internet service provider and download the message. A
POP3 server, if you've ever wondered about the term (you may have
seen it in your e-mail program's settings box or as an occasional
flash on-screen as the program checks your mail) is where incoming
e-mail sits until you log on to download it. In addition to the
popular POP3, there is IMAP, the Internet Message Access Protocol.
</P>
<P>
   With the right settings and e-mail program, POP3 is useful for
people who want or need to retrieve their messages from any
computer that has Internet access, although the IMAP standard is
often considered better at handling mail from different
workstations.
</P>
<P>
   Some online services use their own proprietary software, so call
the prospective company's tech-support line and ask whether it uses
POP3. If you already have online access, explore the support area
of your provider's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
postal mail to:
</P>
<P>
   Questions
</P>
<P>
   Circuits
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times
</P>
<P>
   229 W. 43rd St.
</P>
<P>
   New York, N.Y. 10036-3959
</P>
<P>
   or by e-mail to
</P>
