<HEADER>
A3574 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-TENNIS-ONLINE-ART     08-26 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-TENNIS-ONLINE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS U.S. OPEN NEARS, IT'S EVERYTHING TENNIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By VERNE G. KOPYTOFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The world's top tennis players will not be the only ones
sweating, lunging and sprinting when the U.S. Open championships
start Monday in Queens, New York City. Thousands of the nation's
computers will be doing the electronic equivalent, as their owners
put them through their paces in the name of tennis enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   The two weeks of the U.S. Open are among the busiest times for
many of the hundreds of tennis-oriented Web sites on the Internet.
Not only do people want to know such details as how easily Martina
Hingis squashed an opponent on a given day, but they also are
inspired to learn how to improve their own wristy forehand and
speed up their lazy feet.
</P>
<P>
   According to IBM, which creates the official Web pages for all
four of the major tennis championships (the Australian Open, the
French Open, Wimbledon and the U.S. Open), the U.S. Open site
usually gets the most traffic. Last year, the site measured 63.7
million hits, according to Jeff Ramminger, who lead the design of
the U.S. Open site.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those hits come from tennis enthusiasts like Cheryl
Hand, a nurse from Birmingham, Ala., who browses the Internet, not
just during the big tournaments but nearly every day. In fact, she
spends more time reading online tennis magazines and checking
results on the professional tours than she does on the court
improving her own game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like the other day, I was watching Pete Sampras play on
television and I saw him lose because of a bad line call on match
point,'' Ms. Hand said. ``I looked on the Internet to see what he
said about the call afterward because he was a little vocal about
it on the court.'' Indeed, Ms. Hand eventually logged onto the
official Pete Sampras Web site and sent an e-mail expressing her
sympathy about what she saw as poor officiating.
</P>
<P>
   ``That call just really upset me, so I felt that I had to give
my 2 cents,'' Ms. Hand said. She has yet to get a response from
Sampras, nor does she expect to get one.
</P>
<P>
   One of the easiest ways to find information about the game is to
go to a site like Yahoo (www.yahoo.com) and click on its recreation
and sports subject heading. Browsing among the offerings opens a
window into the diversity of the Web's tennis subculture.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors can experience tradition at the Wimbledon Championships
site (www.wimbledon.org), community at the Gay and Lesbian Tennis
Alliance (www.glta.org), and levity at Alt.Tennis, an instructional
site that promises ``explicit, uncensored, alternative ways to play
tennis'' (www.alttennis.com), which includes between-the-legs shots
and faking out your opponent.
</P>
<P>
   And visitors can see for themselves how tennis on the Web,
perhaps like no other sport, is driven as much by Hollywood-style
glamour as by talent. For example, Anna Kournikova, a teen-aged
Russian tour player who has never won a professional championship
but still draws considerable attention with her starlet looks and
midriff-baring outfits, is listed as the subject of more than 20
sites on Yahoo.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Jana Novotna, of the Czech Republic, this year's
winner of the Wimbledon women's title, perhaps the most prestigious
in the game, has just four Yahoo-listed sites to her name.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many of the general tennis bulletin boards on the Web
appear to be filled with postings about personalities: which pro is
better, more polite, more attractive. However, discourse on the
specialized sites is typically more elevated, particularly when it
comes to asking questions about the quality of equipment.
</P>
<P>
   One feature that some may find especially advantageous about the
Web is the multitude of tennis equipment for sale on line often at
cheaper prices than those in sporting goods stores. With locations
like www.tennis-warehouse.com and their vast stocks of equipment, a
tennis enthusiast may never have to step into a pro shop again.
</P>
<P>
   A Site That Is Much Like The Open
</P>
<P>
   WWW.USOPEN.ORG
</P>
<P>
   Given the festive atmosphere, loquacious crowds and proximity to
Manhattan, the U.S. Open has a reputation as one of the most flashy
of the major tennis championships. So it follows that the
tournament's official Web site is the cyberspace equivalent of
Andre Agassi.
</P>
<P>
   If the goal is to provide what television coverage cannot, then
the site is successful. No other Internet outlet appears to be as
authoritative on the Open nor, for that matter, as whimsical.
</P>
<P>
   In the Interactive Open area, the Netcam shows visitors images
of matches that are updated every 30 seconds. Or they can absorb
some of the championship's atmosphere with an option called
Opencam, which gives computer users the chance to direct stadium
cameras themselves. For those seeking information rather than
amusement, the site offers ample choices, from daily news stories
to point-by-point updates of match scores.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the U.S. Open site is practical, with directions to the
tournament by subway, train and car, a schedule of television
broadcasts and ticket information. A section is devoted to the
biographies of hundreds of players, from reigning champions to
obscure qualifiers (ever wonder how much money Massimo Ardinghi, of
Italy, has won in his career?). To pick the brain of a top player,
visitors to the site can join one of many online discussions with
top competitors that are scheduled throughout the two-week
championship.
</P>
<P>
   Though these chats may be popular, it remains to be seen whether
players will have anything more elucidating to say via keyboard
than in the typical television interview. For even more personal
communication, there are electronic post cards _ an e-mail window
with a tennis-theme background _ that can be sent to competitors.
Whether the players respond, of course, is up to them.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Advice for Playing Better Plus Lots of Gear and Gab
</P>
<P>
   WWW.TENNIS.COM
</P>
<P>
   Watching or reading about tennis professionals chasing a ball
from one side of the court to the other can certainly be
entertaining, but it provides a limited view of the sport. Among
the Web sites offering a more complete version is the one created
by Tennis Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The site devotes considerable coverage to teaching average
players how to improve their tennis strokes, strategy and fitness.
Of course, there is no guarantee that incorporating such advice
into one's game is easier when gleaned from the Internet than from
a magazine, book or a live tennis lesson.
</P>
<P>
   Like Tennis Magazine, the Web site rates the quality of new
racquets and shoes. But readers of the electronic magazine can
offer their own evaluations and ask questions about equipment in a
chat room dubbed ``gear gab,'' found in the ``bbs central''
section.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, this free site has many other features not found in the
monthly magazine, which requires a paid subscription. Among them
are daily updates from the pro tours, weekly rankings,
instructional tips and more chat areas.
</P>
<P>
   (Many of the postings seemed to be the work of adolescent minds,
given the number of expletives and exhortations of ``Sampras
rules.'')
</P>
<P>
   Tennis.com is planning extensive coverage of the U.S. Open, with
photographs and daily stories about matches and the ambiance.
Visitors to the site can also get TV broadcast times, ticket
information and match schedules.
</P>
<P>
   This site is probably the slickest and most mass-market oriented
of all the tennis magazines on the Web. For people with time to
browse only one publication, it is a good choice.
</P>
<P>
   Focusing on Fundamentals
</P>
<P>
   WWW.TENNISSERVER.COM
</P>
<P>
   If there is an equivalent of the neighborhood tennis club
newsletter on the Internet, the Tennis Server could be it. The site
has little in the way of impressive graphics and video clips, but
it does feature extensive coverage about the fundamentals of the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Names like Michael Chang and Venus Williams are only
occasionally mentioned here. Instead, the site focuses on what is
relevant to weekend-playing amateurs, with columns about mental
toughness (the writer has a Ph.D. in psychology), improving strokes
and fitness.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the writing is in the form of personal experience as if
it were being offered by the local club pro. The quality of advice
appears to be good and often unique, at least to someone who has
taken a few hundred tennis lessons during his lifetime. There is
also a guest column that seems to deal with whatever is on the mind
of that month's author. A writer in a recent issue, for example,
told a story about how his tickets to the U.S. Open were stolen by
a pickpocket.
</P>
<P>
   Even a novice player who can barely hit a forehand will probably
feel comfortable here. Information is available on such basics as
the rules governing tennis, tennis clubs and organizations around
the country, and how to store tennis racquets.
</P>
<P>
   Two often neglected groups that this site serves are junior and
senior players. There is a column that takes turns addressing these
two groups: one month, how to better develop junior talent; the
next month, protecting yourself from skin cancer while on the
court.
</P>
<P>
   Helpful in Finding Matches, On Court and Perhaps Off
</P>
<P>
   WWW.TENNISW.COM
</P>
<P>
   It may be comforting to know that there are tennis matches
waiting for you in such far-flung places as Ecuador and Qatar. Or
that James, a Yale student, is looking for a single,
career-oriented woman as a tennis partner ``and possibly more.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennis Worldwide Magazine, an all-purpose Web publication about
tennis, has a particularly personal and somewhat eclectic touch.
The site features conveniently categorized classified sections for
those seeking everything that is tennis related. Among them,
playing partners (and, apparently, a mate), ``certified officials''
who will answer readers' e-mail questions about regulations, and a
section devoted to jokes (``What's the noisiest of all games?
Tennis, because you can't play without raising a racket'').
</P>
<P>
   One especially useful tool here is the Tennis Mall, which links
readers to tennis equipment manufacturers, resorts and tennis
academies. Also interesting are the seven chat rooms with such
titles as ``antiques and collectibles forum,'' ``instructor's and
coach's forum,'' and ``junior tennis forum.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the ample opportunities for conversation, the site offers
minimal coverage of breaking news from the professional tours. The
two or three feature articles that are added to the site each month
often address broad er issues like ``Is Tennis Dead Again?'' and
``U.S.A. Player Devel opment.'' This site would probably appeal
most to regular tennis play ers because of its insider approach.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-26-98 1656EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
