<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980826.0291 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3582 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEWEY-NICKS-FUN-800(2     08-26 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEWEY-NICKS-FUN-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT HOME WITH DEWEY NICKS: ADVENTURES IN THE STAR-STRUCK ZONE  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By AMY M. SPINDLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Dewey Nicks' ebullient fashion photography reminds
you that people have forgotten how to have fun in fashion. Dewey
and Stephanie Nicks' ebullient lifestyle reminds you that people
have forgotten how to have fun  &UR; in life. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Take, for example, the night Frank Sinatra died. The rest of the
country might have popped ``Songs for Swinging Lovers'' on the CD ;
and Mrs. Nicks and their gang headed out to relive Rat Pack
Hollywood. Which meant hitting Matteo's, the Italian restaurant
Sinatra loved _ but perhaps not for its food; Don Rickles, a
regular, might joke that you need to put the tray tables up when
you finish.Then they went to Merv Griffin's new place, The Coconut
Club, at the Beverly Hilton, for some big band dancing. In true Rat
Pack style, they were kicked out.
</P>
<P>
   But the Sinatra tribute didn't stop there, because after that,
they went home, to a living room straight out of ``Ocean's
Eleven,'' the 1960 Rat Pack movie where the men try to rob five Las
Vegas casinos simultaneously _ and where the women are asked to
leave the room with two snaps of the finger and the explanation,
``No chicks.''
</P>
<P>
   The house, on Stone Canyon Road, is convincing enough as a
period set that the photographer Matthew Ralston considered renting
it to recreate scenes from ``The Thomas Crown Affair'' (1968) for a
Madonna video. And Nicks, whose snapshot-style fashion photos are
the champagne antidote to the heroin chic images that depressed
fashion for so long, often uses the house as his backdrop.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when even Hollywood, city of dreams, is in danger of
becoming as homogenized as every other Star-Gap-Republic-infested
town, Nicks and his pack, which isn't ratty but does revere the
rats, have made it their mission to celebrate, maximally, what sets
Hollywood apart. Need a car? Why not get the Lifestyle Car Clubto
soup up a 1996 Buick Roadmaster station wagon? (``You're not sure
if it's a hearse or a limo,'' Nicks said of the result.) Throwing a
pool party? Why not hire a team of synchronized swimmers to
entertain and have it catered by Chasen's.? And when you want to
get a house, why not get two? A monastic concrete cottage by Irving
Gill, the father of California minimalism, built in 1917, to use
for an office. And a 1950's one that reflects the ultimate
living-by-the-pool life in Los Angeles, the kind of life Frank and
the boys took with them to the Palm Springs desert.
</P>
<P>
   When Nicks met his wife to be nine years ago, she was producing
photo shoots for Spiegel catalogs and living on the 61st floor of
the John Hancock building in Chicago; he was living in the Gill
house , and creating upbeat, funny photography for Vogue's
charismatic fashion editors, Elizabeth Saltzman and Lisa Eisner. It
was Ms. Eisner who introduced him to Roy McMakin, a furniture
designer who designed the office furniture for the new Getty
Museum. Back then, McMakin was living in the Gill house while
lovingly restoring Irving Gill's trademark arches and composed
courtyards. Gill, a protege of Louis Sullivan, died in 1936,
unheralded, to be rediscovered in the 1960s. His houses recalled
California's Hispanic past; their Cubist-inspired geometry and
Mission symmetry anticipated European modernism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I drove up the driveway, walked in, and said, `I want to buy
this house,' Nicks recalled. ``It was the first thing I said to
him.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Brad Dunning, now one of Los Angeles' hottest
interior designers, was working on the Gill house. He and Nicks
shared a lifelong passion for architecture and the designer began
helping Nicks find Palm SPrings locations for his work. Nicks was
among the first fashion photographers to gravitate to the resort
town. The light was so perfect, the lines of the architecture so
clean, Nicks said that ``Shooting there taught me how to shoot in a
studio.'' It was the whole look of the place that inspired him: the
car ports, the matching Rolls Royces in the driveway, the pristine
golf courses that dictate entire neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then you meet the people, who happen to be 60 years old, and
they're all about fitness and tan skin and wearing special jewelry
and a particular color pants,'' Nicks said. ``And I thought, this
is cool. This is what my friends should be like, but they're all
worried about being called back for an audition. There was an ease
of life I was really attracted to.''
</P>
<P>
   Working on photo assignments with Dunning, Nicks would often
create elaborate modernist sets; then, when the shoot was over,
he'd destroy them. When they found the Stone Canyon house, it
became a set they could keep. Sold as a tear-down, the house had
been built in 1959 with every shoddy construction practice of the
day. Beneath the suburban facade, they saw a desert home.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of carpet,'' Nicks said. ``And it had a giant
bell for the telephone, so the last owner was obviously was an old
woman. The phone would ring, and it was like school was out.''
</P>
<P>
   Like all L.A. homes, it has a Hollyweird pedigree. Richard
Harris lived there, as did Maud Adams, the onetime James Bond girl.
The minute Nicks walked into the house, he saw it exactly as it
looks now. ``I knew it was going to work,'' he said. He hired
Dunning, and Finn Kappe, the architect, whose father, Raymond
Kappe, was a founder of the Southern California Institute of
Architecture. Although the house has no pedigree, Dunning called it
``trickle-down Neutra and Craig Ellwood,'' combining Richard
Neutra'sfree-flowing plans and industrial materials and Ellwood's
love of the glass box. ``It was a tract house with aspirations of
glamour.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Two Moroccan-style lighting fixtures were all they kept of the
original interior. The proportions of the house were blown up,
almost like an effect from a darkroom: the pool was widened, the
doorways were heightened and broadened, the front courtyard was
opened up to give a view to the hillside behind the house and the
kitchen cabinets were raised. Terrazzo tile was laid throughout the
house, ending only when the terrazzo tumbles into the pool. ``I was
always inspired by the movie ``The Party'' with Peter Sellers,
where the water went through the house,'' Nicks said. Part of the
decision to put tiny chrome legs beneath the new cabinets was to
give the terrazzo a volcanic-lava quality, to suggest that it had
spilled right through the house.
</P>
<P>
   Like a true student of the Rat Pack, Nicks has made High
Fidelity a theme at the house. An early 1970s Mark Levinson sound
system was put together by the actor Vincent Gallo, who's an
audiophile and who Nicks met when he shot him for L'Uomo Vogue. A
speaker was put in the pool, for a surreal surround-sound while
swimming.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the furnishings came from Palm Springs consignment
shops, including a painting of a bull once owned by George
Montgomery, the B-movie actor and artist. It hung over the
fireplace in the house he shared with Dinah Shore.``He's a great
taste hero of mine,'' Nicks said. An exhibit of Montgomery's work
in Palm Springs has, he said, ``a bronze, a bronze, a bronze and a
note from Reagan saying, `Thanks for the bronze.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Eisner says that when things get too serious at the house,
Nicks will say ``This needs a granny touch here'' and throw in
something that doesn't belong. ``That's been our whole thing with
Brad,'' Nicks said. ``He has a great sense of humor, and it's not
some church.''
</P>
<P>
   But owning the Gill house is a bit more of a responsibility.
McMakin had treated the Gill house with reverence. The quirky
Craftsman furniture he made for it was still there. McMakin's
restoration brought back the stucco and cement walls, as well as
one of Gill's trademark archways, which had been removed and stored
at the back of the house. He even restored the first layer of paint
on the porch, light blue, to create the illusion that the broiling
Hollywood sun was throwing cooling shadows on the tilt slab
construction walls. With its many angles, ``you could have 20
people in that house and never even know it,'' Nicks said. Design
elements that at first might seem decorative, like curved walls,
are functional: dust doesn't stick in the corner. Six doors in the
hallway close to create a private phone room. But the house is
never really fully restored: It needs constant upkeep, as the
cement cracks and the stucco bubbles. ``It's like the Golden Gate
Bridge,'' Dunning said.
</P>
<P>
   This house, which transcends trends, is the serious side of the
Nickses, the side that led to their making their first documentary,
``Hell House,'' which is about a Fundentalist morality play acted
out in a religious house of horrors, with Satan as a tour guide.
They are submitting it for consideration to Sundance.
</P>
<P>
   For fun, they always have Stone Canyon. ``I used to say all the
time on shoots, `Let's find a house that, like, the groovy
grandparents own and the kids got the keys for the weekend,'''
Nicks said. ``They bring all their friends. And it has things like
old record players, and records. A bar. A big giant living-room
table you can put 20 people around.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple throw parties, like Nelson Riddle orchestra night, so
friends don't have to meet in restaurants, the L.A. social curse.
``Stephanie and I wake up and take a swim in the pool at seven in
the morning, and say, how lucky are we to be living in this
house,'' he said. ``I worked hard, and I'm glad I was able to make
that happen, but I don't really think I deserve that lifestyle.
That's reserved for Dean Martin _ and Matt Helm. Matt Helm wakes up
in the morning and takes a swim, not me. I'm from St. Louis, man, I
don't know about that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-26-98 1658EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
