<DOCNO> NYT19980826.0293 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3600 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-ECONOMY-0827-C     08-26 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ECONOMY-0827-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SIGNS OF PANIC ON THE STREETS AS RUBLE TUMBLES OUT OF CONTROL
 &HT;    With JOURNAL-RUSSIA-$ADV27.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Anxious Russians camped outside commercial banks
seeking to withdraw their money Wednesday as the Central Bank
conceded it no longer could prevent a freefall of the ruble.
</P>
<P>
   The worst-case scenario for Russia's struggling post-Soviet
economy appeared to be unfolding in the most frantic day yet of the
financial and political crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Currency trading was suspended in Moscow just after it began
when the ruble fell five percent against the U.S. dollar, coming
after a nearly 10 percent drop on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   On the street, apprehension was verging on panic. Hundreds of
commercial banks and currency-exchange points closed after the
ruble plunge, sending alarmed Russians descending on banks in a
largely unsuccessful effort to withdraw their deposits or convert
their rubles to dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have $2,000 in this bank and I want to get as much out as I
can while I can. The doors have been locked for an hour, but I'll
sleep here if I must,'' said 35-year-old engineer Leonid Seleveyez,
who waited in a driving rain with about 100 other Russians outside
a branch of SBS-Agro Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Further steep slides seemed inevitable as the central bank,
dangerously low on hard-currency reserves, announced it could no
longer afford to protect the ruble.
</P>
<P>
   Trading was suspended on the Moscow Interbank Currency Exchange
(MICEX) with the ruble at 8.26 to the dollar, but on the street the
rate hit 10 rubles to the dollar and lower. The declines came after
Russia on Tuesday night announced a plan to restructure about $40
billion in Russian short-term domestic debt held by domestic and
foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the chaos, Prime Minister-designate Viktor Chernomyrdin is
struggling to form a new government after President Boris Yeltsin
sacked the entire cabinet on Sunday. The newspaper Izvestia called
Yeltsin's surprising move ``changing parachutes mid-jump.''
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin abruptly flew to Ukraine for meetings Wednesday
night with Michel Camdessus, managing director of the International
Monetary Fund (IMF), in an appeal for further assistance. The IMF
is scheduled to deliver a $4.3 billion installment of a $22.6
billion bailout package agreed to last month, however the aid is
tied to assurances by the previous Russian government under Sergei
Kiriyenko that it would pursue economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the White House said there were no plans to hold
emergency consultations with world leaders on aid to ease the
Russia crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no shortcuts in restoring market confidence, and the
next steps are up to the Russians,'' White House deputy spokesman
Barry Toiv told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Some leading Moscow financial analysts predicted the ruble, at
6.2 to the U.S. dollar just two weeks ago, could plummet to 15 to
the dollar by next month. In announcing a controlled devaluation on
Aug. 17, the central bank had said it would not allow the ruble to
dip below 9.5 to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   For Russians, further devaluation means their salaries and
pensions are worth less while prices on store shelves, particularly
for imported goods, continue to rise.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rate is changing so rapidly that we are at a loss. We
don't even know at what prices we should sell,'' said Inga
Shapoval, manager of a pet-supplies store in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   On the currency market, traders and banks looking to rid
themselves of rubles then began buying German marks after trading
for dollars was suspended. The ruble ended the day 41 percent lower
in value against the currency.
</P>
<P>
   Financial markets throughout Europe declined on the grim news
from Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's central bank appeared paralyzed by the developments
clearly beyond its control, choosing to pretend that Wednesday
never happened. It declared void all ruble-dollar trading that had
taken place.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, the bank announced that currency trading would
resume Thursday with the ruble rate set at 7.86 to the dollar, the
official rate at the end of trading on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But the rate meant little as it became apparent that Russia can
no longer manage the value of its currency.
</P>
<P>
   ``The central bank is not in adequate control of the situation
and does not see concrete ways out of the situation,'' said
Alexander Ivanishev, an investment analyst at Credit Anstaldt.
</P>
<P>
   The central bank said that it had spent $1.8 billion since Aug.
17 from its dwindling foreign currency and gold reserves to support
the ruble, making any further consequential intervention
impossible. Its reserves were $15.1 billion on August 14.
</P>
<P>
   After whirlwind profits in Russia since Yeltsin's reelection in
1996, some Western investors predicted the flight of foreign
companies from Russia if the consumer economy crashes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has the distinct feeling of a party at 4 a.m. after the
apartment has been trashed and the guests have left,'' said one
American investment analyst.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to win broader support from the opposition-led
parliament, Chernomyrdin has been holding talks with Communist
leaders on a possible coalition government. His ability to consider
including longtime Yeltsin foes in a new government was regarded by
analysts as a further sign that the ailing Yeltsin has ceded
unprecedented powers to Chernomyrdin.
</P>
<P>
   But the Kremlin dismissed rumors sweeping Moscow, U.S. and
European financial markets that Yeltsin might be forced to resign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The press service categorically denies this and declares that
it is stupid,'' said Alexei Gromov, deputy chief of the Kremlin
press service.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin remained secluded at his government estate outside
Moscow, reportedly consulting by telephone with Chernomyrdin about
his trip to the Crimea region of the Ukraine. In addition to
meeting with IMF officials, Chernomyrdin also talked with Leonid
Kuchma, the president of Ukraine, and Alexander Lukashenko, the
president of Belarus.
</P>
<P>
   There was no word on the outcome of his talks with Camdessus.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin's trip took officials at the foreign ministry by
surprise, and raised speculation that Chernomyrdin may be seeking a
closer political alliance with the hardliners running the two
former Soviet republics. One senior foreign ministry official
called the meeting ``some kind of real improvisation.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-26-98 1702EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980826.0294 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3606 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-ECONOMY-0827-C     08-26 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ECONOMY-0827-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
