</P>
<P>
   In an effort to win broader support from the opposition-led
parliament, Chernomyrdin has been holding talks with Communist
leaders on a possible coalition government. His ability to consider
including longtime Yeltsin foes in a new government was regarded by
analysts as a further sign that the ailing Yeltsin has ceded
unprecedented powers to Chernomyrdin.
</P>
<P>
   But the Kremlin dismissed rumors sweeping Moscow, U.S. and
European financial markets that Yeltsin might be forced to resign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The press service categorically denies this and declares that
it is stupid,'' said Alexei Gromov, deputy chief of the Kremlin
press service.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin remained secluded at his government estate outside
Moscow, reportedly consulting by telephone with Chernomyrdin about
his trip to the Crimea region of the Ukraine. In addition to
meeting with IMF officials, Chernomyrdin also talked with Leonid
Kuchma, the president of Ukraine, and Alexander Lukashenko, the
president of Belarus.
</P>
<P>
   There was no word on the outcome of his talks with Camdessus.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin's trip took officials at the foreign ministry by
surprise, and raised speculation that Chernomyrdin may be seeking a
closer political alliance with the hardliners running the two
former Soviet republics. One senior foreign ministry official
called the meeting ``some kind of real improvisation.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
