<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3608 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCIARC-STUDENTS-NYT &LR;      08-26 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIARC-STUDENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARCHITECTURE STUDENTS TAKE A SEAT, BUT FIRST THEY BUILD IT 
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By PHIL PATTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Back-to-school, the time of notebooks and protractors and sales
circulars, has become one of the basic seasons of American
marketing. Even adults decades out of the classroom can succumb to
the pitch; it evokes certain primal school-day sights and smells
and textures. At the Southern California Institute of Architecture
(SciArc), the once-renegade school whose influence has shaped the
look of design in Los Angeles, back-to-school means something
different. There, first-year students don't buy stuff; they build
their own desks.
</P>
<P>
   The process is not just a basic exercise in hands-on
construction and design but a ritual of initiation into the student
body and the philosophy of the school. Stripped-down and basic, at
one level, the desk is a model of a certain sort of design, like
the Levittown Cape Cod customized with a patio and trim, the
stripper Chevrolet fitted out with new wheels and an aerodynamic
package, the mail-order computer souped up with peripherals.
</P>
<P>
   Working from plans drawn by one of the school's first teachers,
the architect Robert Mangurian, the students assemble each
student's desk in teams. The modified assembly-line approach sets a
pattern for each student's relationship with his peers. In this and
other ways, the desk is a lesson in more than design. It is also
one in designing education.
</P>
<P>
   The desks end up jammed together in open rooms that are alive
with activity almost around the clock. As the school year goes on,
said Randall Wilson, the head of the school's wood shop where the
desks are built, students change them. ``The desk's framework can
be individualized and customized,'' he said, ``so it begins to
abstract over time in many wonderful ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Many students, Wilson added, enclose their space with fabric or
old doors so, he said, the desk takes on a shack-like quality, and
the big rooms full of desks in turn assume the look of a
shantytown. The students take their desks with them when they
graduate.
</P>
<P>
   The initiation project began as a kind of furniture design at
the most basic level. It was inspired, Wilson said, by Gerrit
Rietveld's De Stijl crate furniture. But it also reminded me of
Donald Judd's minimalist-sculpture-turned-furniture or even of the
inexpensive coffee tables found in the mall outlets of the This
Side Up chain.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of years ago, Wilson began experimenting with replacing
wood screws and white glue with a metal fastener called the Simpson
connector. SciArc ended up ordering so many connectors _ about 100
desks are built each year _ that a sales representative from the
Simpson Corporation flew out to see what was going on. This year,
the chipboard surface that tops the frame of 1-by-4's is to be
replaced by one made of a material derived from wheat straw: a
token of SciArc's emphasis on sustainable design, using renewable
resources.
</P>
<P>
   Building the desk ties new students to the history of the
school. It is a link to the school's radical origins, its birth in
a countercultural secession by students and faculty from California
State Polytechnic University, Pomona, in 1972. ``It was a social
experiment,'' said Michael Rotondi, the former director of SciArc
and a member of its first graduating class. The first buildings, in
Santa Monica, were refurbished by the students; the existing
building on Beethoven Street near Marina Del Rey, not far from the
planned Dreamworks complex in Playa Vista, is a converted
industrial building.
</P>
<P>
   Social and environmental concerns remain high here, although
many of the first students and longtime faculty have achieved
mainstream success. The rugged ethos and plain style of the desk
sometimes surface in the architecture of alumni and faculty, from
Michael Rotundi, the former director of SciArc and a member of its
first graduating class, to Eric Owen Moss to Michele Saee, in
buildings where exposed studs are combined with drain pipes used as
columns to produce structures with fantastic angles and scarps.
</P>
<P>
   But contemplating the desks at SciArc left me with another
notion. The desk project could serve as a model for education in
general, whose framework corresponds to a basic canon, later to be
supplemented and specialized, like the much challenged but
longstanding idea of ``liberal'' education. The desks put me in
mind of my own education; they made me promise myself to read books
I've been planning to read for years, from Thucydides to George
Eliot. These are overlooked 1-by-4's; I sometimes feel the absence
of them squeaking and creaking beneath my ideas.
</P>
<P>
   During the long winter months, which the back-to-school sales
tell us can't be far off, there will be time to add ornament and
fabric and panels to customize and decorate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
