<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3614 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRADEMARK-SKYLINE-ART     08-26 1197
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRADEMARK-SKYLINE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHOSE SKYLINE IS IT ANYWAY? 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: The word COPYRIGHT in parentheses has been used instead of
the symbol, which is non-transmittable to many newspaper systems.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By DAVID W. DUNLAP   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For years, Bobby Short has been singing at the Cafe
Carlyle that he feels New York is really ``my personal property,
right down Broadway to City Hall.''
</P>
<P>
   Careful, Bobby. That slice of New York skyline you think is
yours may in fact be trademarked.
</P>
<P>
   The art deco spire of the Chrysler Building is a registered
trademark (No. 1126888). So is the neoclassical facade of the New
York Stock Exchange (No. 1761655). Even the Manhattan White Pages
needed permission to depict ``Patience,'' one of the marble lions
guarding the New York Public Library on Fifth Avenue (Trademark No.
1838167).
</P>
<P>
   Rockefeller Center has applied for trademark protection of its
centerpiece skyscraper, 30 Rockefeller Plaza, along with
representations of the skating rink, Prometheus and Atlas. Radio
City Music Hall is considering trademarking its signature art deco
interiors. The Flatiron Building and Grand Central Terminal are
other eligible candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a growing number of landlords are seeking to control the
ways in which images and likenesses of their distinctive buildings
are used by others. They mean business, too.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Stock Exchange has sued the New York-New York Hotel
and Casino of Las Vegas for building a one-third-scale model of the
exchange's facade on the gambling floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never taken the position that somebody who walks in off
Las Vegas Boulevard will think they're in the Stock Exchange,''
said Doreen Costa of Baker &AMP; Botts, lawyers for the exchange. ``But
somebody may believe that this use is licensed.''
</P>
<P>
   And in New York the owners of the Chrysler Building have
demanded that Fishs Eddy, a tableware store, stop selling a line of
dishes called 212, which depicts the building's Jazz Age spire
among other New York landmarks in a skyline border.
</P>
<P>
   The chill from these cases is being felt not just by souvenir
makers, who reproduce buildings on mugs, magnets or salt-and-pepper
shakers, but by designers, publishers, photographers and
horror-film makers in search of fresh landmarks to crush.
</P>
<P>
   Their needs can conflict with those of owners determined to
treat architectural features as valuable _ and exclusive _ assets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the responsibility of the ownership to protect the good
will that is symbolized by the mark,'' said Keri Christ of Milbank,
Tweed, Hadley &AMP; McCloy, lawyers for the owners of the Chrysler
Building, the Flatiron Building and Rockefeller Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is analogous to the situation where a celebrity or a
famous person has a property right in their name and likeness that
enables them to control the commercial exploitation of their
identity,'' she said. ``Why would you want to deny that kind of
protection to a famous landmark?''
</P>
<P>
   Because, said Julie Gaines, the co-owner of Fishs Eddy, ``it's
un-American!''
</P>
<P>
   ``How can they say we can't use the Chrysler Building?'' she
asked. ``We wanted to do a plate that represented New York City.
Leaving off the Chrysler Building would be like leaving off the
World Trade Center.''
</P>
<P>
   David Childs, a partner in Skidmore, Owings &AMP; Merrill, which has
designed corporate icons like Lever House on Park Avenue, was
outraged to learn that the stainless-steel Chrysler spire was a
trademark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does this mean you can't use stainless steel?'' he wondered.
``Does this mean your building cannot come to a point?'' For that
matter, he asked, ``What about Imhotep?''
</P>
<P>
   Come to think of it, William Van Alen's design for the top of
the Chrysler tower does bear an elongated resemblance to Imhotep's
Step Pyramid at Sakkara, Egypt, built almost 4,800 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The notion of trademarking a building is not as ancient as that,
but it is not freshly concocted. It goes back at least to the
1930s, when courts held that White Castle had an exclusive right to
its distinctive diner design.
</P>
<P>
   In 1879, the engineer Gustave Eiffel obtained a patent on his
structural system for the Statue of Liberty. (The statue's image is
firmly in the public domain.)
</P>
<P>
   Patents, which protect inventions, are not usually sought for
one-of-a-kind structures.
</P>
<P>
   ``The type of things that are more likely to be patented are
Fotomats, telephone booths, fast-food restaurants, styles of
layouts,'' said John Kittle, the director of the design examining
group in the Patent and Trademark Office in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Copyrights, which protect original artistic works, are more
often claimed by architects.
</P>
<P>
   Platt Byard Dovell Architects adds a ``(COPYRIGHT)'' to each
drawing. ``Putting a `C' in a circle says to the owner, `You can't
copy my drawing,''' said Paul Byard, a partner in the firm and a
lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Trademarks are indicators _ designs, symbols, words or phrases _
that distinguish the goods and services of one party from those of
others. Federal registration is not required, although it helps in
legal challenges.
</P>
<P>
   The official registration for the stock exchange's trademark
describes it as ``a representation of an actual building facade
with the wording `New York Stock Exchange' located beneath the
pediment.''
</P>
<P>
   The exchange is suing the New York-New York hotel in part
because ``the use of our mark helps them convey the message, even
if implicitly, that `we're a bit fairer than other casinos,''' said
Ms. Costa, the lawyer for the exchange. (In court papers, the hotel
has denied this charge, but it would not comment further.)
</P>
<P>
   As a trademark, a building is no different from any other
three-dimensional object that plays such a role _ the Weber grill,
the Pepperidge Farm Goldfish cracker or the Coca-Cola bottle.
</P>
<P>
   Coke bottles featured prominently in the case of the Rock 'n'
Roll Hall of Fame and Museum in Cleveland, which has sued to
prevent a photographer, Charles Gentile, from selling posters
showing the pyramidal facade of its building.
</P>
<P>
   ``The physical structure of the museum, the I.M. Pei-designed
building, is `the Coke bottle,''' declared Chief Judge Boyce Martin
Jr. of the 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Ohio, in a
dissenting opinion in the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Its building symbolizes something unique and protectable under
the trademark laws,'' he wrote. ``Like the Coke bottle, the
building is also a container. Instead of containing a soft drink,
the museum envelops an array of tangible and intangible elements.''
</P>
<P>
   But the two-judge majority disagreed, lifted an injunction
against Gentile and sent the case back to district court.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we view the photograph in Gentile's poster, we do not
readily recognize the design of the museum's building as an
indicator of source or sponsorship,'' they declared. ``What we see,
rather, is a photograph of an accessible, well-known, public
landmark.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Souvenir makers are already well acquainted with owners who
object to seeing their buildings on ashtrays, baseball caps and
earrings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rockefeller Center does mind,'' said Jack Gindi, the president
of City Merchandise in Brooklyn, makers of 1,200 different items.
So do Radio City Music Hall and the Hard Rock Cafe, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We respect their wishes,'' he added. ``If they don't want free
publicity,'' he said, ``it's fine with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Reproduction on a larger scale was the subject of a case
involving Donald Trump's boomerang-shaped Trump Plaza, at Third
Avenue and 61st Street, built in 1983 to designs by Philip
Birnbaum.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioned by another developer for a project on the opposite
corner, Birnbaum envisioned a monumental gateway to upper Third
Avenue and designed the second tower as a near twin of Trump Plaza.
Trump sued and won a settlement in which the second building, the
Savoy, was redesigned.
</P>
<P>
   Barring the unlikely possibility of duplication, most owners are
more concerned about the dilution of images on which they have
staked their money and reputation.
</P>
<P>
   When the lion sculpture ``Patience'' appeared on the front of
the 1997-98 White Pages, it was accompanied by a notice that the
representation is the trademark and property of the New York Public
Library.
</P>
<P>
   ``As institutions become more nationally and internationally
recognizable, their logos become almost tangible extensions of the
institutions themselves,'' said Robert Vanni, general counsel to
the library.
</P>
<P>
   This belief is shared by Newmark &AMP; Co., which acquired an
ownership interest last year in the Flatiron Building at 23rd
Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time the Flatiron Building image is seen, it's going to
impact who we attract to the building,'' said Barry Gosin, the
chief executive of Newmark. He said he was more concerned about the
unauthorized use of the tower as a business logo than he was about
its destruction in ``Godzilla,'' although he added, ``I don't think
anyone called to say, `We're crushing your building.'''
</P>
<P>
   Movie and television production companies count on being able to
film well-known buildings from public places without securing the
owners' permission or paying fees.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Reed Scott, New York City's commissioner of film,
theater and broadcasting, said the prospect of trademarked
landmarks ``seems like a bad move to me and endlessly
complicating.''
</P>
<P>
   That is, unless filmmakers stick to the Empire State Building.
Having been scaled by King Kong 65 years ago, the building accepts
its place in the public domain _ even in ``Independence Day,''
which showed the tower being atomized.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in good company,'' said Lydia Ruth, a spokeswoman for
Empire State Building Co. ``They got the White House, too.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Empire State Building belongs to everyone,'' she said.
``The last thing I'd want to do is restrict the use of the
building. I know it's kind of diminished when it's got a
thermometer stuck inside. But we love to see the building
everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The owners of the Chrysler Building take a different tack.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, Massachusetts Mutual Life Insurance Co. and Jack Kent
Cooke, who then owned the building, registered the Chrysler spire
as a trademark. The tower was built in 1930 by Walter Chrysler, and
although Chrysler Corp. moved out long ago, it has no objection to
the name being on the building, a spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   Tishman Speyer Properties and Travelers Group, which acquired
the property in January, filed a trademark application in May for
the ``configuration, overall appearance and design'' of the entire
building _ not just the spire _ for possible use on more than 400
goods and services, from real-estate development to horse blankets.
</P>
<P>
   A month later, they demanded that Fishs Eddy ``immediately and
permanently discontinue all use of the mark,'' in part because
purchasers might believe that the china is authorized, endorsed or
sponsored by the owners. They also demanded that Fishs Eddy
``immediately arrange for the prompt destruction of all remaining
inventory.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer for the owners, Ms. Christ, said in an interview
later that Fishs Eddy was not being singled out. ``This is part of
a diligent enforcement program,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gaines of Fishs Eddy thought about replacing the Chrysler
Building with Central Park on the border. What stiffened her
resolve to fight back, she said, was Ms. Christ's assertion that
the depiction of the Chrysler spire on the china was ``inconsistent
with the high standards of quality'' associated with the trademark
_ particularly given the number of knickknacks that capitalize on
the building.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Tamarin of Hall Dickler Kent Friedman &AMP; Wood, the lawyer
for Fishs Eddy, said: ``Most buildings that are landmarked are
going to have similar problems. For years and years, nobody used
them as trademarks. No one associates them with any particular
goods.''
</P>
<P>
   Fishs Eddy is selling more 212 china than ever, thanks to
publicity over the Chrysler issue. ``I can't even keep the pattern
in stock,'' Ms. Gaines said. She has expanded the line to drinking
glasses and has even test-baked Chrysler-shaped cookies.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I get caught,'' Ms. Gaines vowed, ``I'll eat the
inventory.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
