<SLUG> BC-CANADA-ARCHITECTURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARCHITECTURE'S DOYENNE PASSES BATON IN MONTREAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Switzerland)  (lb) 
 By JULIE V. IOVINE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Phyllis Lambert, the formidable doyenne of architecture, whose
youthful rebellion against her father, the liquor tycoon Samuel
Bronfman, resulted in Mies van der Rohe designing the Seagram
Building in New York, announced last week that she had chosen her
successor as director of the Canadian Center for Architecture in
Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Kurt Forster, founding director of the Getty Center for the
History of Art and the Humanities in Los Angeles and, currently,
chairman of the Department of Art and Architecture at the Federal
Institute of Technology in Zurich, Switzerland, will assume the
directorship on March 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The Swiss-born scholar, 63, is expected to bring a considerable
measure of international cachet and academic integrity to the
center that Ms. Lambert, 71, founded, using her own inheritance
money, in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found myself worrying about what would happen if I were
knocked down by a bus,'' Ms. Lambert said last week, ``and I wanted
to be sure that the center was in the most imaginative and
competent hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the past two decades, the Canadian Center for Architecture
_ a museum, library and study center wrapped in a $40-million
edifice designed by Peter Rose _ has amassed a collection strong on
contemporary architecture and sponsored timely and intellectually
challenging exhibitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The CCA is one of the few institutions that regularly has
exhibitions of international importance of the sort that MOMA once
did but hasn't done in a long time,'' the architect Richard Meier
said, referring to New York's Museum of Modern Art. The exhibition
now on display, ``The American Lawn: Surface of Everyday Life''
(through Nov. 8), has attracted significant attention for its
provocative scrutiny of the seemingly mundane suburban lawn.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lambert will continue as chairwoman of the board of trustees
and remain an active member of the acquisitions committee. Her
immediate plans, however, are to concentrate on developing an
exhibition dedicated to Mies van der Rohe's years in America, which
will open at the Whitney Museum of American Art in New York in 2000
and travel to the center in the summer of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Forster, who has been living in Zurich since 1992, will be
moving in February to Montreal. He anticipates a smooth transition
from academia to the museum world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like the Getty, where there were 35,000 books and a
lot of confused ideas about what might be possible,'' Forster said.
``My first obligation is to follow exactly the course Phyllis has
set, and then broaden and sharpen it.'' He added that he is
contemplating a series of exhibitions exploring the role of
defining moments in architecture, such as the year 1910, when Le
Corbusier decided to leave Berlin for France.
</P>
<P>
   Forster's appointment, in fact, may be a kind of defining moment
of its own. ``This is terrific news,'' Terence Riley, chief curator
of the department of architecture and design at the Museum of
Modern Art, said. ``He's a natural to follow Phyllis. And to her
credit, she has selected a personality as strong as her own. This
will heat up the scene, and that's good for everyone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
