<P>
   TEXAS WEATHER-CROPS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The deadly storm system that hit the state
this week has been both cruel and kind to South and Southwest Texas
agriculture. Tropical Storm Charley's spinoffs are running from a
virtual wipeout on up to 8,000 acres of irrigated cotton in the
Winter Garden area to a boost for the red grapefruit crop, revived
ranch pastures in some areas and desperately needed irrigation
water in the still-parched Lower Rio Grande Valley. By WORTH WREN
JR. Story has moved in ``a'' general news category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-FLOODS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DEL RIO, Texas _ When three generations of Calderons fled the
rising waters of San Felipe Creek here this week, Leonara Calderon,
a stubborn octogenarian who uses a walker due to old age and
Parkinson's disease, refused to leave. ``Oh, we've had these floods
before,'' one of her sons, Pat Calderon, 56, recalled the
82-year-old saying not long before spending several harrowing hours
floating on a couch near the ceiling of her living room. By BARRY
SHLACHTER. Story has moved in ``a'' general news category.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-INJURIES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Pull a hamstring or groin muscle and sports
medicine specialists know what to do. But what about the
debilitating pain associated with clarinet wrist, trombone elbow or
fiddler's neck? The Texas Center for Music and Medicine isn't a
household name, but soon this new collaborative effort between the
University of North Texas Health Science Center in Fort Worth and
University of North Texas in Denton could be a major national
center for research and treatment in the budding field of
performing arts medicine. By PAUL BOURGEOIS. Story has moved in
``a'' general news category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   F O O D A N D D I N I N G &QL; 
