<HEADER>
A3627 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-CANADA-$ADV30-     08-26 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CANADA-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS CANADIAN DOLLAR DECLINES, U.S. VISITS RISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., August 30)  
 (JT)  
 By ANTHONY DePALMA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, British Columbia _ A dollar is a dollar, except
perhaps these days in Canada, where one American dollar is now
worth about one and a half Canadian dollars, giving Americans a big
boost as soon as they cross the border.
</P>
<P>
   And they are making the trip north in record numbers so far this
year, according to Canadian tourism officials. American visitors
are up 11 percent here in Vancouver, just slightly ahead of the 9.7
percent increase nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Curiously though, the disparity in the value of the American and
Canadian dollars _ a wider gap than ever before _ is something that
not all Americans are aware of.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm amazed,'' said Patrick Fairchild, a school janitor from
Victor, N.Y., who traveled to Toronto with his family recently to
take in ``Les Miserables'' and see the sights.
</P>
<P>
   Like many other American visitors, Fairchild said he had not
even thought about the exchange rate before crossing the border.
His good fortune only hit him when he took $35 to a currency
exchange and got $47 in Canadian dollars; he could have done better
at another money exchange, but he was happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to hit Niagara Falls on my way back,'' Fairchild
said.
</P>
<P>
   Tourism officials say that because of the similarities between
the United States and Canada, and because Canada's currency is
called a dollar, tourists from the United States tend to assume
that the money is interchangeable. John C. Olsthoorn, of the
Canadian Tourism Commission, said that is especially so for
Americans who do not live near the northern border and are not
familiar with Canadian money.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to raise awareness a bit, but not highlight it
in flashing lights because the dollar will change the other way at
some point,'' Olsthoorn said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the perception problem is that the decline in the
Canadian dollar _ called a loonie because the $1 coin bears the
image of a common loon _ has not been sudden. Rather, the loonie
has been in a long, gradual slide since 1976, the last time one
Canadian dollar was worth the same as one American dollar.
</P>
<P>
   However, it was only this spring that the loonie broke through
its historic low against the dollar. That has been followed by
numerous further declines, which have generated a fair amount of
news coverage and suddenly made Americans aware of the fact that
their dollars can go much further north of the border.
</P>
<P>
   A loonie is now worth just over 65 cents. Canada no longer uses
paper $1 or $2 bills; a $2 coin is commonly called a toonie.
</P>
<P>
   Although it's too early for statistics showing precisely how
Americans in Canada are spending their windfall, Canadian tourism
officials say that many appear to travel to more-remote locations
or to upgrade accommodations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those individuals who would have stayed at a middle-range
establishment are now booking rooms in the upper end of what's
available in places like Vancouver, Victoria and Whistler,'' said
Roderick J. Harris, president of Tourism B.C., the provincial
tourism office for British Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   For American travelers, the decline of the loonie has provided a
more transparent advantage than the currency troubles of some other
countries. For example, in Mexico, where the peso was devalued
precipitously in late 1994 and early 1995, resorts in Cancun and
other places priced hotel rooms in dollar equivalents, as did
Mexican airlines. That wiped out most of the potential advantage
from the peso's decline.
</P>
<P>
   Not so in Canada, tourism officials say. Harris said hotel rates
have been flat or just slightly higher, in part because the Asian
economic crisis has hurt many Pacific Coast resorts and forced them
to keep rates competitive.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the declining loonie has not been accompanied by
any noticeable jump in inflation in Canada, which makes shopping
attractive, at least until Canada's high national and provincial
sales taxes are added. Americans are eligible for tax refunds if
they save original receipts and fill out official forms. The
process is not painless, but the forms are widely available.
</P>
<P>
   Harris recommends that American travelers change their money
into Canadian dollars before leaving home. He does not take into
account the exchange rate, but rather is focusing on a way for
Americans to be able to appreciate just how much more they have
available to spend during their time away.
</P>
<P>
   For those who prefer to change dollars in Canada, there are
plenty of options. Rates at money exchanges, banks and the front
desks of larger hotels tend to be fairly consistent, the only
difference often being whether a commission is charged.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian Pacific's Hotel Vancouver will change up to $1,000 a
day for its guests without a commission, said Oliver Muschamp, a
guest-service agent at the hotel. He recommends that guests change
as much as they want on arrival, and then apply whatever is unspent
at the end of the stay to the hotel bill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
