<HEADER>
A3642 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LITTLELEAGUE-PINS-COX     08-26 0520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LITTLELEAGUE-PINS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pin-trading popular pastime at Little League World Series
 &HT;    By Kim Grizzard
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILLIAMSPORT, Pa. _ When Mike Lilley told Justin Hardee he
missed his chance, he wasn't talking about a great pitch or a
grounder.
</P>
<P>
   Believe it or not, baseball's not the only game in town here.
Pin trading appears to be the second most popular sport at the
Little League World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how far back the whole trend goes, but that's a
big event here,'' said Nancy Scudder, media relations
administrative assistant for the Little League.
</P>
<P>
   Players and fans carry zippered pouches to show off their
collections and allow them to trade for pins from Japan, Mexico and
Saudi Arabia. North Carolina pins are a pretty hot commodity here,
since a team from the Tar Heel state hasn't been to the series
since 1952.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a great hobby,'' Scudder said. ``It's an
international thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Aldridge, 11, of Greenville just took up pin trading, but
he already has an international collection going and was trying to
work a trade with a fan from Saudi Arabia on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just got started yesterday,'' Aldridge said. ``I got a '97
Saudi from somebody on the hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen everybody down here do it. I've seen people with
bags full _ suitcases full. It's just the thing to do down here.''
</P>
<P>
   Players from Greenville have started their own collections.
Hardee started collecting at the Southern Regional in St.
Petersburg, Fla. This week, he's traded pins with Japanese players
and picked up some new ones like the ``uncle'' pins from team
hosts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our team hosts, they have their own pin, so people want to get
an 'uncle' pin,'' Scudder said. ``Our Little League photographer
has his own pin. Our World Series drivers, they have their own
pin.''
</P>
<P>
   Sponsors like Honda, Hershey and Gatorade also have their own
pins.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a lot of fun,'' Scudder said. ``It's not just kids
that do it. It's people of all ages.''
</P>
<P>
   Idamae Danley, 57, laundry supervisor at the Holiday Inn, has
been collecting since 1981. She has one from Guam and two from
Saudi Arabia in her collection, which is large enough to fill three
books.
</P>
<P>
   ``People, when they come here and stay, they bring us pins,''
said Danley, whose daughter, Tina Alter, works at Little League
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Danley wants a North Carolina pin, and they're hard
to come by. Kids at Howard J. Lamade Stadium are getting two for
one in trades for the Carolina pin.
</P>
<P>
   Collectors can pick up official Little League pins at souvenir
stands for $3 apiece. There's a pin-trading tent behind the
stadium, but deals are being made in the stands, on the hill and in
area hotels.
</P>
<P>
   But what will the pins be worth back home in Greenville? It's
hard to say. Unlike baseball cards, the pins don't have
publications that list their values.
</P>
<P>
   ``The value may only be to the traders,'' Scudder said.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Grizzard writes for The Daily Reflector in Greenville, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
