<HEADER>
A3643 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LITTLELEAGUE-TEAM-COX     08-26 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LITTLELEAGUE-TEAM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Like heaven for Little League World Series entrants
 &HT;    Eds: Singular Tar Heel is cq. Greenville plays tonight
(Wednesday) at 8 p.m.
 &HT;    By Kim Grizzard
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILLIAMSPORT, Pa. _ Pete Carraway is in heaven.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's what the scoresheet says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm charting the game, and where it said 'location' I put
heaven,'' Carraway said after a victory this week by his Greenville
Tar Heel All Stars, marking their first appearance in the Little
League World Series.
</P>
<P>
   No team from North Carolina has been in the Little League World
Series in more than 40 years. There's never been a team from
Greenville, and, statistically speaking, there's not likely to be
another. So the hometown fans are making the most of it.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 500 Greenville fans turned out to see Tar Heel in its
first game, and the numbers increased from there. After one loss,
the team played Wednesday night at 8 p.m. in a game they had to win
to advance.
</P>
<P>
   Before he left home late last week, Carraway told his pastor
that he felt a little bit like Moses. But unlike the Old Testament
prophet, who only got a view of the promised land from a
mountaintop, Carraway has been allowed to cross over and enter.
</P>
<P>
   It's a journey that has taken nearly 40 years. After playing
semi-pro ball, Carraway coached his first Little League team in
1961. He's never seen a team go this far.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a dream for Pete,'' his wife, Grace, said.
</P>
<P>
   Standing in the second-row bleachers, Carraway, 79, took in the
view.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can tell when you get here, TV doesn't do it justice,'' he
said of scenic Howard J. Lamade Stadium, leaning on his ``staff,''
a wooden bat he takes to games.
</P>
<P>
   Carraway bought it in 1940 and used it when he coached his first
Little Leaguers. Black tape circles one end, but it's still used to
hit grounders and pop flies during tryouts.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the time, Carraway takes it on the road to Little
League games up and down the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just one of those things you don't know why you do,''
Carraway said of carrying the bat. ``It kind of got to be a
trademark. If I'm going to where baseball is being played, I carry
it with me. When people see me, they expect to see this bat in my
hand.''
</P>
<P>
   When folks from Greenville go to a ballgame, they also expect to
see Marvin Jarman. Jarman, so well known in Greenville that he's
had a street named after him, was noticeably absent during the
regionals in St. Petersburg, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking for Marvin Jarman,'' read a sign shown during the
ESPN2 broadcast of the final game.
</P>
<P>
   He's here, but had to accompany a student back to Greenville for
classes. Pitt County students started classes last week, but you
couldn't tell that by looking in the stands Monday. Kids sporting
painted faces and Southern Regional Champions T-shirts did the wave
and held up signs for their friends back home.
</P>
<P>
   ``WE MISS YOU, KATHRYN. FLY UP,'' one read. Another simply
stated ``Thanks St. Peter's.'' (Guess the school excused her
absence.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We've talked to principals, and they're willing to work (with
us),'' said Joann Wilder, president of the Tar Heel League. ``It
helps the boys. They love to see fans up here.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Hodges, 16, is prepared to miss a week of classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The principal was real nice about having us leave,'' said
Hodges, whose younger brother, Kevin, pitches for Greenville Tar
Heel. ``I wouldn't miss being up here for anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our team was one game away from being in the World Series in
our age group.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity,'' Wilder said. ``This
is what baseball's all about.
</P>
<P>
   ``(When) you start out, you kind of laugh and say, 'We're going
to Williamsport.' We're laughing, but we're here.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim Grizzard writes for The Daily Reflector in Greenville, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
