s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-ARCHITECTURE-COLUM     08-26 0544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ARCHITECTURE-COLUMBUS-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTO THE VOID AT COLUMBUS CIRCLE  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By HERBERT MUSCHAMP    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With the selection of a design for the old Coliseum
site on New York's Columbus Circle and plans afoot to spiff up the
circle's core, this may be the time to appreciate the power of this
place to stir the imagination over the years.
</P>
<P>
   We still think that Billie Tsien's 1983 project, ``Dig a Hole to
China,'' is the best and the darkest of the many proposals ever put
forward. If realized, this anti-monument would certainly put the
Franco-British Chunnel to shame.
</P>
<P>
   And Columbus himself would love it. He's getting awfully tired
of standing there all by himself on top of that column year after
year, as if he were St. Simeon Stylites. With Tsien's project, the
explorer might finally bump into the real Indies, five centuries
after he sailed forth to find them.
</P>
<P>
   First shown with a group of other visionary schemes at the old
Institute for Architecture and Urban Studies on West 40th Street,
Tsien's concept is a tribute to those who eagerly gaze into the
unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Tsien, a principal in the New York firm Tod Williams Billie
Tsien &AMP; Associates, has since gone on to design such acclaimed
works as the Neurosciences Institute in La Jolla, Calif.; Hereford
College at the University of Virginia, and the Museum of American
Folk Art planned for West 54th Street in Manhattan. These buildings
show a natural progression from ``Dig a Hole''; Williams and Tsien
are masters at manipulating spatial voids and simple geometric
forms. In La Jolla and Charlottesville, they have created
hauntingly sublime landscapes. But this would be the firm's first
truly international park.
</P>
<P>
   And let's not overlook the design's immense functional appeal.
It would take a large pit indeed to hold all the models, plans and
renderings that have piled up over the years with successive
efforts to transform this civic space, from Morris &AMP; O'Connor's
1935 proposal for a Municipal Art Center to Moshe Safdie's
ill-fated pair of prismatic towers in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, this could become the symbolic Memory Hole for all of
the many New York visions, both unbuilt and demolished, that have
accumulated throughout the city's history: The grand City Beautiful
groupings. The Lower Manhattan Expressway. Rem Koolhaas' design for
the expansion of the Museum of Modern Art. Just think how terrific
it would be to leap, like Alice toward Wonderland, and see the
Coney Island Steeplechase, the old Penn Station, the Trylon and
Perisphere whizzing rapidly by one's gaze.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you'd have to wear a dress or other outfit that opens
like a parachute.
</P>
<P>
   Or, maybe it should work the other way around: instead of
tossing old buildings and ideas into the hole, we could fish for
new ideas from the other side of the world. If we gathered enough
pagodas, we could stack them up on top of the Coliseum building and
save ourselves the trouble of putting a new building there. The
southwest corner of Central Park could be turned into rice paddies.
We could call them Trump International Rice Paddies. Lincoln Center
could be enclosed within walls punctuated by dragon gates and
declared a new Forbidden City.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-26-98 1711EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980826.0304 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3678 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-VIDEO-CONFERENCIN     08-26 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-VIDEO-CONFERENCING-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIDEOCONFERENCING: FROM STAGE FRIGHT TO STAGE PRESENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By JULIA LAWLOR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A firm handshake, a neat appearance and a thorough knowledge of
your field used to be just about all you needed to land a job or
make a good impression at a meeting. But in today's workplace,
technology that allows meetings to take place between distant
points requires yet another quality _ stage presence.
</P>
<P>
   While the market for home videophones has not taken off, the use
of videoconferencing _ which allows people to ``meet'' at several
locations using video and audio links _ has skyrocketed in the
corporate world in the last several years, as companies try to cut
travel costs and speed products to market.
</P>
<P>
   Videoconferencing equipment sales grew at a rate of 40 percent
to 50 percent a year in the early 1990s, reaching $1.4 billion last
year, said Elliot Gold, president of Telespan Publishing in
Altadena, Calif., which publishes a weekly newsletter on the
teleconferencing industry.
</P>
<P>
   Costs for ``group systems,'' which are designed for corporate
meetings held in conference rooms, and the smaller PC-based
``desktop systems'' have plummeted. In the last two years, the
price of a group system made by 3M dropped to $6,000 from as much
as $60,000, Michael Begeman, manager of 3M Meeting Network, said.
``The only ones who could afford videoconferencing a few years ago
were really big companies,'' he said, adding that declining costs
have ``suddenly put videoconferencing into the price range of small
companies.''
</P>
<P>
   The growing popularity of videoconferencing means that a job
candidate may now be asked at the spur of the moment to walk around
the corner for an interview using a videoconference hookup with a
prospective employer in another city. A salesperson may be required
to make a presentation to a room full of people via a
videoconference hookup. Or a newly formed work team with members in
offices around the world may be asked to brainstorm on camera.
</P>
<P>
   Most people experience some stage fright the first time they are
asked to participate in a videoconference _ and with good reason.
``People judge you by the standards of television,'' said Andrew
Gilman, president of Commcore Consulting Group, a communications
training company in Washington. ``They're used to watching Ted
Koppel or Tom Brokaw on screen, who know how to act in front of a
camera.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the limits of the technology, there is often a slight
delay in the video image, which at first can cause confusion. The
first time that Fernando Agramonte, a client representative for IBM
in New York, used videoconferencing in a course he took last year
at Bentley College in Waltham, Mass., it took him a while to
adjust.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to speak slower because I couldn't tell if my point was
getting across,'' Agramonte said. ``I was looking at the screen,
but I didn't know if the person I was talking to could see me the
same way I could see her, or if she could hear me. There was a
small delay. I would see her move or speak, and I'd hear the words
maybe a split second afterwards. It was like `The Twilight Zone.'''
</P>
<P>
   Most people, after using a system a few times, get used to any
delay and begin to relax. The goal, said T.J. Walker, president of
TJWalker.com, a presentation-training company in Manhattan, should
be ``not to make you look like a TV star, but to avoid the things
you're doing that unknowingly distract people from your message. We
try to prevent people from visually putting their foot in their
mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   Following are some tips for successful videoconferences:
</P>
<P>
   _ Before taking part in a videoconference, try to find out what
type of equipment is being used and whether there is a noticeable
delay in the audio and video images.
</P>
<P>
   While most PC-based desktop systems are plagued by long delays
and jerky video, they are rarely used to conduct large meetings or
job interviews. The best use of a desktop system is for just two
people to collaborate on a document on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Many of today's group videoconferencing systems operate at 384
kilobits per second or higher, which means movement of people on
the screen is fluid, voices are clear and there is practically no
perceptible delay. At 128 kbps, the picture is more jerky and there
is a noticeable pause between the moment a participant says
something and the moment it is received at the far end.
</P>
<P>
   Because most videoconferencing calls take place over one or more
ISDN (integrated services digital network) phone lines, a one-hour
call from New York to California using 384 kbps would cost a
company $65 to $70 an hour, according to Kevin Flanagan, spokesman
for Picturetel of Andover, Mass., the leading seller of
videoconferencing equipment. By comparison, a system running at 128
kbps, which uses a single ISDN line, would cost $20 to $25 an hour
for the same call.
</P>
<P>
   If you discover that the system you will be using has a delay,
be prepared for overlapping dialogue and long pauses. Speak more
slowly, let people know when you are finished talking, so they can
have their turn, and try not to interrupt.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rehearse a job interview or presentation before starting a
videoconference, using videoconferencing equipment if possible. If
not, use a home video camera.
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Hoffman of Media Mentors, a communications training
company based in Philadelphia, suggests sending out detailed
reports or charts to meeting participants before the conference
begins. Although many systems allow you to display graphs, charts,
slides and other visual aids, it can be cumbersome if you are
unfamiliar with the equipment. Keep your message simple; one rule
of thumb is to use no more than three key points.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   _ Get to the conference site early enough to assess the
situation. In most cases, a technician will have set up the camera
and you will not be required to operate it. If you need to run it
for slides, graphs or charts, you need to give yourself plenty of
time to learn how to operate the control board, including how to
pan and zoom the camera and which buttons to push to move the
camera.
</P>
<P>
   Make sure you and your material are properly positioned for the
cameras. You should be close enough so that people on the other
side can see your expressions. Once you walk into a room for a
videoconference, avoid idle talk _ assume someone is watching and
listening.
</P>
<P>
   _ Watch what you wear. Avoid lots of white, red or black. White
reflects too much light, which makes the face dark. Black clothing
causes the face to be overexposed. Red tends to smear. Wear a light
blue shirt, instead of a white shirt, with a suit, and choose solid
colors instead of complex patterns.
</P>
<P>
   Begeman of 3M Meeting Network advises people to stay away from
small prints, thin stripes and plaids. Bulky or baggy clothing
makes you look heavier on screen, tinted eyeglasses give you
raccoon eyes and glittery or dangling jewelry is distracting.
</P>
<P>
   _ Avoid too much side-to-side movement during a videoconference
call, but don't sit rigidly, either. Walker of TJWalker.com
suggests leaning 15 degrees into the camera. ``People focus on your
message more if your face is prominent,'' Walker said. ``Leaning
forward hides the gut and any rolls in the neck. It's the one thing
that can dramatically improve your appearance.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that smiling slightly makes you look confident; without
a smile, you may look like you're frowning. People tend to freeze
and sit on their hands _ a mistake. ``Your message might be
perfect, but the impression is, `Who is this nervous stiff?'''
Walker said. Instead, gesture with your hands, which will
automatically give your voice more energy and inflection.
</P>
<P>
   _ Quirky mannerisms that may barely be noticeable in a
face-to-face meeting are magnified in a videoconference and can
detract from the image you are trying to project. Ms. Hoffman of
Media Mentors cautions against twirling hair or a mustache,
fiddling with your glasses or rocking back and forth in a chair.
</P>
<P>
   There is a temptation, especially in the beginning, to be
mesmerized by your own image on the monitor. And if you use it to
check your hairdo or straighten your tie, others will see you doing
it.
</P>
<P>
   The average person blinks 50 to 70 times a minute, according to
Gilman of Commcore. So don't be afraid to blink. On the other hand,
blinking much more than that will make you look nervous, and maybe
even shifty. Tapping a pen during a videoconference can be annoying
to those involved, since the microphones generally pick up
background noise as well as the sound of voices.
</P>
<P>
   _ Videoconferencing has its own rules of etiquette. All
participants should be given the chance to introduce themselves. It
is poor form, for instance, not to let everyone know that your boss
is sitting just out of camera range.
</P>
<P>
   Never read a speech or presentation at a videoconference,
advises Walker. ``People will be bored out of their minds, and will
start playing tic-tac-toe.'' Moving while someone else in the group
is talking is considered upstaging. And don't get up and walk
around the room during an important presentation. Side
conversations are distracting, so if you need to talk privately,
use the ``mute'' button.
</P>
<P>
   Begeman of 3M Meeting Network said that if you are involved in a
videoconference that includes people from several different
locations, it is a good idea to jot down names of people on a grid
so you can refer to it as you speak, using names whenever possible.
This is a good way of grabbing their attention.
</P>
<P>
   In a videoconference job interview, Begeman suggests making it a
habit to pause a second or two after each question is asked, so
that when a difficult question arises and you need time to think
through a response, the pause will not seem out of place. And when
the hard question comes, don't break eye contact when you answer.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, as you end the videoconference and head back to your
office for the inevitable critique, Begeman recommends that you
remember that ``Very few people are born good at this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
