A3685 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-NJ-ARTS-CARPET-N     08-26 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-NJ-ARTS-CARPET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFRICAN-INSPIRED DECOR ILLUMINATES NEWARK ARTS CENTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(rm) 
 By JOSEPH GIOVANNINI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ Usually it's a bronze statue, an old schoolhouse
or a stately home that becomes the symbol of a town. But the new
contender in Newark is a colorful 12-by 92-foot carpet, an addition
to the New Jersey Performing Arts Center, which was installed last
Thursday in the entrance foyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Afrocentric,'' observed Lynne Falanga, of Watchung, N.J.,
who attended a concert at the center on Sunday. ``They're
incorporating the neighborhood into the arts center, and that's the
best part about it.''
</P>
<P>
   With its rhythmic geometries and blended earth colors, the
runner joins the brightly patterned yellow, green and crimson glass
mosaics in the bathrooms and etched copper elevator doors in the
lobbies as civic icons of an unexpected kind: the center is one of
the first major cultural institutions in the United States to base
its motifs on African decorative arts.
</P>
<P>
   The new carpet, its rusty reds giving way to deep blues and
grass greens, and the etched doors and the mosaics (in place since
the center's opening last October) draw on visual traditions
abstracted from West African textiles, ceramics, sculpture and
architecture. Afrocentric motifs are rare in civic buildings,
especially concert halls, whose decorative schemes historically
have been based on Europe's aristocratic palaces and classical
buildings or on abstract modern compositions.
</P>
<P>
   The rug, mosaics and doors were created by the Los Angeles
environmental graphics firm Sussman/Prejza &AMP; Co., in collaboration
with Barton Myers, the architect of the complex. The decoration
signals the cultural background of Newark's largest constituency.
``It was important to have the architecture reflect Newark's ethnic
diversity,'' Gail Thompson, vice president of design and
construction for the center, said.
</P>
<P>
   This visual subtext was not part of the project when it started.
When the architects built a large model, it was clear the
voluminous foyer needed focus. Enter Sussman/Prezja, best known for
the banners it made for the 1984 Olympics in Los Angeles, which
employed rainbows of chromatic ethnicity: magenta from Mexico,
saffron from Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Inspiration for the runner came from a painting by Paul Klee,
which fortuitously catalyzed the idea of African decoration. ``You
can look at Klee and clearly see he was involved in the discovery
of African arts,'' Sussman said. ``The way color meets color and
line intersects color suggested African imagery.''
</P>
<P>
   Sussman and Holly Hampton, a principal in the firm, who is
African-American, quickly discovered that certain African figures _
the snake, for example _ recurred with widely separated tribes.
Other similarities _ the presence of dots and the tendency to
flatness in surface patterns _ also occurred across cultures, as
did the tendency to fill an area with pattern. (``Very little
void,'' Sussman said.)
</P>
<P>
   The designers first proposed several adaptations of the snake in
the runner. ``It scared everybody,'' Sussman said. ``Everybody felt
more comfortable with a concept that was less overtly symbolic.''
The snake became zigzags, and Hampton began exploring pattern.
``The idea was to give the impression of a woven cloth,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   What emerged at her drafting table was a runner of muted earth
hues in a nonrepetitive, asymmetrical pattern. ``The design didn't
want to be static and fixed, but an experience that would change as
you walked along,'' Hampton said. ``You see it at a distance, and
then close-up, but can't understand it at a glance. It's not a
one-liner.''
</P>
<P>
   The designers worked with the carpet manufacturer to decide how
much open space was needed in the runner, which was woven in
Thailand. ``It's like music, with dense passages and then silent
spaces that make the passages more intense,'' Sussman said.
</P>
<P>
   The dominant impression comes from the pervasive rusty orange,
which heightens the warm glow of the foyer interior at night. The
huge runner centers the room and the weight of the colors grounds
the space, while the syncopated geometries give it rhythm. The
small rectangular shapes relate to the brick facades of the arts
center, which were inspired by the industrial vernacular of the
surrounding factories. The brick, glass and steel building is
itself a symbol of the city's revitalization, some 30 years after
the Newark riots.
</P>
<P>
   The carpet made its public debut Sunday for a Julio Iglesias
concert. Following the patterned runner, a 4-year-old played
hopscotch. One concert goer, Louise Cadorette, from Elizabeth,
N.J., said: ``The colors are very earthy, and they give character
and a sense of tradition to the building. It's alive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
