<HEADER>
A3700 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-RENOVATION-NYT &LR;      08-26 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-RENOVATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFE IN A CRATER WILL DO, FOR NOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By BENJAMIN CHEEVER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``My name is Ozymandias, king of kings:
</P>
<P>
   Look on my works, ye Mighty, and despair!''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing beside remains. Round the decay
</P>
<P>
   Of that colossal wreck, boundless and bare,
</P>
<P>
   The lone and level sands stretch far away.''
</P>
<P>
   Is there any evidence that Percy Bysshe Shelley was writing
about home renovation? Because my wife and I are having our house
renovated. And we feel a lot like Mr. and Mrs. Ozymandias.
</P>
<P>
   We didn't start with the idea of renovating our house in
Pleasantville, N.Y., a 3,000-square-foot Cotswold cottage on
steroids. The house, built in 1907, has what the folks in real
estate like to call character, which means that it takes a lot of
character to live there, because nothing works properly.
</P>
<P>
   No, we started with the idea of moving, inspired by a photograph
of a new mansion in Bedford, N.Y. The Bedford mansion glittered
like a shiny new penny of colossal proportions. The interior was
almost 7,000 square feet. There were pillars on the outside and
eight toilets inside.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty mansions were planned for the development, each designed
to look like the biggest house in town. The McMansion we thought of
as ours had an enormous kitchen, more than two stories high. I
pictured myself making pancakes in it on Sunday mornings. Our boys,
grown suddenly younger and more picturesque, would peer lovingly
down on me from the railing outside their bedrooms.
</P>
<P>
   The kitchen ran into a family room that had acres of polished
wooden flooring and a large stone hearth at the far end. I believe
real estate agents call them gathering rooms. Isn't that where you
take the hay at harvest time?
</P>
<P>
   I saw caterers in black pants and white tuxedo shirts drifting
gracefully through our gathering room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pinot grigio, Mr. Cheever?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why yes, I believe I will.''
</P>
<P>
   The basement was huge and _ conjure this _ dry as a whistle.
Whenever it rained, we piled into the car, raced to Bedford and
checked the basement. No water. None. Ever.
</P>
<P>
   Why so amazed? Well, I knew about water and lies. Eleven years
ago, when we were preparing to buy the house in Pleasantville, I
noticed that a hose had been left on in the pool. The moment we
took possession, I shut off the spigot.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, I heard a horrid groaning sound as if a sperm
whale had beached itself at the foot of our lawn. I galloped down
the hill and found that the water level had plunged 2 feet, and
that all three pool skimmers were drawing air.
</P>
<P>
   Our pool is a long way from the house. That is because the pool
started life as a culvert. The transformation has not been entirely
successful. Sometimes, in a heavy rain, it fills up with mud. A
pool man once told me, ``You know, you should turn this into a nice
garden.''
</P>
<P>
   If the pool doesn't hold water very well, then our basement
does. It is spring fed. And our pipes burst regularly, especially
the ones over the walk-in closet.
</P>
<P>
   When a pipe burst in the bedroom closet one Saturday night, I
turned off the water and looked up the number of a 24-hour
emergency plumbing service. Twenty-four hours later, two men
appeared: the talker and the worker. The talker rubbed his hands
together with glee. The worker was very earnest, and very young.
</P>
<P>
   The pipes in our house are connected _ it's a fairly common
setup. But our pipes are also fragile. The young worker banged one
pipe. Another broke. By the time I got them both out of the house,
I had three new leaks.
</P>
<P>
   We were going to put this all behind us and live a new, elegant
life in Bedford. With new pipes and no history.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, we would have done it, if it weren't for the pictures.
My wife and I drove to the Bedford mansion one day and took
snapshots of each other there, standing by the hearth in the
gathering room. This is us, we thought. The new, the proactive
Cheevers. Striding confidently through life.
</P>
<P>
   Then we had the pictures developed. The house looked imposing,
but who were those tiny, worried people? Was the owner committed to
the employment of the vertically impaired? Were these his servants?
We might be able to buy the house _ the price had been reduced, and
then reduced again _ but we would never own it.
</P>
<P>
   So that's how we came up with the idea of a renovation, which
seemed like a small thing. Doesn't it always? The Pleasantville
house had been altered and enlarged over the years, but the owners
had kept the quaint eyebrow roofs and, of course, the original
plumbing.
</P>
<P>
   We were going to take it back to its roots. At least, that's
what our architect, Mike, said. The pictures Mike drew were
gorgeous and easily changed. That new downstairs bathroom needed a
shower. We said, ``Draw us a shower, Mike,'' and he did.
``Shouldn't this section of the house be stone?'' we asked. And so
it was. Stone is heavy, difficult and expensive to move, but very
easy to draw.
</P>
<P>
   The plan was that we would have a big kitchen, and off that a
large room with a hearth. A sort of gathering room in miniature.
The basement would be dry as a whistle. The drawing part was fun
and imaginary; then actual workers began tearing down part of our
house. This was not imaginary, nor was it fun. Besides which, we
had to clean out the basement.
</P>
<P>
   Our basement was full of papers. The papers were full of water.
There were also the treasures we had bought with high hopes, and
then broken. DeWitt Wallace, the founder of Reader's Digest, once
said that the dead carry to the grave only that which they have
given away. Which sentiment I find admirable. I also think now that
if you die, and wake up and find you still have all your stuff,
then you've gone to hell.
</P>
<P>
   The work went slowly at first. Demolition was busy elsewhere.
Demolition was like a panzer unit: 20 men and a big machine.
Someone cut a notch in the roof of our house so that the demolition
workers would know where to stop.
</P>
<P>
   The excavator they brought in weighed 28,000 pounds and had a
claw 4 feet across. The machine squatted in our driveway and ate
the roof off the garage and the back room. My son John, 12, took
movies. My wife thought our son Andrew, 9, would be upset. Not so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why no wrecking ball?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   I was the one who was upset. When the last doomed section came
down, I could see two bottles of shampoo _ Flex, and Head and
Shoulders _ sitting on what had once been a shower floor. My shower
floor. I expected to be on the evening news: ``A demolition team
swept through northern Westchester yesterday destroying dozens of
homes, including one in Pleasantville.'' Then they would thrust a
microphone into my face, and I could weep.
</P>
<P>
   One-fourth of the house is gone now, replaced by a crater. Mike
tells us that renovation will be completed next spring.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose I should feel grand. They tore down O.J. Simpson's
house. They tore down Jimmy Stewart's house. Then again, Jimmy
Stewart didn't pay somebody to tear down his own house while he was
still in it. Not even O.J. Simpson did that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
