<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-FAST-COMPUTERS-NYT </SLUG>
  
 FAST NEW PCs COMING FOR THE HIGH-END CROWD  
 (Circuits)  
 (bl)  
 By PETER H. LEWIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   More than half the personal computers sold these days cost less
than $1,000, according to industry researchers, and fewer than 10
percent sell for more than $2,000. With the notable exceptions of
Dell Computer Corp. and Apple Computer, the major computer
companies have been aggressively pushing prices well below $1,000
for entry-level machines.
</P>
<P>
   This does not mean, however, that computer makers are ignoring
the high end of the consumer market. Timed to coincide with the
introduction of several new microprocessors from Intel Corp. this
week, most computer makers announced new systems based on the
450-megahertz Pentium II chip, which is about 15 percent faster
than the previous speed leader for Windows machines, the 400-MHz
Pentium II.
</P>
<P>
   The 450-MHz systems cost at least $2,000, not including
monitors, but industry sources say there are plenty of consumers
willing to pay a premium for the fastest machines available.
</P>
<P>
   The microprocessor is but one component of performance in
desktop PCs. High-end customers are also buying more system memory,
better graphics cards for showing off games and business
presentations and bigger hard disks for storing applications and
files. On top of that, the new pacesetter machines have faster
modems, extra storage systems, including Zip and DVD drives, and
even flat-panel LCD monitors, though sometimes at extra cost.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more intriguing members of the fall class is IBM's
new Aptiva SE7, code-named Cobra, scheduled to go on sale in
mid-September.
</P>
<P>
   Just as it sought to define the high end of portable computing
with its ThinkPad line of laptops, IBM is hoping the all-black
Cobra will become the desktop home computer of choice for people
who want both power and panache.
</P>
<P>
   For a suggested list price of $2,399, the Cobra includes the
450-MHz Pentium II engine with 512 kilobytes of level-2 cache (a
performance enhancer), an unusually large, 16.8-gigabyte hard disk,
128 megabytes of high-speed system memory, 4 megabytes video memory
on an ATI Rage Pro Turbo AGP 2X graphics card, a DVD-ROM drive, a
56K modem, and a pair of Infinity speakers.
</P>
<P>
   IBM will offer, as an option, a matching digital ThinkPanel LCD
monitor. The exact price has not been set, IBM officials said, but
added that the total package of Cobra computer and ThinkPanel
display would cost slightly more than $3,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Way down at the other end of the pricing scale, MEI-Micro Center
(www.mei-microcenter.com), a computer store chain based in
Columbus, Ohio, has just started selling a computer for $399,
believed to be a new low for personal computers running the
Microsoft Windows 98 operating system.
</P>
<P>
   The Micro Center Power Spec 1810 Integrated Multimedia Computer,
as the cheap PC is called, is built around a 180-MHz Cyrix
processor and comes with 22 megabytes of usable RAM, a 1.6-gigabyte
hard drive, a diskette drive, a 33.6K modem, Windows 98 and a
collection of other Microsoft products including Works, Money and
Entertainment Pack. It does not include a monitor.
</P>
<P>
   Judged on specifications alone, the Power Spec 1810 would have
been an impressive machine in early 1993, but today it just barely
clings above the abyss of obsolescence. But Micro Center also
offers systems with substantially more vitality for less than
$1,000, including a monitor.
</P>
<P>
   For consumers whose desires and budgets meet somewhere in
between the IBM Cobra and the Micro Center Power Spec, Intel also
released this week a pair of new Celeron processors that will find
homes quickly in computers costing $1,000 to $1,500.
</P>
<P>
   The first-generation Celeron chips, introduced earlier this
year, were the runt siblings of the Pentium II litter. They lacked
the caching feature found on the Pentiums, which greatly improves
the microprocessor's performance. Some computer makers refused to
include the Celeron chips in their computers, choosing instead to
use superior chips made by Advanced Micro Devices and Cyrix, among
others.
</P>
<P>
   Intel has now seen the light, and the new Celerons introduced
this week have been praised by analysts, especially one that
operates at 333 megahertz.
</P>
<P>
   The Celeron 333 comes very close to matching the performance of
the Pentium II chip at the same clock speed. The other new Celeron
chip, called the 300A, has the 128 kilobytes of cache that was
missing from the original Celeron 300.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
