 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE THURSDAY BUSINESS BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These business stories for release Thursday, August 27, 1998,
are moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the financial (f) category. Stories also
moving in lifestyle will be marked with (f, l).
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, features, sports and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   All stories have moved, except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   CHIPS _ Folo on Applied job cuts. What is happening with its
suppliers and other chip companies in Austin? Will there be a
majaor restructuring of the chip industry in town? Has Austin
shifted from reliance on chips in time? (Ladendorf, Austin
American-Statesman) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-BANKS _ AUSTIN _ After three years of record profits,
Texas banks may be headed for some turbulence. The banks' net
interest margins _ the difference between what banks charge for
loans and what they pay for deposits _ took a nosedive during the
quarter, according to Sheshunoff. (Golz, Austin American-Statesman)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
