<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980826.0311 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3728 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GERALDO-UPFRONT-NYT &LR;      08-26 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERALDO-UPFRONT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`UPFRONT TONIGHT': HERE NOW THE (WINK, WINK) NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Watching Geraldo Rivera and NBC News learn to dance together
brings to mind the old line about the luckier pairing of Fred
Astaire and Ginger Rogers: She gave him sex, he gave her class.
This is not meant as a compliment to Rivera, whose relentless
self-promotion based on little substance makes him more the
journalistic equivalent of Ginger Spice than Ginger Rogers. But the
ratings success of ``Rivera Live,'' the talk show about court cases
that earns CNBC's highest ratings, has led NBC News to make a
devilish bargain.
</P>
<P>
   To prevent Rivera from going to the Fox News Channel, NBC gave
him a six-year, $30 million contract that included a half-hour news
show, ``Upfront Tonight,'' which had its premiere on Monday and is
seen weeknights at 7:30 on CNBC. In this partnership, Rivera gives
NBC News ratings; NBC News gives him instant respectability. He is
being thoroughly bolstered by NBC correspondents who appear often
on both of his programs and by his use of taped reports from ``NBC
Nightly News.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Upfront Tonight'' is a slight program and so far seems the
least significant part of the Rivera contract, which also includes
four news specials a year and a role as legal commentator on
``Today.'' In return, he gave up his syndicated tabloid talk show.
But he has retained his tabloid, show-biz sensibility, in which his
own role appears more important than any report.
</P>
<P>
   ``Upfront Tonight'' looks like a news program, with a sleek,
high-tech set. You can tell it's serious because there is a world
map behind Rivera and his co-anchor, Diane Dimond. It begins with a
few reports from the day's headlines, which on the first two
programs were read awkwardly by Ms. Dimond. A veteran of ``Hard
Copy'' and WCBS-TV in New York, she seemed uncharacteristically
wooden. Perhaps it was because she was saddled with lines to make a
viewer wince, including nightly variations on ``Hurricane Bonnie
still lies over the ocean.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Upfront Tonight'' also includes investigative reports; the
first few were inflated attempts at muckraking. Tuesday's report,
about a mentally ill prisoner in Utah who died last year after he
was strapped naked in a restraining chair for 16 hours, began with
Rivera introducing clips from his own most famous reporting. ``More
than 25 years ago, I helped expose the dreadful conditions'' at
Willowbrook, an institution for the mentally retarded, he said,
taking credit for changes in their treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers were near the end of the Utah segment (complete with
graphic videotape) before its reporter, Jane Wells, acknowledged
that the prison has since changed its policy about using the
restraining chair. (The report's second installment, scheduled for
Wednesday night, discussed those changes.) It was a sound report,
but characteristically overblown.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera's intrusive style would matter less if his reporting were
nearly as substantive or important as he makes it sound. On
``Rivera Live,'' legal analysis is an excuse for relentless pursuit
of the national soap opera of the moment (Simpson, Ramsey,
Lewinsky, whatever). On that program, Rivera is always touting some
secret source of his own, and usually turning up information
everyone else has.
</P>
<P>
   ``John, I've done some reporting,'' he said the other night to
NBC's John Palmer, who was covering President Clinton on Martha's
Vineyard. ``One source says Clinton will leave the Vineyard,''
which plenty of sources were predicting (and which turned out to be
the president's scheduled trip to Worcester, Mass., for a speech
Thursday). In this overheated atmosphere, it is still bizarre to
see serious NBC journalists, like the White House correspondent
David Bloom, toss a report back to the studio with, ``Geraldo?''
</P>
<P>
   Rivera's new contract, he said last year, was about ``seeking
that Holy Grail of redeemed reputation.'' In another often quoted
remark, he said he wanted to sit among ``the wise men'' of
television news. There is nothing wrong with trying to change your
image. But if you want to be taken seriously as a journalist, it
helps not to invoke comic images of frankincense and myrrh. It also
helps not to make nasty personal comments about Peter Jennings or
to call Barbara Walters ``a very sexy babe,'' as he did in a recent
Playboy interview. And it helps to admit that you are not the
story.
</P>
<P>
   As a program, ``Upfront Tonight'' may evolve. It is too soon to
tell much about its ratings. (Its second broadcast reached 307,000
households, a slight improvement on the program it replaced,
``Equal Time,'' but nothing near ``Rivera Live,'' which last week,
in an all-time high, reached a million more homes.) Rivera's
approach shows no signs of changing. Whatever you think about their
judgment, Rivera and Andrew Lack, the president of NBC News, are
smart men; wise is a different matter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
