<HEADER>
A3737 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KING-PROBE-HNS &LR;      08-26 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KING-PROBE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENO ORDERS LIMITED REVIEW OF 1968 KING ASSASSINATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: ``Raul'' and ``Raoul'' are cq) 
 
By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Justice Department will begin a limited
investigation into the 1968 assassination of the Rev. Martin Luther
King Jr., amid claims that confessed killer James Earl Ray did not
act alone, Attorney General Janet Reno said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Coretta Scott King, widow of the slain civil rights leader, had
pressed Reno to launch a wide-ranging investigation after an ex-FBI
agent and a former Memphis, Tenn., bar owner alleged that Ray, who
died April 23 at age 70, either did not kill or had help in
assassinating King. Reno decided to conduct a more limited inquiry
into the assassination, after she had an April 8 meeting with
Coretta King.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope this review will provide answers to new questions that
have been raised about a tragedy that still haunts our nation,''
Reno said. The Justice Department, in announcing the investigation,
stated, ``The evidence gathered during the inquiry will be followed
wherever it may lead.''
</P>
<P>
   Coretta King hailed the pending Justice Department investigation
as ``a first step towards revealing the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department said it will examine a claim made by
Donald Wilson, an FBI agent based in Atlanta at the time of the
shooting, that he found an envelope in Ray's car shortly after the
April 4, 1968, assassination. The envelope contained two pieces of
paper with the name ``Raul'' written on them, Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   Ray said he was framed by a man named ``Raoul.'' However, the
existence of this shadowy figure has never been verified, and the
FBI has discounted Wilson's story.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation will also examine the claim of Lloyd Jowers,
who told ABC-TV's ``PrimeTime Live'' in 1993 that he hired someone
to kill King but that person was not Ray. Jowers said a
now-deceased Memphis produce dealer arranged the assassination.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the slaying, Jowers operated Jim's Grill across
the street from the Lorraine Motel. King was shot and killed by a
sniper while standing on a balcony at the Memphis motel.
</P>
<P>
   In a report issued last spring, the Memphis district attorney's
office said it found no evidence tying Jowers to the assassination.
</P>
<P>
   Ray pleaded guilty in March 1969 to killing King and was
sentenced to 99 years in prison. Ray, who later recanted his
confession, was serving his sentence and seeking a fresh trial when
he died of liver disease and kidney failure at Columbia Nashville
Memorial Hospital in Nashville, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   Coretta King, who believes Ray did not kill her husband, called
Ray's death ``a tragedy ... for the entire nation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``America will never have the benefit of Mr. Ray's trial, which
would have produced new revelations about the assassination of
Martin Luther King Jr., as well as establish the facts concerning
Mr. Ray's innocence,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope this inquiry will open a wider investigation of all
pertinent leads,'' she said. ``When this is accomplished, our
family and the American people will at least have the satisfaction
that all relevant evidence has been fully examined.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno said she will issue a report following the Justice
Department's investigation and decide whether further action is
warranted based on her agency's findings. The attorney general did
not say how long the investigation will take.
</P>
<P>
   If the investigation does uncover a conspiracy to kill King, the
conspirators might escape federal prosecution due to statutory time
limits, the department said. But Tennessee could use the federal
agency's findings to conduct its own state prosecution, because
King was killed in Memphis.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI, which harassed and spied on King in the 1960s, will not
be involved in the investigation. The Justice Department said its
Civil Rights Division will oversee the investigation with
assistance from the Criminal Division.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Kowalski, who led the successful federal prosecution of
Los Angeles police officers who beat black motorist Rodney King in
1991, will lead the department's investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The House Select Committee on Assassinations concluded in 1978
that Ray killed the civil rights leader. The special panel added
that, if Ray was part of a conspiracy, the conspirators were most
likely limited to his family members and militant racists in St.
Louis who had offered a reward for King's assassination.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
