<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3739 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CUL-KELLER-BOOK-REVIE     08-26 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUL-KELLER-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESTORING HUMAN FOIBLES TO AN INSPIRATIONAL ICON 
</HEADLINE>
   (Publication notes at end)  
(rm) 
 By DINITIA SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every American schoolchild learns the story of Helen Keller,
deaf and blind from the age of 19 months, who grew up to read Greek
and to become a best-selling author and social reformer. Keller
could recognize people by the vibrations of their footsteps and
tell a person's mood by the touch of his hand. She could
distinguish between a Southern and a Northern accent, and sense
when a storm was brewing. She symbolized the American ability to
conquer all odds and seemed a figure of perfect, virginal, saintly
rectitude.
</P>
<P>
   Keller has been the subject of a Broadway play, ``The Miracle
Worker''; a movie adaptation of the play and numerous biographical
studies, including Joseph P. Lash's definitive 1980 work, ``Helen
and Teacher.'' Now, Dorothy Herrmann, an author of books on Anne
Morrow Lindbergh and S.J. Perelman, has given us perhaps the most
intimate biography. ``Helen Keller: A Life'' offers few startling
facts about Keller, but it does give her back her sexuality. And in
treating her with a degree of skepticism, it also imbues her with a
true humanity that is sometimes missing from the other portraits.
</P>
<P>
   The central mystery of Keller's life is how she learned to
conceptualize, to render touch and smell into mental pictures,
which she communicated by spelling out messages on her
interlocutor's hand. (Herrmann points out that relatively few
children become deaf and blind at such an early age.) Herrmann
provides a fascinating insight into how Keller developed a form of
language. According to the standard Gesell developmental tests, by
19 months Keller would have been able to recognize her mother,
follow simple commands like ``Come here,'' and identify body parts
like her mouth and nose. These months when her senses were intact
formed the seedbed from which sprang her breakthrough on April 5,
1887, when she was 6, and when her teacher, Annie Sullivan, spelled
``w-a-t-e-r'' on one of her hands while water coursed down over the
other.
</P>
<P>
   Keller always referred to the moment that Sullivan entered her
life as ``my soul's birthday,'' and their relationship was
passionate, ``a complicated interplay of power and dependence,''
Herrmann writes. People compared them to Romeo and Juliet and
Orpheus and Eurydice. Keller lived through her fingers, and there
were moments when her relationship with ``Teacher'' seemed to have
an almost sexual intensity.
</P>
<P>
   Through Sullivan, Keller became famous. The deaf and the blind
were a curiosity among the Victorians. Before Keller, there was
Laura Bridgman, who was blind and deaf but learned to speak in
monosyllables _ and to thread a needle. Keller was a vehicle for
the study of the Platonic notion of innate ideas, that ideas, and
language, are part of the deep structures of the brain.
</P>
<P>
   In the Victorian age, blindness was considered a living death.
There was a terror, before modern embalming, of being buried alive.
In an era when fatal childhood illnesses were common, Keller's
predicament coincided with a national preoccupation with death.
</P>
<P>
   Keller graduated with honors from Radcliffe College in 1904,
when few women went to college. She became a Socialist, a
suffragist and an advocate for the handicapped. Through her
appearances and product endorsements she grew prosperous. America
tolerated handicapped people as long as they were sexless, and
Keller, unmarried, angelic-looking, her face suffused with an inner
light, became an icon.
</P>
<P>
   Herrmann interestingly observes that Keller had a ``special
appeal for beautiful, narcissistic women, many of whom were
fascinated that she had never seen her own reflection in a
mirror.''
</P>
<P>
   But, as Herrmann portrays her, Keller was also a strikingly
sensual full-bodied beauty with lustrous hair. ``In the odor of
young men there is something elemental, as of fire, storm, and salt
sea,'' Keller wrote. ``It pulsates with buoyancy and desire.''
</P>
<P>
   Herrmann recounts the story of Keller's brief engagement to
Peter Fagan, and her mother's successful bid to thwart it. While
Lash speculates that Keller probably sublimated her sexuality for
the higher good, Herrmann suggests that she may have slept with
Fagan.
</P>
<P>
   Keller was not without flaws. She could be sentimental and
naive. Sometimes she seemed to care more for ideals like peace and
justice than she did for people. She denounced capitalism, but she
liked to live well; she was beautifully groomed and her homes had
fine furnishings. Right after the death of her companion, Polly
Thomson, Keller, angry that Thomson had left her out of her will,
began wearing Thomson's $8,000 mink coat.
</P>
<P>
   And then there were the nagging questions about the authenticity
of Keller's achievements. Was her writing, with its ``disturbingly
elaborate visual descriptions,'' as Herrmann puts it, just an echo
of what she had been taught by Sullivan and of other writers' work?
Herrmann relates the events surrounding ``The Frost King,'' a
children's tale that Keller wrote when she was 11 and that was
published as her own work. Keller was accused of plagiarism, which
she denied, but the charge caused her pain for the rest of her
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Helen Keller: A Life'' has some of the texture and the
dramatic arc of a good novel. In Keller's later years, she became a
``luxurious captive,'' Herrmann writes, her caretakers conspiring
around her, and guarded by the essentially mad Thomson. Despite her
efforts, Keller never learned to speak clearly. ``Her voice was to
me the loneliest sound I have ever heard,'' one person said of her,
``like waves breaking on the coast of some lonely desert island.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of her life, in the late 1960's, she seemed to
withdraw, her sensory awareness dulled. Her eyes were glass _ her
real eyes had been removed years before for esthetic reasons _ and
her teeth were false. Her face was vacant of the imprint of normal
human experience, and she was living each day looking forward only
to being reunited in death with ``Teacher.''
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   Helen Keller: A Life
</P>
<P>
   By Dorothy Herrmann
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 394 pages. Alfred A. Knopf. $30.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-26-98 1746EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
