<SLUG> BC-CIR-CARS-PC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THESE BABIES ARE LOADED 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (sidebar with CIR-CARS-CHIPS)  
 (bl)  
 By RICHARD STEPLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With all the computers under the hood, how can you tell what's
going on with your car? One solution is the latest in-dash
computer, Clarion's Auto PC, which can tell the driver exactly what
is wrong with the car and recommend action. Instead of pondering
the generic ``check engine'' light on the dash, you can view a
display on the engine that indicates the specific problem.
</P>
<P>
   The Auto PC, a $1,300 combination computer, radio and CD player,
now available on the Infiniti I30 Executive Luxury Special Edition,
recognizes more than 200 voice commands _ it can check for e-mail,
dial a cellular phone, find a restaurant or hotel _ allowing the
driver to operate it while keeping hands on the wheel and eyes on
the road.
</P>
<P>
   A navigation system is standard, as is an address book, a
mileage log and a hands-free voice memo feature. The Auto PC's
infrared data port permits the exchange of data to and from a
hand-held PC.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of concept cars incorporate new applications for
on-board computers. Because new generations of computers are
introduced far more often than new generations of cars, a docking
port on the Dodge Intrepid ESX2 concept car's dash lets you use the
latest hand-held PC to link with the car's computers. You can also
adda cell phone, a modem for Internet access and a Global
Positioning System.
</P>
<P>
   According to Steve Buckley, a Chrysler electronics specialist,
the module that makes this possible could be installed at
dealerships within two years for less than $100. The prototype uses
a Hewlett-Packard 620LX hand-held computer that connects to the
Internet with a 19.2-kbps wireless modem, giving drivers access to
weather forecasts and traffic reports. ``New York City has a pretty
good real-time traffic Web site,'' Buckley noted. ``It even tells
you where the radar traps are.''
</P>
<P>
   The Network Vehicle from Delphi Automotive Systems, a subsidiary
of General Motors, incorporates computer hardware and software
developed by IBM, Sun Microsystems and Netscape Corp. Using
existing technology, the concept vehicle receives broadcasts from
Hughes DirecTV and DirecPC satellites via a flat antenna imbedded
in its roof.
</P>
<P>
   Other features of the car, which is not planned for production,
include wireless communications, GPS navigation, displays
positioned for eyes-on-the-road control of the system, voice
recognition and access to the Web, including the ability to send
and receive e-mail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-26-98 1746EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980826.0320 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3745 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-CARS-CHIPS-2TAKES     08-26 1320
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-CARS-CHIPS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILL IT UP, WITH RAM: CARS GET MORE CHIPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (bl)  
 By RICHARD STEPLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a long day spent in front of your computer screen, you
need a change of scenery. You get behind the wheel of your car,
start the ignition and step on the gas pedal. Once on the open
road, you feel the rush of freedom: you believe you have finally
left the world of binary code far behind.
</P>
<P>
   You are wrong. Chances are, if your car was built in the last 20
years, you have traded one computer for many. Take, for example,
the simple task of stepping on the accelerator. No connection of
modern human beings to machinery is more visceral and familiar. It
is the simplest and most satisfying of nondigital interfaces: the
heavier the foot, the faster the car goes.
</P>
<P>
   But in Volvo's new S80, the company's flagship sedan to be
released this fall, there is no physical link between the
accelerator pedal and the six-cylinder engine. When you depress the
accelerator, you are actually sending a digital signal to the
engine management computer to open the throttle on the engine. The
benefits include smoother operation and lower fuel consumption and
emissions. The pedal, however, might as well be a mouse.
</P>
<P>
   The accelerator is only the beginning. Computers provide the
smarts for many of the S80s other components, including its
electronic transmission, antilock braking, traction control,
climate control, navigation and communication systems. And in more
or less the same way that a PC can be upgraded from 16 megabytes to
32 megabytes of RAM, the S80's turbocharger can be upgraded, adding
50 more horsepower, simply by changing the software in the engine
management computer.
</P>
<P>
   The company says that the new S80 has ``more computers than a
jet fighter.'' While that may be a bit of hyperbole, the car very
likely represents the state of the art in the marriage of the
computer and the automobile. It may also represent the beginning of
a very different relationship between drivers and their beloved
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The first microprocessor appeared in an automobile three decades
ago, in the 1968 Volkswagen 1600. It controlled the air-fuel
mixture in an electronic fuel injection system, improving fuel
efficiency and engine performance and, more important, paving the
way for cleaner tailpipe emissions as more powerful and
sophisticated engine management computers were developed.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, automotive computers have multiplied like rabbits,
and while cleaning up exhaust emissions may remain the computer's
single greatest contribution to automotive technology, that is far
from the only important function computers perform in today's cars.
</P>
<P>
   Engine management computers, networked with microprocessors,
control the transmission, braking, traction and stability control
systems, giving drivers unparalleled control, particularly on icy
or rain-slicked roads. Computers control front and side air bags
and tighten the seat belts in the event of a collision. They also
command the latest air bag innovation, a curtain that inflates in
25 milliseconds from above the side windows. Appearing on 1999
Mercedes-Benz E-Class sedans this month and on the Volvo S80, the
curtain offers protection for both front- and rear-seat passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Microprocessor-controlled antitheft systems _ combined with a
Global Positioning System (GPS) and a cellular phone _ can track a
stolen car and even let the police eavesdrop on conversations
inside the vehicle. Instrumentation, driver information displays _
miles to go until empty _ climate control and entertainment systems
get their brains from computers.
</P>
<P>
   Even the handheld portable computer has found a new home inside
the car, via an infrared docking port in a prototype system. In
some cars, a computer can even tell you how to fix a flat tire.
Unfortunately, a computer will never be able to do it for you.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the progress of the computerized car hasn't been a
completely bump-free joy ride: consider the annoying and
short-lived fad for cars that ``talked'' in the early 1980s,
insistently reminding passengers to fasten seat belts or that a
door was ``ajar.'' It was as though the car had become its own
back-seat driver.
</P>
<P>
   Sensitive to the failure of these frivolities, car makers are
taking a more pragmatic approach to the incorporation of computers
in their latest offerings. There are certainly more computers in
cars than ever, networked in ever more sophisticated ways, but
their functions are typically transparent to the car's driver and
passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for example, the spin-out. In the days before on-board
computers, drivers were taught to turn the steering wheel in the
direction the car was skidding to maintain control. That's no
longer necessary if the car is equipped with a stability control
system, like those found in models sold by BMW, Cadillac,
Mercedes-Benz and Lexus.
</P>
<P>
   Stability control systems receive data from several sensors,
which is typically updated every 40 milliseconds. For example, a
steering wheel position sensor, as the name implies, tells the
system where the driver intends the car to go. Data on what the car
is actually doing is provided by sensors for wheel speed, sideways
acceleration and the yaw rate _ the rotation of the vehicle around
a vertical axis. The computer compares the car's dynamic
performance as measured by this data with a model stored in memory.
Then it compares that with the driver's intentions. If the computer
detects an incipient out-of-control situation _ the car is
understeering or oversteering _ it orders the engine computer to
reduce power or to apply the brakes on one or two wheels to keep
the car going in the direction the driver intends.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a dramatic feeling,'' said Frank Markus, technical
director at Car &AMP; Driver. ``As you turn the wheel, you'll feel some
momentary slipping, but there's not a lot of herky-jerky motion.
You sense the car slowing down and turning the direction you
want.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there is nothing for the driver to do other than to
trust that the system will work. ``It's like an invisible hand of
God has come down to rescue you,'' said Don Sherman, a contributing
editor at Popular Science magazine. ``You feel the car correct
itself in ways that you cannot normally do _ such as applying the
brake on one wheel.'' Without the computerized stability control
system, he continued, ``you can lift off the gas, apply the brakes,
or turn the wheel, but these actions frequently cannot sufficiently
correct an understeer or oversteer condition.''
</P>
<P>
   What is the car with the most computer chips in the land today?
According to Fred Heiler, a spokesman for Mercedes-Benz, it's the
car maker's flagship S-Class sedan, which, depending on options,
contains between 35 and 40 computers. The 1998 Lincoln Continental
has 26 microprocessors, which control such features as antilock
brakes and traction control, engine and transmission management,
ride control, a GPS, as well as comfort and convenience features
like climate control, interior and exterior lighting, stereo and CD
changer, and remote keyless entry. An additional 14 microchips help
manage the data to make all this possible. The total brainpower in
these 40 chips allows the Continental to process more than 40
million instructions each second.
</P>
<P>
   ``The auto industry has introduced so many new electrical
features that the electrical systems themselves are becoming a
problem,'' said Sven Eckerstein, deputy chief executive of Volvo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wiring has become heavy, bulky and very complex. The
number of connections has increased dramatically.'' Today's Volvos
have 4,000 feet of wiring. By comparison, the 1955 model, the first
sold by Volvo in the United States, had 300 feet of wiring.
``Troubleshooting has become almost a nightmare,'' Eckerstein said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One way to reduce all this complexity is with an on-board
computer network. In 1992, Mercedes-Benz introduced the first
computer area network in its S-Class models.
</P>
<P>
   ``In simple terms,'' explained Dave Acton, a director of
electrical engineering at General Motors, ``it means sending a
number of digitally coded messages down the same wire, something
like the old telephone party lines. One of the benefits is to
permit every electronic module in need of a piece of data _ road
speed, for example _ to obtain that information without having to
send it to each module on a separate wire.''
</P>
<P>
   As in the computer world, software development has become
increasingly important in automotive applications. The idea is
simple and compelling: Why redesign the hardware when a software
upgrade will do just as well?
</P>
<P>
   ``The top guns are now in software development,'' said Heiler at
Mercedes-Benz. At Volvo, the software now gets a part number like
any other component in the car, according to Asko Lyytikainen, an
engineer at the company. ``Conceivably you could recall just the
software, or upgrade it to give the customer more benefits,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   If it sounds as though car makers are building more and more
complexity and features into their products _ more and more things
to malfunction, wear out and need service _ don't worry. Too much.
Networked computers also provide powerful diagnostic capabilities.
So when the ``check engine'' message lights up on your car's
dashboard, it is more than likely that when a mechanic plugs a
diagnostic tester into the car's electronics system, he'll be able
to determine what's wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Diagnostic tools are very powerful,'' Heiler said. ``There's
an amazing amount of information there, and some of it is even
predictive.'' The ability to predict that, say, a catalytic
converter will fail within a certain number of miles is important
to insure that vehicle emissions stay within legal limits.
</P>
<P>
   And in one troubleshooting area the computer is proving to be
invaluable: the intermittent malfunction that occurs only late at
night and far from home and never ever recurs when the car is in
the repair shop. Computers, after all, have memories, and a
mechanic can enter command codes that will retrieve information on
past failures.
</P>
<P>
   ``A trained technician can tell you the specific problem your
car had last Friday at 4:10 p.m.,'' Heiler said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
