<HEADLINE>
LASER TAG: A GAME AT THE SPEED OF LIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By DAVID KUSHNER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    The fighter had just sent Sandman cowering through the fog when
he heard the sound of his shoulder exploding. Sweeping his phaser
around the pylons, he fired wildly into the darkness. Surely his
nemesis could not have come back already; the enemy was probably at
his recharger by now, loading up again on shots.
 &HT;    Sucker! The thought flashed through his mind as he was hit
again, and his shoulder sensor pulsed with blood-colored light.
Looking down _ way down _ behind a green neon-tipped pylon, he saw
Sandman's teammate, Caster Troy. Alas, this was his lethal
assailant _ four feet tall, 9 years old, barely able to wrap her
hands around her phaser.
 &HT;    So it goes in laser tag, perhaps the only sport besides jacks
that allows a fourth grader to whip a 29-year-old weighing in at
200 pounds. And one of the things that levels the playing field is
the technology, a sophisticated system of data exchange that works,
quite literally, at the speed of light.
 &HT;    Inspired by ``Star Wars,'' a Texas inventor named George Carter
is said to have created the first laser tag game in the early
1980s. Carter built a string of Photon Laser Centers in Dallas.
There are now more than 500 laser tag arenas, from Tampa, Fla., to
Sydney, Australia, up from only eight only five years ago.
 &HT;    Though the technology has improved, the essential concept
remains the same. Like a science fiction version of
capture-the-flag, laser tag is played in arenas ranging in size
from 2,000 square feet to 12,000 square feet. Players, either
individuals or teams, don vests stitched with sensors; their
weapons are so-called phasers that shoot infrared rays the sensors
pick up. The phasers also fire red lasers, which are just for show.
There's no danger _ the lasers used for recreation must be approved
by the Food and Drug Administration.
 &HT;    The atmosphere at Lazer Park in New York City at 163 W. 46th
St., just off Times Square, is right out of an ``X-Files'' pursuit.
The arena features a maze of towering black plastic pylons;
machines pump water-based fog; fluorescent black-velvet posters of
lunar landscapes glow on the walls. A high-decibel soundtrack with
bands like the Prodigy keeps the adrenaline flowing.
 &HT;    While the players are chasing and shooting their phasers at one
another, the action is indeed fast-paced _ although, for safety
reasons, running is not allowed. Referees roam the labyrinths to
catch runners and to make sure people are the proper distance away
from each other, and penalize violators by suspending them from
play. After repeated violations, some referees will hold a player's
vest in the air and encourage others to riddle it with shots.
 &HT;    To be an accomplished laser-tagger requires lightning-fast
reflexes, but not necessarily impeccable aim. The radius of the
infrared beam allows someone to score a hit by firing within
several inches of a sensor. For die-hards, there's even the
opportunity to collect statistics throughout a season. At the end
of each game, players leave with a fully detailed printout of their
performances.
 &HT;    Eric Guthrie, executive director of the International Laser Tag
Association in Indianapolis, said companies like Q-Zar, Ultrazone
and LaserTron, which operate arenas around the country, help the
industry generate about $15 million in sales a year. Many in the
business would like to make laser tag a legitimate sport. Leagues
compete weekly. Nearly half the players are teen-aged males (no
surprise there). But increasingly adults are joining the fray.
Guthrie said more and more players are coming from corporations
like Chase Manhattan and Salomon Smith Barney, which use the events
as team-building exercises.
 &HT;    At Lazer Park in Manhattan, the owner, Marc Epstein, credited
the increasingly lightweight and simple game gear with the boom in
business. ``We try to provide something high-tech that will keep
people coming back,'' he said. ``If you have the right mix, you
forget about your hard day at work and feel like you've been in
another world. We put you in an alternate reality.''
 &HT;    To get there, players at most arenas pay about $5 for a
five-minute game. Home versions are also popular, but jumping over
couches in one's living room just doesn't have the same oomph as
dodging shots in an arena.
 &HT;    At Lazer Park, a 31-year-old player who would give only his
nickname, Slippery Weasel, said he preferred the excitement of
laser tag over PC shoot 'em up games like Doom and Quake. After a
particularly rigorous match, Slippery Weasel stood outside the
arena dripping with sweat. ``Instead of watching a video game,'' he
said, ``you're in it.''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ARMED, BUT NOT DANGEROUS: LASER TAG GEAR
 &HT;    c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vest: Made of polyethylene foam with a Leatherette finish, the
eight-pound vest contains four sensors (one on each shoulder, the
chest and the back) that register hits in all directions from the
phasers' infrared rays. When hit, the sensors vibrate and flash;
shoulder speakers emit the sounds of explosions and ``Great shot!''
Powered by a central processing unit, the vest has a digital
readout on the front displaying how many shots and lives the player
has remaining, plus the score and the vest's identification number
throughout the game. A radio transmits and receives game data to
and from the transceiver. A battery supplies energy for up to 12
hours.
</P>
<P>
   Phaser: This plastic, soft foam-insulated phaser is connected by
a cord to the vest. When fired, each phaser simultaneously produces
two beams: laser and infrared. The laser beam is harmless, similar
to the beams used in laser pointers. It's the invisible infrared
ray that transmits all the necessary data to sensors on the vests
and bases. A digital readout on the back of the phaser displays a
player's remaining shots and lives.
</P>
<P>
   Game computer: A Pentium-powered personal computer runs laser
tag with customized software. The PC exchanges information with the
transceiver.
</P>
<P>
   Transceiver: The eyes and ears of a laser-tag game, this
one-square-foot black box hangs in the middle of the arena and is
hard-wired to the game computer. The transceiver uses a
900-megahertz restricted band radio, similar to what a cordless
phone would use, that transmits and receives information. It
converts the computer's digital data into radio waves, then
transmits to the vest packs. Data coming from the vests is picked
up by the transceiver, converted back to digital information, then
sent back to the game computer.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Base station: Each team has a base station at its end of the
arena, fitted with sensors similar to those on the vest; a player
can earn points by hitting the opposing team's base with a phaser
blast. At each station, a recharger that transmits radio waves
automatically updates players' vest packs with shots and lives each
time someone passes by it.
</P>
<P>
   When the game starts: After obtaining game-play data from the
game computer, the transceiver signals the vest packs to update to
the appropriate number of shots and lives. Once the vest packs are
charged up, the game begins, with players shooting at the opposing
team and its bases. Every second, the transceiver polls the vests
for new information by sending a radio signal to and from each vest
and each base. Along the way, the information is translated into
digital information for the game computer.
</P>
<P>
   Scoring: Each player's infrared ray carries an identifying piece
of data. Say Player 8 on the Red team shoots Player 7 on the Green
team. Player 8's infrared ray hits player 7's sensor, causing it to
flash, vibrate and produce sound effects. When the transceiver
polls the players' vests, it will be alerted that Red Player 8 has
hit Green Player 7. It will then increase and lower their scores
accordingly, and tell Red Player 8's shoulder speakers to say
``Great shot!''
</P>
<P>
   Hitting Your Opponent's Base: The scoring process is the same as
when a player shoots another player, except that the bases are
linked directly to the game computer; the main transceiver is not
used.
</P>
<P>
   Scorecard: At the end of the game, the computer kicks out a
scorecard for each player with game statistics: who you tagged,
where you tagged them (shoulders, front or back), where you were
tagged and your overall ranking.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
