<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOND PRICES RISE AMID CONCERNS OVER RUSSIAN ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Prices of Treasury securities edged up Wednesday,
amid fresh concerns about Russia's economic crisis and the raised
anxiety level of world equity markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market appeared a bit wobbly today, even as it partially
ignored the release of July durable goods orders due to the
problems in both Russia and Latin America,'' said Anthony Chan,
managing director and chief economist for Banc One Investment
Advisers in Columbus, Ohio. Durable goods unexpectedly rose 2.4
percent last month, their biggest monthly gain in almost a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is probably safe to say that credit markets have already
priced in much of the bad news coming out of Asia, but in the
scheme of things,'' he said, ``Russia and Latin America are the new
kids on the block, which have not been fully discounted by credit
markets.'' Recalling the unfolding of the Asian crisis, he added,
``We may be entering another stage in which credit-market investors
will wake up every morning checking to see what is happening in
Russia and for the prospects in Latin America for that day before
even wondering about which U.S. economic statistics are scheduled
for release.''
</P>
<P>
   By late in the day, the Treasury's 30-year bond was up 4/32, to
a price of 101 7/32, pushing down its yield, which moves in the
opposite direction, to 5.42 percent, from 5.43 percent on Tuesday.
Bond yields are at their lowest levels in three decades.
</P>
<P>
   Chan said the greatest fear among bond investors was whether
they could justify paying more for bonds _ and pushing yields below
5.50 percent _ without an intelligible indication from the Federal
Reserve that the central bank was close to easing short-term
interest.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday the Fed was in the bond market to satisfy its
seasonal needs. In the process, known as a coupon pass, the Fed
bought $1.521 billion in securities. The maneuver added to the
banking system and provided some support to the longer maturities.
</P>
<P>
   The report on July durable goods orders, which was released
early in the session, surprised investors because the aircraft and
electrical order components were so strong that they more than
offset the weakness in autos caused by the General Motors Corp.
strike. However, economists said that the seasonal adjustment
factor for July is especially aggressive to account for the
shortfalls that occur while automakers retool for the next season's
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The market also had to deal with supply Wednesday, as the
Treasury sold $15 billion of new two-year notes at an auction,
which went a little better than expected. The notes were sold at a
yield of 5.125 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, it was a busy day in the municipal market, with $1.6
billion in one-year notes from Texas and nearly $1 billion in new
bonds, including a $542.7 million refunding deal from Utah's
Intermountain Power Agency, with a maximum preliminary yield of
5.25 percent for a bond due in 2019.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-26-98 1758EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
