<DOCNO> NYT19980826.0327 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3767 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SOHO-ART-955(2TAKE     08-26 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SOHO-ART-955(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: THE GHOSTS OF SOHO 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By ROBERTA SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Every swan has its song. The SoHo area is losing out
to Chelsea as the center of the downtown gallery scene and filling
ever more rapidly with hotels, cosmetic boutiques, home-furnishing
stores and designer-shopping opportunities. Its farewell melody to
the art world may be Rachel Whiteread's self-effacing site-specific
sculpture, ``Water Tower.''
</P>
<P>
   The work, a life-size cast in greenish translucent resin of the
interior of a New York wood-slatted water tower, occupies that
ubiquitous structure's natural habitat, a life-size New York roof.
This one is six stories above the intersection of Grand and West
Broadway, the epicenter of the area's thriving bistro scene.
</P>
<P>
   It's a beautiful piece, silent, ghostly, responsive to changing
light, and so fused with its site that it becomes a fitting
memorial to the neighborhood itself. Elevated on its own platform,
it is flanked by several nearly identical versions of the real
thing, to which it relates as a translucent, freshly shed snakeskin
relates to a snake.
</P>
<P>
   The work, which is sponsored by the Public Art Fund, also
suggests a crown so weightless that it might drift skyward at any
moment. (In fact, it is to stay put until next June.) From certain
distances, it hovers near invisibility: You can see blue sky
through it. At night it fades to pale gray, matching the eternal
twilight of New York's glowing, nocturnal sky.
</P>
<P>
   The sculpture is one of the latest, and best, efforts from an
English artist who frequently makes casts of the interior volumes
of things. Made from voids, like all cast sculptures, these pieces
flatfootedly memorialize a familiar but absent object. Previous
Whitereads have used mattresses, bathtubs, the spaces beneath
tables and chairs. An early work, a cast of an entire room, was
appropriately titled ``Ghost.''
</P>
<P>
   To those who have witnessed SoHo's transformation over the last
two or three decades, ``Water Tower'' may memorialize more than
just the increasingly antiquated object that served as its mold. It
symbolizes SoHo's role as an art neighborhood, or village, a place
that in its heyday introduced so much new art _ especially
installation and site-specific art _ and is now changing beyond
recognition and all expectation.
</P>
<P>
   The piece sharpens the eye to see all kinds of things about SoHo
past and present, most immediately the ancient, enormous Coca-Cola
sign painted on the side of the building it is installed on. As it
fades, the names of other painted-over signs are surfacing,
creating a touchingly decrepit collage of word fragments and
letters that begs to be photographed by Robert Rauschenberg, Aaron
Siskind or Walker Evans.
</P>
<P>
   SoHo was pioneered mostly by artists from the
counterculture-baby-boom generation that reached voting age in the
1960s. They were more numerous than preceding generations of
artists and the first to be almost entirely educated at art
schools. Maybe that's one reason the place came to feel like an art
campus, where many of the faces on the street were familiar and the
mood was a little removed, almost insular.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the beauty and unity of SoHo's cast-iron
architecture, which has helped make it the most stylish mall in
America, was also a factor.
</P>
<P>
   In the late '60s and early '70s these artists started flocking
to the area, once dominated by light manufacturing, in search of
studios to live and work in. SoHo had a lot of empty warehouse
space that rented cheaply and seemed perfect for artists of all
varieties, especially those working in the relatively new media of
installation and site-specific art.
</P>
<P>
   Early signs of their arrival were 112 Greene Street, an
intermittently artist-run space that gave early exhibitions to
artists as disparate as Vito Acconci, Susan Rothenberg and Harriet
Korman, and Food, a collaborative health-food restaurant at the
corner of Prince and Wooster (now a trendy boutique), where artists
and dancers took turns cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Art galleries were not far behind, the first being Paula Cooper
and O.K. Harris, who ran shoestring operations compared with the
sleek professionalism that followed. The official opening of the
SoHo art scene and land rush occurred in September 1971, when four
prominent uptown dealers (Leo Castelli, Ileana Sonnabend, John
Weber and Andre Emmerich) opened galleries in a big loft building
at 420 West Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Rumblings of the Future
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately there were objections, like the rhyming,
slightly profane signs that demanded, in part, ``Bring Back the
Trucks.'' But the artists and galleries had started something that
soon had a life of its own.
</P>
<P>
   I remember a sense of awe and there-goes-the-neighborhood
foreboding in 1977, when Giorgio DeLuca's tiny Cheese Shop (now a
fancy takeout place called Olive) crossed Prince Street, became
Dean &AMP; DeLuca and began making retail history.
</P>
<P>
   The next year brought ``An Unmarried Woman,'' Paul Mazursky's
film about a divorced woman (Jill Clayburgh) pursuing a career in
painting that included a scene shot in the Spring Street Bar. These
were mere glimmers of the trendiness _ and rising real-estate
values _ to come.
</P>
<P>
   There are still plenty of galleries in SoHo, but they have
ceased to define the neighborhood's character, which is a strange
cross between Milan's Via della Spiga _ a place where every
high-end fashion designer feels the need to have a presence _ and
Coney Island.
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically, the galleries are now marginalized, on the brink
of assuming an underground position, as they did in the East
Village, which may have its advantages. Walking through SoHo to
visit these galleries, I sometimes feel like an alumna at a college
reunion, surprised by the way the place has changed.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   I first lived in the area as a college student 30 years ago,
when it was still known as the Cast Iron District. At night it was
eerily quiet and empty, which seems unimaginable given its
vociferous night life these days. It was also quite dark; the few
lighted windows signaled where artists lived.
</P>
<P>
   Also part of the nocturnal experience was the smell of freshly
baked bread and doughnuts emanating from the Bakery Building at 130
Prince St., a 1930s industrial building that shortly progressed
from being a prospective private museum to a cluster of swank
galleries to its current incarnation as design and advertising
offices, its remaining galleries having moved en masse to Chelsea
last spring.
</P>
<P>
   Other addresses are similarly layered. I remember when the
Mercer Hotel was the Reese Palley Gallery, when Boom was WPA, and
even before that, when it was Kast's, a narrow coffee shop with
bare wood booths. There, an innocent from the middle of the Middle
West, I had one of the first toasted bagels of my life.
</P>
<P>
   But you know you're not in Kansas anymore when your first
inkling that the Mercer Hotel is finally open for business is a big
glossy spread in Vogue; when news of the opening of Sephora, a huge
makeup emporium on Broadway, is brought to you by W.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the installation pieces are likely to be encountered in
the windows of fancy stores _ displays whose creators have learned
a few tricks from installation art.
</P>
<P>
   At the corner of Prince and Wooster streets is Pleats Please, a
new store selling intricately pleated garments designed by Issey
Miyake. Its windows are coated with a pale green film that changes
in density as you walk past, creating the illusion from some angles
that the store is filled entirely with glowing Kryptonite, as well
as an experience of hazy light not unlike an installation by Robert
Irwin.
</P>
<P>
   Phantoms of the Old SoHo
</P>
<P>
   The paler green Whiteread is invisible to anyone who doesn't
know to look for it, just as SoHo's history is invisible, at least
until it is thoroughly recorded, to anyone who didn't experience
it. Anyone who did has a personal bank of memories, an assortment
of odd collisions between past art and present commerce that can be
activated by a walk along the area's glamorous streets.
</P>
<P>
   The Blum Helman Gallery on Greene Street, where I first saw
Charles LeDray's miniaturized garments on the floor, is now the
Helmut Lang store. Tony Shafrazi's old gallery, once the site of
Keith Haring's raucous shows, houses the designs of Marc Jacobs.
Annina Nosei's old gallery, where Jean-Michel Basquiat made his
debut, is now occupied by Miu Miu.
</P>
<P>
   And rumors of the demise of 420 West Broadway, which have
flitted through the art world for more than a year, are gaining
substance. In the September issue of Artforum, Sonnabend has taken
out an ad announcing that it will relocate to Chelsea in early
1999.
</P>
<P>
   It's not hard to imagine the building as a series of emporiums
Armani, Klein or Karan. And as if to keep the circle unbroken,
Comme des Garcons, the designer that led the fashion incursion into
SoHo in 1983, will close its Wooster Street store next week, and
reopen on 22nd Street in Chelsea in December.
</P>
<P>
   But some things still haven't changed. Walking around at night,
you can still look up and see lofts that must belong to SoHo's
longtime artist-residents, safely ``grandfathered.'' They tend to
be the ones that look seriously unrenovated, complete with dirty
walls, old fluorescent light fixtures and plenty of exposed
electrical conduit.
</P>
<P>
   In one of these windows, I recently saw a large old sign
prominently and, I think, deliberately, displayed, a coded reminder
of the neighborhood's previous incarnations. It read ``E. &AMP; H. Kast
Restaurant, est. 1891.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
