<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: DREAMING AND DANCING; RECONSTRUCTING CHAUCER; THE
CIVIL WAR IN SONG; `CORPUS CHRISTI' IS BACK;  
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What has two Martha Grahams, two Vaslav Nijinskys, a
drag psychiatrist, Judy Garland songs and rave reviews? It's
``Dream Analysis,'' the Mark Dendy Dance and Theater work that
opens the Dance Theater Workshop's fall season Thursday night at 8
at the Bessie Schonberg Theater, 219 W. 19th St. The dance play, a
hit of the Altogether Different Series last season, is built on a
dream recounted to a psychiatrist by a troubled young man.
</P>
<P>
   Word Games
</P>
<P>
   Biochemists at Cambridge University are applying computer
programs used in genetic research to reconstruct the text of the
14th-century manuscript of Chaucer's ``Canterbury Tales.'' Because
the original was lost and later versions vary widely, scholars have
long argued about which are most accurate. The journal Nature
reported Wednesday that the 58 surviving 15th-century manuscripts
of the Wife of Bath's prologue had been fed into a computer, which
identified several versions previously ignored by scholars as being
close to the original. ``In time,'' the report says, ``this may
lead editors to produce a radically different text of `The
Canterbury Tales.'''
</P>
<P>
   Incoming
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ April 22, 1999, is the date, and the St. James
Theater is the place. The event is the musical ``The Civil War: Our
Story in Song.'' Composed by Frank Wildhorn (``Jekyll and Hyde'')
and written by him, Jack Murphy (``Silver Dollar'') and Gregory
Boyd, the artistic director of the Alley Theater in Houston, the
show draws on letters, diaries, contemporary accounts and speeches
and the poetry of Walt Whitman to recount the personal and
philosophical conflicts of the war.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Corley is handling the staging; George Faison, the musical
staging. Jerry Zaks is the creative consultant, and professor Eric
Foner of Columbia University is the historical consultant. Before
going to Broadway, ``The Civil War'' will play the Alley Theater
from Sept. 16 through Oct. 11 and the Shubert Performing Arts
Center in New Haven, Conn., from Feb. 16 through March 7.
</P>
<P>
   Update
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Rehearsals are under way for the Manhattan Theater
Club production of Terrence McNally's ``Corpus Christi.'' The show
about a gay Jesus-like figure attracted protests last spring from a
Roman Catholic civil rights group and bomb threats, was removed
from the club's schedule and was then reinstated after outraged
artists accused the theater of being intimidated into
self-censorship. With Joe Mantello directing a 13-member cast,
``Corpus Christi'' begins previews on Sept. 22
</P>
<P>
   Scott Glenn and Amanda Plummer are Off Broadway bound, to star
in a revival of ``Killer Joe,'' the Tracy Letts play that is
opening in preview on Oct. 18 at the SoHo Playhouse at 15 Vandam
St.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
