<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3780 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KING-DREAM27-COX     08-26 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KING-DREAM27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    35 YEARS LATER, KING'S 'DREAM' STILL NOT REALITY
 &HT;    620&AMP;add. With KING-DATA.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the 35 years since the Rev. Martin Luther King
described a ``dark and desolate valley'' of racial segregation in
his ``I Have a Dream'' speech, America has yet to meet King's
challenge to make real its promise of brotherhood to African
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly in economic terms, the dream of political, social
and economic brotherhood that King shared with the hundreds of
thousands who gathered at the Lincoln Memorial on Aug. 28, 1963 is
a dream deferred for many minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways, we haven't made much progress,'' said Margaret
Simms, an economist and vice president of research at the Joint
Center for Political and Economic Studies, the premier think tank
on issues affecting African Americans.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, of course, all minorities have made tremendous
progress since the ``Jobs and Freedom'' march came to the capital
in 1963. The huge, peaceful gathering helped persuade lawmakers to
sweep away legal barriers to voting, jobs, housing and education,
and set up a system of affirmative action to begin making amends
for past discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   There is considerable evidence that even the private attitudes
of Americans _ and especially those of Southerners _ about racial
matters have changed dramatically since King offered his vision of
a time when Americans would be judged by their character rather
than their skin color.
</P>
<P>
   ``In small towns and rural communities all across the South,
people are in the process of laying down the burden of race,'' Rep.
John Lewis, D-Ga., said in an interview Wednesday. ``We've come a
distance.''
</P>
<P>
   Few Americans can measure that distance as accurately as Lewis,
one of the defining figures of the modern civil rights movement.
And yet, for all the ``sense of hope and optimism'' that he
encounters today in his extensive travels as a member of Congress,
Lewis said that as a nation, ``we have not yet arrived at the
beloved community'' King envisioned.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, ``some people today, blacks and whites, probably don't
believe that we will ever be able to 'sit down together at the
table of brotherhood' or that the 'American dream' King spoke of so
fondly was ever real,'' said Stephanie Larson, a professor at
Dickinson College.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are currently nowhere near the point of realizing much of
King's dream,'' she added. ``Certainly, Mississippi is not 'an
oasis of freedom and justice,' nor are we a nation with 'a
beautiful symphony of brotherhood'.''
</P>
<P>
   But today, in Jackson, Miss., where voter registration workers
were met in 1961 by Mayor Allen Thompson with a machine
gun-equipped tank, the mayor is a young black man, Harvey Johnson
Jr. Likewise, today in Birmingham, Ala., where Police Chief Bull
Connor turned fire hoses on black children in 1963, the mayor,
Richard Arrington, is black. And the park where children's marches
took place is now a memorial to the civil rights movement.
</P>
<P>
   However, the political gains of African Americans have far
outrun social and economic gains.
</P>
<P>
   The Urban League's latest report on ``The State of Black
America'' notes, for example, that African Americans own about 8
cents of wealth for every dollar owned by whites. African Americans
still lag whites in income, employment and educational attainment
as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We, as a nation, have a difficult time confronting the legacy
of racism, the continuing existence of racism, and recognizing the
benefits that whites receive from American society simply by virtue
of being white,'' said Paula McClain, a professor at the University
of Virginia. ``The legacy of race and racism continues to haunt us,
but we treat them like the crazy aunt or uncle in the attic that we
try to ignore and not acknowledge even as their presence creates
tremendous difficulties for us.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Complicating matters is that the rhetoric of King's ``I Have a
Dream'' speech has been ``hijacked'' by those who oppose racial
bias remedies such as affirmative action, said Yvonne
Scruggs-Leftwich, executive director of the Black Leadership Forum,
an umbrella organization for the nation's most prominent civil
rights groups.
</P>
<P>
   Not so, said Gerald Reynolds, president of the Center for New
Black Leadership, a political conservative group at the forefront
of the movement to abolish affirmative action. ``To say we have no
right to honor Dr. King in our way is ridiculous,'' Reynolds said.
</P>
<P>
   But even Reynolds acknowledged that the economic advancement of
African Americans has fallen short of the goals King set in his
speech to the multitudes at the Lincoln Memorial, though he
questioned whether ``any government program can help'' achieve
those goals.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, however, much of the progress that has been made in
the 35 years since the March on Washington has been clouded by the
constant _ and sometimes simplistic _ celebration of King's ``I
Have A Dream'' speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically, we are trapped by this repeated broadcast of the
speech,'' said David Garrow, author of ``Bearing the Cross,'' a
widely acclaimed book about King and the organization he founded,
the Southern Christian Leadership Conference. ``I have worried for
years that especially with younger folks, this portrayal of King as
this Horatio Alger-esque optimist makes him less interesting and
less challenging and less relevant.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the attention to the speech ignores the transcendent
nature of the March on Washington, said Roger Wilkins, a historian
at George Mason University and the nephew of the late Roy Wilkins,
longtime leader of the NAACP.
</P>
<P>
   ``For those of us who were there, the inspiration of that day
lives on,'' Wilkins said. ``It was a rare display that made the
nation, for that moment, believe that it could be better than it
ever was before. Whether it could happen again, who knows? But the
struggle continues on a less elevated plane, but it keeps on.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
