<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3783 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BONNIE-COASTAL-COX     08-26 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONNIE-COASTAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    People living near the North Carolina coast did little more than
wait
 &HT;    By Stuart Savage
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, N.C. _ While the nation watched, people living near
the North Carolina coast did little more than wait.
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie's sluggish pace hardly helped residents of New Bern,
Vanceboro, Washington and other near-coastal regions decide what to
do. Each weather update showed Bonnie's course had changed. So most
people played it safe, stirred to caution by memories of Fran and
Bertha two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Looking over the Trent River in New Bern, Carmalita Wetherington
described how Fran twisted bridges like snakes, mangled boats and
drove water within inches of her doorstep.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like to keep an eye open,'' said Ms. Wetherington, 61.
``We've seen some wild things here.''
</P>
<P>
   Once burned, twice shy was the only advice most hurricane
veterans needed. Bonnie, a category three storm, projected by late
afternoon Wednesday to land near New Bern, was expected to cause
serious flooding in the Albemarle and Pamlico regions. Surges 12
feet or more were expected to force water into the critical areas
where the Neuse, Trent, Pamlico and Chowan rivers flow into the
ocean.
</P>
<P>
   That was compounded by the threat of water swells spilling over
the banks of Wilmington's Cape Fear River, which Bonnie reached at
about 4 p.m. Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In nearby Pamlico County, officials had evacuated low-lying
areas Tuesday, including Hobucken, Lowland and Goose Creek Island,
said Martin Beach, county manager and acting emergency management
coordinator. Fourteen Pamlico County residents stayed at Chicod
School in Pitt County Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Beach said his county shelter, at Pamlico Community College,
could hold 300 people. ``Basically we're in a hunker down mode,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Craven County, Stanley Kite, the emergency services director,
said four shelters were open.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are about 550 people at the shelters now,'' he said
shortly after noon. But, he said, ``We have a lot of people on the
highway and roads. We're pleading with people to seek shelter, move
further inland.''
</P>
<P>
   Uncertainty about when or where the storm would touch down left
many taking the high road.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Chambliss, dock master at the Sheraton Hotel and Marina on
Front Street in New Bern, said boat owners removed their vessels
before the high winds and rains began Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a busy day yesterday and last night. These docks can't
handle 125 mile-per-hour winds. Fran really played havoc with this
place,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing waist-high, yellow wading pants, Chambliss, 69 and a
dock master for more than 13 years, calmly admitted he could do
little else than evacuate the water.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get very concerned,'' he said. ``You just go to work and
get ready for it. We've done all we can do. The worst that could
happen would be a 12- or 14-foot water surge,'' he said, adding,
``The best would be for this storm to just break up.''
</P>
<P>
   Desk attendants at the hotel reported no rooms were available by
noon Wednesday. The hotel offered a lower rate to accommodate the
unexpected business.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, Craven County residents could stay in several
shelters in Vanceboro, New Bern and Havelock.
</P>
<P>
   In Kinston, Roger Dail, emergency management director for Lenoir
County, said people were coming in to the shelter at the Lenoir
Community College.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can put 500 or 600 there,'' he said. ``It's just a wait,
watch and wait game now.''
</P>
<P>
   Communities around New Bern faced the on-coming storm with
caution and awe. Residents flocked to grocery stores, where they
emptied shelves of bread, water, ice, milk and canned food.
</P>
<P>
   A flurry of shoppers to Kite's IGA in Vanceboro caused a parking
shortage and sent drivers scrambling for parking spots on the
streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just trying to get some food in the house,'' said
cashier Shirley Gaskins.
</P>
<P>
   By mid-afternoon, the situation became serious for Billy
Whichard, who owns Whichard's Beach resort near Washington. Heavy
mists, whitecaps and the constant sound of the Pamlico River
lapping against the bulkheads made his dock a lonely outpost.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wind has gotten up quite a bit. I think the tide's on its
way in now, for good,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The marina and campground cleared out earlier and only two empty
recreational vehicles sat, unattended. They may or may not make it,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of them was here during Fran,'' he said, adding, ``We had
some that only had the chassis left.''
</P>
<P>
   Fran, which caused flooding in Raleigh and devastated the coast,
followed Bertha, which swept through the state in the summer of
1996. Whichard said those storms destroyed his game room and tore
the walls, windows and doors out of the covered building near the
marina.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had water in here four feet deep,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Beaufort County shelters were at Washington, Northside and
Chocowinity high schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did a mandatory evacuation of low-lying area,'' a spokesman
said. ``But I have no idea of the number of people that left. If
they got water during Fran, they can expect pretty much the same
this time,'' she predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Whichard vowed to remain at the marina, which his father began
in the mid-1940s, as long as possible, just as he has before every
hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd normally stay here until just before it's unsafe to get
out,'' he said. ``I wouldn't like to see it, but it looks like it's
going to get worse before it gets better.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The DAILY REFLECTOR, GREENVILLE, NORTH CAROLINA
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
