<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3784 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BONNIE-PITT-COX     08-26 1315
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONNIE-PITT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NORTH CAROLINA COUNTY POUNDED BY BONNIE
 &HT;    By Dawn Bryant
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The high winds and heavy rain of Hurricane Bonnie started
pounding Pitt County late Wednesday afternoon, hours after the
storm was expected to hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wind has picked up tremendously,'' Greenville Fire-Rescue
Chief Raymond Carney, the city's emergency coordinator, said about
4 p.m. after a relatively quiet morning. ``Things are going to pick
up really soon Q extremely soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Wind speeds had doubled by the afternoon, with gusts up to 50
mph, Carney said. Conditions were getting worse about 4 p.m. at The
Daily Reflector's early press time.
</P>
<P>
   About the same time, two and a half inches of rain fell in
Greenville in an hour. Spot flooding from the heavy downpour was
reported at First Street and parts of Evans Street and Red Banks
Road, with crews dispatched to post 'high water' warning signs.
Parked cars reportedly started flooding.
</P>
<P>
   County and city emergency centers started receiving calls of
downed tree limbs and minor debris blowing into the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel like this is probably what we are in for for the next
few hours,'' Greenville Public Information Officer Katie Veilleux
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Greenville Utilities Commission reported the first of what
was anticipated to be many power outages about 3:30 p.m. About 60
residents on Skinner Street, Cadillac Drive and Jefferson Drive had
lost power.
</P>
<P>
   Crews were waiting for wind speeds to decrease so they could
respond, GUC Public Information Officer Sue Bizzaro said.
</P>
<P>
   Pitt County residents woke up Wednesday morning to partly cloudy
skies and barely a breeze Q not at all what forecasters had
predicted a day before with Hurricane Bonnie approaching.
</P>
<P>
   Effects of the storm were expected to hit Pitt County early
Wednesday, bringing winds of about 40 to 60 mph that would
strengthen during the day to about 80 mph, with the worst
conditions developing about midafternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie changed her mind, slowing its course and leaving
residents and emergency officials ready and in limbo.
</P>
<P>
   While the Pitt County Emergency Operations Center kept its 3
a.m. opening time, the city of Greenville delayed activating its
center at the Police-Fire Rescue Building for a couple of hours
until about 9 a.m. Officials were trying to prevent workers from
overloading and being exhausted by the time the hurricane Q and
most of the work Q hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hurricanes have their own personalities,'' Veilleux said while
standing in the relatively quiet headquarters Wednesday morning.
``You just have to be prepared to watch and adjust. This one is so
big.''
</P>
<P>
   The 400-mile wide, category 3 hurricane, packing 115-mph winds,
sped up its course toward the North Carolina coast Tuesday then
slowed that night.
</P>
<P>
   Pitt County opened shelters at five local schools at 5 a.m., and
about 700 residents had flocked to those by 3:30 p.m. By then,
forecasters predicted the storm would hit that evening.
</P>
<P>
   The coffee pots at the city's emergency operations center were
still full at mid-morning, a sign of the unexpected slow activity
as Bonnie still had not arrived.
</P>
<P>
   It was the same scene at the county's center at 6 a.m., with a
few workers answering the sparse calls from residents mainly asking
about closings.
</P>
<P>
   During the height of a storm, the center, with more than 20
phones, is busy with callers reporting damage or needing help.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at both centers keep their eyes on television reports
and radar images.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has gotten their stuff in place and is waiting for
the actual landfall,'' Pitt County Public Information Officer Arlen
Holt said Wednesday afternoon. ``The storm is slowing down so much
it looks like it will hit tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   With that delay, some officials, after the early morning start,
took an afternoon break to save up energy for the brunt of the
storm.
</P>
<P>
   The extra preparation time gave county officials the chance to
test new strategies, including a computer-faxing system used to
send information.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying some things for the first time, although we have
practiced,'' Holt said. ``In some respects, this time is good
because we are able to iron out some of the kinks.''
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials used the time to review
after-hurricane responses. They have two main priorities following
hurricane destruction: injuries and looting.
</P>
<P>
   When trees topple onto houses or winds rip through homes,
electricity and telephones are the first to go, Pitt County
sheriff's Lt. Ron Smith said. That makes finding help that much
harder for the injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the storm, we'll go out in the areas and assess damage,
looking for injury. The second thing will be the security of any
destructed areas Q looting, vandalism,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   The devastating tornadoes that killed nine people and injured
100 in March 1984 led to looting problems, he said. It is something
officials are wary of when businesses are damaged, opening them up
as easy targets.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd be surprised. People will do that,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   The National Guard helped the county watch for looting problems
in 1984 and has been called out for Bonnie as well. Gov. Jim Hunt
declared a state of emergency Tuesday, dispatching 150-member units
to Greenville, Tarboro and Lumberton. The soldiers will respond to
requests from state and local emergency officials for assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Greenville Police Department and the Pitt County
Sheriff's Department stationed officers throughout their coverage
areas in preparation for the hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   City officers were using fire departments and city buildings for
shelter, Major J.M. Simonowich said. The department also went to
12-hour shifts, bringing in extra officers.
</P>
<P>
   Deputies were stationed in every area of the county Wednesday
morning, including a deputy in each of the shelters. The Sheriff's
Department called for extra personnel and was expected to need HAM
radio operators to help with communication.
</P>
<P>
   The department had its mobile command center prepared and gassed
up. With the command center, the Sheriff's Department can stay out
of the weather, lay out maps, organize searches and communicate
with other agencies during disasters.
</P>
<P>
   The break frustrated rural power providers at Edgecombe Martin
and Pitt &AMP; Greene electric membership corporations, which provide
electricity to nearly 19,000 people in Pitt and surrounding
counties. They serve about 5,000 people in Pitt County.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a nervous fit,'' said Mark A. Suggs, Pitt &AMP; Greene's
vice president and general manager. ``We want it to go ahead and do
what it's going to do or go away ... staying in a perpetual state
of preparedness is aggravating.S
</P>
<P>
   The utilities have been preparing since Monday, coordinating
efforts with other cooperatives through a central emergency center
in Raleigh. Co-op crews from Georgia, South Carolina, Virginia and
western North Carolina will respond wherever they are needed, and
the utilities have contracted with private companies to assist with
tree removal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of people and a lot of equipment ready to move
quickly,'' said Suggs, whose company serves primarily the Farmville
and Fountain areas. ``We're just waiting to see what we need, where
we need it and how much of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Edgecombe-Martin serves customers primarily in the River Road,
Pactolus and TranterUs Creek areas. That company on Wednesday sent
its crews home to rest in anticipation of a busy day today, said
Eddie Stocks, key account manager.
</P>
<P>
   RDuring the brunt of the storm, thereUs not much we can do but
sit tight and wait for it to get over. Then we'll get out, assess
the damage and get to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The DAILY REFLECTOR, GREENVILLE, NORTH CAROLINA
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-08-26-98 1726E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
