<HEADER>
A3785 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BONNIE-STUDENTS-COX     08-26 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONNIE-STUDENTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    East Carolina University students playing it safe
 &HT;    By Judy Royal
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It wasn't their ideal way to spend a day off from classes, but
Meredith Neely and Amy Floyd didn't want to take any chances.
</P>
<P>
   The East Carolina University students filled their backpacks
with toothbrushes, snacks and other essentials before heading to
one of Pitt County's five hurricane emergency shelters Wednesday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just would rather be safe than sorry,'' Ms. Neely said,
rocking back on her green canvas cushion, which straps together to
create a backrest like a chair.
</P>
<P>
   The women, sitting on the steps outside C.M. Eppes Middle School
in Greenville, are neighbors at an apartment complex near Pitt
County Memorial Hospital. Neither felt safe weathering the storm
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We watched the building behind us go up, and it took about
three weeks. This building has to be built better than ours,'' Ms.
Floyd said.
</P>
<P>
   Uncertain about how their homes would endure Hurricane Bonnie,
hundreds of people like Ms. Neely and Ms. Floyd gathered up their
belongings and loved ones to seek refuge in the relative safety of
emergency shelters officials established at five county high
schools.
</P>
<P>
   The shelters opened their doors at 5 a.m., six hours earlier
than the original schedule, because meteorologists originally
predicted the storm's effects would touch Pitt County a shortly
before noon.
</P>
<P>
   But people waking up Wednesday morning must have somehow known
Bonnie was planning a late arrival.
</P>
<P>
   At 6 a.m. a group of Department of Social Services workers at
Ayden-Grifton High School ate biscuits from Hardee's and watched a
small black and white television to get the latest weather updates.
</P>
<P>
   They had no one to keep them company until three people signed
in at the shelter almost an hour later.
</P>
<P>
   The couple and their 13-year-old grandson fled their mobile home
near the Pitt-Craven County line, Murl Keyes said.
</P>
<P>
   She came prepared with food, blankets, pillows, quilts, a small
mattress and plenty to keep her busy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I brought my radio and I brought my Bible and I got a book
that I want to read,'' Ms. Keyes said.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, James Keyes, seemed content with just a chair to
occupy him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always keep it with me. My legs aren't that good,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Grandson Carlos Curry sat on the floor with his head against the
wall, hoping others would soon join his family.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't have to wait long.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after 7 a.m. a few cars pulled in, and by 3:30 p.m. the
original three had 185 others joining them.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Ayden-Grifton, D.H. Conley High School began getting a
crowd shortly after opening. By 7:30 a.m. almost 50 people set up
camp in hallways. That number grew to 182 by 3:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Many were repeat customers, remembering past hurricanes, Shelter
Manager Al Waters said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fran made a believer out of everybody around here. They're
better prepared,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Melinda Ellison, who sat out Fran and Bertha at the same
shelter, brought 10 other family members with her this time. Some
live in mobile homes and a few in a house, but all were unsure of
Bonnie's effects on their residences.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ellison made two trips to pick up loved ones from Grimesland
and Winterville, including her 7-month-old daughter, Jamia
Worthington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the head of this household,'' Ms. Ellison said, drawing
laughs from her family as she sat down in the middle of her group,
which included eight children.
</P>
<P>
   The youngsters watched a small television they brought, lost
themselves in music from portable compact disc players, shuffled
through cards and ripped open bags of animal crackers as more
people staked out floor space.
</P>
<P>
   They played, chatted and made the best of the situation as if it
were recess, not an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ellison's nephews, Timmy West, 13, and Xavier Guions, 10,
took turns cheerfully picking on each other to pass the time, while
the adults joked about what Bonnie had in store for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it gets rough, I'm getting out of this hallway and going
into the bathroom,'' Ms. Ellison's mother Maggie Ellison said.
</P>
<P>
   Jim and Brenda Richardson's children Q Hope, 11, and Ryan, 5 Q
were a little more timid than those in the Ellison bunch. Both
admitted they were a little scared of the storm.
</P>
<P>
   The family's mobile home in the Wintergreen area withstood the
hurricanes of 1996, but Richardson decided to seek shelter early
Wednesday morning to outsmart Bonnie's uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know what's going to happen, how it's going to
change or what it's going to do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson couldn't have summed it up any better.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Neely and Ms. Floyd kept an eye on weather conditions
throughout the late morning, wondering when Bonnie would make the
grand entrance everyone had been talking about.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters kept postponing the storm's original predicted
arrival time of noon as hours slipped by without any signs of the
hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   But by presstime the rain and wind marched in and warned of an
evening thrashing by Bonnie. Many people at the shelter brought
only enough food and clothing to get them into late Wednesday, but
a sleepover seemed imminent.
</P>
<P>
   No one doubted Bonnie's force, but everyone wanted the storm to
make a quick exit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather it just start now,'' Ms. Floyd said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The DAILY REFLECTOR, GREENVILLE, NORTH CAROLINA
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-08-26-98 1727E
</P>
