</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONNIE-ECU-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ECU student have little fear of hurricane
 &HT;    By Clejetter Pickett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, N.C. _ While concerned parents kept phones ringing
at the East Carolina University Housing Office on Wednesday, the
threat of Hurricane Bonnie caused little fear in students like
freshman Ron Eshbach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been through hurricanes before, and it ain't no big
deal,'' the Sanford native said. ``Some people are pretty scared,
but some of them are laid back like me Q whatever happens,
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Eshbach, who lives in ECU's Aycock Hall, had made no
preparations for the arrival of Hurricane Bonnie as of noon
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't alone.
</P>
<P>
   With classes canceled, many of the 5,000 dorm residents took the
unexpected day off to play football, wash laundry and even study Q
despite instructions from the Housing Office to take precautions
such as moving themselves and their valuables away from windows.
</P>
<P>
   ``My fan is still in my window,'' said sophomore Angela Baker.
``I'm not worried, I'm doing laundry.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker, who is from Fayetteville, said having a hurricane is
``cool.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been through a lot of storms, and me and my older brother
usually go outside and run in the wind,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Angela Farrior of Jacksonville said having grown up on
the coast has made her somewhat hurricane savvy also.
</P>
<P>
   However, she said she would take precautions if necessary,
including moving from her sixth-floor room to the hallway of a
lower floor if the winds got too high.
</P>
<P>
   The Housing Office instructed residential advisors to have
students move to safer areas of the dorms when winds got above 60
mph. Students also were given tips on how to prepare for the storm,
including to have drinking water, flashlights and battery operated
radios, University Housing Director Manny Amaro said.
</P>
<P>
   No evacuations were planned at ECU because the dorms are
considered to be structurally safe, he said. In fact, Amaro said,
some of the 100 calls his office received Wednesday morning were
from parents of students who live off campus but wanted to move
inside the dorms until Hurricane Bonnie passed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are worried about their kids. I would be, too,'' Amaro
said.
</P>
<P>
   However, ECU does not allow students who live off campus to
temporarily move in the dorms, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Courtney Doyle, a junior who lives in Fletcher Hall, agreed with
Amaro that her dorm is a safe place to be, at least during this
storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm worried about my parents because my parents live up in
Kill Devil Hills and didn't leave. So I wouldn't want to be home
right now,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The DAILY REFLECTOR, GREENVILLE, NORTH CAROLINA
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-08-26-98 1730E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
