u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BONNIE-NORMAL-COX     08-26 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONNIE-NORMAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Anything but a normal morning for coastal residents
 &HT;    By Dawn Bryant
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE _ Hurricane Bonnie's delayed arrival here caused some
regular Wednesday activities to continue on what was expected to be
anything but a normal morning.
</P>
<P>
   With only wind and sporadic showers early Wednesday, some
regular routines didn't change. The post office delivered first-
and second-class mail, city Public Works crews collected garbage
and some stores opened as usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of our job,'' letter carrier Leslie Fowden said as
he slid envelops in the mailboxes at Eastbrook apartments. ``We
carry it until we think it would be unsafe.''
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating the storm, city, county, East Carolina University
and Pitt County schools announced Tuesday they would not open
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Officials and residents, already prepared for the potential
power outages and flooding, waited much of the day for those things
to happen.
</P>
<P>
   Main tenants at University Commons, including Target and Barnes
&AMP; Noble, opened on time while some of their neighbors posted signs
on the taped windows notifying would-be shoppers the stores were
closed because of the weather.
</P>
<P>
   How long stores would stay open was a guess.
</P>
<P>
   ``That just depends on Bonnie,'' Target manager Mark Koukal
said. ``We are going to do our best to stay open for the people who
need supplies. We've had quite a few people coming in getting
last-minute things.''
</P>
<P>
   A steady stream of shoppers filtered into the two stores, some
getting last-minute supplies while others were just killing time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're buying curtains,'' Greenville resident Martha Moore said
as she walked into Target about noon. ``We're just bored and tired
of waiting for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenville resident Jane Brown was prepared for Bonnie's
effects, with batteries, flashlights, bottled water and food ready.
She also removed items from her yard that could catch flight in
high winds.
</P>
<P>
   ``You name it, we've done it,'' she said, wearing a yellow rain
jacket.
</P>
<P>
   Brown made one more stop Wednesday at Barnes &AMP; Noble.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are buying magazines to read by candlelight,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   With most residents ready Tuesday evening for the predicted
early morning hit, Bonnie's delay had caused some impatience by
mid-Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of wish it would hurry up and get here so we can get
back to normal,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   The Plaza Mall had its doors open Wednesday morning but most
stores Q with the exception of a few food vendors and Radio Shack Q
were closed.
</P>
<P>
   Inside Radio Shack, manager Joyce Griswell took repeated
requests for D-size batteries, telling anxious weather watchers
that a stash was expected that afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   One angry customer wandering into Radio Shack complained that
the mall's barber shop was not open. Ms. Griswell found the man's
complaint bizarre considering the circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``He
</P>
<P>
   f+i
</P>
<P>
   had
</P>
<P>
   f-i
</P>
<P>
   to get his haircut before the storm,'' she said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Veronica Streeter took advantage of her unexpected day off from
teaching to pay a bill at University Commons. She was optimistic
that the light rain and winds would be the only effects locals
would see.
</P>
<P>
   Those conditions also were a pleasant surprise when she woke up
Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said 'thank you Lord,''' Streeter said. ``I'm thinking this
right here is what we are going to get. I'm tickled to death this
is it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some evacuees from the coast who are staying in Greenville
hotels also took some time to shop.
</P>
<P>
   Steve and Pat Nelson, Pine Knoll Shores residents staying with
friends in Greenville during the storm, stopped by Target to pick
up some items for their planned trip to Ireland on Friday. Pat had
to convince her husband to leave their hometown and seek shelter
here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sat out the last hurricane Q Fran in September '96. It was
a little frightening for me,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Greenville prepares for hurricanes as much as their coastal
town, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're impressed,'' Pat Nelson said before the couple stopped
by a local eatery for lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie interrupted Bill and Chantel Mauney's honeymoon on the
Outer Banks, with the couple checking into the Ramada Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just came here for a couple of days until they tell us we
can go back, Bill Chantel said as he smoked a cigarette outside
Barnes &AMP; Noble. ``Honestly I expected it to hit a little earlier
this morning. I'm shocked it has stayed out there as long as it
has.''
</P>
<P>
   (Staff Writer Greg Rickabaugh contributed to this story.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The DAILY REFLECTOR, GREENVILLE, NORTH CAROLINA
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-08-26-98 1728E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
