<SLUG> BC-BONNIE-TRAILER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Trailer park residents uneasy
 &HT;    By Greg Rickabaugh
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE _ The door to Tonia Moore's trailer hung open Tuesday
just after 1 p.m. as rain sprinkled outside at Quail Village
Trailer Park in Greenville.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Bonnie was on its way, but Tonia and Co. weren't
budging.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to sit here until I have to move,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Tonia's mother, Deborah, and 3-year-old son, Ronald, sat with
her and watched the television weather reports, which they
frequently switched between local meteorologist Phillip Williams
and The Weather Channel.
</P>
<P>
   While the family may be stubborn, it wasn't stupid. Bags in
nearby rooms sat packed with snacks and a change of clothes for
each of them in case they needed to head for one of five schools
where Pitt County officials established shelters.
</P>
<P>
   Wait-and-see seemed to be the overwhelming philosophy at the
trailer park
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Edna Godley will wait until Bonnie is knocking on her
back door.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the wind starts going and the trailer starts shaking,
that's when I'll get out,'' she said, standing outside in her
bathrobe watching the storm clouds loom.
</P>
<P>
   With no telephone or transportation, Ms. Godley didn't know how
she would leave, but expected someone would give her a ride to
safety.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, she waited until the last minute and ended up
hanging out in the Emergency Room lobby at Pitt County Memorial
Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt better there than in the trailer. They said anyone who
stays in a trailer, if it starts getting bad, they're supposed to
leave,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Godley was crossing her fingers that Bonnie would leave her
alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it will go back the other way,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction to Bonnie was mixed at Pinecrest Mobile Home Park,
just down the street. Some evacuated early; others went for the
wait-and-see approach.
</P>
<P>
   Rodrigo Nunez and family followed the lead of local businesses
and put duct tape across their small windows in typical ``X''
fashion. While his neighbors had moved to a hotel on Tuesday, he
preferred to stick around.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it gets worse, we'll go to my brother's house,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nunez's 10-year-old daughter, Miriam, didn't appear scared.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe in God and God will help us,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Clara Little took the same attitude back at Quail Village
Trailer Park, where she kept a close eye on the news alongside
boyfriend David Worthington. The couple was prepared to drive to
Raleigh for a friend's house just in case.
</P>
<P>
   But she didn't expect they would have to.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be fine,'' she said. ``We're going to ride with
faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The DAILY REFLECTOR, GREENVILLE, NORTH CAROLINA
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
