<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRELAND AND ENGLAND SAY CRACKDOWN WON'T THREATEN PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JAMES F. CLARITY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN, Ireland _ Prime Ministers Bertie Ahern of Ireland and
Tony Blair of Britain said Wednesday that the Northern Ireland
peace agreement would succeed despite a terrorist bombing 10 days
ago and that the new security measures they propose will help
curtail future attacks.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing, by a Catholic splinter group calling itself the
Real IRA, killed 28 people in the town of Omagh.
</P>
<P>
   The prime ministers, after meeting in County Mayo, western
Ireland, emphasized that the new security measures would not cause
political problems in the new Northern Ireland Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly, which reconvenes Sept. 14, will deal with a number
of volatile political and security issues as it carries out the
agreement, which gives minority Catholics more power and the
overwhelmingly Catholic Irish Republic more influence in the
affairs of the mostly Protestant northern British province.
</P>
<P>
   The two leaders said the security measures, expected to be
approved by their Parliaments next week, were aimed at cracking
down on a handful of paramilitary dissidents who have not called
cease-fires, as have the Irish Republican Army and all the major
Protestant guerrilla groups.
</P>
<P>
   But the governments' decision to enact laws making it easier to
convict suspected terrorists has been attacked by both Sinn Fein,
the political wing of the IRA, and by hard-line Protestant leaders.
Sinn Fein says they are too harsh; the hard-liners say they are too
soft.
</P>
<P>
   Martin McGuinness, the No. 2 Sinn Fein official and a member of
the new Assembly, said Wednesday that the proposals were tantamount
to internment, the preventive detention of suspects without trial.
The Blair government eliminated internment last year. It is still
possible under Irish law, but Ahern said he has no immediate plans
to use it.
</P>
<P>
   The governments have clearly tried to show the public that, in
the wake of the latest terrorist atrocity, they are doing
something. At the same time they do not want to push either
Catholics or Protestants in the Assembly into hard-line positions
on questions like prisoner release and disarmament of
paramilitaries.
</P>
<P>
   To keep control of unionist votes in the Assembly, David
Trimble, the body's first minister, must seem, like the
governments, to be tough on Catholic terrorists. But Gerry Adams,
the Sinn Fein president, who was interned by the British as an IRA
leader in the 1970s, must hold the traditional Republican hatred of
any hint of internment and shortcuts to conviction. If Trimble or
Adams lose control of their Assembly members, it could delay or
collapse the Assembly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
