<P>
   HURRICANE BONNIE
</P>
<P>
   ATTN EDITORS: Here are resources Cox has covering Hurricane
Bonnie:
</P>
<P>
   _ Atlanta has reporters Marlon Manuel and Chris Burritt in N.C.
for the duration of the storm. Their stories are scheduled to move
on the Cox wire by 8:30 every evening. Also, AJC photographer W.A.
Bridges Jr. will file photos.
</P>
<P>
   _ All three daily Cox papers in N.C. are in the path. Greenville
will file a late-night story on damage after the storm hits, and
will post photos of any destruction on the server.
</P>
<P>
   _ Elizabeth City, on the coast, and Rocky Mount, a couple hours
inland, are afternoon papers whose stories are moving in the
afternoon on the Cox wire. They also will post photos on the Cox
server.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also: West Palm Beach will file a story Danielle, which to
this point is tracking in Bonnie's same path.
</P>
<P>
   BONNIE _ Waiting to see what damage Hurricane Bonnie does to the
North Carolina coast. (Burritt/Manuel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   SCENE _ MOREHEAD CITY, N.C. _ The scene outside along the coast.
(Burritt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) w/photos.
</P>
<P>
   SHELTER _ Talk of those in storm shelters throughout North
Carolina. (Manuel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) w/photos
</P>
<P>
   BONNIE-PITT _ GREENVILLE, N.C. _ The high winds and heavy rain
of Hurricane Bonnie started pounding Pitt County late Wednesday
afternoon, hours after the storm was expected to hit. ``The wind
has picked up tremendously,'' Greenville Fire-Rescue Chief Raymond
Carney, the city's emergency coordinator, said about 4 p.m. after a
relatively quiet morning. ``Things are going to pick up really soon
Q extremely soon.'' (Bryant, Daily Reflector) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BONNIE-STUDENTS _ GREENVILLE, N.C. _ It wasn't their ideal way
to spend a day off from classes, but Meredith Neely and Amy Floyd
didn't want to take any chances.
</P>
<P>
   The East Carolina University students filled their backpacks
with toothbrushes, snacks and other essentials before heading to
one of Pitt County's five hurricane emergency shelters Wednesday
morning. (Royal, Daily Reflector) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BONNIE-NORMAL _ GREENVILLE, N.C. _ Hurricane Bonnie's delayed
arrival here caused some regular Wednesday activities to continue
on what was expected to be anything but a normal morning. With only
wind and sporadic showers early Wednesday, some regular routines
didn't change. The post office delivered first- and second-class
mail, city Public Works crews collected garbage and some stores
opened as usual. ``It's part of our job,'' letter carrier Leslie
Fowden said as he slid envelops in the mailboxes at Eastbrook
apartments. ``We carry it until we think it would be unsafe.''
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating the storm, city, county, East Carolina University
and Pitt County schools announced Tuesday they would not open
Wednesday. (Bryant, Daily Refelctor) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BONNIE-COASTAL _ GREENVILLE, N.C. _ While the nation watched,
people living near the North Carolina coast did little more than
wait. Bonnie's sluggish pace hardly helped residents of New Bern,
Vanceboro, Washington and other near-coastal regions decide what to
do. Each weather update showed Bonnie's course had changed. So most
people played it safe, stirred to caution by memories of Fran and
Bertha two years ago. (Savage, Daily Refelctor) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BONNIE-TRAILER _ GREENVILLE, N.C. _ The door to Tonia Moore's
trailer hung open Tuesday just after 1 p.m. as rain sprinkled
outside at Quail Village Trailer Park in Greenville. Hurricane
Bonnie was on its way, but Tonia and Co. weren't budging. ``I'm
going to sit here until I have to move,'' she said. Tonia's mother,
Deborah, and 3-year-old son, Ronald, sat with her and watched the
television weather reports, which they frequently switched between
local meteorologist Phillip Williams and The Weather Channel.
(Rickabaugh, Daily Refelctor) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BONNIE-ESU _ GREENVILLE, N.C. _ While concerned parents kept
phones ringing at the East Carolina University Housing Office on
Wednesday, the threat of Hurricane Bonnie caused little fear in
students like freshman Ron Eshbach. ``I've been through hurricanes
before, and it ain't no big deal,'' the Sanford native said. ``Some
people are pretty scared, but some of them are laid back like me Q
whatever happens, happens.'' Eshbach, who lives in ECU's Aycock
Hall, had made no preparations for the arrival of Hurricane Bonnie
as of noon Wednesday. He wasn't alone. (Pickett, Daily Refelctor)
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   PBP-DANIELLE (developing, with graphic) _ Update on Hurricane
Danielle. Surfing conditions are excellent with waves breaking at 6
feet at the shoreline, will have numbers on rescues, water
district's plans to lower canal levels, pet shelters booked, EOC
plans, etc. Hurricane Danielle strengthened with steady winds
reaching 100 mph as the storm made a line towards the Caribbean.
(Moffett, Masory, Brogan, Pallesen and Kleinberg, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   LAREDO-FLOOD _ Laredo got hit hard by the Rio Grande flooding on
Wednesday _ worse than predicted. We're there for a straight hard
news story describing how bad it gets. Whether the bridges stay
flooded for long is a major point. (Wear, Tanamachi,
Haurwitz/Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   FLOOD-COLONIAS _ If homes in the Colonias are wiped out, will
authorities allow the troubled settlements to be rebuilt? (Wear,
Tanamachi, Haurwitz/Austin American-Statesman). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   FLOOD-DELRIO _ Gov. George W. Bush tours Del Rio. Also, the San
Felipe Creek neighborhood was evacuated again Wednesday morning.
And other news developments that may arise, including the possible
finding of more bodies. (Harmon, Haurwitz/Austin
American-Statesman). WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   MLK _ Attorney General Janet Reno reopened the investigation of
the 30-year- old assassination of civil rights leader Martin Luther
King Jr., focusing on two allegations of a conspiracy beyond James
Earl Ray. (ABrice, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ECONOMY _ MOSCOW _ The Russian Central Bank announced
that it would no longer intervene in propping up the country's
sagging ruble against the U.S. dollar. Within 45 minutes of the
opening of trading on the currency markets, the ruble fell five
percent -- after a 10-percent slide on Tuesday. Officials halted
trading after the first hour, and later said they would invalidate
all transactions that had happened on Wednesday. In further
evidence of falling confidence in the deteriorating economy, the
run on the banks has begun with hundreds of Russians standing
outside banks demanding money. (Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move by 5 p.m. EDT in both the (i) International and (f)
Financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   JOURNAL-RUSSIA _ MOSCOW _ The search for U.S. dollars is
reaching a fever pitch during the current economic crisis in
Russia. A drastic change in the situation either Monday or Tuesday
for the better not withstanding, the dollar supply has dried up and
Russians and expatriates are unable to lay their hands on
greenbacks. American Express Corp., a major money-changer here, is
holding up wire transfers from the States. It has been almost
impossible since Monday, Aug. 17, for Visa and American Express
card-holders to get cash from ATMs here. One woman said she was
preparing to cash dollars for rubles and was accosted outside a
currency-exchange booth by Russians begging to buy her $20 bill.
And then there's me, the absolute wolf of Wall Street, who shrewdly
exchanged $1,000 for rubles at the 6.2 rate on Monday, literally
minutes before the government announced its devaluation. Go figure.
(Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Tuesday, Aug. 25, in both the (i) International and
(k) Commentary categories for use Thursday, Aug. 27.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   KING-DREAM _ WASHINGTON _ In the 35 years since Dr. Martin
Luther King Jr. delivered his ``I Have a Dream'' speech at the
Lincoln Memorial, how have economic and social conditions changed
for African Americans? A look at the story told by Census Bureau
data. (Shepard, Cox News Service).
</P>
