<SLUG> BC-TV-SURFER27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Group pickets CNN: Tailwind seen as cause
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   About 10 U.S. military veterans held an Operaton
Tailwind-related protest outside CNN Center in Atlanta Wednesday,
wearing T-shirts advocating a boycott of parent company Time Warner
Inc. and handing out leaflets to CNN staffers entering the
building. ``We're angry at the lies being told,'' said George
Forsyth, who paid his own way from New York City to protest.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Marzullo of Englewood, Colo., one of the protest's
organizers, said CNN's Tailwind story, which alleged U.S. nerve gas
use in 1970 but was then retracted by the network, is still being
used in other countries to attack the United States, despite the
retraction. Marzullo and a few of the vets met with CNN spokesman
Steve Haworth Wednesday and suggested a forensic examination of the
site in Laos to prove or disprove the allegation; further action
against correspondent Peter Arnett, who was reprimanded but not
fired, and more positive stories on the U.S. military. Haworth said
he promised to relay the veterans' concerns to CNN senior
management.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we did anything at all,'' Marzullo said, ``I think we
planted a few seeds of ways they could fix this situation.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
