<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3832 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOB-HEARING-BOS &LR;      08-26 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOB-HEARING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOBSTER CHALLENGED ON CLAIM OF FBI IMMUNITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA NEALON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ As Stephen Flemmi has said repeatedly from the witness
stand, he and his criminal partner James ``Whitey'' Bulger had a
simple deal with the FBI: they would be ``protected'' from
prosecution in exchange for information on the Mafia.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday, after Flemmi testified in federal court that his
longtime protector, agent John Connolly, had no role in payoffs to
his corrupt supervisor, John Morris, a federal prosecutor had an
obvious question _ was Flemmi now returning the favor?
</P>
<P>
   ``You're now trying to protect John Connolly like you think he
protected you all those years?'' asked Assistant US Attorney Fred
M. Wyshak Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I'm not,'' replied Flemmi.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Flemmi's version of events contradicts testimony by
Morris in April, and conveniently removes Connolly from Morris's
most damning claims: that Connolly delivered two $1,000 payoffs to
him.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, Morris said Connolly handed one payoff to Morris's
girlfriend, an FBI secretary, after Morris asked Connolly to get
the money from Bulger and Flemmi. The cash paid for her to fly to a
Georgia training program Morris was attending.
</P>
<P>
   The second payoff was hidden in a case of wine that Morris said
Connolly loaded into the trunk of his car at FBI headquarters in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Flemmi said he knew nothing of either payment and reiterated
that the only money he and Bulger gave Morris was a $5,000 ``loan''
that he never repaid. Flemmi denied he had ever given any money to
Connolly.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he had ever given Connolly a diamond ring for his wife,
Flemmi replied, ``I don't recall giving John Connolly any diamond
ring or recall anything of that nature.''
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview Wednesday, Connolly said, ``That is a
question that only a rogue prosecutor would ask and it is
consistent with the smear campaign that Mr. Wyshak has perpetrated
against me from the outset of these hearings.'' Connolly called the
suggestion about the diamond ring ``absolutely untrue.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Morris, Flemmi recalled the men exchanged inexpensive
Christmas gifts: Bulger and Flemmi gave Connolly an Alcatraz belt
buckle and a decorative knife, as well as books.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was aware that Connolly had taken a vacation with
Bulger, Flemmi said, ``I'm not aware of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, Morris testified that Connolly and his former wife
had once stayed at a Provincetown inn with Bulger and his
girlfriend, which Connolly dismissed at the time as ``utter
nonsense.'' Connolly also said he did not recall receiving the belt
buckle or the knife.
</P>
<P>
   Morris, who was Connolly's supervisor in the FBI's organized
crime squad from late 1977 to early 1983, testified under a grant
of immunity. Connolly has refused to testify without a similar
arrangement with prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   But in an interview last spring after Morris's testimony,
Connolly called the allegations ``a malicious lie.''
</P>
<P>
   Flemmi, who was cross-examined for a fifth day Wednesday, is
trying to convince US District Judge Mark L. Wolf to dismiss
extortion and murder charges pending against him because the FBI
had promised him immunity in exchange for information he provided
as an informant.
</P>
<P>
   The government denies Flemmi's claim and says that any such
promises, if made, were improper and legally unenforceable.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, his fifth day on the witness stand, Flemmi would not
answer questions about his alleged involvement in eight murders,
his extortion of bookmakers, or his and Bulger's efforts to control
drug dealing in South Boston.
</P>
<P>
   He refused to discuss their forced takeover of a South Boston
liquor store from a couple who had just purchased it, and invoked
his Fifth Amendment right against self-incrimination at least 80
times.
</P>
<P>
   He would not even acknowledge that the FBI questioned him about
the May 1981 murder of World Jai Alai owner Roger Wheeler in
Oklahoma, and he refused to answer when Wyshak asked if Connolly
had ever told him that Edward ``Brian'' Halloran had implicated him
and Bulger in Wheeler's murder.
</P>
<P>
   Halloran, a fringe gangster, was murdered a few months after he
began cooperating with the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Wyshak also accused Flemmi of regularly feeding Connolly
information that pointed away from them and toward others _ such as
when he linked the murder of World Jai Alai president John ``Jack''
Callahan to a Cuban group in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him what I wanted to tell him,'' Flemmi said.
</P>
<P>
   When Wyshak asked Flemmi if he believed Connolly had broken the
law in his dealings with him, Flemmi quickly answered yes, but
suddenly changed his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I was concerned,'' Flemmi said, ``everything he did
was legal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
