<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3833 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT &LR;      08-26 0424
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, Aug. 27, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday afternoon, Hurricane Bonnie began to slow along the
southeast coast of North Carolina as it entered a zone of listless,
high-altitude steering winds. On Thursday, the lethargic storm will
drift northeast over eastern North Carolina with diminished winds,
setting the stage for recurrent heavy rains as far north as
southeast Virginia. Serious flooding is likely across eastern North
Carolina and southeast Virginia. Strong winds and heavy surf could
prevail as far north as southern Delaware and eastern Chesapeake
Bay.
</P>
<P>
   The cool front that caused severe thunderstorms in parts of
Connecticut Wednesday will stall and weaken along the Northeast
seaboard. Some showers and thunderstorms will develop in eastern
New England along the remnants of the front. Farther inland,
sunshine and comfortable afternoon temperatures will prevail.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Southeast will be sunny and unusually hot with light
winds. Afternoon temperatures between 95 and 100 degrees will be
common in the interior Gulf Coast states. A few afternoon
thunderstorms will form over central and southern Florida as a weak
tropical disturbance passes the area.
</P>
<P>
   Clusters of showers and thunderstorms will move from the
southern Missouri Valley to the western Great Lakes. In the wake of
the disturbance, most of the Plains will be sunny and hot.
</P>
<P>
   In the West, seasonable warmth will cover the Rockies. There
will be a few isolated afternoon thunderstorms in the central and
southern Rockies, but otherwise sunshine will be plentiful. Except
for patchy morning coastal clouds, the West Coast states will be
dry and warm.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Obligatory Watch
</P>
<P>
   An obligatory tornado watch was posted for east North Carolina
Wednesday as Hurricane Bonnie approached land. Almost all
hurricanes making landfall south of New England spawn tornadoes as
they come ashore. Many twisters form in the right-front quadrant of
the hurricane (relative to the eye). Here, onshore winds ease
slightly, due to the greater friction of land, while winds at 5,000
feet blow fiercely. The difference in wind speed causes air to spin
around a horizontal axis. Tornadoes form when rising currents of
air tilt these horizontal rolls into spinning, vertical columns of
air.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-26-98 1841EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980826.0356 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3835 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGO-REBELLION-ART-5     08-26 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGO-REBELLION-ART-565&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT FORCES AND REBELS FIGHT IN CONGO CAPITAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINSHASA, Congo _ The sound of explosives and gunfire
reverberated throughout the capital early Wednesday as government
and rebel forces fought on the city's outskirts.
</P>
<P>
   The government of President Laurent Kabila said its forces and
allies had used machine-guns, mortars and rockets against a column
of rebel soldiers; it is not clear how the rebels returned fire.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting was concentrated in a eucalyptus field near
Kinshasa airport, less than 20 miles southeast of the city center,
government officials said. It marked the most intense fighting near
the capital since the rebellion began on Aug. 2 from the eastern
Congo and spread to the region southwest of here.
</P>
<P>
   When the government's new 12-hour curfew went into effect at 6
p.m., the streets were calm and the sound of fighting had ceased.
But it was unclear whether the government had succeeded in crushing
the rebels' last-ditch attempt to seize Kinshasa, or whether the
rebels were regrouping and planning another assault.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be either of those things,'' said a European
ambassador. ``It could be that we're witnessing the actions of a
lone rebel holdout, or it could be something much more significant
than that. I'm not planning to go out tonight to find out.''
</P>
<P>
   In the city's diplomatic and business center, government
soldiers blocked roads, stopped people from circulating on the
streets and searched the trunks of the few vehicles allowed into
the area.
</P>
<P>
   Government trucks filled with soldiers and armored tanks could
be seen rumbling through deserted avenues, leaving wide white
tracks on the asphalt. Many appeared headed toward the presidential
palace, which lies beyond Kinshasa's former world trade center, an
abandoned skyscraper atop which a giant sign sports this
war-ravaged country's former name, Zaire _ minus the ``a'' and
``r.''
</P>
<P>
   In La Cite, where most of the city's 5 million people live,
residents said the streets were deserted in the morning, as
government soldiers ordered people to stay home. Later in the
afternoon, after the shelling had died down, residents said
soldiers had started allowing people to travel.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's public transportation now and we can circulate,'' said
a UNICEF worker who lives in La Cite. ``But there are barricades
everywhere and the soldiers are not allowing us to carry our
cellular phones.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, since Angola and Zimbabwe began providing arms
and troops to Congo's beleaguered army, the rebels seeking to
overthrow Kabila have been in retreat in the region southwest of
here.
</P>
<P>
   Congo and its allies recaptured a critical military airport. And
although rebels still hold a crucial hydroelectrical dam that
supplies power to this region, the government and its allies appear
to have eliminated the threat to Kinshasa, which at one point
seemed likely to fall any minute.
</P>
<P>
   But even as the pro-government troops made progress in the
southwest, an undetermined number of rebels lingered in the areas
just south of Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
   The government has downplayed the presence of rebels nearby,
saying its soldiers were merely taking steps to completely
eradicate guerrillas from the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the beginning of the end for them,'' said Dr.
Jean-Baptiste Sondji, the health minister. ``We're not completely
free yet of these infiltrators. They could still inflict some small
damage on us. But it's the beginning of the end.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Sondji said the pro-government forces had attacked a rebel
column of 500 soldiers, most of them former soldiers in the army of
the longtime dictator, Mobutu Sese Seko, whom Kabila overthrew less
than two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels are led by ethnic Tutsi from eastern Congo and are
believed to be backed by Rwanda and Uganda, the two countries that
propelled Kabila to power and then became disenchanted with him.
But the rebels in the southwest have also included former Mobutu
soldiers who are not Tutsi and can mix more freely with the local
population.
</P>
<P>
   Sondji said that 300 of the soldiers surrendered, 200 fled into
the eucalyptus field, and allied troops attacked the rebels in the
field, killing scores of them, Sondji said.
</P>
<P>
   This description could not be independently verified. But the
manager of a charter airline that has been flying residents across
the Congo River to Brazzaville, in the Republic of Congo, said all
flights had been canceled.
</P>
<P>
   A man who lives one mile from the airport and left for work in a
downtown Kinshasa hotel at 6 a.m. said hundreds of government
soldiers had arrived in the area by that hour. But he said the
shelling had not started by then.
</P>
<P>
   The sound of gunfire and explosives began echoing in downtown
Kinshasa after 7:30 a.m. and continued with some intensity for
about an hour. The boom of explosives, and what appeared to be
return fire, went on until around 2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   In the rebel-held city of Matadi, about 220 miles southwest of
Kinshasa, a rebel commander said his troops had killed 30
Zimbabwean soldiers during Wednesday's battle.
</P>
<P>
   The commander showed a Reuters correspondent there a collection
of Zimbabwean uniforms, passports and other documents supposedly
belonging to the dead Zimbabweans. ``Our forces killed up to 30
Zimbabwean troops in a fierce battle outside Kinshasa,'' the
commander, Dieudonne Kabengele, said, vowing to march ahead to
Kinshasa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
