<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3844 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLOOD-DISASTER-HNS &LR;      08-26 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOOD-DISASTER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH TOURS DEVASTATION IN FLOODED TEXAS TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA TOLLEY  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEL RIO, Texas _ As Gov. George W. Bush toured this
flood-ravaged town Wednesday and listened to the anguished stories
of survivors who have virtually nothing left and no place to go,
President Clinton declared the area a major disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Bush received word of the presidential declaration through a
cellular telephone call from the White House as he stood outside an
emergency shelter where more than 900 flood victims spent the
night.
</P>
<P>
   The disaster declaration means flood victims can apply for
various grants, loans and other forms of relief such as temporary
housing.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who made the disaster request just hours earlier, called
the quick word from the Clinton administration ``unprecedented''
and said the action is great news for a weary Val Verde County.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's heartbreaking to see people whose whole lives have been
destroyed,'' Bush said after flying over a section of Del Rio where
raging floodwaters wreaked the worst devastation. ``It's hard to
take.''
</P>
<P>
   He pledged to provide ``help as quickly as possible,'' but he
didn't know exactly when some of the federal aid would be made
available.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing that this part of the world went from very dry to
very wet, from too little to too much, in a really quick period of
time. A lot of people are suffering,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Del Rio and much of South Texas had been enduring a long drought
when the remnants of Tropical Storm Charley dumped more than a foot
of rain on the area Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Six people drowned in Del Rio, and as many were killed across
the swollen Rio Grande in Ciudad Acuna, Mexico. The flooding left
hundreds homeless. An estimated 35 people are still missing in Del
Rio.
</P>
<P>
   Joined by Rep. Henry Bonilla, R-Texas, and state Rep. Pete
Gallego, a Democrat, Bush took a helicopter trip over parts of Del
Rio early Wednesday, including San Felipe Creek, where floodwaters
washed away blocks of homes, flattened trees, overturned cars and
boats and made mincemeat of people's possessions.
</P>
<P>
   The area resembled a washed-out ghost town. The only signs of
life were some cattle and a couple of stray dogs. Abandoned cars
were stuck in the mud, large pools of water remained in many spots,
rooftops lay disembodied in the muck and appliances were strewn
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the worst disaster I have ever seen,'' Bonilla said as
he toured Del Rio, a town of about 35,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Piles of debris scattered along the creek's banks told the story
of the madness of the night when the torrential downpour surprised
the sleeping community.
</P>
<P>
   But the mounds may also be hiding an even worse secret. Bush
said officials are concerned some of the missing may be dead and
buried in the debris.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievably devastating,'' Bush said after the trip.
``It's a really powerful scene.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a sad homecoming for Gallego, who represents the area. At
several points as he looked down on the destruction, he prayed and
made the sign of the cross.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, a lot of these people I've known for a long time.
These are friends, family and supporters,'' Gallego said later as
he gazed out across the shelter. ``I bet I've knocked on every door
in that neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I counted the places I've been to that are no longer there,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the Del Rio Civic Center, which has been turned into an
emergency shelter for hundreds of flood victims, a tearful Ortencia
Cardenas told the governor and the two lawmakers in Spanish how she
heard cries of help in the dark from her longtime neighbors but
could do nothing because of the rising water. They died.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's not been able to forget their screams,'' Gallego said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
