<HEADER>
A3847 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-GEEK-NOTES-940(2T     08-26 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-GEEK-NOTES-940(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEEK NOTES: TECHNO NEWS WATCH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash., Calif., Ore.)   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Different Type of Computer Monitor
</P>
<P>
   Better watch what you type. A new generation of software is
emerging to permit employers to record not just which Web sites
employees browse, but also which programs they use, memos they
write, e-mail they send _ in short, every keystroke.
</P>
<P>
   Win What Where, a software company in Kennewick, Wash.
(www.winwhatwhere.com), released its entrant into the field this
month, a program called Win What Where, which costs $285 for each
desktop computer in which it is installed. The company says its
software keeps a record of every keystroke, mouse click and
command.
</P>
<P>
   In June, Tech Assist of Largo, Fla. (www.toolsthatwork.com),
began distributing Desktop Surveillance in North America, a
comprehensive computer-monitoring program by the British company
Omniquad. The software costs $55 per computer and has been on sale
in Europe for about eight months. Desktop Surveillance is being
marketed as the ``software equivalent of a video surveillance
camera on the desktop.''
</P>
<P>
   It permits third-party observers to view, in real time or in
playback, exactly what tasks a user is performing and what
keystrokes he or she is entering.
</P>
<P>
   Each program lets employers hide the fact that the software is
running on an employee's computer. Desktop Surveillance even allows
a record of the employee's activities to be e-mailed to a
supervisor without an employee's knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from both Tech Assist and Win What Where said they saw
a demand from employers concerned about employees' wasting time on
their computers. They also said that employers wanted a record in
case the employees sued or were sued.
</P>
<P>
   Win What Where president Richard Eaton said his company had
struggled with whether to produce software that could be used to
invade employee privacy. ``There was a lot of turmoil internally
about monitoring keystrokes,'' Eaton said. ``It just seemed like
too much, but it was the No. 1 request from our customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Julie Allen, senior product manager for Tech Assist, said
Desktop Surveillance could be set only to record an employee's
actions when certain off-limits activities occurred, such as when
an employee visited a sex-related Web site. ``Companies have proper
use policies for computers and the Internet,'' she said. ``This is
just an enforcer of those policies.''
</P>
<P>
   From the Drudge Report to the Drudge Retort
</P>
<P>
   Internet gossip columnist Matt Drudge may claim to have a handle
on the latest news, but he doesn't have a world exclusive on his
name.
</P>
<P>
   Drudge, who publishes the Drudge Report at www.drudgereport.com,
is competing, in a sense, with a parody of his effort,
www.drudge.com.
</P>
<P>
   Two opportunistic satirists, Rogers Cadenhead, a journalist, and
Jonathan Bourne, a television sitcom writer, have registered the
site and publish the Drudge Retort on it.
</P>
<P>
   The site deftly copies the look and feel of the Drudge Report
but, tongue placed firmly in cheek, seeks to mock Drudge's style of
journalism. Drudge did not respond to e-mail messages seeking
comment.
</P>
<P>
   The satire receives more than 10,000 hits a day, according to
the site's operators, who say some of the traffic has a curious
point of origin: Their logs indicate that a dozen or so of the hits
have come from a server for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   University Takes Magazine to Task on the Internet
</P>
<P>
   Stanford University believes it has a thing or two to teach U.S.
News &AMP; World Report about accuracy. The magazine counters that
Stanford needs a lesson in objectivity.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute surrounds the magazine's college rankings issue,
which reached newsstands Monday and is typically its best-selling
issue.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford is using the Net to press its several-year-old stand
against the rankings, asserting that they mischaracterize the
experience at various institutions. On its Web site
(www.stanford.edu/home/statistics/index.html), the university has
posted data about Stanford that it says more accurately reflects
the Stanford experience; it also has posted a report by
PricewaterhouseCoopers, which audits the universities' data.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. News' report (www.usnews.com) does not disagree that
Stanford's own internal findings are accurate, but the magazine
says its own rankings offer prospective students a more objective
look because U.S. News does not favor any particular institution.
Indeed, a magazine spokeswoman, Celeste James, said that the
publication was well accustomed to hearing criticism from colleges
that did not necessarily agree with how the rankings portrayed
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are an independent source,'' Ms. James said. ``When someone
selects their own data, it is inherently subjective.''
</P>
<P>
   A Stanford spokesman, Terry Shepard, countered that the
university was not complaining about its rank, which consistently
has been in the top six. Instead, he said, Stanford believes that
U.S. News &AMP; World Report generalizes too much and reaches
unsupportable conclusions. For example, he said, the magazine
unfairly seeks to measure student satisfaction partly by
determining what percentage of alumni donate to the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``They count what's countable rather than what's accurate,''
Shepard said, adding that Stanford would like to see the rankings
abolished and might decide not to provide information for the
survey next year.
</P>
<P>
   The current U.S. News &AMP; World Report annual survey, its 12th,
ranks more than 1,300 institutions based on questionnaires sent to
college officials. On at least one point, the magazine agrees with
Stanford. It notes that students should not base their decisions
solely on the rankings.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   New Fax Machine Software Adds E-Mail to the Menu  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The multifunction fax machine, which already is able to scan,
print, copy and, of course, fax, is about to add yet another
function _ e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   A Silicon Valley company, Jetfax. (www.jetfax.com), is working
the bugs out of technology that will make it possible to send an
e-mail directly from a fax machine.
</P>
<P>
   The fax machine scans a document, which is then sent to a server
at Jetfax in Menlo Park, Calif. The server then routes the document
to an e-mail address.
</P>
<P>
   There is one other interesting facet. The server at Jetfax
encodes the document so that it can be viewed in an e-mail
application, without requiring the use of a graphics program.
</P>
<P>
   The company's chief executive Rudy Prince said the technology
will be available in November for ``less than $500.''
</P>
<P>
   Next up: the fax machine that brews your morning coffee.
</P>
<P>
   Artificial Intelligence Program Tries Its Hand at Cards  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chess has Deep Blue. Now bridge has GIB.
</P>
<P>
   GIB, a computer program that plays bridge, gave the world's best
human players a run for their money last weekend in Lille, France,
at the 1998 World Bridge Championships. The program placed 12th out
of 35 in a Par contest, which challenges competitors to solve
tricky bridge puzzles.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first solid finish for the program. It placed
first this summer at the National Conference on Artificial
Intelligence in a competition against other computer bridge
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Ginsberg, a University of Oregon professor who does
research in artificial intelligence, is the creator of the GIB,
which stands for Ginsberg Intelligent Bridge Player
(www.gibware.com). Ginsberg plans to start shipping the software
commercially on Oct. 1 with a price tag of about $80.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its successes, GIB is not without its faults. While it
is quite adept at playing a hand, it is not as effective at
bidding, which may explain why it did not fare better in France. As
a result, the program may not make the best partner for a very
talented bridge-playing human, Ginsberg conceded.
</P>
<P>
   However, Ginsberg said he would continue to improve GIB and
hoped, sooner or later, to put it to a high-stakes test.
</P>
</TEXT>
