<HEADLINE>
THE LITERARY MARKETPLACE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Literary agent  &UR; Lucianne Goldberg &LR; , one of the featured players
in the  &UR; Monica &LR;   &UR; Lewinsky &LR;  scandal, has lost her client
 &UR; Mark Fuhrman &LR; , one of the featured players in the  &UR; O.J. &LR;   &UR; Simpson &LR; 
case. The former police detective has been trying to promote his
new nonfiction book, ``Murder in Greenwich.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Every show that Mark was booked on,'' Goldberg told New York
magazine, ``the first thing they did was ask him, `Do you know
Monica Lewinsky?' It made him crazy, and I don't blame him.''
</P>
<P>
   Another source told the magazine that the fault was the agent's
rather than the media's. Goldberg was ``so consumed with bringing
down the president,'' said the source, that Fuhrman's interests
were being underrepresented.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Jeffrey Toobin &LR; , who wrote a best-selling book about the
Simpson case, has agreed to write a book for Random House about
 &UR; President Clinton &LR; , the  &UR; Paula Jones &LR;  case and the Lewinsky
scandal. Toobin is a staff writer for the New Yorker and legal
analyst for ABC News.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Leonard &LR;  and  &UR; Susan Nimoy &LR;  have given $100,000 to the Museum
of Contemporary Art in Los Angeles for the purchase of  &UR; Nan &LR; 
 &UR; Goldin &LR; 's photo series ``The Ballad of Sexual Dependency.''
</P>
<P>
   _ People who don't have fish as pets are more than twice as
likely to suffer from high blood pressure than people who have fish
as pets, says a new survey taken by the American Pet Products
Manufacturers Association. In addition, said the survey, couples
with fish fight in ``a healthy manner,'' whatever that is.
</P>
<P>
   _ Former state Senator  &UR; Milton Marks  &LR; is in UCSF hospital and
would be greatly cheered to receive get-well cards, says his wife,
 &UR; Carolene &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   _ Grist for the marital mill: Researchers at the University of
Florida have found that women are better than men at remembering
details such as the location of the keys or the items on a grocery
list. This crowd-pleasing study is reported in Weight Watchers
magazine, which is a good bet to have more female readers than
male.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SEND IN THE MARINES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Looking at a newspaper photo of the recent launch celebration
for  &UR; Wilkes Bashford &LR; 's new fragrance,  &UR; Sanford &LR; 
 &UR; Chandler &LR;  noticed the smartly uniformed Marine who looked to be
standing guard outside San Francisco restaurant Le Central. What's
a U.S. Marine doing there? asked Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   Bashford said that he was one of several security guards he
employs who happen to be in the active reserves, and therefore
qualified to wear the uniform. They wear street dress in the store,
of course, but uniforms for special occasions, ``to dress things
up.''
</P>
<P>
   It is O.K. for a member of the Marine reserves to wear his
uniform off duty, said Master Sergeant  &UR; Richard Ecker &LR; , qualifying
his explanation with a caveat that would probably make Bashford
wince.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marines do not wear our uniforms at Kmart openings,'' he said.
``Any time you have a Marine Corps uniform, people automatically
assume the Marine Corps is endorsing this product. We're not. ...
It's probably a no-no.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Q: What is the difference between the aesthetics of (France
and the United States)? A: ... When I was a little girl growing up
in France, my mother worked sewing tapestries. Some of the
tapestries were exported to America. The only problem was that many
of the images on the tapestries were of naked people. My mother's
job was to cut out the ... genitals of the men and women, and
replace these parts with pictures of flowers so they could be sold
to Americans. My mother saved all the pictures of the genitals over
the years, and one day she sewed them together as a quilt, and then
she gave the quilt to me. That's the difference between French and
American aesthetics.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Artist Louise Bourgeois, quoted in Harper's magazine.
</P>
</TEXT>
