<DOCNO> NYT19980826.0367 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3862 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIAN-DANCE-ART-$ADV     08-26 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIAN-DANCE-ART-$ADV30-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN COLLABORATORS FIND THEMSELVES OUT OF STEP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., N.C., Canada)   (For release Sunday, Aug. 30)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
 (JT)  
 By CHRISTOPHER REARDON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BECKET, Mass. _ It sounded like a perfect match. The American
Indian Dance Theater, which began in 1987 as a showcase for
traditional dances from different tribes, was looking for a
dramatic way to reconcile its heritage with the modern world. Laura
Dean, a white choreographer with a penchant for spinning movement
and an eye for ritualism, was hoping to deconstruct some powwow
dances, which share a striking affinity with many of her own
compositions.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, after raising $26,000 from the National Endowment
for the Arts and two private foundations, the Jacob's Pillow Dance
Festival commissioned the postmodern dervish and the folkloric
troupe to make a new dance together.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Ms. Dean created a 12-minute piece called ``New
Dance,'' which American Indian Dance Theater performed for the
first time earlier this month at the Pillow's leafy campus in
Becket, Mass. Jennifer Dunning, writing in The New York Times,
called it ``a shimmering little jewel.''
</P>
<P>
   But the dance barely made it to the stage, and a close look at
how it evolved offers a cautionary tale about leaping into creative
partnerships.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of collaborations look terrific on paper, but for myriad
reasons they don't work out once you get inside the studio,'' said
Pablo Martinez, vice president for programs at Meet the Composer,
which awarded $830,000 this year for 18 collaborations by composers
and choreographers and nine partnerships between artists of
different nationalities. ``I often say, only half jokingly, that
someone should write a book called `Commissioning for Dummies.'
It's crucial to sit down early on and lay out the parameters very
clearly. If you don't, it's a recipe for disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, Ms. Dean had few substantive talks with
American Indian Dance Theater's artistic director, Hanay Geiogamah,
or its producer, Barbara Schwei, before joining the troupe in early
July for a weeklong residency at the National Arts Center in
Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the mild northern air, tensions mounted steadily as
Geiogamah and Ms. Dean realized how differently they viewed the
conception, creation, casting and cost of the commissioned dance.
Each day passed like the one before, with Geiogamah drilling his
dancers for nightly performances, Ms. Dean waiting anxiously in the
lobby for rehearsal time and Ms. Schwei hustling about doing damage
control. They have variously characterized the situation as a
``creative frisson,'' a ``soap opera'' and that ``brouhaha in
Canada.''
</P>
<P>
   The troupe, whose 19 members represent a dozen North American
tribes, had never performed a dance by a non-Indian. Yet there was
no indication that the discord stemmed from ethnic differences.
Instead, some dancers pointed to the disparate worlds of dance and
theater.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dean, 52, who made her mark in the 1970s by stripping dance
to a set of elemental gestures and patterns, regards movement as an
end in itself. Geiogamah, 53, a playwright and professor of
literature, film and Indian studies at UCLA, sees it as part of a
larger dramatic whole. (Ms. Schwei, a white producer who founded
the company with Geiogamah, cut her teeth in music and theater.)
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dean had arrived in Ottawa with plans for an ensemble piece
for eight dancers and two musicians. Over hotel coffee one morning,
she explained: ``My wish is to take some of that movement from the
powwow dancing and spend time with the dancers pushing it out,
experimenting with it. But that takes time. Generally I need six
hours in the studio to make one minute of a dance.''
</P>
<P>
   While that might sound slow, she knows what works. ``I'm now
making my eighth piece for the Joffrey Ballet,'' said the
choreographer, whose exultant opening sequence for ``Billboards,''
a blockbuster set to 14 songs by the artist then known as Prince,
helped the Joffrey out of a difficult financial situation in 1993.
``I've made seven for the Ohio Ballet. And I'm the only American
choreographer to be invited back by the Royal Danish Ballet. I know
how to do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Later she spoke of her work with American Indian Dance Theater.
``This isn't a collaboration. It's a commission, and that's
supposed to give me some independence.''
</P>
<P>
   Geiogamah had other ideas. A member of the Kiowa and Delaware
tribes from Oklahoma, he was creating an ambitious new piece called
``Kotuwokan,'' which means ``come celebrate the dance'' in
Algonquin. Essentially it's a story ballet about a young Indian's
journey to find his place in the modern world. ``We can't keep
doing only the social dances,'' he said while sitting by the Rideau
Canal in Ottawa. ``What we're doing here is dramatizing the
mythological back story that's been assumed by our Indian
audiences, and missed by others.''
</P>
<P>
   Geiogamah envisioned folding Ms. Dean's work into his two-hour
production. As a dance within a dance, it would symbolize the young
Indian's arrival at a new form of dance expression. Ms. Dean, while
adamant that ``I don't do dance theater,'' nevertheless agreed. But
after five days in Ottawa, she had spent only seven hours in
rehearsal, some of it doctoring other scenes at the director's
request. She flew home to Bahama, N.C., a day early.
</P>
<P>
   ``We simply didn't have enough rehearsal time,'' Geiogamah said
later that day. ``I didn't understand Laura's requirements as
clearly as I do now. I've never worked with her before, never seen
her methodologies, her style of rehearsing, her way of working with
the dancers. I respect it, but unfortunately, time is a luxury we
don't have.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Laura's a person of pure dance, and in her mind that has
exquisitely defined and refined requirements,'' he added. ``I'm a
compromiser, a pragmatic compromiser. I do what has to be done.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Few productions are free from backstage drama. What makes this
one worth airing is the extent to which it intruded on the creative
process. Last year the choreographer Blondell Cummings came equally
close to abandoning a collaboration with Philadanco and the singer
Oumou Sangare of Mali. Yet she persisted, and Philadanco performed
her dance, ``100 Percent Cotton/Natural Fiber,'' at the Joyce
Theater in New York last June to favorable reviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the working process was horrendous,'' recalled Joan Myers
Brown, Philadanco's artistic and executive director. ``We were
screaming. She was screaming. It turned out to be a good piece, but
it probably would have been a great piece if a spirit of trust had
been there from the start. You've really got to have a lot of talk
up front to make sure you don't have different assumptions about
what you're making, and how you're going to make it.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Ms. Dean, Ms. Cummings said getting enough creative time
with the dancers was a major sticking point. ``Most repertory
companies are used to people coming in with the steps set up and
just teaching the dance,'' she said. ``But I worked with Meredith
Monk and I come out of that process. I read things to the dancers
so they can share some of my passions and understand where the work
is coming from. It takes a lot of time, and I don't think Joan
always understood that.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who provided the financing for that collaboration on
behalf of Meet the Composer, questioned whether such stormy
ventures are worthwhile in the end. ``How terrible to have to make
work in such an environment,'' he mused. ``And then you have to
wonder whether the people involved will learn anything from the
experience, or just walk away from it with a bad taste in their
mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   Spelling out details early on might ward off a lot of bitterness
and frustration, but there are limits to how much scripting truly
creative partnerships can withstand. With that in mind, Ms.
Cummings suggested that artists should also have access to a
third-party mediator for times when tempers flare.
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, that's essentially how Ms. Dean's stand-off with
Geiogamah and Ms. Schwei was ultimately resolved. Eddie Swimmer, a
champion hoop dancer who has performed with the company since 1987,
stepped forward in Ottawa with a new plan.
</P>
<P>
   Placing a few phone calls to Cherokee, N.C., in the foothills of
the Smoky Mountains where he directs the ceremonial grounds, he
lined up free rehearsal space and lodging. A few weeks later, the
company flew in some dancers, the choreographer drove there and
hired a local musician, and the dance was finally made.
</P>
<P>
   With only four dancers and four days, Ms. Dean scaled down her
original concept, creating a short string of solos and an ensemble
sequence that echoed traditional Indian dances. Wearing just a few
ribbons and feathers over plain black clothes, the dancers revealed
the mechanics of the tribal dances and presented them as a new
modern aesthetic.
</P>
<P>
   A few problems linger. As the company prepares to tour
``Kotuwokan'' in California this fall, Ms. Dean and Ms. Schwei
disagree about the rights to ``New Dance.'' In addition, Michael
Greyeyes, a Cree choreographer and actor who left the ``Kotuwokan''
project last winter because of film commitments, is in a dispute
with the company over authorship and fees. And several dancers say
they plan to move on, partly because of frustration with
last-minute scheduling and bounced paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   Adapting to the unexpected has long been a strength of American
Indian culture. Dawn Russell, a 21-year-old Cherokee from
Tennessee, gave an example that relates to fancy-shawl dancing, a
style Indian women have developed in recent decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we go to clubs, sometimes I'll catch myself doing a
fancy-shawl step to modern urban music,'' she said. ``And sometimes
I'll take a step I learned at a club and work it into my
fancy-shawl routine. We do that with life every day. We take a
little bit from both worlds and combine it to survive.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
