<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Wells Pledges $15 Billion to Community   By Peter Sinton  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Wells Fargo has pledged to lend $15 billion to lower-income and
minority customers and communities in California over the next
three years as part of its bid to win approval of its pending
merger with Norwest Corp. of Minneapolis.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a letter to Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan,
Wells chief executive Paul Hazen committed $8 billion in
small-business loans, $3.5 billion in community development loans
and $2.5 billion in mortgage loans to low-income and minority
homebuyers. It also pledged $1 billion in auto, student and other
loans to low-income consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The commitment is far smaller than the $350 billion community
reinvestment promise BankAmerica and NationsBank made after
announcing their merger plans. But that pledge was for 10 years,
not three, and will be spread over the banks' combined 22-state
operating territory, not just California.
</P>
<P>
   Several consumer groups voiced greater support yesterday for
Wells Fargo's more targeted and more specific commitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time in the last few years that someone has
recognized the importance of California and made a commitment
specifically to this state,'' said Alan Fisher, executive director
of the California Reinvestment Committee, a coalition of about 200
nonprofit groups. ``For that, Wells should receive an A-plus.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells Fargo's previous community reinvestment commitment in
January 1996 totaled $45 billion, but that was spread over 10 years
and 10 states. California's share was about $3 billion a year
instead of $5 billion under the new pledge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wells Fargo is also very specific in all the ways
NationsBank/BofA didn't want to be,'' said Robert Gnaizda, policy
director for the Greenlining Institute, a San Francisco consumer
group. ``For the first time, Wells set a goal of making a minimum
of 35 percent of mortgage loans to minority homeowners.''
</P>
<P>
   Gnaizda also applauds Wells Fargo's new $100 million charitable
contribution and community investment pledge to California over
three years because ``it all will go to low-income economic
development _ the barrio, not the ballet.''
</P>
<P>
   The bank also said it would try to open more branches and ATM
machines in grocery stores in low-income communities. It said it is
committed to having its officers and managers (now 29 percent
minorities and 60 percent women) reflect the diversity of the areas
it serves. And Wells reconfirmed that its 10-year goal is to buy 40
percent of its business supplies from minority-, women-and
disabled-owned companies. Today, the figure is 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Washington Mutual, the Seattle thrift that has acquired a string
of the largest California savings &AMP; loans, also has received high
marks from community groups for pledging to be the leading mortgage
lender to minorities in all its markets.
</P>
<P>
   Wells Fargo and Norwest are expected to make additional
Community Reinvestment Act commitments to some of the other states
they serve.
</P>
<P>
   The United Steelworkers of America says Wells Fargo's community
reinvestment record is dismal in a study released last week titled
``Shortchanging Our Neighborhoods.'' But the union is hardly
impartial since it is engaged in a bitter strike against Wells'
corporate banking customer Oregon Steel and has demanded that the
bank stop financing the company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
