<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Dell Leading a Charmed Life   By David Einstein  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Can anything or anybody stop Dell Computer?
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not likely, at least for the immediate future, say industry
experts who are as agape as the rest of us over Dell's phenomenal
fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of the Round Rock, Texas, company surged $4.88 yesterday
to close at a new high of $124. That's twice as high as it was in
late March and _ get this _ 12 times higher than it was less than
two years ago, toward the end of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Dell has maintained its steady climb despite recent
travails of other technology stocks and the Dow Jones industrial
average, which has fallen 2.4 percent in the past five months.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Dell's stock is 300 times higher than it was when the company
went public in 1988, factoring in six stock splits over the past
six years. That means an original investment of $10,000 now would
be worth $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Dell's runaway success testifies to the efficiency of its
direct-sales approach, which competitors like Compaq, IBM and
Hewlett-Packard are trying to replicate in a limited way. &UR;  &LR; While
those companies must deal with distributors and retailers, Dell
sells its PCs over the phone and the Internet to consumers and
corporations. (Internet sales are up to $6 million a day.)
</P>
<P>
   ``They've taken the high ground by maintaining the most
efficient manufacturing and delivery method in the business, and
with top-quality in customer satisfaction,'' said analyst Rob
Enderle of Giga Information Group. ``They're going to have to
stumble for somebody to move against them. They're the fastest
runner on the track, and they're already ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   In the second quarter, Dell moved into a virtual tie with Compaq
for the lead in U.S. PC shipments. Were it not for Compaq's recent
merger with Digital Equipment, which brought it Digital's PC
business, Dell would have taken over first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compaq is still struggling through the merger and is dealing
with an older delivery model as well as with problems of quality
and customer satisfaction,'' Enderle said. He thinks that Compaq
could be considered in a turnaround phase because of the myriad
problems it faces.
</P>
<P>
   Although Compaq, IBM and HP have suffered earnings
disappointments in recent quarters, Dell has continued to rattle
off increases of more than 50 percent. Last week, it reported
second-quarter profits of $346 million, a 72-percent gain over the
previous year. Revenues, which have set records for 18 straight
quarters, were $4.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The runaway success has turned founder Michael Dell into one of
the richest people in the country. He holds about 16 percent of
Dell's stock, which is worth about $12.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for a 33-year-old college dropout who started the
business in his dorm room at the University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The direct-sales approach that Dell pioneered has proven to have
major advantages over traditional methods
</P>
<P>
   _Because Dell builds computers as they're ordered, there's no
need to keep a big inventory of parts or already assembled PCs.
</P>
<P>
   _Dell can incorporate the latest chips and other new technology
as soon as it comes out, without having to worry about selling PCs
that already are on the shelves (because there are no shelves).
</P>
<P>
   _The company doesn't have to contend with returns from dealers.
</P>
<P>
   _Because there are no middlemen, there's no extra markup. Dell
can afford to sell its products for less than competitors who deal
with the distribution channel.
</P>
<P>
   All of Dell's rivals have been experimenting with ways to build
PCs to order and to embrace direct sales. But at the same time,
they can't abandon distributors, who provide installation and
technical service that the PC-makers aren't equipped to handle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dell will continue to roll until Compaq, HP and IBM take some
very bold steps to combine the direct and indirect channels,'' said
analyst Scott Miller of Dataquest.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet has proven especially fortuitous for Dell, blending
seamlessly with its way of doing business. Not only has it opened
up a new channel for sales, it also has given the company a neat
way to foster and maintain relationships with major corporate
customers. In fact, Dell custom-designs Web sites for companies so
that they can get fast access to information about products and
services they regularly buy.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, Dell, alone among major manufacturers, has been
able to resist dipping into the market for sub-$1,000 consumer PCs.
The reason is that the company has business coming out of its ears
in corporate PCs, workstations and servers, all of which fetch far
higher prices than entry-level home systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we have more opportunities than we can accommodate,''
said spokesman T.R. Reid. So do you chase business in the
thousand-dollar space or in the server category?''
</P>
<P>
   If Dell has a weakness, Miller says, it's the international
market, where direct sales aren't as popular as in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I would ask of the company is greater
international presence, and I think that may be a tough nut to
crack,'' he said. ``It's not that the direct model doesn't work
outside the United States, it's just that it doesn't work quite as
well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
