A3875 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HURRICANE-SHELTER-ART     08-26 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-SHELTER-ART-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHILE SOME SWELTER, THE SAVVY ARE SHELTERED IN STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (With HURRICANE-BONNIE, HURRICANE-CALM) 
(ART ADV: Photo of man in windstorm is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(rm) 
 By MORGAN LEE and MICHAEL LEWIS Wilmington (N.C.) Morning
Star   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, N.C. _ The order came about 8:15 a.m. for about 100
people sleeping in the gymnasium at South Brunswick High School. Up
and out.
</P>
<P>
   Worried that Hurricane Bonnie's heavy winds would damage the
gymnasium's roof, shelter workers ordered people into the school's
hot, cramped hallways, where the sweating began. Shortly after
that, with the wind speed more than 75 mph, the rest of the
shelter's 462 refugees were ordered to move. By 9:30, bodies
covered every inch of the school's floor, and the agitation level
was high.
</P>
<P>
   ``First they tell us to stay, then they tell us to leave,''
grumbled one older man. If only these people had known about
Brunswick County's best-kept hurricane secret.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the Jones/Byrd Clubhouse at Sea Trail Plantation,
Executive Chef Mike Kolcum served pastries, coffee and juice to
about 250 evacuees from western Brunswick County.
</P>
<P>
   The clubhouse, part of a 2,000-acre subdivision and golf course
near the South Carolina state line, was welcoming anyone who needed
shelter, but it advertised only by word of mouth. Sandwiches, beef
stew, chicken and dumplings were prepared for lunchtime, when the
eye of the hurricane was forecast to arrive in Brunswick County.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to stay calm,'' said Kolcum, the chef who nourished
Trail Creek through two hurricanes in 1996. ``If I panic, everyone
panics.''
</P>
<P>
   When Bonnie veered west toward Brunswick at 1 a.m. Wednesday,
the Sunset Beach police and fire departments retreated to the
clubhouse, setting up a radio and television in the kitchen.
Perched on a mound excavated from golf-course ponds, the clubhouse
sits on the highest ground for miles around.
</P>
<P>
   On the porch, ceiling fans spun through hurricane-force winds.
Inside the clubhouse, the golf pro shop sold a sweatshirt and
windbreaker to people chilled by the air conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   The concrete basement was reserved for pets and their owners.
Dijon, a bichon frise lap dog with curly white fur, and Gail
Roberson, a consignment boutique owner, watched the first curtains
of rain fall as the basement garage doors lowered against the
tropical-storm-force winds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen the public shelters on TV, and it looks like they
are confined to a small area,'' Roberson said. ``Here, we can walk
around.'' Roberson brought a television, radio, dog cage and lawn
chairs to the shelter. People without chairs lounged in golf carts.
</P>
<P>
   Upstairs, sleeping bags stretched across the purple paisley
carpet, while retirees played scrabble on white table cloths and
watched television newscasts from Wilmington and Myrtle Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Elouise McCoy, 11, watched the storm through a window with 17
family members who fled their mobile homes on the mainland near
Ocean Isle Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Sea Trail Resort general manager Barry Brooks promised to move
the crowd to the windowless basement if the storm reached Class-4
status. If necessary, the kitchen had 450 cases of Gatorade in
stock. And in case refrigeration quit, it had plenty of ice on hand
for its $40,000 worth of perishable food.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
