u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATTACK-CAPETOWN-585&AMP;A     08-26 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATTACK-CAPETOWN-585&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH AFRICAN POLICE DISMISS LONE CLAIM IN FATAL RESTAURANT
BOMBING 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: ATTACK-U.S., ATTACK-SUDAN, ATTACK-CAMPS,
ATTACK-CAPETOWN) 
(nk) 
 By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.  
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE TOWN, South Africa _ The government Wednesday invited the
FBI to join its inquiry into Tuesday's explosion at a Planet
Hollywood restaurant here that killed one man and wounded 26
people.
</P>
<P>
   A special agent assigned to the U.S. Embassy in Pretoria arrived
Wednesday morning, and two bomb experts who had been investigating
the larger and more devastating explosions at the embassies in
Kenya and Tanzania are expected early Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The minister of Safety and Security, Sidney Mufamadi, said
detectives were following ``some firm leads'' and implied there
might be arrests soon. He declined to give any details.
</P>
<P>
   The only claim of responsibility for the bombing came from a
caller who said he represented an anti-American, anti-Israeli group
called Muslims Against Global Oppression. But a leader of the group
dismissed the claim, saying it was an attempt to discredit Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI was invited not so much to assist local investigators,
the police said, but to see if there are any links between the
Planet Hollywood bombing and others against American institutions
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a long history of bombings in this country, so we've
developed our bomb squads to quite a high ability,'' said police
Capt. Rod Beer. ``But we want to cooperate with the Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Security was increased here not only at American consular
offices but also at other symbols of America, including the
country's 45 McDonald's restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   The police made it clear that they did not think there were any
obvious links to the bombings in Kenya and Tanzania, where 12
Americans and about 250 Africans died. The United States has blamed
those powerful truck bombs on a worldwide terrorist network
supposedly run by a Saudi living in Afghanistan, Osama bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   The bomb here, apparently left on the floor in front of the
restaurant's shimmery blue-tiled bar, was much smaller and left a
gunpowder smell in the air. It seemed similar to pipe bombs used in
warfare between drug gangs and anti-crime groups led by Muslim
clerics in the mixed-race Cape Flats neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   No Americans were hurt. ``They should realize Americans don't
come to South Africa to go to Planet Hollywood,'' a policeman on
the scene said. ``They could go in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten of the wounded are British, police said, one is Argentine
and the rest are South African. The dead man, a 50-year-old South
African, Fanie Schoeman, and some of the worst wounded were
employees of a local bank who were holding a going-away party for a
colleague moving to England.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the seriously wounded are an 8-year-old British girl,
Laura Giddings, whose foot was blown off, and her 3-year-old
brother, Jacob, who had serious spinal injuries. A witness said,
``It looked like someone just took an ice cream scoop out of the
little boy's back.''
</P>
<P>
   Who claimed to have set off the bomb remained murky Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, a radio reporter said she got a call on her
personal cellular phone from a man identifying himself as Jihad
al-Haq and saying his organization, Muslims Against Global
Oppression, was responsible. Wednesday, representatives of the
small group repeatedly denied responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``We unreservedly condemn the attack,'' one spokesman for the
group said. ``We don't have anyone named Jihad al-Haq in our
organization as far as I know, and we sympathize with the
victims.''
</P>
<P>
   About half a million South Africans, slightly more than 1
percent of the population, are Muslims.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In a 5 p.m. talk show on Muslim community radio, callers who
identified themselves as members of the group suggested a possible
scenario: Several days ago the group received permission to march
on the American Consulate here on Saturday to ``show the world how
disgusted Muslims are with the U.S.'' for the cruise missile
attacks on Sudan and Afghanistan. One caller said the bomb might
have been ``a means to divert people'' from the march.
</P>
<P>
   Another caller said the bomb could have been the work of ``drug
barons and gangsters to exploit anger against Muslims.''
Alternatively, he suggested, it could have been the work of
Zionists, or of ``the U.S. security apparatus, which would allow
the FBI to establish a foothold in southern Africa and control
intelligence gathering here.''
</P>
<P>
   The police were careful to blame no one. ``We don't want to
point our finger at Muslims and it turns out to be a right-winger
or an employee with a grudge,'' Beer said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for President Nelson Mandela, Parks Mankahlana, said
religion was not the issue, adding: ``It doesn't matter to this
government if they are Christians or Muslims or Satanists. They
deserve to be punished.''
</P>
<P>
   The South African Broadcasting Corporation said Wednesday night
that it had a tape of a suspect but would not broadcast it for fear
of jeopardizing the investigation. Local newspapers said videotapes
had been retrieved from security cameras inside the restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   The front of Planet Hollywood was blocked Wednesday in
six-foot-high rolls of barbed wire to keep the curious back. Many
wreathes had been left, and 10 bunches of roses and carnations were
left hanging on razor wire by the Interreligious Committee on Crime
and Violence in the Western Cape, a group of prominent imams,
sheikhs, priests, rabbis and Hindu, Bahai and African clerics who
jointly criticized the bombing and said they would ask their
congregations to cooperate with the police.
</P>
<P>
   The normally bustling waterfront tourist area was sudued
Wednesday afternoon. Restaurants that usually turn people away had
empty tables. The Pick &AMP; Pay supermarket, patronized by locals, was
busy, but tourist shops' clerks slumped glumly behind counters.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Fick, a waitress at Delectable Deluxe Donuts, was eating
a grilled cheese sandwich, which she said was the first food she
had been able to eat since the explosion 20 hours earlier. She had
been waiting for a bus home just across from Planet Hollywood when
the bomb went off.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lady screaming, `I can't see! I can't feel my
face!''' she said. ``They carried out a lady with her foot off. I
was shocked. I just started crying and walked away. They had to
give me sugar water at the medic station, I was so upset.''
</P>
<P>
   Police identified one local hero as Marcus Dudley, a chef at the
Victoria &AMP; Alfred Hotel restaurant, who was returning home from
work when the bomb went off and was one of the first to rush into
the smoking nightclub to drag the wounded out. He gave first aid,
helped reunite families and even ripped a limb off a plaza tree to
splint a man's leg.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
