<HEADLINE>
DELAY URGES COLLEAGUES TO VOTE TO RELEASE STARR REPORT TO PUBLIC 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Majority Whip Tom DeLay began organizing
support Wednesday for public disclosure of independent counsel
Kenneth Starr's report on the president's relationship with Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay, a Texas Republican who has called for President Clinton
to resign, broke ranks with some House GOP leaders and urged his
colleagues to vote to release Starr's report once it reaches the
House, probably in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sooner the facts are released, the sooner we can put this
whole thing behind us,'' DeLay said.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Newt Gingrich and Judiciary Committee chairman
Henry Hyde had hoped to amend House rules so Starr's report could
be kept under wraps until a decision is made on whether to begin an
impeachment investigation.
</P>
<P>
   House rules require committees to provide all House members and
the public access to material under consideration by the panels,
and DeLay wants the rules to remain unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Full public disclosure will ensure that the media, the
Congress and the public will all have accurate information,'' DeLay
said.
</P>
<P>
   A White House official who spoke on the condition of anonymity
said Delay ``would be wise to listen to his speaker and chairman
Hyde. The American people would not respond well to yet another
effort to politicize a matter they want put behind them.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the law that governs the Office of Independent Counsel,
Starr is required to report to Congress if he finds ``any
substantial and credible information ... that may constitute
grounds for an impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr's staff is in the process of drafting a detailed report of
findings from a seven-month inquiry in the president's affair with
Lewinsky and alleged efforts to keep the relationship secret.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who denied the affair in a sworn deposition in January,
testified before the grand jury 10 days ago, then went on national
television to admit to misleading the public for the past seven
months.
</P>
<P>
   The president insisted his answers to questions in the
depositions were ``legally accurate'' and did not constitute
perjury. He also said he never asked anyone to lie or destroy
evidence, which would amount to obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   Starr has been investigating whether the president or his
associates tried to silence Lewinsky by helping her find a job in
New York or tried to help her avoid a subpoena in the Jones case by
retrieving his gifts from her.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence expected to earn a mention in Starr's report are the
gifts as well as tapes of Lewinsky gossiping in lurid detail about
her affair with Clinton and a dress allegedly stained during a
White House tryst.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people read his report, they'll want to throw up,''
according to an unnamed source quoted by Newsweek magazine. Some
people will be ``deeply offended by some of the kinkier details,''
the source said.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's team of prosecutors has been examining whether Clinton
lied under oath in the Paula Jones sexual harassment lawsuit and
tried to hinder the lawsuit and subsequent criminal investigation
by concealing the nature of his relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich over the weekend said the threshold for impeaching a
president should be higher than lying about a relationship with a
woman half his age. Instead of ``a single human mistake,'' the
president would have to display ``a pattern of felonies'' for
impeachment to be warranted, Gingrich said.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Republican also urged Starr not to limit his report
to the Lewinsky affair, but to include his findings from the
four-year investigation of Clinton's business dealings in Arkansas,
the misuse of FBI files and the dismissal of the White House travel
staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the Congress could move forward only on
Lewinsky, unless (Starr) had such a clear case, such an
overpowering case,'' Gingrich said. ``But I think we would be
better-served to know the whole story.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Hyde, R-Ill., has instructed his staff to draft a
resolution for handling Starr's report once the leadership receives
word that he is prepared to ship it to the House, where an
impeachment inquiry would begin.
</P>
<P>
   Republican and Democratic staff members are drafting resolutions
for the House to consider that would limit the availability of
Starr's report, once it is delivered, to members of Hyde's
committee and several key staff members.
</P>
<P>
   The committee members and staff investigators (a 14-member team
appointed by Republicans and a four-member team appointed by the
Democrats) would conduct an initial review behind closed doors of
Starr's report to determine whether a formal inquiry should be
held. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
