<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV30-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE ITSELF IS A VICTIM IN THE CLINTON SCANDAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Aug. 30)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A house may be an inanimate object, but in the case
of the elegant mansion at 1600 Pennsylvania Avenue here, it is a
living symbol of the greatness of the world's most enduring
democracy.
</P>
<P>
   When compared with the massive palaces built by the monarchs of
old, the White House is a modest dwelling. But within its walls
have resided men whose leadership converted a tiny republic of 13
states into the most powerful nation in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The President's House, designed and built by Irish-born
architect James Hoban, has for 198 years been a silent witness to
events great and small, noble and tawdry, harmonious and violent.
In the current scandal over Bill Clinton's sexual escapades, it is
one of the casualties.
</P>
<P>
   The legend and the promise that have led generations of
Americans to regard residence in the White House as the ultimate
goal have both been tarnished. We may not know the lurid specifics
of the illicit relations engaged in by Clinton and Monica Lewinsky,
but we do know that their private conduct desecrated the most
public house in America.
</P>
<P>
   We know also that when people are accorded the singular
privilege of taking up residence in the White House they should be
bound by an obligation not just to enjoy its facilities but to
respect the fact that it is one of democracy's most sacred shrines.
</P>
<P>
   Rules of behavior should exclude extra-marital sexual encounters
in the Oval Office or, as in the case of Warren G. Harding, in a
broom closet adjacent to the Oval Office. They also should exclude
parties at which a president, John F. Kennedy, cavorted in the
swimming pool with bimbos while the first lady was away.
</P>
<P>
   In the presidential election of 2000, attention certainly will
be paid to the unsavory Clinton practice of permitting big
contributors to the Democratic Party to spend a night in the
Lincoln bedroom. It also will be paid to the past sexual encounters
of the candidates.
</P>
<P>
   When John Adams moved into the partially finished mansion in
early November 1800 as its first occupant, he wrote a benediction
that should have established a code of conduct for all future
presidents: ``I pray Heaven to bestow the best of blessings on this
house and on all that shall hereafter inhabit it. May none but
honest and wise men ever rule under this roof.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Adams arrived at the President's House, voters
rejected his bid for a second term, choosing Thomas Jefferson
instead. But the Adams benediction, carved into the fireplace
mantle in the State Dining Room, is as relevant today as it was two
centuries ago.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is that not all presidents have been honest and
wise. Long before Clinton's peccadillos caused such a stir, other
presidents lied, entertained illicit-sex partners, sought to
obstruct justice and wielded their executive authority improperly.
</P>
<P>
   Even Adams himself committed a minor, but memorable, breach of
presidential etiquette at the end of his four-month stay in the
White House. Rather than attend the inauguration of his successor,
he left the mansion before dawn on the day of Jefferson's
inauguration.
</P>
<P>
   Only one other president has engaged in such disrespectful
behavior. In 1829, Adams' son, John Quincy Adams, refused to
witness the swearing in of the man who had defeated him _ Andrew
Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   The late historian Fawn Brodie claimed that Jefferson, a
widower, shared his White House bed with a slave, Sally Hemmings,
who allegedly gave him several illegitimate children. Other
historians contend that never happened.
</P>
<P>
   As for old Andy Jackson, he was one of the most flamboyant
characters ever elected president. The hero of the Battle of New
Orleans in 1815, he fought duels, killing at least one man, and
exploded in temper tantrums.
</P>
<P>
   On the his inauguration day, thousands of his supporters, many
of them from what was then the American frontier, crowded into the
White House for a boisterous celebration.
</P>
<P>
   The mansion became so filled with jubilant people eating free
food and drinking whiskey-spiked punch that Jackson had to escape
through a window to avoid suffocation. Although dignity was not the
order of the day, the Jackson inaugural provided the common people
an opportunity to savor the pleasures of one of the shrines of
democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the men and women who have lived in the White House have
conducted themselves properly and have respected the historic
grandeur of both the presidency and the mansion.
</P>
<P>
   For years Richard Nixon seemed to be following that example. But
after Watergate and his own deviousness did him in, many Americans
were appalled to learn from his White House tapes that he had often
used gutter language while sitting in the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy and Nixon were very different personalities, but they
shared two traits that Clinton also has: a powerful intellect and a
weak moral core.
</P>
<P>
   Few previous presidents have possessed Clinton's incisive
intelligence, charm and brilliance as a communicator. Few also have
demonstrated such moral and ethical laxity.
</P>
<P>
   Having lied to the grand jury, the American people and his wife
and delivered a miserable, self-serving explanation of his conduct
on television, Clinton is treading on very unstable ground. The
nation probably would well served by his resignation. Then the
presidency and the aura of the White House could receive a
much-needed restoration.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-26-98 1907EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980826.0378 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3891 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRUNEI-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;      08-26 1089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRUNEI-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BANDAR SERI BEGAWAN, Brunei: government's income.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even to people who could not find his country on a map, the
sultan of Brunei became famous as the richest man in the world. It
is a title he only recently ceded to Microsoft chairman Bill Gates.
Like that of other oil barons, the sultan's net worth declines as
fast as the price of crude.
</P>
<P>
   With an estimated fortune that reached $35 billion in the early
1990s, the royal family has enjoyed life on a grand scale. Prince
Jefri, 44, savored it with particular gusto, buying playthings like
a sleek yacht, an Airbus jet, a Sikorsky helicopter and five-star
hotels such as the Plaza Athenee in Paris, the New York Palace and
the Bel Air in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Prince Jefri's ambitions extended beyond shopping. As finance
minister from 1984 to 1996, he built, among other projects, a giant
amusement park, free to visitors. Prince Jefri pursued his ventures
through a web of private companies and government agencies. Amedeo
Development Corp., a private company owned by the prince, built the
amusement park and other projects in Brunei. Amedeo Crown, a Prince
Jefri-owned company listed in the British island of Jersey,
acquired Asprey, the London jeweler, while Prince Jefri family
trusts own the American hotels.
</P>
<P>
   The Brunei Investment Agency, a government operation that the
prince led as chairman, manages investments and owns more hotels,
including the Dorchester in London and the Beverly Hills Hotel in
California.
</P>
<P>
   Reconstructing what happened at these companies is difficult
because their operations are cloaked in secrecy. The reputed
advisers will not even confirm whether they work for Prince Jefri,
the royal family or the government.
</P>
<P>
   Executives with ties to Prince Jefri said that Amedeo and the
Brunei Investment Agency were both audited by the accounting firm
KPMG Peat Marwick. Citibank is said to be their main adviser. Given
the blurry line between the interests of the royal family and those
of the state, these executives said it would be hard for any
outsider to impose strict financial controls.
</P>
<P>
   In July, reports began to surface of huge, undisclosed losses at
both Amedeo and the Brunei Investment Agency. Financial analysts
said the investment agency's assets might have been pledged to buy
hotels. The losses came as an acute embarrassment to the sultan,
who had offered loans to help his ailing neighbors, Thailand and
Indonesia, only to discover that Brunei could not afford them.
</P>
<P>
   So the sultan abruptly stripped Prince Jefri of his jobs at both
organizations and ordered the government to seize Amedeo's assets
in Brunei. The sultan hired auditors from Arthur Andersen in London
to calculate the losses, which some analysts say could reach
billions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Selamat, the deputy finance minister, declined to comment on
Amedeo's collapse but acknowledged that ``any major corporate
failure is going to have some impact on the economy of Brunei.''
</P>
<P>
   Prince Jefri's financial troubles came after another
embarrassing episode, in which Shannon Marketic, a former Miss
U.S.A., accused him and the sultan of trying to turn her into a sex
slave. The lawsuit is pending, though the sultan has sovereign
immunity and Prince Jefri has immunity as a potential heir to the
throne.
</P>
<P>
   Prince Jefri would seem to have a bleak future in Brunei. But he
contends that because his overseas properties are owned by separate
companies and trusts, he still owns those assets and intends to
keep them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not seek a fight and prefer to be left alone,'' he said
in a statement. ``I shall, however, vigorously defend my position
and interests of my family.''
</P>
<P>
   An adviser to Prince Jefri, speaking on the condition of
anonymity, said the government was exaggerating the losses at
Amedeo to discredit the prince and destroy his power base within
the country. The government also recently seized three oil
concessions that gave Prince Jefri a steady stream of income.
</P>
<P>
   Now the prince and his advisers are plotting a strategy to hold
on to the remaining properties. Brunei's investigation has set off
alarm bells in Europe and the United States, and Prince Jefri's
lieutenants have had to reassure employees and suppliers that the
hotels and other properties are not about to be seized.
</P>
<P>
   Prince Jefri may be finally tightening his belt, too. At Asprey
Group, the venerable but money-losing luxury-goods company he
bought for $388 million in 1995, the Prince is merging the flagship
Asprey with its sister company, Garrard, and selling off
unprofitable businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that because we have a principal who is a prince, we
can spend whatever our hearts desire, is not true,'' said Ian Dahl,
the chief executive of Asprey in London. ``We run a very
tightfisted company.''
</P>
<P>
   Prince Jefri's adviser said he was being hounded by Islamic
militants, including another of the sultan's brothers, Prince
Mohamed. ``This is a classic power struggle between those who favor
a more conservative, religious approach and those who favor a more
open, tolerant approach,'' the adviser said.
</P>
<P>
   Brunei has become more straitlaced in recent years. Alcohol is
no longer served in bars or restaurants. But other facts of life
here may have less to do with religion than money. Several
observers said the sultan's largesse had created a politically
satisfied, even sedated, populace. Even people who live in houses
on stilts in Brunei's 500-year-old water village own satellite
dishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people feel they've gotten a good deal from the sultan,''
said Rex DeSilva, the editor of the Borneo Bulletin, which calls
itself an independent newspaper even though it is controlled by
Prince Mohamed. ``If a ruler can't be popular with all that, who
can?''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the sultan's biggest challenge may be economic rather
than political. For years, he has promised to wean Brunei from its
reliance on oil by diversifying its economy. Yet the government's
efforts to become a trade and tourism center have come to naught.
Given that Brunei has about 23 years of oil reserves left, that
problem may fall to the sultan's son.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Prince Billah may help overcome some of Brunei's
current ills. Unlike his playboy uncle, Prince Jefri, or even his
father at a younger age, Prince Billah projects a less frivolous
image. Educated at Oxford, Prince Billah is said to be a sober
young man. His idea of indulgence, according to royal propaganda,
is a game of snooker and the tame saxophone music of Kenny G.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
