<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 19:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3897 &Cx1f; tab-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO:PROGRESS-LATIN     08-26 2939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO:PROGRESS-LATINTRADE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO: MIDDLE OF THE ROAD
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from Latin Trade magazine.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times sales representatives OLIVIA
VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at 310-996-0075 or fax at 310-996-0089; or
KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11, or fax at 47-42-80-44 or
47-42-18-81; or CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448, or fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (They also have information on how to subscribe to Latin Trade's
service for newspapers _ the magazine's exclusives and other
articles are transmitted every week.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``i''
international and ``f'' financial files.) 
 By BRENDAN M. CASE 
 c.1998 Latin Trade 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    MONTERREY, Mexico _ Mexico might be one of the most dynamic
economies in Latin America these days, but it has also turned into
a bewildering place.
 &HT;    Several politicians have broken all the rules by launching
formal or informal presidential campaigns two years before the next
elections. Even though real wages rose for the first time since the
crisis of 1995, Mexicans are wary of putting too much confidence in
their economic future. And a giant crime wave has broken over the
country, spooking everyone from bricklayers to top executives.
 &HT;    Is this progress or chaos? Maybe a little bit of both.
 &HT;    Mexico is still in the middle of a far-reaching transformation
that goes way beyond free trade. The economic opening the country
embarked on a decade ago is changing the way companies do business,
but it is also spilling into the rest of society. The benefits of
increasing economic and political freedom are already apparent to
some, but the process is far from finished.
 &HT;    ``Mexico is going through a collection of simultaneous
transitions, and they contribute to a sense of chaos,'' says
Antonio Alonso Concheiro, director of Analitica Consultores in
Mexico City and one of Mexico's leading futurists. ``That might be
more perception than reality, but these are delicate processes and
we're going to have to work hard to find new arrangements.''
 &HT;    Mexico has always been a land of extremes, of rich and poor,
north and south, educated and uneducated. The picture today is not
entirely black and white, but the current transition has
accentuated the division between the companies that have fashioned
themselves into world class competitors and the ones that are still
stuck in a bygone era.
 &HT;    Underlying that division is a deeper one between people who have
the education, know-how and spark to take advantage of the real
opportunities opening up, and those who are unprepared. With the
political environment far less authoritarian than it once was,
staying on the promising path of free trade and economic
liberalization will depend on how much their benefits are felt by
all Mexicans.
 &HT;    No part of the country illustrates the bright side of the
economy as well as Monterrey, Nuevo Leon, the industrial center two
hours from the U.S. border. People in this proud, dusty city walk
with a Texas swagger and flaunt their business acumen. Even taxi
drivers leave their business cards with visitors.
 &HT;    Regiomontanos, as Monterrey's residents are called, see their
city as a focus of the North American Free Trade Agreement,
stressing their experience in doing business with Texans and the
rest of the United States. Canada just opened a chamber of commerce
there earlier this year. And many Mexican and foreign businessmen
in Nuevo Leon have turned their companies into NAFTA powerhouses,
exporting US$5.5 billion last year.
 &HT;    ``We've seen about a 25 percent increase in calls from U.S.
companies interested in setting up operations in Monterrey, or
exporting their products to the Mexican market,'' says Santiago
Trevino, director of the Monterrey office of the American Chamber
of Commerce. ``We're even starting to see a shortage of labor,
there are jobs that are getting tough to fill.''
 &HT;    Cemex, perhaps Monterrey's best-known company, is the world's
second-largest cement firm that chairman Lorenzo Zambrano has built
into a respected multinational that happens to have a Mexican
address.
 &HT;    Local neighbors such as glassmaker Grupo Vitro and steelmaker
IMSA have also transformed themselves into international players.
 &HT;    Grupo Alfa, an industrial conglomerate, had to be bailed out by
the government in the early 1980's after much of its domestic
business went bust in an earlier crisis. Last year, however, it
exported a quarter of its $3.9 billion in sales. Pulsar, another
conglomerate, has branched out of its traditional packaging and
agricultural businesses to become a world leader in biotechnology.
And more than anywhere else in the country, a culture of
modernization and reorganization is beginning to suffuse the
region's smaller companies, making Monterrey one of the hottest
places to do business.
 &HT;    ``There's a real stress on making improvements in all companies,
everyone is trying to follow the big companies in boosting quality
levels and productivity,'' says Trevino.
 &HT;    Companies elsewhere are doing something similar. Bread-maker
Grupo Industrial Bimbo exports to the United States and the rest of
Latin America, and recently acquired Texas-based Mrs Baird's
Bakeries. Steelmakers have become regional forces, and even some
nimble small and medium-sized companies have joined the parade,
exporting their goods themselves or supplying the giants.
 &HT;    Multinationals are the other ingredient in the success story.
Automobile companies exported nearly one million cars and trucks
last year, and foreign companies as a whole poured a record $12
billion in direct investment into Mexico last year. The lion's
share still comes from the United States, but Asian and European
firms have also rushed to make Mexico their export platform for the
U.S. and Canadian markets, and in some cases for all of Latin
America.
 &HT;    Indeed, the success of the modern industrial economy is such
that infrastructure in Mexico and along the border is straining
under the weight of trade. Freight arriving at the Port of Veracruz
was backed up for a week last spring and summer, despite huge
efficiency improvements. The railroad system is improving and
Transportacion Ferroviaria Mexicana, the company that runs the
Northeast Railroad between Mexico City and the Texas border, has
invested $1 billion in upgrading its business. But its efforts were
stymied last spring by a series of delays on Union Pacific's rails
in Texas, which simply couldn't handle all the traffic from Mexico.
 &HT;    ``Future growth depends on Mexico increasing its exports, and
the key to becoming more competitive is improving our
inrastructure,'' says Cemex's Zambrano. ``This will lower the cost
of getting our goods to other markets, and in the long run will
make the difference between winning and losing market share. We
must either make the necessary improvements within five years or
watch our exports grow less.''
 &HT;    In other parts of the economy, the apparent success of the idea
behind trade liberalization _ that companies will inevitably become
lean competitors _ is only part of the story. Small and
medium-sized companies around much of the country have been left in
the dust.
 &HT;    ``There's a part of the economy that is extraordinarily
competitive, accounting for as much as 60 percent to 70 percent of
industrial output,'' says Luis Rubio, a noted economist who is the
director of Mexico City-based think tank Center of Development
Research. ``But it only accounts for about 20 percent of the jobs.
The other 80 percent is a sea of inefficiency and (unproductivity).
It's as if companies in that sector are living in another age.''
 &HT;    Incorporating more of the smaller companies into export
production chains will be the key test of whether the new Mexico
can benefit more than just a few big businessmen. That is also
important given another kind of dilemma.
 &HT;    To create enough jobs for the one million people joining the
labor force each year, the economy must grow by at least 5 percent
(it grew 7 percent last year, and is expected to grow a bit less
than 5 percent this year).
 &HT;    Once it grows that fast, however, the trade deficit tends to
rise quickly because of high demand for imports, potentially
destabilizing the economy.
 &HT;    That will remain an acute problem until more domestic companies
are efficient enough to meet consumer demand and the needs of
domestic companies.
 &HT;    Since the big exporters only employ a minority of the labor
force, most workers have jobs in stagnant, low-wage firms in the
old industrial economy or the service economy. In the long run,
that could spell trouble for the consumer market, although that is
hardly a concern today.
 &HT;    In fact, the consumer market is back to driving growth this
year. Retail sales posted yearly gains of more than 10 percent
during the first quarter of the year, and could rise as much as 6
percent on the year, according to analysts. Demand for imports,
which plummeted during 1995, has also increased _ consumer goods
imports rose nearly 50 percent during the first four months of the
year, spearheading a nearly 25 percent overall increase.
 &HT;    ``About 20 percent of our goods were imports in 1994, a
proportion that fell to about 6 percent in 1995,'' says Pedro
Mejia, general manager of Soriana, a Monterrey-based supermarket
chain. ``The figure is now about 11 percent, and could go up more.
The main consideration in 1995 and 1996 was price, and we saw many
consumers move away from the brand-name products they used to buy.
Now, they're beginning to move back.''
 &HT;    But the dual nature of the recovery is again apparent. Cars and
durable goods _ mainly purchased by the middle and upper classes _
have made huge advances, but basic goods that everyone buys such as
food and clothing have posted smaller gains. A 1997 study by
polling firm Mori de Mexico showed that 35 percent of Mexicans
expected their own economic situation to improve during the next
year. That was much better than the 20 percent who thought so in
1996, and it was the first time expectations had improved since the
beginning of the crisis. But it was also far below comparable
expectations in countries such as Brazil and Colombia.
 &HT;    One reason for caution is Mexico's recurrent crises, which have
accompanied the end of each president's six-year term since 1976
(the president may not be reelected to two successive terms). The
next election is in July 2000, and it will be the first in memory
that the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI) has a real
chance of losing.
 &HT;    Vicente Fox, the popular governor of the central state of
Guanajuato, has already announced he will compete for the
nomination of the center-right National Action Party (PAN).
Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, the mayor of Mexico City and the best known
politician in Mexico after President Ernesto Zedillo, is thought to
be planning a run for the center-left Party of the Democratic
Revolution (PRD). And a jumble of PRI politicians are jockeying for
position much more conspicuously than ever before.
 &HT;    Businessmen and economists are already getting nervous.
 &HT;    ``One of Mexico's key challenges is to maintain macroeconomic
stability through the year 2000,'' says Rubio. ``That means
confronting the other challenge, which is to avoid too much
pollution in people's expectations from politics.''
 &HT;    But politics is changing, too. The creaky system of fraud,
patronage and corporatism built during the PRI's seven decades in
power is crumbling. Confidence in the voting process _ and in
Zedillo's apparent eagerness to respect it _ leaped after the
successful midterm election in July last year, which gave
opposition parties a combined majority in the Chamber of Deputies.
 &HT;    As in the economy, however, there is an underside to the
political opening. Just as the more open political environment is
showing a viable alternative to the PRI's traditional dominance,
new social problems are cropping up.
 &HT;    Ancestral shortcomings like low education levels and systemic
corruption have been joined by a new one: the crime wave that has
swept Mexico since 1995. Muggings have become commonplace in Mexico
City, and the U.S. Embassy has repeatedly warned that hailing taxis
on the street is an invitation to be robbed. Violence has become
commonplace in a country where even criminals used to follow
unwritten rules of moderation.
 &HT;    ``It's a monster, and it's a monster we didn't have before,''
says Pete Palmer, a security specialist in Mexico City with U.S.
corporate security firm Kroll-O'Gara Associates. ``Sooner or later,
it's going to have an impact on foreign investment as people will
become unwilling to come down here just because of what they see.''
 &HT;    Mexican companies have already experienced the bittersweet
flavor of radical change, with its high costs for some and rich
opportunities for others. Now, in the willy-nilly process of
finding a new political and balance, the country as a whole is
going through something similar.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    CHIAPAS: THE NEXT FRONTIER?
 &HT;    MONTERREY _ While companies in northern and central Mexico
strive to join the global economy, much of the poor southeast is
being left behind. A conspicuous example is Chiapas, where the 1994
Zapatista rebellion has polarized part of the state and scared away
much investment. But to hear a few plucky businessmen tell it, the
state is full of business potential.
 &HT;    ``Of all our businesses, I like the ones in Chiapas most,'' says
Alfonso Romo Garza, the chairman of Monterrey-based Pulsar
Internacional, which runs a state-of-the-art biotechnology research
center there. ``Hunger is not solved by laws, and it is necessary
to bring economic development projects to Chiapas.''
 &HT;    To be sure, private sector involvement is no panacea for the
state's ills.
 &HT;    The government and the Zapatistas have dawdled so much in peace
negotiations that some skeptics have questioned the commitment of
both to finding a workable solution for the nearly five-year-old
standoff. But both sides concur that a new political agreement
covering the rights of indigenous people needs to be found.
 &HT;    The ruggedly beautiful state might be Mexico's richest in terms
of natural resources. It supplies more than half of the country's
hydroelectric power, holds a substantial share of oil reserves and
is covered with lush tropical and subtropical forests. Moreover,
experts reckon there are plenty of opportunities to develop
smaller-scale businesses, from non-traditional agriculture to
artisanry to ecological tourism.
 &HT;    In the conflict zone near the stunning city of San Cristobal de
las Casas, some once-poor Indian farmers have already carved out a
profitable niche in organically-grown coffee that finds eager
buyers in the United States and Europe. A co-op of 1,300 farmers
called Indigenous People of the Sierra Madre of Motozintla (Ismam)
now has total assets of US$7 million and credit lines of several
million dollars more, according to Father Jorge Aguilar Reyna, a
local priest who helped establish the association.
 &HT;    Small businessmen in the rest of the state are planting rubber
trees and establishing a shrimp-farming industry. A wheat flour
plant in the Soconusco region, far removed from the conflict zone,
currently imports 80 percent of its wheat from the United States
and Canada _ but figures it could cut costs and promote local jobs
if farmers near San Cristobal would plant more wheat.
 &HT;    Then there is Pulsar's center, which exports everything from
broccoli to cauliflower to melons. Meanwhile, several dozen
scientists at the company's International Center for Agricultural
Research and Training in the town of Frontera Hidalgo are
developing disease-resistant crops and other biotech innovations.
In an interview with Expansion magazine, Romo Garza said private
sector involvement would not be enough to solve the conflict by
itself _ but would be essential in assuring lasting peace.
 &HT;    Officials in other poor southern states are also keen on
attracting companies. Indeed, with the area's low salaries and
eagerness for investment, the south is becoming the next frontier
for many labor-intensive businesses.
 &HT;    Far more than Guerrero or Oaxaca states, Yucatan is the leader.
Belying the traditional perception of the maquiladora
assembly-for-export industry as a border phenomenon, the Gulf Coast
has attracted 60 maquiladoras and their 13,000 jobs in the last
four years alone. It wants more.
 &HT;    ``Any company that wants to set up a factory here can have all
the permits it needs in a week,'' says Ricardo Dajer Nahum,
Yucatan's director of economic development. ``We find that the
delays usually come from each company's own planning process, not
the government.''
 &HT;    Dajer Nahum is likely to be a busy man, what with Yucatan's calm
social atmosphere, minute rate of worker turnover and established
sea links with the United States. The underdeveloped south is still
a challenging place to do business. But if other states can
replicate some of Yucatan's conditions, the region might begin to
close the gap with the more prosperous north.
 &HT;     
 -0- 
 c.1998 Latin Trade 
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QL;
</TEXT>
