<HEADER>
A3908 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATTACK-CAMPS-ART-NYT &LR;      08-26 1164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATTACK-CAMPS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUERRILLAS CALL MISSILE ATTACKS INCONSEQUENTIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: ATTACK-U.S., ATTACK-SUDAN, ATTACK-CAPETOWN) 
(ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By RAYMOND BONNER with STEVE LeVINE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANSAHRA, Pakistan _ Guerrillas who have trained at the camps in
Afghanistan that were hit by American missiles last week said
Wednesday that the attack would not interfere with the training of
Muslim revolutionaries there, nor would it harm their morale.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will further motivate people,'' said Bakht Zamin, a
commander of a unit that was trained in Afghanistan and is now
fighting not far from here, in Kashmir. ``They consider it a matter
of pride and a blessing of God to become a martyr.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the camps, mostly mud huts and tents, could be rebuilt
within a week.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration says the camps, in eastern
Afghanistan near the Pakistani border, were part of a terrorist
network run by Osama bin Laden, a Saudi who Washington says was
responsible for the bombings of the American Embassies in Kenya and
Tanzania on Aug. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Zamin, 42, a lawyer with an easy laugh, rejected the notion that
he and his men were terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel we are freedom fighters,'' he said as he sat on the
floor in a single-story house in the cornfields here and shared a
breakfast of beans, yogurt and nan, a thick, circular bread. A
decade ago Washington would also have considered him a freedom
fighter: He was part of the CIA-backed force of mujahedeen fighting
the Soviet army in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   The distinction between a freedom fighter and a terrorist
depends on one's political viewpoint. Two of the three camps hit by
the American cruise missiles have been supported in varying degrees
by Pakistan's intelligence service, say Western diplomats and
Pakistani government officials.
</P>
<P>
   To some degree Afghanistan has lured an amalgam of
revolutionaries, united by fundamentalist Islam, just as Cuba
attracted a cross section of Marxist revolutionaries in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   And just as the United States had trouble fighting Cuban-backed
guerrillas, the missile attack demonstrates that high-technology
wizardry developed to fight a war against another superpower may
not be appropriate against terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   Though the stated goal of the attack was to protect Americans
and American institutions from terrorists, the camps also trained
guerrillas to fight in Turkey, Algeria, Egypt, Saudi Arabia and
India. Earlier graduates have also fought in Bosnia and Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   The American missiles struck four camps in Afghanistan. Two, in
the Jarawah area near Khost, trained Pakistanis and Kashmiris for
the war against India in Kashmir, say Pakistani officials and
journalists who have visited the site. The third, Al Farooq,
nearby, was used primarily by Arabs from several countries,
American and Pakistani officials say.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth camp, Al Badr, 10 miles to the west, also an Arab
camp, was run by bin Laden, according to American intelligence.
Reports filtering out from Afghanistan say that Al Badr was badly
damaged and that the casualties might have been very high.
</P>
<P>
   One of the worst hit camps was operated by a fundamentalist
Islamic organization in Pakistan called Harakat Mujahedeen, or
Movement of Holy Warriors; at least 21 people were killed. The
group had been called Harakat Ansar, but the name was changed after
the State Department put that organization on its terrorist list
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Harakat Mujahedeen leaders, as well as survivors of the attack,
have insisted that the camp was only for religious purposes.
</P>
<P>
   The Jarawah camps are only a few miles from the Pakistani
border, and people and supplies, including weapons, moved freely
across Pakistan to and from the camps for many years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always told the Pakistanis there are dangers in allowing
these camps,'' said a senior Western diplomat who is not American.
``They always denied they had any connection. Last year the
Russians showed them pictures of weapons going from Pakistan to the
camps.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pakistani government dismissed the photos as fakes, the
diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Pakistan's Foreign Ministry nor its Information Ministry
responded to telephone messages seeking comment about the camps and
how they were supplied.
</P>
<P>
   A senior diplomat from another major American ally said there
was ``no doubt'' that the groups that had trained in the camps had
received assistance from Pakistani intelligence services. He said
that when the situation had gotten too hot politically, the
intelligence service would back off for a while.
</P>
<P>
   One of the groups that trained in Afghanistan was the Hezbul
Mujahedeen, or Party of Holy Warriors. This is the group in which
Zamin, the lawyer, is a senior commander, and he said more than
20,000 men had been trained at the camps in the last six years.
</P>
<P>
   The training day begins before dawn with prayers, followed by an
hour or two of running up and down the mountains, then breakfast.
The rest of the morning is for military training, including
instruction in the uses of weapons: automatic rifles, mortars,
rocket-propelled grenades and explosives. After lunch and prayers,
the afternoon is for the study of the Koran and for sports, then
dinner and bed.
</P>
<P>
   It is standard basic training, with the exception of the heavy
religious component.
</P>
<P>
   During what Zamin called ideological training, the focus is on
the jihad _ the holy war _ against America and Europe, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not against the American people,'' he said, carefully
swabbing up beans in a piece of nan. ``We have no bad feelings
towards them. We are against the American policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to other battles that the guerrillas are involved in,
he asked, ``Why does it matter to the Americans if they came here
for training to fight against their regimes at home?''
</P>
<P>
   In Algeria, he said, fundamentalist Muslims are at war against a
government that canceled elections in January 1992 after it became
clear that parties calling for an Islamic republic had won.
Washington and the West did not object to the coup. In Turkey, the
army has refused to let Islamic political parties govern, even
after electoral gains by fundamentalists. In Egypt, the government
discriminates against fundamentalist Muslims, he said _ for
example, by discouraging women from veiling themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The religious underpinning of such battles was emphasized in an
anecdote told by Zamin. Before a fighter is sent into battle, he
must write a letter to be given to his family should he die. Such a
letter was found on the body of Hafiz Shabir Ahmad, who was killed
in Kashmir in June.
</P>
<P>
   The letter read, ``If with the blessing of God, I become a
martyr, please show extreme patience, because life is the trust of
God and if He gets his trust back, there is no reason to cry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-26-98 1913EDT &QL; 
