<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Thursday, Aug. 27. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   FUNDRAISING-GORE (Washington) _ Attorney General Janet Reno
advances a step closer to asking for an independent prosecutor to
investigate Vice President Al Gore's role in fund raising for the
1996 campaign by ordering a 90-day preliminary inquiry into whether
Gore lied to investigators last year when he was initially
interviewed about his telephone solicitations from the White House.
By David Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.N.-RITTER (Undated) _ The senior-ranking American
inspector on the U.N. Special Commission responsible for disarming
Iraq resigns, charging Secretary General Kofi Annan, the Security
Council and the Clinton Administration with betraying the effort to
dimantle Iraq's programs for chemical, biological and nuclear
weapons. By Judith Miller.
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-BONNIE (Wilmington, N.C.) _ Developing.
Tropical-storm-force wind and rain lashed the Atlantic coast as the
Hurricane Bonnie reached the mainland Wednesday afternoon. By Kevin
Sack.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-U.S. (Washington) _ Examining further the U.S.
justification for bombing a Sudanese pharmaceutical factory. Story
includes exclusive developments. Details to come. By Steven Lee
Myers.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-POLITICS (Moscow) _ The inside story of backroom
intrigues that led to the most recent upheaval in Russia's
government: Boris Berezovsky and other tycoons exploited the
financial crisis to install a more pliant government. By Michael R.
Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   With RUSSIA-ECON.
</P>
<P>
   LIBYA-LOCKERBIE (United Nations) _ Libya accepts, but in guarded
language, an American and British proposal that two Libyans wanted
for the bombing of a Pan Am jet in 1988 be tried in the Netherlands
by Scottish judges. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   NYMAYOR-FUNDRAISING _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani is raising money
for other Republicans in Wisconsin and Iowa, where the question
centers on his political plans. Many Iowans seem impressed when he
notes that the number of murders in New York City has declined
during his tenure to 800 a year from 2,000. Many also say they are
familiar with the mayor through his appearances on David Letterman
and the Tonight Show. By Dan Barry.
</P>
<P>
   Reefers:
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT-PRIVACY (Washington) _ FTC administrative law judge rules
that one of the nation's largest credit bureaus is violating law by
selling detailed consumer credit information to merchants and
advertisers without the consumers' knowledge. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   KING-RENO (Washington) _ Attorney General Reno announces a
limited review of two new charges in the Martin Luther King
assassination. By David Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   CONGO-REBELLION (Kinshasa, Congo) _ The sound of explosives and
gunfire reverberate throughout the capital as government and rebel
forces fight each other on the city's outskirts. By Norimitsu
Onishi. (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   BRUNEI (Bandar Seri Begawan, Brunei) _ Oil-rich Brunei is
experiencing something utterly new in its well-lubricated history:
a cash-flow crunch. And on top of that, a bitter feud has broken
out in the royal family since the Sultan stripped his younger
brother of his posts as head of Brunei's state investment agency
and one of its largest conglomerates. By Mark Landler.
</P>
