<SLUG> BC-VIAGRA-DEATHS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FDA, PFIZER DOWNPLAY VIAGRA DEATHS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At least 69 Americans taking Viagra, the impotence medication,
died in the first four months it was on the market, according to
the US Food and Drug Administration's latest count. The
significance of that statistic is being hotly debated.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA insists that Viagra is safe, even though the death toll
has risen by 30 since its last report a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   Several medical groups, meanwhile, say the rising toll
reinforces their calls for better labeling of the drug by its
manufacturer, Pfizer Inc., and greater caution by doctors
prescribing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pfizer and FDA are saying in a cavalier and reckless way that
there's no problem,'' said Dr. Sidney Wolfe, director of the
consumer organization Health Research Group. ``The labeling on the
drug is completely unacceptable to us.''
</P>
<P>
   The American Heart Association and American College of
Cardiology have also expressed concerns, saying Viagra could pose a
risk to more people than is indicated on its label.
</P>
<P>
   But other physicians, along with federal officials, say the
figure of 69 deaths is not that high, since more than 2 million men
have taken the drug, and that many were old enough perhaps to have
died from overexertion.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the basis of data we've seen,'' added an FDA spokesman,
Brad Stone, ``it appears that Viagra is safe and effective when
used as indicated.''
</P>
<P>
   To understand the concerns about Viagra's safety, it helps to
understand the avalanche of interest after the drug was released in
April. In just four months, 3.6 million prescriptions were written
and 30 million tablets dispensed, making it the most instantly
popular prescription medication ever.
</P>
<P>
   But is it safe?
</P>
<P>
   Pfizer insists that it is, although the label warns that
life-threatening low blood pressure can result if people taking
heart medicine containing nitrates also use Viagra. And it cautions
about cardiac risk for people taking the drug who have not been
sexually active.
</P>
<P>
   This month, however, the College of Cardiology and the Heart
Association warned that Viagra can be dangerous for a long list of
other patients, including ones with insufficient blood flow to the
heart, congestive heart failure combined with borderline low blood
pressure, or those taking several drugs for high blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   It also urged special precautions for men with severe liver or
kidney problems, or those taking such drugs as erythromycin or
cimetidine.
</P>
<P>
   The two groups promise a more definitive statement by the end of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the FDA has been tracking Viagra-related
deaths, and released its latest figures this week. While reports
are sketchy, the agency said that through July of this year, it had
solid evidence of 69 patients who had died after taking the drug.
Two had strokes, 46 had heart attacks or cardiovascular troubles,
and the cause of death could not be determined for the remaining
21.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the deaths also varied: 25 died or had onset of
symptoms within five hours of using Viagra; 16 died or developed
symptoms within four days of use; and the time from ingestion to
death was unknown in the rest.
</P>
<P>
   To Wolfe, the consumer activist, the new data back up a petition
he filed last week asking the FDA to review Viagra's side effects
and strengthen its warning label.
</P>
<P>
   But Andy McCormick, a Pfizer spokesman, said that after four
months ``we haven't seen anything different in rare side effects
the way we sometimes do with new drugs.'' And the FDA's Stone said
that while the agency will review Wolfe's petition and the medical
groups' concerns, for now there is no reason to spell out
additional concerns on Viagra's label.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Thomas Graboys, who runs the Lown Cardiovascular Center at
Brigham and Women's Hospital, takes a middle ground on the safety
questions. On the one hand, he said, a certain number of deaths can
be expected, since millions of men are taking the drug, and many
are not used to sexual exertion. On the other, concerns about more
users being at risk than previously believed must be taken
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``The jury is out and we're in a state of watchful waiting,''
Grayboys concluded. ``That requires doctors to spend a significant
time with patients discussing the implications of their problem, of
their impotence and the implication of using the medication.''
</P>
</TEXT>
