<HEADER>
A3934 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FIGHTING-TERRORISM-2N     08-26 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIGHTING-TERRORISM-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS QUESTION MILITARY STRIKES IN TARGETING BIN LADEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: SUBS grafs 11-14 to reflect Pakistani cooperation, sanctions
on India; pickup15thgraf: Joseph Reat)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By NICOLE TSONG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States needs to dramatically increase
the reward for bombing suspect Osama bin Laden and seek greater
cooperation with countries that harbor him to weaken the
millionaire's ability to carry out attacks, an Israeli terrorism
expert said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Ehud Sprinzak, a Hebrew University political science professor
and a senior fellow at the United States Institute of Peace, said
increasing the reward for information on bin Laden might be the key
to finding him. The United States is offering $2 million for
information leading to the capture of bin Laden, but Sprinzak said
it should be $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinzak spoke at a news conference sponsored by the Institute
of Peace, a federal agency created by Congress to promote conflict
resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Arthur, a political science professor at the University of
Ulster and another Institute of Peace fellow, said the United
States needs to build a global coalition to avoid being isolated in
its retaliatory attacks against terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration accuses bin Laden, a wealthy Saudi
outcast, of using his personal fortune to finance terrorist
activities _ including the recent bombings of the U.S. embassies in
Keyna and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   With a high price on bin Laden's head, he would ``very quickly
feel the heat'' from organizations in the Middle East that would be
attracted to a large reward, Sprinzak said.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has long suspected bin Laden as being a
leading sponsor of terrorism. In 1994, he took refuge in Sudan
after losing citizenship in his native Saudi Arabia for opposing
the ruling family. He was ousted from there two years later when
the United States threatened Sudan with trade sanctions, and he
moved to Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   Bin Laden gathers support from groups such as the Taliban, a
fundamentalist Islamic movement that controls much of Afghanistan.
But Sprinzak said some of his reported 3,000 supporters might tell
of bin Laden's whereabouts in exchange for a hefty reward.
</P>
<P>
   Through money and cooperation with countries that currently
harbor him, Sprinzak added, bin Laden might be exiled and then
forced to wander, looking for countries that will protect him.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinzak argued that bin Laden's lack of citizenship will make
it easier to find him because he can be exiled from any nation that
decides it is no longer in its interests to protect him.
</P>
<P>
   Although Pakistan has cooperated with the United States in
hunting down other terrorism suspects, Sprinzak contends that the
Pakistani government could help find bin Laden. If it ``decides
tomorrow that the fellow damages their interests, (Pakistan) can
solve the problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Pakistan have had lukewarm relations in
recent years because of the country's efforts to develop nuclear
weapons. President Clinton imposed sanctions on both Pakistan and
neighboring India after the two South Asian nations traded
tit-for-tat nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Reat, a State Department spokesman, said he had no
immediate comment on Sprinzak's statements.
</P>
<P>
   At Wednesday's news conference, Arthur argued that bin Laden's
lack of citizenship makes it easier for him to escape U.S. efforts
to pursue him.
</P>
<P>
   Bin Laden has an amorphous group of supporters and he isn't
rooted, Arthur said. He described bin Laden's power structure as
``faceless'' and elusive.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to relying on military force to respond to
terrorism, Arthur suggests that the United States build an alliance
against terror.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is in U.S. foreign policy interests to start again
this business of coalition building,'' he said, adding that America
is ``dangerously isolated'' as the sole superpower.
</P>
<P>
   .MDSD/.MDNM/
</P>
</TEXT>
