<HEADER>
A3936 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BO     08-26 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSTER NOT DONE COMPOSING MASTERFUL TENNIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ ``Shut up, Thomas!''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Muster can still hear the kind burghers of Leibnitz
addressing him affectionately when he was a boy at play: ``Shut up,
Thomas!''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not affection,'' he concedes. ``They hated the way I
played.''
</P>
<P>
   But how could those ear-abused Leibnitzers divine the future?
How would they imagine that growing in the midst of their
celebrated vineyards was a kid whose belting of rubber lemons would
one day bring the town more fame than its succulent grapes? A
platinum-headed lefthander possibly destined for a niche in the
International Tennis Hall of Fame at Newport?
</P>
<P>
   It happened because Thomas Muster _ the Moo Man _ burned with a
desire to compete on a tennis court as surely as an earlier
Austrian, Wolfgang Mozart, was hot to outdo every other composer on
earth.
</P>
<P>
   Mozart would understand the way Muster waves his racket as
though a mad conductor demanding fortissimo. And accompanying his
blustering swings with strings, Muster delivers the fortissimo
sound himself.
</P>
<P>
   The Musterian sounds roll forth from his diaphragm, echoing
across the landscape, so that you may say, ``I heard Muster play at
Longwood.'' Even though you might have been across the street and
down the block having your hair cut by Silvio, and not seen him at
all.
</P>
<P>
   Muster hearings are much more common than Muster sightings,
although the customers at the MFS Pro Championships tonight may
combine the two as he wallops and wails at the Ecuadorian Nicholas
Lapentti in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Muster is definitely back in town after a 10-year absence,
even though, if the wind was right, you may have heard him laboring
in Paris as he won the French Open in 1995, or in Miami winning The
Lipton last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Longwood looks the same,'' he said, ``but where's the clay?''
That was the footing in 1988 when he beat Lawson Duncan to win the
title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mind these hard courts now,'' he said. ``In fact, I
like them. It took me a while to get used to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Muster would fight his heart out on any surface
because that's his way _ sound effects with resoundingly smacked,
topspin-dripping groundies. He could be knee-deep in a
grape-stomping tub at home and still battle you to the death.
</P>
<P>
   This quality attracted Ron Leitgeb, his triple-threat
countryman: friend-coach-manager. It's a weird coupling that has
worked wonders since 1984, when Muster was a crude-stroking
16-year-old in the French Juniors and tennis nut Leitgeb was a
25-year-old medical student in Vienna.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to Paris on a holiday to do some radio reports on the
French Open for a friend who owned a station, and I saw _ I mean, I
heard _ Thomas for the first time. Wojtek Fibak (former Polish
Davis Cupper) told me Muster was crazy but he could play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crazy was all right. After all, I'm from Dr. Freud's city. And
I thought Thomas could become a player, too. I wanted to help
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Out the window went medicine, although Leitgeb doesn't deny a
little amateur psychiatry is involved. Naturally. It's tennis. They
became partners in learning the game at a higher level.
</P>
<P>
   ``We learned each day together, and still do. I had a concept, a
bigger picture than other Austrian coaches and the tennis
federation. The good Austrian players got spoiled early, given too
much money. They were content to be local heroes. We went off on
our own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thomas, as you know, is not spoiled, although he's rich. He
does the work.''
</P>
<P>
   Muster's piercing blue eyes crinkle. ``I didn't like to start
working at first,'' he said. ``But when I got on the court ...
</P>
<P>
   ``When Ron met me I had a fair forehand, no backhand, just a
drop shot. We watched (Guillermo) Vilas's and (Henri) Leconte's
topspin backhands. That helped.''
</P>
<P>
   Muster's work ethic was clear as he rehabbed feverishly after
his left knee was injured in a 1989 auto accident, his career left
in rubble. Physicians couldn't believe it: He not only walked
normally but returned to the tour in six months.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was in the hospital I was insecure about what would
happen to me, but I was impatient to play again,'' Muster said. So
impatient that he practiced while in a wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   How much longer does Muster, 31 in October _ as high as world
No. 1, now No. 24 _ want to goad and push himself, to run down
balls like a poor kid chasing quarters?
</P>
<P>
   ``Tennis is complex,'' he said. ``You have to have the mind and
body working together like I did in '95, '96, '97.'' He hasn't
added a title this season to a career total of 44, third among
current laborers, behind Pete Sampras's 55 and Boris Becker's 49.
``You have to set your goals, and I haven't worked mine out this
year yet. Is there more very good tennis left in me? I don't
know.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the sound system is still working in Dolby stereo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've made these awful noises since I was a boy. People didn't
like it. I tried to stop, like Monica Seles did. But I'm like her.
I couldn't play as well quieted down.''
</P>
<P>
   If Mozart were around, he'd love the Muster sounds _ tenor,
baritone, and bass. Maybe Wolfgang would call him the Pavarotti of
the Pavement and incorporate those tones in an opera called ``The
Magic Forehand,'' with Muster as the dragon.
</P>
<P>
   Mozart could sympathize. Probably when he played the piano late
at night, the neighbors yelled, ``Shut up, Wolfie!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
