<P>
   RILEY-EDUCATION (Seattle) U.S. Education Secretary Richard
Riley, in town for back-to-school pep talks, outlined a new
strategy for preventing school violence. In an interview, he said a
new ``early warning'' plan, soon to be announced by President
Clinton, calls for every school to have ``an openness for young
people to feel free to talk'' and to have a plan for predicting and
dealing with violent outbursts such as those in Springfield, Ore.
Riley also said a key to warding off violence is Clinton's pending
proposal to reduce average class sizes to 18 kids _ which would
give our state $236 million for construction and $180 million for
teachers. Riley said smaller classes are the top priority of
security officers in large urban disticts.
</P>
<P>
   By Kathy George. (story will move in the ``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-MARINERS (Cleveland) Mariners play Indians.
</P>
<P>
   By Jim Street. (story will move in the ``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-COLUMN-THIEL (Undated) The tale of two men _ baseball
superstar Mark McGwire and President Bill Clinton. Developing.
</P>
<P>
   By Art Thiel. (story will move in the ``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBC-HUSKIES (Seattle) Reggie Davis came out of Southern
California destined to be a great rover back at the University of
Washington. Then he was going to be a great inside linebacker. Then
a great outside linebacker. Then he was going to get it done at
defensive end, and outside linebacker again, and then at H-back.
Now, facing his last season as a Husky, he is their starting tight
end, and it becomes clearer how his teammates voted the honor of
co-captain to a guy who received two passes last year.
</P>
<P>
   By Bud Withers. (story will move in the ``s'' category)
</P>
