<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3952 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-ECON-450(2TAKE     08-26 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ECON-450(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS RUSSIA'S CRISIS DEEPENS, PREMIER HURRIES TO SEE IMF CHIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also RUSSIA-POLITICS) 
(bl) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ As Russia confronts its worst financial crisis since
the collapse of the Soviet Union and the ruble poised for a free
fall, Acting Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin made a sudden trip
to Ukraine on Wednesday to convince the head of the International
Monetary Fund not to cut off its next installment of credits.
</P>
<P>
   Alarmed by the ruble's 9 percent drop Tuesday, anxious Russians
rushed to their banks Wednesday morning only to be given mixed
signals on when and how they can retrieve their savings. An early
round of dollar trading on the Moscow currency exchange was voided
Wednesday for the first time in the exchange's history, while the
ruble's value fell 40 percent against the German mark in a single
transaction.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's Central Bank, under bitter attack at home and abroad
for its handling of the crisis, said Wednesday it could no longer
afford to protect the ruble. It reporting that it had already spent
$8.8 billion doing so in the last two months.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, the bank said it would not put limits on
currency transactions. Such a move, it said, would be a step back
to ``another economic model.''
</P>
<P>
   As the banking crisis threatens to engulf Russia's entire
financial system, the Central Bank took its first tough action
Wednesday by withdrawing the license of Bank AB Imperial, Russia's
13th-largest bank, which had reportedly defaulted on payments on
foreign loans earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday three major Russian banks announced plans to merge,
while six Moscow banks Wednesday said they would pool their
resources to end the deadlock of non-payments that has crippled
Russian banking transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin's quick trip to the Crimean resort of Simferapol,
where IMF managing director Michel Camdessus was to meet Wednesday
afternoon with Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma, was seen as a
sign of Russia's growing concern that the IMF will refuse to issue
its next installment of $4.8 billion in credits, due to be reviewed
by the IMF's board in September.
</P>
<P>
   Delivery of the funds is now Russia's only hope for a new
injection of foreign aid, as Western leaders warned Wednesday that
it would be up to the Russian government to pull the country out of
its looming financial nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no shortcuts in restoring market confidence, and the
next steps are up to the Russia,'' White House spokesman Barry Toiv
told reporters in Edgartown, Mass., where President Clinton was on
vacation.
</P>
<P>
   That nightmare was already on the horizon for thousands of
Russian companies, caught between the ruble's downward spiral and a
gridlock in the Russian banking system. Several companies Wednesday
reported that their banks have not forwarded payments made by
customers.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``They take money out of your account, and it may or may not
leave your bank, you don't know,'' said an director at a Russian
food processing plant. ``As a client of the bank, I don't care what
they are waiting for,'' said another Russian businessman who also
asked not to be identified. ``After one week of this, they are
killing me.''
</P>
<P>
   President Boris Yeltsin has made no further comment on the
crisis since a televised appearance Monday, when he gave a brief
explanation of his reappointment of Chernomyrdin, the man he had
fired as prime minister five months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Financial and economic policy is a question to which I am
giving my attention minute by minute,'' Chernomyrdin told the
ITAR-Tass news agency. ``I am extremely dissatisfied with the work
of the central bank over the last two days.''
</P>
<P>
   As Chernomyrdin flew to Ukraine on Wednesday, leaders in
Russia's Parliament continued their public bargaining over the
future of his government and its policies. At a press conference
Wednesday, Speaker Gennady Seleznyov, a Communist, said the
Parliament was still working on its own anti-crisis plan, which he
said Chernomyrdin must endorse before his appointment can be
confirmed at a session now scheduled for Sept. 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might be ready by next Monday afternoon,'' said Seleznyov,
referring to the anti-crisis document, ``but we would not want to
rush things since we are speaking about a very serious document.''
</P>
<P>
   In a television interview Wednesday night, Seleznyov again
appealed for Yeltsin's resignation, a possibility that a Kremlin
spokesman dismissed earlier in the day as ``stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin on Tuesday told parliamentary leaders he was open
to a coalition government that would include members of the
Communist opposition, but Seleznyov has insisted that negotiations
over ministerial appointments come after adoption of a joint
strategy to handle the current crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Wednesday at a press conference if the Communist Party,
which holds the largest bloc in the Parliament, will join the new
government, Seleznyov said that the question had not yet been
resolved.
</P>
<P>
   While the political haggling over the new government continues,
financial analysts said Russia's financial situation was worsening
by the hour, with no clear policy from the Central Bank or the
government in sight.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Some banks are really bankrupt,'' said Nikolai Gusev, a trader
at Regent European Securities, an investment company, ``and the
population is going to start withdrawing their money.''
</P>
<P>
   Only 20 percent of Russian savings accounts are held in
commercial banks _ with the rest in the giant government-controlled
Sberbank _ but much of these are held in several of the largest
banks now reported to be in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no clear scheme for an operation transferring
deposits to Sberbank,'' said Gusev. ``There have been only words,
and no concrete words.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Russian banks were putting their walk-in customers
Wednesday on waiting lists, others were returning money in dribs
and drabs. ``You can call and check your place on the list, and
they don't allow people to cut the line as far as I can see,'' said
Pavel Mirovc, a 29-year-old sales consultant who was waiting in
line at downtown branch office of Most Bank. ``But of course I am
worried. They are giving out very little money.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been coming every day,'' said a middle-aged woman, as
she and her husband were leaving the same bank early this evening.
``They give us our money little by little. But at least they are
giving something. But we've become part-time guards of the bank.''
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts attributed Tuesday's heaving trading on Moscow
currency exchange to the Central Bank's continued supply of credits
to Russia's troubled banks, and by its decision last week to lower
the banks' minimum capital requirements, which freed up ruble
reserves that the bankers then exchanged for dollars.
</P>
<P>
   An anti-crisis program, announced Aug. 17 by Chernomyrdin's
predecessor, Sergei Kiriyenko, included a 90-day moratorium on
payments of debts owed by Russia's commercial banks to foreign
lenders. Some Russian banks this week have said they will ignore
the moratorium and pay their debts, but with the fall in the ruble,
many foreign creditors have been left wondering where the other
banks will find the money to meet their debt payments when the
moratorium ends in mid-November.
</P>
<P>
   The government's plan to swap $40 million held in Russian
short-term Treasury bills for new longer term securities has also
left foreign investors with a bitter taste. But its main impact is
on Russian holders of the Treasury bills _ major banks, but also
pension and other investment funds _ which are now stuck with
assets that are worth less than their original value, and are less
accessible.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin on Wednesday tried to distance himself from the
debt restructuring plan, which was originally announced by the
Kiriyenko government. ``I would like people to understand us
correctly: this decision was predetermined,'' he said. ``In actual
fact, our task was only to formulate it, and we could not do
otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   According to most analysts, the Central Bank has to take
decisive action to restore credibility to the financial system.
``What they have to do is limit rubles reserves, and start to close
down banks,'' said Holger Mueller, banking analyst at Fleming UCB,
an investment firm. ``They have to do it right now, and do it as
fast possible, because there is still value in these banks, and
they have to make sure there is no asset stripping.''
</P>
<P>
   At a press conference Wednesday, Dmitry Vasilyev, chairman of
Russia's Federal Securities Commission, joined others in putting
the blame on the Central Bank, in particular a televised statement
by a top bank official on Aug. 12 who shocked viewers with the
announcement of a restriction on access to foreign currency.
</P>
<P>
   ``This caused a panic and huge requests for currency from legal
entities and the population,'' said Vasilyev. ``This drastically
destabilized the situation and ended with the government and
Central Bank statement of August 17. As a result we have an
extremely grave situation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As I see it, it is possible that all that has happened on the
currency market, the actions of the Central Bank may merit an
investigation by law enforcement agencies,'' he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
