<SLUG> BC-MIT-RESIDENCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIT TO REQUIRE ON-CAMPUS RESIDENCY FOR FRESHMEN IN 2001 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Still reeling from a year that began with a student's
death from an alcohol overdose at a fraternity hazing, the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology opened its new year Wednesday
with the announcement that it will require all freshmen to live on
campus beginning in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The change, one of several steps aimed at curbing binge
drinking, was one that has been proposed several times over the
years, only to be postponed by opposition from alumni and faculty
with their own memories of freshman year in MIT fraternity houses _
a tradition that dates back to the school's earliest years.
</P>
<P>
   President Charles M. Vest made the decision reluctantly, and
students and some faculty continued to voice their opposition
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of people have had excellent experiences living
in frats their freshmen year,'' said Steve Lefkowitz, a 20-year-old
junior at Beta Theta Pi &UR; . &LR;  ``Living closely with other guys who are
there with the intention of helping you in the transition into
school.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the aftermath of Scott Krueger's death last September and
the sanctioning of Beta Theta Pi and four other fraternities in the
year since, officials said they had no choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very difficult decision, but it was one that needed
to be made,'' said Neal Dorow, MIT's adviser to fraternities and
sororities. ``It was the necessary thing to do, given the
circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   The Suffolk County District Attorney's office is still
investigating Krueger's death at an MIT fraternity located in
Boston, and the school had received pressure from parents concerned
about their children living in fraternities.
</P>
<P>
   Since almost its earliest days as a downtown Boston campus in
the 1860s, MIT's fraternities have played an unusual role in
housing freshmen.
</P>
<P>
   At other schools, freshmen rush fraternities or sororities in
their first year, but do not live in Greek houses until at least
their second year. But a tight housing market in Boston and
Cambridge and the dearth of residence halls on campus made the
Greeks the residences of necessity for first-year students.
</P>
<P>
   The school's first fraternity was built in 1873, but its first
residence hall was not built until 1916 _ when there were already
21 fraternities. Today, the school has 10 residence halls and 38
fraternities, sororities, and so-called independent living groups.
It offers guaranteed housing to students for all four years, but
cannot house everyone in dormitories, so relies on Greeks for extra
room. The school plans to build a new residence hall on campus to
hold the freshmen.
</P>
<P>
   The fraternities remain a fiercely cherished tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is exactly why, even though it's been obvious this needs
to be done _ making the freshmen live on campus _ we haven't done
it,'' said one administrator who did not wish to be identified.
``Each time we proposed it, the students and the alums got so upset
about the end of tradition, that everyone's backed down. Scott
Krueger's death was a terrible reinforcement of these kinds of
concerns, but there have been other concerns to a lesser degree for
a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   A special working group on dangerous drinking, convened by Vest
after Krueger's death, reported in May that it ``strongly belives
that requiring freshmen to live on campus would reduce that
population's risk of being involved in dangerous drinking. Clearly,
on-campus housing for freshmen would not preclude their
participation in drinking, but it might help to reduce the
perceived social pressure for such activity.''
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Licensing Board gave an eight-month liquor license
suspension to Krueger's fraternity, Phi Gamma Delta, after his
death, and over the past year, the board has sanctioned five other
fraternities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
