<HEADER>
A3964 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GP-COX     08-26 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia-Pacific: Asian turmoil chips away at stock price
 &HT;    By Cynthia Mitchell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Asia's chilly economic winds are buffeting the
overall stock market, but they've hit paper and forest products
stocks with gale force.
</P>
<P>
   And because of its relatively high debt levels and operating
capacity _ what analysts call operating and financial leverage _
the stock of Georgia-Pacific Corp.'s paper, pulp and building
products business is taking a bigger hit than most of its
competitors. The business trades as Georgia-Pacific Group.
</P>
<P>
   Since hitting a high of $81 May 12, Georgia-Pacific Group's
stock has skidded nearly 42 percent, falling to 52-week lows
several times over the past month. On Wednesday, it closed at
$47.12 1/2, down $1.68 3/4 on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Seven other major forest products companies also have hit
52-week lows in August, including the country's biggest,
Weyerhaeuser.
</P>
<P>
   Most of these stocks last traded at these prices in the winter _
again over concerns about Asia's economic crisis, which came to a
head last fall. But they started climbing this spring, spurred by
strong first-quarter earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were saying, 'Gee, we heard Asia was a problem, but we
don't see it yet.' So everybody assumed Asia wasn't relevant,''
explained Sherman Chao, one of the sector's most bearish analysts.
``Some forecasters were thinking if it hasn't happened now, it's
not going to. But now it has.''
</P>
<P>
   Chao is advising clients to sell Georgia-Pacific, Champion
International and Weyerhaeuser.
</P>
<P>
   Asia's impact is most glaring in the markets for paper and wood
pulp, which accounts for about 60 percent of the cost of making
paper. The two areas made up 43 percent of Georgia-Pacific's sales
of $12.97 billion in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Not only have U.S. exports to Asia dropped at double-digit
rates, but the region's weak currencies mean cheaper imports are
flooding the United States as well.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: The world's pulp and paper manufacturers are
chasing a smaller market, so prices have been pushed down. Pulp
prices have fallen 7 percent to 10 percent from year-ago levels,
depending on the grade, and uncoated white paper has dropped as
much as 17.5 percent for a standard 50-pound roll, according to
Pulp &AMP; Paper Week.
</P>
<P>
   The trends are expected to continue through at least the rest of
this year, with most analysts lowering their earnings estimates for
the third and fourth quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike earlier cycles, however, industry watchers are comforted
by the factcompanies are getting smarter about taking production
downtime to dampen the decline, rather than continuing to flood an
unreceptive market, which just makes prices worse.
</P>
<P>
   In the pulp market, which is a money loser at current industry
prices, Georgia-Pacific has made the most dramatic move _ one much
welcomed by the industry.
</P>
<P>
   On July 30, the country's second-largest maker of market pulp
said it was indefinitely shutting down 24 percent of production, or
500,000 tons a year. Most of that is coming from mothballing the
market pulp operations at its Ashdown, Ark., and Port Hudson, La.,
mills, which will result in a $15 million charge to third-quarter
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Market pulp refers to pulp sold to other companies, as opposed
to what companies produce for their own paper-making.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the economic downturn in Asia and its weaker currencies,
Southern hardwood market pulp is not a viable product,''
Georgia-Pacific Chairman and Chief Executive Pete Correll explained
when announcing the closings.
</P>
<P>
   Salomon Smith Barney analyst Chip Dillon has estimated the
reduction amounts to 3 percent of the global hardwood market and
1.5 percent of the overall pulp market _ and a much bigger chunk of
the industry's unused capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Paper struggling
</P>
<P>
   While the prices for communications papers and containerboard
were better than they were in the year-ago second quarter, they're
also down compared with previous quarters and are expected to
continue heading lower.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Georgia-Pacific has taken downtime in the first and
second quarters for those areas as well, and says it's continuing
to do so this quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our view is that we will do whatever is necessary to address
adverse changes in particular markets,'' said Georgia-Pacific
spokesman Ken Haldin. ``That has continued to be our approach to
ensure we stay competitive in those segments and to make sure we
can stay economically viable.''
</P>
<P>
   The question now is whether the current low stock prices mean
it's a good time to buy or a good time to bail. Of the 16
Georgia-Pacific Group analysts surveyed by Multex Professional
Investment Review, half say neither, having issued ``hold''
recommendations. Two are advocating selling, and six think it's a
good time to scoop up more.
</P>
<P>
   Multex calls the stock ``a contrarian's dream,'' given the
sector as a whole is unattractive and Georgia-Pacific's stock is
doing worse relative to the rest.
</P>
<P>
   To the bullish analysts, it's the longer view that's more
important. They're encouraged by the companies' efforts to wring
out excess costs, improve efficiencies and rein in capacity.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. companies increased capacity by just 1.9 percent last year,
according to the American Forest &AMP; Paper Association's annual
year-end survey, and planned to keep expansion at an average of
just 1.2 percent a year through 2000.
</P>
<P>
   And the Asian crisis has forced Asian competitors to halt their
massive investments in new capacity.
</P>
<P>
   There's also industry consolidation through asset sales and
mergers:
</P>
<P>
   Canada's Abitibi-Price merged with Stone Consolidated in a $4
billion transaction in May 1997
</P>
<P>
   In August, James River Corp., maker of Brawny paper towels and
other consumer paper products, struck a $7 billion merger agreement
with Fort Howard, the largest commercial and industrial tissue
maker
</P>
<P>
   This past March, Bowater agreed to buy Avenor, another Canadian
newsprint maker, for $3.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we're struggling with cyclical concerns about
demand, but that restrained capacity should remain in place
substantially longer and be a big long-term benefit,'' said
Prudential Securities analyst Mark Rogers, one of the bulls. ``I
think the worst of the bad news is out.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia-Pacific Corp.'s timber business, which trades as Timber
Group, isn't affected by the global markets nearly as much _ a big
reason Georgia-Pacific Corp. separated it from its highly cyclical
paper and building products businesses last December.
</P>
<P>
   In the eight months since it opened at $25, Timber Group has
traded mostly in the low to mid $20s, closing at $21.50 Wednesday.
Eight out of the 10 analysts that cover it have a ``buy'' rating on
the stock.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
