<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORTHWEST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Facing possible pilot walkout, Northwest scrubs a few flights
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Northwest Airlines is canceling some flights Friday
and Saturday in preparation for a possible pilot strike that could
also affect the carrier's 1,800 mechanics in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The Minnesota-based airline said Wednesday it will scrub 170 of
1,700 flights Friday and an additional 230 Saturday, even if the
strike is averted.
</P>
<P>
   The pilots are free to strike at 12:01 a.m. Saturday, when a
30-day deadline expires.
</P>
<P>
   Last-ditch negotiations between Northwest and its Air Line
Pilots Association unit continued Wednesday amid conflicting
indications of progress.
</P>
<P>
   An aide to President Clinton told Bloomberg News the president
probably wouldn't block a walkout at Northwest, as he did when
American Airlines pilots tried to strike in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest, the nation's fourth-biggest airline and a dominant
carrier in the Midwest and on U.S.-Asia routes, said the advance
cancellations will ensure planes are positioned for an orderly
shutdown and quick resumption of service.
</P>
<P>
   The airline has only 16 daily flights from Hartsfield
International Airport, a tiny market share. Four of Friday's
canceled flights involve Atlanta departures. They are flights 494
and 498 to Detroit; 827 to Memphis; and 731 to Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, three Atlanta-bound flights are canceled: Flight
493 from Detroit; and flights 736 and 738 from Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers will be rebooked on other flights or will get
refunds, Northwest said. (A full list of canceled flights is posted
on Northwest's Web site, http://www.nwa.com.)
</P>
<P>
   While a strike wouldn't disrupt travel for many Atlantans, it
could spill over to the 1,800 mechanics at Northwest's maintenance
hangar at Hartsfield. They are members of the International
Association of Machinists, which is also locked in long-running
contract talks and could be asked by the pilot union to honor
picket lines.
</P>
<P>
   So far, ALPA hasn't made such a request. If it does, mechanics
would have to decide individually whether to honor it, a Machinists
spokesman said, because the union cannot legally wage a sympathy
strike.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest has warned non-pilot workers they could be fired for
joining the strike. It also says layoffs will begin early next week
if the strike persists.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest has lobbied for presidential intervention to prevent a
strike. But the carrier is less far-flung than American, which the
Clinton aide cited as the reason such action is unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Aviation consultant Mike Boyd thinks there's another reason:
American's pilots belong to an independent union, while ALPA is
part of the AFL-CIO, a major Democratic supporter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton won't step in this time,'' Boyd predicted. ``He can't
deny the right to strike to an AFL-CIO union. If he did, Democrats
would have an out-of-body experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
