u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MALAYSIA-FREE-SPEECH-     08-26 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALAYSIA-FREE-SPEECH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA JAILS OPPOSITION LEGISLATOR FOR CRITICIZING JUDICIARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia _ An opposition member of Parliament has
been imprisoned on a charge of sedition for criticizing the
Malaysian judiciary, raising questions about the limits of free
speech here.
</P>
<P>
   The Parliament member, Lim Guan Eng, began serving a three-year
term on Tuesday after losing his final appeal in a case involving a
pamphlet he published in 1995 called ``The True Story.''
</P>
<P>
   In it, he questioned the government's decision not to press
statutory rape charges against a politician while holding the
15-year-old girl involved in ``protective custody'' for three
years.
</P>
<P>
   The London-based human rights group Amnesty International
criticized the ``arbitrary and selective'' use of sedition and
publishing laws ``to intimidate those who express dissenting
opinions and to engender public reluctance to criticize those in
power.''
</P>
<P>
   The news media are tightly restricted in Malaysia and politics
is dominated overwhelmingly by the governing party of Prime
Minister Mahathir Mohamad. Political commentators and ordinary
citizens choose their words carefully when they talk about
politics.
</P>
<P>
   The courts have indicated in the past their sensitivity to
criticism, and Judge Gopal Sri Ram reflected this attitude in
announcing an earlier decision in the case, when he said, ``It is
time that the court sends a clear message that it cannot tolerate
any attack on the judiciary.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement in Geneva last month, the Inter-Parliamentary
Union, representing members of parliaments in countries around the
world, criticized the original court ruling and ``the limits it
sets to the scope of the right to freedom of speech, in particular
to the right and the duty of the elected representatives of the
people to exercise their essential oversight function of the
executive.''
</P>
<P>
   Lim, 38, who is deputy secretary general of the opposition
Democratic Action Party and has been a member of Parliament for 12
years, is the first sitting member to be sent to prison. Under
Malaysian law, a jail term of more than 12 months will cost him his
seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``My political career may have terminated, but my political
struggle will go on,'' Lim said before being handcuffed and led
from the courthouse. ``I have no regrets in what I did. A rape
victim must be protected by the police and authorities and not
detained by authorities.''
</P>
<P>
   His father, Lim Kit Siang, who heads the opposition party in
Parliament, said the case raised the question of ``whether members
of Parliament should be able to speak up against injustices or
whether they should just be robots with no mind of their own.''
</P>
<P>
   Lim was convicted last year of sedition and printing ``false
news'' for criticizing the decision not to press charges against
Abdul Rahim Tamby Chik, a former chief minister from Lim's home
state of Malacca and a member of the governing party, the United
Malays National Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Amnesty International said that other men alleged to have had
sexual relations with the girl were prosecuted but that officials
insisted they did not have enough evidence to proceed against Chik.
</P>
<P>
   The girl, who acknowledged the sexual encounters, was held in a
center for ``wayward girls'' despite continued efforts by her
grandmother to gain her release, the organization said. The girl
gave birth while in custody.
</P>
<P>
   Lim became involved in the case when the girl's grandmother
sought his help in trying to obtain her release.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
