<SLUG> BC-CLINTONS-VINEYARD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VACATIONING PRESIDENT KEEPS LOW PROFILE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDGARTOWN, Mass. _ Under gray skies, President Clinton secluded
himself in his borrowed vacation house again Wednesday, presumably
reading and talking and continuing ahead with what the White House
has described as the healing process within the first family.
</P>
<P>
   From morning until night, Clinton stayed at his compound, far
from cameramen and reporters. The best his spokesman offered in
terms of insight was a list of books Clinton brought to the
Vineyard with him when he arrived last week.
</P>
<P>
   Some aides had broadly hinted that Clinton planned to play golf
Wednesday, which, in sharp contrast to past years when he played
roughly every other day, would have made it the first round of this
trip. There was no known reason why his game never materialized.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Clinton is scheduled to fly to Worcester for a 10:30
a.m. speech on school safety issues. At the event, he also plans to
highlight a federal scholarship program that provides tuition aid
to students who go on to become police officers, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The Worcester speech is expected to draw several hundred
supporters, and will be Clinton's first lengthy public appearance
since his admission on Aug. 17 that he carried on an extramarital
affair with former White House intern Monica S. Lewinsky and then
lied about it.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Barry Toiv said the Worcester speech,
presumably scheduled at the urging of some political strategists,
would not hinder Clinton's attempts to make peace with Hillary
Rodham Clinton and their daughter, Chelsea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that this is going to interfere with the healing
process that's going on,'' Toiv said.
</P>
<P>
   The White House indicated that it is not likely Clinton will
address the Lewinsky relationship in any way, and fended off
criticisms from some key Democrats that Clinton's actions were
``reprehensible'' and that he ought to offer the public an explicit
apology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, the president has spoken to that,'' Toiv said, referring
to the Aug. 17 speech.
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton huddles inside his house, he is also likely preparing
for his trip to Moscow and Ireland, which begins on Monday. The
White House announced Wednesday that Clinton will visit the town of
Omagh in Northern Ireland, the site of the gruesome bombing earlier
this month.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Clinton's reading list includes ``Good Work,'' a Los
Angeles-based mystery by Michael Connelly; a heavier tome called
``The Burning of Washington'' by Anthony S. Pitch, about the
British invasion of 1814; ``Eureka Street,'' by Robert McLiam
Wilson; and ``The Marriage of Sense and Soul'' by Ken Wilber, about
the compatability of science and religion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
