<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3970 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLOOD-BUSH-HNS &LR;      08-26 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOOD-BUSH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH TOURS DEVASTATION AS WHITE HOUSE DECLARES BORDER TOWN A
DISASTER AREA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By THADDEUS HERRICK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEL RIO, Texas _ The White House on Wednesday declared this
flood-stricken border town a disaster area, an announcement that
came moments after Gov. George W. Bush toured the devastation and
visited a shelter housing hundreds of people left homeless by
raging waters.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense is that nature can overpower humans,'' said Bush.
``And it did.''
</P>
<P>
   The disaster declaration means federal assistance for the people
of Del Rio, including unspecified amounts for housing grants and
low-cost loans for both businesses and individuals. It comes just
weeks after the government declared the entire state a disaster
area because of a severe summer-long drought.
</P>
<P>
   The governor praised the Clinton administration for acting
swiftly in dealing with the flood, saying, ``Everything that can be
done is being done.''
</P>
<P>
   While the disaster relief signified the beginning of what
promises to be a long rebuilding effort, rain Tuesday night
triggered more evacuations, and the number of people unaccounted
for in the flash floods surged to 54, renewing fears that the death
toll of 14 across Texas and the Mexican border might rise.
</P>
<P>
   Under partly cloudy skies Wednesday, authorities expressed
confidence that the number of people unaccounted for would dwindle
as locals reconnected with family and friends and realized those
reported missing were fine. However, they said they felt they had
exhausted efforts to locate at least 14 of the missing.
</P>
<P>
   Still, search and rescue workers continued to comb San Felipe
Creek, which Sunday night and early Monday unleashed a torrent that
nearly submerged an entire neighborhood. State authorities said 300
homes in Del Rio were destroyed while another 700 suffered damage.
</P>
<P>
   The number of residents in three temporary shelters rose to
about 1,700 after the Tuesday night evacuation, which focused on
the drier sections of the San Felipe neighborhood. The heart of the
neighborhood, very nearly washed away in the floods, is today a
place of ruin.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the water has receded, the brush has become more visible,''
said Bush. What officials fear, he said, is finding bodies in the
tangle of trees and piles of rubble that line either side of the
creek.
</P>
<P>
   Triggered by heavy rains from Tropical Storm Charley that came
ashore on the Gulf Coast, the floods swept south from the Hill
Country to Del Rio and neighboring Ciudad Acuna, Mexico. Six
people, all but one who has been identified, died in this town
while three are known dead in Acuna.
</P>
<P>
   The water, much of which emptied into the Rio Grande, was
expected to crest well above flood stage in Laredo in the early
evening Wednesday but was not predicted to cause near the
devastation seen in Del Rio. Still, some 800 people living along
the river were reported to be in shelters by late afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   And authorities closed the city's border crossings for the first
time since the 1960s because of torrential rains. With 5,000 to
6,000 trucks crossing its three international bridges daily, Laredo
is the busiest commercial land port in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In Maverick County, which lies between Del Rio and Laredo, some
5,000 people were evacuated, but no injuries were reported in the
flood waters that surged through Eagle Pass and surrounding areas
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican radio Wednesday said an additional three men who had
been sleeping beneath the international bridge connecting Acuna to
Del Rio had drowned. Many of the city's poor ``colonias,'' where
people often live in tar-paper shacks, were swept away, leaving
thousands homeless.
</P>
<P>
   Bush expressed his concern for Acuna, saying, ``There are no
borders when it comes to human life.'' But the governor's sympathy
was most directly conveyed to Del Rio residents, most of them from
the historic San Felipe neighborhood, a place of tidy adobe homes
before the flood.
</P>
<P>
   The floods knocked out the city's water system, leaving the town
of 34,000 with no drinking water and causing health officials
considerable concern. City officials reinstalled the pumps and
purifying system Tuesday, only to pull it out again for fear of
more floods Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Officials do not expect to have potable water for several more
days. In the meantime, they are relying on several hundred thousand
gallons of water a day being trucked in through private and public
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   After a helicopter tour of San Felipe and Cienegas Terrace, a
nearby community also hit hard, Bush made his way to the civic
center, where the Red Cross reported giving shelter to as many as
950 people Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   There, the governor heard stories of women holding their
children in waist deep water at night, hearing nothing but the
rushing current and the screams of their neighbors. One woman,
Diana Ortiz, told Bush that she lost everything and did not know
what would become of her life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm afraid,'' Ortiz said.
</P>
<P>
   To Ortiz and others the governor replied that he was seeking
federal help, which was later granted. Mostly he said, ``I'm
sorry,'' in one case hugging a teary-eyed elderly woman, Paula
Yanes, who was hard of hearing and without any known friends or
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was holding back my tears the whole time,'' Bush told Del
Rio Mayor Robert Chavira after circling the civic center floor for
about 30 minutes. Later the governor said, ``The human stories are
compelling and my heart breaks for the families who went from a
nice, secure home to no home at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Red Cross officials said those who lost their homes would likely
be housed in mobile homes in the coming days. For now they're
sleeping on cots in the civic center, where shock in some cases is
turning to despair.
</P>
<P>
   Silvia Cardenas, who spoke with the governor, said she ventured
back to San Felipe on Tuesday to get a glimpse of her modest home.
She found the refrigerator in a room other than the kitchen and a
foot of mud on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to start all over again,'' she said. ``There's no
way we can rebuild there. I don't think I would be comfortable.
What we need is higher ground.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
