<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3990 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TIM-COUCH-HNS &LR;      08-26 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TIM-COUCH-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
By BILL SULLIVAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   He plays at a school where a 5-6 season was cause for wild
celebration. This year, the going gets even tougher with a schedule
that calls for trips to Florida, LSU and Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Still, no one laughs when you mention Tim Couch and the Heisman
Trophy in the same breath. Certainly, the fellow at the center of
the budding hype seems comfortable enough with the notion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Realistically, I think we can win 'em all,'' the Kentucky
quarterback insists. ``There's no reason why we can't.''
</P>
<P>
   Some may take issue with that, since the Wildcats gave up points
even more quickly than Couch could put them on the board a year
ago. In yielding 363 points overall, Kentucky surrendered 30 or
more on five occasions. In the Southeastern Conference, making a
one-season leap from a sub-.500 finish to the top of the heap
probably is too much to ask, particularly with every game shaping
up as a shootout.
</P>
<P>
   Forgive the UK junior, however, if he has grown accustomed to
thinking big, in terms of both numbers and aspirations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal,'' Couch says without hesitation, ``is to win the SEC
and go to a New Year's Day bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   If the 'Cats don't make it, Couch still figures to make life
interesting. A year ago, as a true sophomore, he adapted to
first-year coach Hal Mumme's innovative offense quickly enough to
lead the nation in passing yardage (3,884), completion percentage
(66.4) and completions (363) and was second in touchdown passes
(37).
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky's 348 points were the second-most in school history.
The Wildcats topped 40 points three times for the first time since
1951.
</P>
<P>
   Folks around the SEC took notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right after he got here, he opened everyone's eyes,'' South
Carolina safety Arturo Freeman said. ``Coming out of high school,
he had all the hype in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he let anybody down.''
</P>
<P>
   That Couch has justified the hype speaks volumes about what he
already has accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   Out of high school in Hyden, Ky. _ an Appalachian town with a
population of 375 _ he was the Parade magazine national player of
the year and the USA Today offensive player of the year. His senior
season, Hyden was drawing crowds of 5,000 for home games as Couch
etched his name in the high school record book by finishing his
career with more than 12,000 yards passing and 133 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   When it was time to pick a college, he was leaning toward
Tennessee, where he would bide his time for a year or so behind
Peyton Manning. Instead, Kentucky coach Bill Curry convinced Couch
he could prosper in a modified option offense.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to stay at home gave hope to a UK program
accustomed to serving as little more than an autumn diversion prior
to the start of basketball season, but a rocky freshman year held
few happy moments for anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Curry inserted the freshman in a game against Florida and
instructed him to run the option. Over the second half of that 1996
season, Couch completed just 38 percent of his passes and pondered
transferring before Curry was replaced by Mumme, a fast gun from
Division II Valdosta State.
</P>
<P>
   The new coach and quarterback wasted little time making their
mark. In his first game in the new system, Couch completed 36 of 50
passes for 398 yards and four touchdowns. In the season finale,
against Tennessee, he passed for 476 yards. In between, he threw
for 355 yards and four touchdowns in a 40-34 win over Alabama, the
first UK win over the Tide in 75 years.
</P>
<P>
   This time out, Couch knows, ``we're not going to surprise
anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Still
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this offense is good enough that we'll do OK whether
people are ready or not,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Even with similar numbers, Couch (who finished ninth in the
Heisman Trophy balloting a year ago) knows that his chances for
college football's most coveted award hinge on the numbers he can
put on a scoreboard _ preferably more than appear on the other
side. Players from 5-6 teams generally drop from the view of
television cameras and voters before the final impressions are
made, no matter how eye-catching the individual stats might be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think for me to win, we have to win eight or nine games and
go to a major bowl,'' he says. ``That would be pretty miraculous,
but I think we're capable of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Either way, Mumme says he isn't worried about his man getting
caught up in the hoopla. He cites Couch's intense preseason work on
improving his deep throws as evidence that the quarterback has his
priorities in order.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would love to play football even if nobody showed up,''
Mumme said.
</P>
<P>
   People will show up. After watching Manning endure the Heisman
spotlight a year ago, though, Couch is aware that things don't
always turn out as planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Heisman is kind of weird,'' he says. ``I expected Peyton
Manning to win it last year _ I think everybody did _ so I don't
know where to place myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens, Couch is likely to place himself high on most
NFL draft boards by the time the season is done. He has taken out a
$3 million insurance policy as a hedge against injury but says a
defection to the pros after the season is not a sure thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that's going to be a decision at the end of the year,''
he said. ``But right now, I'm just enjoying being in college.''
</P>
<P>
   At Kentucky, the feeling is mutual.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
