<HEADER>
A3992 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PREVIEW-COWBOYS-S     08-26 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PREVIEW-COWBOYS-SCOUTING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS SCOUTING REPORT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
RUSHING OFFENSE 
Emmitt Smith, coming off a second consecutive subpar season, is the
starter. Former Pro Bowl back Chris Warren was signed from Seattle
in the off-season as the backup. The Smith-Warren twosome is a
definite upgrade from the Smith-Sherman Williams duo the past two
seasons and should improve the production of 102.3 yards rushing
per game the Cowboys averaged last season.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Smith, who rushed for 1,074 yards in 1997, appears to be healthy
after two injury-filled seasons. However, if Smith struggles, the
Cowboys can turn to Warren, the Seahawks' all-time leading rusher.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest difference is that the offensive line will do more
zone blocking than in the past. This will require Smith and Warren
to read blocks and to run more instinctively rather than run
straight for a hole.
</P>
<P>
   It will also require a better season from the Cowboys' massive
offensive line, which has dropped off considerably from its past
dominance. Guard Nate Newton has lost more than 70 pounds from last
season and should be better, as should center Clay Shiver, who will
have a second season under his belt. The Cowboys also signed
free-agent guard Everett McIver to round out what should be an
improved bunch with Pro Bowl tackles Erik Williams and Larry Allen.
 &QL; 
PASSING OFFENSE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, the Cowboys' pass offense will be more complex
than last season, when it finished 20th in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys quarterback Troy Aikman will operate out of the shotgun
on passing downs, and the alignment will feature four- and
five-receiver sets, screen plays and shovel passes.
</P>
<P>
   Substance, not creativity, will count. The Cowboys are looking
for a solid second receiver behind five-time Pro Bowl selection
Michael Irvin.
</P>
<P>
   However, a quality group of five receivers is necessary for the
Cowboys to succeed with this offense. In addition to second and
third receivers Billy Davis and Ernie Mills, Stepfret Williams has
proved to be a capable third-down receiver. Second-year receiver
Macey Brooks is unproven.
</P>
<P>
   This could also be a breakout season for David LaFleur. New
coach Chan Gailey plans to use the 6-foot-7 tight end in the
passing game.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the offensive line must do a better job of pass
protection than it did last season, when it allowed 39 sacks, the
most in a season since 1990.  &QL; 
RUSHING DEFENSE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rushing defense was the Cowboys' greatest weakness last season.
They ranked 24th in the league, giving up 124.6 yards per game.
</P>
<P>
   The run defense should be better with the return of Pro Bowl
tackle Leon Lett for a full season. Lett missed 13 games last
season because of a league-mandated, substance-abuse suspension.
With Lett playing the first 13 games of 1996, the Cowboys gave up
91.1 yards per game.
</P>
<P>
   Also helping the team improve against the run is a change in
scheme. The Cowboys have modified the traditional 4-3 defense to
feature a 3-4 look. Chad Hennings will line up as the nose tackle.
Lett will flip sides from time to time but will usually line up on
the weak side of the defense. Strong-side end Greg Ellis and
strong-side linebacker Randall Godfrey will usually line up on the
side with the tight end.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys aim to plug the middle and force the running backs
outside, where speedy linebackers Dexter Coakley and Godfrey can
make the plays.  &QL; 
PASSING DEFENSE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even without free safety Brock Marion, who signed a free-agent
contract with Miami, the secondary should be among the league's
best. Cornerbacks Deion Sanders and Kevin Smith and strong safety
Darren Woodson return from a unit that led the league in pass
defense (157.6 yards per game) last season. Omar Stoutmire, Kenny
Wheaton or George Teague will plug in at free safety.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is the pass rush. Aside from Lett, no player has
proved he can get to the quarterback consistently. Ellis, the top
draft pick in 1998, and Kavika Pittman must find a way to get the
job done if the Cowboys are to succeed. Not even Sanders can cover
a receiver forever.  &QL; 
SPECIAL TEAMS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' special teams are as good as any in the league.
Kicker Richie Cunningham earned All-Pro and NFC kicker-of-the-year
honors last season after making 34 of 37 field-goal attempts. He
was second in the league in scoring and led the league in field
goals. Punter Toby Gowin had a solid performance as a rookie last
season, averaging 41.8 yards per punt. However, he waned late in
the season and is looking for consistency.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders will handle punt returns again, and the Cowboys are
seeking a replacement for the reliable Herschel Walker on kickoff
returns. Davis and defensive back Kevin Mathis are leading
candidates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-26-98 2003EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
