u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-AD-COLUMN-510&AMP;A     08-26 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-AD-COLUMN-510&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING:   COMPANIES SEEK TO IDENTIFY PRODUCTS WITH MUSIC 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Minn., Ind.)  (rm) 
 By ANDREA ADELSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Television advertisers, today more than ever, are seeking to
make their commercials music to the ear _ building brand identity
with replays of classic rock tunes and with original scores they
have commissioned.
</P>
<P>
   Automakers seem especially fond of trying to grab attention with
``underscores,'' as they are called. Consider Toyota's ``Everyday
People'' ad, borrowing its hook from the Sly and the Family Stone
tune. Or General Motors' Chevrolet, scoring points about durability
with the Bob Seeger standard ``Like a Rock.''
</P>
<P>
   But carmakers are not alone in sounding like a classic rock
station. The Rolling Stones' hit ``Start Me Up'' provided the
perfect word play for Microsoft's Windows 95 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Also, a handful of traditional retailers have discovered the
brand-building potential of music. The Limited's Victoria's Secret,
Spiegel's Eddie Bauer, the Gap's Banana Republic and Starbucks are
extending their merchandising reach with name-brand CDs, an
unexpected outcome of selecting soundtracks to shape their stores'
environment. The compilations of previously produced work have
proved so popular with customers that Starbucks, for instance, has
issued 20 CDs since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   But some advertisers, sensing that the use of well-known rock
hits is growing tired, are hiring composers to create original
scores that are as important to brand building as imagery is.
Campaigns by Chrysler, BMW and Conseco Insurance are recent
examples.
</P>
<P>
   And Intel and Sears, Roebuck have adopted recognizable aural
icons to sign off each of their television commercials. ``It makes
them original and identifiable,'' said Anthony Marinelli, a Los
Angeles composer, who has rearranged music for Sears into a variety
of musical styles, including an urban rendition.
</P>
<P>
   Also in demand are John Trivers and Liz Myers, a husband-wife
composing team from Manhattan Beach, Calif., who got their start
writing tunes for Blue Oyster Cult. When unemployed, they turned to
commercial composing for Apple Computer. More recently, they
composed an Italian-style opera for Ford Motor Co., which began
using the spot in June but masked the aria with a voice-over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Advertisers recognize that the sound of music can trigger
recognition of their product,'' Myers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more memorable than a tag line,'' Trivers added.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent morning an agency creative director called the
couple's ocean-view recording studio, describing what was wanted
for a soap commercial. ``Not sugary, not sappy; celebratory,
spiritual, breezier, extremely fluid,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Myers, her eyes shifting between a television monitor and the
keys of a baby grand piano, improvised 15 bars or so. Within an
hour of the conference call, she picked three tracks from among
seven to get a full orchestral treatment, but left the decisive cut
to the soap maker's agency.
</P>
<P>
   Trivers, choosing from a dozen or more bass guitars, added a
filling riff. From a keyboard-synthesizer, his wife overlaid a
breezy tinkling of bells and symphonic strings. A sound engineer
minded the tracks.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Conseco got a similar Trivers-Myers treatment for its first
television spots, a $25 million campaign begun in February by
Fallon McElligott &UR;  &LR;  in Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very important for us to be distinctive; there's a lot
of sameness in the advertising of competitors,'' said James W.
Rosensteele, a spokesman for the insurance company, which is based
in Carmel, Ind. ``We were trying to break away in both sound and
image. We wanted to engage people intellectually and not rely on
pure emotional appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the warm and fuzzy images typically associated with
insurers, Conseco's vignettes show life's unexpected turns. The
music also takes unexpected turns.
</P>
<P>
   Paul L. Saylor, a partner at Bozell Worldwide, a unit of True
North Communications, produced six spots for Chrysler, relying on
one musical theme with slight variations. He said buying music
rights was effective when a campaign idea lent itself to the tune,
citing ``Like a Rock'' for Chevy trucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's great about creating new stuff is that it remains fresh
because it's not overplayed,'' he said, adding that longevity is
crucial for an auto campaign that lasts a year.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking an edgy style for BMW's campaign last year, Fallon
McElligott commissioned a pulsating technopop soundtrack, filmed
black and white footage from the driver's point of view and used
text titles instead of a voice-over.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted the music to cut through,'' said Bruce Bildsten, the
agency's group creative director.
</P>
<P>
   BMW's new spots, which are to start Sept. 14, extend the same
visual and musical theme. The arrangement came from Johannes
Hammers and Rico Conning, commercial composers in Santa Monica,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel like we have a musical signature,'' Bildsten said.
``Extending that signature is important to the brand's success.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
