<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-UTILITIES-ART-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UTILITY COMPANIES MUSTER CREWS TO HANDLE OUTAGES 
</HEADLINE>
  (With HURRICANE-BONNIE, HURRICANE-CALM, HURRICANE-SHELTER) 
(ART ADV: Photo of volunteer firefighter and downed power lines is
being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(rm) 
 By BETTIE FENNELL Wilmington (N.C.) Morning Star   c.1998 N.Y.
Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, N.C. _ Widespread power failures occurred Wednesday
as Hurricane Bonnie unleashed her fury on southeastern North
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Some workers were ready to begin repairing the damage as soon as
the winds subsided. Utility and telephone companies and electric
membership cooperatives had backup crews waiting to descend on
storm-damaged areas as soon as it was safe, company officials said.
</P>
<P>
   About midday Wednesday, 79,800 Carolina Power &AMP; Light Co.
customers were in the dark, said John Elliott, community-relations
manager with the company. Most of those were in Brunswick and New
Hanover counties, he said.
</P>
<P>
   About 2,600 contract workers were ready to respond as soon as
the company could complete an assessment of storm damage, Elliott
said.
</P>
<P>
   Another 600 were at staging areas in Raleigh and Florence, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   To get a head start, about 1,000 linemen and tree crews spent
Tuesday night in Raleigh, said Gayle Van Velsor, CP&AMP;L's eastern
region vice president. In addition to company employees, she said,
400 two-person crews from other utility companies were ready to
work.
</P>
<P>
   Rooms were reserved and agreements reached with local
restaurants and caterers to house and feed the workers, Van Velsor
said.
</P>
<P>
   The crews' first task is repairing transmission lines _
high-voltage lines that deliver electricity from power plants to
substations. Substations are next, followed by feeder lines and tap
lines, which deliver power to service lines into individual homes.
Service is restored first to hospitals, police departments,
emergency services and other public health and safety agencies.
Next on the list are lines that serve the largest number of people.
</P>
<P>
   Electric cooperatives in the region also prepared to get help
from other cooperatives in the state and outside North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Four County Electric Membership Corp. had 70 crews ready to make
repairs.
</P>
</TEXT>
