<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-BOAT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPERS A STUDY IN VERSATILITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEREMY BAGOTT  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Such is the life of a boat-camper.
</P>
<P>
   Kim and Cesar Diosdado of San Diego arrived at a Lake Mojave
campsite to find a herd of wild donkeys waiting.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were about eight or nine of them,'' Kim said, ``and they
wouldn't clear out and were heehawing at us aggressively. We
weren't sure if we should try to go ashore and shoo them away or
not. They seemed like they might be dangerous. We ended up staying
on the boat that night.''
</P>
<P>
   Boat-camping is about exploring the amphibious option, though
not exclusively.
</P>
<P>
   Boat-campers cut a wide swath, from those water lovers who
always spend the night aboard their boats to those who only sleep
on terra firma.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever one's preference, boat-camping cuts across all
established and sacred lines in the boating world. Skiff jockeys do
it. Rag sailors do it. Housebargers do it. Stinkpotters do it.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the following from the annals of boat-camping:
</P>
<P>
   __ Meriwether Lewis and William Clark, a pair of canoe bums with
good government jobs, boat-camped for three years along the
Missouri, Clearwater, Snake and Columbia rivers, opening vast new
territories, all without Day-Glo colors, Synchilla fabric or the
proper topographic maps.
</P>
<P>
   __ David Livingstone, a Scottish physician and hopeless
boat-camper, portaged across Africa's Kalahari Desert, discovering
the Zambezi River and Victoria Falls for the Western world. When
H.M. Stanley found him in 1871 (``Dr. Livingstone, I presume''),
the two were so happy they discovered Lake Tanganyika.
</P>
<P>
   __ Two fictional miscreants boat-camped on a large muddy river
and, thanks in part to a guy named Twain, spawned a national
literature.
</P>
<P>
   Local forms of boat-camping occur at California's offshore
islands, at the Colorado River, at area lakes and at harbors along
the coast. With boat-camping, the stress is on versatility.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent trip to the east side of Santa Cruz Island, the
Marcel and Van Koppen families of Summerland spent a weekend at one
of 35 campsites operated by the National Park Service.
</P>
<P>
   They hauled kayaks, wet suits, spear guns, drinking water and
camping gear onto a concessionaire's boat in Ventura Harbor and a
couple of hours later hauled the same gear the half-mile from the
Scorpion Beach landing to the island's campground.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hiked a lot and saw boars and horses,'' said 6-year-old
Annik Marcel. ``I liked seeing the wild horses the best, but we
only saw one ... and two sheep.''
</P>
<P>
   Her friend, Mckenna Van Koppen, 11, enjoyed snorkeling but
wasn't particularly fond of donning a wet suit. Like many camping
trips, there were other sore spots, but the families plan to make
the island outing a yearly event.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ran a little short of food,'' said Lori Marcel, Annik's
mom. ``We figured we would be spearing fish, which we did, but we
ended up getting only mudfish, which wasn't too good.''
</P>
<P>
   A boat-camping option involving kayaks and stamina is the Lower
Tomol Trail, a 36-mile paddle course from Point Mugu in Ventura
County to the Santa Monica Pier, with paddlers coming ashore at
eight authorized landing sites and two paddle campgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   At Lake Casitas in Western Ventura County recently, Chris and
``Stoney'' Stone of Lemon Grove, which is near San Diego, were
breaking camp _ stowing a tent and securing the trailered bass boat
that shared their campsite. The boat's fold-down bimini top allows
them to sleep aboard, which they sometimes do at Lake Havasu.
</P>
<P>
   The one shortcoming of sleeping on a bass boat, says Chris
Stone, is not having the room or privacy for a Porta Potti. When
nature calls, the anchor is weighed and a landing made.
</P>
<P>
   The Diosdados, friends of the Stones through the San Diego Bass
Couples club, echo the sentiment: You're roughing it, whether on
land or sea. But sleeping aboard often has allowed them to be first
to the fishing holes.
</P>
<P>
   On another Lake Mojave trip, the wind kicked up on the Diosdados
in the middle of the night, beaching their boat and collapsing
their tent.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we had were Nutter-Butter (cookies) and wet lunch meat,''
said Kim Diosdado, ``and we were worried we would never get out of
there.''
</P>
<P>
   It's best to count on the unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boat-camping is different for every boater,'' said Janet
Groene, who co-authored ``The ABCs of Boat Camping'' with her
husband, Gordon. ``We prefer sleeping aboard whenever we can. It's
bug-free, the wavelets rock you to sleep and you have the privacy
of being anchored out.''
</P>
<P>
   Janet Groene urges anyone interested in boat-camping not to wait
until they have the money for a large boat with all the amenities.
Start small, she advised, and make the most out of what you have. &QL; 
WHERE TO ANCHOR, BIVOUAC OR BOTH
</P>
<P>
   Along mainland coast:
</P>
<P>
   __ Goleta Beach: Santa Barbara County anchorage sheltered during
calm conditions. Landing at beach or pier. Inland park, with
barbecue, toilet, water and picnic area.
</P>
<P>
   __ Shark's Cove: Picnic anchorage, also known as Fernald Cove,
3.7 miles east of Santa Barbara Harbor. Some degree of shelter from
west swells. Beach landing.
</P>
<P>
   __ Carpinteria: Kelp buffers wind chop. Day anchorage only.
Beach landing. State campground. Call (800) 444-7275 for camping
reservations.
</P>
<P>
   __ Paradise Cove: Good overnight anchorage in Malibu. Keep below
high-water mark on private beaches ashore.
</P>
<P>
   __ Keller's Shelter: Bight formed by kelp and reefs off
Surfrider Beach in Malibu. Day anchorage.
</P>
<P>
   __ Lower Tomol Trail: Kayak paddling and camping route from
Ventura County's Mugu Rock to the Santa Monica Pier. Write to Santa
Monica Mountains Trails Council, P.O. Box 345, Agoura Hills, Calif.
91301, or call (818) 222-4531.
</P>
<P>
   Channel Islands anchorages with nearby campsites:
</P>
<P>
   __ Anacapa: Campground located a half-mile and 154 stairs from
landing.
</P>
<P>
   __ Eastern Santa Cruz: Campground a half-mile hike from Scorpion
Anchorage.
</P>
<P>
   __Santa Rosa: Campground 1{ miles from Becher's Bay anchorages.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; !arrow! &LR; San Miguel: &UR; !off! &LR;  Campground a mile trek uphill from
Cuyler Harbor anchorage.
</P>
<P>
   For above islands, call the National Park Service at (800)
365-2267 for camping reservations and landing information. For
public boat transportation, call (805) 642-7688 or (805) 963-3564.
Conditions are primitive. Must pack out trash. Fresh water
available only on Santa Rosa.
</P>
<P>
   __ Santa Catalina: Two Harbors area, administered by Two Harbors
Enterprises. Call (800) 322-3434 for camping, anchorage
information.
</P>
<P>
   Local lakes:
</P>
<P>
   Most that offer campgrounds provide campsites big enough for
trailered boats. Other lakes allow overnight anchoring. Call the
lake in question.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Dangerous conditions can occur at all anchorages,
especially during Santa Ana wind conditions, winter southeasters
and when gusts blow through inland canyons.
</P>
<P>
   Always consult a detailed coastal cruising guide and charts, and
monitor weather. &QL; 
MAKE THE JOURNEY EASIER
</P>
<P>
   Tips from the bosun's bag:
</P>
<P>
   __ A dunk bag made of netting attached to a cord can be filled
with dirty dishes and thrown overboard for washing at sea.
</P>
<P>
   __ Kitchen matches can be waterproofed by lighting a utility
candle and then dipping the tips in the melted wax. Let dry and,
when ready to use, carefully scrape off the wax and light.
</P>
<P>
   __ Lightly mist an unsliced loaf of bread with vinegar from a
spray bottle. Wrap it in two plastic bags, and you'll have doubled
its shelf life at sea.
</P>
<P>
   __ A telescoping boat hook can retrieve a halyard that has run
up the mast, pull you into to a mooring buoy or snag the handle on
Fido's personal flotation device if he falls overboard.
</P>
<P>
   __ Parents, don't forget the baby wipes and a spray bottle. A
7-year-old can be wiped down from head to toe with three wipes,
rinsed with three tablespoons of fresh water from a spray bottle
and towel-dried for a quickie shower.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
