</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-PRIVACY-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE ORDERS CREDIT BUREAU TO STOP SELLING CONSUMER RECORDS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JOEL BRINKLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal administrative law judge Wednesday
ordered one of the nation's largest credit bureaus to stop selling
detailed credit information on millions of consumers to advertisers
and marketers without the consumers' permission.
</P>
<P>
   The company said the judge was wrong and it would continue its
practice until an appeal was decided.
</P>
<P>
   The credit bureau, Trans Union Corp., maintains exhaustive
financial records on as many as 200 million Americans. The company
defended its right to sell the information, including details on
credit card accounts, mortgages, auto and student loans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our position is, this is not private and personal
information,'' said Oscar Marquis, the company's general counsel.
He added that Trans Union would appeal the ruling and continue its
marketing practices in the meantime.
</P>
<P>
   Trans Union is one of three national credit bureaus that gather
extensive credit and financial data on virtually every adult in the
nation, for use by banks, mortgage companies and credit-card
issuers that need the information when deciding whether to make a
loan or issue a credit card.
</P>
<P>
   The other two agencies, Equifax Credit Information Services
Inc., and Experian, a unit of Great Universal Stores PLC, agreed
several years ago not to sell the information.
</P>
<P>
   But Marquis said Trans Union stills sells much of the
information it gathers to catalog companies, newspaper and
magazine-subscription vendors among others _ including banks and
insurance companies, according to the Federal Trade Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Reidenberg, a privacy expert at Fordham University's law
school who served as a government witness in the case, said he
believed Trans Union continues to pursue the case ``because it's a
very profitable business for them, particularly when the other two
companies have gotten out of this business.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's ruling by Judge James Timony of the Federal Trade
Commission found that ``Trans Union offers data showing open
automobile loans, loan type,'' as well as ``expiration dates for
the lease or loan and the high credit amount of the most current
leases or loans.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling also said the company sells similar information on
first and second mortgages, home improvement loans and student
loans. In addition, Trans Union offers information on whether
individuals are mail-order buyers and whether they hold credit
cards from ``upscale stores,'' the ruling said. The company also
sells what it calls ``an income estimator,'' an estimate of an
individual's income based on credit data.
</P>
<P>
   Marquis said the data the company sells was not as detailed as
the judge asserted in his ruling. ``We sell lists of people who
have recently moved,'' he said, ``lists of people who have
mortgages and auto loans,'' but not details of those loans.
</P>
<P>
   A trade commission official said Trans Union might have changed
its marketing practices in that regard while the government's
lawsuit was pending.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The trade commission first brought charges against Trans Union
in 1992, saying the company's practices violated the Federal Fair
Credit Reporting Act. The law's preamble says its purpose is ``to
ensure that consumer reporting agencies exercise their grave
responsibility with fairness, impartiality and respect for the
consumers' right to privacy.''
</P>
<P>
   The law prohibits the release of credit data in most
circumstances, unless a consumer authorizes it _ explicitly by
signing a release, or implicitly by applying for a loan or credit.
</P>
<P>
   Under the law, credit bureaus are also entitled to sell
information to banks or other companies that lend money or issue
credit, as long as the companies do in fact offer credit to the
people on whom they have acquired information.
</P>
<P>
   A credit-card company, for example, will give Trans Union a
description of the sorts of people it wants to solicit. Trans Union
will then sell the company a list of names of people who meet the
criteria. At that point, under the law, the credit-card company is
required to make an offer of credit to the individuals.
</P>
<P>
   When the trade commission first sued Trans Union in 1992,
another administrative law judge issued a summary judgment against
the company. Trans Union appealed to the full Federal Trade
Commission, which upheld the ruling. But a federal appeals court
overturned the ruling, saying a summary judgment was unwarranted. A
trial was required, the court said.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Timony held that trial early this year and issued his
ruling Wednesday. Marquis said Trans Union would now appeal the
ruling to the full commission again _ though, given the history of
the case, Marquis acknowledged that the commission was not likely
to rule in Trans Union's favor.
</P>
<P>
   Marquis said Trans Union would appeal an unfavorable trade
commission decision to a U.S. Court of Appeals. Under federal law,
the company can take the appeal to any appeals court it chooses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
