<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-WORCESTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORCESTER COUNCILMAN WON'T WELCOME CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GEETA ANAND  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WORCESTER, Mass. _ While most Worcester residents eagerly
anticipated President Clinton's arrival Thursday, one city
councilor was doing the very opposite _ refusing an invitation to
welcome him at the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Worcester City Councilor Konstantine Lukes, a lawyer by
profession, a Democrat by party affiliation, and a contrarian by
nature, said she wanted to signal her disapproval of Clinton's
affair with Monica S. Lewinsky and his statements about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a citizen, sometimes you have to stand up and say, `The
emperor has no clothes,''' she said. ``I think Bill Clinton has
shamed himself, he's shamed his family, he's shamed the country and
he's shamed the presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   Lukes is no stranger to controversy. As a city councilor of nine
years, and a school committee member for eight years before that,
she has routinely questioned authority. Not even the ethics of her
colleagues has escaped her purview. Rarely, if ever, has she voted
for a city budget. She even rejected funding for the very popular
convention center.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Raymond Mariano, who is helping organize Clinton's visit,
sounded irritated with Lukes's stand, but said he was not
surprised. ``That's just like Konstantine Lukes,'' he said.
``That's her style.''
</P>
<P>
   Mariano and the majority of Worcester residents interviewed,
however, preferred to focus on the positive: the fact that a
sitting US president was about to swoop down on a city that too
often feels ignored.
</P>
<P>
   US Representative James McGovern's office reported giving out
all 1,700 tickets to Clinton's speech within three hours Wednesday.
Senators Edward M. Kennedy and John F. Kerry, as well as Attorney
General Scott Harshbarger, planned to be there, McGovern's
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Lukes's stance was drawing lots of attention Wednesday as
the media focused in on Worcester, where Clinton is said to be
trying to repair his image by turning attention to the issue of
school safety. By late afternoon Wednesday, Lukes had already been
interviewed by five newspapers and wire services.
</P>
<P>
   Lukes says she took her stand in a phone conversation Wednesday
morning with a White House official who informed her Clinton would
be arriving at Worcester Regional Airport at 9:15 a.m. and asked if
she would be present.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said I choose not to be there,'' she said. ``I somewhat
resent being used as a barometer and to boost his popularity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-26-98 2008EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980826.0434 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4003 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHELTER-COX     08-26 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHELTER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Strangers under a common roof
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel and Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, N.C. -- Lovis Ettore and her 20-year-old son, Brian,
packed up and moved here from northern Louisiana 3 1/2 weeks ago.
They knew nothing about hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought it was like a thunderstorm; it would hit the Outer
Banks and move on,'' Brian Ettore said.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, they learned the hard truth about a wobbly,
erratic hurricane named Bonnie. More than 300 miles across, Bonnie
took her sweet time about clearing out, first battering Wilmington
_ on the coast 150 miles south _ before jolting this area late in
the evening and in the wee hours.
</P>
<P>
   The two transplants were among 400 who spent Wednesday night at
Washington High School, one of three Red Cross shelters in Beaufort
County, tucked about 90 miles inland from either tip of the Outer
Banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I can make it once I get past the first one,'' said
Lovis Ettore, who nervously chatted for 10 minutes in a stuffy
hallway with no windows.
</P>
<P>
   ``So they say,'' Brian Ettore said.
</P>
<P>
   Lovis Ettore came to Washington, on the banks of the flood-prone
Pamlico River, as a pre-kindergarten teacher. She's been learning
from her class of 18. ``They told me more about hurricanes than I
knew,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Another adviser was Lovis Ettore's sister in New Orleans, who
has dealt with hurricanes for 30 years. One tip: Get to the shelter
early to get a good spot. The Ettores woke up at 4 a.m. Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the two main corridors, connected in a V-shape,
people laid out sheets, pillows, blankets, coolers and puzzles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We headed to Winn-Dixie,'' Ettore said. ``We started Sunday
after church, buying canned goods and water.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who didn't bring food today will eat cheese toast and
cereal for breakfast. Lunch will be chicken soup and a peanut
butter sandwich.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who don't bring food can't complain,'' said 17-year-old
Gene Woolard. Other than his change for the vending machine,
Woolard's most cherished supply: His six packs of Newport
cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   Woolard abandoned a doublewide trailer in a wooded area. ``Too
many winds,'' he said. ``It just wasn't safe out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Shelter director Alice Espenshade said the anxiety level inside
the modern brick high school didn't rise till late because light
rain and docile winds blew most of the day in advance of the
storm's real gusto. Taped to plate glass were warnings that had
been trans- lated into Spanish _ Evitar Ventana! _ Stay Away From
Windows During Storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're either fighting boredom or fighting terror,''
Espenshade said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 after Hurricanes Bertha and Fran, James and Tina Stokes
cleaned up a flooded kitchen. And, as James said, the storm
``ruint'' a 1990 Oldsmobile he had just bought. So there was no
doubt they'd spend Wednesday in a shelter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's odd being in here, but it's better than anywhere else,''
said James, 73. He found comfort in a meal of Vienna sausages and a
nap on the school's terra-cotta floor. ``I love to sleep on a hard
floor sometimes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To the south, in Morehead City, Jean West, 50, spent Tuesday
night at West Carteret High School with her two daughters,
9-year-old Sarah and 11-year-old Carol. She returned home Wednesday
morning to check on her dog, cat, parrot and husband, but she
returned to the shelter, with misgivings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not know whether to stay or go,'' said West, who
evacuated because of warnings that the rising Newport River could
flood her home.
</P>
<P>
   Some others pondered leaving. ``It's like a normal rainy day,''
Pauline Smith complained Wednesday morning. The 42-year-old
substitute school teacher and professional singer slept Tuesday
night on a blanket on the concrete floor of West Carteret High
School.
</P>
<P>
   Smith enlivened the atmosphere at the shelter Wednesday morning
with an impromptu concert in the West Carteret Fighting Patriots'
gymnasium. Some of the 200 people danced and clapped as she belted
out such oldies as ``The Twist and ``White Lightning.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, people returned to their temporary quarters in the
school's dim hallways. They passed the time lounging on cots and
air mattresses, tending to fussy babies, playing cards and board
games, or reading. Some tried to sleep amid strangers thrown
together by the Atlantic season's first hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are like one big family,'' said Mark Whittaker, a Newport,
N.C., pipe layer and Red Cross volunteer in charge of the shelter.
</P>
<P>
   To ease boredom, some people waded through water in the parking
lot to listen to radioes in their cars, some with tags from as far
away as New Jersey and Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Cross is serving three meals a day. Shortly before noon,
a crowd lined up for a lunch of bologna sandwiches, baked beans and
potato ships. Some people gathered in a breezeway outside, where
they smoked cigarettes and stared into the sheets of rain.
</P>
<P>
   ``A shelter is a dry, safe place,'' Red Cross official Cal
Jeffries said. ``But you are among strangers. The food is not as
good as you'd get at home. The sleeping accommodations are not the
master bedroom.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
