<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980826.0435 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4007 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PREVIEW-TEX     08-26 2576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PREVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PUZZLING SEASON, A RIVETING MYSTERY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a beautiful, crisp early winter evening, with the sun long
having disappeared over the hole in the roof. As day turns to
darkness, a chill sets in, but it's a good chill, bracing and
invigorating.
</P>
<P>
   This town can suck the life out of you in the summer, especially
the one we had this year. I can't remember what made me sweat more,
the heat or the thought of the next electricity bill.
</P>
<P>
   But that's just a bad memory now. This is the kind of day that
makes you glad to be alive. You can see your breath in front of
you, but that's a lot better than watching your sweat drip to the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, my big, shiny jacket with the star on the back will
keep me warm.
</P>
<P>
   The jacket? A gift from the man who became my boss a few months
back. A gift, like the sideline pass hanging from my belt loop.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, it's a great night for a football game, which is a good
thing because I'm about to watch one.
</P>
<P>
   I'm on the sideline at Texas Stadium for the Cowboys' biggest
game in a couple of years. What game is it? For now, let's just
call it an important game. I guess someone with a more soulful
disposition might even say this can be a day of redemption.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose it is at that, and I'm lucky enough to have one of the
best seats in the house.
</P>
<P>
   Did I say lucky? Let me take that back.
</P>
<P>
   You might envy my place on the sideline, my
up-close-and-personal view of Troy, Emmitt, Deion and the boys, but
you shouldn't. I earned my spot here. Oh boy, did I earn it.
</P>
<P>
   The name's Thomas O'Rourke, and I suppose I'm a walking cliche.
Irish cop turned detective. I was a good cop, a clean cop, an
honest cop. That was my downfall.
</P>
<P>
   A snitch passed on a rumor about a couple of rotten cops on the
take. I did some digging, but I guess I got a little too close.
Late one night, I was jumped and worked over pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next time, you won't get off so easy,'' was the last thing I
heard before I blacked out.
</P>
<P>
   When I came to, I took stock of the damage _ broken nose,
swollen eye, cracked rib _ and figured I wasn't cut out for any
hero stuff, so I quit the force. Now I'm a private eye.
</P>
<P>
   So how did I come to be standing here, watching the Cowboys warm
up before kickoff?
</P>
<P>
   It all began with a phone call nine or 10 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The voice at the other end sounded kind of muffled.
</P>
<P>
   ``My boss has a proposition for you,'' it said. ``Could be very
lucrative if you're the right man for the job, but it's very
hush-hush.''
</P>
<P>
   The hush-hush part's pretty standard for someone in my line of
work. The lucrative part, though, that was different.
</P>
<P>
   His boss wanted to meet me someplace quiet, where no one would
see us. He suggested Cowboys Cafe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nah,'' I said. ``I know some establishments where poking your
nose in someone's business can get you a one-way ticket to the
emergency room, so no one bothers.''
</P>
<P>
   The guy kind of gulped, but agreed. I gave him the name of a
place, The Tarnished Image, and we fixed a time for me to meet
``Mr. Jones.''
</P>
<P>
   The next day I got there early to check things out. It's not
that I didn't trust the guy, but in my line of business it pays to
take precautions.
</P>
<P>
   Everything looked like it should, so I settled in to wait.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, a couple of suits came through the door.
Big suits. Hired muscle, obviously. They proceeded to give me the
once over, eyeing me like some reject from the casting call for
``Homeless in Seattle''. So maybe I hadn't introduced my face to a
razor in a couple of days. Maybe my clothes hadn't seen an iron in
a couple days. Sue me.
</P>
<P>
   They looked around the rest of the room, at the biker types
shooting pool and the bleary-eyed lushes drinking whiskey for
breakfast. Compared to them, I look like something out of ``GQ''.
The suits figured I must be their man, so they sauntered over.
</P>
<P>
   ``You the man supposed to meet Mr. Jones?'' the more intelligent
of the Neanderthals finally grunted.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I'm the neighborhood welcome wagon,'' I retorted.
</P>
<P>
   I was tempted to drop more smart-aleck responses on him, but the
word ``lucrative'' came back to me so I clammed up.
</P>
<P>
   The muscle gestured toward the door, and a couple more suits
came in. Nice suits. Expensive suits. Italian, from the look of
them.
</P>
<P>
   One of the mugs above the silk ties looked familiar. I tried to
place the face. Then it came to me. I'm not much of a sports fan,
but I watch TV now and then.
</P>
<P>
   This ``Mr. Jones'' was the one who owned the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   He gave me that big, crooked smile of his and a firm handshake.
You'd figure a rich guy like him would be nervous looking at the
boys with the long hair, the tattoos and the big biceps who had
stopped shooting pool and started staring at him, but it didn't
phase him. Pretty tough guy, I figured.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Jones didn't say much. It's the other guy, the younger guy
who looked a little like him who did the talking.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad's got a job for you,'' he said in this slight twang I
figured comes from somewhere in Arkansas. ``We've got a lot of
money invested in our football team, see, and we want to protect
our investment. The last couple of years have, frankly, been a
major embarrassment. We've had a coach arrested for carrying a gun.
We've had players involved with drugs and `exotic' women. Our
public image has taken a beating. Instead of revered, we're
ridiculed. We can't afford another season like that. We hired a
God-fearing coach and drafted an upstanding young man, and that
helped. But it's not enough if we continue to have players hanging
out with the wrong people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell me something I don't know,'' I replied. ``I read the
papers. I know the jokes. America's Team to America's Most Wanted.
But let me give you some advice.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, normally I don't go dispensing advice to rich and powerful
men, but that's because I'm not around them much. I figure
everybody needs a little counsel now and then, and I'm not
reluctant to give it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, your image is a problem,'' I said. ``But drop in a few
more of those 6-10 seasons, and the front-running fans around here
won't care if you've got nothing but choirboys on your team.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't worry about that, son.'' It was the big man himself,
finally chiming in. ``We've still got some talent. We just need to
keep them healthy. And we need to keep them focused on football.
That's where you come in. Here's the deal. We want you to keep our
football players out of trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Like I said, I read the papers. I watch the TV now and then. I
knew that keeping 50-odd players on the straight and narrow
wouldn't be easy. What do I know about making large men with no
more sense than the good Lord gave a grasshopper toe the line? Not
my regular line of work.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not the brightest bulb in the chandelier, but I know my
limitations. I was about to tell Mr. Jones to take a hike and take
his crazy idea along with him.
</P>
<P>
   Then the younger guy mentioned a dollar figure that would pay
the bills for a couple of years. And then some. When I managed to
pick my jaw up off the table, I had a question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why me?'' I said. ``There's gotta be guys with more experience
in this kind of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We checked you out,'' he answered. ``You were a good cop
before you turned tail and ran. You're honest and you don't have a
big mouth, and that's important. This is strictly a low-profile
job. Very discreet. No one _ especially that nosy media _ must know
we're doing this. We can't afford the bad publicity if that
big-mouthed guy on Channel 8 finds out we've hired a professional
baby sitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Not what you'd call high praise, but I figured I could live with
it. The job might make me a professional baby sitter. But at least
I'd be a well-paid baby sitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Jones,'' I said, looking directly at the brains of the
outfit, ``you've got your man. If, that is, I get expenses to go
along with that nice figure your boy mentioned a few minutes ago.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't that I was being greedy. I just figured that tagging
along at some of the places I've heard these players frequent could
put a little dent in the pocketbook. Not that I planned on folding
any dollar bills in half, or anything.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Jones let out this big laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got yourself a deal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   We shook on it _ this is a man whose handshake is better than a
contract _ and walked out together. The suits climbed into some
big, fancy sedan. I got into my beat-up, 10-year-old Honda and
drove back to the office.
</P>
<P>
   I began to do some background work, and called up some old
friends in the force to find out what they knew about the
lifestyles of the rich and sometimes stupid. I separated the
naughty from the nice, and figured out a game plan. Yeah, I said
game plan. If I was going to baby-sit a football team, I thought it
might help to start thinking in sports cliches.
</P>
<P>
   By the time training camp started, I knew enough to know I was
in way over my head, but I dutifully pointed the car in the
direction of Wichita Falls.
</P>
<P>
   The first couple of weeks were quiet. Too quiet. It was like one
big lovefest. Call me a cynic, but I knew it was too good to last.
</P>
<P>
   I was right. I was outside the dorms one night, doing my usual
sweep to keep the local lovelies from sneaking inside and embarking
on an empty life as a football groupie, when I heard a commotion
inside.
</P>
<P>
   I dashed up the stairs, suspecting that the idyllic atmosphere
was about to be shattered. The sight of blood dripping out of an
open wound on the neck of a certain player confirmed my suspicions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boys,'' I said, ``didn't your mother tell you never to run
with scissors.''
</P>
<P>
   I was going for the light-hearted approach, hoping they would
start laughing and break it up. It wasn't quite that easy.
</P>
<P>
   How did I handle the situation? Let's just say scissors don't
stand a chance against a handgun the size of the one I pulled out.
Prima donna football players might not respect a two-bit private
eye, but these guys are familiar with handguns. They had to respect
the business end of my piece.
</P>
<P>
   ``Horseplay,'' it was called later. I had to laugh at that.
Yeah, kind of like the horses in ``Ben Hur'' pulling those chariots
with the spiked wheels.
</P>
<P>
   As for that reported payoff, well, let's just say it wasn't Mr.
Jones' money. At least it wasn't until I turned in the expense
account.
</P>
<P>
   Things calmed down for a while after that. There's something
about an offense that can't move the ball that tends to depress
high spirits.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys won the first game, beating the Cardinals at home.
There was some celebrating afterward, but nothing that got out of
hand.
</P>
<P>
   The celebration quickly died as the 'Boys lost five of the next
seven. And as the losses mounted, tempers got hot.
</P>
<P>
   The quarterback got mad at one of those large linemen after one
particularly boneheaded penalty, and they got into a shouting match
on the sideline. No big deal, happens all the time.
</P>
<P>
   But when they carried it into the locker room, I had to step in
and get it calmed down before they let the minicams in. It wouldn't
be good for the team's image to see the superstar flat on his back
after a roundhouse right.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, I took the roundhouse right. It hurt, but it broke the
tension.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, I figured that would be the worst of my problems.
This team was looking old. I didn't think they had the energy to go
out and get in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   That's when they started to win. They beat the hated Giants,
lost at Arizona the following week, then started a three-game
winning streak. It started with a victory against Seattle, another
against the Vikings in the Thanksgiving game, and the third in New
Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, as the victories returned so did the problems.
</P>
<P>
   There was a big party at a local establishment after the victory
against the Giants. It was supposed to be private, but a handful of
drunken Yankees tried to crash. They yelled a few choice words in
those annoying New Yawk accents, and a couple of linebacker types
wanted to take care of them.
</P>
<P>
   I had to step in, again for image control. Beat up a couple of
drunk New Yorkers in public, and it's all over talk radio the next
morning.
</P>
<P>
   The victory in New Orleans presented another problem. It was
pretty rowdy on the flight back, and a lot of the boys were in no
shape to drive home. I couldn't have anyone driving into a concrete
divider on the freeway, so I had to call a late-night limo company
and have them scramble the fleet. Cabs would have been cheaper, but
after a couple of victories these guys were thinking first class.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, there weren't enough limos to go around, and I
had to give a couple of guys a ride. I won't name names, but
suffice it to say one of them had caught a couple of touchdown
passes earlier that day.
</P>
<P>
   They weren't ready to go home, and wanted to visit a so-called
gentlemen's club where nothing good could happen. I never could
figure out why they're called that, by the way. I followed a couple
of players into a few of them to make sure they didn't get into
trouble, and gentlemen were in short supply.
</P>
<P>
   ``That wouldn't be the most brilliant thing you can do,'' I
said. ``Go home while you're ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   But no, they wanted to go party. It gave me a bad feeling to go
into one of those places. Maybe hanging around Deion and Emmitt had
rubbed off. But rather than create an unpleasant scene, I agreed.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good thing I did. While these two guys were doing their
best to circulate more dollars into the community, I saw one of my
old snitches.
</P>
<P>
   He tipped me off about a mob figure heavily involved in gambling
who was about to set up a star player in a scenario involving a
hotel room, exotic dancers and cocaine. The plan was to videotape
the sordid affair and use it as blackmail.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, I got wind of the plan this time and was able to
stop it before it started. No one ever had to find out.
</P>
<P>
   With no exotic dancers luring players astray, no one injured
from drunk-driving accidents and no one serving drug-related
suspensions, the Cowboys headed into the final three games with a
chance to do it on the field.
</P>
<P>
   They were 7-6 heading into the game at Kansas City on Dec. 13,
and things were looking pretty good. But that's when the season
almost unraveled. Troy Aikman was leveled by a blind-side hit early
in the game and sustained a concussion. Without him, the team had
no chance.
</P>
<P>
   Even that turned out OK, though. Troy was so groggy he became
convinced that the Barry Switzer regime was just a bad dream. It
took a couple of days before he realized that no, it really
happened.
</P>
<P>
   That served to lighten the mood of the team, and it create a
renewed determination in the quarterback. The Eagles the next week
had no chance.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys now were 8-7. Not exactly the stuff of Super Bowls,
but it beat the heck out of 6-10.
</P>
<P>
   At least they had a chance to reach the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   That's what they're doing today, on this early winter evening.
It's Dec. 27, and the Cowboys are hoping for a belated Christmas
present. Beat the Redskins, and a wild-card playoff berth awaits.
</P>
<P>
   Can they do it? I don't know enough about football to make a
prediction. But I do know this: At least they have a chance.
</P>
<P>
   Like I said, I earned this jacket and sideline pass.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
