<DOCNO> NYT19980826.0436 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4009 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-2TAKE     08-26 1245
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINANCIAL BARON'S MANEUVERS CONTRIBUTED TO RUSSIAN PREMIER'S
OUSTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: 2nd-take is scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET) 
(See also RUSSIA-ECON, RUSSIA-SOROS) 
(bl) 
 By MICHAEL GORDON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Tycoon Boris Berezovsky had been waiting months for
this moment of triumph, quietly plotting to depose Russia's earnest
prime minister, Sergei Kiriyenko.
</P>
<P>
   Last Saturday, Berezovsky went to the huge Soviet-era government
headquarters that looms over the Moscow River. There, in a private
meeting with Anatoly Chubais, one of the government's most
passionate reformers, Berezovsky told Chubais that the Kiriyenko
team was finished. President Boris Yeltsin, the tycoon pronounced,
would soon sign a decree sacking the entire cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Chubais did not resist. He sensed itwas a fait accompli and
later told Kremlin aides that Berezovsky's aim in telegraphing the
punch was to demonstrate clearly that the financial barons who
dominate Russia's industry and banks were making a move to reassert
their power.
</P>
<P>
   Kiriyenko had concluded that his days might be numbered.
Russia's wealthy businessmen, who had made a fortune buying and
selling companies once controlled by the government, had bridled at
his tough talk about about collecting back taxes and allowing
money-losing enterprises to go bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the day after Berezovsky delivered the news, Yeltsin
summoned the prime minister to his dacha outside of Moscow and told
him that he was planning some unspecified personnel changes.
</P>
<P>
   Confused, Kiriyenko left the meeting unsure when the axe might
fall. Within hours, though, the official notice came. Kiriyenko was
out. Viktor Chernomyrdin, the prime minister who was fired in the
last shake-up, was back in.
</P>
<P>
   Just four months ago Kiriyenko and his young team of reformers
set out to carry forward Russia's unfinished economic revolution.
The sudden demise of the Kiriyenko government was facilitated by
the nation's deepening financial crisis and Yeltsin's penchant to
turn loyal subordinates into scapegoats.
</P>
<P>
   But it also was a demonstration of the lingering power of
Berezovsky and other tycoons, who exploited the nation's financial
woes and Yeltsin's weakening position to install a more pliant
government.
</P>
<P>
   Now Berezovsky and his allies are playing role of go-between in
the formation of that government, helping to win support for
Chernomyrdin from the Communists who dominate the lower house of
Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The drama is still far from over. The burning issue now is not
whether the Communist-dominated Parliament will approve the stolid
Chernomyrdin _ that seems assured _ but whether a physically ailing
and politically besieged Yeltsin will completely cede power to
Chernomyrdin by eventually resigning and calling for early
elections.
</P>
<P>
   That would enable Chernomyrdin to take the reins as the nation's
acting chief executive and would give him an enormous advantage as
a candidate in a presidential contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very big danger for the country,'' said Boris
Nemtsov, one the Kiriyenko supporters who resigned his top Kremlin
post this week, in an interview. ``A resignation would be bad not
just because of the problem with the currency but because of the
history of Russia. If any czar decides to resign it could lead to a
real time of troubles.''
</P>
<P>
   Berezovsky had never made a secret of his opposition to
Kiriyenko or his own doctrine that the government should be a
servant of politically-connected businessmen.
</P>
<P>
   A former mathematician, Berezovsky made a fortune as a car
dealer and media mogul after the collapse of the Soviet Union. He
was one of Yeltsin's major financial backers during the 1996
presidential elections and claimed his reward by being named deputy
secretary of the national security council.
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately, he locked horns with Kremlin reformers like
Chubais, who once presided over Russia's troubled privatization
program.
</P>
<P>
   Nemtsov, the former governor of Nizhny Novgorod region who
Yeltsin once touted as possible successor, prevailed on the
president last year to fire Berezovsky from his security post,
complaining that the businessman was mixing his business and
government interests.
</P>
<P>
   Berezovsky, however, remained close to the corridors of power.
He maintained connections with Valentin Yumashev, Yeltsin's chief
of staff, and Tatyana Dyachenko, Yeltsin's daughter and political
adviser. And he used his control over the ORT television channel
and his newspaper, Nezavisimaya Gazeta, to inveigh against his
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   In March, when Yeltsin anointed Kiriyenko _ a former energy
minister, banker and Nemtsov ally _ as prime minister, Berezovsky
inveighed against the choice.
</P>
<P>
   At first, it appeared that Berezovsky would be the loser. Aided
by Chubais, the Kiriyenko team negotiated a $17 billion bailout
package with the International Monetary Fund. Western officials
praised the new prime minister's dedication and acumen.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone was so enthusiastic. Some of Russia's financial
community was alarmed by Kiriyenko's talk about putting the
nation's house in order by refusing to bail out politically-well
connected banks and enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the IMF bailout, investors continued to flee the
world's emerging markets. The Parliament resisted Kiriyenko's
program, much of which was tied to the additional loans from the
fund. Worse, the ruble began to falter and Russian banks were
having trouble paying back their borrowings.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the government, after insisting that it would never
devalue the currency, reversed itself and allowed the currency to
decline in value. It also took some steps to protect the nation's
oligarchy, including a 90-day moratorium on the repayment of the
banks' foreign debt.
</P>
<P>
   But Russia financial crisis also gave the prime minister's
opponents the opening they had been waiting for. ``Kiriyenko
prepared a packet of measures to that would lead to the bankruptcy
of ineffective banks or financial industrial groups,'' Nemtsov
said. ``When the oligarchs sensed this they decided to change the
government.''
</P>
<P>
   As last week came to an end, there was talk that Kiriyenko might
be ousted, but it was far from clear who might take his place.
</P>
<P>
   In the halls of the Kremlin, several successors were mentioned:
Moscow's pugnacious major, Yuri Luzhkov; Yegor Stroyev, the head of
the upper house of Parliament; and Chernomyrdin, the prime minister
Yeltsin unceremoniously ousted in March.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin had his liabilities. During his first term as prime
minister, the former head Gazprom, Russia's huge natural gas
monopoly, he had gone along with Russia's stutter-step journey
toward a capitalist democracy. But he had also presided over the
insider deals and half measures that led to Russia's economic
quagmire.
</P>
<P>
   Politically, however, he had good connections across the
spectrum. As a former Gazprom chief he was an unofficial member of
the financial oligarchy. He also enjoyed close ties with the
Communist leadership in the Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   During the months after he was cast out of the Kremlin, he also
met with Berezovsky, including a reported meeting this month in
southern France.
</P>
<P>
   Berezovsky glories in self-promotion and his enemies also
sometimes exaggerate his role. But while Berezovsky was not the
only baron supporting Chernomyrdin, he was an active and important
adviser.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
