<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4012 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RENO-FUNDRAISE-BOS &LR;      08-26 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENO-FUNDRAISE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENO MAY BE READY TO PROBE GORE FUND-RAISING EFFORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Creating a new layer of political problems for Vice
President Al Gore, Attorney General Janet Reno reportedly decided
Wednesday that there are enough questions about Gore's fund-raising
practices to warrant a 90-day review, after which she will decide
whether to seek an independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   The decision comes 10 days after President Clinton said he had
an inappropriate relationship with former White House intern Monica
S. Lewinsky, an admission that already has threatened to tar Gore
and harm his presidential campaign prospects in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials Wednesday declined to confirm
Reno's decision, which was first reported by CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal law, Reno can seek a 90-day review period if she
determines an allegation is specific enough to warrant
investigation. But such reviews do not mean she will ask a
three-judge panel to appoint an independent counsel. Reno is
looking at the narrow issue of whether Gore solicited unregulated
``soft money'' in campaign telephone calls from the White House,
but independent counsels often seek to expand their probes.
</P>
<P>
   Reno last year decided after a 90-day review that there was not
enough evidence to warrant an independent counsel to look at the
fund-raising practices of both Clinton and Gore. That decision
prompted an onslaught of Republican criticism, especially when word
leaked that a top Justice Department official and FBI Director
Louis Freeh wanted a counsel to be appointed.
</P>
<P>
   Reno is currently locked in a dispute with some House
Republicans over her refusal to release a July 16 memo from Charles
G. LaBella, former chief of the Justice Department's campaign
finance investigation, &UR;  &LR; that reportedly said an independent counsel
should be named. LaBella reportedly said a special prosecutor would
be in a better position to investigate whether fund-raising abuses
occurred in the Clinton administration. Freeh also had written his
memo with a similar recommendation last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Dan Burton of Indiana, chairman of the House
Government Reform and Oversight Committee, who has demanded the
memo for months, said Wednesday in a statement that Reno's action
didn't go far enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Attorney General's action _ or inaction _ today has done
nothing to allay our concerns that something is seriously wrong at
the Justice Department,'' Burton said. ``Earlier this month, the
Attorney General promised a decision in three weeks, now she says
it will take three more months.'' Burton said that reinforces the
need to obtain the memos by Freeh and LaBella he has subpoenaed.
</P>
<P>
   Burton's committee has voted to recommend that the full House
find Reno in contempt for not turning over the two memos. Earlier
this week, Burton rejected an offer from the Justice Department to
brief members of his committee.
</P>
<P>
   Reno said on Aug. 20 that she will be criticized no matter what
she does. ``If people want to call me chicken or wimpy, they can do
that,'' Reno said. ``I'll get fussed at if I go one way and cussed
if I go the other. I'm never going to be Miss Popularity in this
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore aides have said privately that they expected the 90-day
review because Reno has been under so much pressure from
Republicans to appoint an independent counsel. But the Gore aides
said they believe Reno will not wind up asking for a counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Last December, after a similar 90-day review, Reno decided
against seeking an independent counsel to investigate Gore. Reno
said the vice president's telephone calls from the White House in
1995 and 1996 were not in violation in a law prohibiting
fund-raising on federal property. In explaining her decision, Reno
said that law applied only to federally regulated contributions,
known as ``hard money,'' while Gore was soliciting unregulated
contributions, or ``soft money.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno reopened the question when the Justice Department recently
obtained a memo that appears to suggest Gore knew he was also
soliciting hard money from the White House. In the Nov. 21, 1995,
memo, first reported last week by The New York Times, David
Strauss, a Gore aide, wrote the fund-raising would be ``65 percent
soft, 35 percent hard.'' The memo also quoted Gore as saying
``count me in'' on fund-raising calls.
</P>
<P>
   Gore aides have said the memo is vague and does not show that
the vice president violated any laws. Gore reportedly was
interviewed by Justice officials about the memo earlier this month.
Gore has said that if his phone calls resulted in raising hard
money, he was unaware of it.
</P>
<P>
   Gore aides could not be reached for comment last night.
</P>
<P>
   Reno also has been reviewing whether an independent counsel
should examine the fund-raising activities of former Clinton deputy
chief of staff Harold Ickes. No decision was announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The probe centers on 45 telephone calls made by Gore in 1995 and
1996. That is just a small element of the fund-raising practices
that have come under investigation in the last year and a half.
</P>
<P>
   As required by the independent counsel law, Reno transmitted her
decision Wednesday to a three-judge court that picks counsels, but
the court did not immediately authorize her to publicly disclose
it, officials told the Associated Press. The department said it
would have no announcement on the case Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, a Republican-led Senate committee investigated an
array of campaign finance allegations, including suggestions that
Democrats illegally raised money from foreign interests. The Senate
Governmental Affairs Committee concluded that Clinton orchestrated
an effort to evade campaign finance laws by raising soft money for
the Democratic National Committee, which then aired millions of
dollars worth of ads that were de facto reelection commercials for
the Clinton-Gore team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-26-98 2021EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
