<DOCNO> NYT19980826.0444 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4020 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-26 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NAME OF THE GAME IS: POSTSEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No Red Sox player will admit when he stopped worrying about
catching the Yankees, but let's put it this way: if he's a
school-age parent, his kid was still dreaming about summer
vacation.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have spent the last 2, 2 1/2 months in some sort of
parallel baseball universe, from which they have only recently
returned with four consecutive losses entering Wednesday night's
game with the Angels. In Ye Olden Days, being stuck behind such a
ridiculous juggernaut would have guaranteed a boring August and
September. There would be nothing to speak of but individual goals
(Nomar's total bases, Pedro's Ks, Mo's homers, Johnny Val's
doubles, etc.). The Yankees would win the division, and there
wouldn't be a damn thing anyone could do about it except to say,
``See you next spring.''
</P>
<P>
   Not now. Not when the Red Sox go into a game like Wednesday's
against the A's 10 up in the loss column.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the late nineties. Welcome to the world of the OPR,
the Other Pennant Race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm kind of old-fashioned,'' says Mo Vaughn. ``When they put
the wild card in, I thought it was a reward for mediocrity. But now
I look at it that we've got the second-best record in the American
League and we should get something for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Which, if they keep on doing what they're doing, they will. They
will be the American League's wild card playoff entry.
</P>
<P>
   If Mo's old-fashioned, then I'm positively medieval. If I could
have one summer to live over, it would be 1967, and in this locale
I'm hardly alone. Now that, you young'uns, was a capital P,
Pennant, capital R, Race. It was a daily carnival of baseball
thrills, culminating in the extraordinary events of Oct. 1, when
Jim Lonborg willed his way past the Minnesota Twins in game 162.
</P>
<P>
   If it wasn't the best pennant race of all, it was, as Dizzy Dean
would say, among 'em. The old baseball pennant races were the best
races in all of American sport, but the winner-take-all days are
gone and no wailing by a baseball purist like me can bring them
back. It's a wild card world. I can either accept it or turn to
street luging.
</P>
<P>
   Technically speaking, there is no pennant race in the American
League East. The Yankees will enter the post-season through Door
No. 1. This does not concern the Boston Red Sox because they will
feel no shame whatsoever by waltzing into the postseason through
Door No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of what sport you're in,'' reminds Bret Saberhagen,
``all you're trying to do is get into the postseason.''
</P>
<P>
   Let the Yankees play for regular season history. The Red Sox
have another issue. They have the OPR. All they know is that if it
looks like a pennant race, feels like a pennant race and smells
like a pennant race, then it surely is a pennant race.
</P>
<P>
   They watch the scoreboard each night to see what Baltimore,
Texas and Anaheim are doing. ``You definitely keep an eye on the
other teams,'' says John Valentin. ``The way Baltimore was playing,
how could you not?''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees? They're of no direct interest, except for one
thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can root for them,'' points out Saberhagen. ``They can
help you out.''
</P>
<P>
   If anything, the Yankees are a source of amusement. First of
all, it's hard to imagine what it's like to play for them. But the
big thing is speculating about what it will be like to be a Yankee
when the playoffs start.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be great pressure on them,'' says Vaughn. ``How can
you have a team like that and then go out and lose in the playoffs?
There will be pressure on them from the owner, the fans, the media
_ everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I can see it,'' echoes Valentin. ``You have a season like
that, and then it's `How can you not win the World Series?' I mean,
if we were winning every game, I'd expect us to win it all, too.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You never want to be a favorite like that,'' agrees Dennis
Eckersley, who has some experience in these matters. ``The best
team doesn't always win, anyway, let alone in a five-game series.
All it takes is one hot starting pitcher. Both times we (Oakland)
lost in the Series one starter knocked our (body part) off. (Orel)
Hershiser did it in '88 and (Jose) Rijo did it in '90.''
</P>
<P>
   You will be hearing a great deal in the coming weeks about the
notion that ``anything can happen in a short season,'' and the fact
is it happens to be true. Few players are students of history, so
let this be a source of inspiration to all the wild card hopefuls:
the two ballclubs with the best season records in each league were
beaten in the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   The 1906 Chicago Cubs went 116-36 and were defeated by the
Chicago White Sox. Forty-eight years later the Cleveland Indians
went 111-43 to establish the all-time American League record. They
were swept by the New York Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Eckersley arched his eyebrows when apprised of this information,
but he is all too well aware of just what kind of trouble can lurk
in a baseball series.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, no one needs as much to get by in the post-season as
it does over the Big 162. ``What you need,'' maintains Dan
Duquette, ``are the vital ingredients _ pitching and defense _ and
I think we have them.''
</P>
<P>
   On this subject, at least, Mo Vaughn finds himself in agreement
with the somber general manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think pitching and defense are the big things when you get
into the post-season,'' contends Vaughn. ``Offensively, it's always
going to be someone you don't think about. But pitching and defense
are always going to get you through the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Pitching and desire,'' adds Valentin. ``I got that from
(Roger) Clemens. ``He can go out there without his best stuff, but
still find a way to win with desire, knowledge and heart. I believe
that plays a factor. I know nothing's more important than talent,
but you need more than just talent to win.''
</P>
<P>
   It has escaped no one's attention that the reigning champion of
the known baseball world entered the 1997 postseason through Door
No. 2. As far as know, the winners' checks didn't bounce and the
rings were authentic.
</P>
<P>
   ``With our pitching staff we've got as good a chance as anyone
in baseball,'' says Vaughn. ``Getting to the postseason is what you
play for. When we win this (i.e. the wild card), it will be just
like winning the division in '95.
</P>
<P>
   Door 1. Door 2, it doesn't matter. They lead to the same room.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-26-98 2026EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
