<HEADER>
A4026 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PREVIEW-NFCEAST-T     08-26 2587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PREVIEW-NFCEAST-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFC EAST CAPSULES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
NFC EAST CAPSULES 
 
DALLAS COWBOYS 
1997: 6-10, 3-5 in NFC East 
Coach (record): Chan Gailey (0-0) 
Stadium: Texas Stadium (65,675) 
Ticket information: (972) 579-5000 
Pieces in place 
QB Troy Aikman (19 passing TDs), RB Emmitt Smith (1,074 rushing
yards), WR Michael Irvin (1,180 receiving yards), T Larry Allen, DT
Leon Lett, CB Deion Sanders (NFL-record 14 career TDs on returns),
CB Kevin Smith, SS Darren Woodson. 
Key newcomers 
Coach Chan Gailey, DE Greg Ellis, OT Flozell Adams, G Everett
McIver, RB Chris Warren, WR Ernie Mills. 
Key losses 
FS Brock Marion, T George Hegamin. 
Missing piece 
The Cowboys have not had a consistent wide receiver to play
alongside Irvin since Alvin Harper. Kevin Williams, in Buffalo
after a year in Arizona, was never more than a utility receiver.
And former Pro Bowl player Anthony Miller was never more than fast
last season. The candidates for the No. 2 spot this year are Billy
Davis, second-year man Macey Brooks and free-agent veteran Mills.
Because Gailey plans to use a five-receiver formation on some
plays, all will be counted on for production in certain situations.
Still, the coaching staff is hoping one emerges as another target
for Aikman. 
Biggest test 
The NFL community will know very early in the season whether last
season's dismal record was a mirage or a sign of things to come.
The Cowboys open the season at home against the up-and-coming
Arizona Cardinals, then go on the road to play the defending Super
Bowl champion Denver Broncos on Sept. 13 and the defending NFC East
champion New York Giants on Sept. 21 on Monday Night Football. 
Watch out for 
How this club responds to Gailey. Right now, the former offensive
coordinator is being called a breath of fresh air by veteran
Cowboys who had grown weary of Barry Switzer's act. But how long
will that last? Will the team have confidence in him after the
first blowout loss or lengthy losing streak? How will Gailey react
under the pressure of being the coach of the most visible team in
pro sports? 
Milestones 
Emmitt Smith needs 12 rushing touchdowns to surpass retired running
back Marcus Allen (123) as the all-time career leader. 
Overview 
The Cowboys have the best quarterback and best defense in the
division. They also have more future Hall of Famers on the roster
than anyone else. Yes, they are getting old. But with an influx of
young talent via the draft, and a new coach, Jerry Jones' money men
have one more run of greatness left. 
Prediction: 10-6 
 
STARTING LINEUP 
Offense 
QB Troy Aikman 
RB Emmitt Smith 
FB Daryl Johnston 
WR Michael Irvin 
WR Billy Davis 
TE David LaFleur 
LT Larry Allen 
LG Nate Newton 
C Clay Shiver 
RG Everett McIver 
RT Erik Williams 
 
Defense 
RDE Greg Ellis 
RDT Leon Lett 
LDT Chad Hennings 
LDE Kavika Pittman 
MLB Fred Strickland 
OLB Dexter Coakley 
OLB Randall Godfrey 
CB Deion Sanders 
CB Kevin Smith 
FS Omar Stoutmire 
SS Darren Woodson 
 
Specialists 
KR Kevin Mathis 
PR Deion Sanders 
K Richie Cunningham 
P Toby Gowin 
 
NEW YORK GIANTS 
 
1997: 10-5-1, 7-0-1 in NFC East 
Coach (record): Jim Fassel (10-5-1) 
Stadium: Giants Stadium (78,148) 
Ticket information: (201) 935-8222 
Pieces in place 
DE Michael Strahan (14 sacks), LB Jessie Armstead (134 tackles), CB
Phillippi Sparks (5 interceptions), DT Robert Harris (10 sacks), DT
Keith Hamilton (8 sacks), QB Danny Kanell (11 passing touchdowns). 
Key newcomers 
S Shaun Williams, WR Joe Jurevicius, WR Brian Alford. 
Key loss 
RB Rodney Hampton. 
Missing piece 
Offense. Offense. Offense. The Giants need plenty of it. Their
defense will keep them in most games, but the Giants desperately
need offensive playmakers to successfully defend their NFC East
title. Oddly, the Giants' first pick in the draft went to defense.
So, Fassel and company will hope that a running-back-by-committee
run game and Kanell, in his third year, will improve by leaps and
bounds to help a unit that ranked 27th in total yards last season.
Kanell will need help from last year's top draftee, speedy wide
receiver Ike Hilliard, who was limited to two receptions in 1997
because of a neck injury. The club's leading receiver in 1997 was
Chris Calloway (58 receptions). Calloway is more of a possession
receiver. 
Biggest test 
Four of the Giants' six games from Nov. 15 to Dec. 20 are against
Green Bay, San Francisco, Denver and Kansas City. If you are
wondering whether the Giants' 1997 worst-to-first season was a
fluke, you'll know by the morning of Dec. 21. 
Watch out for 
Who is behind Kanell. The Giants will probably go into the season
with halfback Tiki Barber and fullback Charles Way as the starters.
Way is a solid blocker and was the club's leading ground gainer and
second-leading receiver. If Barber struggles to give the Giants
consistent yards, don't be surprised to see journeyman Gary Brown
getting plenty of action. He gained 945 yards rushing as a
part-time player with San Diego last year. Tyrone Wheatley also
adds to the logjam at running back. 
Milestones 
The Giants, who became the first NFC East team to go through the
division schedule undefeated in 1997, have not lost to a division
team since a 24-0 loss at Philadelphia on Dec. 1, 1996. 
Overview 
The Giants can't possibly go through the division undefeated again.
And with the nondivision schedule much stronger than last season,
New York's hold on the division title could be short-lived. The
saving grace: Eight of the Giants' first nine opponents missed the
playoffs in 1997. So perhaps a fast start could give the club the
momentum it needs to pull out an upset against a San Francisco or a
Green Bay. But that's highly unlikely. 
Prediction: 9-7 
 
