WASHINGTON REDSKINS 
1997: 8-7-1, 4-3-1 in NFC East 
Coach (record): Norv Turner (26-37-1) 
Stadium: Jack Kent Cooke Stadium (78,600) 
Ticket information: (301) 276-6050 
Pieces in place 
RB Terry Allen (724 yards), RB Stephen Davis (567 yards), CB
Darrell Green (second among active players in career interceptions
with 44), CB Cris Dishman (4 interceptions in '97), WR Michael
Westbrook (16.4 yards per catch), QB Gus Frerotte (17 passing
touchdowns), LB Ken Harvey (9.5 sacks), KR Brian Mitchell (2,081
total yards). 
Key newcomers 
DT Dana Stubblefield, DT Dan Wilkinson, TE Stephen Alexander, RB
Skip Hicks. 
Key losses 
OT Darryl Ashmore, DE Chris Mims. 
Missing piece 
The Redskins have lots of talent at the skill positions but will
need an overachieving effort from the offensive line to be a major
force in the division. The talent on the offensive line is average
at best and incompetent most of the time. The club desperately
needs a talented left tackle, but failed to obtain one through free
agency or the draft. That means Joe Patton, who is a better left
guard, will fill in to protect Frerotte's blind spot. Left guard
Tre Johnson is coming off two shoulder surgeries. The right side of
the line is manned by guys named Shar Pourdanesh and Brad Badger.
Yikes. 
Biggest test 
We should know how the season will turn out for the Redskins before
the end of September. They open at the New York Giants, play host
to San Francisco, travel to up-and-coming Seattle and close the
month at home against Denver. 
Watch out for 
Westbrook and Frerotte. These guys are the keys to getting Turner
into the playoffs for the first time as a head coach. Both are
immensely talented. But both made boneheaded mistakes last season
that eventually kept this team out of the playoffs. If Westbrook
can control his anger and Frerotte his urge to throw dumb passes at
the worst possible times, the Redskins have a good chance of
winning the NFC East. 
Milestones 
Green, a 16-year veteran, has 44 career interceptions, second among
active players behind Atlanta's Eugene Robinson (49). 
Overview 
The Redskins should have one of the best defenses in the league and
an offense that will excite from time to time. But six of their
first eight opponents reached the playoffs in 1997. After a slow
start, look for the Redskins to rally in the latter half of 1998,
only to fall short of postseason play for the sixth consecutive
season. But watch out in 1999. 
Prediction: 9-7 
 
