ARIZONA CARDINALS 
1997: 4-12, 2-6 in NFC East 
Coach (record): Vince Tobin (11-21) 
Stadium: Sun Devil Stadium (73,273) 
Ticket information: (800) 999-1402 
Pieces in place 
WR Rob Moore (1,584 receiving yards), WR Frank Sanders (13.6 yards
per catch), FB Larry Centers (54 receptions), DT Eric Swann (7.5
sacks), DT Mark Smith (6 sacks), DE Simeon Rice (5 sacks), CB
Aeneas Williams (6 interceptions). 
Key newcomers 
WR/KR Eric Metcalf, DE Andre Wadsworth, S Corey Chavous, RB Mario
Bates, RB Adrian Murrell. 
Key loss 
LB Eric Hill. 
Missing piece 
The offensive line. The Cardinals' best anchor, left tackle Lomas
Brown, is 35. The Cardinals added massive tackle Anthony Clement
(6-8, 348) in the draft, and he could be starting soon on the right
side. But not much else was done to improve a unit that allowed a
league-high 78 sacks in 1997. That's bad news for a club that is
resting its hopes for its first nonstrike playoff berth since 1975
on second-year quarterback Jake Plummer. 
Biggest test 
At the Cowboys for the season opener Sept. 6. The Cardinals ended a
13-game losing streak to the Cowboys with a victory in Tempe,
Ariz., last season. But they have not won at Texas Stadium since
1989. One reason for the Cardinals' sorry records this decade has
been slow starts. A victory against the Cowboys _ even if they are
a few All-Pros short of their glory days _ would give the young
Cardinals the emotional firepower to make a playoff run. A loss and
the same old doubts probably start to creep in. 
Watch out for 
Plummer's production. General manager Bob Ferguson has done a
wonderful job of stocking talent in the desert the past few years.
The addition of Metcalf helps special teams. The addition of
Murrell and Bates helps the running game, and the addition of
Wadsworth helps an already solid defense line. Now it is up to
Plummer, the second-year quarterback from Arizona State, to
produce. Yes, he has a shaky offensive line. But if he can stay
away from making the stupid plays (15 interceptions in 1997) and
let his playmakers win games for him, the Cardinals have as good a
shot as anyone to win what has become one of the weaker divisions
in the NFL. 
Milestones 
The Cardinals have not reached the playoffs in a nonstrike season
since they won the division in 1975. No club has gone longer
without a nonstrike-season playoff berth, and only the New York
Jets (1969) have gone longer without a division title. 
Overview 
The Cardinals lost six games in 1997 by a total of 20 points,
including three in overtime. This came despite having a rookie
quarterback, a defense that finished 27th in total yards allowed,
and a running game that ranked 30th. They added loads of talent via
trade and the draft. And in a division that saw one club make the
playoffs last season, the additions may be enough for a playoff
berth in the Valley of the Sun. 
Prediction: 7-9 
 
