<SLUG> BC-HURRICAN-STRIKES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BONNIE LASHES CAROLINAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, N.C. _ Hurricane Bonnie howled into the Carolinas
Wednesday, slashing coastal communities and summer playlands, and
sending more than a half-million residents and vacationers
scurrying for safety.
</P>
<P>
   Roofs vanished, roads flooded, and trees snapped after the storm
struck land near Cape Fear, just south of Wilmington. Bonnie
battered the waterfront city and surrounding region throughout the
day and was expected to thunder northeast toward the state's
fragile Outer Banks.
</P>
<P>
   With top winds of 115 m.p.h., Bonnie threatened to wreak as much
as havoc as Hurricane Fran, which killed 24 people and caused more
than $5 billion damage when it raged across Cape Fear into the
Carolinas in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The National Hurricane Service said Bonnie, which was virtually
stalled over the Wilmington area Wednsday night, will continue to
produce powerful rain and hurricane-force winds for up to 36 hours.
The hurricane, stretching 450 miles wide, could continue pounding
North Carolina through Friday, metereologists said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had terrific damage,'' said North Carolina emergency
management spokesman Ben Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Public safety officials said they hoped to limit Bonnie's
devastation with preventative measures they learned from Fran. But
as the storm inched up the coast, conditions remained too perilous
in many areas for authorities to fully assess the damage.
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service has forecast that Bonnie could pass
just southeast of New England Friday night or Saturday. Heavy-surf
advisories remained in effect through Friday, with the threat of
downpours across Rhode Island and southeastern Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Amid pelting rain, seas surging higher than houses, and severed
power lines sizzling in the streets, many seaside communities in
North Carolina resembled battered ghost towns Wednesday. They had
emptied in a mass exodus, as more than 330,000 people heeded recent
orders to evacuate the North Carolina coast, from Sunset Beach,
near the border with South Carolina, north to Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   An additional 200,000 people were evacuated from coastal
counties in South Carolina, although they escaped the brunt of the
storm.
</P>
<P>
   Not so in North Carolina, where fears of looting, including an
attempted break-in at a grocery store in Wilmington, prompted
authorities to impose curfews as early as 8 p.m. in several
southern coastal counties. The National Guard was called in to
Wilmington, where the swollen Cape Fear River flooded much of the
city's historic district.
</P>
<P>
   The closest brush with tragedy occurred at Brunswick Community
Hospital, 25 miles south of Wilmington, where a large section of
the roof ripped off, forcing officials to move 31 patients to other
facilities during the storm's full force. No injuries were
reported, although five of the patients were in critical condition
before the roof disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Yet other signs of a dangerous storm abounded: toppled trees,
bent billboards, shredded flags, broken traffic lights dangling
feebly above branch-littered intersections.
</P>
<P>
   All commerce and public transportation stopped. A cable tower
buckled and fell in Sea Breeze, just north of Cape Fear. Scores of
windows shatttered, including dozens at a high school in New
Hanover County, near Wilmington. And a steeple broke off a church
in the Wilmington suburb of Leland.
</P>
<P>
   For many mainland residents who brushed off official requests to
voluntarily evacuate, few amenities remained. Widespread phone
outages were reported. And nearly 200,000 electric customers lost
power, although the number was less than the 380,000 who lost
electricity in North Carolina during Hurricane Fran.
</P>
<P>
   The extent of damage to the region's most vulnerable spots
remained a mystery, as police continued to enforce mandatory
evacuation orders, particularly on barrier islands that were rocked
by Fran in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some residents said they expected the wreckage to rival
the destruction caused by Fran and Hurricane Hugo, which killed 26
people and caused $7 billion of damage in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``The damages are very similar to what we had with Hugo and
Fran,'' said Al Leonard, the town manager in Tabor City, west of
Wilmington. ``It's pretty much the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Others disagreed. ``At this point, it's certainly no Fran,''
said Allen O'Neal, manager of New Hanover County.
</P>
<P>
   As frustrating as the storm was for tens of thousands of
tourists, many of whom abandoned pricey vacation rentals in such
pleasure spots as Nags Head and Surf City, Bonnie was a potentially
costlier menace for many year-round residents, particularly
tourist-related businesses and farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Just west of Cape Fear, Southport postmaster Marvin Watson
regretted not getting off Oak Island before the only bridge closed
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you one thing _ it's scary out there,'' he said as
the wind pushed sheets of water across the island. ``If I had my
choice right now, I'd be sitting over in Wilmington somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   On Hatteras Island, most homes and businesses were closed and
only a few people were on the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Jodi Austin, who is accustomed to storms after living on
Hatteras for seven years, defied the evacuation order. She said she
planned to ``lay some candles out, get a good board game and sit
around with my friends.''
</P>
<P>
   West Carteret High School in Morehead City was converted into a
shelter, with 200 people lodged there. Many brought sleeping bags,
cots, blankets, radios, books and lanterns. Some of the refugees
had gathered before.
</P>
<P>
   ``We met each other during a storm years ago,'' said Iris
Salter, who was chatting with Edwin and Gertha Lewis of Harker's
Island.
</P>
<P>
   One hurricane tradition on the North Carolina coast survived
intact, officials said. Residents reported that someone broke into
the three-story Old Baldy Lighthouse near Cape Fear and rode out
the storm there. Smith Island is six miles off the coast near
Wilmington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every storm we have somebody breaks into that lighthouse and
then gets a T-shirt that says `I survived (Bonnie) in the
lighthouse,' '' said Brunswick County spokesman Huey Marshall.
``That's probably the safest place on the island to ride out the
storm, and the view is fantastic.''
</P>
<P>
   While Bonnie approached the coast, Hurricane Danielle was
strengthening over the Atlantic _ 645 miles east of the Leeward
Islands _ and moving toward the northwest at 21 mph with winds of
105 mph that were expected to strengthen. Forecasters said it was
too early to tell whether Danielle would threaten the US mainland.
</P>
</TEXT>
