<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, Aug. 30,
1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (`e' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FILMS-APES-NYT (Undated) _ Adapted from the novel by Pierre
Boulle and written by Rod Serling and Michael Wilson, who had been
blacklisted in 1951 for supposed communist connections, ``Planet of
the Apes'' was relentlessly promoted from the time it was just a
concept by the producer Arthur Jacobs. Hollywood, however, found
the idea of costumed apes uncomfortably close to Saturday-morning
cartoons. Only Richard Zanuck, the head of 20th Century Fox, was
willing to make the film. By Peter M. Nichols.
</P>
<P>
   FILMS-LYMAN-NYT (Los Angeles) _ In the movie ``Why Do Fools Fall
in Love,'' which opened on August 28, starring Halle Berry, Vivica
Fox, Lela Rochon and Laranz Tate, courtroom testimony takes up only
a few minutes. But the fact that a legal battle really happened is
the reason the story of Frankie Lymon finally made it to the screen
at all. By Jamie Diamond.
</P>
<P>
   FILMS-MERRY-WAR-NYT (Undated) _ ``Gordon halted outside a great,
garish picture-house. He hated the pictures, of course, seldom went
there even when he could afford it. Why encourage the art that is
destined to replace literature?'' So wrote George Orwell in his
1936 novel, ``Keep the Aspidistra Flying,'' but it is not a
vignette that makes it into Robert Bierman's ``The Merry War,'' the
new film adapted from the book. That comically high-minded rebuke
hangs over the movie, though, and over every attempt to bring the
work of this gifted, peculiar writer to the screen. By Ty Burr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INDIAN-DANCE-NYT (Becket, Mass.) _ It sounded like a perfect
match. The American Indian Dance Theater was looking for a dramatic
way to reconcile its heritage with the modern world. Laura Dean, a
white choreographer with a penchant for spinning movement and an
eye for ritualism, was hoping to deconstruct some powwow dances,
which share a striking affinity with many of her own compositions.
Last spring, after raising $26,000 from the National Endowment for
the Arts and two private foundations, the Jacob's Pillow Dance
Festival commissioned the postmodern dervish and the folkloric
troupe to make a new dance together. But the dance barely made it
to the stage, and a close look at how it evolved offers a
cautionary tale about leaping into creative partnerships. By
Christopher Reardon. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART-ANTIQUES-ARCHITECTURE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ANTIQUES-MAINE (Bar Harbor) _ In 1922, Dr. Robert Abbe, a New
York surgeon who summered in this coastal town, was struck by
inspiration. He had just bought a small collection of ancient stone
implements that had been found in the region, filling him with
wonder about the hands that had held them in prehistoric times. And
rather than leave the artifacts on a shelf in his house, he wanted
to create a place where others could see them. So he set about
enlisting the support of other local collectors, and on Aug. 14,
1928, the Robert Abbe Museum of Stone Age Antiquities opened in a
quiet glen near here at the edge of Acadia National Park. By Paula
Deitz.
</P>
<P>
   NY-ARCHITECTURE-COLUMBUS-NYT (New York) _ With the selection of
a design for the old Coliseum site on New York's Columbus Circle
and plans afoot to spiff up the circle's core, this may be the time
to appreciate the power this place has had to stir the imagination
over the years. By Herbert Muschamp.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MUSIC  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHAMBER-MUSIC-NYT (Undated) _ It's odd how quickly the world
forgets about chamber players. For a time they may occupy something
close to center stage in the public imagination; then, almost
without warning, they disappear from the scene. The process may
seem natural where retirement or death is concerned. Still, it is
hard to see why the performers should vanish from the communal
memory. By David Mermelstein.
</P>
<P>
   STRING-QUARTETS-NYT (Undated) _ For most music lovers, the
historical map of the string quartet is drawn on well-traveled
roads. We tend to trace and retrace the great highways named
Mozart, Beethoven, Brahms and Bartok and ignore the byways. Many
are the roads not taken, especially on the landscape of our own
time. But the Kronos Quartet would have us draw the world
differently, in greater detail and from a more modern perspective.
By Lawrence B. Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   POP-MUSIC-ART-NYT (Los Angeles) _ A former Yalie chases the rock
'n' roll dream. By Neil Strauss. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL (`t' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PRACTICAL-TRAVELER (Undated) _ Cooking schools from Albuquerque,
N.M., to Bangkok, Thailand. By Florence Fabricant.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Travel news and notes: Tours for fans
of Burns and ``Mrs. Brown.''
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Questions and answers on travel: On and
around Loch Ness _ Nessie exhibits and a guided tour. By Suzanne
MacNeille.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-DRINKS (Undated) _ A snifter worth a thousand words: the
drink that says it all. By William Grimes.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-CANADA (Undated) _ Of loonies, toonies and lower Canadian
prices. By Anthony DePalma.
</P>
