</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-BONNIE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUGE AND POWERFUL HURRICANE SLOWLY COMES ASHORE IN NORTH CAROLINA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic map
tracking hurricane along East Coast is being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(See also: HURRICANE-WILMINGTON-NYTR, HURRICANE-CALM-NYTR,
HURRICANE-SHELTER-NYTR, HURRICANE-UTILITIES-NYTR) 
(bl) 
 By KEVIN SACK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, N.C. _ A vast and plodding Hurricane Bonnie rumbled
ashore near the mouth of the Cape Fear River on Wednesday
afternoon, bringing whipping winds and horizontal squalls through a
region that is still recovering, both physically and emotionally,
from the trauma of back-to-back hurricanes in the summer of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   As of early Wednesday evening, there were no reports of deaths
or serious injuries in the region from the category 3 hurricane,
which carried maximum sustained winds of 115 miles per hour. But
state officials and weather forecasters worried that the worst
could still be ahead as the slow-moving storm continues its
northerly movement up the North Carolina coast Wednesday night and
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   A particular concern for residents of the Outer Banks, a narrow
and ecologically fragile chain of barrier islands, was that Bonnie
would move straight up Pamlico Sound nd create surging floodwaters
that could cut new inlets and submerge the islands' single highway.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters predicted that damage assessments of the Outer
Banks, and of much of the rest of the North Carolina coast, would
not be possible until well into Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   As Bonnie finally made land after two days of anxious
anticipation, residents here seemed fatalistic about the weather
currents and rotten luck that have brought three hurricanes to
their quaint, well-mannered town in only two years. In 1996, a mild
hurricane named Bertha struck in July, only to be followed two
months later by a devastating category 3 storm named Fran. That
hurricane resulted in 24 deaths in North Carolina, and 34 total,
and caused an estimated $6 billion in property damage, including
hundreds of downed trees in Wilmington.
</P>
<P>
   Fran's impact was symbolized by the destruction of the
197-foot-tall steeple at the First Baptist Church, a local landmark
that is still being rebuilt.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first thought when we heard about this one was that it
couldn't happen again, that you just can't have three in a row,''
said C. Bruce Williams III, a spokesman for New Hanover County's
emergency management team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it's just one of those things.'' Gary Green, a
37-year-old cook who was waiting out the storm at a shelter at MCS
Noble Middle School here, said he liked the area enough to put up
with the enduring threat of wicked weather. ``Where are you going
to run on this planet?'' he asked. ``If you go to the Midwest you
put up with tornadoes. You go to the west coast and you put up with
earthquakes. You choose your poison as best you can.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service in Miami said that Bonnie's speed
had decreased gradually throughout the day to 8 miles per hour from
nearly double that speed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bonnie will be persisting over eastern North Carolina for at
least another day, creating a serious flood threat from rain,'' the
forecasters said in their 5 p.m. advisory. ``Rainfall totals of 6
to 12 inches are possible. Totals could be much larger, possibly in
excess of 15 or 20 inches if the forward speed of Bonnie decreases
further.''
</P>
<P>
   More than half a million residents and tourists evacuated
coastal areas of North Carolina and South Carolina on Tuesday and
Wednesday morning, filling makeshift emergency shelters in schools
and government buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Curfews were declared across the region and most bridges from
the mainland to barrier islands were blocked by police cars. An
estimated 97,500 households were without electricity along North
Carolina's southern coast.
</P>
<P>
   In Supply, about 30 miles south of Wilmington, Bonnie's winds
destroyed a portion of the roof at Brunswick Hospital, forcing
officials to move 34 patients to another unit. Here in Wilmington,
a gust blew out a 40-foot section of windows at New Hanover High
School.
</P>
<P>
   On Bald Head Island, near the point of the hurricane's landfall,
47 people were stranded after missing the last ferry Tuesday night
and some took shelter in the island's lighthouse after breaking its
lock. ``It certainly would be better than even the more modern
houses,'' said Andy James, a spokesman for the state's emergency
management team. ``It's been there a long time and weathered a lot
of storms.''
</P>
<P>
   The lighthouse squatters were not the only ones trapped by the
storm. On North Topsail Beach on Wednesday afternoon, two young men
stranded on the island ran through the blinding rain when they saw
a sheriff's car stopped on a road. Mitch Fowler, of Burlington, and
Dennis Poythress of Sneads Ferry, had spent the day trying to
repair Fowler's car.
</P>
<P>
   But after getting the car going, it became buried in the sand
and was eventually flooded by rising sea water, Poythress said. ''I
didn't care if it was the pope,'' said a soaking Poythress as he
crawled into the sheriff's car. ``I was ready to get off the
island. I'm about to starve. I want some dry clothes and a dry
cigarette.''
</P>
<P>
   Here in Wilmington, the storm splintered a number of the oak
trees that give this city of 60,000 its elegant grace. Power lines
all across town drooped limply from poles and debris-littered
streets became obstacle courses for the few drivers braving the
roads. The almost universal outages forced the daily newspaper
here, the Morning Star, to send its eight-page Thursday edition to
Fayetteville to be printed.
</P>
<P>
   Although local officials warned that it was early to make broad
assessments, the damage to trees and property here seemed far
milder than that caused two years ago by Hurricane Fran.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had some air views of damage and some scouting around by
people,'' David Paynter, a spokesman here for the New Hanover
County Emergency Management Agency, said late Wednesday afternoon.
``It seems the hurricane has not created that much damage, but
we've got at least seven more hours before the main part of the
storm leaves this area.''
</P>
<P>
   While thousands of people along the coast fled the hurricane, at
least one family drove here deliberately to witness it. Doug Shales
and his 21-year-old daughter, Sarah, detoured to Wilmington while
returning from Tampa, Fla., to their home in Columbia, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've wanted to experience a hurricane for a long time,''
Shales said. ``We just came on the spur of the moment. It's very
special for us to happen to land somewhere where you're going to be
in the eye.''
</P>
<P>
   The Shaleses spent the day watching the hurricane through the
picture windows in their room at a Holiday Inn. Shales noted that
his family spent time in 1993 in an historic blizzard atop Beech
Mountain. ``We just kind of really enjoy weather extremes,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But many people here remained exasperated that they had been
struck by another hurricane before finishing repairs from the last
one. Kathy Rackley, a 39-year-old housewife from Wilmington, said
she still has trees in her yard that were felled by Fran.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of depressing,'' she said. ``You want to see
everything done before something else comes along and blows it all
down.'' Jack Goodhue, who fled a barrier island to take shelter in
a Wilmington motel, summed up the mood of many. ``What's happened
here?'' he asked. ``Have they pinned a target on Wilmington?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
