</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-WILMINGTON-ART-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
80,000 POWERLESS AS BONNIE BATTERS SOUTHEASTERN NORTH CAROLINA 
</HEADLINE>
  (With HURRICANE-BONNIE, HURRICANE-CALM, HURRICANE-SHELTER,
HURRICANE-UTILITIES) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(rm) 
 By THE WILMINGTON (N.C.) MORNING STAR   c.1998 N.Y. Times News
Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, N.C. _ Hurricane Bonnie's turn to the north didn't
come in time for southeastern North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The storm's worst winds battered Brunswick and New Hanover
counties Wednesday afternoon, flooding beach areas, cutting off
power to nearly 80,000 people and causing other scattered reports
of damage.
</P>
<P>
   At midafternoon, Brunswick County's emergency management center
in Bolivia dispatched vans to the Brunswick Hospital at Supply,
where at least part of the roof had been blown off.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-five patients were in the hospital when the sheet metal
roof over one ward was blown off, said Brunswick County spokesman
Huey Marshall. The five most-critical patients, including a mother
and her premature child, were taken to Grand Strand Medical Center
in Myrtle Beach. Officials were moving the other patients to other
hospitals in the area Wednesday night and were preparing to close
the hospital until after the storm.
</P>
<P>
   At South Brunswick Middle School in Boiling Spring Lakes, about
60 people had to be moved to the nearby high school about 3 p.m.
after a roof leak flooded the middle school.
</P>
<P>
   Between 2:30 and 3 p.m., the eye of the storm crossed Bald Head
Island, much farther south than forecasters had predicted Tuesday.
Meteorologists said a trough of air north-northwest of the storm
kept it from turning north and put it on a direct course for
Brunswick and New Hanover counties.
</P>
<P>
   At 3 p.m., Hurricane Bonnie was centered about 40 miles south of
Wilmington. The storm was moving north about 10 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane-force winds extended up to 115 miles from the center,
battering much of the region. Gusts of 90 to 100 mph were recorded
across parts of New Hanover, Brunswick and Pender counties by
around 11:30 a.m., the National Weather Service reported.
</P>
<P>
   The storm center was expected to curve to the north-northeast
Wednesday night, raking across much of the North Carolina coast.
Bonnie's slow speed and immensity _ nearly 400 miles across _
threatened to keep winds battering the region for 12 to 18 hours
and potentially keep the storm in the region through two high-tide
cycles, increasing the possibility of devastating storm surges.
Surges were running about 9 to 11 feet above normal tide levels
Wednesday, the National Weather Service reported.
</P>
<P>
   The storm was expected to maintain its strength over land,
eventually reaching Currituck Sound about 8 a.m. Thursday before
heading north-northeast.
</P>
<P>
   The storm's wide eye _ about 15 miles _ had Scott Garner
worried. The Brunswick County emergency management assistant was
afraid people would be lured outside during the lull.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people want to evacuate or they need help, we'll try to get
help to them,'' he said. ``But this is only a lull.''
</P>
<P>
   Some 300 National Guard troops, the 30th Brigade from Raleigh,
were sent to Wilmington to protect lives and property.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency management officials were still hunkered down in safe
buildings Wednesday afternoon and had only scattered reports of
damage. A resident leaving Southport called the town's emergency
center to say a church steeple was down, but no one ventured out to
confirm the report.
</P>
<P>
   A fire broke out at the General Wood plant in Leland, which
makes utility poles. But the Leland Fire Department had to abandon
the scene because of high winds. No damage estimates were
available.
</P>
<P>
   Wilmington firefighters were responding to calls of downed
electric lines, fallen limbs, sparking transformers or alarm
systems set off by power surges within city limits. But New Hanover
County Emergency Medical Service crews stopped sending ambulances
to the south end of the county as early as 4 a.m. Wednesday because
heavy winds were rocking trucks on the road. At Fifth Avenue and
Market Street, the steeple at First Baptist Church, which is being
rebuilt after Hurricane Fran toppled it in 1996, was holding late
Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Although the tide peaked at Wrightsville Beach well before the
center of the storm hit, portions of the town were under water, in
some places, as much as 3 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The water was washing over the sandbags at Shell Island Resort,
but it did not appear to be moving the bags, John Nesbitt, public
works director for Wrightsville Beach, said.
</P>
<P>
   The water was washing over the dunes at some locations, he said,
but it didn't appear to be washing sand away as badly as Fran did
at a similar point in the storm, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not had the wind with this storm that we had in
Fran,'' he said. ``The waves are not anywhere near the size they
were in Fran.''
</P>
<P>
   In Brunswick County, winds estimated at 110 mph at 2 p.m.
Wednesday snapped pine trees, downed power lines, stripped shingles
from roofs and separated a Calabash house, possibly a mobile home,
from its foundation.
</P>
<P>
   All Brunswick County's islands had been evacuated the night
before the storm. Sunset Beach officials resorted Wednesday
afternoon to binoculars to survey the island for damage. No major
damage was reported as of 1 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   About 40 people remained on Bald Head Island, said Fire Chief
Kent Brown. Some ventured out Wednesday afternoon when the eye of
the storm passed over the island, and they reported light damage,
Chief Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   In Pender County, Emergency Management Director Carson Smith
said the Topsail Beach police chief told him there were loose
shingles and small objects blowing around on Topsail Island, but no
major damage.
</P>
<P>
   Power was out in the western end of the county, but eastern
Pender still had power in the early afternoon. The only damage
emergency officials had heard about was flooding and downed trees.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency workers went to Topsail Island during a low in the
storm. They saw flooding and breaches in protective dunes, but no
homes destroyed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
