<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4041 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-STARR-350&AMP;ADD     08-26 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-350&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON URGED TO PRODUCE WRITTEN REPORT TO COUNTER STARR'S 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JAMES BENNET   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Some of President Clinton's political advisers have
recommended that his lawyers write an account of his legal troubles
to counter an expected report to Congress from Independent
Prosecutor Kenneth Starr, administration officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Starr is preparing a summary of his seven-month investigation of
Clinton's relationship with former White House intern Monica
Lewinsky. The report, which would serve as the basis for a likely
congressional inquiry, may also deal with other aspects of Starr's
four-year investigation, which originally focused on the Clintons'
Whitewater real estate investment.
</P>
<P>
   A report on the president's behalf would probably cover the
range of matters that Starr has investigated, administration
officials said. White House aides maintain that the prosecutors are
biased against Clinton and will not produce a balanced account of
the facts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a growing sense that the report will not be either
complete or objective,'' an administration official said. ``There
is some desire to offer a counter to the report.''
</P>
<P>
   The official said that a recommendation for such an alternative
report was made Tuesday to the White House counsel's office. But
David Kendall, the president's private lawyer and chief legal
strategist, is away on vacation, and no decision has been made.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has acknowledged that he had an intimate relationship
with Ms. Lewinsky and misled the public about it, but he has denied
breaking any laws.
</P>
<P>
   The White House may also choose to disclose some sensitive
information in advance of the report, officials said. The
president's aides have frequently used that approach in the past to
dull the impact of any disclosures by investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Another administration official called the proposal for an
alternative report one of ``many ideas that span a large range that
are being talked about internally here.'' Some of the ideas have
been passed on to Clinton, he said, but ``I don't think the
president has signaled back how he wants to proceed.'' Clinton is
on vacation with his family on Martha's Vineyard.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Some of the president's advisers have been urging him to make a
fuller apology to the public than he offered in his public remarks
about Ms. Lewinsky in a four-minute speech Aug. 17.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, when Clinton interrupts his vacation to speak about
crime and school violence in Worcester, Mass., he probably will
make a brief reference to his efforts to repair relations within
his family. But he is not expected to make detailed remarks about
his relationship with Ms. Lewinsky, his aides said.
</P>
<P>
   They are expecting him to be asked about the former intern at a
joint news conference to be held in Moscow next week with Russian
President Boris Yeltsin. One administration official said Clinton
wanted to say ``something short and simple'' about his troubles
Thursday ``to avoid having to deal with it for the first time
publicly when you're standing in the Kremlin.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats reacted with consternation Wednesday to comments
by House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt and others that were
critical of Clinton and receptive to the possibility of impeachment
hearings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democrats are fueling the problem and making it worse by
this ridiculous hand-wringing,'' said Bill Knapp, a Democratic
consultant who has advised Clinton in the past. ``They're pouring
kerosene on it, and lighting a match, and the Republicans are just
laughing.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Gephardt called Clinton's actions ``reprehensible'' and
said he would reserve judgment on whether the president should be
impeached. He said that he would review Starr's report before
deciding.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, in an interview with Reuters, Gephardt seemed to
retreat a bit. ``I'm as disappointed as anyone about what's
happened, but that's history,'' the news agency quoted him as
saying. ``It's time to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   For its part, the White House responded mildly to Gephardt's
comments on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I understand it, what Congressman Gephardt said was that
the Congress has very serious constitutional responsibilities with
respect to this issue, that it should be approached completely
without partisanship, and that members should not prejudge the
facts,'' said White House spokesman Barry Toiv on Martha's
Vineyard. ``And there's nothing there that I can see to disagree
with.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Gephardt's use of the word ``reprehensible,'' Toiv
said, ``Well, I think that's a judgment that he has made.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
