<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4043 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PREVIEW-QB-TEX     08-26 1945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PREVIEW-QB-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUEPRINT FOR THE QB OF THE FUTURE CAN BORROW FROM THE PAST,
PRESENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By ANDY FRIEDLANDER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forty years ago, Johnny Unitas was the standard by which all
quarterbacks were judged.
</P>
<P>
   Young, smart and able to gun the ball through coverage with
sheer arm strength, Unitas was the prototype for an NFL passer. And
in 1958, he used those skills to lead the Baltimore Colts to the
league championship by beating the New York Giants, 23-17, in
overtime in what became known as The Greatest Game Ever Played.
</P>
<P>
   But take the 25-year-old Unitas out of 1958 and drop him into an
NFL offense in 1998 and he becomes a relic. At 6-foot-1, 190
pounds, he is dwarfed by the likes of Troy Aikman, Drew Bledsoe,
Kerry Collins and Ryan Leaf. He lacks mobility, making him a
sitting duck for swift, powerful pass rushers.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 model quarterback is gifted in ways Unitas couldn't
have imagined, beginning with the size and strength of Leaf and
Bledsoe, the quick feet of Mark Brunell and the spectacular running
ability of Kordell Stewart. He combines the powerful arm of Brett
Favre with the deft touch of Aikman, not to mention Steve Young's
uncanny ability to digest a War and Peace-size playbook and
Manning's born-to-be-a-quarterback football acumen.
</P>
<P>
   There is, of course, no set formula for NFL success. With his
knowledge of the game, his arm and his toughness, Unitas would
likely be a terrific quarterback today despite his physical
limitations. Indeed, the list of current great or potentially great
passers who are conspicuously missing one or more of the key
elements includes Miami's Dan Marino (painfully slow), Young (too
small), Arizona up-and-comer Jake Plummer (small and lacks a
top-of-the-line arm) and Tampa Bay's Trent Dilfer, a 1998 Pro Bowl
selection who has struggled with the mental aspects of the
position.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, I don't think what you're looking for has changed a
lot,'' Washington Redskins general manager Charley Casserly said.
``I mean, everyone wants a mobile quarterback, but there really
aren't that many of them out there. You want an athletic guy with a
strong arm who can make all the throws. You need a certain level of
intelligence and instincts and the ability to make good, quick
decisions. It's no different now.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, the position has evolved noticeably in the past 40
years. Quarterbacks can make more plays in more ways while facing
increasingly more athletic and complex defenses and sorting through
more sophisticated audibles and reads.
</P>
<P>
   In piecing together the quarterback of the future, the first
clues could come this season with the debuts of Indianapolis'
Manning and San Diego's Leaf, the first and second picks in the '98
draft, both of whom are being touted as perhaps the next great one.
In Denver, the Broncos say third-round choice Brian Griese can be a
star and are preparing him to replace John Elway.
</P>
<P>
   If they reach their potential, these three rookies could make an
impact similar to the one made by the famed draft class of 1983,
led by Elway, Marino and Jim Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly has retired, Elway has said this is his last season, and
Marino will follow soon. They are now the past. In their place is a
generation of quarterbacks whose parts add up to the prototype.
</P>
<P>
   These days, NFL quarterbacks are not required to call plays as
Unitas did, but they have far more to sort through, at the line of
scrimmage and after the snap. Multiple-receiver sets, many of which
call for the receiver to make reads along with the quarterback,
give passers more choices. Defenses counter with complex and
well-disguised coverages and rush schemes.
</P>
<P>
   Unitas never had to contend with the trendy zone blitz.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may not call the plays, but he has to make the adjustments
at a second's notice,'' Hall of Fame quarterback Terry Bradshaw
said of today's quarterback. ``He still has to be in charge and
make the plays. He has to be someone who can take the heat and can
perform in adverse situations, a guy who won't lose his poise.''
</P>
<P>
   Poise is a key ingredient, but one that's hard to categorize. It
goes beyond intelligence, or the ability to read defenses.
</P>
<P>
   All quarterbacks know their offenses, and most are as familiar
with their opponents' defenses. And Young not only knows where all
the San Francisco receivers and opposing defenders are supposed to
be on a given play, but he knows what to do when they're ``not''
where they're supposed to be.
</P>
<P>
   Young knows when to stand in and deliver the ball just before
taking a shot, and he knows when to run. He puts the ball in the
right place, which doesn't always mean right on the numbers; a good
quarterback throws the ball where the receiver can get it but the
defender can't.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has such a grasp of the position,'' Casserly said. ``He
knows all the tricks and uses them to make plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the arm is stronger than the mind at times. Favre can
make a questionable decision but make the play work because he can
fire the ball between defenders.
</P>
<P>
   The truly gifted _ such as Favre, Elway and Jeff George _ make
not only the standard throws but also passes that defy convention,
throwing accurately across their bodies on the run or off the wrong
foot.
</P>
<P>
   Strength is only part of the equation. Accuracy is necessary
because an ``open'' receiver in the NFL is usually a step or less
ahead of a defender. And a quick release is essential to get the
pass off ahead of rushers.
</P>
<P>
   That ability is what the Colts saw in Manning, the former
Tennessee star. When San Diego general manager Bobby Beathard saw
Manning on film, he called Manning's father, former NFL quarterback
Archie, and said: ``I was just watching the Tennessee-Alabama tape.
Tell me, how does your boy get rid of the ball so fast?''
</P>
<P>
   If the protection collapsed around Unitas or Joe Namath, they
might sidestep the rush or step up in the pocket, or they could
throw the ball away, but most often they would ``eat the
football,'' tucking it away in preparation for the inevitable hit.
</P>
<P>
   Then Fran Tarkenton came along and changed everything,
scrambling away from trouble. Playing behind the expansion
Minnesota Vikings' porous offensive line, it was run or be killed.
</P>
<P>
   Once it became apparent that a scrambler could succeed, they
became more common. Scramblers gaining credibility after Roger
``The Dodger'' Staubach carried the Cowboys to their first Super
Bowl victory in 1972. Eventually, mobility went from luxury to
necessity.
</P>
<P>
   Even drop-back passers such as Aikman and Bledsoe can move and
buy time when pressed, a trait known as ``escapability.'' The best
runners, Pittsburgh's Stewart and Jacksonville's Brunell, are
running backs in disguise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kordell runs faster than most wide receivers,'' Bradshaw said.
``That's a little different than what we're used to seeing. He's
someone coaches have to be aware of, because if he gets outside,
you're not going to catch him.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart is so effective as a runner that Steelers coach Bill
Cowher changed the rules by which most passers operate. Most young
quarterbacks have a problem staying in the pocket long enough to go
through their reads and let receivers come open. Stewart was
staying in long enough, but Cowher felt that was wasting his
talent. So he had Stewart take less time looking at the defense
before making his decision to pass or run. It's a strategy that
might become common as more running quarterbacks enter the league.
</P>
<P>
   Although mobility can help avoid a pass rush, it won't keep a
quarterback from taking a pounding. No matter how swift or agile,
he's going to get hit, and the blows can take a toll.
</P>
<P>
   That's one reason 230-pound quarterbacks are no longer a rarity.
Carolina's Kerry Collins is 6-5, 240. Troy Aikman goes 6-4, 219.
And Leaf, the Chargers' rookie starter, is 6-5 and weighs 250 or
more, depending on when you catch him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ability to stay healthy is a high priority, and obviously
a guy with a lot of size is better able to stand up to the hits,''
New Orleans scout Tom Marino said. ``You want at least 215-220
pounds, and you also want the height to be able to see the whole
field.''
</P>
<P>
   Whereas a 220-pound quarterback used to inspire awe in coaches,
now he is greeted by shrugs. Manning is a solid 6-5, 225, but, to
draft analysts, he was the small quarterback, small compared to
Leaf. Griese, the midget of the rookie class at 6-3, 215, is two
inches taller and 25 pounds heavier than his Hall of Fame father,
Bob.
</P>
<P>
   Said St. Louis Rams offensive coordinator Jerry Rhome: ``Today's
game makes it very difficult to be small.''
</P>
<P>
   If there has been a Unitas of the '80s and '90s, it was Elway.
At 6-3, 215, he has the size scouts wanted and, of course, the arm,
which has been the strongest in football history.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of mobility, well, Elway ranks fourth in career rushing
yardage among quarterbacks. His knowledge of the game is
unquestioned, and as for leadership and heart, he has an
unparalleled 45 come-from-behind victories, including The Drive of
98 yards to win the 1986 AFC title.
</P>
<P>
   But the prototype has begun to pass Elway. The latest examples
are Manning and Leaf, who represent opposite ends of the
quarterback spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   Leaf is the embodiment of physical prowess, huge and gifted. He
has a vertical leap of 36 inches and runs 40 yards in 4.7 seconds.
At Washington State, where he was taller than four of his five
offensive linemen, Leaf set weightlifting records to go with his
passing marks.
</P>
<P>
   No shrimp himself at 6-5, 225, Manning is the thinking man's
prospect. He has the arm and the release, but his football
knowledge makes him special. He has been tutored by his father
since his youth. By the time he was in high school, Manning was
breaking down film and organizing off-season drills.
</P>
<P>
   And the next step up the evolutionary ladder might already be on
the horizon. When the expansion Cleveland Browns open the 1999
draft, they are expected to select a quarterback to carry the
franchise. At the top of the board will likely be Daunte Culpepper
and Tim Couch, who have all the expected tools and add dimensions
to the position.
</P>
<P>
   If Couch elects to leave Kentucky after his junior season, he
could give the Browns the latest incarnation of the classic
drop-back passer. He is a 6-5, 233-pounder who, like Manning, has
been raised practically from birth to be a quarterback. As a
sophomore in 1997, Couch led the nation in passes (547),
completions (363), percentage (.664) and yardage (3,884). And he's
still improving; the deep ball was his project during the
off-season.
</P>
<P>
   Like Leaf, Central Florida's Culpepper is gigantic, fast and
powerful, with the arm to match.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's as big as a house, 6-5 and 250, and a tough kid,'' Tom
Marino said. ``But his first game as a freshman, he went 18-for-21.
Last year, he had his best game against Nebraska. That tells you a
lot.''
</P>
<P>
   The halftime score of that game _ Central Florida 17, Nebraska
14 _ said enough. Even in losing, 38-24, Culpepper emerged as a
national star, going 24-of-35 passing for 318 yards and a touchdown
against the Cornhuskers. Perhaps his most eye-opening play was a
bruising 10-yard touchdown run in which he showed speed and power
in bulling through two defenders at the goal line.
</P>
<P>
   It's not exactly the kind of thing you would picture Unitas
doing. Then again, Culpepper has a lot to learn about other phases
of the game. When the two come together, will that, then, be the
quarterback of the future?
</P>
<P>
   ``The trend is pretty easy to spot,'' Bradshaw said. ``Bigger,
stronger, faster, better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
