<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI, THE NONCANDIDATE: CITY SLICKER IN THE HEARTLAND 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: 2nd-take is scheduled to move by 9:30 p.m. ET) 
(ART ADV: Photo of Mayor Giuliani is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DAN BARRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CEDAR RAPIDS, Iowa _ Moments after lecturing on his favorite
subject, the crime reduction in New York City, to his preferred
audience, a group of law enforcement officials, New York Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani received a compliment Wednesday that could only be
described as peculiarly Iowan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor should look very closely at our Iowa caucus,'' said
Steve Grubbs, the Republican state chairman, before introducing
Giuliani to a gaggle of Iowa and New York reporters. ``If he ran
for president, he would finish in the top three.''
</P>
<P>
   There are problems associated with such an invitation, however
flattering. To start with, the caucus is 18 months away. What's
more, the mayor would be a moderate in a field that favors
conservatives. Oh, and Giuliani has acknowledged no interest
publicly in seeking the presidency in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   True to form, he responded to Grubbs by saying again that he has
given no thought to such a lofty goal, and was in Iowa only to
raise money for fellow Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the very public invitation brought smiles of satisfaction
to the faces of Giuliani's aides. Their boss had come to the
Midwest in the seemingly innocuous role of Republican
soldier-cum-star, with no professed motive other than to support
colleagues and share his musings on the party's future. And yet the
mayor, in a slightly softer manifestation than the one routinely
seen in New York City, had charmed many Iowa Republicans with his
big-city tales of a plummeting murder rate and a crackdown on
welfare. He had succeeded in the often subtle game of Keep Me in
Mind.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the standing ovations Giuliani received Wednesday in
Iowa City, Cedar Rapids, and Waterloo really constituted anything
more than Midwestern hospitality remains to be seen. After all, he
is a social moderate who favors gay rights, gun control and
abortion rights, in a state in which 75 percent of those who vote
in the Republican caucus are against abortion.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he is nationally recognized as a crime fighter
_ ``the leading warrior,'' he was called at a crime conference in
Cedar Rapids _ at the same time that Iowa has become obsessed with
crime, particularly a proliferation of the drug methamphetamine.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor so impressed Bill Kidwell, chairman of the Johnson
County Republican Committee and a retired police detective, that he
immediately began envisioning a country in which Giuliani was
addressed as Mr. President.
</P>
<P>
   ``He spoke of law and order, he spoke of welfare, he spoke of
drug dependency,'' Kidwell said. ``I think that he's just the man
who can turn this country around to when I was a kid and you all
were dinky shavers.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
