<SLUG> BC-FBN-PREVIEW-NFCCENTRAL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFC CENTRAL CAPSULES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
NFC CENTRAL 
TAMPA BAY BUCCANEERS 
1997: 10-6, 3-5 in NFC Central 
Coach (record): Tony Dungy (16-16) 
Stadium: Raymond James Stadium (65,394) 
Ticket information: (813) 879-2827 
Pieces in place 
QB Trent Dilfer (21 passing TDs), RB Warrick Dunn (1997 rookie of
the year), FB Mike Alstott (10 TDs), DT Warren Sapp (10.5 sacks), C
Tony Mayberry (1997 Pro Bowl), LB Derrick Brooks (1997 Pro Bowl),
LB Hardy Nickerson (1997 Pro Bowl). 
Key newcomers 
WR Bert Emanuel, RB Lorenzo Neal, WR Jacquez Green, CB Brian
Kelly. 
Key losses 
TE Jackie Harris 
Missing piece 
The Buccaneers reached the playoffs in 1997 for the first time in
14 seasons despite an offense that ranked 29th in yards per game
(273.5) and last in points scored (18.7). The main problem with the
Buccaneers' offense was its anemic passing game, which mustered a
measly 152.6 yards per game, last in the league. The club's leading
receiver last season was Dunn, who caught 29 passes. Dungy hopes he
correctly addressed his wide receiver problem through free agency
with Emanuel, who led Atlanta last season in receptions (65), yards
(991) and touchdowns (9). Dungy drafted Green, the speedy Florida
receiver, with his first pick in the draft. Reidel Anthony, who
will probably begin the season as the starter opposite Emanuel,
Horace Copeland and Karl Williams give the Buccaneers depth at the
position. All in all, Dilfer, a Pro Bowler in 1997, should have
plenty of weapons to take Tampa Bay deep into the playoffs. 
Biggest test 
The Buccaneers have two killer stretches in their schedule. They
open with three of their first four games on the road against
division foes Minnesota, Green Bay and Detroit. They were 2-1 in
those cities last season. Then, from Nov. 15 to Dec. 13, they play
at Jacksonville, vs. Detroit, at Chicago, vs. Green Bay and vs.
Pittsburgh. 
Watch out for 
Sapp. He anchors a defensive line that helped limit 2,000-yard man
Barry Sanders to fewer than 100 yards rushing in two of their three
games last season _ 20 in a regular-season contest and 65 in the
playoffs. Sapp single-handedly dominated some teams last year (ask
San Francisco and Green Bay), and he looks like he will become the
next great defensive superstar. Sapp has plenty of talent around
him. The unit limited 11 teams to less than 20 points last year. 
Milestones 
The Buccaneers have not won a road game in December since a 17-14
victory at Washington on Dec. 18, 1994. 
Overview 
The Buccaneers have a Super Bowl-contending defense. They have a
solid running game. If Dilfer can continue to play mistake-free
football, and if one of the young wide receivers can turn into a
big-play threat _ two ifs that are not unlikely _ the Buccaneers
could be Super Bowl-bound. 
Prediction: 11-5 
 
Puzzle piece 
WR Bert Emanuel 
 
STARTING LINEUP 
Offense 
QB Trent Dilfer 
RB Warrick Dunn 
FB Mike Alstott 
WR Reidel Anthony 
WR Bert Emanuel 
TE Dave Moore 
LT Paul Gruber 
LG Frank Middleton 
C Tony Mayberry 
RG Jorge Diaz 
RT Jason Odom 
 
Defense 
RE Chidi Ahanotu 
RT Warren Sapp 
LT Brad Culpepper 
LE Regan Upshaw 
MLB Hardy Nickerson 
OLB Derrick Brooks 
OLB Jeff Gooch 
CB Donnie Abraham 
CB Anthony Parker 
FS John Lynch 
SS Charles Mincy 
 
Specialists 
KR Karl Williams 
PR Karl Williams 
K Michael Husted 
P Tommy Barnhardt 
 
GREEN BAY PACKERS 
1997: 13-3, 7-1 in NFC Central 
Coach (record): Mike Holmgren (71-35) 
Stadium: Lambeau Field (60,790) 
Ticket information: (920) 496-5719 
Pieces in place 
QB Brett Favre (35 passing TDs), RB Dorsey Levens (1,435 rushing
yards), WR Antonio Freeman (1,243 receiving yards), WR Robert
Brooks (7 receiving TDs), DT Santana Dotson (5.5 sacks), SS LeRoy
Butler (5 interceptions). 
Key newcomers 
DE Eric Curry, RB/KR Glyn Milburn, DT Vonnie Holliday. 
Key losses 
CB Doug Evans, S Eugene Robinson, DE Gabe Wilkins, G Aaron Taylor. 
Missing piece 
The Packers, who have won more regular-season games (37) than any
team the past three seasons, were exposed in their Super Bowl loss
to Denver. Broncos running back Terrell Davis pounded the soft
underbelly of the Packers' defense, and that of massive tackle
Gilbert Brown, for 157 yards and three touchdowns. The Packers'
defense, which was 20th against the rush in 1997, continued to take
its lumps during the off-season as Robinson, Wilkins and Evans
departed for big free-agent contracts. The departure of Wilkins and
the on-again, off-again retirement antics of Reggie White in the
spring have left the defensive line in a mess. White will play in
1998, but no one knows how effective he'll be. No. 1 draft choice
Holliday will make the switch from tackle to replace Wilkins at the
other end. And Holmgren will depend on a rotation of Dotson, Brown
and Vaughn Booker at defensive tackle. Coaches worry most about the
350-pound Brown, whose lackluster conditioning has made him a
liability late in some games. 
Biggest test 
Prime Time. No, Favre won't have to worry about having an
interception return for a touchdown by the Cowboys' Deion Sanders.
We're talking about television here. The Packers play four night
games on national television; vs. Minnesota on Oct. 5, at Detroit
on Oct. 15, at Pittsburgh on Nov. 9 and at Tampa Bay on Dec. 7. The
world will get to see whether the Pack has slipped back into the
pack. 
Watch out for 
Who else but Favre. The three-time most valuable player is one of
the few players who can win it by himself. If the defense is having
a bad day, he can win the game with five touchdowns. He can also
lose it by himself, as he did with two crucial turnovers in the
Super Bowl. There are a lot of things happening in Green Bay, with
all of the free-agent defections and the holdout of Levens. But the
overachieving Packers live and die on the right arm of its resident
super hero, Favre. 
Milestones 
The Packers have won 23 consecutive regular-season home games. If
they win the first five home games of the 1998 season, they will
break the 1971-74 Dolphins' record for most consecutive home
victories (27). The Fab Five on Green Bay's home schedule are
Detroit, Tampa Bay, Minnesota, Baltimore and San Francisco. Hmmm.
Maybe the Dolphins' record will live on. 
Overview 
No NFC team has been to three consecutive Super Bowls. But any team
with Favre is a worthy Super Bowl contender. Thus, despite the fact
that they lost several key free agents and that they play in the
toughest division in pro football, the Packers should be considered
division and conference favorites. Sooner or later, those questions
on defense will come back to haunt the Green and Gold and, perhaps,
help open the door for a new conference champion. 
Prediction: 11-5 
 
Puzzle piece 
Vonnie Holliday 
 
STARTING LINEUP 
