P Sean Landeta 
 
MINNESOTA VIKINGS 
1997: 9-7, 3-5 in NFC Central 
Coach record 
Dennis Green (56-44) 
Stadium: Hubert H. Humphrey Metrodome (64,182) 
Ticket information: (612) 989-5151 
Pieces in place 
QB Brad Johnson (20 passing TDs), RB Robert Smith (1,266 rushing
yards), WR Cris Carter (13 receiving TDs), WR Jake Reed (1,138
receiving yards), DT John Randle (15.5 sacks), OT Todd Steussie
(1997 Pro Bowl), G Randall McDaniel (1997 Pro Bowl). 
Key newcomers 
WR Randy Moss, CB Jimmy Hitchcock, CB Larry Brown. 
Key losses 
CB Dewayne Washington, CB Leonard Wheeler. 
Missing piece 
The Vikings could not stop anyone in 1997. They were 29th in total
defense, 29th against the pass and last in average yards allowed
per play. Oddly, despite losing three cornerbacks to free agency,
they spent their first pick in the draft on the talented but
troubled Moss. But Green thinks he has shored up his pass defense
with the signings of Hitchcock from New England and Brown, who
spent the past two seasons in Al Davis' doghouse in Oakland.
Hitchcock, Brown and incumbent starter Corey Fuller are not Pro
Bowl players, but Green hopes they can parlay their veteran savvy
into big plays out of the Vikings' zone defense. 
Biggest test 
Overconfidence. The Vikings play eight games in 1998 against clubs
who missed the playoffs in 1997. If they can avoid too many upsets
and play .500 or better against the clubs who did make the
playoffs, Dennis Green could find himself in the playoffs again. 
Watch out for 
Moss. With the emotional guidance from former bad-boy Cris Carter,
Moss, the troubled wide receiver from Marshall University, wasn't a
problem in the off-season. If he continues on the straight and
narrow, the Vikings' explosive offensive unit could rack up a bunch
of 400-yard days. If Moss acts up, which he hasn't in more than two
years, he could take the whole team down with him. So far, so good
if you are a Vikings fan. 
Milestones 
Running back Robert Smith has not fumbled in 415 attempts from
scrimmage. 
Overview 
The Vikings have too much offense not to reach the playoffs for the
sixth time in seven seasons. And maybe this is the season the club
can sneak into the conference finals. That's highly unlikely,
though, with its questions in the defensive secondary. 
Prediction: 10-6 
 
