DETROIT LIONS 
1997: 9-7, 6-2 in NFC Central 
Coach (record): Bobby Ross (9-7) 
Stadium: Pontiac Silverdome (80,368) 
Ticket information: (248) 335-4151 
Pieces in place 
RB Barry Sanders (2,053 rushing yards), QB Scott Mitchell (19
passing TDs), WR Herman Moore (104 receptions), WR Johnnie Morton
(1,057 receiving yards), DE Robert Porcher (12.5 sacks), DT Luther
Elliss (8.5 sacks), FS Mark Carrier (five interceptions). 
Key newcomers 
OLB Allen Aldridge, C Jim Pyne, OLB Rob Fredrickson, DT Dan Owens,
CB Terry Fair. 
Key losses 
OLB Reggie Brown, C Kevin Glover, CB Corey Raymond, DT Mike Wells. 
Missing piece 
The Lions have Super Bowl-type talent limited by wild-card
quarterback Mitchell. Three of the club's losses came by nine or
more points to clubs that missed the playoffs in 1997. In those
games _ against New Orleans, Buffalo and Washington _ Mitchell
threw four interceptions and two touchdowns passes. If the Lions
are to win the division and perhaps have home advantage part or all
of the playoffs, Mitchell must play better against weaker teams. To
help him achieve that, the Lions brought in former Seattle QB Jim
Zorn as Mitchell's position coach. 
Biggest test 
From Nov. 22 to Dec. 14, the Lions are at Tampa Bay, Jacksonville
and San Francisco, and they are home against Pittsburgh on
Thanksgiving Day. 
Watch out for 
If there was ever a problem with the Lions it was their rushing
defense. Opposing offensive lines pushed around the Lions' smallish
front four of Tracy Scroggins (255 pounds), Mike Wells (287
pounds), Elliss (291) and Porcher (270) for an average of 114 yards
per game, 18th in the league. Things seemingly did not get better
in the off-season as Wells, the club's best run stopper, signed
with Chicago. The club picked up Dan Owens (290) from Atlanta to
replace him. Owens, like the other Lions defensive linemen, is a
better pass rusher (8 sacks) than run stuffer (41 tackles). In all,
the front four the Lions will put on the field this year totaled 36
1/2 sacks in 1997. So, if the Lions can force teams into passing
situations, they'll give themselves a better chance of winning. 
Milestones 
With one touchdown, Barry Sanders will move into sole possession of
eighth place on the all-time career list. Sanders has 105
touchdowns, tied with former Packers WR Don Hutson. 
Overview 
The Lions are the fourth-best team in the best division in football
and that should be enough to earn a playoff berth. If Zorn can turn
Mitchell into a clutch quarterback, and Sanders stays injury-free,
this club could go far into the playoffs. 
Prediction: 9-7 
 
