CHICAGO BEARS 
1997: 4-12, 1-7 in NFC Central 
Coach (record): Dave Wannstedt (36-44) 
Stadium: Soldier Field (66,944) 
Ticket information: (847) 615-2327 
Pieces in place 
QB Erik Kramer (14 passing TDs), WR Curtis Conway (3 games with 100
yards receiving), DT Jim Flanigan (6 sacks), MLB Barry Minter (6
sacks). 
Key newcomers 
RB Edgar Bennett, RB Curtis Enis, RB Bam Morris, C Olin Kreutz, TE
Alonzo Mayes, DT Mike Wells, S Tony Parrish. 
Key losses 
LB Bryan Cox, RB Raymont Harris, KR Tyrone Hughes, DE Alonzo
Spellman. 
Missing piece 
The Bears feature three new starters at linebacker this season,
though Minter started on the outside last season. Minter replaces
Cox. Candidates to flank Minter are Michael Lowery and Sean Harris.
``Who?'' That's what Bears fans are asking. These guys will be
counted on to help a defense that ranked 19th against the run last
season and a respectable 12th overall. Minter is the closest thing
they have to a playmaker at this position. Overall, the club is
hoping that improved front-four play will hide some of the
weaknesses of its no-name linebacker crew. 
Biggest test 
Every game. The Bears have the second-toughest schedule in the
league. Each of their division opponents reached the playoffs last
season. Their first two nondivision opponents, Jacksonville and
Pittsburgh, also were in the playoffs. They do have a stretch of
four games in five weeks against non-playoff teams. 
Watch out for 
The Bears' offense, which was 28th in scoring, may surprise a few
people. First-round draft choice Enis and former Green Bay RB
Bennett are upgrades from the Bears' anemic 1-2 punch of Rashaan
Salaam and Raymont Harris. In the passing game, Conway runs a
sub-4.4-second time in the 40-yard dash. The Bears were 3-4 when he
was healthy last season, 1-8 when he was out of the lineup.
Opposite Conway, the Bears want to start World League phenom Marcus
Robinson, who is 6-foot-5 and runs a 4.35. Mayes and John Allred
give the Bears better-than-average tight ends. The Bears' offensive
line is as physical as any in the league, helping the club lead the
league in time of possession in 1997. Leading the charge will be
Kramer, who split time with the struggling Rick Mirer last season.
Management thought so highly of Kramer that they let Mirer go, and
re-signed Kramer to a three-year, $9 million contract. 
Milestones 
Among active place-kickers, the Bears' Jeff Jaeger, who spent much
of his career with the Raiders, is ninth in career field goals with
206. 
Overview 
The Bears have too many questions on defense to make much of an
impact in what is clearly the toughest division in pro football. 
Prediction: 3-13 
 
