<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-PREVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONGHORNS IN HURRY TO REVEAL NEW SPEED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Inspectors are indispensable if you need to sell a
house. As the husband of a real-estate developer, Mack Brown
understands this concept.
</P>
<P>
   But the first-year Texas coach doesn't need them on his football
team. Not if they play defense and fit the definition of the word
Brown is teaching his Longhorns.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can't run, you're an inspector. You get there as
everyone is unpiling and inspect what happened,'' Brown said. ``We
don't want that. We want guys who are angry and get there in time
to create chaos. To do that, you've got to have speed.''
</P>
<P>
   That has meant swapping size for speed throughout a Texas
defense that allowed a school-record 366 points last season. No
position is more indicative of the fresh mind-set than outside
linebacker, where the Longhorns plan to start a former fullback and
a converted safety at the respective spots in the team's Sept. 5
opener in Austin against New Mexico State.
</P>
<P>
   One is De'Andre ``DeDe'' Lewis, a redshirt freshman who played
fullback on the scout team in 1997. The other is Aaron Babino, who
made 87 tackles at strong safety, but lost his starting job in the
final month of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Neither has played a down at his new position in a college game.
But that doesn't make them unique. Of the Longhorns' 11 projected
defensive starters, seven were playing other positions at this time
last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of weird to look around out in practice,'' said
middle linebacker Dusty Renfro (6-foot, 240 pounds), a senior and
third-year starter. ``I'm used to seeing two other linebackers
built like me: short, stocky, plug-the-hole guys. Now, I've got
guys on both sides that are so fast, you have to tell them to be
careful and not overrun the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis runs the 40-yard dash in 4.5 seconds. Babino has been
clocked in 4.4. Both will be asked to blitz frequently in a
pressure-oriented scheme that will place nine men near the line of
scrimmage on most downs.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who inherits a team that finished 4-7 in its final season
under predecessor John Mackovic, said he wants to use an aggressive
defense to change the team's mind-set.
</P>
<P>
   ``Attitude is 90 percent of football,'' Brown said. ``You change
the attitude, you can change the results.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis (6-1, 225) and Babino (6-1, 215) say they've enjoyed
changing positions, as well as perspectives, since last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't miss carrying the ball. This is where I need to be,''
said Lewis, who requested the move during off-season workouts. ``I
had no idea what type of defense I was stepping into when I asked
to move. But I've loved it since the first day.''
</P>
<P>
   Babino said he did not have to think twice when coaches
approached him with the idea of playing closer to the line of
scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love blitzing. I wish they'd send me on every play,'' Babino
said. ``This gives me a chance to make more big plays. Plus, I was
already big for a defensive back. It should be easier for me to
cover the tight ends and running backs than it was to cover wide
receivers.''
</P>
<P>
   Both players concede they have areas to improve upon in their
new positions. Lewis said he occasionally struggles with
overpursuing on misdirection plays. Babino said he sometimes feels
overmatched when taking on offensive tackles.
</P>
<P>
   Renfro, however, said he has seen significant progress from both
during fall drills. At a recent practice, Lewis knocked out
scout-team tailback Tony Ellis with a tackle. By the end of the
workout, Babino recorded two interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Linebackers have to be the meanest guys on the field,'' Renfro
said. ``And they're both doing a good job of sticking their noses
up in the holes and hitting guys hard. I don't think I'm going to
have to give either one of them meanness lessons.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor will Mack Brown worry about whether they should arrive on
time to make plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're both really fast for linebackers,'' he said. ``The
negative is they don't have any experience. But the positive is,
they'll run and get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown hopes they arrive long before the inspectors.
Texas at a glance 1997 record: 4-7, 2-6 in Big 12 (tied for 4th in
South Division) Coach: Mack Brown (first year at Texas, 86-74-1
overall) Stadium: Royal-Memorial (80,216) Returning starters
(offense): 8 Returning starters (defense): 9 All-star candidates:
TB Ricky Williams, OT Jay Humphrey, LB Dusty Renfro, DE Aaron
Humphrey Key newcomers: LB De'Andre ``DeDe'' Lewis, CB Chris
Butcher, WR Ryan Nunez, K Kris Stockton, DB Ahmad Brooks, DB Ervis
Hill, LB Miguel McKay, LB Everick Rawls
