<SLUG> BC-SURGE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wind, water brings rising tide of trouble
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, N.C. -- As Hurricane Bonnie crawls through North
Carolina, officials are worried about flooding today, not so much
from the storm surge caused by intense winds but simply from the
volume of rain a stalled storm will dump into the Pamlico River.
</P>
<P>
   Places in eastern North Carolina could receive up to 20 inches
of rain over the next 24 hours, said Daden Wolfe, director of
emergency management for Beaufort County, 90 miles inland from
either tip of the Outer Banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a pretty good handle when (Bonnie) was going 14 mph,''
Wolfe said. ``Now it's going at a snail's pace. You're just going
to have rain on top of rain. Buckets full.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe said one computer model put the eye of the storm in
Washington about 2 p.m. today. Diminished winds may be less than
hurricane force. Driving winds cause storm surge, a wall of water
that has the effect of raising sea level. The slower winds may not
be any better news for Washington, which contended with partial
flooding of downtown in 1996 during Hurricanes Fran and Bertha.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just different news,'' Wolfe said. Wednesday, some local
roads had flooded here and in nearby Greenville.
</P>
<P>
   Early Wednesday, before squall lines churned across the area in
counterclockwise fashion and contributed to scores of traffic
accidents and minor flooding, a few police officers gathered at the
bulkhead that holds the Pamlico out of downtown. They looked at
nearly 20 boats parked in the middle of the river and wondered
which ones would sink.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will flood so quick here,'' said Patrolman S.F. Szabo. By
late afternoon, the Pamlico lapped at the top of the bulkhead
</P>
<P>
   The Police Department is just three blocks from the river, so
officers were prepared to stow their things in patrol cars. They're
expecting to stay on continuous duty through at least tonight.
</P>
<P>
   When Fran and Bertha socked it to this area in 1996, the water
rose close enough to the top of the drawbridge that anyone standing
at the top had only to lean over to reach the river.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest of Beaufort, rain poured into the Tar River in
adjacent Pitt County. The Tar heads downstream and feeds into the
Pamlico.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to get some flooding,'' Wolfe said. ``We just
don't know where.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
