<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    On Deck:St. Louis Cardinals
 &HT;    Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When: Tonight and Friday at 8:10 p.m., Saturday at 1:15 p.m. and
Sunday at 8:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Where: Busch Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Radio/TV: WUPA-69 will telecast tonight's game, TBS will
telecast Friday, WAGA-5 will telecast Saturday and ESPN will
telecast Sunday. WSB 750-AM will broadcast all four games.
</P>
<P>
   Probable starting pitchers: Tonight, LHP Denny Neagle (12-11,
3.62; 5-5, 4.04 lifetime vs. Cardinals) vs. RHP Matt Morris (4-3,
2.17; 0-2, 4.50 lifetime vs. Braves). Friday, RHP Greg Maddux
(17-6, 1.91; 17-14, 2.39 lifetime vs. Cardinals) vs. LHP Kent
Mercker (8-11, 5.57; 1-2, 5.04 lifetime vs. Braves). Saturday, LHP
Tom Glavine (17-5, 2.57; 11-4, 3.73 lifetime vs. Cardinals) vs.
Kent Bottenfield (4-5, 4.51; 1-1, 1.80 lifetime vs. Braves).
Sunday, RHP Kevin Millwood (14-8, 4.29; 1-0, 4.38 lifetime vs.
Cardinals) vs. LHP Donovan Osborne (3-3, 2.81; 1-2, 4.95 lifetime
vs. Braves).
</P>
<P>
   Series history: Atlanta trails the all-time series 183-219 but
is 21-8 against St. Louis in the Tony La Russa era.
</P>
<P>
   Past meetings: The Braves are 4-1 versus the Cardinals this
season, sweeping a two-game set in St. Louis May 13-14 and winning
two of three at Turner Field July 31-Aug. 2. The Cardinals have hit
.185 against Braves pitching and while Atlanta has held Mark
McGwire to one homer, Ray Lankford has hit three. This is not a
fluke season. The Cardinals have had just one winning year against
Atlanta this decade.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals leaders: Ave.: Brian Jordan (.321); HR Mark McGwire
(53); RBI McGwire (114); SB Delino DeShields (21). W Kent Mercker
(8); ERA Matt Morris (2.17). Saves Jeff Brantley (14). Strikeouts
Kent Bottenfield (88).
</P>
<P>
   Quickly: In the midst of a short six-game homestand, St. Louis
took a four-game losing streak in Wednesday night's game with
Florida. The Cardinals were 11-12 this month, 22-23 since the
All-Star break and have been under .500 since June 25th. Somehow,
they still remain 9-1/2 games back in the NL wildcard race. . . .
Despite all the offensive fireworks the team's 172 homers are
second only to Atlanta's 177 St. Louis ranks seventh in NL scoring
and its team batting average (.258) is 12th. Only San Francisco has
left more men on base (an average 7.6 a game) and the team strikes
out seven times a game. . . . But it is pitching that has really
betrayed the Cards this year, through injury and ineffectiveness.
Six pitchers have been on the DL (Alan Benes has been there all
year), forcing manager Tony La Russa to experiment with 14
different starters. Darren Oliver, acquired from Texas for opening
day starter Todd Stottlemyre, is 1-2 as a Cardinal. The club has
lost 14 times after leading in the eighth inning. . . . They can
reach the fences. Ten different Cards contributed to the team's
first 34 homers this month. They have homered five times in five
games against the Braves but the Braves are hitting .279 against
St. Louis pitching, 94 points higher than the Cards. . . . Morris,
tonight's starter, only rejoined the rotation at the All-Star break
due to a tender right shoulder. He and the absent Benes comprise
the pitching future of the organization. Though just 4-3, Morris's
support has been spotty. In his 10 starts, the Cardinals have
scored three or fewer runs six times. He won in New York in his
last start, limiting the Mets to two runs on six hits through seven
innings. On the DL: RHP Alan Benes (right shoulder surgery), RHP
Mike Busby (right elbow ligament strain), INF David Howard
(shoulder strain).
</P>
<P>
   Who's hot: OF Ray Lankford had brought his average up 21 points
since the All-Star break, with 13 homers and 13 doubles among his
last 51 hits. OF Ron Gant has 20 homers in his last 32 games. OF
Brian Jordan is hitting .339 at home this season.
</P>
<P>
   Who's not: 2B Delino DeShields is hitting .204 since coming off
the DL Aug. 10. Close Jeff Brantley has seven blown saves in 21
save opportunites.
</P>
<P>
   C Eli Marrero is hitting .189 with runners in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
