<HEADER>
A4056 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-COX     08-26 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Make no mistake
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Walk him.
</P>
<P>
   That has been the strategy for most teams facing Mark McGwire
this season. McGwire has walked 138 times in 131 games and is on
pace to break Babe Ruth's major league record of 170.
</P>
<P>
   But the Braves' pitching staff takes a different approach. They
view McGwire as the ultimate challenge and go right at him with
their best. That approach is expected to continue tonight, when
Atlanta begins a four-game series against the Cardinals in St.
Louis.
</P>
<P>
   The results have been eye-opening.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, whose 53 homers average out to one every 7.7 at-bats,
has faced Atlanta pitchers 20 times this season. He has three hits,
one home run and a .158 batting average. Atlanta pitchers have
walked McGwire once. They have struck him out nine times.
</P>
<P>
   When the Braves faced McGwire in Atlanta earlier this month, he
didn't get a ball out of the infield during an 0-for-11 stretch. He
struck out seven times.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's because of the guys who are throwing,'' Braves pitching
coach Leo Mazzone said. ``I'll say this, that we're not going into
the game looking to walk him. We're looking to get him out.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's ability to shut down McGwire helps prove the adage
that good pitching beats good hitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't come up with any unique strategies or anything,''
Mazzone said. ``What we worry about is beating the Cardinals and
not placing any more emphasis on McGwire than the rest of their
lineup. He may get to us yet. Who knows?''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire will get his chance against Denny Neagle, Greg Maddux,
Tom Glavine and Kevin Millwood. During the July-August series,
McGwire faced Maddux, Glavine and Millwood. John Smoltz, who
started Wednesday in Houston, has never pitched against McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love to face him when I am at my best,'' Smoltz said.
``It would be like facing Barry Bonds of late. He's gotten me a
couple of times lately, but I didn't back down. And I wouldn't back
down to Mark. But that series we pitched against him in Atlanta,
that was incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   Each of the Braves pitchers has a different approach when going
against McGwire. Millwood, who struck him out twice, tried to match
him with power.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went with pure stuff,'' Mazzone said. ``He didn't sacrifice
stuff for location. He didn't back off at all. He looked like he
tried to turn it up a notch.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to get ahead of him and take him out,''
Millwood said. ``I wasn't going to give him a pitch he could do a
lot with. I got excited pitching against him. He is a good hitter,
on top of hitting all those home runs. It is a little bit more
exciting getting those types of guys out.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddux spends his time trying to outfox McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was locating well against him, forcing McGwire to guess,''
Mazzone said. ``And he guessed wrong. That doesn't happen all the
time, but Greg has this way of fooling people.''
</P>
<P>
   Glavine will work both sides of the plate against McGwire. On
Aug. 1, he worked the inside part on McGwire's first at-bat, then
outside. McGwire went 0-for-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tommy is never going to give in to the strike zone to
anyone,'' Mazzone said. ``He's not going to accommodate him by
throwing the ball over the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Neagle probably will have to work the hardest. It will be his
first appearance against McGwire this year. McGwire was 0-for-7
against him last year with four strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing is you can't be intimidated,'' Neagle
said. ``He is human. Guys get too nervous facing him, and they
worry about making the perfect pitch. Then they make a mistake and
give up a homer. He is a great home run hitter, but he also has
some mistakes in his swing.''
</P>
<P>
   Mazzone said his pitchers have not made mistakes against
McGwire. And it's a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a great mistake hitter, and, on a mistake pitch that
someone else may send into the air in center for an out, McGwire
hits it 500 feet,'' Mazzone said. ``Then there are times like last
year, when Tommy threw a pitch off the plate low and away, and
McGwire went down and got it and hit it into the center-field
stands. When that happens, you tip you hat to the hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   That's something Atlanta has done very few times.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
