<HEADER>
A4057 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-IRL-STEWART-COX     08-26 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-IRL-STEWART-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta 500 Classic At A Glance
 &HT;    By Kent Mitchell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Any race-car driver, even the legendary A.J. Foyt, will admit
that luck has to be a factor in winning or losing. And Kenny Brack
is on an incredible lucky streak, as well as on the verge of a
historic winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   All he has to do is cross the finish line first in Saturday
night's Atlanta Classic 500. A victory here would give Brack an
unprecedented three straight IRL victories.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure must be growing.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Brack said Wednesday. ``The only pressure on myself is
from myself. It's always been that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Brack is the hottest driver in the Indy Racing League. He has
won the last two races, the VisionAire 500 on July 25 at Charlotte
Motor Speedway and the Radisson 200 on Aug. 16 at Pikes Peak
International Raceway, in his Power Team Racing
Dallara/Aurora/Goodyear owned by four-time Indianapolis 500 winner
Foyt.
</P>
<P>
   And there is how he won, which is where the luck factor comes
in:
</P>
<P>
   At Charlotte, Brack made a daring pass of Jeff Ward with 12 laps
to go for his first career IRL win. He took the scary high position
exiting turn 2 in a three-wide formation _ the same thing could
happen at AMS on Saturday night _ on lap 196, and went on to beat
Ward by 5.602 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   He ran out of fuel in turn 4 on the last lap of the Radisson 200
but coasted down the front straightaway to win his second
consecutive IRL race. Luck goes both ways _ Brack ran out of gas
while leading the Indy 500. Before the existence of IRL, drivers
have had longer streaks _ Foyt won seven in a row in 1964 _ but
racing wasn't awash in dollars then as it is now.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to race purses, the victory at Charlotte put Brack
in position to share $1 million with a fan through the MCI Pep Boys
Million Dollar Driver sweepstakes. Brack must win at Atlanta and at
the season finale Oct. 11 at Las Vegas to split $1 million with a
lucky fan who picked him to sweep the three races.
</P>
<P>
   Another turn of luck has him No. 2 in the IRL championship
points race with the chance to share another million-dollar poke.
</P>
<P>
   Brack, with 232 points, is one behind leader Scott Sharp.
Earlier in the week, the IRL took 15 points away from former
leader, Tony Stewart, as part of a penalty to Team Menard for
technical violations at the Radisson 200. Team Menard also drew a
$25,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart is in third place with 227 points. Five or six points
might look like a slim lead, but Stewart won the 1997 championship
by six points.
</P>
<P>
   There should be some furious racing between Brack, Sharp and
Stewart on Saturday night, and Brack has the momentum.
</P>
<P>
   A distant seventh in the point standings after the New England
200 on June 28 at Loudon, N.H., Brack trailed leader Stewart by 58
points after that race.
</P>
<P>
   Brack and the Foyt team have done well on super speedways this
year. Brack finished third in the June 6 True Value 500 at Texas
Motor Speedway, a sister track to Atlanta Motor Speedway and
Charlotte Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   He also recorded the fastest speed among drivers participating
in a Goodyear tire test July 28-29 at AMS, 221.185 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Brack will have plenty of challengers at AMS, with one of the
biggest fields of the Pep Boys Indy Racing League season competing.
</P>
<P>
   His teammate, Boat, is at the top of the list. Boat won the True
Value 500 but couldn't compete at Charlotte because of injuries
suffered in a crash at the New England 200. However, he came back
strong by winning the PPG Pole for the Radisson 200.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart also must be considered a prime threat. He knows his way
around AMS, having recorded an unofficial track record speed of
228.505 mph July 7 in his Glidden-Menards Special
Dallara/Aurora/Firestone during the league's Open Test at Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
