<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-NASCAR-COKE27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Earnhardts enjoy chance to unveil Monte Carlos
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seconds after Dale Earnhardt Jr. uncovered the shiny black No. 1
Chevrolet Monte Carlo with the decal of the Coca-Cola polar bear
decal on the hood, a rumble of a NASCAR engine on MLK Jr. Drive
grabbed everyone's attention.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Earnhardt Sr., driving a shiny red No. 3 Chevy with the
checkered-flag Coke bottle design on the hood, pulled beside the
other car at the World of Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   The fans gathered behind the crowd-control ropes cheered as if
The Intimidator had entered victory lane. ``Pretty neat, isn't
it?'' Dale Sr. said, after climbing out of the car. ``Dale Junior's
got the polar bear car with the teddy-bear driver. Earnhardt's (car
is) the classic.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Earnhardts and Coca-Cola unveiled the cars that
will be driven in a November race in Japan. Father will drive
against son for the first time in the season-ending exhibition
race, Nov. 22, at the Twin Ring Speedway in Motegi.
</P>
<P>
   It also marks Coke's return to car sponsorship in stock-car
racing for the first time since sponsoring Bobby Allison in 1974.
At the moment, it's a one-time deal, accompanied by a full line of
souvenirs.
</P>
<P>
   The Earnhardts appeared to be as excited about their cars on
Tuesday as they are to be racing against each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real good-looking race car,'' Earnhardt Jr. said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a change of pace (for me), with the red car and red
uniform,'' Earnhardt Sr. said. ``I didn't know if we'd ever see
Dale Jr. in a black car, because I drive the black 3, but here he
is in a black No. 1.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the Earnhardts began some good-natured kidding: ``I can
ground the kid, and I also can dock his pay,'' Dad said.
</P>
<P>
   The Earnhardts race in different leagues. Earnhardt Sr., of
course, is the seven-time Winston Cup champion and winner of this
year's Daytona 500. Earnhardt Jr., who turns 24 next month, is
leading the Busch Grand National points race in his third season,
winning five times in the No. 3 Busch car that his father owns.
</P>
<P>
   The Japan race will be Junior's first in a Winston Cup car, and
his dad said Tuesday the son will move up to the big-league level
in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll go test Dale Jr. in Homestead and get him some time in a
Winston Cup car,'' Earnhardt Sr. said. ``He's used to the downforce
of the Busch cars. We want to get the Winston Cup car tuned in for
him.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
