<HEADER>
A4059 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-RACING-NOTES-COX     08-26 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-RACING-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Team Menard penalized for technical violations
 &HT;    By Kent Mitchell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Indy Racing League has penalized Team Menard for violations
discovered in the postrace inspection after the Radisson 200 on
Aug. 16 at Pikes Peak International Raceway. The rear wings of both
Team Menard cars were found to be in violation of technical
specifications, IRL officials said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Team Menard was fined $25,000 and 15 points were
deducted from each entrant point total. Tony Stewart and Robbie
Buhl also had 15 points deducted from each of their season driver
point totals.
</P>
<P>
   IRL at AMS
</P>
<P>
   A large group of small people will be cheering especially loudly
for Eddie Cheever Jr. and Robbie Unser, who drives for Team
Cheever, during Saturday's Atlanta Classic 500. Volunteers for CURE
Childhood Cancer are busy getting pledges for every lap Cheever and
Unser complete during the 208-lap race to raise money for CURE and
Georgia's children with cancer. To volunteer or make a pledge, call
770-986-0035. ... A.J. Foyt will be the Grand Marshal for the
inaugural Atlanta 500 Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Road Atlanta motorcycling IRL won't the the only racing game in
town this weekend. Road Atlanta will host the North American Sport
Bike World Cycle Fest Friday-Sunday. The event includes pro-am
racing in all classes, and Roadracing World Track Day on Friday
gives fans a chance to get an on-track experience. Ticket prices
are $10 Friday, $15 Saturday, $20 Sunday or $25 for a advance
weekend ticket. For more information, call 800-997-6272.
</P>
<P>
   Team Panoz
</P>
<P>
   Plagued by a crash and a questionable decision by officials, the
best the Panoz team could do was fourth place in Sunday's Six Hours
of the Glen at Watkins Glen, N.Y. A yellow flag went out
immediately after the No. 5 Panoz team of Raul Boesel, Eric Bernard
and Andy Wallace, running first in class and second overall at the
time, entered the pits. Officials held the Panoz team for 36
seconds once the pit stop was completed because they thought the
yellow flag came out before the car had entered the pits, closed
for the first lap of the caution period. Wallace lost almost a full
lap, and Panoz never was able to regain it. The No. 4 Panoz was
involved in a multicar accident on lap seven that took it out of
the race. Driver David Brabham was uninjured. The CanAm team of
Gianpiero Moretti of Italy, Didier Theys of Belgium and Mauro Baldi
of Monte Carlo won in a Ferrari 333SP and celebrated Moretti's
retirement in victory circle.
</P>
<P>
   New Sebring debuts
</P>
<P>
   The NAPA Auto Parts Sebring Classic Sept. 17-19 will inaugurate
the new and improved Sebring race course. Panoz Motor Sports,
leaseholder of Sebring, has made considerable improvements to the
historic track since it obtained the lease in January 1998. The
famous Sebring hairpin has been moved back slightly and modified
and a large section of the circuit has been repaved to smooth out
some of the bumps.
</P>
<P>
   NHRA
</P>
<P>
   Tom Martino of Farmingdale, N.J., claimed his first Pro Stock
win of the season Sunday, outrunning Mark Osborne in the final of
the 17th annual VisionAire NorthStar Nationals at Glendora, Calif.
Warren Johnson of Duluth lost to Osborne in the semifinals but
still increased his points lead. Johnson has 1,293 points, 339
ahead of Jeg Coughlin of Columbus, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
