<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-BOXER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN TIGHT CALIFORNIA RACE, THE TOP ISSUE IS CLINTON
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With a new poll showing their contest a virtual
dead-heat, Sen. Barbara Boxer and state Treasurer Matt Fong traded
jabs Wednesday over abortion, the death penalty and President
Clinton's relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Fong, a Republican, repeatedly sought to paint Boxer, the
Democratic incumbent, as a hypocrite for having been relatively
circumspect in her initial comments about accusations that Clinton
was involved with the former White House intern, while having
strongly criticized Republicans like former Sen. Bob Packwood and
Justice Clarence Thomas over allegations of sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barbara, your silence on this issue is deafening,'' Fong
declared at the beginning of the first face-to-face encounter of
their campaign, an hourlong debate at a television station here in
which the first three questions from a panel of journalists
involved the Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   It was the most pointed exchange so far in a race that national
political analysts are watching for signs of potential fallout from
the president's admission of the relationship last week.
</P>
<P>
   But Boxer, whose daughter, Nicole, is married to Hillary Rodham
Clinton's brother Tony, sought to blunt the attack, echoing her
comments after Clinton's speech last week by saying crisply: ``What
the president did was wrong,'' and adding, ``He should have stepped
forward sooner and taken responsibility.'' But, in what quickly
became a refrain, Boxer also asserted, ``We can stand under a cloud
and get nothing done, or we can do what we have to do for the
American people.''
</P>
<P>
   In the debate and exchanges with reporters afterward, Fong
himself repeatedly declined to answer whether Clinton should
resign, saying that as a potential member of the Senate, which
would hold any impeachment trial, he did not want to prejudge the
case. Boxer said that meant the two of them had the same position.
</P>
<P>
   Asked after the debate if she thought the president's behavior
constituted sexual harassment, Boxer said, ``That's a matter for
Monica Lewinsky to state.''
</P>
<P>
   Since she won office with 48 percent of the vote in 1992, Boxer
has reliably ranked as California's most liberal officeholder, this
in a state that has lately preferred moderates, and politicians
here have predicted for some time that she would face a close race
this year. In fact, Fong, who narrowly won the Republican
nomination after a divisive primary battle in June with Darrell
Issa, a millionaire businessman, is now within easy striking
distance, according to public opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   The latest Field Poll, released Wednesday, showed Boxer and Fong
running even, with each drawing the support of 45 percent of likely
voters.
</P>
<P>
   The survey of 625 likely voters, conducted over the last week,
had a margin of sampling error of four percentage points, and it
found that Boxer's support among women had been cut in half from
1992 levels.
</P>
<P>
   But in a brief news conference after the debate Wednesday, Boxer
attributed her standing in part to the fact that she had yet to
begin broadcasting television advertisements in her campaign, and
that, unlike her Democratic colleague, Sen. Dianne Feinstein, who
faced a closely fought contest in 1994, she had not been a presence
on the airways in a state in which politics sometimes seems to
exist only in paid commercials.
</P>
<P>
   In the debate, Boxer displayed the verbal fluency that has made
her among the most outspoken members of Congress but little of the
abrasive edge about which critics in both parties have sometimes
complained.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the soft-spoken Fong, a lawyer and former Air Force
officer who has been state treasurer since 1995, showed his
relative inexperience with several verbal missteps, once declaring
that Boxer was ``not soft on crime,'' only to catch himself, laugh
and say he had meant the reverse.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer, 57, sought to portray Fong, 44, as willing to ``unravel''
Roe vs. Wade, the Supreme Court decision upholding the right to
abortion. But Fong countered by noting that while he was an adopted
child proud that his birth mother ``chose life,'' he supported
abortion in the first trimester. He said he opposed taxpayer
financing for abortion, and favored requiring parental consent for
minors, and accused Boxer of trying to ``scare women.''
</P>
<P>
   In an exchange that pointed out how thoroughly both major
parties in California now support the death penalty, Boxer claimed
that she had voted 100 times in Congress to impose it, and balked
only at executing juvenile offenders. Fong answered the question by
saying that if anyone ever harmed his 15-year-old daughter, ``I'd
certainly want to break his neck,'' adding ``even including her
boyfriend.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked after the debate for a clarification, Fong said, ``I would
find it very difficult'' to apply the death penalty to juveniles,
but aides said that he would be willing to do so for at least 16-
and 17-year-olds.
</P>
</TEXT>
