<HEADLINE>
RILEY OUTLINES PLAN TO PREVENT SCHOOL VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KATHY GEORGE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Schools will get help in preventing deadly outbursts
from troubled students, such as in Springfield, Ore., under a plan
outlined Wednesday by U.S. Education Secretary Richard Riley.
</P>
<P>
   Riley was visiting Seattle and Tacoma for back-to-school pep
talks promoting business and community involvement in schools. Most
area schools start next week and Seattle starts Sept. 8.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with the Post-Intelligencer, Riley said students
need closer connections to adults, whether through a more trusting
atmosphere or smaller class sizes.
</P>
<P>
   He said a new set of ``early warning'' recommendations call for
each school to have a violence prevention plan and to have ``an
openness for young people to feel free to talk'' about their
troubles.
</P>
<P>
   The recommendations are part of an advisory guide to be mailed
to all school principals within a couple of days. They are to be
announced Thursday by President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The guide will recommend how to tell if a student is on the
verge of an outburst, how to quell that rage and how to react if a
student actually does unleash violence at a school.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton asked Riley to develop the guide in the wake of the
Springfield school shooting.
</P>
<P>
   On May 21, 15-year-old Kip Kinkel killed his parents at home,
then went to his high school and opened fire, killing two and
wounding two dozen others. He was known to be fascinated with guns
and bombs, and was suspended for bringing a gun to school the day
before the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the shooting, Riley told a safe schools
conference, ``We must commit ourselves to one very basic idea: that
every child in America in a school has a positive and caring
relationship with at least one adult. This simply has to be the new
standard we set for our nation's schools and communities.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, he said his plea is still urgent.
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of School Psychologists helped develop
the new guide.
</P>
<P>
   Riley said the intent is to help, not to label, children.
``We'll make that clear,'' he said, adding that all children may go
through phases of strange behavior that never lead to violence.
</P>
<P>
   Another tool for preventing violence is smaller classes, Riley
said.
</P>
<P>
   Riley recalled his surprise earlier this year when, at a meeting
with security officers from large urban schools, the officers told
him that smaller classes would do more than metal detectors or
anything else to quell violence.
</P>
<P>
   It makes sense, he said, because ``giving the teacher a chance
to have a personal interaction'' with students is crucial to
identifying who might explode into violence.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has asked Congress to spend $12 billion over the next
seven years to reduce class sizes around the nation. But the
pending proposal, unveiled in the president's State of the Union
address in February, is aimed at the 1st through 3rd grades because
of studies showing class size matters most in early learning.
</P>
<P>
   None of the school killings in recent years, such as in Moses
Lake, Wash., Edinboro, Pa., Jonesboro, Ark., West Paducah, Ky., and
Pearl, Miss., involved children in those early grades.
</P>
<P>
   Under Clinton's proposal, some federal money could be used to
reduce class sizes in upper grades, but only in states that have
money left over after achieving an average of 18 students in the
earliest grades.
</P>
<P>
   Washington state would get $180 million to train and hire an
additional 1,361 teachers, plus $236 million to build more schools.
Seattle alone would receive $32 million of that federal
construction money, said U.S. Education Department spokeswoman
Erica Lepping.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle's acting schools superintendent, Joseph Olchefske,
agreed that smaller classes could help diffuse violence.
</P>
<P>
   He said the new ``early warning'' guide will enhance Seattle's
efforts, already underway, to identify and help potentially violent
students. Those efforts include ``increasing the sophistication of
our security people,'' maintaining a ``zero tolerance'' policy for
weapons and violence, and improving adult relations with middle and
high school students, Olchefske said.
</P>
<P>
   What's still needed, said Seattle School Board president Barbara
Schaad-Lamphere, is a greater effort to keep guns out of the hands
of children.
</P>
<P>
   ``The laws are already in place. It's an enforcement issue,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   She and Olchefske said they are considering sending letters to
all middle and high school parents, asking them to lock up their
guns and to check periodically to make sure they remain locked.
</P>
<P>
   While in town Wednesday, Riley announced $8.5 million in federal
magnet grants for Seattle and Tacoma schools over the next three
years. Seattle will receive $1.2 million a year for a new
international school scheduled to open next year, an international
program at Sealth High School in West Seattle and a performing arts
program at Rainier Beach High School.
</P>
<P>
   Riley encouraged more business support for schools in a
breakfast speech to local business, community and education leaders
including Mayor Paul Schell and Police Chief Norm Stamper.
</P>
<P>
   He and U.S. Sen. Patty Murray also toured a Tacoma middle school
and spoke with parents, students and staff there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-26-98 2105EDT &QL; 
