<HEADLINE>
NFC WEST CAPSULES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
NFC WEST 
 
SAN FRANCISCO 49ERS 
1997: 13-3, 8-0 in NFC West 
Coach (record): Steve Mariucci (13-3) 
Stadium: 3Com Park at Candlestick Point (70,270) 
Ticket information: (415) 656-4900 
Pieces in place 
QB Steve Young (104.7 passer rating), RB Garrison Hearst (1,019
rushing yards), WR Jerry Rice, WR Terrell Owens (936 receiving
yards), WR J.J. Stokes (733 receiving yards), DT Bryant Young (4
sacks), LB Ken Norton, FS Merton Hanks, SS Tim McDonald. 
Key newcomers 
DT Brentson Buckner, CB Antonio Langham, LB Winfred Tubbs, DE Gabe
Wilkins, CB R.W. McQuarters, C Jeremy Newberry. 
Key losses 
DT Dana Stubblefield, CB Rod Woodson, FB William Floyd, K Gary
Anderson, LB Kevin Greene, TE Brent Jones, C Jesse Sapolu, DE
Marvin Washington. 
Missing piece 
At most positions, particularly linebacker, cornerback and
defensive end, the 49ers did a super job by replacing older
veterans with younger stars via free agency. Problems exist,
however, on the offensive line, especially at both tackle
positions. The club's best tackle, Kirk Scrafford, came out of
retirement, but he is not at full speed because of a neck injury.
Derrick Deese has been penciled in at right tackle, the side that
protects Steve Young's blind side. Deese started 13 games at left
tackle last season and allowed 4.5 sacks. That's not a bad number.
But more pressure will be on him in 1998, because one blind-side
hit on Young, 37, could lead to a career-ending concussion. The
left tackle is Jamie Brown, who started two games for Denver last
season. The middle of the 49ers' line is fine, but depth is a
concern after Newberry tore an anterior cruciate ligament during
minicamp. He is not expected back until November. 
Biggest test 
The 49ers have the 27th easiest schedule in the league. Part of the
reason is because the four other clubs in the NFC West combined to
go 14 games under .500 last year. No one will know how good this
club is until Nov. 1, when the 49ers play Green Bay at Lambeau
Field. 
Watch out for 
How Rice cooks. Jerry Rice, the soon-to-be Hall of Famer, has been
working maniacally to get back to 100 percent after two serious
knee injuries. After missing 14 games last season, he is expected
to begin the season in his customary starting role. But how
effective will he be? And with the development of Terrell Owens and
J.J. Stokes, will he be angry if Young does not get him the ball 90
to 100 times in 1998? 
Milestones 
Young needs four rushing touchdowns to break Jack Kemp's NFL record
of 40 career rushing touchdowns by a quarterback. 
Overview 
Considering they lost their last games played against Tampa Bay and
Green Bay, the 49ers are the third-best team in the conference. But
because the rest of the conference is mediocre and the Buccaneers
and Packers play in the same division, the 49ers should be a lock
to reach the NFC Championship Game for the fifth time this decade.
They'll need a surprising performance from Hearst and an
injury-free season from Young. And that might not be enough to beat
the Packers or Buccaneers for a berth in the Super Bowl. 
Prediction: 13-3 
 
STARTING LINEUP 
Offense 
QB Steve Young 
RB Garrison Hearst 
FB Marc Edwards 
WR Jerry Rice 
WR Terrell Owens 
TE Greg Clark 
LT Jamie Brown 
LG Ray Brown 
C Chris Dalman 
RG Kevin Gogan 
RT Derrick Deese 
 
Defense 
RE Gabe Wilkins 
RT Junior Bryant 
LT Bryant Young 
LE Roy Barker 
MLB Winfred Tubbs 
OLB Ken Norton Jr. 
OLB Lee Woodall 
CB Antonio Langham 
CB Marquez Pope 
SS Tim McDonald 
FS Merton Hanks 
 
Specialists 
KR Chuck Levy 
PR R.W. McQuarters 
K John Becksvoort 
P Tommy Thompson 
 
CAROLINA PANTHERS 
1997: 7-9, 4-4 in NFC West 
Coach (record): Dom Capers (26-22) 
Stadium: Ericsson Stadium (73,248) 
Ticket information: (704) 358-7800 
Pieces in place 
RB Fred Lane (7 rushing TDs), TE Wesley Walls (746 receiving
yards), CB Eric Davis (5 interceptions), KR Michael Bates (27.3
yards per kickoff return), ILB Micheal Barrow (8.5 sacks). 
Key newcomers 
S Brent Alexander, ILB Jeff Brady, CB Doug Evans, FB William Floyd,
DE Sean Gilbert, OLB Kevin Greene, RG Corbin Lucina, DE Jason
Peter. 
Key losses 
SS Chad Cota, NT Greg Kragen, LB Sam Mills, WR Ernie Mills. 
Missing piece 
The Panthers have a new offensive coordinator, former Green Bay
wide receivers coach Gil Haskell, who plans to implement a form of
the original Bill Walsh-type offense. But the quarterback in
Carolina is Kerry Collins, not Brett Favre or Joe Montana. After
being selected to the Pro Bowl in 1996, Collins had a league-low
55.7 passer rating and a league-high 21 interceptions in 1997. An
off-field racial incident and a broken jaw led to the subpar
results. Collins also didn't see eye-to-eye with Joe Pendry, the
unimaginative offensive coordinator whom Haskell replaced. The
bottom line is this: Collins must regain the form that led the
Panthers to the 1996 NFC Championship Game. 
Biggest test 
The Panthers open the season against division rivals Atlanta and
New Orleans. They get a bye before playing host to Green Bay on
Sept. 27. If they can get off to a quick start, maybe they go into
the Packers game with enough confidence at least to stay close or
perhaps to pull off the upset. 
Watch out for 
Capers was given more responsibility for personnel when GM Bill
Polian accepted a job to become president of the Indianapolis Colts
two days after the 1997 season. After the disappointing season,
Capers signed five free agents who will probably start on the
Panthers' defense, including Greene, Gilbert and Evans. The
Panthers are weak at both safety positions, but the rest of the
defense, which ranked 15th last season, is good enough to win games
by itself. 
Milestones 
Michael Bates was the first player to lead the league in
kickoff-return average in consecutive seasons since 1962-1963. No
player has led the league in that category in three consecutive
seasons. 
Overview 
Everything must fall right for the Panthers to have a shot at the
playoffs. And even then, with nondivision games against the likes
of Green Bay, Dallas, Tampa Bay, Miami and Washington, improvement
might not guarantee a much better record than last season. 
Prediction: 8-8 
 
Puzzle piece 
Sean Gilbert 
 
