NEW ORLEANS SAINTS 
997 record 
6-10, 1-7 in NFC West 
Coach (record): Mike Ditka (6-10 with Saints, 112-72 overall) 
Stadium: Louisiana Superdome (69,028) 
Ticket information: (504) 731-1700 
Pieces in place 
OT William Roaf, WR Andre Hastings (5 receiving TDs), DE Joe
Johnson (8.5 sacks), DT Wayne Martin (10.5 sacks), LB Mark Fields
(8 sacks), FS Sammy Knight (5 interceptions). 
Key newcomers 
SS Chad Cota, WR Sean Dawkins, CB Tyrone Drakeford, WR Qadry
Ismail, LB Andre Royal, RB Lamar Smith, OT Kyle Turley, TE Cameron
Cleeland. 
Key losses 
CB Eric Allen, RB Mario Bates, DE Darren Mickell, LB Winfred Tubbs,
TE Irv Smith. 
Missing piece 
The Saints were last in total yards and total points scored last
season. They signed Dawkins from Indianapolis and Smith from
Seattle in free agency. Both will start, but no one should expect a
miraculous turnaround for the Saints' offense. Dawkins had six
touchdown receptions in his past three years with the Colts. Smith
had four starts in four seasons with the Seahawks. The Saints made
a few switches on the offense line and drafted San Diego State's
Turley, who has been handed the left-tackle spot. But this is
basically the same unit that allowed 50 sacks last season. Even if
the runners run, the blockers block and the receivers catch, the
quarterback is Billy Joe Hobert. He's better than the other
quarterbacks who started for the Saints last season: Heath Shuler
and Danny Wuerffel. Hobert has 16 touchdowns and 19 interceptions
in four seasons in the NFL. He is 2-7 as a starter after leading
the Saints to a 2-2 record at season's end. 
Biggest test 
The Saints have one of the easiest schedules (tie for 25th) in the
league. There is, however, a stretch of three games when they play
the New England, San Francisco and Tampa Bay from Oct. 4 to Oct.
25. 
Watch out for 
Mike Ditka. Players seem to like his fiery personality, though it
led to a rift with Allen, who was traded to Oakland. Because
quarterback is the main concern, it is up to Ditka to pick his
starter and stick with him through thick, thin and game-killing
interceptions. The Saints started four quarterbacks last season. 
Milestones 
Martin has started a club-record 112 consecutive games. 
Overview 
There are too many questions at quarterback and on the offensive
line for the Saints to be considered even an average football team.
Even the defense, ranked fourth last season, took a couple of hits
in the off-season. If the Saints match their six-victory 1997
season it will be a surprise. 
Prediction: 5-11 
 
