ST. LOUIS RAMS 
1997: 5-11, 3-5 in NFC West 
Coach (record): Dick Vermeil (5-11 with Rams, 59-58 overall) 
Stadium: Trans World Dome (66,000) 
Ticket information: (314) 982-7267 
Pieces in place 
WR Isaac Bruce (815 receiving yards), RB Amp Lee (61 receptions),
LT Orlando Pace, FB Craig Heyward, CB Ryan McNeil (9
interceptions), FS Keith Lyle (8 interceptions). 
Key newcomers 
LB Eric Hill, DT Joe Phillips, DE Grant Wistrom, RB Robert
Holcombe. 
Key losses 
DT Bill Johnson, DE Leslie O'Neal, WR Torrance Small. 
Missing piece 
This is a make-or-break season for QB Tony Banks, who is in the
final year of a three-year contract. Despite his arm strength and
mobility, the former Michigan State star has not progressed as
hoped. His passer rating in two seasons is 71.5. He has only one
more touchdown pass (29) than interception (28). And he has fumbled
36 times. The Rams hope Banks can repeat the last half of the 1997
season, when he had a passer rating of 82 with nine touchdown
passes and six interceptions. He'll at least expect to have his
main weapon healthy in 1998. Bruce, who led the league with 1,338
yards receiving in 1997, missed five games with a hamstring injury
in 1997. Should third-year man Eddie Kennison can regain the form
in which he posted 924 yards and 11 touchdowns as a rookie, Banks
will be clean out of excuses if the Rams fail to improve on a
scoring offense that was tied for 23rd last season. 
Biggest test 
If the Rams have any chance of making the playoffs, they'll have to
endure a killer schedule in which they close with three of their
final four games on the road against Philadelphia, Carolina and San
Francisco. The home game sandwiched in between is, gulp, New
England. 
Watch out for 
The defensive secondary. The unit produces high-risk, high-reward
excitement. Paced McNeil, who led the league in interceptions, and
Lyle, the Rams tied for second with 25 interceptions. But the group
also played a big part in the 26 passing touchdowns allowed,
fourth-highest total in the league. The secondary basically
remained intact, although SS Toby Wright missed a great deal of
summer workouts because of knee surgery. What this unit needs is
more of a consistent pass rush from the front four. But it is hard
to see where they improved. Its best lineman, Bill Johnson, took a
free-agent contract with Philadelphia, and Vermeil released Leslie
O'Neal. So, the Rams will put their hopes on free-agent veterans
Ray Agnew and Phillips, and rookie Wistrom. Only time will tell
whether they can force quarterbacks to throw more errant throws in
1998. 
Milestones 
Bruce has three career 200-yard receiving games, one fewer than
Jerry Rice, and two fewer than the career leader in that category,
Lance Alworth. 
Overview 
The Rams have not had a winning season since reaching the NFC
Championship Game in 1989. That's eight consecutive seasons. There
are too many holes on this roster to avoid consecutive losing
season No. 9. 
Prediction: 4-12 
 
Puzzle piece 
Grant Wistrom 
 
