<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-FLOODS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVERFLOWING RIO GRANDE SURGES THROUGH LAREDO 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEL RIO, Texas _ While residents of this water-logged border
town struggled Wednesday to clear the mud and debris from Monday's
flash flooding and President Clinton declared the area a federal
disaster area, the balloon of water that caused the trouble was
rolling down the Rio Grande through Laredo.
</P>
<P>
   The Rio Grande, normally about 50 feet wide at Laredo, sluggish
and shallow enough to walk across, was a 100-yard wide
chocolate-colored surge early Wednesday evening, oozing across the
low-lying parklands, inching up the bridge pillars and carrying
past a surreal array of flotsam: telephone poles, huge tangles of
mesquite trees, lampposts, sagebrush, dead animals and a garbage
dumpster.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an unbelievable flood,'' said Laredo Mayor Betty Flores
while watching the water from the roof of a riverside shopping
mall.
</P>
<P>
   Laredo Fire Capt. Louis Sosa said late Wednesday afternoon:
``The river is 26.5 feet above normal under the downtown Laredo
bridges right now. We're expecting 5 or 6 feet of rise over the
next 6 hours.'' That is several feet lower than earlier predictions
and would leave the river below the lowest of the three brides.
</P>
<P>
   All three of the international bridges in Laredo had been closed
in anticipation of the surge. The blocks nearest the river were
cordoned off by police, most downtown businesses were closed and
residents near the river were advised to evacuate. Although about
2,000 people live in the areas that Laredo officials wanted
evacuated, the officials said only about 600 residents left their
homes.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, dozens of people gathered along both banks of the Rio
Grande to watch the spectacle in a carnival-like atmosphere.
Federal officials kept spectators far from the river's banks, but
in Nuevo Laredo, on the Mexican side, onlookers were standing right
alongside the river, sometimes three or four deep.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are just flood-watchers,'' Ms. Flores said.
``The most difficult part is convincing people of the danger, not
only from water and debris but from wild animals running from it.
I've heard lots of reports of snakes seen heading for high
ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the floods had crippled Del Rio's water system,
probably for days, Laredo had responded to a similar flood in 1954
by relocating its water system on high ground, so the water in the
city of 180,000 residents continued to flow. Nuevo Laredo's 600,000
residents, however, were without potable water this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush toured Del Rio on Wednesday morning,
first taking a helicopter ride over the San Felipe Estates
neighborhood in south Del Rio, where most of the destruction
occurred, and later meeting with some of the 850 flood victims who
had spent Tuesday night on cots and foam mattresses in the Civic
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the residents had tried to return to their homes on
Tuesday, but were forced back into the shelter when another
rainstorm threatened further flooding. Some creeks in the area did
overflow their banks again, emergency officials said, but there
were no reports of fresh damage.
</P>
<P>
   By Wednesday, many residents were making their way back home
again, although some returned to find an orange ``X'' on their
front door, declaring the structure uninhabitable and scheduled to
be torn down.
</P>
<P>
   Officials have confirmed 10 deaths from flooding in Del Rio and
directly across the border in Ciudad Acuna, Mexico, and an
additional six deaths elsewhere. Scores of residents remain
unaccounted for, emergency officials said, though most of them are
thought to be safe somewhere in shelters or with friends.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, with the water receding in Del Rio, a city of more
than 30,000 people, searchers were pushing through the newly
uncovered debris to look for bodies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was witnessing a terrible offense of nature,''
Bush told reporters after his tour.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 17 inches of rain had fallen on Del Rio and surrounding
Val Verde County on Sunday and in the early hours of Monday,
choking all of the creeks and arroyos and eventually causing a
five-foot wall of water to rush down San Felipe Creek into Del
Rio's poorest neighborhood, damaging more than 300 homes.
</P>
<P>
   The floodwaters moved downriver into Eagle Pass on Tuesday,
flooding some of that city's streets but causing no injuries. Just
beyond Laredo is Lake Falcon, which officials believe will swallow
up much of the floodwaters.
</P>
<P>
   The storm that caused the problems _ the remnants of Tropical
Storm Charley _ finally broke into pieces early Wednesday and
scattered.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the nervousness of city officials in Laredo, the streets
along the river remained festive as the water slowly rose through
the afternoon. A man in an ultralight flew over the crowds, waving
happily.
</P>
<P>
   Flora Torres, 43, whose house is about 50 yards from the river,
leaned against the fence in her yard and watched the scene. ``I
don't expect anything special to happen,'' she said. ``Around here,
it never does.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
