<HEADLINE>
AFC EAST CAPSULES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
AFC EAST 
NEW ENGLAND PATRIOTS 
1997: 10-6, 7-1 in AFC East 
Coach (record): Pete Carroll (10-6 with Patriots, 16-16 overall) 
Stadium: Foxboro (60,292) 
Ticket information: (617) 931-2222 
Pieces in place 
QB Drew Bledsoe (3,706 passing yards), TE Ben Coates (8 receiving
TDs), WR Terry Glenn (431 receiving yards), LB Chris Slade (9
sacks), FS Willie Clay (6 interceptions). 
Key newcomers 
FB Tony Carter, RB Robert Edwards, CB/S Tebucky Jones. 
Key losses 
RB Curtis Martin, FB Keith Byars, FB Sam Gash, CB Jimmy Hitchcock. 
Missing piece 
The Patriots lost three quality running backs, including Martin,
who rushed for 3,799 yards in three years with the Patriots. And
so, if there is anything to stop this club from winning its second
AFC crown in three years, it is at running back. The club drafted
Georgia's Edwards in April, but he had a run of nagging injuries in
college and his durability is a big question. Sedric Shaw, his
likely backup, is in his second season from Iowa and has not
touched the football in the regular season. The fullback is Carter,
who started 32 games in four seasons with Chicago. Carter is a nice
receiving threat with 106 career receptions. Carter, Edwards, and
Shaw, though, are a major step down from the Patriots' 1997 attack
of Byars, Gash and Martin. 
Biggest test 
The Patriots went 0-3 against Denver and Pittsburgh last season and
are 2-17 vs. both clubs since 1984. They open the season in Denver
on /{Monday Night Football/ and are at Pittsburgh on Dec. 6. 
Watch out for 
Whether he succeeds or flops, rookie Jones has a chance to make a
big impact. Jones, a former running back from Syracuse, played
safety in his only season on defense. But Carroll thinks Jones is
athletic enough to play cornerback in the Patriots' bump-and-run
scheme. If Jones can't handle cornerback, he'll learn the ropes at
safety behind Clay and Lawyer Milloy. Meanwhile, that would force
the club to play the injury-prone Steve Israel at cornerback
opposite Ty Law. Israel has one career interception in six NFL
seasons. And Carroll knows he needs a better playmaker at the
position to replace Hitchcock, who had four interceptions in two
seasons for the Patriots. 
Milestones 
Among active quarterbacks, Bledsoe's career average of 241.4
passing yards per game ranks third behind Warren Moon (243.4) and
Dan Marino (257.7) 
Overview 
The Patriots' running backs situation may cost them a game or two.
But this club has as much talent as any in the AFC. The key, then,
is Bledsoe. He has put up monster numbers in six NFL seasons. The
good news for the Patriots is that quarterbacks such as John Elway
and Jim Kelly have led weaker teams to the Super Bowl. The bad news
is that Bledsoe, at least as far as mental toughness, has not
proved to be Elway or Kelly. 
Prediction: 11-5 
 
Puzzle piece 
Robert Edwards 
 
