P Tom Tupa 
 
NEW YORK JETS 
1997: 9-7, 2-6 in AFC East 
Coach (record): Bill Parcells (9-7 with Jets, 118-88-1 overall) 
Stadium: Giants Stadium (77,716) 
Ticket information: (516) 560-8200 
Pieces in place 
WR Keyshawn Johnson (963 receiving yards), CB Aaron Glenn (1997 Pro
Bowl), LB Marvin Jones, WR Wayne Chrebet (799 receiving yards), QB
Glenn Foley (86.5 passer rating). 
Key newcomers 
RB Curtis Martin, OG Todd Burger, FB Keith Byars, C Kevin Mawae, DE
Anthony Pleasant. 
Key losses 
LB Marvin Jones, TE John Burke, C Roger Duffy, DE Hugh Douglas, WR
Jeff Graham, RB Adrian Murrell, G William Roberts, OT David
Williams. 
Missing piece 
Despite the presence of high profile wide receiver Johnson, the
Jets are without a deep threat. Johnson has one 100-yard game in
his career, and he had no receptions of at least 40 yards last
season. Parcells is hoping this proves to be a breakout year for
the mouthy Johnson, who has not lived up to being the No. 1 pick in
the 1996 draft. Johnson's progress is key to the development of
Foley, who was all but given the job when the team decided not to
re-sign Neil O'Donnell. If Foley falters, however, Parcells will
have no problem going to veteran Vinny Testaverde. Either
quarterback will have slim pickings at wide receiver. There is a
dropoff after Johnson, with the overachieving Chrebet (10 career
TDs) expected to win Graham's old job. The backups are Alex Van
Dyke and Dedric Ward. 
Biggest test 
The Jets play their first /{Monday Night Football/ game in six
seasons when they travel to New England on Oct. 19. If things fall
right, the Jets could be 3-2 or 4-1 at that point. 
Watch out for 
Despite Glenn's presence, the Jets' pass defense has real problems.
The defensive front four combined for a paltry 13.5 sacks in 1997.
The cornerback opposite Glenn, Otis Smith, was burned for nine
touchdowns. Smith did collect six interceptions and returned three
for touchdowns. But the Jets must be more consistent with their
pass rush or the secondary could be in for an even longer 1998. The
club signed Pleasant from the Atlanta Falcons and is expecting him
to start. But the line is so weak that Parcells might employ a
three-man front to take advantage of the club's biggest strength,
linebacker. 
Milestones 
To mark the 30th anniversary of their Super Bowl IV upset victory
over the Baltimore Colts, the Jets will wear jerseys like the ones
Joe Namath and company wore during the 1968 season. The apparel
includes white helmets. 
Overview 
The Jets will get more consistency from the quarterback position,
and that alone will lead to one or two more victories. With that,
Parcells and company should be in the playoff hunt down to the last
week, and, if things fall right, they could make their first
playoff appearance since 1991. 
Prediction: 9-7 
