MIAMI DOLPHINS 
1997: 9-7, 4-4 in AFC East 
Coach (record): Jimmy Johnson (17-15 with Dolphins, 61-51 overall) 
Stadium: Pro Player Stadium (75,192) 
Ticket information: (800) 255-3094 
Pieces in place 
QB Dan Marino (3,780 passing yards), RB Karim Abdul-Jabbar (16
TDs), WR O.J. McDuffie (943 receiving yards), MLB Zach Thomas (129
tackles), LB Derrick Rodgers (5 sacks), CB Terrell Buckley (4
interceptions). 
Key newcomers 
FS Brock Marion, G Kevin Donnalley, RB John Avery, DE Kenny Mixon,
LB Robert Jones. 
Key losses 
G Everett McIver, FB Roosevelt Potts, S George Teague. 
Missing piece 
With the Cowboys, he had Charles Haley. With the Dolphins, he has,
well, never mind. Johnson's club lacks a dominant pass rusher. In
the off-season he threw a lot of money at John Randle, Sean Gilbert
and Chester McGlockton, but each chose other clubs. So, Johnson
drafted Louisiana State's Kenny Mixon and penciled him in as the
starter at left defensive end. Fourth-round pick Lorenzo Bromell
has also shown flashes this summer and could earn a starting role
if Mixon falters. Nevertheless, one will join Jason Taylor, Daryl
Gardener and Tim Bowens. This fearsome threesome combined for 11.5
sacks in 1997. Unless one of these guys has a career year, the
Dolphins will have serious problems rushing the passer without
blitzing. 
Biggest test 
It is imperative that the Dolphins come out of training camp strong
because they play eight of their first nine games against AFC
opponents, including six division rivals. Any major slips could
push the Dolphins well out of playoff contention by mid-November. 
Watch out for 
How much does Marino have left? Will new offensive coordinator
Kippy Brown make much of a difference? There are a lot of questions
surrounding the Dolphins' offense. But this much is certain: They
will be a more physical unit in 1998. Johnson intends to reduce the
amount Marino uses audibles. The Miami offensive linemen won't have
such a mental burden right before the snap, which should allow them
to be more physical. And whoever starts the season at running back,
Abdul-Jabbar or No. 1 pick Avery, should have more holes to run
through. Early on, look for Johnson to go to a running back by
committee. 
Milestones 
Marino needs 15 passing touchdowns to reach 400. 
Overview 
The Dolphins have enough talent to be competitive in the
ever-improving AFC East and should sneak through for at least a
wild-card playoff berth. But Johnson is a few players away from
getting this team to the elite level. 
Prediction: 9-7 
 
