BUFFALO BILLS 
1997: 6-10, 5-3 in AFC East 
Coach, record: Wade Phillips (first season with Bills, 16-16
overall) 
Stadium: Rich Stadium (80,091) 
Ticket information: (716) 649-0015 
Pieces in place 
WR Andre Reed (880 receiving yards), RB Antowain Smith (840 rushing
yards), DE Bruce Smith (14 sacks), DT Ted Washington (4 sacks), SS
Henry Jones. 
Key newcomers 
QB Rob Johnson, G Joe Panos, WR Kevin Williams, FB Sam Gash. 
Key losses 
LB Chris Spielman, CB Jeff Burris, T Corbin Lacina, LB Mark Maddox,
LB Bryce Paup, WR Steve Tasker. 
Missing piece 
The Bills gave up a No. 1 pick to Jacksonville to get Johnson. In
his only start, he was 20-of-24 for 294 yards and two touchdowns in
a 28-27 victory last season. Bills management is hoping that game
was a sign of things to come, not a fluke. Even if Johnson is as
good as his one shining moment, it will take a lot more to right
the wrongs of an offense that was 25th in total yards and 29th in
scoring, and led the AFC in turnovers by a wide margin. The main
problem is on the offensive line, which allowed 46 sacks and
numerous hurries and knockdown. To upgrade, Bills management signed
Panos, who'll play on the right side. The left guard is set with
Pro Bowler Ruben Brown. And the center is Dusty Zeigler, who has
lots of potential. But the club needs help at both tackle
positions. 
Biggest test 
The Bills have one of the weakest schedules in the league (tied for
27th). No one will know how good they really are until an Oct. 4
game against San Francisco and an Oct. 18 game against
Jacksonville. 
Watch out for 
Bruce Smith. The Bills' defensive end is 35. His performance has
really dropped off in the second half of the past two seasons. In
1996, he had two sacks in his last five games. He had one sack in
his last five games in 1997. The club is switching to the 4-3
defense, which should take advantage of the strong defensive line,
where players such as Smith, Phil Hansen, Sean Moran and Washington
will be counted on to make more plays. Smith is a future Hall of
Famer, Hansen had 122 tackles, 18 quarterback pressures and six
sacks last year, and Washington earned his first Pro Bowl berth
last season. 
Milestones 
Reed and Jerry Rice are the only players in NFL history with at
least 50 receptions in 11 consecutive seasons. 
Overview 
The Bills should be able to stay in the playoff race with their
weak schedule. But they will eventually be doomed by too many
problem areas on offense and too many aging stars on defense. 
Prediction: 7-9 
 
