A4076 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLOOD-DELRIO-COX     08-26 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOOD-DELRIO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gov. Bush tours Del Rio
 &HT;    By Dave Harmon
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ One day after federal officials flew over a
flood-ravaged neighborhood here, Gov. George W. Bush visited
Wednesday and announced _ after receiving word from the White House
midway through his tour _ that Del Rio has been approved for
federal disaster aid.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement means that hundreds of families whose homes and
businesses were badly damaged or destroyed in flooding spawned by
Tropical Storm Charley can begin applying for grants and loans to
rebuild.
</P>
<P>
   Bush arrived in Del Rio, a border city of 34,000 in southwest
Texas, around 8 a.m. He boarded one of the Blackhawk helicopters
used in the relief effort and surveyed the San Felipe neighborhood,
where some houses were washed away.
</P>
<P>
   By 10 a.m., the governor was wandering narrow aisles between
folding cots at a shelter where more than 900 residents spent
another night wondering where they will go from here and how they
will replace what they have lost. With each handshake, Bush heard
another heartbreaking story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm real sorry for you. We're going to try to get you help as
quick as possible,'' Bush told one family, whose members smiled at
him politely. When he realized they didn't speak English, he
switched to Spanish: ``Estoy muy triste por su familia,'' meaning,
``I'm very sad for your family.''
</P>
<P>
   After exchanging a smile and a handshake with Bush, Reynaldo
Baesa, 76, said he lost everything inside his house and his 1973
Chevrolet. Just talking about it brought Baesa to tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good that (Bush) visited us and talked to us, because we
need help, '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he was going to help us very quickly,'' said Delma
Rodriguez, who has been at the improvised shelter at the city's
civic center since she and her family evacuated their home early
Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Six people in Del Rio have been confirmed dead from the
flooding. As of Wednesday, 14 people were confirmed missing and the
whereabouts of more than 40 others could not be determined, said
Lt. Judy Altom, a spokeswoman with the Texas Department of Public
Safety. Altom said workers were going to specific houses trying to
locate people and had found 26 who previously had been unaccounted
for.
</P>
<P>
   The flood destroyed 300 homes and seriously damaged 100 others.
The state Health Department has shipped in 3,000 doses of tetanus
vaccine in anticipation of flood-related illness.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Robert Chavira said the city plans to restart its water
system by Friday afternoon, but he cautioned residents that the
water will not be potable right away because the lines were
contaminated during the flood.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives from the Federal Emergency Management Agency
toured the city on Tuesday, and halfway through Bush's visit
Wednesday, an aide handed him a cellular phone. On the other end,
President Clinton's chief of staff, Erskine Bowles, gave him the
news this city has waited all week to hear: Val Verde County has
been declared a federal disaster area.
</P>
<P>
   Residents can qualify for FEMA's disaster housing grant to help
rebuild homes and the individual and family grant program which
will help pay for damage to belongings, damages to cars, medical
expenses and funeral expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The Small Business Administration will offer loans to replace
and repair homes and businesses, said U.S. Rep. Henry Bonilla,
R-San Antonio, who accompanied Bush on the trip.
</P>
<P>
   The small business administration offers several disaster
low-interest loans to homeowners, renters and business-owners.
</P>
<P>
   The disaster declaration could be expanded to other counties,
and the scope of the aid could be widened after damage assessments
are completed, the White House said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really appreciate how quickly (the federal government)
responded to the request,'' Bush said. ``A lot of people are
suffering. My heart breaks for the families who went from nice
secure homes to no homes at all.'' Bush said, adding that the state
may send in mobile homes to house flood victims until they can
rebuild.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the state could have done more for Del Rio
immediately after the flood, Bush said ``it seems to me that
everything that could possibly be done is being done. We are making
progress, and that's what people need to know -- there is hope.''
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Pete Gallego, D-Alpine, whose district includes Del
Rio, also pledged his help.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will build a stronger, more alert, more aware Del Rio, to
prevent this from ever happening again,'' Gallego said.
</P>
<P>
   About 550 people in the hardest-hit part of town, along San
Felipe Creek, were evacuated for a second time in 48 hours when
rain brought a renewed threat of high water late Tuesday and early
Wednesday. The creek rose at least 2 feet, but no flooding
occurred, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   There is a 20 percent chance for more rain today in Del Rio and
Eagle Pass, with temperatures in the mid 90s under partly cloudy
skies, said Jeff Orrack, with the National Weather Service in New
Braunfels. Orrack said no rain is expected in Laredo today and
temperatures should heat up to about 100 with partly cloudy skies.
The Rio Grande is rising expected to crest at 35 feet by midnight
Wednesday. Residential flooding will occur at about 38 feet, Orrack
said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
