<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4077 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCENE-COX     08-26 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCENE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coast dwellers make the most of anxious wait
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, N.C. -- As Hurricane Bonnie inched its way Wednesday
toward this riverside town named for the first president of the
United States, accountant Sharon Brickhouse paid homage to the man
who could not tell a lie: She was busy making a buck.
</P>
<P>
   With her office downtown just 200 yards north of the Pamlico
River, which has a history of spilling its banks during major
storms, Brickhouse worked till about 1 p.m. Wednesday despite a
lingering hurricane warning. She was a rarity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The weather just wasn't bad enough not to work,'' said
Brickhouse.
</P>
<P>
   The day started with a mottled sky _ gray, white and blue in
spots, giving rise to the notion that nothing bad was afoot.
</P>
<P>
   That had changed by late afternoon, when feeder bands _ squalls
that radiate from the hurricane's eye like a pinwheel spinning
counter-clockwise _ swept over the area and inundated several of
the city's low spots.
</P>
<P>
   The storm stalled Wednesday afternoon, heightening the chance
for local flooding. Beaufort County officials reported some downed
trees and power lines attributed to a tornado that didn't stay on
the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Most businesses heeded warnings. On U.S. 17 five minutes from
downtown, the fast-food row of McDonald's, Long John Silvers,
Wendy's and KFC stayed closed Wednesday. Burger King opened briefly
for breakfast while Popeye's served as a general canteen, its
deep-fryers cranked up from 9:30 a.m. till midday.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown, which partially flooded two years ago during
hurricanes Fran and Bertha, was just as free of business. Shop
owners nearest the river piled sandbags at their doorsteps to keep
the Pamlico River out.
</P>
<P>
   Doris Dellinger wasn't one of them. She opened her pawn shop on
the north side of Main Street at 9 a.m., ``like normal.'' Instead
of sandbags at the entrance, a $3,000 black Peavey drum greeted
customers. In the back, 11 television sets were tuned to the
Weather Channel, where brilliant radar pictures fanned across the
screen like the plume of a peacock.
</P>
<P>
   Dellinger exuded nonchalance. ``I don't think it's going to be
as bad as they predicted,'' Dellinger said. She took comfort in
being on the high side, perhaps dryside, of Main. ``Usually, this
side of the street is better than the other,'' she said. ``People
on the other side need to be better prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   To break a day of boredom, 37-year-old Washington native Donny
Woolard window-shopped at Dellinger's.
</P>
<P>
   He greeted Bonnie with the shrug of a shoulder, the cockiness of
someone who's weathered hurricanes before.
</P>
<P>
   ``There ain't a whole lot to it,'' he said. ``If it hits, it
hits. There's not a whole lot you can do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Leggett owns Nicki's restaurant across the street. He
lives in an apartment above the restaurant and spent the night
there. Wedged between two buildings and 1-foot thick brick walls,
Leggett pronounced himself safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``During Fran and Bertha, this building was like a rock,''
Leggett said. Nicki's stayed open during Bonnie's late night
wake-up call, serving emergency crews from the city. ``You just sit
here and wait,'' said waiter Roger Meylane.
</P>
<P>
   In Wilmington, which caught the early, first wave of Bonnie, the
scene was a little more frantic.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Wiggins and his Siberian husky, Sam, sat in his white
pickup truck Wednesday as the sea water lapped over the front
wheels and pieces of driftwood knocked against the door. Wiggins
wanted to take one last look at his boat, Hammerhead, before
retreating inland from Hurricane Bonnie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen three go by so far, just out of control. Gone, just
floating,'' the Wrightsville Beach man said, wondering if his boat
would suffer the same fate. ``It's covered. It's insured. What
happens, happens.'' The few cars out on the road didn't bother to
stop for the red lights, not that many still worked. The winds blew
water in zigzag patterns down the slowly flooding roads.
</P>
<P>
   Across from the blocked drawbridge to fragile Wrightsville
Beach, Jay Lowe videotaped through the open window of his rented
red Chevy Cavalier, oblivious to the saltwater creeping up from the
other side.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe is a State Farm Insurance agent from Irving, Texas, but he
wasn't there to drum up business _ he's an amateur hurricane
chaser.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back home, I'm known as the hurricane man,'' said Lowe, who
flew into Newport News, Va., just before midnight Tuesday and drove
down to the find the storm's eye. ``I go to speak to the kids in
school about hurricanes, and they're always wanting video.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowe has chased eight hurricanes, and he always tries to call
his wife when he's in the eye. He's been in Wilmington so many
times he's even staked out a favorite phone booth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like deja vu,'' he said as the car rocked in the wind.
``I was just here two years ago with Bertha. Forty days later, I'm
down here with Fran in the same phone booth, calling her. And now,
here I am again. I just can't believe this.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's weird. Out of all the coastline we have in the United
States, I keep ending up in Wilmington.'' Mark Attar of Lucky Star
Chinese Restaurant in Wilmington, made 25 deliveries in the midst
of the storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crazy, huh?'' said Attar, as he ran a $25 sesame chicken order
up to the sixth floor of the Comfort Inn along I-40, where the
elevator wasn't working because there was no power. ``It's kind of
fun and crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   He received an $8 tip for the delivery.
</P>
<P>
   As he tried to leave the building, hungry guests besieged him
with orders as he shouted, ``No, no more deliveries today. It's too
dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-26-98 2116EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980826.0477 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4078 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-U.N.-RITTER-1STL     08-26 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-U.N.-RITTER-1STLD-WRITETHRU-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. WEAPONS INSPECTOR IN IRAQ RESIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Expands earlier story.)  (lb) 
 By JUDITH MILLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The senior U.S. weapons inspector in Iraq resigned Wednesday,
charging that the U.N. secretary-general, the Security Council and
the Clinton administration had stymied the inspectors on ``the
doorstep'' of uncovering Iraq's hidden weapons programs.
</P>
<P>
   The inspector, William Ritter, said in his resignation letter
that the failure to push aggressively ahead with the inspections
was ``a surrender to Iraqi leadership'' that made a ``farce'' of
the commission's efforts to prove that Iraq was concealing
chemical, biological and nuclear weapons programs.
</P>
<P>
   Ritter asserted that the lack of will stemmed from a policy
shift by the U.N. Security Council and the secretary-general that
was backed ``at least implicitly by the United States.'' He made
his resignation letter public in an effort to force the United
States and the United Nations to return to a tougher stance.
</P>
<P>
   The administration heatedly denied Ritter's conclusions, saying
it had faithfully backed the inspections in Iraq. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan declined to comment, as did Richard Butler, chairman of
the inspection team.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Ritter asserted that the administration had
been secretly trying since late last year to find a diplomatic
solution for its confrontation with Saddam Hussein and in doing so
had abandoned a policy _ in effect since the end of the Persian
Gulf war in 1991 _ to use sanctions and the threat of military
force to compel the Iraqi leader's cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   The administration has publicly backed the inspectors, who have
insisted on full and unfettered access to sites in Iraqi suspected
of being used to conceal weapons or the expertise needed to make
them. Twice in the last year the United States has threatened
military action against Iraq for obstructing the inspections, and
in February, U.S. warships were moved within striking distance.
</P>
<P>
   But last week, U.S. officials acknowledged that the United
States and Britain had privately urged Butler to stop trying to
hold surprise inspections of sites in Baghdad. The officials said
they wanted to avoid an open confrontation with Iraq after Hussein
said he would no longer cooperate with the inspections.
</P>
<P>
   ``The illusion of arms control is more dangerous than no arms
control at all,'' Ritter wrote Wednesday. ``What is being
propagated by the Security Council today is such an illusion, one
which in all good faith I cannot, and will not, be a party to.''
</P>
<P>
   Ritter, a former Marine intelligence officer, joined the
commission in September 1991, soon after its creation, and was
assigned to help the inspectors ferret out whether Iraq was hiding
information and material relating to its programs to build weapons
of mass destruction, and if so, how.
</P>
<P>
   The Iraqis moved to block many of the inspections led by him and
accused Ritter of being a U.S. intelligence officer, a charge
Washington emphatically denied.
</P>
<P>
   Ritter said that the ``beginning of a slow death'' for the
inspection team began in earnest last October after Iraq blocked
inspectors and provoked a crisis that led Clinton administration
officials to predict that military action would be necessary if
Iraq did not back down.
</P>
<P>
   Ritter said administration officials told the inspectors then
for the first time that ``there was not enough military power in
the region'' to provoke a confrontation with Iraq, even though the
inspectors had ``indisputable proof'' that the effort to hide
information relating to Iraq's weapons programs was ``run by the
presidency of Iraq and protected by the presidential security
forces.''
</P>
<P>
   The administration repeated its assessment in late November, he
said, warning the inspectors again not to conduct more inspections
aimed at revealing how Iraq was concealing the information.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In addition, Ritter said, administration officials told the
inspectors that military action over the Christmas holidays was
``domestically unsustainable,'' meaning it would be politically
unpopular.
</P>
<P>
   Ritter declined to discuss which administration officials gave
him and the other inspectors this guidance.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to defuse the crisis in February, Annan and Saddam
Hussein signed an agreement that allowed new rules governing the
inspections. Ritter said that while he and other inspection
officials were deeply worried about the agreement's impact, he
decided not to resign, but rather to test Iraq's willingness to
comply with the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   He was encouraged, he added, by the fact that the Security
Council warned Iraq of ``severest consequences'' if it blocked the
inspectors _ language that suggested the United States might carry
out military strikes on Iraq if Baghdad reneged on its word.
</P>
<P>
   Ritter, in fact, returned to lead a controversial inspection in
early March.
</P>
<P>
   But in June, Ritter said, the Clinton administration decided
that it would no longer support intrusive inspections solely for
the purpose of gaining access to sensitive sites, inspections that
Ritter characterized as critical to the inspectors' mission.
</P>
<P>
   In meetings with his U.S. counterparts at the State Department
and the Pentagon, he said, he sensed a lack of support for what he
called ``concealment inspections,'' and felt that such inspections
were becoming in the administration's view a ``political
liability.''
</P>
<P>
   In July the inspectors received what Ritter called ``two of the
best pieces of intelligence information we've had in a long time''
about Iraqi weapons activities. Ritter declined to disclose the
nature of the information. But he said he advised Butler, the
chairman of the inspection team, that the time had come to act, and
that Butler agreed.
</P>
<P>
   While Ritter refused to discuss the nature or target of the
inspections that he claimed the administration helped stop, he said
they were aimed at one of Saddam Hussein's principal secretaries,
Abed Hamid Mahmud, who he said is responsible for orchestrating
Iraq's effort to conceal information and material, and at the
Special Security Organization, which carries out Mahmud's orders.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Foley, the State Department spokesman, said Wednesday:
``Scott Ritter has done an admirable job under difficult, even
dangerous, circumstances. He has our respect for the substantial
contributions he has made to UNSCOM. We regret, therefore, that
Ritter decided to leave UNSCOM. He has been a key member of the
UNSCOM staff, particularly in his efforts to investigate the means
by which Iraq continues to conceal its prohibited weapons program.
We agree with Ritter that inspections should be continued, for this
work continues to be necessary to verify Iraqi disarmament.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
