<DOCNO> NYT19980826.0478 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4083 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MLK-COX     08-26 1165
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MLK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MLK slaying: Attorney general initiates probe of new allegations
 &HT;    By Arthur Brice
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno opened a limited investigation
Wednesday into the killing of the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. 30
years ago in Memphis.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department probe will look at two recent allegations
that indicate that James Earl Ray may have been involved in a
conspiracy or may not have been the triggerman.
</P>
<P>
   In March, former FBI agent Donald Wilson revealed two pieces of
paper with the name ``Raul'' written on them. Wilson said he
retrieved the papers from Ray's abandoned car in an Atlanta housing
project a week after the April 4, 1968, assassination. Ray, who
pleaded guilty in 1969 but recanted within days, maintained he had
been set up by a shadowy smuggler he only knew as ``Raoul.'' Ray
was serving a 99-year sentence when he died in April.
</P>
<P>
   The second part of the probe will focus on allegations made in
1993 by former Memphis cafe owner Loyd Jowers that a now-dead
Memphis produce dealer with mob ties to New Orleans paid him
$100,000 to hire an assassin to kill King.
</P>
<P>
   On the 30th anniversary of King's death in April, Coretta Scott
King and her four children asked President Clinton for a full
investigation that would include a truth and reconciliation
commission with power to offer immunity from prosecution in
exchange for testimony. Clinton referred the matter to Reno, who
had been in discussions with the Kings for a couple of months over
the scope of the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Saying this is ``a first step toward revealing the truth,'' the
King family accepted the attorney general's decision when she
informed them of it in a brief telephone call Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly would have hoped that the truth and
reconciliation commission would have been granted,'' Mrs. King said
Wednesday evening. ``We feel, though, that this is an important
first step and will remain cautiously optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno decided not to use the FBI or its laboratory in the probe
because the King family and others have questioned the agency's
impartiality. Under the instigation of the late Director J. Edgar
Hoover, the FBI engaged in a widespread pattern of surveillance and
harassment of King.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it would be very suspect if they were involved,''
Dexter Scott King said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In a further move that would seem to signify Reno's desire to
avoid any appearance of improperiety, she assigned the case to be
investigated by the department's civil rights division instead of
the criminal unit.
</P>
<P>
   The probe will be headed by Barry Kowalski, who prosecuted the
federal case against the Los Angeles police officers who beat
motorist Rodney King.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Jowers nor Wilson knew Wednesday how much they will
cooperate in the investigation. Jowers has offered to testify if
granted immunity, but Memphis prosecutors have refused. It was not
known whether federal officials will make any such offers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure if he's going to voluntarily tell them anything
unless he obtains some type of immunity or promise not to
prosecute,'' said Jowers' attorney, Lewis Garrison.
</P>
<P>
   An investigation conducted by Memphis prosecutors this year
determined that Jowers was not involved in the assassination.
</P>
<P>
   Reached at his suburban Chicago home, Wilson said he had not
been contacted by Justice Department officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll wait to get official word from them about what they're
going to do before I decide what my response will be,'' said
Wilson, a 10-year FBI veteran whose first assignment was in Atlanta
in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   In March, the FBI dismissively referred to Wilson's evidence as
a ``fabrication'' and insisted he was not involved in the search of
Ray's 1965 white Ford Mustang.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now they want to be nice,'' said Wilson, who added that the
only way to find the truth is to empanel the commission the Kings
wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything short of that,'' he said, ``is a waste of taxpayers'
time and money.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno insists, though, that she will conduct a thorough and
unbiased probe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The evidence gathered during the inquiry will be followed
wherever it may lead,'' Reno said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department will consider whether any further action
might be needed and will issue a report when the investigation is
over.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will look at whatever information comes our way, but our
focus is on these two aspects,'' said Justice Department spokesman
Myron Marlin.
</P>
<P>
   There are those who question Reno's commitment. Circuit Judge
Arthur J. Hanes Jr. of Birmingham is one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Hanes and his late father, Arthur J. Hanes Sr., were Ray's first
lawyers in 1969, before he fired them in favor of Percy Foreman.
</P>
<P>
   Hanes said Wednesday he has evidence that he refused to
characterize but which he termed ``significant.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If the attorney general has any interest in what the truth is,
she can contact me,'' said Hanes, who maintains that Ray was
innocent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt in the fact that the evidence at the time was
such that there was a conspiracy and that he did not fire the shot
that killed Dr. King,'' Hanes said. ``The attorney general is
probably grandstanding to divert the focus of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Ray's brothers, Jerry Ray, also expressed little faith in
the probe Wednesday and called for the appointment of a special
prosecutor. The Justice Department considered that option but
decided to give the case to Kowalski.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't amount to anything,'' Jerry Ray said. ``It might turn
out worse because they'll come back and say everybody's lying and
this is the third or fourth time we've investigated, so let's put
an end to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The initial FBI probe in 1968 fingered Ray as the sole culprit.
An investigation by the House Select Committee on Assassinations
determined in 1979 that Ray was the gunman, though it's possible he
was involved in a conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   Ramsey Clark, the U.S. attorney general at the time of King's
murder, supported Reno's decision, though he says he's still
convinced that Ray acted alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't close investigations,'' he said. ``You just keep
looking. You do whatever's reasonable under the circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   The new probe also found support from one of Ray's lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm elated,'' said Memphis attorney Wayne Chastain.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings also expressed optimism, particularly because they're
not limiting themselves to this investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one avenue,'' Dexter King said. ``We still haven't
pursued other avenues. We are also considering complementary
alternatives, which may include civil litigation and/or
congressional intervention.''
</P>
<P>
   Garrison, Jowers' attorney, said his client is willing to
cooperate, especially since he's in failing health.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's agreed that if they want to sue him for the purpose of
history, he'd go along with it,'' Garrison said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
