<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS PICK UP ENFORCER, SIGN SEVERYN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Stars filled their void for an enforcer
yesterday, signing unrestricted free agent Brent Severyn to a
one-year contract paying $425,000.
</P>
<P>
   Severyn, 32, brings size (6-foot-2, 211 pounds) and a notable
zeal for fighting _ something the team will be able to use as they
move into the Pacific Division, where every team has stocked up
with an enforcer over the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not fighting so much as a physical presence. And every
team in our division has that,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said.
``These players know their role, and they have a sense of timing.
And Brent is a guy who I think can fit very well into our system.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars took their time looking for a tough guy throughout the
summer, general manager Bob Gainey said, because they wanted to do
research. Severyn is a former teammate of Stars forwards Mike Keane
and Brian Skrudland, and came highly recommended as a player who is
tough but is skilled enough to log eight to 10 minutes a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a terrific team person and a solid role player,''
Hitchcock said. ``Our philosophy is that if you're going to play
for us in October, we'd like you to be playing for us in May or
June. And we see that in Brent.''
</P>
<P>
   Severyn is not expected to contribute much in the scoring
department _ he has scored 37 points (nine goals, 28 assists) in
298 career games. But he has 775 career penalty minutes, including
133 in 37 games last season with the Mighty Ducks of Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   He might be best known by Stars fans for his two fights with
Darryl Sydor in the Ducks' bench-clearing brawl with the Stars on
March 13 _ where he was standing up for Ducks superstar Teemu
Selanne, who had been knocked out by Stars defenseman Craig Ludwig.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a heavyweight; I assure you of that,'' Sydor said. ``We
have a good, tough team, but he's a solid addition to our
toughness. He can throw them.''
</P>
<P>
   Severyn missed 32 games with a herniated disk in his neck Oct.
25-Jan. 1, but is recovered. He can play left wing, right wing or
defense, giving the Stars plenty of options on their fourth line. &QL; 
HULL CHOOSES NO. 22 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New Stars winger Brett Hull has chosen No. 22 for his sweater.
Hull had worn No. 16 his entire life, but said when signed by the
Stars on July 3 that he would not try to take that number away from
fellow veteran Pat Verbeek.
</P>
<P>
   No. 22, he said, has no special meaning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no one's birthday or not lucky or anything, it's just
what they had left over,'' Hull said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-26-98 2120EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980826.0480 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4085 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUTLER-CLINTON-COVENA     08-26 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUTLER-CLINTON-COVENANT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BURDEN OF SITUATIONAL ETHICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York Times
Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative CONNIE
WHITE in Kansas City at (800) 444-0267 or (816) 822-8448, or fax
her at (816) 822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 By DIANA BUTLER BASS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Not long ago, Bill Clinton promised a New Covenant. Envisioned
as a spiritual contract of compassion and prosperity, the president
pledged to make America a better place for all.
 &HT;    Oddly enough, and in spite of scandal, Bill Clinton fulfilled
his promise. In the six years of his presidency, the economy has
expanded, wealth increased, the budget balanced, creative social
programs launched, and welfare reformed.
 &HT;    Unbelievably, he did much of what he promised and what some
considered impossible -- he combined the economic shrewdness of
conservatism with the social passion of liberalism. He kept this
covenant with the American people.
 &HT;    However implicit, we had another covenant as well. After
candidate Clinton admitted causing ``pain in his marriage,'' we
forgave him and expected him to behave himself in the future.
 &HT;    But he broke this promise.
 &HT;    If not for Monica, Bill Clinton would go down in history as an
innovative -- if not great -- president.
 &HT;    In the midst of events, it is difficult to know how history will
judge anyone. If current attitudes, however, are any guide, future
generations will look back with ambiguity on this unseemly episode.
 &HT;    Excluding those who have always hated him, most of us feel
ambivalent about Clinton. We approve of how he has handled his job;
we disapprove of his character.
 &HT;    Until recently, we ignored his personal life, dismissing rumors
with pseudo-sophistication. ``Personal morality doesn't matter,''
became the mantra, ``Look at Kennedy, Eisenhower, even Thomas
Jefferson. They had mistresses. They were good presidents.''
 &HT;    True enough. Does sexual fidelity matter?
 &HT;    Asking the question is rather new. Traditionally, Americans
expected leaders to be good, faithful family men (back then, men).
Equally, however, people expected affairs to be discreet. One lover
-- maybe two -- in the past or kept out of public view.
 &HT;    Until Ronald Reagan, no president had been divorced -- even that
vaguely immoral. Americans assumed fidelity essential to
leadership.
 &HT;    Those assumptions grew from Victorian values where biblical
literalism reigned and ``polite'' society silenced talk about sex.
During this century, however, sexual ethics changed radically.
Sometimes for the worse, sometimes better, but generally toward
greater openness and compassion.
 &HT;    We may worry over our children's choices, or rue our mistakes,
but few of us prefer our great-grandparents' world when it comes to
sex.
 &HT;    It is not surprising that the question of fidelity and
leadership should arise during the nation's first baby-boom
presidency. After all, baby- boomers came of age in this new
climate. We imbibed sexual situational ethics -- where sexual
morality is determined by context. No rules; only informed personal
choice.
 &HT;    Given this potential chaos, it is surprising there exists any
agreement regarding sexuality. But there are generally accepted
guidelines: Partners should respect one another. Relationships
should be honest and responsible. People should postpone sex until
maturity. A faithful marriage is the ideal for sexual fulfillment.
 &HT;    Whether straight or gay, single, divorced or married, most
people think standards basic to healthy sexuality. As a culture, we
believe sexual expression rests on adult choice -- not fear of the
rules.
 &HT;    In a more rigid culture, Clinton might not have broken the
rules. Too risky. Or, as with Kennedy, he would not have been
caught because no one dared ask.
 &HT;    In our permissive society, however, no social taboo compelled
him to keep his pants zipped. And everyone -- including Ken Starr
-- is rude enough to ask.
 &HT;    Moreover, Clinton violated the code of sexual situation ethics.
Not that he had an affair -- or even an affair with a much younger
woman. Rather, he made bad choices. He broke his marriage covenant
for no good reason (did he love or was only using Monica?) in the
Oval Office (of all places!) and then lied about it to his wife,
God and everybody else on television.
 &HT;    The affair was stupid; the context made it even worse.
 &HT;    In an age of situational ethics, fidelity matters. In every
case, a person must be trusted to make good decisions, to judge
situations wisely and make choices equal to a particular demand.
 &HT;    When constrained by rules, fidelity is less important. People
are faithful because they must be and an individual's character
matters less. With no external pressure, however, character --
fidelity and trustworthiness included -- becomes crucial to
leadership. Expanded moral choice makes it harder to govern well.
 &HT;    Although we often deny it, public and private covenants are of a
piece. Personal morality grounds public behavior.
 &HT;    If honest, we know how hard it is to live in fidelity. Knowing
our failings, we forgive.
 &HT;    Rest assured, Bill, like Hillary, we'll forgive again. We know
you can keep promises. Nevertheless, the question nags: which ones?
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    c.1998 Diana Butler Bass
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Diana Butler Bass, Ph.D., writes a religion column for the
Santa Barbara News-Press and is associate professor of religious
studies at Rhodes College in Memphis, Tenn. Her latest book is
``Standing Against the Whirlwind: Evangelical Episcopalians in 19th
Century America,'' published by Oxford University Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-26-98 2121EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980826.0481 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4088 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUTLER-CLINTON-COVENA     08-26 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUTLER-CLINTON-COVENANT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BURDEN OF SITUATIONAL ETHICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York Times
Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative CONNIE
WHITE in Kansas City at (800) 444-0267 or (816) 822-8448, or fax
her at (816) 822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 By DIANA BUTLER BASS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Not long ago, Bill Clinton promised a New Covenant. Envisioned
as a spiritual contract of compassion and prosperity, the president
pledged to make America a better place for all.
 &HT;    Oddly enough, and in spite of scandal, Bill Clinton fulfilled
his promise. In the six years of his presidency, the economy has
expanded, wealth increased, the budget balanced, creative social
programs launched, and welfare reformed.
 &HT;    Unbelievably, he did much of what he promised and what some
considered impossible -- he combined the economic shrewdness of
conservatism with the social passion of liberalism. He kept this
covenant with the American people.
 &HT;    However implicit, we had another covenant as well. After
candidate Clinton admitted causing ``pain in his marriage,'' we
forgave him and expected him to behave himself in the future.
 &HT;    But he broke this promise.
 &HT;    If not for Monica, Bill Clinton would go down in history as an
innovative -- if not great -- president.
 &HT;    In the midst of events, it is difficult to know how history will
judge anyone. If current attitudes, however, are any guide, future
generations will look back with ambiguity on this unseemly episode.
 &HT;    Excluding those who have always hated him, most of us feel
ambivalent about Clinton. We approve of how he has handled his job;
we disapprove of his character.
 &HT;    Until recently, we ignored his personal life, dismissing rumors
with pseudo-sophistication. ``Personal morality doesn't matter,''
became the mantra, ``Look at Kennedy, Eisenhower, even Thomas
Jefferson. They had mistresses. They were good presidents.''
 &HT;    True enough. Does sexual fidelity matter?
 &HT;    Asking the question is rather new. Traditionally, Americans
expected leaders to be good, faithful family men (back then, men).
Equally, however, people expected affairs to be discreet. One lover
-- maybe two -- in the past or kept out of public view.
 &HT;    Until Ronald Reagan, no president had been divorced -- even that
vaguely immoral. Americans assumed fidelity essential to
leadership.
 &HT;    Those assumptions grew from Victorian values where biblical
literalism reigned and ``polite'' society silenced talk about sex.
During this century, however, sexual ethics changed radically.
Sometimes for the worse, sometimes better, but generally toward
greater openness and compassion.
 &HT;    We may worry over our children's choices, or rue our mistakes,
but few of us prefer our great-grandparents' world when it comes to
sex.
 &HT;    It is not surprising that the question of fidelity and
leadership should arise during the nation's first baby-boom
presidency. After all, baby- boomers came of age in this new
climate. We imbibed sexual situational ethics -- where sexual
morality is determined by context. No rules; only informed personal
choice.
 &HT;    Given this potential chaos, it is surprising there exists any
agreement regarding sexuality. But there are generally accepted
guidelines: Partners should respect one another. Relationships
should be honest and responsible. People should postpone sex until
maturity. A faithful marriage is the ideal for sexual fulfillment.
 &HT;    Whether straight or gay, single, divorced or married, most
people think standards basic to healthy sexuality. As a culture, we
believe sexual expression rests on adult choice -- not fear of the
rules.
 &HT;    In a more rigid culture, Clinton might not have broken the
rules. Too risky. Or, as with Kennedy, he would not have been
caught because no one dared ask.
 &HT;    In our permissive society, however, no social taboo compelled
him to keep his pants zipped. And everyone -- including Ken Starr
-- is rude enough to ask.
 &HT;    Moreover, Clinton violated the code of sexual situation ethics.
Not that he had an affair -- or even an affair with a much younger
woman. Rather, he made bad choices. He broke his marriage covenant
for no good reason (did he love or was only using Monica?) in the
Oval Office (of all places!) and then lied about it to his wife,
God and everybody else on television.
 &HT;    The affair was stupid; the context made it even worse.
 &HT;    In an age of situational ethics, fidelity matters. In every
case, a person must be trusted to make good decisions, to judge
situations wisely and make choices equal to a particular demand.
 &HT;    When constrained by rules, fidelity is less important. People
are faithful because they must be and an individual's character
matters less. With no external pressure, however, character --
fidelity and trustworthiness included -- becomes crucial to
leadership. Expanded moral choice makes it harder to govern well.
 &HT;    Although we often deny it, public and private covenants are of a
piece. Personal morality grounds public behavior.
 &HT;    If honest, we know how hard it is to live in fidelity. Knowing
our failings, we forgive.
 &HT;    Rest assured, Bill, like Hillary, we'll forgive again. We know
you can keep promises. Nevertheless, the question nags: which ones?
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    c.1998 Diana Butler Bass
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Diana Butler Bass, Ph.D., writes a religion column for the
Santa Barbara News-Press and is associate professor of religious
studies at Rhodes College in Memphis, Tenn. Her latest book is
``Standing Against the Whirlwind: Evangelical Episcopalians in 19th
Century America,'' published by Oxford University Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
