<HEADLINE>
AFC CENTRAL CAPSULES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
AFC CENTRAL 
PITTSBURGH STEELERS 
1997: 11-5, 6-2 in AFC Central 
Coach (record): Bill Cowher (64-32) 
Stadium: Three Rivers (58,600) 
Ticket information: (412) 321-0650 
Pieces in place 
QB Kordell Stewart (21 passing TDs, 11 rushing TDs), RB Jerome
Bettis (1,665 rushing yards), WR Charles Johnson (568 receiving
yards), FS Darren Perry (4 interceptions), SS Carnell Lake (6
sacks, 3 interceptions), LB Jason Gildon (4 1/2 sacks), LB Levon
Kirkland (5 sacks). 
Key newcomers 
C Roger Duffy, CB DeWayne Washington. 
Key losses 
OT John Jackson, G Tom Myslinski, WR Yancey Thigpen, CB Donnell
Woolford, LB Greg Lloyd. 
Missing piece 
The Steelers were hurt by free agency again in the off-season. But
the lumps were felt most in the club's receiving unit, where
Thigpen (79 receptions, 1,398 yards, seven TDs) signed a free-agent
contract with the Oilers. Too bad, because Stewart appears on the
verge of being a Pro Bowl quarterback. Now, he'll have to improve
on his first season as a starter with a group of untested veterans.
Replacing Thigpen will be Courtney Hawkins (45 receptions, 3 TDs)
and Will Blackwell, who caught 12 passes in an injury-plagued
rookie season. The veteran of the wide receivers is Stewart's best
friend, Charles Johnson. In 1996, when Thigpen was hurt, Johnson
had his best season with 60 receptions for 1,008 yards. The
Steelers would love it if Johnson can have that kind of performance
this season. 
Biggest test 
From late October until the end of the season, the Steelers, who
have the league's toughest schedule, will be in a war. Oct. 26 and
Nov. 9, they are on /{Monday Night Football/ against Kansas City
and Green Bay. They close with five of their final seven against
teams that reached the playoffs in 1997. 
Watch out for 
The thing that can separate the Steelers from a nice record of 11-5
and an outstanding record of 14-2 will be special teams. The club
did not block a punt, field goal or extra point last season, and
forced only two fumbles. In the final seven games, punter Josh
Miller had seven punts of 26 yards or less. Also, the punt-coverage
team allowed 11.8 yards per return, among the worst in the league.
If the Steelers don't shore up this unit, they could find
themselves on the wrong end of close games against mediocre teams. 
Milestones 
Lake was the first defensive back to lead his team in sacks since
it became an official statistic in 1982. 
Overview 
The Steelers return most of the key parts from their rushing
offense and defense, both of which ranked No. 1 in the NFL last
season. If Stewart continues to improve, the Steelers could make
their second Super Bowl appearance of the 1990s. 
Prediction: 12-4 
 
STARTING LINEUP 
Offense 
QB Kordell Stewart 
RB Jerome Bettis 
FB Jon Witman 
TE Mark Bruener 
WR Courtney Hawkins 
WR Charles Johnson 
LT Justin Strzelczyk 
LG Will Wolford 
C Dermontti Dawson 
RG Brenden Stai 
RT Jamain Stephens 
 
Defense 
RE Kevin Henry 
NT Joel Steed 
LE Nolan Harrison 
ILB Levon Kirkland 
ILB Earl Holmes 
OLB Jason Gildon 
OLB Mike Vrabel 
CB DeWayne Washington 
CB Carnell Lake 
FS Darren Perry 
SS Lethon Flowers 
 
Specialists 
KR Will Blackwell 
PR Jahine Arnold 
PK Norm Johnson 
P Josh Miller 
 
JACKSONVILLE JAGUARS 
1997: 11-5, 6-2 in AFC Central 
Coach (record): Tom Coughlin (24-24) 
Stadium: Alltel (73,000) 
Ticket information: (800) 618-8005 
Pieces in place 
QB Mark Brunell (18 passing TDs), WR Jimmy Smith (1,324 yards), WR
Keenan McCardell (1,164 yards), LT Tony Boselli, DE Tony Brackens
(7 sacks), CB Deon Figures (5 interceptions), K Mike Hollis (134
points). 
Key newcomers 
C Quentin Neujahr, LB Bryce Paup. 
Key losses 
S Dana Hall, FB Ty Hallock, RB Natrone Means, DE Clyde Simmons. 
Missing piece 
The Jaguars have a dominant passer, dominant wide receivers and a
huge offensive line. What they have never had is a dominant running
game. They'll need one if they are to make a serious Super Bowl
run. Means went back to San Diego, and Hallock is in Chicago. The
halfbacks competing for Means' job will be the Jaguars' No. 1 pick
this year, Fred Taylor, and their No. 1 pick in 1995, James
Stewart. A 1,000-yard season from one of these guys would give the
Jaguars one of the most dominating offenses around. But even that
figures to be a challenge as no Jaguars running back has rushed for
more than 823 yards in a season since the team began play in 1995. 
Biggest test 
Five of the Jaguars' last seven games are against teams that
reached the playoffs in 1997: Tampa Bay, Pittsburgh, Detroit,
Minnesota and Pittsburgh in the season finale on /{Monday Night
Football/. 
Watch out for 
The Jaguars signed Paup to pump life into a pass rush that was
already solid, netting 48 sacks last year, sixth-most in the
league. Paup had 9.5 sacks last year and has 65.5 in his career. He
should easily make up for the departure of Simmons, who was waived
in a salary-cap move last spring despite leading the Jaguars with
8.5 sacks. The Jaguars have questions at cornerback, with the likes
of Dave Thomas, Deon Figures and Aaron Beasley competing for a job.
All are coming off injuries in 1997. 
Milestones 
The Jaguars are the only expansion team to reach the playoffs in
two of its first three seasons. 
Overview 
The Jaguars have enough talent to reach the playoffs for a third
consecutive season. To get to the next level, this club needs to
get meaner. That means establishing the running game and stopping
the other guys from running the ball. They used the off-season to
shore up the running game on offense, but the defense against the
run remains suspect. They'll be able to hide this deficiency during
the regular season, but it'll catch up to them in the later rounds
of the AFC playoffs. 
Prediction: 10-6 
 
STARTING LINEUP 
Offense 
QB Mark Brunell 
RB Fred Taylor 
FB Daimon Shelton 
TE Pete Mitchell 
WR Jimmy Smith 
WR Keenan McCardell 
LT Tony Boselli 
LG Ben Coleman 
C Michael Cheever 
RG Brian DeMarco 
RT Leon Searcy 
 
