PR Reggie Barlow 
K Mike Hollis 
P Bryan Barker 
 
TENNESSEE OILERS 
1997: 8-8, 2-6 in AFC Central 
Coach (record): Jeff Fisher (24-30) 
Stadium: Vanderbilt Stadium (41,600) 
Ticket information: (888) 313-8326 
Pieces in place 
QB Steve McNair (2,665 yards), RB Eddie George (1,399 yards), DE
Kenny Holmes (7 sacks), C Mark Stepnoski, CB Darryll Lewis (5
interceptions), FS Marcus Robertson (5 interceptions). 
Key newcomers 
TE Jackie Harris, P Craig Hentrich, WR Yancey Thigpen, WR Kevin
Dyson, CB Samari Rolle. 
Key loss 
G Kevin Donnalley. 
Missing piece 
The Oilers were solid on defense last season, but they desperately
need playmakers, people who can sack the quarterback, force fumbles
and make interceptions. Only five clubs had fewer than the 35 sacks
Tennessee had in 1997, and the club's 14 interceptions were tied
for 19th. Because pressure on the quarterback usually causes
fumbles and interceptions, the Oilers are hoping for continued
improvement from Holmes, who led NFL rookies in 1997 with seven
sacks. DT Gary Walker also had seven sacks in 1997. But if CBs
Lewis and Denard Walker hold up, Fisher will probably blitz more,
utilizing the once-famous ``46'' defense to help the cause.  
Biggest test 
Four of the Oilers' first six games are against AFC Central
opponents. They end with eight clubs that were a combined 88-55 in
1997, including Pittsburgh, Jacksonville, Green Bay and Tampa Bay. 
Watch out for 
This is a make-or-break season for McNair. Already backed by a
George-led ground game that ranked No. 3 in 1997, McNair will have
an outstanding group of wide receivers to speed his development.
The club stole Thigpen (1,398 yards, 7 TDs) from Pittsburgh and
drafted Dyson in the first round. Some had Dyson the top-rated wide
receiver on the board, ahead of Randy Moss. With all this offensive
firepower, McNair must produce. In his first season as a starter,
McNair completed 52 percent of his passes with 14 touchdown passes,
13 interceptions and a quarterback rating of 70.4. He seemed to get
worse as the season went along, throwing four TD passes and six
interceptions in the final eight games. The Oilers are talented
enough offensively, and if McNair struggles and the playoffs are in
sight, don't be surprised if the club goes with 40-year-old Dave
Krieg late in the season. 
Milestones 
LG Bruce Matthews has played 165 consecutive games. 
Overview 
The Oilers have the talent to compete in most divisions. But the
AFC Central has two of the strongest teams in the AFC. Tennessee
will do well to reach the playoffs as a wild card, but it needs
McNair to play like the Oilers' brass think he is capable of
playing. 
Prediction: 9-7 
 
STARTING LINEUP 
Offense 
QB Steve McNair 
RB Eddie George 
FB Frank Wycheck 
WR Yancey Thigpen 
WR Kevin Dyson 
TE Jackie Harris 
LT Brad Hopkins 
LG Bruce Matthews 
C Mark Stepnoski 
RG Jason Layman 
RT Jon Runyan 
 
Defense 
RDE James Roberson 
RDT Henry Ford 
LDT Gary Walker 
LDE Kenny Holmes 
MLB Barron Wortham 
OLB Joe Bowden 
OLB Lonnie Marts 
CB Denard Walker 
CB Darryll Lewis 
SS Blaine Bishop 
FS Marcus Robertson 
 
Specialists 
KR Rodney Thomas 
PR Derrick Mason 
PK Al Del Greco 
P Craig Hentrich 
 
CINCINNATI BENGALS 
1997: 7-9, 3-5 in AFC Central 
Coach (record): Bruce Coslet, (14-11 with Bengals, 40-49 overall) 
Stadium: Cinergy Field (60,389) 
Ticket information: (513) 621-3550 
Pieces in place 
RB Corey Dillon (1,129 yards, 10 TDs), WR Darnay Scott (797 yards),
CB Ashley Ambrose (3 interceptions), CB Corey Sawyer (4
interceptions). 
Key newcomers 
DE Michael Bankston, QB Neil O'Donnell, CB Thomas Randolph, DE
Clyde Simmons, LB Takeo Spikes, LB Brian Simmons. 
Key losses 
DT Brentson Buckner, LB Andre Collins, QB Boomer Esiason, DT Dan
Wilkinson. 
Missing piece 
Jeff Blake went into training camp as the starter, and many in the
organization want to see him succeed the way he did from 1995-1996,
when he threw 52 touchdown passes. But he lost his starting job to
O'Donnell, whom the Bengals signed in the off-season. O'Donnell
locked up the starting position with a 15-18 performance in a 33-19
exhibition game victory against the Lions Saturday night. He needs
to provide that kind of leadership for the Bengals to contend. If
he fails, Blake could get another chance. 
Biggest test 
The Bengals have the third-toughest schedule in the league. Nine
games are against 1997 playoff teams. The club's home schedule
includes Super Bowl XXXII participants Denver and Green Bay. 
Watch out for 
Opponents walked all over the Bengals' 29th-ranked defense in 1997.
But things should change drastically in 1998. The club signed
run-stopping Bankston and pass-rushing Simmons. It drafted Simmons
and Spikes to upgrade the linebacking crew. These acquisitions
should greatly improve the front seven of the Bengals' 3-4 defense.
The fact that the club expects former New York Giants reserve
Randolph to start at cornerback shows how weak the Bengals are in
the secondary. But if the front seven can pressure the quarterback
in 1997, perhaps the secondary can play better. 
Milestones 
Lee Johnson, an 11-year veteran, has had punting averages of at
least 42 yards for eight consecutive seasons. 
Overview 
The Bengals have not had a winning season since 1990. An improved
offense and defense should make them respectable, and if O'Donnell
produces, and running back Corey Dillon plays like he did in 1997,
a winning season is not out of the question. 
Prediction: 6-10 
STARTING LINEUP 
Offense 
QB Neil O'Donnell 
RB Corey Dillon 
FB Brian Milne 
TE Tony McGee 
WR Carl Pickens 
WR Darnay Scott 
LT Kevin Sargent 
LG Rich Braham 
