<SLUG> BC-HURRICNE-BONNIE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WILMINGTON, N.C.: be printed.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although local officials warned that it was early to make broad
assessments, the damage to trees and property here seemed far
milder than that caused two years ago by Hurricane Fran.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had some air views of damage and some scouting around by
people,'' David Paynter, a spokesman here for the New Hanover
County Emergency Management Agency, said late Wednesday afternoon.
``It seems the hurricane has not created that much damage, but
we've got at least seven more hours before the main part of the
storm leaves this area.''
</P>
<P>
   While thousands of people along the coast fled the hurricane, at
least one family drove here deliberately to witness it. Doug Shales
and his 21-year-old daughter, Sarah, detoured to Wilmington while
returning from Tampa, Fla., to their home in Columbia, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've wanted to experience a hurricane for a long time,''
Shales said. ``We just came on the spur of the moment. It's very
special for us to happen to land somewhere where you're going to be
in the eye.''
</P>
<P>
   The Shaleses spent the day watching the hurricane through the
picture windows in their room at a Holiday Inn. Shales noted that
his family spent time in 1993 in an historic blizzard atop Beech
Mountain. ``We just kind of really enjoy weather extremes,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But many people here remained exasperated that they had been
struck by another hurricane before finishing repairs from the last
one. Kathy Rackley, a 39-year-old housewife from Wilmington, said
she still has trees in her yard that were felled by Fran.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of depressing,'' she said. ``You want to see
everything done before something else comes along and blows it all
down.'' Jack Goodhue, who fled a barrier island to take shelter in
a Wilmington motel, summed up the mood of many. ``What's happened
here?'' he asked. ``Have they pinned a target on Wilmington?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
