<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-BEACHES-ART-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME VOW TO STAY PUT AS BONNIE HITS THE BEACHES 
</HEADLINE>
  (With HURRICANE-WILMINGTON, HURRICANE-BONNIE, HURRICANE-CALM,
HURRICANE-SHELTER, HURRICANE-UTILITIES) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(rm) 
 By THE WILMINGTON (N.C.) MORNING STAR c.1998 N.Y. Times News
Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, N.C. _ For southeastern North Carolina's beach
towns, the story was scripted in plywood nailed to ocean-facing
windows at Carolina Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scram Fran,'' a leftover from the September 1996 hurricane
warned. ``Cheers Bertha,'' read another piece used during the July
1996 hurricane that swept by Pleasure Island.
</P>
<P>
   A more recent addition read: ``My Bonnie lies over the ocean _
Wish she would stay there.''
</P>
<P>
   By midmorning Wednesday, that wish appeared to be a pipe dream.
In Carolina Beach, Hurricane Bonnie's progress was measured in the
size of objects it kicked about on vacant streets _ first shingles,
then street signs and finally plywood and trees.
</P>
<P>
   The same was true in Brunswick County, where officials said
beach towns, and Southport, had considerable damage.
</P>
<P>
   Screaming winds and late predictions of a direct hit led some
people to make a last-minute escape Wednesday morning from Pleasure
Island. But scores more decided to ride out their second Category 3
hurricane in less than two years.
</P>
<P>
   As strong gusts tossed shingles and store signs about the
streets of Carolina Beach, Ron Leach wondered if he should stay on
a 42-foot fishing vessel moored in the water.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it goes to the east or the north, I'm going to ride it
out,'' Leach said from The Hooker, a fiberglass boat equipped with
a generator. Other than that, I'll look pretty foolish staying
here.''
</P>
<P>
   He watched television as the boat tossed steadily.
</P>
<P>
   Leach said he was going to pick a spot on the bulkhead and would
flee to his beachfront home two blocks away if the water rose above
that point. He had promised to keep an eye on the $180,000 vessel
for the owners, who didn't have time to move the boat because they
were boarding up their inn Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figure I'm probably safer here than in my house,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   By 11 a.m., emergency crews prohibited anyone from driving on
the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Gusts kicked sand onto Carolina Beach Avenue along the northern
end of the island, where Fran buried the streets in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Nine cavalier Carolina Beach residents were staring into
Bonnie's fury at The Mariner, a 10-unit apartment complex.
</P>
<P>
   Some neighbors, who gathered on a common porch connecting the
second floor apartments, stayed put for Fran as well.
</P>
<P>
   Jackie Calvary said the small American flag crackling in the
wind on their porch was the group's good luck charm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found it after Fran, and it's been there ever since,'' she
said. The group drank beer and soda at 8 a.m. Wednesday as they
listened to rock music and Bonnie's whistling winds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll stay here until it blows us into the house,'' Calvary
said. Joe Bishop, another member of the cheerful group, said Fran
sent the ocean tumbling over the dune line and into the apartment
below.
</P>
<P>
   ``This building should be fine,'' he said. ``It used to be an
army barracks.''
</P>
<P>
   To the north, Wrightsville Beach Fire Chief Everett Ward saw
3-to 4-foot swells in Banks Channel around 10:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Some docks were floating high and likely would see damage, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the 50 Wrightsville Beach residents who had decided to
tough it out found themselves calling police for a ride out as
winds hit gale force Wednesday morning. Police obliged.
</P>
<P>
   The town had turned off power and water to the beach at
midnight. In Topsail Beach, Becky and Fritz Lenker were having
coffee Wednesday morning in the kitchen of their their-story home.
</P>
<P>
   With steady wind at 50 mph to 60 mph and gusts to 70 mph, Lenker
said shingles were flying, roads were flooding and 15-foot waves
were breaking, though they had not washed over the dunes.
</P>
<P>
   She said they had stayed during Fran and Bertha and previous
storms. This time, she said, her husband wouldn't leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may sound old-fashioned, but my husband won't leave, and I
don't want to leave without my husband.'' She said their house,
which lost its roof during Fran, has a strong frame. ``It's
strapped from A to Z and bolted down well.''
</P>
<P>
   Though they had lost power and water, they were fully equipped
with hurricane supplies and had boarded up all but one window, in
the kitchen, which was giving them some light.
</P>
<P>
   Six other family members were staying with them, as well as nine
cats and two dogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a touch apprehensive,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
