<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-SOROS-635&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOROS FUND LOSSES IN RUSSIA PUT AT $2 BILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: EMERGING-MARKETPLACE, DERIVATIVES)  
(lb) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Russia's financial crisis has deepened, Wall Street traders
have played a guessing game: Which international investors have
taken the biggest hits since the ruble was devalued and Russia
announced its drastic debt restructuring? And when would they start
owning up?
</P>
<P>
   The disclosures began Wednesday as several big-name investors
stumbled out of the Russian chaos. Stanley Druckenmiller, the
manager of George Soros' Quantum Fund, said that Soros' $21.5
billion group of funds _ operated by Soros Fund Management _ had
lost $2 billion in Russian markets during the last year.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Pattison, a spokesman for Soros Fund Management, said that
even with the losses the Quantum Fund's assets of $10.6 billion
were up 19.13 percent for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Druckenmiller is known for making big bets in currencies, bonds,
stocks and commodities around the world. The fund's investments in
Russia were a mix, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great majority of it was equities,'' Druckenmiller
continued. ``There were some GKOs and some dollar bonds,'' he
added, referring to the country's short-term ruble-denominated
zero-coupon Treasury bills and its dollar-denominated bonds,
respectively. So far this year, Russian stocks are down 80.1
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Word of the Soros fund losses, which were first disclosed on the
CNBC cable channel, came less than two weeks after The Financial
Times of London published a letter from Soros in which he voiced
concern over the turmoil overtaking the Russian economy and
financial markets. ``The meltdown in Russian financial markets has
reached the terminal phase,'' began the letter, which appeared on
Aug. 13. ``Immediate action is required.''
</P>
<P>
   In his letter, Soros argued that the International Monetary
Fund's solution to the Russian economic crisis _ imposing tight
monetary and fiscal policy on the nation _ was wrong. Instead, the
financier advocated the introduction of a currency board in Russia
after a modest devaluation of between 15 percent and 25 percent for
the ruble. A currency board is a system that fixes a nation's
currency to the value of its richest trading partner, thereby
taking away discretion over monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
   The day Soros' letter was published, Russian stocks plunged 15
percent before trading was halted for 35 minutes. The market
recovered a bit the following day but ended the week down 13.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Market analysts immediately began to wonder if Soros, one of the
world's most famous financial speculators, was ``talking his book''
_ or advocating a devaluation so as to benefit his concern's
investment portfolios. Had he still owned Russian stocks, for
example, he would have been hurt. Had he sold short Russian stocks
or the ruble, he would certainly have benefited.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted the letter to serve as a wake-up call'' to the
leading industrial nations, said Pattison, the Soros Fund
Management spokesman. ``The Russian media looked at it in terms of
him calling for a devaluation. He didn't advocate the devaluation
unless it was carried out along with the currency board.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Pattison, Soros went on Russian radio advocating
that the nation's leaders accelerate tax reform and set up a
streamlined bankruptcy process for the country's enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was hurt by the attempt to blame him for the events of Aug.
13,'' added Pattison, referring to the tidal wave of selling that
hit Russian markets that day.
</P>
<P>
   Soros, who considers himself something of a diplomat on
financial affairs, is perhaps best known for the $1 billion he said
he made selling British pounds in 1992. That trade made him known
as the man who broke the Bank of England. The investors in Soros'
hedge funds tend to be wealthy individuals with an appetite for
risk.
</P>
<P>
   What Soros is up to now is anybody's guess.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Druckenmiller declined to comment on whether he was going to
return to Russian markets anytime soon. He did say in his interview
with CNBC that Yeltsin's days are numbered. ``Yeltsin is clearly
out; it is just a formality,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another money manager hurt by the Russian crisis is Leon
Cooperman, head of Omega Advisors and former partner at Goldman,
Sachs &AMP; Co., whose firm manages approximately $4 billion in assets.
Three Omega Advisors employees were leaving the firm for reasons
related to performance, the firm said in confirming a report by
Bloomberg News. The individuals were not identified. The firm is
said to have invested less than 1 percent of its portfolio in
Russian debt.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Russia announced the terms of its debt
restructuring, replacing some $48 billion in debt with bonds of
longer maturities worth roughly 30 percent of their previous value.
It then became clear how much investors in the debt, a favored
hedge-fund play, had been hammered as well. Because hedge-fund
managers borrow money to make their investments, one bad call can
wipe out much of their capital.
</P>
<P>
   There were some very big sellers of long-term U.S. Treasury
securities on Wednesday, a sign to some traders that firms were
liquidating profitable positions to cover margin calls from
unprofitable ones.
</P>
<P>
   Stan Jonas, managing director at Fimat U.S.A. said: ``If hedge
funds have losses in Russia, there's only one thing they can do and
that's shrink their portfolio. They have to sell other things to
meet margin calls.''
</P>
<P>
   One money manager said that Wall Street had bought into the view
that ``Russia was too big to fail,'' adding that ``it's going to be
quite a long time before foreigners step back into this market.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
