<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-GIANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOMO FANS 10 IN METS' 4-1 WIN OVER GIANTS  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JASON DIAMOS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Hideo Nomo has seemed to spend as much of this
season battling himself as he has opposing hitters. Coming into
Wednesday's game against San Francisco, he was tied for the
National League lead in both walks and wild pitches and was coming
off three poor performances in a row, all of them losses. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday afternoon at 3Com Park, Nomo responded with one of
his best performances of the year, a complete game in which he gave
up just 3 hits and 1 run while walking 2 and striking out 10. For
one day, at least, he was the old Nomo and that led to a 4-1
victory that let the Mets (73-60) break a three-game losing streak
and hang on to their one-game wild-card lead over the Chicago Cubs;
the Giants dropped two games back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why my control is bad, so when it's good, I don't
know why, either,'' Nomo said through his interpreter. He insisted
that he had done nothing different Wednesday from any other outing
this season. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to try and analyze it, I'm just going to take it
for what it is,'' Mets Manager Bobby Valentine said. ``And it was
fabulous. I think if we give him some runs to work with, you will
see a guy who can be devastating. And Lenny took care of that with
one swing of the bat.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lenny in question was Lenny Harris, who, Valentine said,
figures to see more playing time now that Todd Hundley will no
longer play left field. Leading off the game, Harris, starting in
right field, homered off Orel Hershiser on his first swing.
</P>
<P>
   And when Brian McRae singled home Edgardo Alfonzo from second to
give Nomo a 2-0 advantage before he had even thrown a pitch, Nomo
had all the runs he would need, as he tossed four perfect innings
before keeping the Giants in check on three singles the rest of the
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can pitch better than that, I'd like to see it,''
Valentine said. ``He had an explosive fastball, a devastating
splitter, he got his curveball over when he had to and he pitched
out of that one jam. He looked like the guy we need. Not only did
he keep a real hot team from scoring any runs, he kept our bullpen
out of the game. I couldn't have asked for more.''
</P>
<P>
   For Nomo (6-11), the performance had to be a confidence booster.
And it came in a park where the pitcher has had success. In 31
innings here, Nomo has allowed just four earned runs, for an earned
run average of 1.16. For his career, Nomo is 3-0 in the stadium
that used to be Candlestick Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe he just feels comfortable here, I don't know,'' the
Mets' pitching coach, Bob Apodaca, said. But, Apodaca added, Nomo
did seem to benefit from sessions in the bullpen on Sunday and
Monday, when he worked on not opening up too soon with his front
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Whether those sessions helped, Nomo certainly threw more
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had more than one pitch today, and he was throwing them
over the plate,'' catcher Mike Piazza said. ``The thing that has
hurt him most has been the walks. His stuff has been good enough to
get guys out when he's over the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   When the day began, Nomo was third in the league in both
strikeouts per nine innings and accumulated batting average of
opponents. And he did nothing to hurt those statistics by striking
out Barry Bonds three times Wednesday on split-finger fastballs and
not allowing a base runner until Jeff Kent opened the bottom of the
fifth with a single.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, Nomo had a 4-0 lead, thanks to a two-run fifth in
which the Mets were helped by a Rich Aurilia throwing error, a
Hershiser wild pitch and another run-scoring single from McRae.
After Kent singled in the fifth, however, Nomo walked Ellis Burks.
Kent then took third on a wild pitch, and Burks stole second. Then
Joe Carter hit a sacrifice fly to drive Kent home.
</P>
<P>
   In other outings, Nomo might have crumbled. But he got Bill
Mueller to ground out to second. And then John Olerud made a
sensational diving play to rob Brian Johnson of an extra-base hit
and get the Mets out of the inning. The only other time Nomo was in
trouble was in the seventh, when he stranded Giants at first and
third by striking out Mueller to end the threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't explain it,'' Piazza said, when he was asked why Nomo
can be so out of control one day, and be so in control the next.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
