<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR THURSDAY, AUGUST 27
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Thursday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-MISSING-NOBEL-CHECK-NYT (moved on Friday, August 21)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, August 21,
about the fate of the cash award from the 1988 Nobel Peace Prize,
which was given to United Nations peacekeepers, misstated the year
of Secretary General Dag Hammarskjold's death. It was 1961, not
1967. The article also referred incorrectly to the Oxford college
where the warden is Sir Marrack Goulding, who was in charge of
peacekeeping when the prize was awarded. It is St. Antony's, not
St. Anthony's.
</P>
<P>
   BC-FOSTER-SIBLINGS-NYT (moved on Tuesday, August 25)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, August
25, about a new effort to keep siblings together in foster care
misspelled the surname of the spokeswoman for the Administration of
Children's Services in New York. She is Jennifer Falk, not Folk.
</P>
<P>
   BC-LINCOLN-PHOTO-NYT (moved on Wednesday, August 19)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, August
19, about a daguerreotype that some scholars believe to be the
earliest known likeness of Abraham Lincoln misstated the hometown
of Lloyd Ostendorf, an expert who disagrees. It is Dayton, Ohio,
not Akron.
</P>
</TEXT>
