<HEADER>
A4114 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIBYA-LOCKERBIE-1STLD     08-26 1266
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIBYA-LOCKERBIE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIBYA SIGNALS ACCEPTANCE OF PLAN TO TRY LOCKERBIE SUSPECTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to change ``apparently accepted'' to ``indicated it would
accept'' in lede sentence, and modifies 2nd sentence accordingly;
in 10th graf, renders Lockerbie deaths more precisely)  (mk) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ In guarded language, Libya indicated Wednesday
that it would accept an American and British proposal that two
Libyan suspects in the bombing of a Pan Am jet in 1988 be tried in
the Netherlands by Scottish judges.
</P>
<P>
   A statement was read Wednesday night on Libyan television and
circulated by the official news agency.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere in the one-page statement was there any promise to turn
over the two suspects, and further Libyan delays are widely
expected. But an agreement in principle among the Libyans, British
and Americans on how to proceed with the trial would be the first
major breakthrough in the case in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   The Libyan statement said only that the government would ``deal
positively'' with the American and British offer ``and give it the
interest and care it deserves.'' Libya also demanded a complete end
of the sanctions imposed on the country in 1992; Washington has
proposed suspending the curbs as a first step.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, Britain and the Arab League, where the
proposal originated, reacted cautiously to the announcement,
sensing that there may be further demands by Libya.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Libyans indicated that they had not finished
studying the proposals. In one passage, as circulated in English by
the official news agency, Libya seeks proof that the proposals
``are free from any conditions laid down by the governments of the
United Kingdom and the United States to impede the holding of the
trial.''
</P>
<P>
   British and American diplomats say that the plan is
straightforward: All Libya needs to do is turn over the suspects,
and then justice will take its course.
</P>
<P>
   The Libyan announcement was a response to a proposal formally
offered on Monday. The proposal included a resolution presented to
the United Nations that would suspend sanctions when the two
suspects reach the Netherlands but would also threaten further
steps if the Libyans failed to comply.
</P>
<P>
   The government of Col. Moammar Gadhafi asked the Council to
postpone voting on the British and American resolution; the vote
may come on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, the Scottish judiciary would establish an
unusual offshore court in a still undecided location in the
Netherlands. The explosion of Pan Am Flight 103 over Lockerbie,
Scotland, killed 270 people _ 259 aboard the plane and 11 on the
ground. There were 189 Americans among the dead on the
London-to-New York flight.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the Security Council, Ramadan Barg, Libya's
charge d'affaires at its U.N. mission, said Libyan judicial
authorities needed ``sufficient time'' to study the plan and other
relevant documents, which are being translated into Arabic. But the
Libyans got no support for a delay from Arab nations or members of
the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no decision to delay anything,'' said Danilo Turk,
Slovenia's representative and this month's Security Council
president, when asked about the Libyan letter after Wednesday's
session.
</P>
<P>
   Libya's request for more time was seen by some diplomats here as
a last-ditch attempt by Gadhafi to avoid exposing intelligence
agents to scrutiny in a foreign court.
</P>
<P>
   The Libyans also want to draw Secretary-General Kofi Annan into
the deliberations, further holding up movement toward a trial. Some
Arab diplomats say Gadhafi wants assurances that questions at the
trial will involve only Lockerbie, and that his intelligence
network, which many accuse of supporting terrorism, will not be
scrutinized.
</P>
<P>
   In Edgartown, Mass., a spokesman for the vacationing President
Clinton said Wednesday that the United States was losing patience
with Libya. ``Libya must comply promptly,'' said the spokesman,
Barry Toiv.
</P>
<P>
   The Arab League, where the proposal for a Scottish trial in the
Netherlands originated, obliquely warned the Libyans against
obstructing the compromise, which Gadhafi endorsed in January
before the United States and Britain adopted it.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Libya has counted on the support of the Arab, African and
nonaligned countries to bring about a solution to this problem,''
Hussein Hassouna, the Arab League's representative at the United
Nations, said in an interview Wednesday before the Libyan
announcement. ``I don't expect them to take a position that will
lose them this support in coming phases of the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Gomersall, the deputy British representative, said he
was ``very encouraged'' by the support for their proposal that
Britain and the United States were getting around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Libyan government obviously has the right to study the
text,'' Gomersall said. ``But the Libyan government has also had
access to legal expertise on the Scottish system for a long time.''
The proposal to try the Libyan suspects in the Netherlands in front
of Scottish judges had been discussed for months before it was made
public in July.
</P>
<P>
   Rita Hauser, an international lawyer and former American
delegate to the United Nations who is now chairman of the
International Peace Academy, described the promotion of the
proposal by Britain and the United States as a ``highly creative''
move that had caught the Libyans off guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know of any other case where a country was willing to
move an entire court to another country in this way,'' she said.
``Libya probably thought that the U.K. and the U.S. would never
agree to this.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington and London had earlier insisted that the two
suspects, Abdel Basset al-Megrahi and Lamin Khalifa Fhimah, be
tried in the United States, the home of most of the victims, or in
Scotland. The midair explosion killed 259 people on the plane _ 189
of them Americans _ and 11 on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gomersall said Wednesday that there was no time limit
set on Libya's accepting or rejecting the proposal, the American
and British resolution now taking shape in the Security Council
puts pressure on the Libyans to accept, or face wider sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   There was also pressure on the United States and Britain to make
the offer before a meeting of the Nonaligned Movement in South
Africa. At the meeting, which begins this weekend, more than 100
nations are expected to follow the lead of the Organization of
African Unity and declare they will no longer abide by sanctions
against Libya, even if there is no movement in the case.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Britain, which have seen enthusiasm for
sanctions eroding, could not afford to see the erosion of the
limited sanctions _ bans on air travel to Libya and on some imports
from Libya.
</P>
<P>
   Hassouna, of the Arab League, said Arab and African nations had
welcomed the British and American offer as ``the best practical way
to bring about an early solution to this crisis that has been going
on for 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This has left, on one hand, the families of the victims not
having their legal redress,'' he said, ``and on the other hand, a
whole country suffering from the hardship of sanctions because just
two suspects were not brought to justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Libya also has an outstanding case with France. In 1989, UTA
Flight 772 was blown up over Niger, killing 171 people. The French
accused Libya of plotting the explosion, and the case remains
unresolved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
