<HEADER>
A4116 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-FLOODS-TEX     08-26 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-FLOODS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLOODED SOUTH TEXAS GETS DISASTER DECLARATION
</HEADLINE>
 (EDS: Reference to 80-year-old man with 9-year-old daughter is CQ) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARRY SHLACHTER AND JOHN MORITZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEL RIO, Texas _ After visiting areas devastated by flash
flooding and learning firsthand of survivors' misery, Gov. George
W. Bush announced what this stricken community wanted most: a
federal disaster declaration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was holding back my tears the whole time,'' Bush was heard
confiding to Del Rio Mayor Robert Chavira after chatting with and
sometimes hugging some of the 947 residents who took shelter at the
civic center after their homes were destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   In Laredo, residents spent two days preparing for flooding, and
hundreds moved into shelters. But officials said Wednesday
afternoon that the Rio Grande was about as high as it will get, and
the only flooded area was a mall parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   Three international bridges linking the city with Nuevo Laredo,
Mexico, were closed all day. Officials planned to meet Wednesday
night to consider reopening at least one bridge.
</P>
<P>
   The worst flooding in Del Rio occurred Sunday night and Monday,
but rain pelted the area again Tuesday night, spurring a more flash
flood warnings and sending even more people into shelters.
</P>
<P>
   About 750 people took shelter in a school and church, said Jane
Pratt, a Del Rio Red Cross official. She said people remain
traumatized by the flooding, which occurred after remnants of
Tropical Storm Charley dumped about 18 inches of rain within 24
hours.
</P>
<P>
   When flash flood warnings went out again Wednesday night, some
people were crying and upset, Pratt said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These were people who had lost everything, and here we had
more rain. They were devastated,'' she said. But the rain Tuesday
night caused only minor flooding, and the death toll remained at
six.
</P>
<P>
   At noon Wednesday, officials said that more than 80 people were
still considered missing, but by evening that number was down to
54. Border Patrol spokeswoman Patricia Mancha said 40 were
unaccounted for, meaning that others have reported them missing and
they haven't checked in at shelters.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen more are ``verified missing,'' Mancha said, after
house-to-house checks could not locate them. Authorities have been
given only vague information about four others whose whereabouts
are unknown, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was told of the federal disaster declaration Wednesday in a
phone conversation with White House chief of staff Erskine Bowles.
</P>
<P>
   ``My heart breaks for those who went from nice, secure homes to
no homes at all,'' Bush said. He thanked Bowles for expediting the
request and told him simply, ``It's really sad here.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor, dressed in cowboy boots and jeans, was confronted
by a schoolgirl who said her father had left for San Antonio before
the storm hit, and she wondered if he knew they were hurting.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're listening, your little girl is here'' Bush later
said, addressing the girl's father through a line of TV cameras at
a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the governor we're afraid,'' said Diana Ortiz, 35, a
mother of two who was to start a new job Monday and whose husband
is disabled. ``We don't know what's going to happen to us. We've
lost our furniture, our cars, our home. He promised to help.''
</P>
<P>
   With the disaster declaration, Bush said, Small Business
Administration loans will be available to individuals and
businesses, and smaller cash grants will be provided to people who
do not qualify for loans.
</P>
<P>
   Federal and state agencies will arrange temporary housing, which
at first will probably be mobile homes, the governor said.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Millwee, state coordinator of the Texas Emergency Management
Division, said a survey showed that the flooding in Del Rio
destroyed 300 homes and caused major damage to 100 and lesser
damage to 600. In addition, 50 businesses were destroyed or
sustained major damage, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A lack of water and sewer service remains a major problem. On
Tuesday, the water department reinstalled four 200-horsepower pump
motors on the city wells and then quickly pulled them out when new
flood warnings were issued.
</P>
<P>
   The flood destroyed $150,000 worth of electronic equipment at
San Felipe Springs, which is the city's water source and is where
the first Mass in Texas was celebrated in 1675, local residents
say.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the springs and the main pump station are between the
sixth and seventh holes of the San Felipe Country Club golf course.
A backup pump station, also shut down by the flood, is between the
fourth and fifth holes.
</P>
<P>
   With the pumps reinstalled, the first flow of untreated water
was expected Wednesday night, water superintendent Mitchell Lomas
said. He estimated that chlorinated drinking water won't be
available for about a week.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, residents formed long lines to collect drinking water
at a supermarket parking lot, and they got water to flush toilets
at the Penney's parking lot or from nearby creeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spend three hours a day picking up water,'' said Dan
Peterson, 80, who was pushing a supermarket cart filled with empty
jugs. His wife and 9-year-old daughter pushed another cart outside
the H.E.B. Supermarket, which is bringing in potable water in
5,500-gallon tank trucks.
</P>
<P>
   The rush of floodwater from Del Rio pushed the Rio Grande well
above flood stage Wednesday in Laredo. As a precaution, officials
shut down much of the downtown tourist district, and Mayor Betty
Flores said about 900 people sought refuge in temporary shelters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been hard to convince people that there's a flood
coming, because we're still in a drought,'' Flores said. ``But this
is a very dangerous river right now.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those hard-to-convince people was 38-year-old Freddy
Madrigal, who lives in a riverside ``colonia'' south of Laredo.
Madrigal plunged into the river for a swim Wednesday and retrieved
a deflated inner tube that was floating downstream.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing to fear from this river if you know what
you're doing,'' Madrigal said, but officials said his actions were
foolhardy.
</P>
<P>
   The river at Laredo was at about 25 feet Wednesday afternoon,
well over its flood stage of 8 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The indications are, at least at this stage, that the water's
slowing down,'' said Gene Garza, Laredo port director for the U.S.
Customs Service. ``But this is the most water I've ever seen on the
river.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
