<DOCNO> NYT19980826.0498 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4120 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-1STLD     08-26 1266
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINANCIAL BARON'S MANEUVERS CONTRIBUTED TO RUSSIAN PREMIER'S
OUSTER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (adds 2nd take; also some editing refinements in original
material)  (See also RUSSIA-ECON, RUSSIA-SOROS) 
(bl) 
 By MICHAEL GORDON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Boris Berezovsky, one of Russia's emerging tycoons, had
waited months for this moment of triumph, quietly plotting to
depose Russia's earnest Prime Minister, Sergei Kiriyenko.
</P>
<P>
   Last Saturday, Berezovsky went to the White House, the mammoth,
Soviet-era government headquarters that looms over the Moscow
River, and there, in a private meeting with Anatoly Chubais, one of
the government's most passionate reformers, he told Chubais that
the Kiriyenko team was finished. President Boris Yeltsin,
Berezovsky declared, would soon sign a decree sacking the entire
Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Chubais did not resist, people familiar with the weekend's
events said. He sensed it was a fait accompli and later told
Kremlin aides that Berezovsky's aim in telegraphing the punch was
to demonstrate clearly that the financial barons that dominate
Russia's industry and banks were making a move to reassert their
power.
</P>
<P>
   Kiriyenko had concluded his days might be numbered. Russia's
wealthy businessmen, who had made a fortune buying and selling
companies once controlled by the government, had bridled at his
tough talk about collecting back taxes and allowing money-losing
enterprises to go bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the day after Berezovsky delivered the news, Yeltsin
summoned the prime minister to his dacha outside Moscow and told
him that he was planning some unspecified personnel changes.
</P>
<P>
   Confused, Kiriyenko left the meeting unsure when the axe might
fall. Within hours, though, the official notice came. Kiriyenko was
out. Viktor Chernomyrdin, the prime minister who was fired in the
last shake-up, was back in.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden demise of Kiriyenko's four-month-old government came
partly from the deepening financial crisis and Yeltsin's penchant
for sacrificing loyal subordinates. But it also was a demonstration
of the power of Berezovsky and other tycoons, who exploited the
crisis and Yeltsin's weakened position, to install a more pliant
government.
</P>
<P>
   Now Berezovsky and his allies are playing the role of go-between
in the formation of that government, helping Chernomyrdin negotiate
with the Communists who dominate the lower house of Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The drama is still far from over. The burning issue now is not
whether the Parliament will approve Chernomyrdin _ that seems
assured _ but whether a physically ailing and politically besieged
Yeltsin will cede to Chernomyrdin by eventually resigning and
calling early elections.
</P>
<P>
   That would enable Chernomyrdin to take the reins as the nation's
acting chief executive and would give him an enormous advantage as
a presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very big danger for the country,'' Boris Nemtsov,
one of the Kiriyenko supporters who resigned his top Kremlin post
this week, said in an interview. ``A resignation would be bad not
just because of the problem with the currency but because of the
history of Russia. If any czar decides to resign it could lead to a
real time of troubles.''
</P>
<P>
   Berezovsky had never made a secret of his opposition to
Kiriyenko or his own doctrine that the government should be a
servant of well-connected businessmen.
</P>
<P>
   A former mathematician, Berezovsky made a fortune as a car
dealer and media mogul after the collapse of the Soviet Union. He
was one of Yeltsin's major financial backers during the 1996
presidential elections and claimed his reward by being named deputy
secretary of the National Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately, he locked horns with Kremlin reformers like
Chubais, who once presided over Russia's troubled privatization
program.
</P>
<P>
   Nemtsov, the former governor of the Nizhny Novgorod region who
Yeltsin once touted as possible successor, prevailed on the
president last year to fire Berezovsky from his security post,
complaining that the businessman was mixing his business and
government interests.
</P>
<P>
   Berezovsky, however, remained close to the corridors of power.
He maintained connections with Valentin Yumashev, Yeltsin's chief
of staff, and Tatyana Dyachenko, Yeltsin's daughter and political
adviser. And he used his control over the ORT television channel
and his newspaper, Nezavisimaya Gazeta, to attack his opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Last March, when Yeltsin anointed Kiriyenko _ a former energy
minister, banker and Nemtsov ally who also comes from Nizhny
Novgorod _ as prime minister, Berezovsky inveighed against the
choice.
</P>
<P>
   At first, it appeared that Berezovsky would be the loser. Aided
by Chubais, the Kiriyenko team negotiated a $17 billion bailout
package with the International Monetary Fund. Western officials
praised the new prime minister's dedication and acumen.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone was so enthusiastic. Some of Russia's financial
community was alarmed by Kiriyenko's talk about putting the
nation's house in order by refusing to bail out well-connected
banks and enterprises. Some of Russia's new tycoons, who had built
their fortunes by buying privatized government enterprises at
bargain prices with the help of political connections, have not
proven to be very adept business managers and now fear the idea of
free market competition
</P>
<P>
   Even with the IMF bailout, investors continued to flee the
world's emerging markets. The Parliament resisted Kiriyenko's
program, much of which was tied to the additional loans from the
fund. Worse, the ruble began to falter and Russian banks were
having trouble paying back their borrowings.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the government, after insisting that it would never
devalue the currency, reversed itself and allowed the currency to
decline in value. It also took some steps to protect the nation's
oligarchy, including a 90-day moratorium on the repayment of the
banks' foreign debt.
</P>
<P>
   But Russia financial crisis also gave the prime minister's
opponents the opening they had been waiting for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kiriyenko prepared a packet of measures to that would lead to
the bankruptcy of ineffective banks or financial industrial
groups,'' Nemtsov said. ``When the oligarchs sensed this they
decided to change the government.''
</P>
<P>
   As last week came to an end, there was talk that Kiriyenko might
be ousted, but it was far from clear who might take his place.
</P>
<P>
   In the halls of the Kremlin, several successors were mentioned:
Moscow's pugnacious major, Yuri Luzhkov; Yegor Stroyev, the head of
the upper house of Parliament; and Chernomyrdin, the prime minister
Yeltsin unceremoniously ousted in March.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin had his liabilities. During his first term as prime
minister he had gone along with Russia's stutter-step journey
toward a capitalist democracy. But he had also presided over the
insider deals and half measures that led to its economic quagmire.
</P>
<P>
   Politically, however, he had good connections across the
spectrum. As the former head of Gazprom, Russia's huge natural gas
monopoly, he was an unofficial member of the financial oligarchy.
He also enjoyed close ties with the Communist leadership in the
Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   During the months after he was cast out of the Kremlin, he also
met with Berezovsky, including a reported meeting this month in
southern France.
</P>
<P>
   Berezovsky glories in self-promotion and his enemies also
sometimes exaggerate his role. But while Berezovsky was not the
only baron supporting Chernomyrdin, he was an active and important
adviser.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As Berezovsky schemed behind his back, Kiriyenko worried that he
was running out of time. But when he went to see Yeltsin on Sunday
he wasn't sure what would happen next.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question was asked by the president: would I agree to stay
in the government if some changes in it took place,'' Kiriyenko
told the newspaper Kommersant Daily. ``I answered that first of all
I would like to take a break. Secondly, it would be wrong as a
matter of principle.''
</P>
<P>
   After his meeting with Yeltsin, Kiriyenko huddled with his old
friend, Nemtsov, who had worked on and off with Yeltsin for eight
years.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing Kiriyenko describe the conversation with the
president, ``I said the decision will be made immediately,''
Nemtsov recalled.
</P>
<P>
   That night Kiriyenko and Nemtsov ventured out of the White House
for a final meeting with striking coal miners who have pitched a
nearby squatters' camp to protest the failure to pay back wages.
</P>
<P>
   Still the buttoned-down technocrat, Kiriyenko was dressed in a
gray suit and tie. But the telegenic Nemtsov was wearing blue jeans
and had a sweater draped around his shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   The ousted Kremlin officials brought a bottle of vodka as a
gift. A gaggle of body guards accompanied the dispirited pair from
the government headquarters but maintained a respective distance.
</P>
<P>
   For 40 minutes, the former ministers and the unpaid miners
commiserated about the cut-throat world of Russian capitalism, as
some of the miners snapped photos.
</P>
<P>
   ``We discussed a lot of topics, including the oligarchy,''
Nemtsov said. ``They asked who is stealing the money. The prime
minister said it was the result of crony capitalism.''
</P>
<P>
   To the miners Kiriyenko appeared nervous and shaken while
Nemtsov seemed more relaxed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came out and said, `Guys, we're unemployed like you and
we don't know where to go,'' recalled Volodya Kapyto, a 45-year-old
miner from Perm. ``They said, `We wanted to do something, but they
did not let us.'''
</P>
<P>
   Added Valera Ustiantsev, a 46-year-old miner, ``They said they
wanted to pay the government's internal debts, but that Yeltsin
chased them out.''
</P>
<P>
   After the guests left, however, Sergei Pervushkin, a 30-year-old
miner from the far northern city of Vorkuta, grabbed the vodka
bottle and smashed it against the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should have come sooner and not with vodka, but with
concrete proposals,'' Pervushkin said.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin did not explain his decision until the next day. Looking
drawn, the 67 year-old president gave a terse, mid-day television
address, in which he touted Chernomyrdin as a force for stability
and his heir apparent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five months ago, no one expected the world financial crisis to
hit Russia so hard,'' Yeltsin said, alluding to his earlier
decision to substitute Kiriyenko for Chernomyrdin. ``Today we need
those who are commonly referred to as heavyweights.''
</P>
<P>
   The political U-turn has sparked a further collapse of Russia's
weakened ruble and unnerved investors, who fear Chernomyrdin will
retreat from Kiriyenko's reformist course.
</P>
<P>
   It also plunged the nation into a political upheaval as
financiers vie for posts on the new government team along with
Communists, whose support Chernomyrdin needs to win approval in the
Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   While the composition of the government is unclear, one thing
that is certain is that Kiriyenko's allies will go.
</P>
<P>
   A Kremlin official said that Chernomyrdin and Berezovsky are
pushing to strip Chubais of his post as head of Russia's electrical
monopoly. Chubais held that job when he negotiated last month with
the IMF.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Moscow is debating whether the prime minister post
Chernomyrdin has regained is a waystation to the presidency.
Yeltsin has suggested that Chernomyrdin would carry forward his
banner in the election in 2000. But some officials say Chernomyrdin
and his sponsors may not want to wait that long.
</P>
<P>
   If Yeltsin were pressed to resign for reasons of health,
Chernomyrdin would become acting president and early elections
would be organized when Chernomyrdin enjoyed the benefits of being
an incumbent but before he may be blamed for a collapsing economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chernomyrdin knows that his chances of being elected president
are slim if he waits until 2000,'' the newspaper Segodnya observed
Wednesday. ``But the situation will be radically difference if he
runs for president as an acting president in 1998.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
