K Todd Peterson 
P Jeff Feagles 
 
OAKLAND RAIDERS 
1997: 4-12, 2-6 in AFC West 
Coach (record): Jon Gruden (first year) 
Stadium: Oakland-Alameda County Coliseum 
Ticket information: (800) 949-2626 
Pieces in place 
QB Jeff George (3,917 yards, 29 TDs), RB Napoleon Kaufman (1,294
rushing yards), WR Tim Brown (104 receptions, 1,408 yards), FS Eric
Turner, DT Russell Maryland. 
Key newcomers 
CB Charles Woodson, OT Mo Collins, CB Eric Allen, TE Derek Brown,
SS Anthony Newman. 
Key losses 
CB Larry Brown, LB Rob Fredrickson, G Lester Holmes, DE Chester
McGlockton. 
Missing piece 
The Raiders were atrocious on defense in 1997, finishing last in
the league in rushing defense and passing defense, and 28th in
scoring defense. Drafting Heisman Trophy winner Woodson to play
cornerback should help. But the problems for the defense are up
front, which suffered a big blow with the off-season death of
rookie DT Leon Bender. The team will go with Russell Maryland and
Darrell Russell, last year's No. 1 pick, at the tackles. Russell
played end last year, and coaches think the switch back to his
natural position will help. The Raiders are really weak at
linebacker, where they traded away their best player at the outside
position, Fredrickson. Team owner Al Davis did not deal for a
linebacker or grab one early in the draft. So that spot will
probably be a weakness again for the Raiders in 1998. 
Biggest test 
They Raiders could be out of playoff contention before the end of
September. They are at home against Kansas City, the New York
Giants and Denver, then are at the Cowboys. 
Watch out for 
A bunch of games that end 45-40. The Raiders might not play enough
defense to stop a good college team. But their offense can score
points on anyone. With 3,917 yards passing, 29 touchdowns and only
nine interceptions, George probably put up the best stats ever
while leading a 4-12 team. Kaufman gained 1,294 yards on only 272
carries (4.8-yard average), and Brown led the AFC with 104
receptions. No telling how much more offense there will be in 1998
as Gruden, a West Coast disciple, hired Gary Stevens as his
offensive coordinator. Stevens came over from Dan Marino's Miami
Dolphins. 
Milestones 
At least the Raiders draft well. Four of their past five No. 1
draft picks are starters with the team. That doesn't include
Woodson, this year's No. 1, who is the projected starter at
cornerback. 
Overview: The games should be exciting. And Davis' relationship
with the young Gruden will bear a story or two. But the results
will be the same: Another sad season for what was once one of the
league's top franchises. 
Prediction: 5-11 
 
STARTING LINEUP 
Offense 
