SAN DIEGO CHARGERS 
1997: 4-12, 1-7 in AFC West 
Coach (record): Kevin Gilbride (4-12) 
Stadium: Qualcomm Stadium (71,000) 
Ticket information: (619) 280-2121 
Pieces in place 
LB Junior Seau, G Raleigh McKenzie, DE William Fuller (3 sacks), SS
Rodney Harrison, CB Dwayne Harper, DT Reuben Davis. 
Key newcomers 
QB Ryan Leaf, RB Natrone Means, LT John Jackson, LG Aaron Taylor,
WR Mikhael Ricks. 
Key losses 
RB Gary Brown, K Greg Davis, QB Jim Everett, WR Tony Martin, WR
Eric Metcalf. 
Missing piece 
The Chargers could be pretty decent on offense, with the drafting
of Leaf, and the free-agent signings of Means, Jackson and Taylor.
But the defense still has a bunch of problems, particularly the
pass rush, where the Chargers did nothing in the off-season to
upgrade. Davis, the club's best tackle, is back after missing 1997
with an Achilles' heel injury. But Fuller, who is 36, and Marco
Coleman, who has underachieved, combined for five sacks in 1997.
You need much more pass rush production than that from your
starting ends to survive the pass-happy AFC West. The Chargers were
23rd against the pass and last in the league in points allowed. And
even with Seau, that total statistic doesn't figure to change
much. 
Biggest test 
The Chargers have only five games against playoff teams, including
two each against Kansas City and Denver. Some of the weak teams
they face are the Indianapolis, Oakland (twice), Arizona,
Baltimore, Buffalo and Philadelphia. But, those teams are probably
saying the same thing about having the Chargers on their schedule. 
Watch out for 
How Leaf falls. The last first-year quarterback that had a great
impact on the league was Dan Marino in 1983. So no one should
expect too much from the rookie from Washington State. The key
things to determining his development are all tangible. Does he
have respect from his teammates? Does he show no fear in the
pocket? If the postseason answer to both is ``yes,'' then the
Chargers will be better off, no matter how many losses pile up. 
Milestones 
The Chargers tied the Broncos last year by scoring an NFL-high 10
touchdowns on defense and special teams. 
Overview 
This is a rebuilding year for Gilbride and GM Bobby Beathard. With
a weak defense and an offense featuring a rookie quarterback and
starting wide receivers that have combined for five career
touchdown receptions, expect a lot of games to get out of hand. If
Leaf stays healthy, the season will have been a success. 
Prediction: 3-13 
 
Puzzle piece: Ryan Leaf 
 
