<HEADLINE>
`TITANIC' VIDEO TO DOCK AT STORES TUESDAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE McNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Get ready for another pop culture frenzy of
titanic proportions.
</P>
<P>
   The home video of James Cameron's Oscar-winning ``Titanic'' goes
on sale Tuesday, and Paramount Studios has already shipped more
than 20 million copies to retailers. Many stores will re-open at
midnight or stay open all evening Monday so that legions of
``Titanic'' fans can buy or rent the video as soon as it's
available.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt this is going to draw a lot of 15-year-old
girls,'' said Barbara McNamara, an industry tracker with Alexander
&AMP; Associates. ``Making it into an event will draw in the real
Leonardo DiCaprio fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Many outlets in the 4,000-store Blockbuster chain, which
generate a third of the nation's video revenues, plan to hold ``bon
voyage'' parties Monday night and the chain is running a nationwide
sweepstakes to win a cruise vacation to anywhere in the world. Best
Buy will re-open all of its 289 stores at midnight and give all
``Titanic'' buyers a free ``Titanic'' calendar.
</P>
<P>
   Cable-shopping giant QVC reported it has received more than
230,000 orders for the video, which it will ship Tuesday, since it
began selling the tape for $19.95 on June 15. It topped QVC's
record for pre-orders, set by the ``Star Wars'' trilogy, three
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Virgin Megastore in suburban West Hollywood will feature
performances by Gaelic Storm, the band that appeared in the movie
in the party scene in steerage, beginning at 10 p.m. Monday before
the tape actually goes on sale at 12:01 a.m. Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Paramount and Virgin also will set up a ``green screen'' video
system to tape fans and drop them into a scene from the movie,
Paramount publicist Corey Weiss said.
</P>
<P>
   The hype has reached the Internet too, where Reel.com is taking
a calculated financial bath by selling the tape for just $9.95,
plus $3.90 in shipping and handling.
</P>
<P>
   The company acknowledged it's losing money on every ``Titanic''
order, but hopes to draw customers to its site at www.reel.com.
</P>
<P>
   Many brick-and-mortar chains have offered customers the chance
to pay $5 down in exchange for trinkets like ``Titanic'' lapel
pins. ``Pre-sales were the highest for any title we've ever had and
exceeded our expectations,'' said Best Buy's Laurie Bauer.
</P>
<P>
   Paramount, which received high marks for its handling of the
theatrical release, launched the video campaign in mid-August.
Shipments to retailers included warnings that the studio would
clamp down on anyone selling before 12:01 a.m.. Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're having to be very adamant about people not selling the
tape early,'' said Paramount spokeswoman Dorrit Ragosine. To that
end, Paramount has set up a toll-free phone line for rival
retailers to report violations and will punish offenders by
delaying future orders.
</P>
<P>
   The double-cassette version of the 193-minute movie comes just
as the film is crossing the $600 million mark in domestic
theatrical grosses. That's nearly $140 million more than the
nearest rival _ ``Star Wars,'' which generated $450 million in its
two releases. Even after 36 weeks, ``Titanic'' was still able to
gross more than half a million dollars at 570 theaters last
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Video sales should reach equally uncharted waters, according to
analysts. Most expect it to easily top the current live-action
record holders: ``Independence Day'' and ``Jurassic Park,'' both
with 17 million.
</P>
<P>
   Still, that's well short of The Walt Disney Co.'s top four hits
_ 30 million copies of ``The Lion King,'' 25.5 million for ``Snow
White and the Seven Dwarfs,'' 24 million for ``Aladdin'' and 22
million for ``Beauty and the Beast.'' Disney's heavyweights became
breakout successes due to the studio's ability to target parents of
young children wanting to watch the animated stories over and over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think 20 million for `Titanic' seems like a reasonable
number,'' said Tom Adams, president of Adams Media Research. ``But
it's not going to do `Lion King' numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes hitting the 20-million mark impressive is that the
most likely buyers _ the teen-age girls and young women who
generated most of the repeat business for ``Titanic'' _ are not
traditionally heavy buyers of videos. ``This is an opportunity for
the industry to expand their customer base,'' McNamara said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Titanic'' should also help the home video business wipe out
the memory of an anemic 1997, when it posted its first year-to-year
decline with domestic revenues falling 6.5 percent. Analysts
believe both rentals and video sales will post single-digit upturns
this year, due in no small part to the ``Titanic'' effect.
</P>
<P>
   20th Century Fox, which sold off part of its ``Titanic'' rights
to Paramount for a $65 million investment, will start selling the
video in foreign markets on Sept. 30; those sales could amount to
another 10 million copies.
</P>
<P>
   The economics of videotapes are impressive: Titles costing $4
each to duplicate are sold to wholesalers for $12. That means
Paramount and Fox stand to take in another $200 million in profits
_ not revenues _ to add to the $400 million in profits the studios
have already banked from the movie.
</P>
<P>
   It's amazing turnaround from last summer, when ``Titanic''
wasn't just a movie about a 1912 disaster; it was also a financial
disaster. It had been pulled from the summer release schedule and
its $200 million production cost made it appear a certain
money-loser.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
