<SLUG> BC-RENO-GORE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENO DECIDES TO OPEN PRELIMINARY INQUIRY OF FUND-RAISING CALLS BY
GORE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno has decided to take a
second look into whether an independent counsel is needed to
investigate campaign fund-raising calls made by Vice President Al
Gore, officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The 90-day preliminary inquiry by Justice Department lawyers
will focus on dozens of telephone calls Gore made from his
government office in late 1995 and early 1996 soliciting money for
the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   In December, Reno ended a similar probe, saying there was not
sufficient evidence to require naming an independent counsel to
conduct a full investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Reno, who faces mounting political pressure from Republicans in
Congress, on Wednesday notified a three-judge court that oversees
independent counsels that she was initiating a second preliminary
inquiry, an indication that there is a specific allegation of
wrongdoing by the vice president needing further examination.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department last week obtained a 1995 White House
memorandum bearing handwritten notes that appear to contradict
Gore's account of his fund-raising telephone calls, according to
government officials.
</P>
<P>
   The notes indicate that Gore and several Democratic Party
officials discussed how some of the large, soft-money contributions
being solicited by the vice president would be channeled into
hard-money accounts to directly finance the Clinton-Gore campaign,
government officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The note contradicts Gore's repeated claims that the 45 calls in
question were made to solicit only soft-money contributions for
party building and issue ads.
</P>
<P>
   While raising soft money from federal property is legal, many
experts believe hard-money solicitations are strictly prohibited.
</P>
<P>
   The handwritten notation by Gore's deputy chief of staff at the
time, David Strauss, was on a memo summarizing a Nov. 20, 1995,
meeting of high-level White House and Democratic National Committee
officials about fund raising. Strauss' note quotes Gore saying
``count me in on the calls'' and later indicates the money raised
would be ``65 percent soft/35 percent hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Gore was interviewed by Justice Department
investigators and asked about the DNC memo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vice president volunteered to be interviewed, and he has
been interviewed twice,'' said his private attorney, James F. Neal.
``I am totally satisfied that Vice President Gore has fully,
completely and honestly answered every question asked of him, and I
am confident that when this investigation is completed, the
Department of Justice will reach the same conclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press reported late Wednesday that former White
House deputy chief of staff Harold Ickes also was questioned about
the memo. Unnamed sources quoted by the AP said Ickes told
investigators that Gore was present at two or three White House
meetings in which so-called hard- and soft-money contributions were
discussed.
</P>
<P>
   A report submitted to Reno in mid-July by Charles LaBella,
former head of her campaign finance task force, asserts that Ickes
was at the center of an effort to circumvent campaign-funding
restrictions. Ickes has denied wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly two years Reno has resisted calls from congressional
Republicans for an independent counsel investigation into alleged
Democratic fund-raising abuses in the 1996 campaign. A House
committee on Aug. 6 cited Reno for contempt of Congress for
refusing to turn over the LaBella memo and correspondence from FBI
Director Louis Freeh, who _ like LaBella _ had recommended
appointment of an independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the 90-day preliminary inquiry, Reno can ask for
an additional 60 days to wind up the probe, seek appointment of an
independent counsel or report that her agency found no credible
allegation warranting further inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dan Burton, chairman of the panel that cited Reno for
contempt, was not satisfied with the attorney general's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attorney general's action _ or inaction _ today has done
nothing to allay our concerns that something is seriously wrong at
the Justice Department,'' the Indiana Republican said. ``Earlier
this month, the attorney general promised a decision in three
weeks, now she says it will take three more months.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore spokesman Chris Lehane said the vice president had not been
notified of Reno's decision. ``At whatever stage this review
process ends, we are confident it will once again conclude that
everything the vice president did was legal and proper,'' Lahane
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hours after word of Reno's decision was sent to the three-judge
panel of the U.S. Court of Appeals, Gore arrived back on the U.S.
mainland after a two-week Hawaiian vacation and headed immediately
to a Democratic fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president was the main draw at a cocktail party in a
giant stone mansion overlooking San Francisco Bay to raise money
for a former aide, Machela Alioto, who is running for California
secretary of state.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's schedule also calls for him to attend a fund-raising
luncheon for California Democratic gubernatorial nominee Gray Davis
on Thursday before flying back to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
