<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIETNAM-VET-LIAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIE EXPOSED, A MURDERER IS BACK IN CUSTODY 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ They came for Joseph Yandle on Wednesday, as he had
feared they would: two Massachusetts parole officers to escort him
from his home in Rutland, Vt., back to prison, possibly for life.
</P>
<P>
   His lie had unraveled.
</P>
<P>
   It had been not merely a fib but a whopper. Sentenced to life
without parole for first-degree murder and desperate to be freed,
Yandle had passed himself off to the governor of Massachusetts, the
state pardon board, veterans' groups and national news outlets _
including CBS News' ``60 Minutes,'' which introduced him to the
country _ as a decorated veteran of the Vietnam War. In fact, he
did serve during the Vietnam War, but only as a clerk with the
Marines on Okinawa, he has now admitted.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Mike Wallace of ``60 Minutes'' reported that Yandle had
served two tours in Vietnam as a Marine and ``came home with a
Bronze Star for valor, two Purple Hearts and something else, too: a
heroin habit.''
</P>
<P>
   That Vietnam-acquired habit, Yandle's story went, had led him
into crime, including a string of armed robberies that ultimately
cost the life of a liquor store clerk, Joseph Reppucci, in a 1972
holdup that Yandle helped a partner commit.
</P>
<P>
   With veterans' support, and sympathetic news coverage that
focused largely on how he had been rehabilitated in prison and even
earned both a bachelor's degree and a master's while incarcerated,
Yandle won commutation in 1995 and was freed on the parole that his
sentence had denied him. He had served 23 years.
</P>
<P>
   Although it was not the only element in the decision to commute
Yandle's sentence, his claim of Vietnam combat clearly influenced
the pardon board and William Weld, then the governor, who made the
final decision. Weld said at the time that Yandle ``went to serve
his country in Vietnam'' and ``returned a scarred man, and he has
served a lengthy prison sentence.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Acting Gov. Argeo Paul Cellucci moved to revoke the
commutation of Yandle's sentence. Cellucci submitted his
recommendation to that effect to the eight-member Governor's
Executive Council, which is to consider it next Wednesday. In the
meantime, Yandle is being held in state prison, because the state
parole board is already considering revocation of his parole, the
board's spokeswoman said Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Yandle's fabrication might have held, and he might have kept
living with the wife he had married and the two children he had
fathered on prison furloughs, if not for a Dallas businessman named
B.G. Burkett, also known by the nickname Jug, who had turned up his
lies in the course of writing a book about Vietnam veterans and
impostors.
</P>
<P>
   Burkett took his doubts to ``60 Minutes'' about four months ago,
said Kevin Tedesco, the spokesman for the program. On Monday,
Wallace finally succeeded in interviewing Yandle about the
accusations that he had lied. In a segment broadcast that night on
the ``CBS Evening News,'' Yandle admitted to lying and said he felt
particularly sorry about hurting the real combat veterans who had
earned real medals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are the people that I most need to apologize to,'' he
said, ``the Vietnam veterans and the people who supported me.''
</P>
<P>
   Yandle, now 49, managed somehow _ he has not publicly specified
how _ to fabricate a convincing set of documents attesting to his
phony wartime record. Both The Boston Globe and The Boston Herald
carried apologies Wednesday from Yandle in interviews. In the
Herald, he said he had made up the Vietnam lie as a way of
protecting himself in prison, and ``it snowballed into something I
could no longer control, as most lies do.'' In the Globe, he
admitted, ``The fact is, I just wanted to go home after 23 years in
prison, and I had no other opportunity of ever getting home.''
</P>
<P>
   But his apologies seem to be having little effect. Cellucci, for
one, has denounced Yandle's lie as ``a massive fraud'' and ``an
insult to veterans who clamored for the commutation and to the
family of the victim.''
</P>
</TEXT>
