<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-JURY-DUTY-325&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANHATTANITES NOW CALLED LESS FREQUENTLY FOR JURY DUTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With twice as many people showing up for jury duty in
Manhattan because of recent reforms to the system, residents of the
borough are now being called for jury duty only once every four
years instead of once every two years, New York state's chief judge
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The less-frequent jury service, effective Aug. 1, is the fruit
of a host of changes implemented by Chief Judge Judith Kaye that
have forced more people to heed the call to sit on juries. The
changes, made over the last four years, have eliminated exemptions
from jury duty for 20 professions, allowed for broader lists of
potential jurors, and required stepped-up enforcement against those
who ignore summonses.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the changes, the percentage of Manhattan
residents responding to the summonses has increased to 35 percent
today from roughly 15 percent in 1993, court officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, court officials have tried to make jury duty more
pleasant, rather than a drawn-out civic nightmare marked by filthy,
overcrowded jury rooms and surly court officials.
</P>
<P>
   With the change in Manhattan, the Bronx remains the only county
in the state where residents are called for jury duty every two
years.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there may be room for improvement. Erie County, which
Judge Kaye praised as a model, requires jury duty every seven
years.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Kaye said her long-term goal was to have all residents of
the state called for jury duty at the most every four years. And
once called, residents should serve as jurors on a single trial or
for a single day if they are not immediately chosen to sit on a
case, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Court officials say that people are not only being called less
frequently, but they are also spending less time in the courthouse
once called. These days, Manhattan residents are spending as little
as two days waiting to be selected, as opposed to as long as a week
on average in the past, court officials said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Julia Vitullo-Martin, director of the Vera Institute of
Justice's Citizens Jury Project, an independent group selected by
Judge Kaye to monitor the implementation of reforms, praised the
initial efforts as a national model. But she cautioned that
improving the system further _ including changing the grand jury
and civil court duties _ could prove more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judge Kaye has taken care of the major set of complaints,''
Ms. Vitullo-Martin said. ``And now we need phase two.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Vitullo-Martin said the project had installed booths in
three courthouses in Manhattan and one in Brooklyn to gather
feedback. She said jurors still complained that they spent hours
waiting before they were assigned to a jury or dismissed. She said
the courts needed to install a computerized system and new
procedures to minimize the time wasted by prospective jurors.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Vitullo-Martin also said that some fundamental problems
still needed to be addressed, like overcrowded court buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Kaye agreed that problems remain. ``I'd say we'd come a
good distance, and we have a long way to go,'' she said. ``It's a
huge system.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
