<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-SHORE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT SHUT BEACHES, SURFERS TEMPT HURRICANE'S FURY
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(With HURRICANE-BONNIE-NYT, HURRICANE-WILMINGTON-NYTR,
HURRICANE-CALM-NYTR, HURRICANE-SHELTER-NYTR,
HURRICANE-UTILITIES-NYTR, HURRICANE-BEACHES-NYTR) 
(rm) 
 By AMY WALDMAN c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For the truly committed, the risk paled next to the
potential high.
</P>
<P>
   While New York City closed all seven of its beaches for swimming
Wednesday because of the huge waves and merciless undertows
generated by Hurricane Bonnie, for the die-hard surfers at Rockaway
Beach in Queens, the red flags signaling the beach's closing were
like a matador's cloth waving in front of a bull.
</P>
<P>
   About two dozen surfers were riding the rapture Wednesday
afternoon, with the waves, at 5 feet, double their normal height.
</P>
<P>
   After washing onto shore, Yakira Cordero, 21, of Brooklyn,
called the force that propelled her ``the wave of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Cordero, a student at St. John's University, saw the rough surf
as an opportunity, rather than a menace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been tracking the storm, waiting for it to get bigger,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   The hurricane reached land in North Carolina Wednesday with 115
mph winds and closed beaches along the East Coast, as its force
churned the surf, creating strong riptides and dangerous conditions
for swimmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like a job,'' Cordero said. ``Professionals only.''
</P>
<P>
   City officials, concerned about an invisible but potentially
deadly undertow, closed all city beaches for the first time in at
least six years, said Henry Stern, the city's commissioner of parks
and recreation.
</P>
<P>
   One swimmer in the region drowned on Monday and another is
presumed to have drowned after they encountered heavier than usual
currents that were attributed to Bonnie.
</P>
<P>
   At Rockaway Beach, Arthur Skotedis, 42, of Astoria, Queens, went
swimming after lifeguards had left the beach and was sucked down by
the undertow. After he was pulled unconscious from the water by two
surfers, rescue workers tried unsuccessfully to revive him.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Monday, Antonio Mandarino, 23, of Oakland, N.J., was
caught by a riptide and pulled out to sea while wading at Point
Pleasant Beach in New Jersey. He is presumed dead.
</P>
<P>
   Stern said that lifeguards and park enforcement patrol officers
were waving surfers in from the water, but would not go into the
ocean after them unless they were in distress.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't ask lifeguards to risk their own lives to rescue
surfers looking for the big wave,'' he said, but added that people
who swim or surf at closed beaches may be subject to fines.
</P>
<P>
   Meteorologists said the hurricane will veer out to sea near the
North Carolina-Virginia border and is not expected to hit the New
York region.
</P>
<P>
   But on Wednesday, lifeguards at state beaches also had their
hands full because of Bonnie.
</P>
<P>
   Flooding was so severe at Jones Beach, as well as Robert Moses
and Hither Hills State Parks, that it created large pools in picnic
areas and on the sand, said George Gorman, a spokesman for the New
York State Office of Parks, Recreation and Historic Preservation.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to swim in the ocean, children were swimming in the
pools, Gorman said, and the lifeguards were charged with monitoring
the ``little lakes.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service had heavy surf and small craft
advisories in effect yesterday, but that didn't deter determined
riders of the waves.
</P>
<P>
   Cordero said that earlier in the day, she had been at Long
Beach, on Long Island, where the waves were eight feet high.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to paddle out for about 30 minutes, but I couldn't
make it,'' she said. ``The rip was really strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than give up, she had simply moved to the beach in
Queens.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to live on the edge a little bit,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
