<SLUG> BC-FBC-PREVIEW-TCU-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCHIONE TAKING CHARGE AT TCU
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By TERRANCE HARRIS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was Dec. 15, 1997, and Dennis Franchione had just finished
being paraded around as the new TCU football coach in front of the
media, faculty and alumni.
</P>
<P>
   Then came his most important meeting.
</P>
<P>
   He stood before 60 or so young men who had just become his new
team. Franchione informed his captive audience that he was now
theirs and they were his.
</P>
<P>
   Then he looked into the dazed eyes of a group still reeling from
a 1-10 season, and started asking questions: Who, in the room,
aspired to win a Western Athletic Conference championship?
</P>
<P>
   Arms shot toward the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   With his suit coat off, tie loosened and sleeves rolled up,
Franchione followed with the most telling of questions: How many
were willing to work for that title?
</P>
<P>
   To a man, the players responded by raising their arms toward the
ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to TCU football, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``That really set the tone for what we had to do,'' said TCU
punter/receiver Royce Huffman. ``Coach Fran is real strict and
stern about what he wants to do and how he's going to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of his way or the highway, which is the way it needs
to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   The Horned Frogs understand and even expect it as they turn to
their new coach to rebuild the confidence left after 2 1/2 losing
seasons under former coach Pat Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   In Franchione they find a man who readily admits, ``I've done
this before, I've rebuilt struggling programs.''
</P>
<P>
   The question now facing the man who transformed a once
bottom-feeding New Mexico into last season's WAC Mountain Division
champs and Insight.Com Bowl invitees is whether he can fit the
pieces of the TCU football puzzle into a recognizable picture. That
of a winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can believe in somebody who believes in himself,'' said
senior tailback Basil Mitchell. ``Coach Fran certainly believes in
himself and what he is doing. And he has a proven track record
behind him.''
</P>
<P>
   Franchione says the four qualities the Frogs need immediately
are not all that much different than what he found in his previous
programs. There are needs for attention to detail, organization,
discipline and work ethic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are things that have been missing in every program that
I've taken over,'' said Franchione, who had three winning seasons
at New Mexico and compiled a 33-36 record in six years. ``There may
have been others, but those are the common threads.''
</P>
<P>
   Gaining the belief and trust in the new coach has certainly been
paramount, but now Franchione faces his biggest task _ convincing
the Frogs to believe in themselves.
</P>
<P>
   This is a team that saw its hopes ripped apart often in the
fourth quarter last season. The team expected to find a way to
lose. The only victory was in the season-finale, when TCU upset SMU
to avert the program's first winless season since 1976.
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs had not only lost faith in Sullivan's system, they
were no longer certain of their own abilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember saying to the team la2D &AMP;E &Cx1f; n &QL; 5atJ
</P>
</TEXT>
