972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or (212) 556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 26, 1998 -- FUNRAISING-RENO, 8-26 --
Attorney General Janet Reno ordered a 90-day preliminary inquiry
into whether Vice President Al Gore lied to investigators last year
when he was initially interviewed about his telephone solicitations
to donors from the White House. If there is evidence that Gore
misled investigators, Reno will be obligated under the independent
counsel law to refer the case to an outside prosecutor. (Stephen
Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) ROCKAWAY BEACH, N.Y. -- Aug. 26, 1998 --
HURRICANE-BEACHES, 8-26 -- Surfers riding hurricane influenced
waves at Rockaway Beach. A massive storm more than 450 miles
across, Hurricane Bonnie packed a one-two punch for the Carolina
coast Wednesday, and her strength was even felt at beaches in the
New York region. (James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) CAROLINA BEACH, N.C. -- Aug. 26, 1998 --
HURRICANE-BONNIE, 8-26 -- Carolina Beach resident Bob Bradley
covers his face as Hurricane Bonnie arrives at the New Hanover
County Beach mid morning on Wednesday. Bonnie, a storm more than
450 miles across, pounded the coastline with hurricane force winds,
torrential rains and a heavy surf for hours before the eye hit.
(Tyler Hicks/Wilmington Star-News)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- Aug. 26, 1998 -- NY-TRADEMARK-SKYLINE-2,
8-26 -- The neoclassical facade of the New York Stock Exchange, a
registered trademark. A number of New York City landlords, are
determined to treat architectural features as valuable and
exclusive assets. As a trademark, a building is no different from
any other three-dimensional object that plays such a role, like the
Pepperidge Farm Goldfish cracker or the Coca-Cola bottle. (Jack
Manning/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- Aug. 26, 1998 -- NY-TRADEMARK-SKYLINE-1,
8-26 -- The art deco spire of the Chrysler Building, is a
registered trademark. In New York, a growing number of landlords
are seeking to control the ways in which images and likenesses of
their distinctive buildings are used. The owners of the Chrysler
Building have demanded that Fishs Eddy, a tableware store, stop
selling a line of dishes, which depicts the building's Jazz Age
spire in a skyline border. (Jack Manning/New York Times Photo)
*LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) UNDATED -- Aug. 26, 1998 -- HOME-IMPROVEMENT-B&AMP;W, 8-26
-- Buying a new home can be an adventure, but it can also be a
nightmare if the house has major defects that go unnoticed until
after you move in. Ideally, the seller should disclose all
potential problems before the sale, but, unfortunately, many do
not, so buyers must make a careful inspection of the house before
they buy. (Edward R. Lipinski/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- Aug. 26, 1998 -- GERALDO-UPFRONT, 8-26 --
Geraldo Rivera and his co-anchor, Diane Dimond, on the set of the
half-hour news show, ``Upfront Tonight.'' To prevent Rivera from
going to the Fox News Channel, NBC has given him a six-year, $30
million contract that includes the half-hour news show. In the
partnership, Rivera gives NBC News ratings; NBC News gives him
instant respectability. (Norman Y. Lono/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Aug. 26, 1998 -- NY-SOHO, 8-26 -- An emblem
of SoHo's fading art scene, Rachel Whiteread's self-effacing
site-specific sculpture, ``Water Tower,'' far right. The work, a
life-size cast in greenish translucent resin of the interior of a
New York wood-slatted water tower, occupies that ubiquitous
structure's natural habitat, a life-size New York roof. (Sara
Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEWARK, N.J. -- Aug. 26, 1998 -- NJ-ARTS-CARPET-2, 8-26
-- The bathrooms at the New Jersey Performing Arts Center,
decorated with bright African patterned glass mosaics. The center
is one of the first major cultural institutions in the United
States to base its motifs on African decorative arts. (Suzanne
DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEWARK, N.J. -- Aug. 26, 1998 -- NJ-ARTS-CARPET-1, 8-26
-- The carpet at the New Jersey Performing Arts Center, in the
entrance foyer, uses syncopated, abstract African geometries.
Afrocentric motifs are rare in civic buildings, especially concert
halls, whose decorative schemes historically have been based on
Europe's aristocratic palaces and classical buildings or on
abstract modern compositions. (Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times
Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) SEATTLE -- Aug. 26, 1998 -- CIR-MUZAK, 8-26 -- In Muzak
extensive library, Alvin Collis, front, Rickio Woods, left, and Taj
Heniser, have been instrumental in the company's extensive image
makeover. ``Now businesses recognize that they can put the power of
music to work to create emotional connections.'' says Collis,
Muzak's vice president. (Robert Sorbo/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) ANDOVER, Mass. -- Aug. 26, 1998 --
CIR-VIDEO-CONFERENCING, 8-28 -- A videoconferencing demonstration
at Picturetel, the leading seller of videoconferencing equipment.
While the market for home videophones has not taken off, the use of
videoconferencing has skyrocketed in the corporate world in the
last several years, as companies try to cut travel costs and speed
products to market. (Rick Friedman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Aug. 26, 1998 -- CIR-FLAT-PANELS-2, 8-28 --
On the crowded desktops of a Barclays Bank trading room, most bulky
CRT's have been replaced with flat panels. In the last year, prices
for flat-panel displays have fallen by as much as two-thirds.
(Philip Greenberg/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Aug. 26, 1998 -- CIR-FLAT-PANELS-1, 8-28 --
If price were no object, flat-panel displays, like these, would
probably take over the computer monitor business overnight. These
slender new displays, which are essentially desktop versions of the
liquid crystal displays attached to high-end portable computers,
take up only a fraction of the desktop space hoarded by
conventional computer monitors, which are known as cathode-ray tube
displays. (Naum Kazdan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) LAKEWOOD, Calif. -- Aug. 26, 1998 -- CIR-WEB-MYSTERIES,
8-28 -- Marisa Babjak-Wiggins, who runs Femmes Fatales,
mall6.register.com/femfatal, a catalog of mystery gifts that she
sells on the Internet. Ms. Babjak, 39, web site opens a window on
hundreds of mystery-related Internet sites where people have taken
up residence to chat, read about their favorite authors, buy gifts
and books, solve whodunits and answer trivia questions. (Edward
Carreon/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) UNDATED -- Aug. 26, 1998 -- CIR-CARS-IDIOTS, 8-26 -- The
How to Drive Like a Moron (members.aol.com/doggiesnot) is decorated
with illustrations and animation crudely depicting bad driving
habits. This Web site is one of many sites inspired by the culture
and psychology of the roadway. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) UNDATED -- Aug. 26, 1998 -- CIR-HOLLERIN-ONLINE, 8-26 --
At http://sunsite.unc.edu/hollerin/hollerin.htm you can learn
everything you need to know about the art of hollerin'. According
to the Website, hollering is thought to be one of the earliest
forms of human communication, and falls into four categories:
functional, communicative, pleasure or distress, the latter known
for ``falsetto and a sense of urgency,'' though they pretty much
all fit that description. (New York Times Photos)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) UNDATED -- Aug. 26, 1998 -- CIR-TENNIS-ONLINE, 8-26 --The
two weeks of the U.S. Open are among the busiest times for many of
the hundreds of tennis-oriented Web sites on the Internet. From the
top, the U.S Open's official web site created by IBM at
www.usopen.org. Center is Tennis Worldwide Magazine at
www.tennisw.com, an all-purpose Web publication about tennis, has a
particularly personal and somewhat eclectic touch and Tennis
Server, which features extensive coverage about the fundamentals of
the game. (New York Times Photos)
</P>
