<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4141 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-SIDEBAR27-     08-26 0256
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-SIDEBAR27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Galarraga suspended for fight
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Houston, Texas _ To the surprise of no one, the National League
suspended Andres Galarraga on Wednesday. Just as predictably, the
Braves first baseman is going to appeal.
</P>
<P>
   NL president Len Coleman notified Galarraga via fax he would be
suspended three games and fined $1,000 for charging Los Angeles
right-hander Darren Dreifort after being hit by a pitch Saturday.
The suspension is effective today, though Galarraga is free to
continue playing until his appeal can be heard, most probably
during the Braves visit to New York next weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe the umpires don't know what happened before,'' said
Galarraga, alluding to the Aug. 16 game in L.A. when Dreifort hit
Galarraga a first time. ``It's almost automatic, anytime you fight
_ three games. It's not fair. I shouldn't get a suspension for any
days.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the Braves contention Dreifort threw purposefully at
Galarraga, a charge that is difficult to prove, even though the
first incident included words and gestures between the two players.
Though suspensions are rarely overturned, the Braves are eager for
a day in court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to wait to tell our side of the story,'' said
manager Bobby Cox, who lambasted Dreifort as an ``idiot'' after the
fight. ``It's not we're a team that has a problem with that type of
thing in the last nine years.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-26-98 2205EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980826.0515 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4142 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BONNIE27-COX     08-26 1415
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONNIE27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Damage piling up as N.C. takes brunt
 &HT;    By Steve Visser and Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOREHEAD CITY, N.C. -- Hurricane Bonnie continued to batter the
North Carolina coast Wednesday night after rumbling ashore at Cape
Fear at the southern end of the state.
</P>
<P>
   The extremely wide storm slowed to a forward crawl of 6 mph,
allowing 115 mph winds to pummel the historic city of Wilmington,
said Cathy Henry, a spokeswoman for the North Carolina Emergency
Management Agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of like stalled,'' she said early in the evening.
``Our coast is being pounded by hurricane-force winds. There won't
be a total on damage for weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the best ``guesstimate'' Wednesday was that the storm
would lay siege to North Carolina for 36 hours. ``But Bonnie has
been an unpredictable storm,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   No deaths or serious injuries were reported, but the massive
storm did a lot of damage in Brunswick County, especially along
Holden Beach and Caswell Beach. Winds ripped a roof off
Columbia-Brunswick Hospital, caused extensive flooding and knocked
down trees.
</P>
<P>
   The hurricane had wiped out electricity to more than 200,000
homes in North Carolina and 80,000 more in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Five people took refuge from the brunt of the storm in a
historic Bald Head Island lighthouse. They went back to their homes
later Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In Wilmington, wind gusts bent trees sideways, and torrential
rain came in stinging, horizontal sheets. A salt spray smell hung
in the air. Broken tree limbs and downed power lines littered some
areas of the city.
</P>
<P>
   The hurricane _ the third to hit Wilmington in two years _
surged ashore Wednesday afternoon at the Cape Fear River.
</P>
<P>
   The storm was expected to continue pushing slowly northward
through North Carolina throughout Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Gillikin was waiting for Bonnie in its full form in
Beaufort, N.C., and he knew enough about hurricanes to joke that it
helped to have a small brain or a large bottle to ride one out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was born and raised down here, and I've been through a lot
of them, and none have been pleasant,'' he said, weathering Bonnie
out in this town just south of the Cape Lookout National Seashore.
``This one is just going to be long. It's not the meanest one we've
ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   The storm followed a similar course to Bertha and Fran,
hurricanes that punished eastern North Carolina in July and
September 1996. Bonnie slowed as it passed near Wilmington,
spurring predictions that the huge storm would hurl sustained winds
and tidal surges throughout today as it plodded northward.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is just going on forever and forever,'' said Bruce
Williams, New Hanover County's agricultural extension director.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 500,000 people were ordered off North Carolina's coastal
islands and out of South Carolina's two northernmost coastal
counties ahead of the storm Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``After Hurricane Fran and Hurricane Bertha, I think people are
beginning to pay more attention to hurricane watches and
warnings,'' said Henry, the spokeswoman for the North Carolina
Emergency Management Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Three critical-care patients and a mother and her premature baby
at Columbia Brunswick Hospital in Supply were transferred Wednesday
afternoon to Grand Strand Hospital in Myrtle Beach after wind blew
off a section of roof of the Brunswick County hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wind got under one corner of the roof and lifted it off,''
Brunswick County spokesman Huey Marshall said. He described the
section of roof as the ''size of a golf cart.''
</P>
<P>
   The damage occurred near the hospital's electrical supply boxes,
so administrators were planning to close the hospital and transfer
patients to other facilities, Marshall said.
</P>
<P>
   Amid gusts that reached 110 mph, five Bald Head Island residents
left their homes Wednesday and broke into ``Old Baldy,'' a
lighthouse built in 1817. Another 42 people remained on the resort
island at the mouth of the Cape Fear Island, village manager Wade
Horne said.
</P>
<P>
   Horne said there were reports of minimal damage to homes and
some trees down.
</P>
<P>
   One Bald Head homeowner reported to Horne that he planned to
take his dog for a walk when he saw the sun come out during the
passing of the storm's eye.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was no major overwash and no infrastructure damage,''
said Horne, who had left Tuesday night. Despite an evacuation order
that required vacationers to leave and urged residents to do so,
Horne said, some residents claimed they were left behind by Bald
Head's boats.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are certain people on the island who would like to
portray that we left them,'' he said. ''We did not intentionally
leave people.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in Brunswick County, the storm blew the roof off a
bank on Sunset Beach, and a tidal surge washed over the two-lane
road at Caswell Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Trees fell on several homes in Calabash, a fishing village near
the South Carolina line. Tumbled trees knocked out electricity in
rural areas, although county officials couldn't provide an estimate
of how many residents lost power.
</P>
<P>
   Carteret County officials reported the storm blew away a roughly
60-foot section of Iron Steamer Pier at Pine Knoll Shores, a
community between Atlantic Beach and Emerald Isle.
</P>
<P>
   It was the sheer width of the storm that astounded Gillikin up
in Beaufort, which he said has historically been sheltered by
barrier islands from the brunt of storms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never heard of one this big. It's 140 miles from the eye
to the outside of the hurricane,'' he said. ``A 140 miles as the
crow flies is from here to Raleigh on both sides of the eye.''
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina officials prepared for the worst. Gov. Jim Hunt
had already requested federal disaster relief from President
Clinton and the Federal Emergency Management Agency, whose Atlanta
office would evaluate the request, Henry said.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina Power and Light Co. had 2,100 line and service workers
staged in inland cities like Raleigh and Florence, S.C., ready to
go to work once Bonnie did its damage.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman Mike Hughes said an additional 600 linemen were
expected to arrive from Tennessee, Georgia and Alabama on
Wednesday. ElectriCities _ a confederation of municipal power
systems in the state _ said it also had crews from Tennessee,
Georgia, Virginia and South Carolina on standby.
</P>
<P>
   Other states were helping out with the basics. Ten truckloads of
ice were on the way from Ohio, 10 truckloads of water were coming
from New York and a convoy of ``comfort stations'' was motoring
from Texas. The comfort stations include ice and water trucks and a
rest room truck.
</P>
<P>
   The state prisons had convicts lined up to help clear roads and
debris, as they did after Bertha and Fran.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in several towns and counties near Wilmington were
taking precautions against any looting even before the hurricane
hit. Carolina Beach officials enacted a curfew effective at 10:30
a.m. Wednesday. The curfew prevents anyone except for emergency
personnel from roaming the town. Kure Beach ordered a curfew
effective at 11:30 a.m. A countywide curfew was ordered for Pender
County from 9 p.m. Wednesday until 6 a.m. today.
</P>
<P>
   While emergency management officials warned the slow storm would
probably dump dumpsters of rain, North Carolina Agricultural
Commissioner Jim Graham said the state was much drier than it was
before Hurricane Fran and the low-water levels should avert some
flooding and associated pollution problems. The coast is the center
for the state's pork industry with nine million hogs, already in a
whirlwind of controversy because of pollution.
</P>
<P>
   ``As dry as it's been, I don't expect any (animal waste) lagoons
to overflow,'' Graham said. ``Bring the rain on. We can use it. ...
But we don't need it beating us on the head. The good Lord's
shining on us this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham said much of the tobacco crop already has been harvested,
but corn, soybeans and cotton are vulnerable because harvesting has
not yet started.
</P>
<P>
   Other officials were more worried about flooding. Richard Moore,
North Carolina's secretary of public safety, expressed concern
about strong winds raising water levels in the northeast sounds by
9 to 11 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not talking about one burst of water, like a tidal
wave,'' he said. ``We're talking about the water being backed up in
our sounds by the winds for as long as the hurricane lingers.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
