A4144 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DANIELLE-COX     08-26 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DANIELLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Danielle loses some of its strengthen
 &HT;    By Dan Moffett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. -- The angry Atlantic gave Florida more
worries and riptides Wednesday. Hurricane Bonnie stirred seas as it
exited and Hurricane Danielle stirred emotions as it approached.
</P>
<P>
   Waves as high as 8 feet pounded Palm Beach County's shoreline,
chasing swimmers out of the water and surfers into it.
</P>
<P>
   Danielle, a compact storm in a hurry, continued its dash to the
west-northwest but lost strength.
</P>
<P>
   Winds fell from 105 mph to 85, and the National Hurricane Center
expected no strengthening today.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are forecasting some weakening during the next 12 to 24
hours, but a gradual strengthening is indicated thereafter,'' said
Lixion Avila, a hurricane specialist at the center. ``It's a very
similar path to Hurricane Bonnie.''
</P>
<P>
   Moving at a brisk 21 mph, Danielle was expected to stay well
north of the Leeward Island of Anguilla, and forecasters said there
was only a slight chance the eye would pass within 65 miles of the
Virgin Islands or Puerto Rico by Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The strong surf generated by Bonnie's passing swept a Lake Worth
woman under the barnacle-covered north jetty at the Boynton Inlet
just before noon Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   An Ocean Inlet Park lifeguard, Brian Daub, 38, of Delray Beach,
and Florida Marine Patrol Officer Ron Simmons helped Rosa San
Miguel onto a buoy, until lifeguard Lt. Brad Cripps came with an
inflatable boat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The waves pushed her into the jetty and she was stuck in
there,'' Cripps said. ``(Daub) could see her face and he reached in
and grabbed her. If he hadn't been there, she would have been a
goner.''
</P>
<P>
   San Miguel was covered in scrapes from the rocks and pilings but
escaped serious injury.
</P>
<P>
   Most beachgoers thought better about venturing into the water.
</P>
<P>
   ``There weren't that many swimmers,'' said Julia Leo, Palm Beach
County beach patrol spokeswoman. ``They took one look at the surf
and just sunbathed instead.''
</P>
<P>
   Surf was breaking over the jetties at Jupiter Inlet and dozens
of surfers rode waves, but erosion south of the inlet was minor,
said lifeguard Paul Drucker. At nearby Carlin Park, 6-feet waves
were breaking onshore, said lifeguard Dave Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's off the scale,'' Taylor said. ``We recommended swimming
in DuBois Park (inside Jupiter Inlet) for weaker swimmers.''
</P>
<P>
   At Ocean Reef Park on Singer Island, surfers skipped work and
enjoyed the rare 4- to 6-foot swells.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took the whole week off work,'' said Terence Branch of
Delray Beach. ``This is the biggest it's been in a while. I'm my
own boss, so I make my own hours. I'll just have to make up for it
later.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Bussert, of Juno Beach, had two broken fingers, but went
surfing anyway. ``We've been waiting for this,'' he said. ``Waves
like this only come once in a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Nahed drove from Miami to surf at the park.
</P>
<P>
   ``The waves here are bigger. It's crazy,'' he said. ``It just
keeps getting better. When I heard about the hurricane, I was
hoping it would bring waves down south, too.''
</P>
<P>
   About 4:15 p.m. in the Boynton Inlet, a small boat capsized in
the strong current and two people were thrown into the water. A
patrol boat pulled them out and neither required medical attention,
said Joe Peloquin, safety supervisor for the six beaches in south
county.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a real good swimming day,'' Peloquin said. ``Most of
the people at the beach were staying out of the water. For
conditions like this, people were respecting it.''
</P>
<P>
   Delray Beach lifeguards made no rescues, though two young women
from Italy said they felt themselves being pulled into a rip
current and quickly swam clear, lifeguard Lt. Eric Feld said. ``A
lot of educated people (were) making sure they talked with the
lifeguards and swam near lifeguards,'' Feld said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a tropical wave near Cuba that forecasters thought
might develop into a depression faded as a threat but could still
bring some rain today.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got caught between Danielle and Bonnie and couldn't get its
act together,'' Avila said.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters called for cloudy skies today with a 30 percent
chance of rain and a high in the low 90s. The wind should diminish
to 10 mph and continue from the northeast, helping to reduce
humidity. The weekend forecast calls for scattered showers and
cloudy skies.
</P>
<P>
   Staff writers Eliot Kleinberg, Joe Brogan, Monika Gonzalez, Tim
Pallesen and Rachel Masory contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
