A4145 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-USAMATEUR-COMPTON     08-26 0530
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-USAMATEUR-COMPTON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Compton loss has no effect on stature
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rochester, N.Y. _ Erik Compton's abilities to inspire were
evident early in his U.S. Amateur experience. On Tuesday, during
the second round of qualifying, Compton was followed faithfully by
14-year-old Daniel Gilbert, a Rochester ninth-grader who has
undergone two heart surgeries.
</P>
<P>
   For Compton, 18, who for six years has carried the transplanted
heart of a donor under an 8-inch scar on his chest, they will go
down as his most heartwarming moments of what become a shattered
week on Wednesday. After qualifying play concluded Tuesday night,
Gilbert and his family entertained Erik and his parents, Eli and
Peter, with a barbecue dinner at their home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured if he could do it, so could I,'' said Daniel, who
read a newspaper article about Compton and eagerly awaited his
arrival at Oak Hill Country Club as his host in golf's showcase
amateur event. ``That's when he became my motivation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he followed every shot,'' said Compton, who will play
at the University of Georgia this fall. ``It was nice. I don't mind
talking about (the transplant), especially when it inspires people
like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Young Daniel was in the gallery again Wednesday as Compton, who
is from Miami, was upset by Auburn's Jason Dufner in his
first-round match 2 and 1. Shaken and depressed after the defeat,
Compton walked away from the scoring area, his head down. Up walked
little Daniel. Compton emerged briefly from his thoughts, put an
arm around the boy and said, ``Good luck, buddy.''
</P>
<P>
   Compton's appearance in the U.S. Amateur is a noteworthy
accomplishment, but it was difficult to convince him Wednesday, as
he reflected on a round that got away. Three-up early, Compton
allowed Dufner to go 1-up by 4-putting the 14th and totally lost
his concentration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I putted probably worse than anyone could have putted in the
whole world,'' Compton said.
</P>
<P>
   For Dufner, fully aware of Compton's medical history, the
victory was not without compassion for his opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to get too caught up in it emotionally,''
Dufner said. ``He's definitely had a rough go compared to everybody
else, but I just had to look at him as a golfer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe, it's all for the best,'' Compton said. ``If I putted
like that the rest of the week, I would never have had a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   The real chance, of course, came six years ago, when a new,
healthy heart could beat in Compton's chest, thanks to the family
of an anonymous car-accident victim in Tampa. Then 12 years old and
suffering from dilated congestive cardiomyopathy, which weakens and
enlarges the heart, Compton was at the time merely trying to
survive. Now he can lead a relatively normal life with twice-a-day
medication, regular biopsies and blood work. Erik's mother, Eli,
who is of Norwegian descent, doesn't mind that her son's medical
situation has become the reason for media inquiries. She likes to
say, ``He's a good golfer who just happens to have a transplant.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
