A4146 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-USAMATEUR-COX     08-26 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-USAMATEUR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kuchar advances with strong round at U.S. Amateur
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCHESTER, N.Y. _ For first-round matches in a title defense, it
was the equivalent of Evander Holyfield flooring his sparring
partner.
</P>
<P>
   Winning his last six holes and one-putting seven times,
defending champion Matt Kuchar, 20, of Georgia Tech defeated Jamie
Broce of Muncie, Ind., 8 and 7 Wednesday at Oak Hill Country Club
in his first-round match at the U.S. Amateur Championship. If
Kuchar's putter remains this hot, the Yellow Jacket junior could be
hanging around all week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you putt well, it's really tough on your opponent,''
Kuchar said. ``I played wonderfully today. It was all I could
want.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanford's Joel Kribel, Kuchar's opponent in the 1997 finals and
a loser to Tiger Woods in the 1996 semifinals, was not so fortunate
Wednesday. After emerging as the qualifying medalist with rounds of
70-66, Kribel was eliminated 2 and 1 by Texas Christian's J.J.
Henry of Fairfield, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ``To go as far as I have the last couple of years and then have
some high expectations, to happen like this in the first round is
really disappointing,'' Kribel said.
</P>
<P>
   Kuchar, who meets Florida Southern's Matthew Sagilo of
Clearwater, Fla., in the second round today, could face Spain's
Sergio Garcia, the British Amateur champion, in Friday's
quarterfinals. Third-round matches are this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia freshman Erik Compton of Miami, the first heart
transplant recipient to play in the U.S. Amateur, was eliminated in
the first round, 2 and 1, by Auburn's Jason Dufner. Also ousted was
Georgia's No. 1 player, Ryuji Imada, who was beaten by Bob Kearney
of Houston, 1-up.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech's Bryce Molder, of Conway, Ark., the nation's top
collegiate player last year, after being 2-down after 12 holes,
defeated David Miller of Daphne, Ala., 1-up, and today faces Jerry
Courville of Milford, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech's Mauricio Muniz bogeyed the 18th hole, but
prevailed 2 and 1 when his opponent, Brad Hyler of Raleigh
double-bogeyed. Muniz meets Richard Dukelow of Chicago today.
</P>
<P>
   Augusta's Charles Howell of Oklahoma State won his first-round
match against Australia's Cameron Percy, 4 and 2, and today plays
Ryan Lavoie of Pasco, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Andy McLendon of Carrolton won his match against Rich Morris of
El Dorado, Kan., 2 and 1, and today faces Bill Lunde of
Hendersonville, Nev.
</P>
<P>
   Jedd McLuen of Colbert, Ga., who shot a second-round 67 to make
match play, advanced with a 1-up, 21-hole victory over Chris
Mundorf of Greensboro, N.C. Wilfredo Morales of Columbus State lost
5 and 4 to Randy Leen of Dayton Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Notes...Storms that hit the course late Tuesday afternoon sent
scores soaring for players caught in the altered conditions.
Roswell's Mark Northey of Georgia was one of the victims, shooting
a 79 after a first-round 68 and failing to qualify for match play.
...Former USGA and PGA Tour official David Eger lost to Andy
Miller, son of Johnny Miller, 3 and 2.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
