<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 8/26/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or (212) 556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 26, 1998 -- FUNRAISING-RENO, 8-26 --
Attorney General Janet Reno ordered a 90-day preliminary inquiry
into whether Vice President Al Gore lied to investigators last year
when he was initially interviewed about his telephone solicitations
to donors from the White House. If there is evidence that Gore
misled investigators, Reno will be obligated under the independent
counsel law to refer the case to an outside prosecutor. (Stephen
Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) ROCKAWAY BEACH, N.Y. -- Aug. 26, 1998 --
HURRICANE-BEACHES, 8-26 -- Surfers riding hurricane influenced
waves at Rockaway Beach. A massive storm more than 450 miles
across, Hurricane Bonnie packed a one-two punch for the Carolina
coast Wednesday, and her strength was even felt at beaches in the
New York region. (James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) CAROLINA BEACH, N.C. -- Aug. 26, 1998 --
HURRICANE-BONNIE, 8-26 -- Carolina Beach resident Bob Bradley
covers his face as Hurricane Bonnie arrives at the New Hanover
County Beach mid morning on Wednesday. Bonnie, a storm more than
450 miles across, pounded the coastline with hurricane force winds,
torrential rains and a heavy surf for hours before the eye hit.
(Tyler Hicks/Wilmington Star-News)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- Aug. 26, 1998 -- NY-TRADEMARK-SKYLINE-2,
8-26 -- The neoclassical facade of the New York Stock Exchange, a
registered trademark. A number of New York City landlords, are
determined to treat architectural features as valuable and
exclusive assets. As a trademark, a building is no different from
any other three-dimensional object that plays such a role, like the
Pepperidge Farm Goldfish cracker or the Coca-Cola bottle. (Jack
Manning/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- Aug. 26, 1998 -- NY-TRADEMARK-SKYLINE-1,
8-26 -- The art deco spire of the Chrysler Building, is a
registered trademark. In New York, a growing number of landlords
are seeking to control the ways in which images and likenesses of
their distinctive buildings are used. The owners of the Chrysler
Building have demanded that Fishs Eddy, a tableware store, stop
selling a line of dishes, which depicts the building's Jazz Age
spire in a skyline border. (Jack Manning/New York Times Photo)
*LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) UNDATED -- Aug. 26, 1998 -- HOME-IMPROVEMENT-B&AMP;W, 8-26
-- Buying a new home can be an adventure, but it can also be a
nightmare if the house has major defects that go unnoticed until
after you move in. Ideally, the seller should disclose all
potential problems before the sale, but, unfortunately, many do
not, so buyers must make a careful inspection of the house before
they buy. (Edward R. Lipinski/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- Aug. 26, 1998 -- GERALDO-UPFRONT, 8-26 --
Geraldo Rivera and his co-anchor, Diane Dimond, on the set of the
half-hour news show, ``Upfront Tonight.'' To prevent Rivera from
going to the Fox News Channel, NBC has given him a six-year, $30
million contract that includes the half-hour news show. In the
partnership, Rivera gives NBC News ratings; NBC News gives him
instant respectability. (Norman Y. Lono/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Aug. 26, 1998 -- NY-SOHO, 8-26 -- An emblem
of SoHo's fading art scene, Rachel Whiteread's self-effacing
site-specific sculpture, ``Water Tower,'' far right. The work, a
life-size cast in greenish translucent resin of the interior of a
New York wood-slatted water tower, occupies that ubiquitous
structure's natural habitat, a life-size New York roof. (Sara
Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
