u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYMAYOR-FUNDRAISING-A     08-26 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYMAYOR-FUNDRAISING-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 CEDAR RAPIDS, Iowa: dinky shavers.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Other Republicans were more reserved in assessing Giuliani than
Kidwell, who seemed to bond with the mayor on some law-enforcement
level. Still, many said that the ``story of New York City'' _ as
they often referred to the re-emergence of the city as a safer,
kinder tourism mecca _ distinguished Giuliani in the parade of
politicians who have recently eaten their share of Iowa corndogs,
asking to be remembered in the months to come: former Vice
President Dan Quayle, House Speaker Newt Gingrich, Steve Forbes and
Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., are but a few.
</P>
<P>
   After all, they said, Giuliani is the one who, the comedian Jay
Leno tells them, cleaned up Times Square. He is the one who dressed
like an old woman on ``Saturday Night Live.'' But when it came to
whether they would actually support him as a presidential
candidate, many demurred _ complimenting his abilities, but
reserving judgment because of the obstacles that an Iowa caucus
presents to a moderate Republican from the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Iowa,'' explained David Yepsen, a political reporter
for the Des Moines Register. ``People can be very civil, very
hospitable. They'll hear him out.''
</P>
<P>
   After attending a fundraising event in Milwaukee on Tuesday
night, Giuliani began his Iowa tour in Iowa City, at a fundraising
luncheon for Rep. Jim Leach. More than 100 people paid $25 each to
dine on grilled-chicken salad, admire the American flag
centerpieces at their tables, and hear the mayor regale them with
stories from New York City. He was introduced by the Olympic
wrestler Dan Gable, who told of how his wife had recently visited
New York City, ``and it was as safe as her own house.''
</P>
<P>
   In a part of the country where murder is a titillating rarity,
Giuliani told of reducing the murder rate from 2,000 a year to
under 800, a statistic that had many in the audience shaking their
heads in disbelief. He also told of reducing the city's welfare
rolls, which once hovered at about 1.2 million people _ about a
third of Iowa's population. In a theme that is standard to his
on-the-road speeches, he talked of returning freedom to the city's
residents.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Barker, a retired high school principal, was so moved that
after the speech he made a point of shaking the mayor's hand and
thanking him for rejuvenating New York City, which he considered to
be ``our city as well.''
</P>
<P>
   But when asked whether he would support a Giuliani candidacy,
Barker laughed, took another bite of a chocolate chip cookie, and
delivered what amounted to a general letter of recommendation: ``I
don't know him that well. But he certainly has to be taken
seriously in whatever endeavor he chooses to pursue.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani then traveled 20 miles to Cedar Rapids to talk to
law-enforcement officials about fighting crime and, particularly,
drugs. He seized the opportunity to repeat his stand against
methadone, and to criticize the country's drug czar, Barry
McCaffrey, for promoting the use of the drug to stem the habits of
heroin addicts.
</P>
<P>
   After that speech, Grubbs extended his invitation to the caucus.
He later explained the complicated calculus behind his offer. If
enough candidates run in the caucus, then those against abortion
will split 75 percent of the vote, leaving 25 percent to the
moderates _ like Giuliani. As a result, he could finish second or
third.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, Giuliani's aides have informally conducted any number
of calculations. Publicly, Giuliani gave standard statements of
non-committal. ``The people of Iowa are concerned with the same
issues that the people of New York are concerned with,'' he said.
Asked whether he was flattered by being asked so often about his
future plans, he answered, ``It's better than being booed.''
</P>
<P>
   Then it was 70 miles to Waterloo, for a $50-a-plate fundraising
dinner for former Rep. Jim Ross Lightfoot, who is running for
governor. There Giuliani was alternately referred to as the
country's ``king of mayors'' and the man who had managed to make
even the citizens of New York friendlier.
</P>
<P>
   Again, Giuliani waved off questions about his aspirations,
saying that he would return to Iowa if he were asked to go golfing.
After concluding his speech, he and his aides left the Lightfoot
function for a private flight _ paid for by Iowa Republicans _ back
to New York City.
</P>
<P>
   But one aide had developed a quantitative analysis of his final
Iowa appearance for the day: six applause breaks and two standing
ovations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
