<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Sun-Diamond Unit to Pay Fine for Contributions   By Peter Sinton  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
A subsidiary of Sun-Diamond Growers pleaded guilty yesterday to
violating federal campaign finance laws and agreed to pay $480,250
in fines.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In its plea agreement with the Department of Justice, the
subsidiary, Sun-Land Products of California, acknowledged that in
1992 and 1993 it used stipends paid to outside directors to make
$37,000 of illegal campaign contributions to the Bush-Quayle
presidential campaign and Senator Robert Dole's political action
committee.
</P>
<P>
   To settle two misdemeanor counts, Sun-Land agreed to pay the
maximum $400,000 criminal fine, an $80,000 civil penalty to the
Federal Election Commission and $250 in special assessments.
</P>
<P>
   Sun-Land, which produces dried fruits and nuts for Sun-Diamond,
was originally investigated by independent counsel Donald Smaltz as
part of his probe of illegal gratuities by the giant Pleasanton
agricultural co-op and its units to former Secretary of Agriculture
Mike Espy.
</P>
<P>
   Once Smaltz's staff determined that Sun-Land's $2,500 stipends
to 16 nonmanagement directors benefited politicians other than
Espy, they turned over their findings to the Justice Department. A
federal law prohibits corporations from contributing to federal
election campaigns or directing others to make contributions.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, after issuing the stipends, unnamed Sun-Land managers
``suggested'' that the Bush-Quayle '92 Primary Committee receive
contributions. Subsequently, nonmanagement directors and certain
family members gave $16,000 to the Republican presidential
campaign. The following year, $21,000 in stipends similarly were
directed to Dole's Campaign America committee.
</P>
<P>
   Sun-Land said it is ``pleased to have this investigation come to
an end.''
</P>
<P>
   Independent counsel Smaltz has had mixed results in his case
against Sun-Diamond. Two years ago, a jury in the District of
Columbia convicted the co-op of one count of making illegal
gratuities worth $6,000 to Espy, two counts of mail fraud and five
counts of making illegal campaign contributions. But in March, a
federal appeals court threw out the gratuities conviction. Another
conviction against longtime Espy friend and former Sun-Diamond
executive Richard Douglas was overturned, but last month he was
fined $3,100 for lying to the FBI about making illegal gratuities
to Espy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
