<SLUG> BC-BRIDGESIDE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Traditional Pastimes Trump Other Web Games   By Benny Evangelista  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
Traditional games like hearts, chess, spades, backgammon and bridge
have become more popular among Internet game players than action or
role-playing games, according to the online research firm Jupiter
Communications.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``There's been a tremendous swing in momentum back toward card
games, parlor games, traditional games and away from the `Dune'
audience that helped build the hype for online gaming,'' said Mark
Mooradian, a director of consumer content research for Jupiter
Communications.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; Why the swing? Mooradian said traditional games attract a
wider audience who like the familiar games they grew up with. Also,
some action games suffer from ``time lag'' glitches, which don't
matter when you're playing a slower, problem-solving game like
bridge, he said.
</P>
<P>
   There are no clear statistics showing how many traditional game
players are online, but overall, Jupiter estimates about 3.7
million gamers will be online by the end of this year. That total
is expected to surge to 26.8 million by 2002, although there may be
a swing back toward action games by then as game console-makers
start to offer online services, Mooradian said.
</P>
<P>
   Online game revenues are projected to hit $81 million for 1998,
about double the total last year, and soar to $1.1 billion in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Old-time parlor games like bridge, blackjack and backgammon are
gaining more popularity at online sites like Microsoft's Internet
Gaming Zone, Yahoo Games and Mpath.
</P>
<P>
   For bridge players in particular, setting up a game online can
be easier than bringing partners together in one room. The most
experienced bridge players now practice online to keep sharp for
major tournaments, said David Silber, CEO of the American Contract
Bridge League.
</P>
<P>
   The ACBL, which is the game's major organizing group for North
America, has 165,000 members, but hopes online games will help
bring in new members in a game that has seen flat growth in the
past decade, Silber said.
</P>
<P>
   That would be good news for Matthew Clegg, a University of
California at Berkeley graduate who turned his online bridge
playing software into a $2 million a year business, OKbridge, based
in San Diego. The service, which has about 13,500 members paying an
average $99 per year, has found a niche among champion bridge
players and high-powered executives like Warren Buffett and Bear
Stearns CEO James Cayne.
</P>
<P>
   ``The World Bridge Federation estimates there are 1.5 million
people who play bridge competitively,'' Clegg said. ``There's quite
a lot of room for growth within the market of serious bridge
players.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
