<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 A Software Survivor, Symantec's CEO Says the Thrill Isn't Gone   By Tom Abate  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
When Gordon Eubanks started cranking out PC software way back in
1975, singer Paul Simon ruled the charts with his hit ``Still Crazy
After All These Years.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now 23 years later, as chief executive of Symantec Corp.,
Eubanks still is grinding out anti-virus software and, hopefully,
quarterly profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't many (computer) people from the '70s or even the
'80s who are still around,'' Eubanks reflected the other day,
citing a tiny club that includes Bill Gates and Steve Jobs.
</P>
<P>
   To be honest, Eubanks didn't invite me to his Cupertino
headquarters to stroll down memory lane. He was flogging Symantec's
new product, a $100 software suite called SystemWorks that includes
a slew of utilities to prevent disk crashes, repair system glitches
and cure viruses.
</P>
<P>
   Eubanks is a great source, one of the rare execs who is both
candid and accessible. So of course, I was happy to listen. But as
I sat there thinking this sounded like the software equivalent for
new-formula Metamucil, I wondered: How does Eubanks feel after all
these years on the job?
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  At 51, he's forced to compete with the likes of 43-year-old
Network Associates chieftain Bill Larson, who has boundless
ambition and a seemingly insatiable appetite for buying smaller
anti-virus and software utilities firms.
</P>
<P>
   So as politely as possible, I asked Eubanks whether the thrill
was gone.
</P>
<P>
   He blinked, like he couldn't understand why I'd ask.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a job like this, you're the steward of something more
important than yourself,'' he said. ``It isn't about making the
most money, it's about creating jobs and creating value for
customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Having survived the '70s and '80s, when many software firms
flopped because they made ``cool'' rather than ``useful'' their
watchword, Eubanks is fanatic about the corny notion of giving good
value.
</P>
<P>
   Eubanks insisted that his customer-care formula would repel the
onslaught of Network Associates and other barbarians.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can provide customers with a superior value, we're
betting we take more share from our competitors than from
ourselves,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Young blood: &LR;  Stephan Schambach is software's latest
wunderkind. At 28, he is chief executive of Intershop
Communications, a San Francisco firm that sells the software used
by companies like Hewlett-Packard and Electronic Arts to run their
electronic-commerce Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   In an industry of young studs, Schambach has an added
distinction. He and co-founders Wilfried Beeck, 38, and Karsten
Schneider, 34, are natives of what once was East Germany who caught
entrepreneurial fever after the Berlin Wall fell.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewed in his office overlooking Multimedia Gulch,
Schambach explained how Intershop's e-commerce software was a
byproduct of his first business _ selling and installing PCs in
Jena, in the former East Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Forced to phone in orders to his supplier, Schambach got tired
of waiting on hold. A self-described technology freak, Schambach
used a NeXT workstation, Steve Jobs' spectacular hardware failure
of the early '90s.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  But even in failure, NeXT spawned one insanely great thing:
The World Wide Web was developed on NeXT computers, and Schambach
was one of the first to plug in.
</P>
<P>
   So in his spare time, Schambach wrote a program to put his
supplier's 20,000-product inventory into a Web page. He offered to
sell the software to his supplier in 1994. When they refused, he
offered to give it away to save the aggravation of ordering by
phone.
</P>
<P>
   When the supplier again refused, Schambach decided to start
Intershop. In 1996, he got $1 million in seed funding from one of
Germany's two venture capital firms and flew to San Francisco to
locate his new company in the heart of Net country.
</P>
<P>
   Today, he employs 100 people in San Francisco and another 150 or
so in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Intershop went public on the Neuer Markt, Germany's
version of the Nasdaq, where investors valued it at $900 million.
</P>
<P>
   Schambach smiled as he told me the punch line. About the same
time Intershop was going public, his old supplier, the one that
wouldn't take his software for free, sold itself to a larger firm
for about one-ninth of Intershop's market cap.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, to be young, rich and enjoy such revenge!
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; No exit? &LR;  How does Silicon Valley cook up so many companies
and create so many jobs? Insiders cite three reasons: lots of smart
entrepreneurs, plenty of early stage money to back startups, and a
stock market receptive to new offerings, giving financiers and
execs an ``exit strategy'' _ that is, a way to get rich quick.
</P>
<P>
   Other countries have the brains, and some are developing
Valley-style venture funds. What has been lacking is stock markets
to buy up shares in young firms to create this exit path.
</P>
<P>
   That's why I think the Neuer Markt, which has listed some two
dozen companies and created 4,500 jobs since it opened last spring,
is a story of a German high-tech Renaissance waiting to be told.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a tip, gripe or brainstorm? Tom Abate wants to hear it by phone
(650-961-2689), fax (650-961-5023) or e-mail (abate(at
sign)sfgate.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
