<SLUG> BC-ROBOTICS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 New Robotics Tap the Mind, Help the Heart   By Jamie Beckett  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Heart bypass operations that require a deep chest incision could
soon be done with no more than a skin cut.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scientists unveiled yesterday a new robotic device, developed by
a Peninsula firm, that will allow doctors to perform the complex
operation by slipping a pencil-size instrument through a small cut
and controlling it remotely.
</P>
<P>
   The device &UR;  &LR; was among a host of new robotic technologies,
including artificial muscles and robotic Legos, which SRI
International in Menlo Park showed off yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The presentation was part of a promotion for the robotic Legos,
which SRI helped develop. The toy, called Lego Mindstorm, is being
rolled out next week.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  SRI, a not-for-profit research center spun off by Stanford
University in the 1960s, has been the birthplace of some of Silicon
Valley's most important innovations, including the modem, the mouse
and liquid-crystal display technology.
</P>
<P>
   The 50-year-old center has created technology behind such
wind-ranging products as household laundry detergent,
high-definition television, a medicine for malaria and a
telecommunications system for the hearing impaired.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The institute has been building robots since the 1960s, when a
roomful of computers was needed to operate a single robot costing
millions of dollars. Now, SRI is building sophisticated robots like
a mine-detection robot that can be mass-produced for as little as
$2,500, said S. Venkat Shastri, senior research scientist.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Some of the institute's work is independent. Other research
is conducted under contract for government or commercial clients.
In the past few years, the institute has been spinning off
businesses with commercial potential. Total revenues from all
ventures top $300 million.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; One spin-off, Intuitive Surgical of Mountain View, is working
on a new surgical technique based on technology developed at SRI
that makes it possible for doctors to use minimally invasive
surgery for complex operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't cut you open with this technology,'' said Joel
Jensen, program manager at SRI. ``Instead of making a big incision,
the surgeon just pokes a tubelike instrument between the ribs.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike current instruments, which are hard to manipulate,
so-called telepresence instruments mimic the movements of the
surgeon's hand.
</P>
<P>
   SRI's device looks like a video arcade game. The surgeon sits at
a console, looks at a 3-D image and grasps the control handles.
Watching the screen, the doctor manipulates the surgical
instruments quickly and precisely _ just as in conventional
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Several tests of the new cardiac surgery were performed this
year, and Intuitive Surgical is in the process of applying to the
FDA for approval to market the system commercially.
</P>
<P>
   While Jensen performed mock surgery in one corner of the room,
Roy Kornbluh used electrical impulses to make an artificial
butterfly's wings flap.
</P>
<P>
   Kornbluh, a research engineer, is part of a team making
artificial muscles that work like real ones. Eventually, the
muscles may be used in prosthetic hands and other limbs, but
scientists currently are working with U.S. defense agencies on a
more unusual kind of project: building robotic bugs.
</P>
<P>
   The bugs _ cockroaches, mainly, and some butterflies _ could be
used as tiny spies, infiltrating enemy territory unnoticed,
Kornbluh said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you going to pay attention to a butterfly fluttering
around you? Probably not,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The bugs use artificial muscles made from rubber and electrodes
and controlled by a microprocessor. They can carry tiny cameras or
microphones and send data back to military officials, transmitting
information about hostage situations, pictures of buildings,
battlefield terrain or even enemy positions.
</P>
<P>
   The bugs represent the newest generation of robots at SRI.
</P>
<P>
   Other projects include a robot called Magpie being used by Osaka
Gas of Japan to inspect gas lines. The same technology could be
used to inspect sewer lines, Shastri said, acting as ``remote
roto-rooters.''
</P>
<P>
   SRI is also developing robots that look for hidden land mines,
Shastri said.
</P>
<P>
   Also on display was a simple robot-building kit developed by
SRI, MIT and Lego that will be mass produced and sold in stores,
starting next week.
</P>
<P>
   Called the Lego Mindstorm, the $200 kit contains all the
equipment _ microprocessor, CD-ROM, 727 Lego pieces, light and
touch sensors and two motors _ needed to build a robot that can
walk across a table, wink, and deal cards. Kids can program the
robot to do other things as well.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists see the kit as a tool for learning and creativity:
Kids learn simple programming and problem-solving and get to put
their ideas into action.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
