<SLUG> BC-FAA-AIR-SAFETY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIR TRAFFIC CONTROLLERS TESTIFY ABOUT OLD, FAILING EQUIPMENT
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JOHN T. McQUISTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RONKONKOMA, N.Y. _ Even though the government has spent many
millions of dollars to upgrade air traffic control equipment in the
New York area, several controllers and technicians testified
Wednesday that much of the indispensable electronics gear at
airports and control centers in the region is aging and close to
failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of it's being held together with spit and gum,'' said
Henry Brown, a representative of the Professional Airways Systems
Specialists union. Noting that much of the equipment was 35 years
old, he said: ``In some cases we have no spare parts left on the
shelf and have to go shopping at Radio Shack. We need to update and
repair our aging critical systems before any more rubber meets the
runway.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, whose union has long been at odds with the Federal
Aviation Administration, was among several witnesses who testified
at a public hearing at a Long Island hotel held by Rep. John
Duncan, R-Tenn., chairman of the House Transportation Subcommittee
on Aviation.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing was called at the request of Rep. Michael Forbes, a
Republican whose district encompasses much of eastern Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems each year in New York we are presented with evidence
of something seriously wrong in our skies,'' Forbes said. ``Error
rates are highest in the New York region, and the New York center
that controls all flights entering New York airspace has an error
rate over three times the national average. It's high time the
Federal Aviation Administration responded.''
</P>
<P>
   James Hevelone, the FAA's regional facilities manager, said the
agency was working to reduce the error rate, and he disputed
Brown's contention about the older equipment as a gross
exaggeration. ``We have brought in a lot of new state-of-the-art
equipment, and it's held together with modern materials and
technology,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hevelone said that older equipment was carefully monitored and
that 99.8 percent of it was operational at all times, and backed up
by an adequate supply of redundant equipment.
</P>
<P>
   In his testimony, Brown acknowledged that engineers and
technicians did manage to keep the equipment running 99.8 percent
of the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we have to work our people to death to do it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Air traffic controllers said at the hearing that efforts by the
government to train more controllers were falling far short of the
number projected by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Monaghan, a representative of the National Air Traffic
Controllers Association, which has battled the FAA for two decades,
noted that there had been ``an alarming increase in the number and
severity of operational errors and near midair collisions'' at the
metropolitan area's three major airports over the last two and a
half years.
</P>
<P>
   He said there had been one nonfatal accident, 11 near-collisions
and approximately 22 less serious violations of federal rules, all
due to controller errors, which he attributed to cuts in staff and
lack of qualified replacements.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Hatfield, the FAA's New York regional air traffic manager,
told the hearing that the number of controllers working in the New
York region had increased during the last two years from 218 to
340.
</P>
<P>
   However, he said that only 235 members of the staff were fully
qualified.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-26-98 2223EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
