<HEADLINE>
SENSOR DEVICE MAY AID MINIMED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Officials at MiniMed Inc. said say the company
could see an unexpected boost in 1998 sales after the U.S. Food and
Drug Administration granted an expedited review to its blood
glucose sensor.
</P>
<P>
   If review of the device goes smoothly, MiniMed could begin
marketing the sensor on a limited basis as early as this fall, said
President Terrance Gregg.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fully expect this product to be approved by the end of this
year and then limited release into commercial channels,'' Gregg
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts believe sales of the device could add a few hundred
thousand dollars in fourth-quarter revenue, though Gregg would not
comment on projected sales.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Phillip Nalbone at investment bank Volpe Brown Whelan in
San Francisco said within three years the glucose sensor could
generate $30 million in annual sales for MiniMed. ``We think the
medical community will really embrace the idea of continuous
glucose monitoring,'' Nalbone said.
</P>
<P>
   Existing methods for testing a diabetic's blood-sugar level
generally involve pricking a finger with a pin and squeezing out a
drop of blood for testing. In addition to being painful, the method
offers only a snapshot of the glucose level at the moment of the
test.
</P>
<P>
   MiniMed's sensor, which is inserted under the skin of the
abdomen and can be worn for up to three days before being replaced,
offers continuous monitoring, offering patient and doctor a clearer
picture of daily blood sugar cycles and allowing for more
aggressive treatment of diabetes, Nalbone said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, if a patient's glucose level falls dangerously low, the
sensor will sound an alarm, alerting the person to take a dose of
insulin. MiniMed already markets an external insulin infusion pump
that provides a steady flow of insulin into the bloodstream over
the course of the day.
</P>
<P>
   MiniMed shares fell 50 cents Wednesday to close at $58.125.
</P>
</TEXT>
