<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONNIE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BONNIE HOWLS ASHORE IN NORTH CAROLINA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By TONY FREEMANTLE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, N.C. _ Hurricane Bonnie howled ashore near here
Wednesday afternoon and then slowed to a dangerous crawl, raising
fears of severe flooding Thursday as it continued to unleash heavy
rains.
</P>
<P>
   As of late Wednesday, no deaths or serious injuries were
reported from the storm, which carried winds of 115 mph and spawned
tornado watches inland. Power was cut to more than 500,000 people,
roads were flooded and commercial signs and trees were twisted and
flattened. A hospital lost its roof in Brunswick County.
</P>
<P>
   But residents who had stayed behind in lowland and coastal towns
that were nearly emptied by massive evacuations Tuesday were
surprised by the storm's slow, sloppy advance.
</P>
<P>
   The area, no stranger to hurricanes, was raked as recently as
1996 by Hurricane Fran, a smaller storm that crashed ashore,
smashing hundreds of homes and killing several people.
</P>
<P>
   The main threat late Wednesday was slow inundation from hours of
heavy rain as Bonnie languished over the coastline.
</P>
<P>
   The storm hit land at Cape Fear, slowing from 16 mph to 4 mph
after it landed. Forecasters said it could stay over North Carolina
for more than a day and drop 20 inches of rain before veering out
to sea farther north near Virginia. Tides were expected to reach 11
feet above normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not talking about one burst of water, like a tidal
wave,'' state Public Safety Secretary Richard Moore told The
Associated Press. ``We're talking about the water being backed up
in our sounds by the winds for as long as the hurricane lingers.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Knight, spokesman for the North Carolina Emergency
Management Services, said the eye of Bonnie passed over Wilmington
at 8 p.m., EDT, and was moving slowly north. But he said much of
the huge storm, which stretched 400 miles wide, remained out at
sea.
</P>
<P>
   Knight said 121 shelters had been opened in North Carolina to
absorb some of the thousands of evacuated residents and tourists.
About 11,000 people were in shelters Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Some coastal residents ignored evacuation warnings and spent
Wednesday watching their boats rocking in the chop of the
intercoastal waterway.
</P>
<P>
   Marjorie Cartier stood on the expansive veranda of her
Wrightsville Beach home looking across the water, trying hard not
to think about the storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to talk about it,'' she said grimly of the
prospect of damage to her house. ``Besides, what's the point? You
can't control Mother Nature.''
</P>
<P>
   Like thousands of other New Hanover County residents, Cartier
had lost electrical power to her home about 2 a.m. Wednesday, but
kept her gas and telephone.
</P>
<P>
   County officials said that at the height of the storm at least
97,000 Carolina Power and Light customers were without electricity.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the day Wednesday, New Hanover County emergency
management officials were expressing cautious optimism that they
had seen the worst of what Bonnie had to offer even though the
``backside'' of the storm was still to pass over the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a storm, a strong storm,'' said Allen O'Neal, New
Hanover County manager. ``It was a little worse than Bertha, but
not nearly as bad as Fran. At this point, though, it looks like we
may be lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Bertha also made landfall near here in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   One official said preliminary reports indicated minor damage
from Bonnie to the county's three, fragile barrier islands _
Wrightsville, Carolina and Kure beaches _ and their structures.
</P>
<P>
   However, officials cautioned that if Bonnie stalled and dumped
rain for several days flooding and erosion would be severe.
</P>
<P>
   Renee Hoffman, with the North Carolina Emergency Management
Services, said low lying areas would be inundated and barrier
islands might be re-sculpted ``When you have a storm this size
behaving the way this one is we have the potential of new inlets
being cut and there is some evidence that this is already
occurring,'' she said, comparing Bonnie to Hurricane Hazel in the
1950s. That hurricane followed a similar slow pattern and caused
storm surges that carved new breaches in the state's barrier
islands.
</P>
<P>
   Relative to other Category 3 hurricanes, however, initial damage
Wednesday from Bonnie was moderate. Officials said the damage would
mount as the storm lingered.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, the Brunswick Columbia HCA hospital in Brunswick
County lost part of its roof. Thirty-one patients, including a
premature infant born Tuesday night, had to be evacuated to Myrtle
Beach, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   David Wittmer, a ``semi-retired'' construction engineer stood in
his front yard near Wilmington after the winds and rain had
subsided and looked at his neighbors' flooded homes. His house,
which stood on a hill only a few yards higher, was dry.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can quote me on this,'' he said. ``I hate these things
now. After Bertha and Fran, I'm really getting to hate them.''
</P>
<P>
   As Bonnie approached the North Carolina coast Tuesday, officials
in that state, South Carolina and Virginia had ordered the
evacuation of 500,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   David and Linda Myers and their four children heeded that order
and spent the night at the Topsail Middle School. On Wednesday,
along with nearly 300 others, they sat and waited while Bonnie made
up her mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll probably stay here until the weather breaks, whenever
that is,'' David Myers said.
</P>
<P>
   Some officials predicted that break might not arrive for 36
hours.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
