<DOCNO> NYT19980826.0539 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 22:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4188 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-CON-ED--NYT &LR;      08-26 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CON-ED--NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATERFRONT SITES FOR SALE, ALL EQUIPPED WITH GENERATORS
</HEADLINE>
   (rm) 
 By LESLIE EATON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's not every day that 88 acres of waterfront
property _ some with spectacular views of Manhattan _ go on sale in
New York City. But there is little chance that luxury apartment
buildings will rise on these sites any time soon; the parcels for
sale include the huge power plants that have supplied New Yorkers
with electricity for decades, and will continue to do so for the
foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
   Consolidated Edison, under pressure from regulators, is
reluctantly selling virtually all of its electric generation
stations in the city. The sale marks the end of an era that began a
century ago, as Thomas A. Edison was perfecting the light bulb and
creating the company that would supply power to almost all New
Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   The properties include landmarks like the Ravenswood generating
station, with its three striped smokestacks, at the foot of the
59th Street Bridge in Queens.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly who is interested in the properties should become clear
early next year, when Con Ed expects to announce the winning
bidders in an auction that began this month. Con Ed's investment
advisers at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter have sent information to
more than 100 potential buyers.
</P>
<P>
   While any billionaire with a yen for power is a theoretical
possibility, the most likely buyers are other power companies,
according to the utility and its regulators.
</P>
<P>
   In the short run, neither customers nor passers-by will notice
much difference after the plants change hands. ``The only thing
they'll see that's different is the name on the plants,'' said
Andrew L. Jacob, Con Ed's chief engineer for energy management, who
is running the sale.
</P>
<P>
   But in the longer term, the sale should help reduce electric
rates for city consumers and businesses, who pay some of the
highest prices in the country, said Maureen Helmer, chairwoman of
the New York State Public Service Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators hope to force electric companies to compete against
one another to generate power the way that long-distance companies
now compete to provide telephone service. Generation costs account
for a third to a half of a customer's electric bill.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, customers will be able to choose the generating
company that gives them the best deal. When generating companies
make their money based on how much energy they sell, rather than on
how much money regulators allow them to charge, they will have
incentives to operate more efficiently, Helmer said.
</P>
<P>
   Con Ed will continue to distribute electricity to homes and
businesses, and, of course, to send bills. It will buy electricity
from other utilities, generate some through its ownership of the
Indian Point 2 nuclear plant near Buchanan in Westchester County,
and have the ability to generate a relatively small amount at
plants that also generate steam.
</P>
<P>
   But almost all of its generators in the city are on the block.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the Ravenswood plant, the generating stations, which
last year supplied 23 percent of the electricity Con Ed sold to
customers, include the giant Astoria plant near the Triborough
Bridge; the Arthur Kill station, whose lone smokestack rises over
western Staten Island near the Fresh Kills landfill, and two gas
turbines located on barges off Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   The properties have been divided into three ``bundles,'' each of
which must go to a different buyer.
</P>
<P>
   The plants employ about 700 people, and Con Ed officials say
they hope those workers will be hired by whoever buys the plants.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Con Ed officials nor Helmer of the commission would
speculate on how much money the plants might bring. For accounting
purposes, the company values the generators at about $1.2 billion,
Jacob said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, New York State Energy &AMP; Gas announced that
it and a partner had sold a generating station in Pennsylvania for
$1.8 billion, or almost $1,000 for each kilowatt it can generate.
At that rate, Con Ed's plants could fetch more than $5 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-26-98 2233EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
