<DOCNO> NYT19980826.0540 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 22:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4190 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-PREVIEW-WAC-TEX     08-26 1479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-PREVIEW-WAC-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPENDING BREAKUP GIVES WAC A PECULIAR FEELING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is little doubt that defending champion Colorado State
ranks as the preseason marquee team in the Western Athletic
Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Loaded with veterans and riding a nine-game winning streak
capped by a bowl victory, Sonny Lubick's Rams represent the
league's best early hope for national recognition.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Rams' growing popularity is such that their annual
in-state brawl with Colorado has been moved to Denver's Mile High
Stadium to accommodate the expected crowd.
</P>
<P>
   All of which prompted a member of the Colorado media to approach
WAC commissioner Karl Benson recently and remark, ``Well, I guess
we'll see you on Sept. 5.''
</P>
<P>
   To which Benson replied, ``You will if you're in Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the third, last, and probably ugliest season in the
brief history of the 16-team WAC. Next June, according to the
announced scenario, eight members _ Colorado State, Wyoming, Air
Force, Brigham Young, Utah, New Mexico, San Diego State and
Nevada-Las Vegas _ will take their ball and form a new league.
</P>
<P>
   So, as far as Benson is concerned, the Rams can trample Michigan
State in their opener (Aug. 29), rise to Mile High glory against
Colorado and cover themselves with national acclaim, and it will
matter little.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 5, Benson will be in Rice Stadium watching the Owls and
SMU, two members of next year's WAC, of which he will still be
commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Those two will be joined by TCU, Tulsa, UT-El Paso, Fresno
State, San Jose State, Hawaii and, possibly, a guest or two to be
named later.
</P>
<P>
   Just how long that configuration will last is anyone's guess _
and everybody has one _ but Benson is certain of one thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This,'' he said, ``is going to be an awkward year.''
</P>
<P>
   It began in the spring, when Benson was lying in bed at home,
recuperating from eye surgery, and the phone rang.
</P>
<P>
   The voice on the other end was that of Dr. Albert Yates, the
Colorado State president, calling with the remarkable news that the
presidents of eight universities had managed to hold secret talks,
concoct an alliance, and were severing all ties with the WAC.
</P>
<P>
   Given the myriad problems the WAC had _ it was hurriedly
conceived, snubbed by the Bowl Alliance, suffered from logistical
problems and insufficient revenue sources, and had the geographical
cohesiveness of OPEC _ the decision to break it up was not all that
surprising.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as New Mexico basketball coach Dave Bliss said last year,
``There's a reason why nobody else has a 16-team league.''
</P>
<P>
   The manner in which it was done, however, left a bad taste in
several mouths.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really shocking,'' said Rice athletic director Bobby
May. ``Whoever choreographed this thing certainly did not have the
league's best interests at heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically it started out with three presidents talking, and
that became five. Pretty soon they had eight, and they just decided
to bolt. It's pretty amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   SMU athletic director Jim Copeland has similar thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure the eight schools that did this really thought
this thing through before they made their decision,'' he said.
``But it's done now, and there's no turning back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure some of the meetings this year will be a little
stressful.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the catalyst for the split was a realignment plan that
separated Air Force from traditional rivals Colorado State and
Wyoming, the WAC simply had too many problem areas for survival in
16-team form.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knew the league was too big,'' said Wyoming AD Lee
Moon, whose son, Lee Jr., was a freshman guard on TCU's basketball
team last year, ``but there was no mechanism for asking people to
leave. There was no other way to do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that it's done, Benson said, a large headache remains.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job will be to try and wear two hats, represent both
factions for one more year, but it will be difficult,'' he said.
``There are many issues to be resolved, including some legal ones.
One of the most difficult things, probably, is that in the future
we will be competing with the other group for television contracts,
bowl bids, and a number of other things.''
</P>
<P>
   Benson said he strongly feels the snub of fifth-ranked BYU by
the Bowl Alliance in '96 was a blow from which the WAC never really
recovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of revenue was involved, along with a major stake in how
the WAC was perceived nationally,'' he said. ``It was a major blow
to everyone in the league, and I'm sure that a lot of the thought
process that led to this was set in motion then.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the league is struggling to salvage ties to the Holiday and
Cotton bowls, and could be facing a scenario this year where its
champion winds up in the Aloha.
</P>
<P>
   Projections (and rumors) about the future of the remaining WAC
include expansion, or a situation in which the remaining members
scatter to whatever havens are available. At UTEP, abandoned by old
pal New Mexico at the last moment, athletic director Bob Stull is
even talking about a revived Southwest Conference.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, there are mostly brave smiles. But there has
also been a meeting of the abandoned eight, and some are feeling
life might not be so bad after all.
</P>
<P>
   At SMU, where Mike Cavan's football team had a winning season
and challenged for a division title, things are on the upswing.
Football recruiting has picked up, both basketball teams are
strong, alums are flocking back, and a $53 million facilities
upgrade, including a new stadium, is in progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've already had a meeting, and I think there was definitely
a sense of solidarity,'' Copeland said of the remaining eight.
``It's a little strange to have teams on our schedule this year
that we're not really in the same league with anymore, but there's
nothing we can do about that.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a league, we need to look at a lot of things _ bowls, TV,
revenue sharing _ and that process is beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   Drawing a contrast with the situation three years ago, Copeland
said he thinks SMU is both better-positioned, and looking at
different goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we joined the WAC, our supporters were just thankful that
we were in a league,'' Copeland said. ``But there really wasn't
much of a sense of identity with our new partners, and it was hard
to build enthusiasm. And even then, people just weren't real sure
about this league.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time, we are definitely working on the commitment that we
have to be in a strong league, whatever that turns out to be. I
think that this time, we will be in a position to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   During the past three years, the school has acquired an
energetic new president, R. Gerald Turner, and Copeland has made
strong hires in football (Cavan) and men's basketball (Mike
Dement). Rhonda Rompola's women's basketball team is a perennial
winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had our best fund-raising year since the mid-'80s, and we
get the plans for the new stadium Sept. 1,'' Copeland said. ``What
we're going through now ... we have no doubt that we will emerge at
the other end in good shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a matter of getting from here to there.''
</P>
<P>
   At Rice, Ken Hatfield has put together back-to-back 7-4 seasons,
average attendance has climbed to 35,000, and future schedules
include Texas, Michigan, Nebraska and Oklahoma. Women's basketball
is strong, and Wayne Graham's baseball team is a national power,
playing in four consecutive regionals and reaching the College
World Series two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel a little differently than we did when the SWC
folded,'' May said. ``Back then, it was pretty frightening, but
this time we feel that in most respects we're where we want to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, realistically the WAC is a moving target right now.
There's a lot of uncertainty, and that may not be a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there are rapid changes all over the industry these days,
and they occur in a very short time frame. There are likely to be
changes all around us in the next few years _ things popping up
with other leagues _ and you never know what that will bring.''
</P>
<P>
   For the present, May said, things could be worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an eight-team league, and we have to make it the best
that it can be,'' he said. ``There are some distant destinations
that will put more of a strain on our budget, but that goes with
it. It could also expand to nine schools or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the increased exposure in football and baseball the
last few years has helped us; it has given us a chance to put what
Rice stands for on display, and we have an underdog quality that
people seem to identify with.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyway, about all any of us can do right now is play the cards
we were dealt. It may not be the situation you would have picked
for yourself ... but we didn't have that option.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
