<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CRISIS IN RUSSIA WORSENS AS COUNTRY ABANDONS RUBLE
</P>
<P>
   The Central Bank of Russia said it could no longer afford to
protect the ruble after spending $8.8 billion doing so in the last
two months. With the ruble poised for a free fall, the acting prime
minister, Viktor Chernomyrdin, went to Ukraine to try to persuade
the head of the International Monetary Fund not to cut off its next
installment of $4.8 billion in credits.
</P>
<P>
   The market turmoil in Russia, the plunge of the ruble, the
increase in prices and the banking crisis led that country's
financial barons to reassert themselves and install an acting prime
minister who will accede to their concerns.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis in Russia has caused turmoil in Latin America. It has
pummeled the region's markets, caused currencies to drop and forced
interest rates so high that some bankers are urging customers not
to borrow. Analysts are lowering what had been healthy growth
estimates for Latin America for next year and perhaps beyond.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS DECLINE ON PROFIT CONCERNS
</P>
<P>
   Stocks fell as the Russian crisis deepened fears that slumping
economies around the world would cut corporate profits. The Dow
Jones industrial average decreased 79.30 points, to 8,523.35. The
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index declined 8.66, to 1,084.19, and
the technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index dropped 30.04, to
1,768.13. The Russell 2000 index of small stocks fell 9.34, or 2.4
percent, to 380.42.
</P>
<P>
   JUDGE HALTS THE SALE OF CREDIT DATA
</P>
<P>
   A federal administrative law judge ordered one of the United
States' largest credit bureaus, Trans Union Corp., to stop selling
detailed credit information from consumers to advertisers and
marketers without the consumers' permission. Trans Union said it
would appeal. The company maintains financial records on as many as
200 million Americans.
</P>
<P>
   MERCK IN ACCORD WITH FTC
</P>
<P>
   Merck &AMP; Co. and its Merck-Medco Managed Care unit have agreed
with the Federal Trade Commission to bar Medco from discriminating
against drugs made by Merck's competitors or exploiting private
marketing information about other drug makers that Medco receives.
</P>
<P>
   STARWOOD SET TO CHANGE STRUCTURE
</P>
<P>
   Starwood Hotels and Resorts Worldwide is expected to announce
Thursday that it will convert to a standard corporate structure.
Starwood recently lost a battle with Congress and the White House
to extend the tax advantages of its corporate structure as a
``paired share'' real-estate investment trust.
</P>
<P>
   DURABLE GOODS ORDERS ROSE IN JULY
</P>
<P>
   Orders placed with the nation's manufacturers for durable goods
unexpectedly rose 2.4 percent in July as demand for aircraft and
electronics offset a fall in auto orders linked to the General
Motors strikes. Excluding transportation goods, durable goods
orders rose 3 percent in July.
</P>
<P>
   HARNISCHFEGER TO CUT 3,100 JOBS
</P>
<P>
   Harnischfeger Industries said it would cut about 3,100 jobs, or
20 percent of its work force, because a glut of paper was reducing
demand for its products. The company also reported a quarterly loss
that was wider than analysts had expected.
</P>
<P>
   RESEARCHERS SHRINK COMPUTER CHIP
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at Texas Instruments have invented a computer-chip
manufacturing technology that will allow the company to build the
tiniest transistors ever, with a length of just 0.07 micron _ a
thousandth of the thickness of a human hair.
</P>
<P>
   LONG BOND YIELD PLUNGES TO 5.42 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the 30-year Treasury bond declined slightly to 5.42
percent, from 5.43 percent on Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
