<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bautista out with ailing knee
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Outfielder Danny Bautista left the team Wednesday and
returned to Atlanta for an MRI on his right knee. Thought at first
to have sustained a mere bruise in a Monday collision with Los
Angeles catcher Tom Prince, subsequent examinations found the knee
to be so loose that trainer Dave Pursley sent him for a
precautionary examination by team orthopedist Joe Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted to play (Tuesday) night,'' said manager Bobby Cox.
``He was kind of mad. We're just trying to do the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bautista, who has made 24 starts in left field in a right-handed
platoon situation with Ryan Klesko, plowed into Prince while trying
to score on a safety squeeze in the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He might be out for a while,'' said Cox. ``His knee is a
little wobbly. I haven't seen the report yet but it never swelled
up. It fooled us a little bit. He could go upstairs and downstairs
but when he turned on it, it bothered him a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Should Bautista require some time on the disabled list, Damon
Hollins appears the first option from Class AAA Richmond. Curtis
Pride has been slowed by a nagging leg injury and the right-handed
hitting Hollins would better fit the needs for the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Attrition
</P>
<P>
   Already down to 24 men after Bautista returned to Atlanta, Cox
found his roster dwindle down to 22 before the Braves got out of
the first inning. Chipper Jones was lost for ``a few games,''
according to Pursley, when he aggravated a muscle pull in his right
rib cage in his first at-bat. Jones first felt the pull during
batting practice but when he put his first ball in play with a
line-out to center, the pain was enough that he barely made it down
the baseline.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Lockhart had been penciled in at second base, after
resting a sore right hamstring for three games. But after testing
the leg in batting practice, he was pulled and replace by Tony
Graffanino.
</P>
<P>
   Precedent
</P>
<P>
   Andres Galarraga served a three-game suspension last year after
taking on Dennis Cook, then pitching for Florida, after hitting him
in the same game Galarraga struck a 529-foot homer at Pro Player
Stadium. His appeal was denied then. After being suspended again
Wednesday, he does not expect his appeal to be successful this time
either.
</P>
<P>
   ``They hit me many times after I hit a home run,'' said the
Atlanta first baseman. ``Why they won't hit me after I strike
out?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
