<HEADER>
A4205 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-FOOTBALL-DUKE     08-26 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FOOTBALL-DUKE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Duke hopes experience begins to pay off
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Durham, N.C. _ Fred Goldsmith says this is the best football
team he's had at Duke since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty bold stuff until you look at his record and you see that
since 1994, when Duke started 7-0 en route to its last bowl
appearance, his teams have won only five games. Yet, the Blue
Devils do have a couple of things going in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   First, they have a dozen four-year juniors and three-year
sophomores playing key roles on this squad. Secondly, although
compiling only a 2-9 mark last season, Duke played eight teams
tough, losing late in the game to Virginia and Clemson and almost
overtaking Georgia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will survive what we've been through the last few years,''
Goldsmith said. ``We've done better than we deserved in recruiting,
and we've gotten some pretty good talent here. I can see
improvement. But how is that going to be reflected against our
opponents? That's the question.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldsmith also points out that at least one player from every
Duke team for the past 20 seasons has gone on to medical school.
Although that stat won't help on an off-tackle slant, it did help
the Devils sign their starting quarterback _ Spencer Romine.
</P>
<P>
   Romine, from Cullman, Ala., is an excellent student who wants to
become a pediatrician, thus his matriculation at Duke instead of
Georgia Tech, which also recruited him. It's no coincidence that
Romine was the quarterback of record in Duke's two wins last
season. He played in only six games, sitting out the other five
with a hip injury and a severe ankle sprain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, we had a lot of very young players, and they were
concentrating on playing instead of winning,'' said Romine, a
redshirt sophomore. ``This year, we've got some experience. I'm
absolutely convinced we will win.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to a healthy Romine, Duke has an excellent tailback
in Letavious Wilks and a very good fullback in Dawud Rasheed.
Freidman and Rasheed are the only two senior starters on offense.
</P>
<P>
   The receiver position is also strong, if not deep, with Scottie
Montgomery and Richmond Flowers capable of making first-team
all-ACC. Reco Owens is the only backup receiver with any
experience.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, the Blue Devils return eight starters, with the
defensive line anchored by Chris Combs, a 6-foot-6, 275-pound
all-conference tackle. Lamar Grant might be one of the better
cornerbacks in the league.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter which way you cut it, Duke is 0-16 in the league
the past two years and 1-23 the past three. The Blue Devils might
not finish in the cellar of the ACC this year, but they won't
finish in the upper half of the conference, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a better understanding of the offense,'' said senior
left guard Lennie Friedman, another pre-med major.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our quarterbacks, especially Spencer, have so much confidence,
it has spread throughout the team. You can tell he's making the
calls and checks so much quicker. We played in a lot of close games
last year. The fact that we didn't graduate that many people,
that's going to make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   DUKE UNIVERSITY
</P>
<P>
   Location: Durham, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Enrollment: 6,085.
</P>
<P>
   Coach: Fred Goldsmith is 13-39 in four years at Duke, 38-70-1
overall.
</P>
<P>
   Nickname: Blue Devils.
</P>
<P>
   Stadium: Wallace Wade (33,941).
</P>
<P>
   All-time record: 427-353-31.
</P>
<P>
   ACC championships: 7 (1953, 1954, 1955, 1960, 1961, 1962,
1989-tie).
</P>
<P>
   1997 record: 2-9, 0-8 ACC.
</P>
<P>
   Schedule: Sep. 5 vs. Western Carolina, Sep. 12 at Northwestern,
Sep. 19 at Florida St., Sep. 26 vs. Virginia, Oct. 3 at Georgia
Tech, Oct. 10 at Wake Forest, Oct. 17 at N.C. State, Oct. 24 vs.
Clemson, Oct. 31 at Vanderbilt, Nov. 14 vs. Maryland, Nov. 21 vs.
North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
