<SLUG> BC-BBO-LITTLE-LEAGUE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 TOMS RIVER LITTLE LEAGUERS DON'T MAKE EXCUSES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ED GUZMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILLIAMSPORT, Pa. _ Perhaps it was during the East regional
tournament in Bristol, Conn., that Toms River East manager Mike
Gaynor had a feeling about what his Little League team was capable
of. Gaynor stepped up to the plate with one of the players' bats
during a practice and was jammed by the pitch, fouling it off.
Gaynor started complaining that the bat was too small, and without
hesitation, every member of the Toms River team, in unison, yelled
at Gaynor, ``No excuses, coach!''
</P>
<P>
   It has been that kind of attitude that has carried Toms River to
a perfect 3-0 record thus far in the 52nd annual Little League
World Series. With a spot in Thursday night's semifinal game
against Greenville, N.C., Toms River is only two victories from
winning the Little League World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just don't say boo,'' Gaynor said of his players'
attitude. ``They just go out and play baseball. I don't know if
it's their personalities, but they just go out and play ball and
they've been getting it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's because these unflappable 12-year-olds have been too
busy having fun, despite not having spent a lot of time with their
families, in the last three weeks. During the Toms River practice
Wednesday morning on one of the fields outside Howard J. Lamade
Stadium, you would not have thought that they had a big game coming
up. When they were not practicing, the kids were busy trading
stories about pranks they have pulled on one another or teasing
shortstop Todd Frazier about the picture that ran in a newspaper
showing Frazier after his two-run home run Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody grabbed my leg,'' Frazier said, trying to explain his
facial elation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some kids step on the plate and celebrate with their
teammates,'' Gaynor said jokingly to Frazier. ``You step on the
plate and look for the camera.''
</P>
<P>
   But hamming it up for the camera aside, Frazier has proven to be
an important asset to Toms River, hitting two home runs, scoring
seven runs and pitching a complete-game victory in the three games
here.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's our spiritual leader,'' Gaynor said of Frazier. ``He's
the reason I felt we'd have success here because he's an `up' kind
of kid.''
</P>
<P>
   If Frazier is the spiritual leader, then second baseman Joey
Franceschini has to be the unofficial mascot. Standing 4 feet 9
inches and weighing 65 pounds, the 12-year old Franceschini is the
lightest player at this year's World Series. Wearing a jersey that
is too big for him _ or maybe he's too small for it _ Franceschini
bats fourth in the Toms River batting order, a spot usually saved
for kids who weigh at least twice as much as he does. Donna
Franceschini, whose husband, Joe, is a coach for Toms River,
rejoiced in her son and her husband at Wednesday morning's practice
and marveled at the wonder of it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never expected anything like this,'' Donna Franceschini said
of the Toms River team. ``It just shows that size does not matter,
but heart does. And boy, they have heart.''
</P>
<P>
   She added: ``Between my husband and my kid, it's hard not having
them around. But it's worth it just by being here. We have a
lifetime together, so three weeks is nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   With banners lined up on Route 37 in Toms River and Muggsy's,
the local Toms River sports bar, packed for every game this week,
the bandwagon is clearly gaining speed. ''If there's not 500 East
people here tomorrow, I'll be surprised,'' Gaynor said.
</P>
<P>
   As practice ended and the kids headed back to the dorms, catcher
Brad Frank stopped and said to the reporters gathered around the
practice field: ``No more comments, except for Franceschini's
nickname.''
</P>
<P>
   After hesitating for a minute, he said proudly, ``We call him
Teeny-Weeny Fettuccine Franceschini.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
