<HEADLINE>
POLICE SAY FORMER FOOTBALL STAR KILLED PREGNANT WIFE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Terry Underwood, a standout running back for Wagner College when
it won a Division III national championship in 1987 and a
three-time all-American, has been arrested and charged with
murdering his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors in Monmouth County, N.J., said Underwood stabbed his
wife, Theresa, who was six months pregnant, at their Aberdeen,
N.J., apartment on Monday night while their two children slept in
another room.
</P>
<P>
   Former teammates and coaches of Underwood, who went on to play
in the Canadian Football League and in Europe, reacted with shock
to the charges Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known Terry all my life,'' said Mike Jones, who played
football with Underwood at Matawan (N.J.) High School and at
Wagner. ``We went to church with Theresa. ... We can't believe
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Underwood's bail was set Wednesday at $350,000, and he remained
in custody.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said Underwood, 31, called the Aberdeen police at
1:39 a.m. Tuesday and said he had returned home to find Theresa,
30, dead.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said Underwood murdered his wife and then tried to
establish an alibi by going to a friend's house to watch a football
game and by talking to a toll collector before returning home.
There were no signs of forced entry, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Theresa Underwood died from stab wounds, prosecutors said, and
her body showed signs of blunt trauma. The children, Terry, 5, and
Alexandra, 4, were not harmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does maintain his innocence,'' said Brian Ansell,
Underwood's lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Ansell said Underwood worked for an organization called Spur
Services in Orange, N.J. Calls to the group's office were not
answered Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Theresa Underwood worked as a dental hygienist and taught a
Bible class for children at Calvary Baptist Church in Aberdeen. A
man who answered the telephone at the home of her parents said the
family had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're shocked and all just kind of shattered over this
tragedy,'' said Steve Oswalt, the pastor at Cavalry Baptist Church.
``She was a wonderful lady, an extremely devoted mother and a very
sweet spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple began dating as teen-agers at Matawan High.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Underwood still holds school records at Wagner for most rushing
yards in a career (5,010), in a season (1,809) and in a game (363).
</P>
<P>
   Wagner is in Staten Island and has an enrollment of about 1,500.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a terrific kid, good work ethic, good sense of humor,
who fit in well,'' said Mark Collins, the head coach at St. Peter's
College, who was an assistant at Wagner when Underwood was there.
``I don't recall a dark side or a bad temper.''
</P>
<P>
   Underwood went to training camp with the Jets but was cut in
August 1989. He played in just two games with the Toronto Argonauts
of the Canadian Football League, rushing 29 times for 135 yards and
1 touchdown. He played in the World Football League in Europe for a
short time and then returned home, where he went to work for
nonprofit organizations that worked with children.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said Underwood was somewhat bitter that he never succeeded
in pro football.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he was having some financial problems,'' Jones said.
``You can't make any money working like that with kids. He had been
making a lot of money when he was playing in Europe, but now he was
living in an apartment with two kids and waiting for a third kid.
It was difficult.''
</P>
</TEXT>
