<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTES27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DeBerg to be evaluated before others considered
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljoh n
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Atlanta Falcons did not try Wednesday to acquire any players
released by other teams, and general manager Harold Richardson said
team officials have had no discussions with the Cincinnati Bengals
or the agent for quarterback Jeff Blake about acquiring him.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson and coach Dan Reeves also said it's very unlike the
Falcons will attempt any such moves any earlier than Saturday, if
at all.
</P>
<P>
   Backup quarterback continues to be the area of greatest concern,
but coaches want to get another look at 44-year-old Steve DeBerg
before doing anything. He'll play the second half Friday night in
the final preseason game against the Bengals in the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons are unlikely to try to trade for Blake, who has lost
his starting job to Neil O'Donnell, but might be interested if he
is released this weekend, when rosters must be cut from 60 to 53
players.
</P>
<P>
   The Bengals want to renegotiate Blake's contract, which calls
for a salary of $1.95 million this year, and $2.65 million next.
Blake and his agent, Ralph Cindrich, are resigned to the idea of
renegotiating, but while they want to do it for one year, the
Bengals want to do it for two.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati is paying quarterback Neil O'Donnell about $5
million, and reserve Paul Justin about $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Reeves said it's not an issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``That bridge isn't even open,'' he said after a two-hour
practice Wednesday. ``I'll cross it if it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said looking at other players before coaches can
evaluate DeBerg _ and players at other positions for that matter --
would be ``counterproductive.'' He said the only way the Falcons
would go after a player right now is if they were positive the
player would make the team.
</P>
<P>
   Another player released Tuesday who could be of interest to
Atlanta is guard Doug Widell (released by the Packers), brother of
Falcons reserve C/G Dave Widell. The Widell brothers played
together with Denver (and Reeves and Richardson) from '90-92.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
