<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 22:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4212 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONSQA-MATHIS-     08-26 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONSQA-MATHIS-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   The thing is 53 guys playing as a collective unit, winning
games'
</P>
<P>
   By Matt Winkeljohn(backslash)
</P>
<P>
   C. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   Since joining the Atlanta Falcons in 1994 after four seasons
with the New York Jets, Terance Mathis has seen his career take
off. During the first four years of his career, Mathis, a Stone
Mountain native and Redan graduate, scored four touchdowns. Since
then, he has caught 320 passes, third in Falcons history behind
Andre Rison's 423 and Jim Mitchell's 359, and scored 33 touchdowns,
fourth in team history behind Rison's 56, Alfred Jenkins' 40, and
Michael Haynes' 34. At 5-feet-10, 185 pounds, Mathis is crafty,
sneaky quick and works hard. He puts in a lot of time off the
field, too. His Terance Loves Children (TLC) Foundation began in
1996, and he helps hand out 1,000 turkeys during the holidays. He
also has ``adopted'' 10 families at Christmas. Seldom at a loss for
words, Mathis sat down with Journal-Constitution Falcons beat
writer Matt Winkeljohn.
</P>
<P>
   AJC: Do Atlanta sports fans take the Falcons seriously? Why or
why not?
</P>
<P>
   Mathis: When you play in the same city with the Atlanta Braves,
America's team that everybody watches on TBS, cheering for a
hometown football team which hasn't been successful is tough. In
the past, I think (the Falcons were) just a gimmick around here.
You had (former coach) Jerry Glanville and the run-and-shoot. You
had Deion Sanders, Andre Rison, Jeff George _ you had some talented
guys. That's not the thing, though. The thing is 53 guys playing as
a collective unit, winning football games.
</P>
<P>
   AJC: What's the biggest mis-impression fans have about NFL
players?
</P>
<P>
   Mathis: That we're aggressive, we have tempers, that we're
rowdy. That may be 10 percent of the players around the league.
Fans need to realize that football is what we do; it is not what we
are. When we leave the Georgia Dome, we go home to our families
like any other working man and deal with problems at home,
situations like any other man. I think people need to realize we're
not bigger than life. We're men.
</P>
<P>
   AJC: That said, pro athletes obviously are held up as role
models, chiefly by children. Is that reasonable?
</P>
<P>
   Mathis: Kids want the money, the fame, the nice car, the
clothes, the big house, the jewelry and all that. What I tell young
people in general is ... once a professional athlete retires, he's
out of the limelight, he's no one's hero anymore. You need to look
in your own homes, churches, neighborhoods, wherever, and find
people you interact with every day (to look upon as role models).
You interact with us on television, radio, billboards; maybe you
get a chance to meet a professional athlete once in your life, so
why would you make that guy your role model? What is he or she
giving back to the community? What kind of impact does this person
have on society besides sports?
</P>
<P>
   AJC: Speaking of the way public figures are held up to different
standards, which camp do you belong to, that Bill Clinton's private
life is his business and not the nation's, or that as president his
private life is a national concern?
</P>
<P>
   Mathis: Who are we to judge? We're not God. He has to face his
creator. There's not a perfect person on this Earth. Whatever
president Clinton does on his personal time, that's his personal
time. He has to deal with the consequences.
</P>
<P>
   AJC: What's going to make this team better than last year's?
</P>
<P>
   Mathis: What's going to make this team better is believing in
each other. Last year, we were finding ways to point fingers at
someone and say it was his fault or the coaches fault, or the plays
were bad. I think now, whatever play is called, we're determined to
execute it. When the game is close... there's a mentality now that
we're going to win. There's not a panic situation, and I think
that's what's going to take us over the top.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
