</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMS-LYMON-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FIFTIES QUESTION RECONSIDERED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., August 30)  
 (JT)  
 By JAMIE DIAMOND    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With jowls, deep lines around her mouth and about
30 extra pounds, Halle Berry doesn't look like the Halle Berry
we've come to know. Still, on this sound stage in February, she
moves regally, like a star, which is exactly what she's playing:
Zola Taylor, the flashy singer for the Platters, at the age of 48.
What's most important about this scene, set in a federal court in
New York in 1986, however, is the fact that Zola Taylor is the
widow of Frankie Lymon, the pop singer who wrote the 1950s doo-wop
hit ``Why Do Fools Fall in Love?'' And she has come to court to
claim a share of his royalties.
</P>
<P>
   There's only one problem. Two other women are there, and each
says she is Lymon's widow. Apparently divorce was not in the
golden-voiced singer's repertory.
</P>
<P>
   For a moment, Ms. Berry stands off to the side, breathing
deeply, hand over her face, an actor preparing. Then, wearing a
``fat pad'' _ a leotardlike garment with batting at the hips, bust
and stomach _ under a fashionable suit, she takes the witness stand
as Zola Taylor to describe a relationship with the self-destructive
Lymon. ``He was talented and funny and knew how to work that charm
thing on me,'' the character testifies. Her voice is a minute away
from tears. She tells of losing her home because Lymon bought
heroin and entertained other women rather than paying the mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   During this emotional testimony, the director Gregory Nava lifts
a pencil up and down as if he's conducting an orchestra. Ms. Berry
finishes, and the crew claps. Nava turns to the actress and asks:
``I think we got it. What do you think?''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Berry is so drained she can only nod.
</P>
<P>
   In the movie ``Why Do Fools Fall in Love,'' which opened on
August 28 and also stars Vivica Fox, Lela Rochon and Laranz Tate,
courtroom testimony takes up only a few minutes. But that a legal
battle really happened is the reason the story of Frankie Lymon
finally made it to the screen at all.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years ago, a script based on Lymon's life was written by
Tina Andrews, a soap-opera actress. It was a faithful account of
how this charismatic singer came to have his big hit in 1955 at the
age of 13 _ with a group called the Teen-agers _ and then enjoy a
few more years of stardom. In the 60's, unable to sustain a career
as a soloist, Lymon became a heroin addict, and he died of an
overdose in 1968 at the age of 26.
</P>
<P>
   That script kicked around Hollywood for years before Ms. Andrews
showed it in 1995 to Rhino Films, a division of Rhino Records,
which had just acquired the rights to Lymon's music. She had the
words, they had the tunes; it should have been a wonderful
marriage. ``But we didn't want it,'' Stephen Nemeth, a co-producer
of the film, says of the original screenplay. ``It was a standard,
linear biopic. He dies of a heroin overdose. No one cares.''
</P>
<P>
   That would have been the end of it, except for the fact that the
folks at Rhino had seen a television program and then a story in
The Philadelphia Inquirer about a legal fight over Lymon's
royalties _ and the surprising appearance of three Mrs. Lymons. So,
they ordered a transcript of the court proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that was, by far, the most interesting way to tell
the story, with three gals battling it out in court with no prior
knowledge of the others' marriages,'' says Nemeth, who relayed
these thoughts to Ms. Andrews. ``We had a star, a hooker and a
schoolteacher: we couldn't have written better fiction. We got to
tell Frankie's story a la `Rashomon,' and have three tour-de-force
roles for women of color. And unlike a `black film,' which is not
embraced in the foreign market, this one everyone could relate to.
We've all been fools in love.''
</P>
<P>
   Nava is known for making movies that are explicitly steeped in
Hispanic culture (``El Norte,'' ``Mi Familia,'' ``Selena''), but
there was a certain logic, too, in his being chosen to direct ``Why
Do Fools Fall in Love.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He did `Selena,' one of the most popular pictures about a rock
singer last year,'' explains Paul Hall, another co-producer, who,
like Ms. Andrews, is black. ``He has heart in terms of his
storytelling, and he can look at the emotions of the culture. Also,
this film is about rock-and-roll, which brought the cultures
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the rock-and-roll connection was as important a factor
in getting the film made as finding a more upbeat framework for the
narrative. ``Without the music, it's just three widows talking
about a junkie,'' says Hall. But the casting of the widows was
crucial. Everybody wanted to play the dazzling singer Zola Taylor,
wife No. 1, and nobody wanted to play the drab schoolteacher Emira
Eagle, wife No. 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was offered the role of Emira, but I always play sweet,
innocent girls-next-door,'' says Ms. Berry. ``Or crack heads. I'd
never played a diva, and I wanted to do something a little
saucier.''
</P>
<P>
   The Zola role was spoken for, so Ms. Berry made other plans.
Later, things changed; Ms. Berry won the part she wanted and, with
a significant amount of sauce, got to strut around like a diva in
eye-catching outfits, big hair and very high heels.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, Ms. Fox, who plays Elizabeth Waters, wife No. 2,
wasn't impressed by the part she was offered either. ``Elizabeth
goes to jail, gets strung out, becomes a prostitute and Frankie
kind of kills her dog,'' she says. ``I didn't think my audience
could handle seeing me like that. I'm coming off the successes of
`Independence Day' and `Soul Food,' and, in a way, I'm America's
little sweetheart.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
