<HEADLINE>
SPRINTER REVS UP FOR NEW SPORT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The question tested Marcus Bivines' memory: ``So
how long have you been playing football?'' He thought for a second
before answering the question with a question: ``How long have we
been in camp?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer to both questions is, about two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Bivines is practically a world-class sprinter but a football
novice. Yet he's also one of the most impressive newcomers in camp
at Cal State Northridge and could realistically become a fixture in
the Matadors' running-back rotation.
</P>
<P>
   A transfer from the University of Oklahoma, Bivines was eighth
in the nation this year in the 55-meter dash, clocking a
6.18-second finish.
</P>
<P>
   But the 20-year-old sophomore has no track record to speak of in
football. He didn't watch it growing up in Midwest City, Okla.,
hasn't played a down at any level, never even stepped onto a
football field until his senior year of high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a nerd, in fact. I graduated with a 3.9 (GPA),'' Bivines
said. ``I wasn't into sports.... I was more into reading a book or
something.''
</P>
<P>
   Asthma kept Bivines away from athletics as a youth, but he
overcame the affliction as he grew older. He tried to play football
his senior year, but his lack of experience meant spending the
entire season on the scout team. He ran track for the first time
that spring and earned a partial scholarship to Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Once there, Bivines clocked a 10.3 in the 100-meter dash and was
part of the nation's fifth-fastest 4x100 relay team. Then Bivines
convinced NFL scouts, who were visiting campus, to let him
participate in their tests. His 4.33-second 40-yard dash was the
fastest time they saw, and they urged him to play football.
</P>
<P>
   With that encouragement, Bivines arranged to transfer to CSUN
and has received scholarships in track and football. Alhough he's
probably third or fourth on the depth chart, he has impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He shows incredible potential,'' head coach Ron Ponciano said.
</P>
<P>
   Bivines is the fastest man in camp but is learning how to be a
running back instead of a runner. Still, Ponciano said he'll use
him on kick returns and might even give him a few carries next
Saturday at Boise State.
</P>
<P>
   __ Quarterback quandry: No decision has been announced, but it
appears redshirt freshman Marcus Brady has a firm grip on the
starting-quarterback job. The Matadors held their second full-speed
scrimmage of camp Wednesday, and Brady again took the majority of
snaps with the No. 1 offense and again performed well.
</P>
<P>
   Among the four quarterbacks competing for the starting job,
junior Josh Fiske holds the edge in experience, but Brady has
played the best. Ponciano plans to name a starter today.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his steady play, Brady said he doesn't feel like the
front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could do better,'' he said. ``I'm still making mistakes out
there. I'm just trying to make the least amount of mistakes
possible.'' &UR; !dlim!!end!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-26-98 2255EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980826.0550 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 22:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4215 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILMS-LYMON-$ADV30-2N     08-26 0638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMS-LYMON-$ADV30-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 LOS ANGELES: little sweetheart.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   She changed her mind, though. And as the floozy, she got to
deliver lines with the most punch.``I got to be the one who wasn't
perfect and pretty all the time,'' says Ms. Fox. ``And it was fun
to play someone really raw. I didn't have to worry about dieting. I
didn't have to eat all those carrots. When you're perfect, people
love to find out what's not right with you. Elizabeth's flaws are
hanging out all over the place, and as a result, you root for
her.''
</P>
<P>
   Which still left the troublesome Emira. ``I didn't think I was
right for her at all,'' says Ms. Rochon. ``She's so
goody-two-shoes. But I got together with Gregory and came up with
the story line that she's the one who never got over Frankie. She
buried him. She still wears her wedding ring. And she still loves
him. That gave me higher stakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the film is structured around the battle for royalties,
the three actresses have several scenes in which they squabble and
nearly pull one another's hair out. Asked if it is something of a
stereotype to show women fighting, then bonding, Nava bristles.
``When you do a Latino film, or a film of this type, you hear the
word stereotype bandied about,'' the director says. ``But I've
never heard of anyone reading `Hamlet' and saying: `You know what?
This play is going to put forth the stereotype that all white men
from Denmark are indecisive.'''
</P>
<P>
   On the day after the courtroom scene, Tate, who plays Lymon, is
wearing an Army uniform, holding a bouquet and standing in front of
the oldest building in Santa Monica. The building, nestled between
a boarded-up adult theater and a youth hostel, is doubling as an
Atlanta schoolhouse. The scenes filmed here will make up a montage
showing Frankie, well past his glory days, as a traditional suitor,
albeit an AWOL one, falling in love with Emira.
</P>
<P>
   He paces in front of the schoolhouse, waiting for her to emerge,
and eventually she does, wearing a wool jumper and a turtleneck,
covered by a shapeless brown coat.
</P>
<P>
   To capture the look of three different decades, the wardrobe,
hair and props people have been kept busy. ``Back in the 50s, black
people pressed and curled their hair with heated pressing combs and
curling irons, not with chemicals,'' says Ken Walker, the primary
hair stylist. ``So we have a little stove and I can just tell by
the smell of it when it's heated up right.''
</P>
<P>
   It's no accident that Emira is dressed in brown. The wives have
been color-coded. ``Emira's from the South, the homeland of
African-American culture, so that's the earth,'' explains Nava.
``Her story is about groundedness, so she wears earth-tone colors.
Zola wears bright colors because she's a flamboyant entertainer.
And Elizabeth has no grounding; she's always changing, like water.
So she wears muted water colors, blues and grays.''
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in his earth-tone Army uniform, Tate shyly hands Ms.
Rochon the bouquet. She responds with a little smile, and Frankie
Lymon is another step down the road to polygamy.
</P>
<P>
   So, why did these women _ fools or not _ fall in love with a cad
like Lymon? Nava prefers to talk about the situation's farcical
aspects. ``That comedy and tragedy are two sides of the same coin
is very much the way Latinos see the world,'' he says. ``All our
literature, like `One Hundred Years of Solitude,' for instance, is
funny and tragic. And I like the double-edgedness of it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Tate simply believes that everyone involved, including Lymon,
was human. ``He's not hard to defend, because I don't think he was
a bad person,'' the actor says. ``Do you look at Chris Farley and
say he was a bad person? Was John Belushi a bad person? Frankie
Lymon touched people. He made them feel like dancing and singing
and cheering.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
