<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-YOUTH-MARCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE REJECTS EFFORTS TO BLOCK MILLION YOUTH MARCH IN HARLEM
</HEADLINE>
   (rm) 
 By ABBY GOODNOUGH c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A federal judge ordered New York City Wednesday to
allow the so-called Million Youth March to take place next week in
Harlem, saying the city's decision to deny marchers a permit was
unconstitutional and based on rules that were ``breathtaking in
their lack of standards.''
</P>
<P>
   City officials said they would immediately appeal the decision.
But with only nine days remaining before the event, organizers of
the march said they would forge ahead with planning and step up
efforts to recruit young black people from around the country to
attend.
</P>
<P>
   The march has been the subject of increasing controversy in
recent weeks, with Mayor Rudolph Giuliani denouncing it as a poorly
planned ``hate march'' and the organizers accusing the city of
violating their constitutional rights and vowing to hold the event.
</P>
<P>
   In his ruling, Judge Lewis Kaplan of Federal District Court said
the city's rules for weighing permits for street events were too
broad and its decisions too arbitrary. He also said the alternative
venues the city had proposed _ Randalls Island or Van Cortlandt
Park in the Bronx _ were unacceptable because they were remote and
would ``adversely affect'' the organizers' ability ``to get their
message out.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan said that the city had considered the application ``on an
ad-hoc basis'' and that the city was not ``free to impose a ban
like this without a persuasive showing that the event poses a
significant threat'' to governmental interests, like public safety.
</P>
<P>
   The organizers have billed the march, which would actually be a
stationary rally along Malcolm X Boulevard, as a show of unity
among young blacks from across the country, much like the Million
Man March that was held in Washington in 1995. But Giuliani has
repeatedly condemned the event's chief organizer, Khalid Abdul
Muhammad, for making anti-Semitic and anti-white remarks, and has
criticized Muhammad's plans to invite gang members to the march.
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad and the other organizers sued the city in Federal
District Court last week, saying that discriminatory policies of
the Giuliani administration prompted it to deny their application
for what the organizers called a ``First Amendment Educational
Event.'' But Kaplan's ruling did not address whether the city
rejected the application based on the philosophies of Muhammad, who
was ousted from the Nation of Islam after a 1993 speech in which he
referred to Jews as ``bloodsuckers.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, based on testimony by police and fire officials, Kaplan
said the city had ``ample ability'' to insure the safety of
participants in the rally, onlookers and residents.
</P>
<P>
   He told the organizers that they would have to abide by whatever
safety provisions the police deemed necessary, like keeping
emergency lanes open on either side of Malcolm X Boulevard. But he
rejected the city's argument that the neighborhood could not
accommodate the thousands of people expected to attend the march,
planned for between 7 a.m. and 7 p.m. Sept. 5.
</P>
<P>
   While saying he understood Kaplan's concern about First
Amendment issues and acknowledging the marchers' right to make
their point, Giuliani, who was in Iowa for Republican fund-raisers,
ridiculed the judge's determination that the police could handle
the event safely. ``The judge said he was sure the Police
Department could handle it,'' he said. ``The Police Commissioner
isn't sure, and he knows a little more about the Police Department
than the judge does.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the city had tried to convince Kaplan that the march
could not take place over the Labor Day weekend because other major
events, like the West Indian Day Parade in Brooklyn, were already
in the works. Police resources would be too strained, they said. If
hundreds of thousands of people crowded onto Malcolm X Boulevard,
the march could be ``catastrophic,'' said Michael Hess, the city's
corporation counsel.
</P>
<P>
   But the organizers, who originally predicted that more than a
million people would attend, told Kaplan that they expected no more
than 175,000. The judge said he thought that even fewer people
would come and that they would ``drift in and out'' of the rally
all day.
</P>
<P>
   Even if more show up, he said, the city has enough police
officers ``to deal with whatever problems of congestion, emergency
action, overcrowding and fire risk may arise.''
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad has kept a low profile throughout the dispute, allowing
his lawyers and fellow organizers to wage a public battle with the
city. But he was in the courtroom for most of the eight-hour
hearing Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
