<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUSTATASTE-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESEARCHERS USE SPICE TO KILL E. COLI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JILL WENDHOLT SILVA  
 c. 1998 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Could a strong dose of cloves in your hamburger help ward off E.
coli?
</P>
<P>
   For centuries spices have been used to retard the spoilage of
food in countries close to the equator.
</P>
<P>
   More recently outbreaks of E. coli in hamburger and apple cider
have heightened fears of potential outbreaks in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Now researchers at Kansas State University in Manhattan have
discovered that common spices such as garlic, clove, cinnamon,
oregano and sage can kill up to 99 percent of this
food-contaminating bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers tested 23 spices in E. coli-contaminated raw
ground beef and salami. They found a mixture of 7.5 percent clove
to 92.5 ground beef killed 99 percent of the bacteria in hamburger.
Hefty doses of garlic killed 99 percent of the bacteria in salami.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used spices straight off the shelf, although the amount we
put in is more than most people really do,'' says Daniel Fung, a
food microbiologist with K-State's department of animal sciences
and industry.
</P>
<P>
   A more palatable 2.5 percent clove in hamburger killed 90
percent of the pathogens. When a more moderate dose of garlic was
used the spice killed about half of the E. coli.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, however, a heavy dose of spice does not eliminate
the need to thoroughly cook hamburger.
</P>
<P>
   Fung presented the research findings earlier this summer at a
meeting of the Institute of Food Technologists in Atlanta. He says
a scheduled two-hour presentation quickly turned into a four-hour
talk with food industry representatives and consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If these spices can kill E. coli there are also applications
for salmonella and other food-borne pathogens. E. coli is very hard
to kill compared to other pathogens,'' Fung says optimistically.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, as news of the work has spread, Fung has received calls
from around the country. Many of the callers are eager to suggest
other applications for his research.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, after talking with cider producers, one of his
student researchers will test whether the addition of cinnamon can
kill E. coli in apple cider.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the young farmer in North Carolina who called to
tell Fung that he had added spice to chicken feed and detected a
lowered incidence of E. coli in the chicken feces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows? If you feed chicken spices, you may get good
flavor! This whole thing can go on and on,'' Fung says with obvious
enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   Fung and associates E. Ceylan and D.H. Kang also plan to test
the spices on cooked hamburger products. Their goal is to try to
isolate the compounds in the spices that kill E. coli. ``We need to
think about how to put more spice in food so we can put more
protection in food,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of cloves in hamburger doesn't sound very appealing?
</P>
<P>
   Fung insists ``human eating habits can change. Chinese don't
usually like blue cheese when they first get here, but then in time
they begin to like it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
