A4349 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-PREVIEW-TEXAS-TEX     08-26 1460
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-PREVIEW-TEXAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING RICKY WILLIAMS THE BEST IS BEST FOR TEXAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Mack Brown, Texas' first-year football coach,
figured he was at the apex of his honeymoon period with Longhorns
fans.
</P>
<P>
   It was mid-January, eight months before Brown would have a
chance to lose his first game and a few days after tailback Ricky
Williams, the team's Heisman Trophy candidate, announced he would
bypass millions in projected NFL earnings and return for his senior
season.
</P>
<P>
   As Brown toured the city, familiarizing himself with local
landmarks in his first month as an Austin resident, he passed a
sign of the times. On a small message board in front of one
business was a poignant reminder that a coach's public-relations
work is never done.
</P>
<P>
   The sign read: ``Give it to Ricky 40 times, Mack, you idiot.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown laughed.
</P>
<P>
   Little did the business owner realize that the new coach, unlike
the old one, had no concern about a maximum number of carries each
game for a player who could break the NCAA career records for
rushing yards and rushing touchdowns with a standout senior season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agreed with them. I didn't think that was too harsh,'' Brown
said of the hand-scrawled message that he will adopt as a plan of a
attack in 1998. ``A lot of people said I did a great job of talking
Ricky into staying. The truth is, I should have begged him. I
didn't know how good he was.''
</P>
<P>
   After watching the 6-foot, 225-pound Williams in spring drills
and fall two-a-days, Brown has a better handle on the type of
talent he will feature as the centerpiece of the Texas offense. In
fact, Brown has made Williams' Heisman quest the rallying point for
a team trying to rebound from a 4-7 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Heisman Trophy is not an individual award. It's obviously
a team award,'' Brown said. ``You never see a player with the
Heisman Trophy on a team that doesn't perform at the highest level.
So, from our standpoint, we've challenged our football team. We
told them, `If you want Ricky to win the Heisman, we've got to win
a lot of football games.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It's a novel method of motivation. But the Longhorns, who
inherit 1997 powers Nebraska (13-0) and Kansas State (11-1) as road
opponents on the rotating Big 12 schedule, have not been projected
among the title contenders in a conference they won in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Brown knows his team needs some sort of seasonlong rallying
point. And the players seem to like the idea of playing for
Williams, the top returning vote-getter in the Heisman balloting
last season, when he finished fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, winner of last season's Doak Walker National Running
Back Award, needs 1,928 yards to break the NCAA career rushing mark
set in 1976 by Pittsburgh's Tony Dorsett (6,082 yards). He needs 20
rushing touchdowns to eclipse the NCAA career record of 64 by
Indiana's Anthony Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   In 11 games last season, Williams rushed for 1,893 yards and 25
touchdowns, leading Division I-A players in both categories. But he
averaged only 25.3 carries per game, a figure Brown has vowed to
increase dramatically to take advantage of Texas' four returning
starters in the offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   A heightened workload for Williams, it is assumed, will lead to
increased yards and points. And increased production by the offense
will take pressure off a defense that allowed a school-record 366
points (33.3 per game) in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Middle linebacker Dusty Renfro, an Alvarado High School
graduate, is on board with the idea of teammates banding together
in an effort to put a Heisman on Williams' mantel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any kind of thing that gives you drive to do better is good.
And it would be good for us having him in the Heisman race,'' said
Renfro, the team leader in tackles (116) and sacks (four) last
season. ``Ricky means a lot to this team. I would die for the
man.''
</P>
<P>
   That has not always been the case, Renfro pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first met him, I didn't like his looks. I didn't like
his dreadlocks,'' said Renfro, a senior who joined Williams as a
member of Texas' 1995 recruiting class. ``But I learned to like
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ricky is a good guy who always has a smile on his face and
doesn't treat people bad. He's the premier player in college
football, but he hasn't let that go to his head. I realize now my
first impression of him was 100 percent wrong. There's nothing I
wouldn't do for the guy, and a lot of players on this team feel the
same way.''
</P>
<P>
   Ben Adams, a two-year starter at right guard, said Williams has
``a selfless nature that inspires the entire team.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams' decision to cut short his summer baseball season and
begin voluntary football workouts in July further endeared him to
Texas teammates. A member of the Philadelphia Phillies' Class A
team in Batavia, N.Y., Williams was hitting .288 when he returned
to Austin to lift weights and concentrate on his Heisman chase.
</P>
<P>
   ``That tied the last piece of the puzzle together,'' Renfro said
of Williams' early return from professional baseball. ``It showed
us that Ricky really cared about us and thought we could win. The
offensive linemen have set a goal to get him 2,000 yards. We're all
excited about it.''
</P>
<P>
   So is Williams, who has taken a hands-on approach in helping
school officials craft what is being billed as a low-key Heisman
campaign. After announcing his return to Texas and receiving
permission from Brown to switch to jersey No. 34 for his senior
season, Williams suggested to school officials that he and Brown
pose for a publicity picture with the new digit.
</P>
<P>
   John Bianco, Texas' associate director of media relations for
football, said Williams envisioned a shot that would parody NFL
draft-day photos of first-round picks holding their new jerseys
while posing with commissioner Paul Tagliabue. So, Williams and
Brown posed, side-by-side, with each holding a shoulder of a Texas
jersey with the No. 34 on it. The photo graced the cover of Texas'
spring prospectus, above the headline, ``A Perfect Fit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ricky wanted something that said, `I picked Mack,' '' Bianco
said. ``He's having fun with this (Heisman hype). Some days, he'll
come in and answer the phone for half an hour when he has time to
kill. He knows nine out of 10 calls are to set up interviews with
Ricky Williams.''
</P>
<P>
   Usually, Bianco said, Williams takes a message and lets Bianco
arrange an interview at a time of mutual convenience. But Williams
surprised a couple of out-of-town reporters this summer by saying,
``This is Ricky'' and doing interviews on the spot.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, a computer maven, also has sent e-mail to Heisman
voters, offering his personal top-10 lists on topics ranging from
music to the greatest college running backs of all time. He has
taken part in electronic chat rooms with ESPN SportsZone.
</P>
<P>
   Bianco's goal, as the season unfolds, is to keep Williams' name
on the minds of Heisman voters without oversaturating them. To that
end, he is unsure if Texas will engage in weekly mass mailings to
promote their tailback. A weekly conference call, Bianco said, is
probable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ours is going to be a pretty low-key campaign,'' Bianco said.
``He's going into the season as a front-runner, so the most
important thing he needs to do is keep putting up the numbers. I'm
not sure he needs more exposure. My job will be more trying to
control his time.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams' job will be to avoid opposing tacklers. He said he
looks forward to the challenge and the Heisman spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not once have I looked back and wished I'd made a different
decision,'' said Williams, who was projected to be one of the top
seven picks in the 1998 NFL draft if he bypassed his senior season.
``The Heisman is important to me. The records are important. But
it's more important to win ball games. If we win enough games, all
the individual stuff will come to me later. That's why I try and
focus attention back on the team. Without them, I'm nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   It could just as easily be argued that, without Ricky Williams,
the 1998 Longhorns would have no rallying point. For now, however,
his quest for a Heisman Trophy dominates the thoughts of coaches
and teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Even opponents envision college football's most coveted award
landing in Williams' trophy case this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he deserved it last year,'' said Missouri linebacker
Barry Odom, who watched Williams carry 23 times for 235 yards
against the Tigers in 1997. ``It seems like, to win the Heisman,
you have to be in contention to win the national championship. But
it's supposed to go to the best player in the nation. I think Ricky
Williams was that last year. And, once again, I think he has a good
chance to be that again this year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
