<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-SLUMS-REVIEW-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SLUMS' SPINS CHARM, ORIGINALIITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 CALVIN WILSON  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Slums of Beverly Hills,'' a comedy, is rated R for language
and adult situations. Running time is 1 hour 31 minutes. Three out
of four stars.
</P>
<P>
   Vivian has a big problem _ or more accurately, two big problems.
</P>
<P>
   They're between her neck and her waist, and they're driving her
crazy. It's 1976, she's a teenager, and her breasts are taking over
her life.
</P>
<P>
   Or at least, she thinks they are. The daughter of an
unsuccessful businessman who keeps moving the family from place to
place, Vivian has enough to worry about without also having to deal
with lustful males.
</P>
<P>
   That ``Slums of Beverly Hills'' spins something charming and
original from this dubious premise is due not only to the lightly
comic touch of writer//director Tamara Jenkins but also to the
film's quirkily charismatic star, Natasha Lyonne.
</P>
<P>
   As the scrappy but vulnerable Vivian, Lyonne (``Everyone Says I
Love You'') delivers a performance of loopy authority. Her Vivian
is a reluctant nomad, a girl who constantly encounters new
surroundings only to leave them.
</P>
<P>
   When her father, Murray (Alan Arkin), steers Vivian and her two
brothers into the latest in a series of rundown apartments _ this
one on the outskirts of Beverly Hills _ she assumes it will be just
another stop. But the move will permanently affect her attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``Slums of Beverly Hills'' is a coming-of-age story, but without
the self-conscious angst that often infects that genre. Although
Vivian's situation is sometimes painful, the character isn't
self-pitying or powerless. She's just a kid who feels overwhelmed
by the world. It's called adolescence.
</P>
<P>
   In a summer of gross-out comedy, ``Slums'' is an anomaly. It's
funny without being insulting, sensitive without being sappy,
insightful without being earnest.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins doesn't push for laughs. Rather, she creates an
atmosphere in which they emerge organically and surprisingly.
Characters, not shocks, come first.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't hurt that Jenkins has assembled a splendid cast.
Arkin convinces us that Murray deserves his children's love without
neglecting his childlike irresponsibility.
</P>
<P>
   As a laid-back neighbor, Kevin Corrigan (who recently turned up
in both ``Buffalo 66'' and ``Henry Fool'') shows off his trademark
blend of affability and eccentricity. And as Vivian's troubled
cousin Rita, who moves in with the family in an attempt to
straighten herself out, Marisa Tomei is as incandescent as usual.
</P>
<P>
   In this company, it's no small achievement that Lyonne commands
attention. Claire Danes, Christina Ricci and Natalie Portman will
have to make room for yet another impressive young actress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-26-98 2312EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980826.0561 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-26 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4352 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-THIEF-REVIEW-KA     08-26 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-THIEF-REVIEW-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN DRAMA IS WIDE-EYED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 ROBERT W. BUTLER  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Thief,'' a drama, opens is rated R for sexual situations
and nudity. Running time is 1 hour 37 minutes. In Russian with
English subtitles. Three out of four stars.
</P>
<P>
   Child actors are at their best when they haven't yet discovered
that they're actors.
</P>
<P>
   Check out Jackie Coogan's crying scene in Chaplin's ``The Kid.''
It works because there's not even the slightest suggestion of
manipulation in the boy's performance. It's absolutely heartfelt
and real.
</P>
<P>
   Something similar happens in the Russian ``The Thief,'' a drama
of disillusionment about a Stalin-era crook as seen through the
eyes of a 6-year-old boy. Misha Philipchuk delivers an absolutely
captivating performance as our wide-eyed protagonist _ and I mean
``wide-eyed'' in both the physical and intellectual sense.
</P>
<P>
   Young Philipchuk possesses two of the biggest, roundest, bluest
eyes ever captured on celluloid. His face is soft, almost
featureless, with his tiny mouth usually clenched in a tight
grimace. But those eyes ... they allow us to read every thought,
every emotion that passes through his tiny frame.
</P>
<P>
   And Sanya, his character, experiences a lot. The son of a Soviet
soldier who died in combat before the boy's birth, Sanya is being
raised by his doting mother, the beautiful Katya (Ekaterina
Rednikova), who is little more than child herself.
</P>
<P>
   As the film begins in 1952, they're on a crowded train where
they encounter Tolyan (Vladimir Mashkov), a charismatic army
officer who in short order sweeps both mother and son off their
feet. Mama responds to him sexually. As for Sanya, he's won over
when Tolyan conspiratorially asks the kid to keep watch over his
automatic pistol.
</P>
<P>
   Posing as a family, the three move into a boarding house in a
provincial city. The adults indulge is lots of lovemaking. Sanya
makes friends with a neighbor girl and gets picked on by the local
bullies. Tolyan rises to heroic status when he coaches the boy in
self-defense. (In one glorious moment Sanya triumphs over his
adversaries and has to be dragged from the fray; halfway home he
spins around and kicks viciously at nothing in particular, just out
of sheer machismo.)
</P>
<P>
   The only problem with all this cozy domesticity is that it's
built on a lie. Tolyan isn't an army officer. He's a career thief
who routinely cleans out their fellow tenants, then makes his
escape with Katja and Sanya on a midnight train. In the next city
they'll repeat the process.
</P>
<P>
   Katya may complain, but she's in love and can't leave him _ even
when he resorts to thuggish behavior to impose his will.
</P>
<P>
   A nominee for this year's Oscar for Best Foreign Language Film,
``The Thief'' gets a great deal of mileage out of its setting.
Besides the fine performances, writer//director Pavel Chukhrai
expertly evokes the atmosphere of Stalinist Russia _ the monumental
government buildings, the cramped apartments and communal kitchens,
the drab clothing, the sound of accordion-music drifting down a
poorly lighted hallway.
</P>
<P>
   It's not an overtly political film _ none of the characters seem
to harbor particularly strong beliefs, although most accept without
question that Comrade Stalin has their best interests at heart. But
metaphorically it's all about politics _ like Stalin, Tolyan has
the ability to make others think he's generous, outgoing and
patriotic. In reality, he cares about nothing but himself.
</P>
<P>
   It's a lesson that little Sanya will learn the hard way, and
that will stay with him forever.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
