A4355 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-GREY-REVIEW-KAN     08-26 0397
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GREY-REVIEW-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILMMAKERS ARE STAR-STRUCK JUST LIKE THE REST OF US 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 CALVIN WILSON  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Grey Gardens,'' a documentary, is unrated. Running time is 1
hour 35 minutes. Two and a half out of four stars.
</P>
<P>
   Edith Bouvier Beale and her daughter Edie are elderly women who
live on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   Their home is filthy, and they're unkempt. They bicker. They
talk to the filmmakers. A raccoon pokes its head into the house.
The women bicker again.
</P>
<P>
   You get the picture. This is cinema verite, and the fact that
we're allowed to listen to these women nattering on in their ratty
mansion is supposed to mean something.
</P>
<P>
   But all it really means is that the highly overrated Maysles
Brothers, who directed the film, first released in 1976, were as
starstruck as the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   You did catch the name Bouvier, didn't you? As in Jackie O. As
in Kennedy. `It's highly likely that the only reason 79-year-old
Big Edie (the mother) and 56-year-old Little Edie became film
subjects was because they were the aunt and first cousin of
Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis. And therefore fascinating. Right.
</P>
<P>
   The case could be made that Albert and David Maysles (along with
three collaborators) were trying to solve a mystery: How could the
two Edies, formerly entrenched in high society, sink so low? Or
maybe they were simply attempting to show the dark side of the
Kennedy clan. Or maybe they just wanted to embarrass the Kennedys.
</P>
<P>
   But on all three counts, they failed.
</P>
<P>
   Each strategy could have yielded fertile results. But the
brothers don't follow through. It's as if they thought just turning
on the camera and filming extensively was enough. Right _ if you
like tedium.
</P>
<P>
   What the late David Maysles and brother Albert apparently lacked
was the sense of irony that would have made ``Grey Gardens''
something more than a gross invasion of privacy. Neither did they
possess the artistry to make the film a metaphor for lost hope.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these criticisms, the film is weirdly compelling in a
``Truman Show'' sort of way. Just watching these two apparently
clueless women being exploited is an odd thrill. And a shameless
thrill, to be sure. Who wouldn't enjoy catching a glimpse of a
79-year-old woman's backside?
</P>
<P>
   These days, you take your thrills where you can get them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
