<HEADER>
A4356 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-WHITE-KANSAS-     08-26 0484
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-WHITE-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOK OUT! 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JACKIE WHITE  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Another look at Diana
</P>
<P>
   Young, naive and unsophisticated, Princess Diana first emerged
in the public spotlight under the influence of her mother's dowdy
English style.
</P>
<P>
   When she married Prince Charles, she fell under the tutelage of
the English Vogue editors, thanks to her sister, Lady Jane
Fellowes, who had once worked at the magazine. Diana frequently
made her own decisions, however, and in an effort to fit in with
the royals and in keeping with the excessive fashion of the early
1980s, she was often a vision of fussy hats and suits that seemed
too old.
</P>
<P>
   But as she matured and suffered through painfully public
personal difficulties, she honed her instincts. Ultimately she
learned to use her image to enhance both her personal power and
effectiveness in her charity work.
</P>
<P>
   The anniversary Monday of Princess Diana's death has triggered
publication of a series of new Diana books. One notable example is
Diana, The Secrets of Her Style (GT Publishing, $30) by Diane
Clehane, in which her transformation from Sloane Ranger to
Cinderella bride to a Versace-dressed beauty is eloquently traced.
</P>
<P>
   The author, an American reporter who covers celebrities, talked
to British designers such as Donald Campbell, who dressed Diana in
the beginning. ``She thought fashion was a necessary evil,'' he
said of those early years. She made her own decisions generally
without his advice or approval.
</P>
<P>
   But ultimately, she adapted a sleek, simple look that emphasized
her beauty. She became the woman of whom Donna Karan said: ``...She
took a role and created it with style and grace under enormous,
enormous difficulty ...''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, she inspired women to copy her sleek haircut and her
penchant for pearl chokers, but it was the reinvention of herself
as a strong, modern woman to whom we could relate that made her a
style icon in the '90s. The book, with many photos not seen before,
is a worthy tribute.
</P>
<P>
   You're on what corner?
</P>
<P>
   You're traipsing about New York City in desperate search for,
say, Diesel jeans or antique buttons. You can't remember how to get
to Barney's, the trendy specialty store. You're in SoHo streets and
you're starving. Or you're determined to find the J. Crew store on
lower Fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Here is help. It's the New York Shopping Guide, 1999 (Tobe, $18)
produced by editors of The Tobe Report, a weekly retail trade
publication. The paper-bound book contains 11 walking tours by
neighborhoods and includes department stores, boutiques and home
furnishing stores along with restaurants and museums from New
Yorkers who know about such things. The information includes
addresses, type of merchandise and business hours.
</P>
<P>
   To order, call (212) 867-8677, Ext. 226, or fax (212) 867-8662.
Count on $3 for shipping.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
