A4357 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-PREVIEW-UTCAPSULE     08-26 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-PREVIEW-UTCAPSULE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS LONGHORNS CAPSULE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
TEXAS LONGHORNS 
1997 record: 4-7, 2-6 in Big 12 
Coach (record): Mack Brown (first year at Texas, 86-74-1 overall) 
Stadium: Darrell K. Royal-Memorial Stadium (80,216) 
Ticket information: (800) 982-BEVO, (512) 477-6060 
PIECES IN PLACE 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Senior TB Ricky Williams (1,893 yards, 25 TDs), senior TE Derek
Lewis (20 catches, 2 TDs), senior RT Jay Humphrey (1997
all-conference selection), senior MLB Dusty Renfro (116 tackles, 8
for losses), junior DE Aaron Humphrey (76 tackles, 12 for losses).
Williams, the team's Heisman Trophy candidate, has an experienced
line in front of him and a chance to carry at least 35 times per
game. Beyond that, off-season overhauls of the passing game,
kicking game and defense make all three areas unknown commodities. &QL; 
KEY NEWCOMERS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LB De'Andre Lewis, CB Chris Butcher, K Kris Stockton. Lewis, a
converted fullback, is expected to be one of the team's primary
pass rushers from his outside linebacker spot. Butcher, a converted
tailback, must master man-to-man coverage skills to succeed in the
team's blitz-oriented defense. Stockton might be the first Texas
player since Russell Erxleben in 1978 to handle both punting and
placement duties. &QL; 
KEY LOSSES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   QB James Brown, K Phil Dawson, C Ryan Fiebiger. The Longhorns
will be hard-pressed to replace Brown, a four-year starter and the
leading passer in school history. Dawson, a two-time All-American,
became a security blanket for an inconsistent attack. Fiebiger, a
three-year starter, provided stability and a consistent crease for
Williams between the tackles. &QL; 
MISSING PIECE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Senior Richard Walton, Brown's replacement at quarterback, has
completed 84 of 153 passes for 1,091 yards in spot duty during his
college career. But he struggled in 1997, throwing for only 314
yards with more interceptions (three) than touchdowns (one). Walton
seemed to lose confidence after Texas was swamped by UCLA, 66-3, in
his only start. Regaining the form Walton exhibited in his first
two seasons, rather than 1997, will be critical for the team's
success. &QL; 
BIGGEST TEST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A two-week stretch with road games at UCLA (Sept. 12) and Kansas
State (Sept. 19) should tell volumes about the team's mental
makeup. Texas cratered after a 66-3 loss to UCLA in 1997, and Mack
Brown has vowed not to let disappointment fester with this team. &QL; 
WATCH OUT FOR &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Blown defensive assignments, especially early in the season.
Four projected defensive starters played other positions last
season, and Brown has indicated a willingness to play all four of
his incoming freshmen linebackers to get more speed on the field.
Radical changes in personnel and defensive philosophy might work
over time, but expect some growing pains in September. &QL; 
Milestones: Brown must win at least six games to match the initial
efforts of the past three men who have tried _ and failed _ to
replace coach Darrell Royal in the hearts and minds of Texas fans.
Fred Akers was 11-1 in 1977, David McWilliams was 7-5 in 1987, and
John Mackovic was 6-5 in 1992. &QL; 
PREDICTION: 6-5 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Texas will be overmatched physically against Top 25 opponents
UCLA, Kansas State, Nebraska and Texas A&AMP;M. They'll make a
difficult road trip to Texas Tech (Nov. 14) and have a tough home
game Nov. 7 against Oklahoma State. A winning record is not
guaranteed. But Williams should be good enough to squeeze this team
into the Alamo Bowl. &QL; 
OVERVIEW &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The change in philosophy from the stoic Mackovic to the
emotional Brown should breathe life into an underachieving team.
But at some point, the excitement will fade and talent will win
out. And Texas, at this point, does not have enough defensive
talent to be much better than a .500 team. &QL; 
PUZZLE PIECE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Richard Walton must throw the ball effectively
enough that defenses can't crowd the line against tailback Ricky
Williams, the team's Heisman Trophy hopeful. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
