<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CADARET JOINS RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Greg Cadaret joined the Rangers yesterday and
was pleased to be with a contender, but he's not quite sure what
he's doing here. The left-handed reliever was released by the
Anaheim Angels despite having a respectable 4.14 earned-run average
and holding left-handed batters to a .230 batting average.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised to be released there,'' he said. ``They had no
explanation other than they needed a roster spot. It was totally
unexpected and frustrating, to be sure.''
</P>
<P>
   While he joins a contender, he leaves a first-place team. The
Rangers trail the Angels in the American League West. Cadaret would
like nothing more than to catch his old team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It adds a lot of spice to it,' he said. ``I had intended to
help them win the pennant. It's a good group of guys over there.
But I'd be more than happy to take that playoff spot away from
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Cadaret doesn't yet know if he'll be the first or second lefty
out of the bullpen, but he said that's not important.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care what the role is,'' he said. ``It's all about
winning the pennant. I'll throw every day the rest of the season if
that's what it takes.''
Trying too hard
</P>
<P>
   Pitching coach Dick Bosman watched tape of Todd Stottlemyre's
outing against the Tigers on Tuesday, and came away with one
inescapable conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``His location is not good,'' Bosman said.
</P>
<P>
   Bosman didn't spot anything mechanical that would lead to the
bad location, but suspects it's because Stottlemyre is
overthrowing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good competitor,'' Bosman said. ``He wants to do well,
and when the wheels come off you try to do more. When you try to do
more, you generally end up doing less.''
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre, whose ERA rose to 7.03 after allowing five runs on
eight hits in 3 1/3 innings, sustained an injury to his lower back
and rib cage sliding into a base for the St. Louis Cardinals before
the trade to the Rangers. But manager Johnny Oates said that is not
a factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt in my mind he's healthy,'' Oates said.
``Mechanically, I don't see anything different than I've ever seen.
It's just a matter of relaxing and making pitches.''
Newson optioned out
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder Warren Newson was optioned to Triple-A Oklahoma to
make room on the roster for Cadaret as the Rangers elected to keep
12 pitchers instead of an extra bench player.
</P>
<P>
   Oates opted for the pitcher because the Rangers play a
doubleheader tomorrow in Chicago and because designated hitter Lee
Stevens, like Newson a left-handed hitter, could return from the
disabled list by the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a doubleheader coming up, and with the possibility of
Lee coming back we felt that was the way to go,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   As a player with more than five years of major-league service,
Newson could have refused an assignment and declared free agency.
But after being assured he would rejoin the team in 10 days, he
decided to go to Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand the situation,'' he said. ``I'm the lowest man on
the totem pole.''
Gonzalez out of field
</P>
<P>
   Juan Gonzalez was the designated hitter for the second
consecutive game, and he is unsure when he'll return to right
field. Gonzalez has a sore right calf muscle that shows no signs of
improving.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's bothering me,'' he said. ``I don't feel good.''
Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez took a .298 batting average into last night's game, and
is aiming for a .300 batting average for the third time in his
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Power hitters don't need to hit .300,'' he said. ``But when
you get close, you try harder.''
</P>
<P>
   Umpire Rocky Roe left the crew that worked the game yesterday
because of a knee problem that will require surgery. He was
replaced by Eric Cooper. Farm report Triple-A Oklahoma (Pacific
Coast League): The RedHawks lost at Omaha, 3-2 in 12 innings,
Tuesday. Eric Moody pitched 4 2/3 innings in relief, but lost on an
unearned run. Center fielder Les Norman had three hits, including
his 10th homer.
</P>
<P>
   Double-A Tulsa (Texas League): The Drillers lost to Jackson,
6-1, with starter Ken Juarbe giving up all the runs in 5 2/3
innings. Scheduled starter Dan Smith was scratched because of the
flu.
</P>
<P>
   Class-A Charlotte (Florida State League): Shawn Gallagher
homered and drove in two runs as the Rangers won at Clearwater,
7-6. Gallagher is third in the FSL with 22 homers and leads with
105 runs batted in. Francisco Saneaux earned the victory in relief
by allowing one run in four innings.
</P>
<P>
   Class-A Savannah (South Atlantic League): The Sand Gnats won at
Columbus, 5-4, to snap a six-game losing streak. Starting pitcher
Aaron Bond gave up two runs in 6 1/3 innings, but wasn't involved
in the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Pulaski (Appalachian League, rookie): Starting pitcher Matthew
Kosderka struck out 14 batters in seven innings, the most for a
pitcher in the Texas organization this season, but the Rangers lost
at Martinsville, 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   Gulf Coast (Gulf Coast League, rookie): The Rangers fell to the
Red Sox, 9-3, to fall out of first place in the Western Division of
the Gulf Coast League.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
