<HEADLINE>
HOMER MAKES WILLIAMS UNLIKELY HERO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Talk about making the most of an opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Reggie Williams hit his first career major-league home run
Wednesday and it couldn't have come at a better time. His blast in
the first game of the doubleheader gave the Angels a 3-2
fifth-inning lead on their way to a 6-4 win over the New York
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never envisioned having a shot in a pennant race,'' said
Williams, who before this season had played 10 years of
professional baseball but only 15 games in the majors. ``God has a
way of working things out.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who was called up from Triple-A Vancouver Aug. 10,
threw his fist into the air as he ran between first and second on
the homer and was obviously excited upon reaching the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   ``He about broke everybody's hands high-fiving in the dugout,''
Angels manager Terry Collins said. ``He should be (excited). He's
just trying to have some fun. It's been a long season for a lot of
us. Guys like him and (Orlando Palmeiro) have brought some life to
the club.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, 32, spent most of his career in the Angels
organization until being traded to the Dodgers for pitcher Mike
James in 1994. The Dodgers released him after the 1996 season and
he was playing in Mexico last summer when the Angels signed him
last August.
</P>
<P>
   __ Going on guts: Troy Percival needed 39 pitches to throw 12/3
innings and save Tuesday's game and wasn't expected to be available
for Wednesday's first game. Not only was he available, Percival
closed it out, pitching the ninth for his career-high 37th save.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever I can do,'' Percival said. ``It's August. We're in a
pennant hunt right now. Unless I don't think I can get the job
done, I'll go out there. We've got guys like (Gary) DiSarcina and
(Darin) Erstad grinding every day for nine innings, I can go one
(inning).''
</P>
<P>
   __ Up, then down: Yankees pitcher Ryan Bradley made his first
major-league start in the first game and just his third
major-league appearance. He got the start because scheduled starter
Ramiro Mendoza was a late scratch after having a cyst removed from
his buttocks.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, the Yankees' first-round pick out of Arizona State last
year, shut the Angels out through four innings but surrendered
three runs in the fifth, three more in the sixth to take the loss.
</P>
<P>
   He started this season in Single-A, then made stops in Double-A
and Triple-A before joining the Yankees on Aug. 21. But after the
game, Bradley was optioned to Triple-A Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley and Angels third baseman Troy Glaus had a reunion of
sorts. In 1996, Bradley was playing for Arizona State and Glaus for
UCLA when Bradley hit Glaus in the head with a pitch, sending Glaus
to the hospital. There were hard feelings, and Bradley hit Glaus
with a pitch the next time the two faced each other later that
season. Wednesday, Bradley got the best of Glaus, striking him out
twice in two at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   __ Roster shuffling: &UR; !off! &LR;  The Angels will be forced to move
someone off the roster on Friday to make room for Ken Hill.
Left-handed reliever Trevor Wilson is expected to go.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
