<SLUG> BC-BBN-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASTIANELLI SETTLED AS SURE RECEIVER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVINE, Calif. _ USC wide receiver Mike Bastianelli fractured
his collarbone last spring, but he's shown no ill effects from the
injury and is considered one of the Trojans' top two receivers
heading into Sunday's game against Purdue.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Billy Miller, Bastianelli will be expected to pick up
the slack for R. Jay Soward, who is suspended from the Purdue game
for poor academic performance.
</P>
<P>
   Bastianelli relishes the extra responsibility, in part because
he feels he has matured this summer. He recently got married and is
now more worried about graduating and planning his future life than
just playing football.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've grown up. I don't do anything anymore,'' Bastianelli
said. ``I'm a husband. I sit at home. I don't go out and goof off.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past two years, I consider myself to have become a
totally different person.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing that hasn't changed are Bastianelli's sure hands. He
is USC's No.1 possession receiver after catching 33 passes last
season and he figures to surpass that total this year.
</P>
<P>
   His versatility remains a key for the Trojans. Bastianelli will
hold on field goals and extra points this year and is also a backup
punter. He can also kick off if needed.
</P>
<P>
   __ Alumni return: Former USC defensive linemen Matt Keneley and
David Webb visited practice Wednesday. Keneley was on his way out
of town before stopping at UC Irvine. He was called by the Detroit
Lions on Wednesday morning and told to report to their training
camp, where he will join the practice squad.
</P>
<P>
   __ Injury update: Offensive lineman Ken Bowen is officially
listed as questionable with a hyperextended elbow, but it is
unlikely he will play. Freshman quarterback Jason Thomas' sore
ankle was examined by doctors Tuesday evening and rest was
prescribed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until he's ruled out being an emergency player, he will be
standing right next to me (during the game),'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Collision course: It's one thing to practice with reckless
abandon, but things got out of hand when graduate assistant Jason
Gelber and a motorized cart he was driving flipped.
</P>
<P>
   Gelber barely escaped injury, but the noise and smoke from the
accident were of a serious enough magnitude to stop the nearby
drills.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
