<SLUG> BC-FBC-BRUINS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRESH PRINTS AROUND BRUINS CAMP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's no secret why UCLA is ranked No.7 in both
polls and picked to win the Pac-10 championship. Quarterback Cade
McNown is a Heisman Trophy contender. Strong safety Larry Atkins
and left tackle Kris Farris are among the best in the nation at
their positions, while Chris Sailer is an All-America kicker.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, if the Bruins get to the Rose Bowl or better still, the
Fiesta Bowl it won't be without a big contribution from this year's
freshman class.
</P>
<P>
   The group of 24 scholarship players UCLA signed in February was
rated either No. 1 or No. 2 in the nation by five recruiting
services and it hasn't taken long for it to make an impact. Even by
the time the Bruins had their first full-contact practice
Wednesday, seven of the recruits had crept up to at least third
string.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA coach Bob Toledo said he expects 8 to 10 of the freshmen to
play this year about twice the norm and a handful could start.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're physically capable and mentally capable, there's no
reason for them not to play,'' Toledo said. ``In this day and age,
freshmen have to play and contribute.''
</P>
<P>
   McNown, one of 14 Bruin upperclassmen who played as freshmen,
says the most important thing is arriving at school ready to play
mentally and physically.
</P>
<P>
   ``The No. 1 thing in order for a true freshman is to spend the
summer thinking about what it takes to play college football,''
McNown said. ``The coaches don't know what to expect but you'll get
a chance. If show you can do it, there will be more
opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   The players expected to contribute the most this year are
tailback DeShaun Foster, inside linebacker Robert Thomas,
cornerback Lovell Houston and nose guard Ken Kocher.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, Foster and Kocher each were unanimous Best in the West
selections this year and Houston was one of the most coveted
defensive backs in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Foster, a 6-foot-1, 205-pounder from Tustin High, is the one
running back the Bruins have who can replace Skip Hicks as an
every-down back. But Foster has missed most practices so far by
re-aggravating a groin injury he first hurt practicing for the
Californa-Texas Shrine game last month.
</P>
<P>
   Kocher, a 6-4, 292-pound nose guard from San Diego Patrick
Henry, will help the Bruins get bigger and stronger up front, one
of Toledo's top recruiting priorities. ``He's mature and his
capable,'' Toledo said of Kocher. ``The only thing will be how fast
can he learn, but he will play. It will be kind of like (sophomore
defensive end Kenyon) Coleman. We'll get him a certain number of
snaps.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston, a 6-1, 180-pounder from Denver Jefferson, has been
slowed by a thigh injury, but he's expected to play at cornerback
and also may have an impact returning kicks, something ``we need
dearly,'' said Toledo.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, a 6-2, 225-pounder from Imperial, has such tremendous
speed that he's drawing comparisons to All-Pro linebacker Ken
Norton Jr., a former Bruin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel a lot of pressure,'' Thomas said of the expectations.
``I'm a highly touted linebacker and I expect to play, but I enjoy
the pressure. Everyone's good out here and that makes you want to
work harder.''
</P>
<P>
   Left tackle Blake Worley and right guard Mike Saffer have also
been impressive, moving up to second string. But playing time may
be hard to come by backing up Farris and Andy Meyers, one of the
Pac-10's to guards.
</P>
<P>
   The best opportunities to play are on defense where only four
starters return and only two players Atkins and outside linebacker
Brendan Ayanbadejo are guaranteed starting jobs. Julius Williams, a
cornerback and teammate of Foster's at Tustin, has looked good in
coverage drills, moving up to third string. Rusty Williams, an
outside linebacker/defensive end from Vista, has impressed
defensive coordinator Nick Aliotti.
</P>
<P>
   Two walk-ons, kicker Adam Griffith from Gardnersville, Nev., and
long snapper Jeff Grau from Loyola, have also worked their way to
the second team.
</P>
<P>
   In the next two weeks, Toledo will have a better handle on who
should be able to contribute and who will be candidates to
redshirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``As they find out more and more who won't play or (who will)
redshirt, it becomes a little bit of a problem, but that's my job
to constantly talk to them,'' Toledo said. ``They're all highly
recruited guys and it's not easy when they come in here and
redshirt or don't play or don't start right away. In turn, it's the
same problem with the guys who are here some of those freshmen are
moving ahead of them. But those are good problems. I can handle
those.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
