<HEADLINE>
COETZER LIVES UP TO HER REPUTATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JACK CAVANAUGH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN, Conn. _ When she beat Steffi Graf for the first of
three times last year in the Round of 16 in the Australian Open,
the 5-foot-2-inch Amanda Coetzer was dubbed the Little Assassin, an
appellation attributable to her stalking, tenacious, never-give-up
style of play.
</P>
<P>
   The nickname stuck, and Coetzer more than lived up to that
reputation Wednesday in the second round of the inaugural Pilot Pen
Women's Championships.
</P>
<P>
   With 17-year-old Anna Kournikova serving for their match at 5-3
in the third set, Coetzer ran off the last four games and
prevailed, 1-6, 6-4, 7-5.
</P>
<P>
   That hardly came as good news to Graf, who, although she has
beaten Coetzer 10 times in 14 meetings, lost to the 26-year-old
South African in three of four matches last year and must face her
in the quarterfinals Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The 29-year-old Graf is playing in only her ninth tournament of
the year after spending eight months recuperating from knee
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The German accepted a late wild card into this event, and on
Tuesday night she routed 19-year-old Henrieta Nagyova of Slovakia.
</P>
<P>
   Kournikova has had a better year than Coetzer this season,
beating 33 of 45 opponents, including Martina Hingis, Lindsay
Davenport, Monica Seles and Arantxa Sanchez-Vicario. Kournikova is,
however, ranked two notches lower, at No. 14, than Coetzer, who has
a 21-14 record against lesser opposition.
</P>
<P>
   But Coetzer has been ranked as high as third in the world, and
eventually was named the most improved player on the Women's Tennis
Association Tour in 1997. Wednesday afternoon, at the Connecticut
Tennis Center, she demonstrated once again why she is known as one
of the most resolute players on the tour.
</P>
<P>
   After losing the last six games of the opening set to the
aggressive, hard-hitting Kournikova, Coetzer struggled to take the
second set and then mounted her late comeback to close out the
match.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been looking for this kind of match to set me up for my
next matches and the U.S. Open,'' Coetzer said. ``I feel I was
lacking a little bit of that tenacity and self-encouragement to
pull out of a tough situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Coetzer, essentially a baseliner whose temper sometimes has got
the best of her, was nothing if not tenacious in breaking
Kournikova at love when the Russian teen-ager was serving for the
match. Having dodged that bullet, Coetzer then won the next three
games.
</P>
<P>
   Kournikova, who is seeded 15th in the U.S. Open, which begins
Monday, cited Coetzer's determination as the key factor in the
match.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she was just hanging in the match and just trying to
get all the balls back and not try to make mistakes, which she
didn't,'' Kournikova said. ``She was just being tough out there and
she kept on going. And I started staying back, which I shouldn't
have been doing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
