<SLUG> BC-GOLF-SHOW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS SHOW, THE INTERNATIONAL WAS MERELY A SHORT DRIVE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By MIKE STACHURA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS, Nev. _ It seems almost a city ordinance here that all
things, regardless of their substance or worth, must be grotesquely
large. Whether it's hotel casinos, neon signs or breakfast buffets,
nothing can get away with being low profile.
</P>
<P>
   Still, despite having the largest number of exhibitors in show
history, low profile is precisely what this year's PGA
International Golf Show here last week turned out to be. Whether
you were talking about the popular new style of fairway woods or
the sentiment that kept some major manufacturers from exhibiting at
this show at all, almost everything about golf's trip to the Strip
this year was decidedly low profile.
</P>
<P>
   Equipment giants like Titleist, FootJoy, Cobra, Spalding and
Etonic opted out of exhibiting at the industry's semiannual
show-and-tell expo, as did several mid-range companies like Ben
Hogan Golf, Bridgestone and PowerBilt. Some had new products they
introduced this summer anyway, like Titleist's new irons and
PowerBilt's affordably priced line of fairway woods, but most did
not.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the show, which occupied some 775,000 square feet (or
about 13 football fields) inside the Las Vegas Convention Center
once again provided no shortage of curiosities. The equipment buzz
ran the gamut from ``multimetal'' clubhead materials like those in
the new Liquidmetal driver to the ``biomagnetic'' innersoles in
Florsheim's new Magneforce spikeless golf shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Ely Callaway, the patriarchical wizard behind Callaway Golf,
once again could smile at the frenzied activity around his
company's mammoth booth in the center of the show floor.
</P>
<P>
   The Callaway excitement centered on its new Steelhead metal wood
line, designed with a lower center of gravity to help players
launch their shots on the proper trajectory. The line replaces the
company's wildly popular War Birdline of stainless steel woods, as
well as combats the recent success that many smaller companies have
had with low-profile fairway woods.
</P>
<P>
   Callaway was happy his company was here, almost as happy as he
was that some of his competitors were not. ``We like for our
competitors to make mistakes in judgment,'' he said. ``Of course,
any well-developed product can exist without a show, but I feel a
new product does better with one than without.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the competition surely agreed in their own low-profile
ways. The booth at Orlimar, a small Northern California-based club
maker that struck gold this summer with its infomercial sensation
Tri-Metal line of fairway woods, was busy as the company unveiled a
new similarly constructed driver, as well as new low-slung
Tri-Metal irons. And Nike reintroduced its modified Air Zoom TW
(Tiger Woods) shoe, dropping the retail price from $225 to $160.
</P>
<P>
   Most new iron introductions reflected a return to simpler looks
with a high-tech twist. Maxfli offered two blade-like irons,
including the sharp-looking ``tour cavity'' Revolution iron, which
has been seen in Fred Couples' bag of late. Mizuno, the leading
iron company among PGA Tour players, also introduced the Comp EZ,
an oversized forged iron.
</P>
<P>
   Still, much of the talk centered on what wasn't unveiled here.
Adams Golf, whose success story has inspired many imitators,
extended its fairway wood line, but there were rumors that a new
driver is in the works for January's PGA Merchandise Show in
Orlando, Fla. Callaway Golf, which has spent $130 million in
developing a ball product line, could be ready for a debut in
January, too. Also lurking in the ball game for an Orlando rollout
is Nike, which has been showing off its prototypes to selected
parties for the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping a curiously low profile in Las Vegas was Taylor Made,
which had the good fortune to have its products in the bags of the
winners of three of the four majors this year, and as a result is
selling the most drivers in stores this summer, according to some
surveys.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor Made's president, George Montgomery, suggested that
titanium's popularity may be coming to a close.
</P>
<P>
   ``By my count, there have been about six million titanium
drivers sold and that's very close to the number of avid core
golfers out there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The folks at the startup company, Liquidmetal Golf, think they
have just that product. Their line of drivers, irons and putters is
constructed of a special multimaterial metal alloy that is touted
as being twice as strong as titanium. Liquidmetal's waterfall booth
was anything but low profile, and so are its economics. The putters
will retail for $400, the drivers for $595 and the set of eight
irons will cost at least $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   But company president John Hoefflich doesn't see anything out of
touch about the price. ``We don't sense any resistance to this
price because this is a unique product,'' he said. ``I think what's
happening is golfers have decided not to buy anything until
something better comes along. Maybe what they've been waiting for
is our product.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
