HARD WORK KEEPS McEWAN AT NO. 3 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
 !head!Hard work keeps McEwan at No.   3!dlim! !by1! By  Jon
Wilner  
!by2!Daily News Staff Writer!dlim!
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; !text! &LR; There was no siren, no flashing red light. But Bruins
coach Bob Toledo seemed to be placing redshirt freshman quarterback
Scott McEwan, a Thousand Oaks native, on alert.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's No. 3, but he'll get a lot of push from (true freshmen)
Ryan McCann and Cory Paus,'' Toledo said. ``They have the ability.
Now it's a matter of us coaching them. We're pleased with both of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words: If McEwan did not improve quickly and
decisively, he could plummet on the depth chart _ behind not only
Cade McNown and backup Drew Bennett but also Paus and McCann, a
Westlake Village native.
</P>
<P>
   Well, McEwan has improved. He's more confident and more poised.
His passes are crisp, tight spirals, not the floating, wobbly balls
he launched in spring practice. A week into training camp, he
stands as one of UCLA's most improved players. And has established
himself as the No. 3 quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not doing bad,'' offensive coordinator Al Borges said.
``He still could have better accuracy. But he understands the
offense better. His fundamentals have improved. He's progressing
steadily.''
</P>
<P>
   McEwan credits his improvement to familiarity with the offense.
Last season, he was preoccupied with the passing game nuances and
abandoned his mechanics. After an offseason of studying film and
the playbook, he instinctively knows the pass patterns and can
concentrate on his delivery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel much more relaxed,'' McEwan said. ``I just have to keep
improving. That can never stop, so that next year Drew and I are
fighting it out.''
</P>
<P>
   __ No offense taken: Asked if he took the recruitment of Paus
and McCann as a no-confidence vote in his future, McEwan went the
diplomatic route.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the competition,'' he said. ``To get pushed from behind
helps to keep you from settling. Besides, when I came in, there
were two quarterbacks (McEwan and Ed Stansbury, who has moved to
linebacker). I could have taken the whole thing personally, but
that would be wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!How they stand:!off! Borges on the performances of
quarterbacks not named McNown or McEwan.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett: ``Until (Monday) he was struggling, but he picked it
up. He's got a better spiral. He's starting to get back. Early on,
he was shaking off the dust.''
</P>
<P>
   Paus: ``He's got a really good arm and natural leadership skills
that will manifest themselves as he gains experience.''
</P>
<P>
   McCann: ``He's exactly what we thought. He has a quick release
and a good arm.''
</P>
<P>
   Barring a spate of injuries, McCann and Paus will redshirt.
</P>
<P>
   __ Going fast: UCLA expects a crowd of at least 70,000 for the
Sept. 12 home opener against Texas. That figure is closer to a
sellout that it would have been in the past, since offseason
renovations have reduced the Rose Bowl's seating capacity from
100,000 to 90,000.
</P>
<P>
   __ Injury update: The Bruins experienced their first significant
injuries on the first day of full-contact workouts. Third-string
center Tony Ippolito fractured his right ankle and is out 6-8
weeks. Freshman cornerback Joe Hunter, who was expected to
redshirt, sprained his left knee and will miss 4-6 weeks. Nose
guard Ken Kocher, one of the most impressive freshmen, was carted
off the field Wednesday afternoon. The preliminary report was a
bruised right ankle.
</P>
</TEXT>
