<SLUG> BC-RAC-SARATOGA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVERS COULD BE VICTORY GALLOP'S `SUMMERTIME DERBY' 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ Victory Gallop, the only veteran of the
Kentucky Derby who will run in the Travers Stakes, lay quietly in
his stall Wednesday morning after an easy jog around the track at
Saratoga Race Course. His trainer, Elliott Walden, considered the
shifting fortunes of life in the big leagues of racing and said:
``You hate to be overconfident, but I like where we are coming into
the Travers.''
</P>
<P>
   This is where Walden is: His star colt, second in the Derby in
May to Real Quiet and second in the Haskell in July to Coronado's
Quest, will run in ``the summertime Derby'' on Saturday with a new
jockey and one old and dangerous rival. The jockey is Alex Solis,
who replaces the injured Gary Stevens; the old rival is Coronado's
Quest, the dynamite horse of the season's second half, who will
fight Victory Gallop for the leadership of the 3-year-old division.
</P>
<P>
   Seven colts were poised to enter the Travers Stakes when post
positions are drawn on Thursday, but Victory Gallop, who won the
Belmont Stakes, remained the only one with Triple Crown
credentials. Still, he was in the position of a baseball team that
has a scrapbook but not yet a championship, with half the season to
play. And Coronado's Quest was alive, with four victories in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Walden said that he was not perturbed by the change in jockeys.
Stevens, the regular rider on Victory Gallop, tore ligaments in his
knee at Del Mar last weekend. But Solis was the rider when Victory
Gallop won the Arkansas Derby in April and ran second in the
Kentucky Derby one month later.
</P>
<P>
   ``You certainly don't like to make changes at this stage,'' the
trainer said, ``but it won't affect Victory Gallop. Alex has ridden
him before, and won on him before, so that won't make any
difference. And remember, this horse is used to adversity. We had
to deal with a skin rash and a broken ankle before the Belmont
Stakes.''
</P>
<P>
   The skin rash bedeviled Victory Gallop for a couple of weeks,
making it uncomfortable for him to be saddled; the broken ankle
bedeviled Walden, who broke it while playing in a pickup basketball
game. But they both endured, and Victory Gallop indeed defeated
Real Quiet by a nose in the Belmont and ruined his shot at sweeping
the Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   But Coronado's Quest had his own problems: His springtime was
spoiled by violent behavior before races and later by a foot
injury. He has emerged to become the monster of the second half of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very much on the same schedule as Seeking the Gold was
for his Travers,'' said Shug McGaughey, who trained both horses.
``They both ran in the Dwyer and the Haskell.''
</P>
<P>
   Seeking the Gold lost the Haskell in 1988 and then the Travers
to Forty Niner, who is the sire of Coronado's Quest. McGaughey did
win the Travers twice, with Easy Goer in 1989 and Rhythm in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Coronado's Quest did some galloping Wednesday morning, then was
led to the paddock before noon. It was his first visit to the
Saratoga paddock and he became ornery, but McGaughey accepted his
behavior with the assurance of a man who has been there before.
</P>
<P>
   The two big horses expect to be confronted in the Travers by
Raffie's Majesty, Grand Slam, Archers Bay, Dice Dancer and Deputy
Diamond. Those choosing other races included Thomas Jo, Limit Out
and Tomorrow's Cat.
</P>
<P>
   Don Zuckerman, the owner of Tomorrow's Cat, agonized over the
decision, saying at one point: ``What if the hurricane hits?'' To
which his trainer, Mark Hennig, replied: ``Don, I'm not even sure a
hurricane would help us.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
