<SLUG> BC-BBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUIZENGA ON ANDRO-GATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)(SLANG) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Dr. Robert Huizenga probably has as much insight
into the power and destructiveness of performance-enhancing drugs
than any doctor working in sports medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Huizenga was a team doctor for the Los Angeles Raiders, a period
of his medical career that was a fertile clinic into the medical
and drug abuses in professional sports, by the athletes themselves
as well as their alleged medical caretakers.
</P>
<P>
   As the personal physician for Lyle Alzado, he had a
heartbreaking ringside seat for the former Raiders' tortured death
due to cancer after years of steroid use.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lyle denied using steroids viciously until he developed a
life-threatening cancer as a result of them,'' Huizenga said. ``He
spent the rest of his life telling people how dangerous steroids
can be.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, messages like those are rarely long-lasting and
do not always get to the right people. That's exactly where
Huizenga separates himself from the tumult of the Mark McGwire
controversy.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, who is challenging baseball's home run record, last
week acknowledged that he is taking androstenedione, a product the
body turns into testosterone. It is not banned by baseball, but it
is banned in the NFL, NCAA and Olympic community. Those on the
extreme edges of the controversy have been quick to either admonish
or exonerate McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   Huizenga sees a lot of gray area.
</P>
<P>
   ``My biggest concern about this issue and Andro concerns all of
the Little Leaguers and kids who want to emulate their heroes,'' he
said. ``That's more worrisome to me than anything else.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know kids are looking for ways to get bigger. At the time
Lyle died, the estimates said 5-to-10 percent of high school-age
kids had used anabolic steroids, and a third of those weren't even
in sports. Medically, the consensus is that adolescents who use any
form of testosterone are more susceptible to side effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids have the desire to attain adult stature, become more
aggressive, get the girls. There are as many social issues involved
as there are sports issues.''
</P>
<P>
   When Huizenga looks at McGwire, he understands fully why the
Cardinals' first baseman chose to take andro, and that he is hardly
the only baseball player doing it, and that there are no studies
which confirm any long term dangers.
</P>
<P>
   But kids don't make those kind of distinctions, and andro does
not offer the black-and-white simplicity of anabolic steroids.
Huizenga can tell a college freshman that steroids killed his
friend Alzado.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's a poor doctor to do about education when a drug, which
seems to augment performance, offers no evidence of long-term side
effect because there are no decent long-term studies?'' Huizenga
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, honest education can encourage young athletes to
use a certain drug. They see McGwire as a role model and they
decide to take a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   The andro issue is reminiscent of another sports medicine
situation from our past.
</P>
<P>
   In the '60s, at the height of rampant steroid use and abuse in
track and field, especially in East Germany and the Soviet Union, a
San Gabriel-based doctor, Dr. Robert Kerr, felt that limited
steroid use, under a doctor's careful guidance, could be beneficial
without any long-term impact.
</P>
<P>
   Kerr eventually gave up the fight not because he changed his
mind on steroids, but because he could not control human nature.
His athlete patients succumbed to peer pressure and exceeded his
modest, monitored dosage behind his back.
</P>
<P>
   Andro, in at least one sense, is a victim of guilt by
association. The leagues and organizations that test for steroids
and testosterone levels the NFL, NCAA and Olympics found andro
while they were looking for steroids or high testosterone levels.
</P>
<P>
   As a synthetic form of testosterone, those organizations put
andro on the list of banned substance simply because they knew it
had muscle-building properties. It was a buckshot approach to
shooting down use of any kind of performance-enhancing product.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic groups have known about it since the '60s. The NFL
didn't add it to its list until 1996. ``The NFL does random testing
for elevated test levels, and andro can certainly alter that,''
Huizenga said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is, we don't have all of the answers. There are no
long-term studies because the product is relatively new.''
</P>
<P>
   Huizenga said a lot of natural substances are sold over the
counter. But just because they're natural does not mean they are
necessarily safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the FDA (Food and Drug Administration) doesn't regulate it,
we have no way of knowing (if it is safe),'' he said. ``It wasn't
that long ago where tryptophan was sold as a sleep aid. All it took
was one bad batch to kill a few people and take the product off the
shelves.''
</P>
<P>
   Huizenga would hate to see a drug witch hunt, or as he put it,
``reefer madness.'' Ironically, he noted that the World Health
Organization recently declared that testosterone can be used safely
as a male contraceptive, ``so there's a little bit of a double
standard here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question comes to where we draw the line?''
</P>
<P>
   And who is doing the drawing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-26-98 2347EDT &QL; 
