<HEADLINE>
AREA CLASS DOWN FROM LAST YEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE IRVINE  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ Dick Lascola, who operates the
Fallbrook-based Scouting Evaluation Service, says that this year's
crop of Southern California prep football talent is not as good as
last season.
</P>
<P>
   That, however, may not be as bad as it sounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought last year was one of the best we've had in a long
time,'' said Lascola, in his 22nd year scouting prep talent.
</P>
<P>
   Lascola did add that this year's crop is ``better than
average.'' But one area of concern is the lack of quarterback
depth.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of Southern California quarterbacks whom Lascola does
like are Poly's Chris Lewis (6-foot-4, 200) and Venice's J.P.
Losman (6-3, 180).
</P>
<P>
   ``(Lewis) is a big-time player,'' Lascola said. ``(Losman) had a
good year on a terrible team. I was impressed watching him and he
figures to get even better.''
</P>
<P>
   The only other pure quarterback Lascola lists as a preseason top
prospect is Moreno Valley's Kevin Jackson (6-4, 200).
</P>
<P>
   We'll now lead you through his views of some other top Southern
California talent in the world according to Lascola:
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Poly has an awesome team this year,'' Lascola said. He
mentioned Lewis, running back Larry Croom (5-9, 185), receiver
Kareem Kelly
</P>
<P>
   (6-1, 185) and cornerback Darrell Rideaux (5-9, 175) as
Jackrabbits to watch.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Amat safety-receiver Dennis Wyrick (6-1, 205) and running
back Mike Wagner (5-9, 180) should draw plenty of attention.
Wagner, though, is coming off a junior season-ending hip injury and
Wyrick may choose a future as a baseball player.
</P>
<P>
   The best Southern California running back could be bruising 6-1,
225-pound Joe Weber of Pacific. ``He's a kid who it seems has been
around forever,'' Lascola said. ``He has to be one of the top kids
around.''
</P>
<P>
   Westchester offensive linemen Courtney Morgan (6-2, 315)
``passes the look test. Now we'll see if he can play.'' Morgan will
block for Charles Drake, one of the region's best running backs.
</P>
<P>
   Sylmar has a pair of the top prospects in running back-safety
Corey Neal
</P>
<P>
   (5-11, 175) and tight end George Wrigster (6-4, 225).
</P>
<P>
   A trio of running back-defensive back types to watch are
Monrovia's Akil Harris (6-0, 195), Highland's Brandon McElvaine
</P>
<P>
   (6-1, 218) and Fontana's Cameron Spence (6-0, 180).
</P>
<P>
   Riverside North's Cory Kipp is ``a guy we like a lot,'' Lascola
said. The 6-5, 246-pound Kipp, by the way, visited USC's practice
last week and spent some time with defensive line coach Ed Orgeron
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the top prospects in Northern California are Concord De
La Salle back Atari Callen (5-10, 185), Oakland Skyline linebacker
Omar Nazel (6-4, 215), Fresno Edison athlete Ricky Manning (5-10,
160) and Sacramento Grant running back Onterrio Smith (5-11, 200).
A trio of linemen to watch are Hanford's Chris Murphy (6-7, 280),
Stockton St. Mary's Joe Blunt (6-5, 280) and Hughson's Luke Mackay
(6-5, 250).
</P>
<P>
   It's a ``very average year'' for San Diego area prospects.
``There are only about eight (big-time) kids, other than that,
nobody stands out,'' Lascola said. Offensive linemen Mike Sullivan
</P>
<P>
   (6-7, 305) of Vista and linebacker Ammon Mauga (6-0, 210) of
Oceanside stand out as much as anybody. Running back Rashaan
Sanders (6-0, 185) and quarterback Detroci Watts (6-0, 175) of tiny
San Diego Horizon could be big-time players. Offensive lineman
Gerald Sykes (6-4, 290) of San Diego Kearney is another guy to
watch.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, it's very early in the evaluation. ``It's a
wait-and-see-type situation,'' Lascola said.
</P>
<P>
   Is Randall going to Texas?
</P>
<P>
   As we've said before, early commitments aren't written in stone.
Texas supposedly landed its 14th prospect with the announcement by
Houston Yates offensive lineman Alfio Randall (6-5, 265) after an
unofficial visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I committed to the coaches,'' Randall was quoted as
saying. ``My family and I really loved it.''
</P>
<P>
   His father, though, had a different view: ``Alfio is not
committed to any school. We did visit Austin and loved it. We were
very impressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Get a head start in Nevada
</P>
<P>
   The first Friday for high school football in Southern California
is Sept.11, but if you want to get a head start, venture to Nevada.
The Nevada season actually opens up this weekend, but perhaps the
most interesting matchup in the first two weeks comes on Sept. 5.
On that day, traditional power and perennially national-ranked St.
Louis of Honolulu comes to Las Vegas to play Green Valley of nearby
Henderson in the Silver Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis has a big-time prospect in linebacker Joe Siofele
</P>
<P>
   (6-2, 230) and a several others who could be playing in college
real soon. Defensive lineman Junior Tagoai (6-3, 290) and running
back Noah Campbell
</P>
<P>
   (6-0, 215) are drawing interest. Offensive lineman Shayne
Kajioika (6-4, 340) and receiver Kanale George (5-11, 160) are also
worth watching.
</P>
<P>
   Green Valley knocked off Poly in the 1996 season opener.
</P>
<P>
   BYU's receiving corps took a major hit when Jonathan Pittman and
Eugene Childs both failed to qualify. Pittman is a former St. John
Bosco and Long Beach City College receiver and Childs is a recent
graduate of Westchester.
</P>
</TEXT>
